<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SWEPT BY A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels walked with a swagger throughout June, but
they stumbled into the All-Star break after their fifth consecutive
loss, a 5-4 setback to the Oakland A's on Sunday afternoon before
23,208 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The losing streak is the Angels' longest of the season, and the
three-game sweep at the hands of the A's is the first time they've
been swept in a three-game series since the Indians did it to them
April 3-5.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Angels is that they're still in first
place in the American League West _ by 1{ games _ and the three
days off will give them a chance to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get away from each other,'' shortstop Gary
DiSarcina said. ``We spend so much time together, it's good to get
away and spend some time with your family. We've been together
every day since spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time for them to get away from me, and for me to
get away from them,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``Then get
after it on Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels certainly played like a team that was tired, and
tired of each other on Sunday. They had a 4-1 lead after a four-run
fourth inning, highlighted by Jim Edmonds' 15th home run and
DiSarcina's RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   But even with starter Chuck Finley on the mound, the Angels
couldn't hold the lead. The A's tied the game in the eighth on
Kevin Mitchell's first home run of the year and went ahead in the
ninth against Troy Percival (1-3), who got the loss. Percival
walked Mitchell with the bases loaded to force in what turned out
to be the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had their chances but failed to do what they had done
so well during June, when they went 22-6 _ like moving runners up.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had runners on first and third with one out in the
seventh inning when Damon Mashore _ pinch running for Tim Salmon _
got picked off first after A's pitcher Mike Fetters faked to third
and threw to first. Cecil Fielder struck out to end the frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fetters has got a real good third-to-first move,
outstanding,'' Collins said. ``(Third base coach) Larry (Bowa) told
him about it. But until you go out there and actually see it, you
don't know how good it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, the Angels had Garret Anderson on second with a
leadoff double. Matt Walbeck tried to get him to third. But
Walbeck's bunt went right back to Fetters, who threw Anderson out
at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very good during the homestand; that's
obviously an understatement,'' Collins said. ``All the things that
went right in June, we didn't do any of that the last five days. We
didn't make the big pitch, get the big hit or make the big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetters (1-2) got the win and Billy Taylor pitched the ninth to
earn his 18th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels now have three days to rest and get ready for the
second half of the season, and Collins said he hopes the five-game
losing streak eats at his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they do,'' Collins said when asked if his players will
contemplate the slump over the break. ``Because that's what you do,
you get angry. I know I am. My coaches are. You don't play the game
to get beat. You don't make up nine games in a month to lose five
games in a row. I hope they stew. They can have all the fun they
want in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Angels, though, say they need to have a little fun
away from the ballpark now. Upon finishing up a chat with reporters
after Sunday's game, Edmonds said, ``The sun's going down, got to
get to the river.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
