<HEADLINE>
JERRY BRUCKHEIMER _ HOLLYWOOD'S $1 MILLION MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News Staff Writers Glenn Whipp and   Dave McNary   also
contributed to this story) 
BY BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
  ``Armageddon,'' the most expensive movie of the summer, opened in
time for the holiday weekend, backed by all the hype and
intimidation Disney's formidable marketing machinery can muster.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet with a star-studded cast (Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Billy
Bob Thornton, Liv Tyler), perhaps the most bankable name on the
credits is producer Jerry Bruckheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Call him Hollywood's $100 &UR;  &LR; million man.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer belongs to an elite club _ including Steven
Spielberg and James Cameron _ that film studios gladly give free
rein, even in a time when most in the business are trying to limit
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for Bruckheimer's inclusion is obvious. His string of
hits includes ``The Rock,'' ``Con Air'' and, with late partner Don
Simpson, such pop phenomena as ``Flashdance,'' ``Beverly Hills
Cop,'' ``Top Gun,'' ``Dangerous Minds,'' as well as summer hits
like ``Crimson Tide'' and ``Bad Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``Armageddon,'' which cost $140 &UR;  &LR; million to make and
$60 &UR;  &LR; million to market, already has met with critical disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it opened to a somewhat disappointing $52.5 &UR;  &LR; million in
its first five days, according to estimates Sunday from studio
sources.
</P>
<P>
   If that and the lackluster performance of the summer's other
predicted, sure-fire smash, ``Godzilla,'' has the 54-year-old
producer worried that audiences are tiring of his high-decibel
style of moviemaking, he doesn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there is the pressure of knowing that nobody's
going to hit it out of the park every time,'' he said
philosophically. ``You don't try to strike out. You try to do the
best you can, but you're not always going to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   So the question looms large: Are the kinds of shallow-yet-strong
impact films Simpson and Bruckheimer made a Hollywood staple still
the summer moneymaking machines they've been for more than two
decades?
</P>
<P>
   Soft-spoken, without a hair on his scalp or face out of place,
Bruckheimer projects the confidence of a man who possesses the
elusive Hollywood megahit formula. Or, as he repeatedly tries to
frame it, an even rarer, more mystical attunement to the mass
audience's ever-changing tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think about making a blockbuster,'' Bruckheimer said.
``I think about trying to make an effective movie. There's always
more pressure when a movie is expensive and there are high
expectations bandied about in the press. I'd rather come in with
something that hasn't been talked about and, because you did your
job effectively, it becomes a hit. That's the most fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you've gotta listen to the people who are paying their
money,'' he adds. ``You have market indicators, predictions can be
made, but there's a whole mass out there making decisions
independently that are geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer's films are distinguished by their rapid narrative
momentum, exciting visuals, big action sequences, deafening
soundscapes, seasonings of raucous humor and broad emotional
strokes. They're easy to get and, some would say, just as easily
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bruckheimer has repeatedly insisted that the staple of
serious cinema _ character development _ is fundamentally important
for his movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to populate your films with punctuation points that
the audience can identify with emotionally,'' he said. ``I've
always felt that, no matter how spectacular your production may be,
if you don't care about the characters, the movie isn't going to
please many people. It's about creating characters and themes that
are engaging, then surrounding them with drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, though, say Bruckheimer's movies have little to do
with creating characters and drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like it or not, Simpson and Bruckheimer are responsible for
devaluing the moviegoing experience during their lifetime and were
able to package a kind of violence and adrenaline in an attractive
way,'' said Charles Fleming, author of ``High Concept: Don Simpson
and the Hollywood Culture of Excess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spawned legions of imitators who have been able to
make similar movies. ... These movies have affected our perspective
as moviegoers and we have accepted a certain level of violence and
hollowness that we would not have accepted before,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   Film critic Leonard Maltin, though, gives Bruckheimer his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give a lot of people what they want to see,'' he said.
``Critics can talk themselves blue in the face, but that fact
remains. What troubles me is that his movies are also a product of
a marketing machine that makes people think they're what they want
to see _ whether they deliver the goods or not. I didn't hear
anyone raving about `Con Air,' but they got those people to pay
their money and see it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
