<HEADER>
A1371 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRUCKHEIMER-2nd-take-     07-06 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUCKHEIMER-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
 
(their money and see it.'')
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps two of the reasons audiences flock to Bruckheimer's
films are themes that pop up over and over _ patriotism and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer is big on technology. He thinks most directors and
screenwriters lag behind their audiences when it comes to embracing
new media and innovations. Audiences, he said, are used to surfing
the Internet and cable channels and thus want faster and more vivid
movies. If the movies don't deliver that, they'll get their kicks
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely frightening what you can do now with film,''
Bruckheimer said. ``The envelope has been pushed so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer movies also have a strong jingoistic element. You
can hardly sit through 10 minutes of ``Armageddon'' without seeing
an American flag, military uniform or some strong, nationalistic
image.
</P>
<P>
   Said actor Owen Wilson, one of the movie's oil riggers: ``Jerry
pitched it like, if you don't do the movie, you're not patriotic.
In fact, you're probably a communist.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer is the first to admit that his brand of box-office
magic doesn't always work. The Detroit-reared son of German
immigrants, he cut his professional teeth producing commercials for
car companies before moving on to Madison Avenue, then to
Hollywood, where he initially had middling success with such
projects as ``Farewell, My Lovely'' and ``American Gigolo.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand slams started coming when Bruckheimer teamed up with
former Paramount executive Simpson in the early '80s. They had
their first surprise blockbuster with 1983's ``Flashdance,'' and as
time went on displayed an amazing knack for getting rising,
not-quite-there stars into their breakthrough vehicles: Eddie
Murphy in ``Beverly Hills Cop,'' Tom Cruise in ``Top Gun,'' Will
Smith in ``Bad Boys,'' and, probably, Affleck in ``Armageddon''
(who won the role before the release of ``Good Will Hunting,'' when
he impressed all the female assistants at Bruckheimer's production
company).
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer said that even if he changes his approach, one thing
always will remain constant: `I'm still going to try to make
pictures that excite me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
