<HEADLINE>
COLLINS: MORE INTENSITY NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Manager Terry Collins ripped his players for a lack of
intensity after Saturday night's loss to the Oakland A's, and he
says they'll need to get it back after the All-Star break if they
hope to maintain their lead in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with tremendous intensity in the month of June,
where every game meant something,'' Collins said. ``We need to do
that again because the second half of the season is when pennants
are won. You've got to go out every night and forget about the day
before. If we approach it that way, we'll win our share of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins pointed to the four games against the Dodgers that might
have drained the club emotionally going into the final stretch
before the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There sure was a lot of emotion in those four games,'' Collins
said. ``You play the game on emotion and we might have used up a
lot. It's a good time to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a break,'' pitcher Troy Percival said. ``The guys
have to stay mentally strong. We're not the most talented team in
baseball. We're not even the most talented team in the AL West. But
we're definitely the toughest and most resilient.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels do return, they play four against the Mariners
in Seattle. Even though the Mariners are in last place in the
division, Collins says the games will be big.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a bad first half, but they are a better team than
that,'' Collins said. ``They know it, everybody knows it. Coming
out of the break, one thing that might get them going is to beat us
up a little bit. One thing we need to do is win a couple games.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins decided to change his pitching rotation for the series
in Seattle in order to give Jarrod Washburn a few extra days of
rest. Washburn felt ``tightness'' in his left (pitching) forearm in
his start Saturday and left the game after five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Olivares will start Thursday, followed by Chuck Finley,
Jason Dickson and Steve Sparks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
