<HEADLINE>
MY WORLD CUP RUNNETH OVER WITH BOREDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Searching for some information on the British Open
golf tournament, I called a fellow in England, who quickly turned
the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When are you Yanks going to get serious about football?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another proselytizer trying to convert an American soccer
heathen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably about the time you Brits develop a cuisine,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   The chat deteriorated, pointing up the most personally annoying
part of the World Cup: the soccer fanatic's insistence on
inflicting his god on those of us who worship rocks, trees and
300-pound offensive linemen (amazing how little difference there is
sometimes between the three. But I digress).
</P>
<P>
   The world is a big place. It has lots of things going on. If
soccer is among those recreations that turns your crank, bully for
you. Far be it from me to deny any man or woman the thrill of
one-nil.
</P>
<P>
   But I reserve the right to say no thanks to the buttonholing,
cajoling, coercion and subversion that occurs every four years when
World Cup fans insist on the event holding as much meaning to me as
them.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude has nothing to do with xenophobia or American
chauvinism. Nor is it a failure to understand the game. Frankly,
there are few sports simpler, which is why it has such wide appeal.
It's also a great sport for kids, who can learn the virtues of team
play without having to be either large or injured a lot.
</P>
<P>
   But as spectator entertainment, well, give me the back of the
cereal box. And please don't try to sell me on last week's
England-Argentina match. Yes, it was close and dramatic. Guess
what? Sports are supposed to be close and dramatic. Don't confuse
closeness with wonderfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Here's four reasons for allowing the rest of the sports world to
continue its party without my valued contribution:
</P>
<P>
   Hands. For anyone raised in America, hands are everything. It's
part of the culture. We like to be handy. We're hands-on kind of
folks. We're often put off by hand-outs, but we can respect a
hands-off boss. We've always lent a hand. But as competitors, we
don't show our hand.
</P>
<P>
   In soccer, only the goalies can use hands, and most of the time
they may as well be clubs for all the dexterity involved in
stopping shots. Any kid who watches Ken Griffey Jr. make a leaping
catch at the wall, or Jerry Rice pluck a pass off the grass or
Michael Jordan strip a ball from Karl Malone, knows that something
is missing in a game where hands are nothing more than penalty
makers. Hey, pro football scouts even grade offensive linemen on
the ability to grab.
</P>
<P>
   Until science creates a foot with an opposable thumb, soccer's
fundamental flaw will prevent persuading kids who want to do more
than shove hands into their jean pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: I know, this is an old complaint. But it's not just the
lack of scoring, it's what lack of scoring does to the contest.
When the U.S. fell behind 1-0 in their Cup game against Iran, I
swear that every Iranian in the world was standing in the
goal-mouth to prevent a U.S. score. Because scoring is so hard, the
first lead, especially in major international matches, tends to
stick because of defensive paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Ties: If baseball were to condense an entire game to moments of
action, the video would last 10 minutes. For a football game, maybe
15 minutes. Soccer proudly boasts of having more action than
either, but to what end? The tie is often regarded as a good
result. Including qualifying, the Italian team in the Cup played
three 0-0 games and three 1-0 games. Even though soccer has
conceded to overtime periods, many matches still come down to the
shootout, which is as silly and irrelevant a contrivance for
deciding a sports event as ending Game 7 of the NBA Finals with
paper-scissors-rock.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalism: Through no fault of the sport, soccer bears the
hopes and fears of entire nations. It can't shed that dubious
baggage, as the French cops have discovered. World Cup results
should have no bearing on national identity except for pride, but
inevitably it makes some people crazy, as we've seen with the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately in this country, since the fall of the Soviet Union
ended the last great international athletic rivalry for the U.S.,
it appears most Americans don't get too worked up anymore (how much
sleep was lost worrying about the meager American medal count in
the Winter Olympics?). We're too busy trying to dominate the world
with computers, airplanes and ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S., Cup TV ratings predictably have been wretched.
Telecasts of American matches during the day failed to outpoint the
soap operas they pre-empted. The international matches on ESPN
don't outdraw the X-Games.
</P>
<P>
   But I imagine American basketball, baseball and football
wouldn't get much of an audience in Europe or South America. That's
OK. Even we Yanks have a hard time watching Russ Davis play third
base or Vin Baker shoot free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a private pain, one in which no obligation is felt to
share with the world.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
