<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ROLL PAST MARINERS, 8-4, AS GONZALEZ REACHES 101 RBI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Hank Greenberg knocked in 103 runs before the
All-Star break in 1935, but the Detroit Tigers' slugger didn't go
to the big game. The two American League first basemen that season
were Jimmie Foxx and Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez one-upped Greenberg last night.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez hit two home runs and drove in four runs to power the
Rangers to an 8-4 victory against the Seattle Mariners at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Rangers' right fielder 101 RBI as the All-Star
break begins today. And unlike poor Greenberg, Gonzalez is going to
the big game.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is scheduled to start for the AL tomorrow night in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   He heads to the game as a star among the All Stars. RBI records
might not be as scintillating as home-run records; they don't make
for spectacular highlights on ``SportsCenter''.
</P>
<P>
   But what Gonzalez did last night is just as incredible as
anything that Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr. and Sammy Sosa did in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while you have a very special night that comes
along,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``This game's been played a
long time, and not too many guys have driven in 100 runs before the
All-Star break. It's a very special night for Juan Gonzalez, and a
special night for our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   To be exact, now there's two. Greenberg and Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred ribbies before the All-Star break is amazing,''
said Gonzalez, who couldn't stop smiling after the game. ``It is
the best moment in my career, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of the home runs came off Mariners starter Randy Johnson
(7-8). The first, with Roberto Kelly aboard in the first inning,
gave the Rangers a quick lead. The second, with Will Clark on after
a run-scoring double, broke the game open in the seventh inning and
make a winner of reliever Xavier Hernandez (3-1).
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won their second consecutive game after breaking a
six-game losing streak. They picked up another game on the Anaheim
Angels in the AL West, and go into the break 1 1/2 games out of
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to be in a better position than we are now, but it
could be a lot worse,'' Oates said. ``I said in spring training
nobody's got the pitching to run away with the division. It's going
to be nip and tuck the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   But on this night, the division race was secondary to Gonzalez's
achievement for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unbelievable,'' said Mike Simms, who also hit a
two-run home run off Johnson. ``You have to tip your hat to him,
and shake your head and say wow at the same time. I think everyone
in this clubhouse is looking forward to the second half to see what
kind of numbers he can put up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, the second half. The Rangers will try to run down the
Angels, and Gonzalez will take aim at another name from history,
namely Hack Wilson and his record 190 RBI in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is on pace for 188.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``Records aren't easy. The key is
to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he'll have to be content with being the second man with
100 before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe Juan has 101 RBIs,'' Mariners manager Lou
Piniella said. ``It used to be a barometer for a very successful
full season.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez established 100 before the break as a goal when he got
to 96, but then he went through a six-game drought. He broke it
with one Saturday but still needed three yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying,'' he said. ``I never quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he shook his head and smiled some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, man,'' he said. ``One hundred ribbies before the
All-Star break. It's a great moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Greenberg, he doesn't have three days off to enjoy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
