<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BOMBARD JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ At their current pace, the Mariners will
finish last in the American League West, lead the majors in errors
and possibly blown saves, and rank right up there in make-overs.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman David Segui recently bleached his hair blond.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Ken Griffey Jr. went bald.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, the Mariner center fielder is going to the All-Star Game in
Denver as a Barry Bonds look-alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't a guy get a haircut?'' Griffey asked after the Mariners
stumbled into the three-day All-Star break with an 8-4 loss to the
Texas Rangers before 38,053 fans at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The series finale featured two home runs by Juan Gonzalez, who
drove in four runs and became only the second player in major
league history to drive in more than 100 runs before the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has 101 RBIs, two fewer than Hank Greenberg in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that 100 RBIs was a very successful season,''
Mariner manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is threatening to break Hack Wilson's single-season
record. Wilson drove in 190 runs for the Chicago Cubs in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   The M's are threatening to go from first to last in the AL West
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed a couple of opportunities here to pick up some
ground,'' said Piniella, whose defending division champions lost
the final two games of the three-game series after reeling off
three straight wins. They still trail first-place Anaheim, losers
of five straight, by 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Griffey's new look took away some of the focus
from another so-so start by Randy Johnson. The left-hander looked
good at times, striking out 12 Rangers, but only ordinary at
others.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nine hits he surrendered were Gonzalez home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Ranger run-producing machine socked his 25th homer of the
season in the first inning with Roberto Kelly aboard on a single,
and capped a game-clinching three-run Texas rally in the seventh
with his 26th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Randy pitched better than the final score would
indicate,'' Mariner pitching coach Stan Williams said. ``It wasn't
up to par with the game he pitched in San Diego (Johnson's seventh
and last win), but he got hurt (Sunday night) with some bloopers
that fell in.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's worst season in years continues with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Good at times. Bad at times.
</P>
<P>
   He has struck out 12 batters in each of his past four starts,
but the eight runs Johnson surrendered were the most he has allowed
in one game since June 16, 1995 against the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have dealt Johnson two of his eight losses this
season, scoring 14 earned runs in 11 innings. Gonzalez became the
second player this season and sixth overall to hit two homers off
Johnson in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Johnson) had stretches when he threw the ball good,''
Piniella said, ``and stretches when he got hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He struck out the side in the third inning. The fourth inning
began with Ivan Rodriguez's double and opposite-field homer to
right by Mike Simms, giving Texas a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners retaliated in the fifth, wiping out the three-run
deficit on RBI singles by Alex Rodriguez and Griffey and a
bases-loaded walk to Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But reliever Xavier Hernandez, who walked Martinez, kept Seattle
from going ahead by retiring Glenallen Hill on a first-pitch pop-up
to Ranger catcher Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners put the potential go-ahead runner on second base in
the sixth inning when Rico Rossy, replacing Russ Davis at third
base, singled and advanced on Joey Cora's groundout. Alex Rodriguez
fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   Rossy drew solid reviews for his defense, handling four chances
crisply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has good hands and did a nice job over there,''
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who went into the series finale with 35 homers and a
.297 batting average, walked his first two times, singled in the
fifth to get his average to .299 and then lined out to right field
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   And then he got a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks great, man,'' bald teammate Jay Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey showed off his new look to his wife, Melissa, standing
outside the visiting clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks just like Barry (Bonds),'' she said. ``I might get
mine bleached.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
