<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USWOMEN'SOPEN-BOS     07-06 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH START FOR OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN'S OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ It was 45 feet perhaps, maybe longer. Jenny
Chuasiriporn, perhaps too young to realize what she was about to
do, only wanted to know one thing before putting: ``Joey, tell me a
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Her brother/caddie didn't hesitate. ``Foot left.'' And as his
sister settled over the putt, Joey added: ``Give it a good run.''
In other words, said Jenny, ``he didn't want me to leave it
short.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball rolled over a small hill in the 18th green at Blackwolf
Run and as it picked up steam, it kept its line. Fifteen feet from
the hole, Chuasiriporn could not believe what she was seeing. ``My
eyes popped out.'' The ball dropped and Chuasiriporn, having shot a
1-over 72, put her hand over her mouth, stunned, almost
embarrassed, her youthful innocence shining through. ``I was really
thinking two-putt from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the incredible birdie putt left us with this most
improbable scenario _  &UR; today &LR;  at noon a 20-year-old amateur who
made up a four-shot deficit on the final day will play off over 18
holes for the US Women's Open championship against a 20-year-old
professional from South Korea, Se Ri Pak, who missed an 8-foot
birdie attempt after Chuasiriporn's dramatics and settled for
76-_290.
</P>
<P>
   It figures that a couple of kids will stick around and play a
course that simply beat up the finest women golfers in the world.
It's the first time since 1984 that the winning score was over par,
and the highest winning score since 1983, when 6-over also won.
Over the final 36 holes here, only one player posted a sub-par
round.
</P>
<P>
   The money already may have been decided (as an amateur,
Chuasiriporn can't be paid, so Pak will get the top prize of
$267,500), but both young women have their sights set on making
history. Only one amateur (Catherine LaCoste, 1967) has won the
women's national championship, and regardless of who prevails
Monday, she will be the youngest champion in the history of this
event.
</P>
<P>
   No one would have imagined such an ending, but as this US
Women's Open played out on a near impossible course, it became
apparent that anything was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Pak started the day a shot ahead of Mhairi McKay, a 23-year-old
from Scotland who was playing her first US Women's Open, and
Liselotte Neumann, the 32-year-old Swede who won this event in
1988. The wind, which had hammered the field Saturday, was less a
factor, though birdies remained but a whisper at this 6,412-yard
layout. Pak would make just one, as would McKay, while Neumann
didn't make any. Chuasiriporn made two, most memorable the one at
18, but in a US Open, where pars are as a valuable as Bill Gates's
portfolio, it was her steady par-35 on the front that got her a
share of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   She needed help, of course, which first Pak, then McKay
provided.
</P>
<P>
   At the 402-yard, par-4 third, Pak pulled her drive into the
rough and committed an Open sin: She tried to pound a long shot out
of it. ``I hit 5-iron,'' she said. ``A mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot went even farther left into grass that was up to her
knees. She slashed it out, but ended up with a double bogey, tied
with McKay at 3-over.
</P>
<P>
   McKay, paired with Pak, parred the par-4 fourth and found
herself in the lead when Pak missed the green and made bogey. But
her Open spotlight was about to be buried in a greenside bunker the
size of Seagull Beach. It's where her approach to the par-4 seventh
landed, and though she learned her game over the holy ground of
Turnberry, this difficult shot proved too much. McKay took three
shots to get out, made a 7 and fell from the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Duke senior, Chuasiriporn, who about that same time
was curling in a 20-footer at the par-3 eighth to go back to
5-over. She was tied with Pak and Neumann, but not for long. Pak,
from thick rough, made another mistake at the par-4 ninth, electing
to go for a green guarded by water. ``I was thinking lay up, then I
said, OK, I go.'' She went, all right, directly into the water and
fell to 6-over, a shot behind.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, as she had done Saturday, too, picked up a rash of
bogeys (Nos. 7, 11, 12), and fell two behind Chuasiriporn, who was
ripping off six straight pars, the type of play that is usually
reserved for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really have too many expectations,'' said
Chuasiriporn. ``I really just went out there just trying to hit a
lot of fairways and greens.''
</P>
<P>
   She followed that strategy pretty well, until 15 when she drove
it left into a fairway bunker. It led to just her second bogey of
the day. But it came at about the same time as Pak was making her
only birdie of the afternoon, a 7-footer at the 14th. The powerful
Pak, who stormed into prominence with her triumph in the LPGA
Championship two months ago, was back in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Chuasiriporn pushed her tee ball on the par-3 17th over a
mound into thick rough and made bogey, Pak had a two-shot lead and
seemed assured of being the first since Juli Inkster in 1984 to win
two majors in her rookie season. But golf can take as quickly as it
gives, and Pak put her tee shot on the 17th almost exactly where
Chuasiriporn did. She, too, made bogey, which grew more significant
by the festivities going on up on the 18th green at about the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, a Baltimore native whose parents are from
Thailand, thought her birdie bomb had given her second place, that
she was two shots behind. ``What is she, at how many over?'' she
asked at the scorer's tent. Told that she was tied for the lead,
Chuasiriporn nearly lost it. ``I just kind of turned to my brother
and he was just delighted, almost in tears, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The tears flowed even more moments later when Pak, having
nestled her approach to about 8 feet of the 18th pin, missed the
birdie putt that would have won it. Instead, she missed it right,
meaning two youngsters will get another crack at a course that many
veterans probably would never like to see again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to explain it,'' Chuasiriporn said, standing
amid a group of USGA people who probably were trying to make sense
of it all, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
