</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS SEIZES GRAIL _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It was the third coming of Goran the Croat. Seeming a
bearded Biblical holy man calling down thunderbolts on his enemies,
enspiriting his flock, preaching life after defeat ... he
nevertheless wound up in the wilderness again.
</P>
<P>
   This time his people, most of Sunday's multitude of 13,120 in
the tennis shrine called Centre Court, looked into his mesmerizing
chestnut eyes and believed. They believed he would be forgiven the
sins of his two previous comings to the Wimbledon final: 1992,
flesh turning weak in the fifth set, wilting before Andre Agassi;
and 1994's faint-hearted drubbing by the philistine Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   But this was surely to be the day of atonement for Goran
Ivanisevic. In his Italian-tailored loincloth, swinging a
lightning-spurting crozier, he was smiting Sampras mightily,
pushing the King of Grassland into a fifth-set corner. Having risen
from the dead-end season he'd been enduring, Goran the Croat was in
a ``seek and ye shall find'' mood.
</P>
<P>
   He came, he sought _ and he found hellfire yet smoldering within
Sampras. Ivanisevic got burned, 6-7 (2-7), 7-6 (11-9), 6-4, 3-6,
6-2, and his flock wailed and tore their hair.
</P>
<P>
   A notable hair-tearer for Ivanisevic all right, one that plunged
him into the abyss of despair:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only kill myself. It will be too much to come back
again. This was my worst moment. I gave everything to win the
fourth set, but then it was like somebody hit me. I went down, he
went up. But my legs ... my legs were tired. I couldn't get to the
net like I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But his resurrection to respectability really had foundered long
before. Sampras twice stood on the brink of a two-set pit at 5-6
and 7-8 in the second-set tie-breaker, naked to Goran the Croat.
The King of Grassland had nothing more to offer than second serves
that stood up like masochists, begging to be flagellated.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic obliged by lashing them ... but into the net, and
would recall them as damning his chances for salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete didn't play well,'' he said. ``This was my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   This was also what once more confirmed Sampras's greatness.
Winning when the temperature of The Heater (as he calls his best
friend, his serve) drops severely, his forehand looks docile and
his head droops like a yo-yo is the quality that makes him an
all-time champion. Winning ragged because his heart wouldn't let
him lose, because his pride in possession of the prize among prizes
_ Wimbledon _ was a shield against all the thunderbolts that Goran
the Croat hurled. That sets Sampras apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place does something for me,'' Sampras says. ``I can
reach down and find something extra here.''
</P>
<P>
   Never before in 13 major finals had he been pinched in a fifth
set, but he reached and found. His record in fifth-set crucibles
tells you much about the champion: 26-9 career; 4-0 at the Big W.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different, the fifth, new,'' he said. ``You don't want
to make a mistake.'' He didn't, summoning the necessary service
returns. His miserly three unforced errors in the ultimate set (19
for the match) said that though his majesty was missing, he was
defending the crown zealously. Calmly, patiently, he let Ivanisevic
make the mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Becker, thrice the king, used to say there was something
mystical about the somber forest green ampitheatre where they're
crowned. He felt inspirational tremors running through him as he
entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nothing like that,'' the undramatic Sampras said with a
shake of his head. ``But it's a special place.'' Sampras's place.
His magical garden.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is becoming a man for the ages, though merely 27 next
month. He doesn't recall meeting Laurie Doherty or Willie Renshaw.
Maybe in the next life. But he does know Bjorn Borg, who 18 years
ago became the third man to bring Wimbledon to its grass-stained
knees on five occasions. And Sampras makes four in the tournament's
112 years.
</P>
<P>
   Britons Doherty and Renshaw may have jiggled in their tombs.
Doherty won five titles between 1902 and 1906 and Renshaw the
rec-ord seven between 1881 and 1889, a simpler time when it was
virtually a British intramural affair. No barbarians from America
or Croatia butted it.
</P>
<P>
   None of those guys, however, is safe from Sampras the Stalker.
He's sneaking up on 61-year-old Roy Emerson, whose record for major
titles _ a dozen _ has been inviolate for 31 years. Sampras has 11
now, and Ivanisevic doesn't own the one he might have had by
flogging those tie-breaker returns properly.
</P>
<P>
   But Goran the Croat made Sampras play, made his loud and hopeful
flock pray _ and made the day for a championship that seldom goes
the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goran was terrific,'' says Sampras. ``But only one name can go
on the trophy ... there's nothing I could say to make him feel
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The third coming has come and gone. Sampras is this much of a
believer: he thinks there will be a fourth. ``Goran will win this
someday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Goran the Croat, anguishing about that second set
tie-breaker, will pace and curse despondently in the wilderness,
wearing the requisite hairshirt. But at least one from his Italian
tailor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
