<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYCLING-LONGSJOCLASSI     07-06 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-LONGSJO </SLUG>
 CLASSIC-BOS  
 McCORMACK SHOWS METTLE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FITCHBURG, Mass. _ Granted, this city is not known for being a
party place, but it's a fair bet that there was a lot of
celebrating going on Sunday night after the four-day
Fitchburg-Longsjo Classic bike race. Especially for riders on the
Wisconsin-based Saturn team.
</P>
<P>
   That team's Frank McCormack, of Leicester, won the men's overall
race, covering 243.5 miles in 9 hours 22 minutes 34 seconds. On the
women's side, Dede Demet of Boulder, raced the 127 miles in
6:04:23. To top it off, Karen Bliss Livington, also of the Saturn
team, won the women's 25-mile stage Sunday. (The Saturn victories
ended there, as Czeslaw Lukascewcicz of the Canadian Club Cycliste
Espoir won the men's 49.5-mile stage).
</P>
<P>
   But McCormack, 29, insisted that the celebrations would be
low-key.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think things will be real quiet tonight,'' he said,
indicating that his mom and dad from Plymouth, along with brothers
Shawn and Mark, would be headed home after being houseguests for
the past four days. ``So we'll take it easy tonight and go to the
beach tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing McCormack on the podium with the winner's jersey was a
familiar sight to fans of the 39-year-old Fitchburg race _ he won
it once before in 1994. But back then he wasn't affiliated with a
national team (nor did he have the twin 3-year-old sons he held on
the podium). So the victory then was what he thinks was his ``big
stepping stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year the Saturn team signed him up, and the following
year he went on to win the National Criterium race, something he
repeated the next year. He's kept on the winning track with an
overall victory in the Tour of Japan in May.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Sunday's race, McCormack was wearing the leader's
jersey after Saturday's 103-mile circuit race at Wachusett
Mountain, and was in front of Trent Klasna by 14 seconds, which is
seemingly not a lot. But in Sunday's race, which covered 55 laps of
the 9/10ths-of-a-mile course that circled downtown Fitchburg, all
McCormack had to do was stay with the main pack to retain his lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Knickman and Danny Pate bolted in front of the pack of 116
riders with more than 40 laps to go, and built a lead of more than
a minute on the pack. But no one, including McCormack, seemed too
concerned. Knickman, after all, sat at more than 8 minutes back in
the overall classification, so even though he lapped the field, he
was really no threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be patient and not go after every break,''
McCormack said. He acknowledged, though, that he also couldn't
afford to get too complacent. ``Yeah, I'd be sitting back in the
pack, and Brian (Walton) would come get me,'' he said, referring to
his teammate and third-place overall finisher.
</P>
<P>
   So McCormack and his teammates rode not to win, but just to
place, and let the guys in front knock themselves out in the
82-degree weather. Knickman ended up with the sprinter's prize and
$560 in ``primes,'' or lap prizes, but McCormack walked away with
the gold medal and $1,300. Brother Mark finished seventh overall,
while Shawn placed 66th.
</P>
<P>
   Demet held on to her overall lead by staying with her teammates
in the final sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two turns to go on the final lap, I just didn't have the
legs,'' she said. ``But luckily, Karen did.''
</P>
<P>
   No argument from winner Bliss Livingston. ``I just really
punched it with 200 meters to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So she got the stage win, and Demet the overall win and $400.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturn team must have slept well Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
