    DEATH TOLL REACHES FIVE IN TACOMA BAR SHOOTINGS
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS, RUTH TEICHROEB AND RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Five people were killed and six others were
wounded early Sunday when three gunmen walked into a karaoke bar
and blasted away at employees and customers in this city's worst
multiple homicide in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they have no suspects but hinted that the slayings
at the Trang Dai Cafe in the Lincoln business district of south
Tacoma could have been gang-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're speculating it was gang-related because of the type of
shooting,'' said police spokesman Jim Mattheis. ``It wasn't a
robbery. They didn't say anything and didn't take anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar, one of several Southeast Asian businesses in the
neighborhood, was targeted in a drive-by shooting June 28. No one
was injured in that incident. Police said they don't know whether
it was related to the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Police also had an ongoing investigation of the bar at South
38th Street and South Yakima Avenue because of ``criminal
activities,'' Mattheis said, but would provide no details.
Residents of the neighborhood yesterday said the bar had a
reputation for drug activity and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   The dead were identified as Tuong Hung Do, 33, Duy Le, 24, and
Tuyen Vo of Tacoma, a 21-year-old waitress at the bar. All three
were from Tacoma. Names of two other victims were not available
last night.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wounded was in critical condition last night at
Madigan Army Hospital at Fort Lewis, and was not expected to
survive. The other four were taken to Tacoma General Hospital and
St. Joseph Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   A woman was treated for minor injuries at St. Joseph Medical
Center and released, while Pat Nguyen, 40, the owner of the bar,
was treated for a gunshot wound to his upper body and released.
</P>
<P>
   At Tacoma General, 28-year-old Hoai Nguyen was in satisfactory
condition last night after undergoing surgery for a gunshot wound
to his left shoulder. Another man was released after being treated
for a bullet wound to his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the gunmen _ at least one carrying a semiautomatic
rifle _ walked in through the front doors of the bar and opened
fire on about 16 employees and customers about 1:40 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dark. There was no way the victims knew something was
coming,'' Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   The only light in the one-room bar was a disco ball and black
lights, he said. The ball was still spinning slowly as Pierce
County medical examiners removed the last three bodies from the bar
about 16 hours after the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The intruders rapidly pumped off dozens of rounds, spraying the
entire interior of the bar. Police said they did not appear to
target anyone in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen continued firing as they backed out the front door
moments later.
</P>
<P>
   They fired several more times through the one-story building's
thin wooden walls as they hurried down a side alley to the back of
the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the three men fled in a waiting car.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a pop, pop, pop, pop, pop, and I thought it was
fireworks,'' said Charlene Armstrong, who lives on the corner south
of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard a car skidding by.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who has lived in the neighborhood since April, said
it is usually a quiet area.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids run around all the time,'' Armstrong said. ``This
surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived about 1:45 a.m., four people were dead. One
body lay under a table near the front door. Two others were by
booths at the side of the room, and a fourth lay by the back door.
</P>
<P>
   Things were calm by the time police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was inside the building and kind of wandering around
in shock,'' Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone in the bar was armed, none had a chance to shoot back,
Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings stunned Lincoln business district residents and
merchants. They said there have been occasional problems in the
area, but nothing like this.
</P>
<P>
   Police interviewed four of the shooting victims but would not
reveal what they said. Police also are reviewing a security
videotape they obtained from a nearby business.
</P>
<P>
   Police pleaded for the public's help in catching the killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take someone to come forward,'' Mattheis said.
``This is a close-knit community. It's going to take somebody to
put their fears aside and come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Brian Ebersole said yesterday that he hoped the slayings
would not taint the city's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is unprecedented,'' he said. ``It could have
happened anywhere in America. Unfortunately, it happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersole, who once lived in the neighborhood, said it has not
been plagued by any more problems than other
</P>
<P>
   areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragic day for the city of Tacoma, and for the
Vietnamese community,'' Ebersole said. ``This is an aberration.
We'll work through this and will continue to make this a safe
community.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that Tacoma has about 2,500 residents of Vietnamese
descent.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 residents of the neighborhood _ most Vietnamese
American _ crowded the sidewalk across the street from the bar
yesterday after the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Some came hoping to learn the whereabouts of relatives they
believed were in the bar when the shootings occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Jimmy Win, whose cousin Vo waitressed at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Vo didn't come home after work and her car was still parked in
front of the bar yesterday afternoon, Win said before he learned of
her death.
</P>
<P>
   Win said he heard about the June 28 drive-by shooting right
after it happened and came looking for Vo because he was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard they had some trouble with a couple of people, a
couple of weeks before the drive-by,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tien Nguyen said he came to the scene looking for his
brother-in-law, Huynh Khanh, who was at the bar Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Khanh, 28, worked at the bar, playing the karaoke music for
customers, Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for my brother-in-law,'' he said shakily. ``I
heard about all this on TV this morning. He didn't come home last
night and I'm worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuan Nguyen was in the same situation.
</P>
<P>
   He was looking for his brother, Tung Nguyen, 23, an Alaskan
fisherman who had gone into the bar as a customer Saturday night,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Khanh nor Tung Nguyen had turned up by late last night.
</P>
<P>
   Pira Chap, 21, who often eats at a nearby restaurant, said the
Trang Dai is known as a gang hangout.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattheis would not confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some interest in this because of some criminal
activity, but I wouldn't call it a gang hangout,'' Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   Donald O'Donnell, manager of Lincoln Bowl across the street and
two doors down from the bar, said the community and police had
worked together to reduce crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a shame for the neighborhood,'' O'Donnell said.
``This area, as far as I'm concerned, in the last several years is
on an upswing.''
</P>
<P>
   The bowling alley was closed Saturday because of July Fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
