<SLUG> BC-GLF-HARTFORD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPPER BROWNE WINS GHO 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Olin Browne's golfing dreams began when he was
19, working a summer in the bag room at New Seabury on Cape Cod.
The road became a long and twisting one, leading him through the
mini tours in Florida, the Hogan and Nike Tours, until his moment
in the sun finally came 20 years later in the most dramatic of
fashions in Sunsday's final round of the Greater Hartford Open at
the TPC at River Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   As defender Stewart Cink and Larry Mize watched from the green,
Browne lofted a sand wedge from the side of the green and watched
it roll into the cup for a birdie on the first hole of a playoff.
When Cink (67_266) missed his uphill putt from 12 feet beneath the
pin, Browne (67) had come full circle in the game to earn his first
PGA Tour victory. Mize (69) already had played his third stroke at
the end of an afternoon that saw him sitting on a four-stroke lead
as he approached the 15th tee.
</P>
<P>
   It was there he unraveled, opting to strike a 5-iron from the
tee on the par 4 296-yard hole. When it slid right and into the
trees, he ended up returning to the tee and hitting the same 5-iron
into the fairway but ended up with a 6. After Mize missed a putt
from inside 2 feet on the next hole, the heat had been turned on
full blast. Mize still could have won it, but he hit a 4-iron
second shot over the 18th green, left his third short, and missed.
They returned to the 18th tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may say 15 was the key hole, but I still could have won
the golf tournament,'' said Mize. ``I made a silly mistake on 18. I
know better. I had 189 yards to the hole. The wind's in our face.
The 4 is probably perfect under normal conditions. Maybe at the end
of the day my brain's not working right. I know better. You can hit
it over the green real easy. We talk. I never blame the caddie. I'm
the boss. I still pull the club. I'm the final decision. I hit the
shot I needed to hit. I pulled the wrong club.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink, who was at 12-under when he left the 15th tee and Mize
18-under, played the final seven holes 4-under par. ``Honestly,
when I finished 17 I didn't think I had a chance at a playoff,''
said Cink. ``Someone said Larry bogeyed 16, and after that I knew
that 17 and 18 were difficult into the wind. I gave myself a chance
for a birdie. I had hit a good 3-iron into the green. I had the
putt going straight and a little left. I know now it's a little
slower than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, whose chances seemed dashed when his tee shot on the
par-4 10th went into the trees to the left and said he ``had no
shot,'' ended up with a 6 to drop out of a share of the lead. He
birdied the par-5 13th out of a bunker and the 16th when he struck
a 7-iron to 8 feet. He ended up with virtually the same shot he had
in the playoff on the 18th and nearly holed it. ``I had to ease it
up over a hump,'' said Browne. ``It bent a little more. This was
more uphill and less left to right. As a result of where I chipped
from earlier, I had a good idea what it was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne's best previous finish was a tie for fourth in Tucson
seven years ago but he gained a dose of confidence when he finished
tied for fifth in the US Open last year at Congressional. ``I'm not
sure I'll know how it feels until tomorrow or later,'' he said.
``I'm obviously exceedingly pleased and excited at the moment.''
The chip? ``It looked good, then it hit the pin and dropped. A
magical moment.'' This was a moment that rewarded all the work and
desire to excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game teaches you resilience and it teaches you to accept
defeat,'' said Browne. ``It's a hard thing for an athlete to do. If
you hit one great shot, you have 10 mediocre shots and five
horrible ones. The learning process is so demanding, and the
learning curve is so extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Through 20 sometimes struggling years, Browne learned well.
</P>
</TEXT>
