<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O. ANIBAL AYALA, 71, INTERNATIONAL BANKER 
ALEXANDER WAUGH, 90, NEW JERSEY JUDGE 
CALEB SAMPSON, 45, FILM SCORE COMPOSER 
MAURICE SORRELL, 84, NEWS PHOTOGRAPHER 
ERROL PARKER, 72, JAZZ DRUMMER AND PIANIST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Md., N.Y., Paraguay, France, Algeria)   (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Oscar Anibal Ayala, an economist who helped start the
Inter-American Development Bank in 1959, died June 22 at Georgetown
University Medical Center in Washington. Ayala, who was born in
Paraguay and lived in Alexandria, Va., for more than 40 years, was
71.
 &HT;    The cause of death was pancreatic cancer, said Nivea N. Ayala,
his wife.
 &HT;    Ayala was the first to serve as under secretary at the
Inter-American Development Bank, which arranges development loans
for member governments and for private investment and advises
members on financial issues. The bank was started by the United
States and 18 Latin American and Caribbean countries and now has 46
members.
 &HT;    Ayala left the bank in 1986 to become a financial consultant.
 &HT;    Before 1959, he worked as an economist and census director in
Paraguay and studied at the American University in Washington,
where he received master's and doctoral degrees in economics.
 &HT;    He immigrated to the United States in 1955 and worked in the
economic research division at the Organization of American States
until he helped start the development bank. He received a master's
degree in business administration from Loyola College in Baltimore
in 1980.
 &HT;    Ayala is survived by his wife, of Alexandria, and a daughter,
Maria Mercedes Ayala of New York.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alexander P. Waugh, a retired judge of Superior Court of New
Jersey, died June 21 at his home in Chatham, N.J. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Waugh sat on the court from 1956 to 1972, hearing Essex County
cases until 1965, and from then until his retirement serving as
assignment judge for Morris, Sussex and Warren counties.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Caldwell, N.J., he received his bachelor's degree
from Columbia College in 1939, nine years after earning his law
degree at what is now Rutgers Law School in Newark, N.J. A
Republican, he served as a state assemblyman in the early 1930s and
as a municipal judge in Verona, N.J., from 1937 to 1940.
</P>
<P>
   He was mayor of Verona in 1942 when he resigned to enter the
U.S. Navy. He served in the Pacific and was discharged as a
lieutenant in 1945 but continued to serve in the Naval Reserve,
reaching the rank of lieutenant commander.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gov. Robert Meyner appointed him to Superior Court, he
was a judge of Essex County District Court and Essex County Court.
After his retirement from the bench he was in private practice at
the firm of Riker, Danzig, Scherer, Hyland &AMP; Perretti in
Morristown, N.J., until four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Waugh is survived by his wife of 55 years, Jean Martin Waugh;
two daughters, Margaret W. Howie of Florham Park, N.J., and
Catherine W. Gilbert, of Warren, N.J.; a son, Superior Court Judge
Alexander P. Waugh Jr. of Princeton, N.J.; seven grandchildren, and
a great-grandson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Caleb Sampson, a composer for films and an unusual band called
the Alloy Orchestra, who also wrote music for silent films, died
June 8 at Cambridge City Hospital in Cambridge, Mass. He was 45 and
lived in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   He committed suicide, said his wife, Kathleen Hickey.
</P>
<P>
   Using metallic junk like bedpans and truck springs for
percussion instruments, as well as keyboards and synthesizer, the
Alloy Orchestra played for six years at many international film
festivals, creating vivid, humorous music for silent film classics
like ``Nosferatu,'' ``Metropolis'' and ``Steamboat Bill Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson had written music for filmmaker Errol Morris. He
provided the soundtrack for Morris' 1997 film ``Fast, Cheap and Out
of Control.'' He had also composed music for many independent
filmmakers and animators, as well as for ``Sesame Street'' and some
HBO television specials.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Sorrell, a photographer who covered the height of the
civil rights era in the South and became the first black member of
the White House Photographers Association, died June 22 at
Providence Hospital in Washington. He was 84 and lived in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrell was a news photographer in the Washington bureau of
Johnson Publishing Co., which publishes Jet and Ebony magazines,
from 1962 until he retired in 1993. He photographed civil rights
events in the 1960s despite ``dogs snipping at my heels, tear gas,
bayonets at the back,'' he once recalled in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the White House Photographers Association in 1961
after some trouble working with other White House photographers. As
he recalled: ``They had a little thing where they would get arm in
arm and try to push me back. Once they found out that I could shoot
as well as they could, they accepted me.''
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering in Sorrell's honor in 1997, a letter from
President Clinton was read that lauded his achievements in
``capturing history on film.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Washington, went to schools there and became
fascinated by photography. He worked for years at the Federal
Bureau of Printing and Engraving and at the Defense Department, but
not as a photographer. He was a staff photographer for The
Afro-American newspaper in Washington before joining Johnson
Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Beatrice, and a sister, Lillian
Strange, of Hyannis, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jazz drummer, pianist and composer Errol Parker,
whose thick and highly arranged music doggedly confirmed African
connections in jazz, died at Cabrini Hospice in Manhattan Thursday.
He was 72 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was liver cancer, said his daughter, composer Elodie
Lauten.
</P>
<P>
   Parker was born Raphel Schecroun in Oran, Algeria, which was
then French. He fought in the French army in World War II, and in
Paris he studied sculpture at the Ecole des Beaux-Arts. A
self-taught pianist, he played with Django Reinhardt while in Paris
in his mid-'20s and later played with James Moody, Don Byas and
Kenny Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 he wrote the song ``Lorre,'' a classical-jazz piece that
became a hit in France. He moved to New York City in 1967 and
started his own record label (Sahara Records), on which he issued
more than a dozen records. He finally switched to drums to realize
his vision of a North African style of jazz drumming, with minimal
cymbals and a conga drum in place of snare. In 1983, he formed the
Errol Parker Tentet, one of the more innovative bands of the 1980s.
He wrote a memoir published by Cadence Books in 1995 and by
Filipacchi in France the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Parker died shortly after hearing his music performed by the
Errol Parker Tentet at St. Peter's Church, at a benefit concert on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter, he is survived by his sister,
Janine Beisson, of Gif-sur-Yvette, France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
