<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CROATIA-BLAZEVIC-     07-06 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROATIA-BLAZEVIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZEVIC MAN OF MANY SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PARIS _ There are many mysteries at the top levels of soccer,
and some of the most intricate originate where economic and social
systems have been radically altered.
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav ``Ciro'' Blazevic qualifies among the most interesting
of those mysteries. On the surface, he is a multi-lingual charmer,
close friend of high-level politicians such as Croat President
Franjo Tudjman, a kind father figure to the players on the Croatia
national team. He is also a national hero after guiding the team to
Wednesday's World Cup meeting with France at Stade de France _ the
first time a nation has qualified for the semifinals in its World
Cup debut in the tournament's modern history.
</P>
<P>
   But Blazevic also has a dark side, rooted in the struggles of
the Balkans, in the wars and the treachery that have marked this
complex region.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Blazevic is the most imaginative of survivors. He has
had to be in order to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Blazevic first made his mark in this drama that is playing out
as both an expression of nationalism and sporting accomplishment by
coaching Dynamo Zagreb to the Yugoslavian championship in 1982.
Croats used this as a symbol of their desire to reassert their
identity and to create their own country, which had been considered
impossible while Josip Broz Tito ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, as Croatia continued to regard soccer as a
key element in its fight for independence, midfielder Zvonimir
Boban kicked a Serbian policeman who had been harassing a fan
during a Dynamo Zagreb-Red Star game. The photograph of Boban's
kick became a point of reference for Croats, but it also caused
Boban to be banned from the Yugoslav national team for the 1990
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   By '91, Croats had voted to secede from Yugoslavia. Tudjman
considered soccer an important vehicle for promoting the nascent
republic and named Blazevic minister of sports.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, the not insignificant matter of Blazevic's role in the
Olympique Marseille scandal jeopardized his status. Blazevic, who
had coached at Nantes, spent at least one night in a France jail
after a Marseille court discovered that routine payoffs had been
made by Olympique Marseille officials, including team president
Bernard Tapie.
</P>
<P>
   Tapie, among the most ambitious and richest of Frenchmen, spent
more than a year in prison. Blazevic escaped relatively unscathed _
fortunately for the Croatian national team and for the image of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Though Croatia has other highly qualified coaches, such as
Tomislav Ivic, the designated savior is Blazevic. He has nurtured
the current generation of players, many of whom were part of the
1987 Under-20 World Championship team while playing for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a father-son relationship with him,'' said
midfielder Alijosa Asanovic, who scored the first goal for
Croatia's national team in a 2-0 win over the US in 1990. ``If I am
sad, he is sad. If I am happy, he is also.''
</P>
<P>
   With his outgoing personality, blunt comments, and almost
surreal ability to overcome obstacles, Blazevic removes pressure
from his players. Blazevic is an excellent tactician whose 3-5-2
alignment has frustrated opponents, and a master motivator.
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss journalist who spends summers fishing in Montana made
the unsolicited claim Sunday that the US national team should hire
Blazevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the best soccer coach in the world, the best teacher of
the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Blazevic's off-field controversies, the journalist
said: ``Maybe he is mafia. But if you want the best, it is
Blazevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazevic as US national team coach is a longshot at best. But if
he is being excluded for reasons unrelated to coaching ability, it
raises questions about what standards Blazevic should be judged by.
Should Blazevic be condemned for not having a Pollyanna background?
</P>
<P>
   ``My two brothers died for Croatia during the Second World
War,'' Blazevic said in a recent interview with Libertion in
Croatia's headquarters in Vittel, in the Vosges region. ``And my
mother died, also, from grief. Me, I had a terrible childhood in
which I had to deal with Hitler fascists.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, Blazevic became a pragmatist. Born in Bosnia, he
travels on a Swiss passport after having coached in Switzerland. He
mixes humor and irony, and an astrologer's predictions, in
assessing his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be coach of this team as long as I live,'' Blazevic
told Zdravko Reic of World Soccer. ``It's written in the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   But the astrologer also predicted that Blazevic could suffer a
heart attack while sitting on the bench during the World Cup.
Judging by Blazevic's past, it would take more than that to keep
him down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
