<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HAPPY WITH WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Revolution coach Thomas Rongen stood in the steamy
visitors locker room of Houlihan's Stadium late Saturday night, his
shirt drenched in sweat, his necktie pulled apart, sporting a weary
smile. It had been quite some time _ nine games, to be precise _
since he last enjoyed a Major League Soccer victory.
</P>
<P>
   But, after watching his team match its own league record for
futility with those nine straight losses, Rongen and the Revolution
rekindled that winning feeling with a rousing 3-2 victory over the
Tampa Bay Mutiny on a sweltering Fourth of July evening before a
crowd of 22,704.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Kansas City (where New England suffered a 1-0 setback
Wednesday night), we knew we had played well and it would be just a
matter of time before we turned it around,'' said Rongen. ``The
manner in which we did _ going up twice, and them tying the game,
and then for us just to hang in there in a very humid environment
that really takes a lot out of a team _ speaks volumes. I didn't
stop believing and they didn't stop believing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Revolution, Raul Diaz-Arce never stopped
believing either.
</P>
<P>
   After Ivan McKinley broke a scoreless stalemate in the 53d
minute with his first goal of the season, Diaz-Arce rallied his
team with a pair of tie-breaking goals. He broke a 1-1 deadlock
with a penalty kick in the 75th minute _ that resulted from the
red-card ejection of Mutiny goalkeeper Thomas Ravelli _ then
tallied the winner in the 84th minute by converting a pass from
Oscar Pareja.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I never had my doubts,'' said Diaz-Arce, who surpassed
Joe-Max Moore (11 goals in 1996) as the team's leader for goals in
a season with his 12th and 13th. ``I believed in this team. I
believed that if we stayed together we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravelli's ejection came after he kicked the ball at referee
Ruben Rodhas, who was busier than a Vegas blackjack dealer in
dishing out eight yellow cards and two red cards. Rodhas flashed
the other red at Revolution midfielder Imad Baba, who was banished
in the 89th minute for violent conduct after he threw a ball at the
head of Tampa defender Chris Houser. Baba and Ravelli will miss
their next games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the league will understand that I didn't do it
deliberately,'' Ravelli said. ``I tried to tell the referee that I
didn't mean to do it, but he didn't want to hear me. It's sad when
something like that happens. It feels like everything is against us
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution could relate. But Saturday night they finally
turned the tables in scoring a victory that carried with it many
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to snapping their losing streak, the Revolution
scored their first road victory in 18 games vs. Eastern Conference
opponents and won for the first time in five visits to Tampa. They
also climbed back into the playoff picture by improving to 5-12
overall (good for 13 points in the standings) and leapfrogging over
Tampa (4-13) and Miami (6-12), with 12 points apiece. New England
moved from sixth to fourth place in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggested to the guys that it's a brand new season,''
Rongen said. ``I told the guys, `We've got 16 games left, so let's
pretend this is the break and here's where it's going to start.' I
think we played that way. We really played like we weren't going to
lose. On this level, it's all about overcoming adversity, and only
good teams can do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
