<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS CLAIMS 5TH CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Pete Sampras did it again Sunday, winning his second
consecutive Wimbledon singles championship, the fifth time he's
taken the world's most important tennis crown, tying him with Bjorn
Borg for most in the open era.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras beat Goran Ivanisevic, 6-7 (2-7), 7-6 (11-9), 6-4, 3-6,
6-2, in a match that lasted 2 hours 52 minutes, and his victory
enabled the 26-year-old to retain the No. 1 world ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras picked up a check for $722,000 and Ivanisevic pocketed
$361,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras now has 11 Grand Slam titles, more than any other active
player, and he's now one from tying Roy Emerson's record of 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time for it to sink in, but it's a bit
overwhelming to have won five and be a couple from the record,''
Sampras said. ``It's really hard to talk about. It's overwhelming
to think of myself in those terms. I've always tried to stay humble
through all my accomplishments. It's hard to believe (tying) Borg's
five; I thought that would never be broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a lot of years left in me. This is like the
Super Bowl. This is what the game is all about to me. But I'm not
thinking much about next year. I just want to try to enjoy this. As
a kid, when I saw Borg's five, I never thought that I would be in a
position to tie it, and it's a little overwhelming to think about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has won a Grand Slam title every year since 1993, and
now has 55 career singles titles. This was his third this year, to
go with wins in Philadelphia and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to all the finals I've played, this is by far the
toughest,'' Sampras said, ``but all Wimbledons are very, very
sweet. This one _ I didn't think I was quite in control of the
match, and Goran was playing huge _ and the fifth set was really
anyone's ballgame. There's not really much that separates us, just
a couple of points here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who had only 12 aces to Ivanisevic's 32, believed he
was fortunate to take the second-set tie-breaker, when the
Croatian's serve-and-volley forehand landed long, setting up a
service winner to the forehand for Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   That was especially important since Ivanisevic had won the first
set by tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second set tie-breaker was a huge part of the match,''
Sampras said. ``There was a shot that he missed by about an inch.
He converts on one of those and it's two sets to love and I'm
digging myself a big hole to come back. It takes a little luck to
come back, especially this one in the final.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the fifth set. Ivanisevic, going for his
first Grand Slam title after having lost in the final here in 1992
and 1994, grew tired, possibly carryover from defeating Richard
Krajicek, 15-13, in the fifth set of Friday's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He raised his game in the fifth, but I was getting slower and
he could return better on my serves,'' said Ivanisevic. ``If I had
gone up, 2-0, that's a different story. I don't think he would have
come back, no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, indeed, began doing better on Ivanisevic's serves in
the fifth, chipping them back. With Ivanisevic slower in getting to
the net, it was easier to pass him.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also believed it was to his advantage that he got to
serve first in the fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big mental advantage,'' he said. ``You're always a game
up, and you feel like if you break him you're up three games. It's
not a huge part of the match, but it certainly helps to start
serving the fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said he had no idea that Ivanisevic was getting worn
out, however. But he broke Ivanisevic twice in the fifth set, in
the sixth and eighth games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of a weird feeling but, you know, this is what
the game is all about,'' Sampras said. ``We're two heavy hitters
going at it and one of us is going to win and I was fortunate
enough to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``His serve was still coming in real big. The fifth set of a
Wimbledon final, you just have to suck it up as best you can, but
he's played a lot of tennis over the past three or four days. Maybe
that took its toll, but I didn't sense him getting tired at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
