<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GIULIANI-FIRST-AME     07-06 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-FIRST-AMENDMENT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S GOAL OF CIVIL CITY RUNS INTO FIRST AMENDMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-GIULIANI-FIRST-AMENDMENT-SUM, sidebar on judicial
decisions stemming from lawsuits against the city). 
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his pursuit of a ``civilized'' New York of
small-scale protests and huckster-free sidewalks, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani keeps bumping up against the First Amendment and getting
bruised.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional guarantee of free expression and assembly has
been invoked in about a dozen lawsuits that successfully challenged
the mayor's most cherished quality-of-life initiatives and in
reaction to his often testy confrontations with critics.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is deploying a phalanx of police officers to block a
taxi drivers' protest, charging higher fees for the right to
operate a newsstand or relegating sex shops to industrial zones,
Giuliani has seen his administration accused of trading New York's
boisterous tradition of free speech for a quieter but less colorful
urban landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have not passed judgment on the mayor's vision for
the city or on his temperament, although a federal appeals court
judge did poke fun at him for objecting to a bus advertisement for
New York magazine that used his name.
</P>
<P>
   But with one major exception _ the sex shop zoning law, upheld
by a federal appeals court last month _ they have found fault with
the way the city regulates activities protected by the First
Amendment. Two weeks ago, the sex shop owners asked the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for a rehearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give him credit for a lot of things, but I think he is
plainly far less sensitive to First Amendment concerns,'' said
Richard D. Emery, a lawyer who has brought two free-speech lawsuits
against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's office did not respond to requests for an interview.
But the mayor, a former federal prosecutor, is clearly riled at the
frequently voiced suggestions that both his style and his
substantive programs lack proper respect for the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent news conference, for example, a reporter asked the
mayor how he would respond to those who say he wants to quash
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wrong,'' the mayor curtly replied.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment lawsuits and less-formal complaints against
the Giuliani administration fall into two broad categories. One
concerns the mayor's attitude to dissent (vindictive, critics say).
The other focuses on the inevitable tension between a government
trying to manage public spaces and people seeking to parade,
protest, preach and pitch their wares on public property.
</P>
<P>
   Such issues are not unique to New York or to this
administration, Giuliani's lawyers say, nor is the mayor breaking,
or losing, new ground. Former Mayor Ed Koch, for example, fought a
free-speech challenge to a city law that required performers at the
Central Park band shell to use city sound-control technicians. The
U.S. Supreme Court upheld the law. Under former Mayor David
Dinkins, the city tried to stop the Learning Annex, an adult
education program, from installing newspaper boxes on sidewalks but
eventually lost that case on First Amendment grounds.
</P>
<P>
   If Giuliani appears to land in court on such issues more often,
it is only because he is an aggressive and engaged manager, said
Lorna Bade Goodman, a spokeswoman for the city's Law Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Law Department has been very busy under Giuliani,'' she
said. ``He has an idea a day. He is really a very active, active
public administrator, constantly thinking about new problems and
areas for city government to tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to establish exactly how many of the 8,000
lawsuits filed annually against the city raise First Amendment
issues. What sets Giuliani's record apart from the record of his
predecessors is that free-speech lawsuits repeatedly challenge the
laws at the center of the mayor's most high-profile programs.
Neither Koch nor Dinkins provoked anything close to the number of
free-speech lawsuits in state and federal courts, civil liberties
lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 13 years, and my legal director has been here
even longer, and we've never filed as many cases involving one
administration,'' said Norman Siegel, executive director of the New
York Civil Liberties Union, which staged an Independence Day rally
on the steps of City Hall to spotlight its continuing First
Amendment battles with the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel's organization has weighed in, either as counsel or in
friend-of-the-court briefs, in 12 lawsuits against the
administration that involve free-speech issues. They include the
taxi drivers' complaint last month over Giuliani's blockade of
their protest, two cases challenging city rules prohibiting
employees from talking to the news media and a lawsuit by a church
in the South Bronx that saw its AIDS education program kicked out
of a city park. The plaintiffs prevailed in each of those cases,
although the city has appeals pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``His vision is a new New York,'' Siegel said, ``and it's a
vision that is more authoritarian, repressive and antithetical to
our rich tradition of tolerance for the right to protest and
dissent. It's inconsistent with what the city has been.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Republican mayor in a generation, Giuliani rode to
office in 1994 on a wave of popular disgust _ with crime and the
perceived tyranny of panhandlers, homeless people and thugs who
seemed to have taken over the city's parks and sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   A nonpolitician in a job traditionally held by men who rose step
by step through the political ranks, he spoke about improving New
Yorkers' quality of life and carried a big stick, aggressively
enforcing existing city regulations and initiating new regulations
of his own to clear the sidewalks, reduce noise and lessen
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His targets fought back. A street musician who was charged $45
for a one-day permit to perform filed suit, arguing that the city
charged too much for regulating an activity protected by the First
Amendment. A federal judge agreed, and the city is now studying its
permit fees. A sidewalk artist shooed away by the police for not
having a permit also filed suit. The case went to a federal appeals
court, which said that selling art is also an activity protected by
the First Amendment. The city can license artists, but it must
stick to the stricter standards that federal courts require when
regulating speech and expression. The Supreme Court declined to
hear the city's appeal, letting the ruling stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Giuliani striking out on a new urban path here?'' asked
Myron Magnet, editor of City Journal, a publication of the
conservative Manhattan Institute, which urges the mayor to battle
on against other urban scourges like earsplitting car alarms and
rude public servants. ``I would say he is returning to an old one.
All that Giuliani is doing in his civility campaign is to try to
take back those public places that were hijacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery, the First Amendment lawyer, had a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say Giuliani is trying to redefine the public space,''
he said, ``but he's also just striking out.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this century, federal courts have provided plenty of
judicial guidance to governments in how far they can go in
reasonably limiting the time, place and manner of activities that
are protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The basic rule is that any restriction must be neutral regarding
the content of the expression, it must serve a specific government
purpose, and it must leave open ample alternative channels of
communication.
</P>
<P>
   In recent New York City cases, judges have faulted the Giuliani
administration for not completely meeting those standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the newsstand case, for example, a federal judge criticized a
regulation giving the city unfettered power to terminate a
newsstand operator's concession without a hearing. That could
induce a news vendor to censor the materials he sells out of fear
of offending city officials, the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of judicial rulings against New York City mirrors
the national trend, said Robert C. Post, a law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley who has written extensively on
the issue of public spaces and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole,'' he said, ``the courts have been sympathetic to
speech and unsympathetic to giving too much discretion to
politicians who want to enforce bourgeois norms in public space.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's singlemindedness when it comes to his anticongestion
campaign is both his strength and his weakness, say urban affairs
experts and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an enforcer, and he's defining laws more narrowly than a
healthy community would define them,'' said Fred I. Kent III,
president of Project for Public Spaces, a nonprofit group based in
New York that advises cities nationwide on how to revive and
nurture their neighborhoods. ``His quality-of-life program _ it is
mostly good, but you have to define your parameters and let
creativity come out. I don't think he knows what the limits are.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent said that Giuliani's plan to reduce congestion by banning
vendors of food and general merchandise from large swaths of
midtown and the financial district in Manhattan might be an example
of exceeding the limits and passing into the realm of urban
sterility. It is a plan that raises not only First Amendment
questions _ since it would encompass sellers of written material _
but also basic questions about the mayor's vision of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's missing something very important _ a good street
with a lot of activity on it is self-controlling,'' Kent said.
``Street life is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Giuliani often staked out the more extreme approach to
regulating the use of public space. His original zoning plan for
keeping sex shops out of residential areas was more drastic than
the law finally approved by the City Council and upheld as
constitutional on June 3 by a three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals. Similarly, his vendor-control plan is
much more sweeping than one developed by the city's 40 business
improvement districts, which endorse opening up additional streets
to vendors but assigning each one a street corner.
</P>
<P>
   In his zeal to insure the free flow of traffic and pedestrians,
Giuliani also recently declared that no more than 30 people may
assemble at one time on the steps of City Hall, a favored venue for
the news conferences and photo opportunities of some of Giuliani's
political adversaries. The mayor said he was only reviving a
longstanding police rule intended to preserve order at the entrance
to City Hall, but his edict set off a predictable chorus of
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of Saturday's rally staged on the City Hall steps by
the New York Civil Liberties Union, Siegel sent a letter to the
Police Department informing it of the Independence Day
demonstration. The city responded that it would ``authorize'' 35 to
50 speakers, but the civil liberties union wrote back that he had
written to the Police Department only as a courtesy, not as a
request for permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position,'' the group wrote, ``is that individuals wishing
to hold press conferences on the steps of City Hall need not seek
nor obtain the permission of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Hall rule has been ignored for ceremonies on the steps
that are approved by Giuliani, including awards ceremonies for
firefighters and for David Wells, the Yankees pitcher. It has been
applied, however, to many of Giuliani's political adversaries,
among them state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, who tried to make an
announcement there and was banished with his audience of 30-plus
people to City Hall Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of selective enforcement that makes you
vulnerable to First Amendment accusations,'' said Gene Russianoff,
senior attorney for the New York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, however, is not the first mayor to abruptly invoke the
mantra of public order when he is irritated with crowds of
lobbyists and protesters on the City Hall steps. Russianoff
recalled a time during the Koch administration when the
Straphangers Campaign, a public-advocacy group, brought a big
roulette wheel to the steps as a prop for a news conference about
subway safety. A police officer, improvising on the spot, told them
to leave, saying City Hall could not be photographed with a game of
chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
