<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-FIRST-AMENDMENT-SUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMARY OF FIRST AMENDMENT CASES AGAINST CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-GIULIANI-FIRST-AMENDMENT) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following is a summary of judicial decisions stemming from some
of the First Amendment lawsuits brought against the Giuliani
administration.
</P>
<P>
   DEMONSTRATIONS: A federal judge said in May that the city
violated the First Amendment rights of taxi drivers by refusing to
permit more than 20 drivers to assemble for a protest. The city is
appealing the granting of a preliminary injunction. A request for a
permanent injunction is pending in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   SEX SHOPS: The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in upholding a
lower court decision, said city zoning laws to prevent sex shops
from clustering in residential areas do not violate the shop
owners' First Amendment rights. The sex shop owners have petitioned
the court for a rehearing.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEWALK ARTISTS: Saying that artists enjoy the same First
Amendment protection as vendors of written material, a federal
appeals court found the city's licensing regulations for sidewalk
artists unconstitutional. The U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear
the city's appeal on that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   A group of artists filed a new lawsuit in March that challenges,
on First Amendment grounds, a separate Department of Parks and
Recreation rule requiring artists to obtain a permit to display
their works in front of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The museum
sidewalk is under the department's jurisdiction. That case is
pending in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, a federal district judge said the city's
$45-a-day permit for street musicians did not meet the standards
for regulating a First Amendment-protected activity. The fee is
excessive, the judge said, and does not accurately reflect the
city's cost to administer the permit program. The city has
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTANDS: The U.S. District Court for the Eastern District
said that operating a newsstand is a First Amendment activity and
that regulations give the city too much leeway to terminate a
newsstand concession. The judge said a state court must rule on a
separate claim by the newsstand operators that the city's new fee
schedule for newsstand concessions is unconstitutional. The city
has not decided whether it will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLE-BLOWERS: The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said in
March that city rules barring employees from talking to reporters
infringe on the employees' First Amendment rights. The decision
stems from lawsuits filed by the Latino Officers Association and by
a former supervisor in the Administration for Children's Services
who was fired after speaking to a reporter. The city's Law
Department said it would ask the Supreme Court to hear an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ACCESS TO PARKS: The Appellate Division upheld a state court
decision that found that the Department of Parks and Recreation
violated the First Amendment rights of the All Saints Lutheran
Parish when it prevented the church's AIDS education project from
demonstrating and distributing condoms in a South Bronx park. The
city did not appeal.
</P>
<P>
   BUS ADS: A federal judge said the city and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority violated the First Amendment when it
removed New York magazine's ads from buses at the request of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who was lampooned in the ads. On appeal in the
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, the city was dismissed from the
case but the ruling was upheld against the transportation
authority, which may still appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
