<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ROCKINGHAM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOVATE ENJOYS ROCKINGHAM TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
 BREEDERS CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ Grass races, run on tight inner courses, are all
about trips. In a nine-horse field that contains only two
legitimate contenders, whichever of the top two gets the best trip
will win, and that's how Innovate defeated Heaven's Command in the
$79,300 Rockingham Park Breeders' Cup Handicap Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The race shaped up as Innovate, the 2-1 ($6.60 to win) second
choice, vs. Heaven's Command, the 3-5 favorite, in a field rounded
out by seven overmatched locals. Innovate, ridden by Frank Lovato,
had a perfect outside trip from post No. 6, got the jump on
Heaven's Command, who had to swing out five-wide for the drive
under Chris DeCarlo, and held the odds-on pick safe to the wire.
Innovate, who had a 2-length lead at the eighth-pole, prevailed by
three-quarters of a length in 1:44 4/5 for a mile and one-16th over
the firm grass course. Sandy Gator, the best of the horses based at
Rock, was along in time to be third under Rudy Baez, a length and
one-quarter farther back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trip was clean, that was the winning difference,'' said
Lovato, who rode Innovate for the first time. ``I got the setup. My
filly was pretty fresh. She was a little sharper than her form
might indicate. I was clear on the outside. Heaven's Command was
behind a couple of horses. I was afraid that she might get through,
but she didn't. I had to have the horse to do it. Innovate put me
in the position I had to be in. She gave me a big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Innovate, a 4-year-old daughter of Relaunch, is trained by noted
New York conditioner H. James Bond and owned by William Clifton and
Rudlein Stable. Innovate was defeated by Heaven's Command in the
Columbiana Handicap at Hialeah May 2, the last time Innovate ran.
However, it was discovered that Innovate was suffering from an
entrapped epiglottis and she underwent laser surgery to correct the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``She threw her head up during the stretch run of the Columbiana
and we knew something was wrong,'' said Carlos Correa, assistant
trainer for Bond. ``We had her 'scoped and found the problem. She's
been doing great since then and she was right for this race,
believe me. Heaven's Command beat her last time but our filly was
having trouble breathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innovate also had a shoulder problem last year that came back
and bothered her again this year. She's had her problems, but when
we have her right, she's a nice filly. I believe we'll be back for
the Spicy Living (Aug. 2). She didn't race too hard today and she
likes this course. When the other filly came to her, she still had
a lot left. We'll be back. We like coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   DeCarlo blamed a slow break from post No. 3 for the problems of
Heaven's Command, who is trained by Christophe Clement, and she did
break last. Still, she was trapped behind four horses turning for
home after trying to get up the rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was my horse didn't break,'' said DeCarlo, who
was riding Heaven's Command for the first time. ``I didn't get the
position I wanted. Chris told me that she usually breaks pretty
hard but she didn't come out today. I didn't have the greatest of
trips but I definitely think the break beat me. It was one of those
things. I thought I had a shot at Innovate at the quarter-pole but,
when I got to within three-quarters of a length, Innovate just
stayed there and I knew I was in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our horse moved a little too late,'' said Nicholas Balachard,
assistant trainer for Clement. ``She had to be swung to the
outside. That's the way it goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
