<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MONARCH OF CENTER COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 6:
</P>
<P>
   This has been a vintage year for fans who appreciate great,
seasoned athletes performing brilliantly in the hallmark
competition of their sport. First there was John Elway, the Denver
Bronco quarterback, leading his team to a Super Bowl victory, the
first of his distinguished career. Then Michael Jordan propelled
the Chicago Bulls to another National Basketball Association
championship. Sunday, it was Pete Sampras' turn. He dispatched
Goran Ivanisevic in a difficult five-set match to win his fifth
Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
   Like Elway and Jordan, Sampras is the rare athlete who can lift
a game to a new level of excellence and keep it there for years. He
couples the power of previous players like Pancho Gonzalez and Jack
Kramer with the finesse of John McEnroe, a combination that has now
produced 11 Grand Slam titles. Only Roy Emerson, the skillful
Australian player of several decades ago, has won more Grand Slam
men's titles. Sampras is one behind, along with Rod Laver, the
great Australian player, and Bjorn Borg, the groundstroke master
from Sweden. At Wimbledon, the only man besides Sampras to win five
titles in the modern era was Borg.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who is 26, ought to set a new standard for Grand Slam
victories before his career ends. Even when his sizzling first
serve is not landing consistently, the case Sunday, he can still
carve the court with pinpoint volleys and a powerful baseline game
that he uses sparingly but effectively. There is no better
all-around player.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, a Croat, can uncork even faster serves than Sampras,
some topping 130 miles an hour, but he still lacks the stroke
repertoire necessary to win at Wimbledon, even in a
serve-and-volley showdown. Too many of his volleys Sunday slapped
into the net or carried beyond the baseline. In the second-set tie
breaker, the pivotal juncture of the match, Ivanisevic simply could
not equal the determination and steely nerves of Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras was making room for himself in the pantheon of
men's tennis, Jana Novotna won her first Wimbledon title. It was an
especially sweet victory for the Czech veteran who had won no Grand
Slam singles championships. Twice before she made the Wimbledon
final but lost. Like the men's final, her match with Nathalie
Tauziat of France was a serve-and-volley contest.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis connoisseurs who prefer the intricate strategy and
sustained tension of baseline play did not find much to savor in
the Wimbledon finals. That is nothing new on the grass courts.
Still, it was a good fortnight of tennis. One of the finest players
ever to take the court put on a show to remember.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 0151EDT &QL; 
