<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMATEUR'S 45-FOOT PUTT FORCES A PLAYOFF WITH PAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ By the time Jenny Chuasiriporn reached the 18th
green at the U.S. Women's Open Sunday, she had already accomplished
more than anyone had expected. There she was, a 20-year-old amateur
between her junior and senior years at Duke University, facing a
birdie putt from around 45 feet to tie Se Ri Pak for first place
and force an 18-hole playoff on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Only one amateur has ever won the women's Open, Catherine
Lacoste of France in 1967. And considering the pressure of the
moment, and the length of the putt, the odds against Chuasiriporn
finding a way to make it were great.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, she did it. In a moment that will be etched in
Chuasiriporn's mind for a lifetime, she made a textbook stroke,
watched the ball roll slowly across the green, then covered her
mouth in disbelief as the putt dropped while her 21-year-old caddie
and brother, Joey, ran to give her a triumphant high-five. ``The
last 15 feet, my eyes probably popped out because it was going
straight in,'' Chuasiriporn said. ``I didn't expect it to go in at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak and Chuasiriporn, both 20, will play on Monday thanks to an
incredible fourth-round finish that unfolded Sunday at Blackwolf
Run golf course. Pak, who shot a 5-over-par 76, and Chuasiriporn,
who shot a courageous 72, finished four rounds of emotionally
draining golf tied at 6-over-par 290 for the tournament, one stroke
ahead of Liselotte Neumann (291), who did not make a birdie while
shooting a 76 and whose final chance to join the playoff ended when
she missed a 90-foot putt for birdie at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, playing in the group behind Chuasiriporn, was standing on
the tee box at No. 18 when she heard the gallery erupt, reacting to
Chuasiriporn's putt. Now it was Pak's chance to try for a birdie at
No. 18, which would have won the tournament. But Pak could not
deliver. After hitting a solid drive, followed by an accurate
approach shot, Pak was left with a putt for birdie from around 9
feet. But it slid just right of the hole, and after Pak tapped in
for par, it was assured that a dramatic championship, filled with
improbable twists and turns, would continue for another day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Who can predict what will happen? Will Pak, who won the LPGA
McDonald's Championship in May, become the first LPGA Tour rookie
since Juli Inkster in 1984 to win two majors in the same year? Or
will Chuasiriporn, an effervescent psychology major from Baltimore,
become the first amateur in 31 years to win the national women's
championship? The answer will unfold Monday, and Chuasiriporn, who
had checked out of her hotel, will have to check back in. But for
both players, the ride to get to this point has been thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy,'' said Pak, who reached the 17th tee holding a
two-stroke lead but bogeyed that hole, opening the door for
Chuasiriporn. ``I do my best tomorrow, same thinking. I don't want
money, but I want the trophy.'' No matter what happens Monday, Pak,
who started the fourth round with a one-stroke lead over Mhairi
McKay and Neumann, will see the money. As an amateur, Chuasiriporn
is not eligible for the $267,500 first-place prize.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, an outstanding collegiate player who won the
Atlantic Coast Conference title the past two seasons, will become
far more familiar to golf fans, however. Her parents, originally
from Thailand, own a restaurant in Timonium, Md., called the
Bangkok Place, where Chuasiriporn washed dishes as a child. But the
restaurant was closed all last week, and it will be closed again
Monday, so that Chuasiriporn's parents can watch proudly from the
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn said that win or lose, she will return to Duke for
her senior year. If she does win, she will be eligible for an
automatic one-year exemption for the LPGA Tour in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pressure, Chuasiriporn has taken time to enjoy the
moment. While playing No. 16, she stopped to notice former
President George Bush walking through the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about to hit my second shot, I turned to Joey, and I'm
like, `There's George Bush down there,''' she said. ``Joey was
like, `Are you going to hit the shot or what?'''
</P>
<P>
   With admirable poise and a flair for the dramatic, Chuasiriporn
managed to catch Pak despite starting the day tied for fourth
place, four strokes off the lead. Her 72 was the second-best score
of the day, topped only by the 71s shot by Danielle Ammaccapane and
Hollis Stacy. For the second consecutive day, nobody broke par, and
while the wind was calmer than it was on Saturday, tougher pin
placements and final-round pressure made this another severe test
of skill.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn passed like a veteran, making only three bogeys and
avoiding the double-bogeys or worse that sank so many others. After
four consecutive pars, she bogeyed No. 5, but she responded with a
birdie at No. 8, making a 25-foot putt, a sign of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Chuasiriporn reached the 13th tee, she was leading
the tournament, one stroke ahead of Pak, who struggled on the front
nine, shooting a 5-over 40. Pak double-bogeyed No. 3 after she
pulled her drive into the deep rough. She bogeyed No. 8, missing a
6-foot putt. Then she bogeyed No. 9, hitting her second shot into
the water, after her drive landed in the rough. Meanwhile, making
seven consecutive pars from No. 8 through No. 14, Chuasiriporn
remained in control, while many other contenders faltered. Chris
Johnson stayed close for a while, but a double-bogey at No. 14 and
a bogey at No. 16 ruined her chance for victory; she faded to a tie
for fourth at 292. McKay never fully recovered from two holes, a
triple-bogey at No. 7 and a double-bogey at No. 11, shooting a 78
and finishing tied for seventh at 293.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 0205EDT &QL; 
