<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TOMFOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKER'S GOLD WINS IN PHOTO FINISH AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ For the fourth time in 15 years, a horse trained
by Allen Jerkens won the Tom Fool Handicap at Belmont Park Sunday,
but this time, he cut it tantalizingly close. Banker's Gold edged
Boundless Moment and Partner's Hero in a three-horse photo finish
after a furious rush to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   They hurtled down the homestretch past the odds-on favorite,
Richter Scale, who had held the lead with his natural speed until
they turned for home. Then, as Richter Scale surrendered his lead,
it was a 200-yard race to decide a winner. And in a driving finish,
Banker's Gold prevailed by a head over Boundless Moment, who held
second place by a head over Partner's Hero.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scramble, it was one length back to Western Borders,
and then five long lengths back to Richter Scale, who had won his
last two races and six of nine overall.
</P>
<P>
   Banker's Gold, a 4-year-old son of Forty Niner, scored for the
first time since February after running second in the Carter and
Metropolitan Handicaps in his last two starts. Jerkens said he was
relieved the colt closed the gap from second to first, and added:
``His last three races have all been good ones, and it's really
nice to finally win one. He was in good position, and, when he made
the lead, my main concern was that he tends to fool around when
he's in front. But he got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   He got the job done because Richter Scale suddenly faded in the
stretch, and Boundless Moment and Partner's Hero were breathing
down his neck. Jockey Jerry Bailey even had positioned Richter
Scale on the rail, where he had won the True North Handicap last
month. ``But,'' Bailey reported, ``he just didn't finish the way he
did in his last two wins, for whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jorge Chavez, the rider on Banker's Gold, wasn't counting
his money yet, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went past Richter Scale,'' he said, ``I thought I moved
too soon because it looked like Jerry wasn't even moving his hands.
But when I realized his horse was stopping, I thought I was home
free at the 16th pole until I saw that horse coming on the outside.
Thankfully, we just had enough to hold him off.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant Boundless Moment. And soon another late intruder,
Partner's Hero, who had also been running at the back of the pack,
made a move, and it took a photo to sort them out.
</P>
<P>
   Banker's Gold, who is owned by Georgia Hofmann, has won 6-of-13
races and has run in the money 10 times. He ran the seven furlongs
in 1 minute 21 seconds, paid $6.60 for a $2 bet to win and earned
$90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jerkens said the next race for Banker's Gold would probably be
the Whitney at Saratoga on Aug. 8, despite its distance of a mile
and an eighth, and added, ``I think he can go a lot farther, if you
can rate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mott, Richter Scale's trainer, said his horse did not seem
to be troubled by the cracked hoof that had bothered him in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any excuse as far as the running of the race
goes,'' he said. ``He seemed to be comfortable with everything
going into this race.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES:
</P>
<P>
   After you break a world record, what can you do for an encore?
Elusive Quality, the 5-year-old horse who broke the world record
for the mile Saturday while winning the Poker Handicap in 1:31 3/5,
has one ultimate goal: the Breeders' Cup Mile on the grass at
Churchill Downs on Nov. 7. His trainer, Bill Mott, said his horse
seemed to be thriving on grass since he switched in May and won two
straight. The only question was how far he could run that fast.
``You have to think he can do it, especially if the grass is
helping him get the mile,'' Mott said. ``He won the first time out
of the box at a mile and a sixteenth, but the more we ran him, the
shorter he got. The question was if he could go a Breeders' Cup
type of mile. But that looks like a question he just answered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
