<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-HARTFORD-425&AMP;ADD-     07-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HARTFORD-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNE CAPTURES HARTFORD AFTER A FADE BY MIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ With four consecutive birdies having propelled
him into a four-stroke lead with four holes to play, former Masters
champion Larry Mize seemed destined to end a five-year victory
drought Sunday in the Canon Greater Hartford Open.
</P>
<P>
   But an errant tee shot, a missed 2-foot putt, an overshot green
and a potentially tournament-winning 15-foot putt that suddenly
broke left erased Mize's lead over those four holes to force a
playoff with defending champion Stewart Cink and Olin Browne.
</P>
<P>
   After another bad drive into a fairway bunker on the first
playoff hole, the 444-yard, par-4 18th, Mize soon fell out of
contention. Meanwhile, Cink appeared en route to a repeat victory
when his approach shot landed within 15 feet of the flag and Browne
landed on the left fringe, 40 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old Browne then electrified the huge throng on the
natural amphitheater surrounding the 18th hole when he chipped in
for a birdie to win his first tournament. Browne's victory was
sealed when the 25-year-old Cink's attempt at a birdie missed to
the left by about 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his mind-set was before his winning chip shot _ which
he virtually had to make if he were to win the tournament on the
first playoff hole _ Browne, said: ``I was pretty sure he would
make the putt. I had a good bead on the hole, and I just wanted to
make the best shot I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne's triumph, which earned him $360,000, marked the second
year in a row that a nonwinner on the PGA Tour had achieved a
breakthrough on this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After his four successive birdies, Mize took a double-bogey at
the 296-yard, par-4 16th hole and a bogey at No. 16. But he parred
the 17th and went to the last hole with a one-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mize's tee shot was dead-solid perfect. But then, in what he
later described as the biggest mistake during his late collapse,
the lanky Georgian drilled a 4-iron shot over the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a stupid mistake,'' said Mize, who has won four
titles including the 1987 Masters in a 17-year professional career.
``I should have taken less club, but I was pumped up, and I think
that's what aggravates me the most. Anyway, that was the real
killer. All that other stuff earlier just happens.''
</P>
<P>
   That included his tee shot on the 296-yard, par-4 15th hole, a
5-iron that caught a branch and landed about 25 yards into a wooded
area. It cost him two penalty strokes and, eventually, a
double-bogey. He finished the day at 69; Cink and Browne each shot
a 67.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mize, whose game has fallen on hard times in recent years _ he
had only one top-10 finish in 21 tournaments in 1997 and only one
in 15 events this year _ finished at 14-under-par 266 along with
Browne and Cink, breaking the tournament record by one shot. The
runners-up each collected $176,000 from the $2 million purse.
</P>
<P>
   A stroke behind at 267 were Duffy Waldorf, Fred Funk and the
48-year-old Doug Tewell. Another stroke back was David Duval, the
leading money winner this year, who carded a 68, and Scott Hoch,
who started the final round tied with Mize and Grant Waite of New
Zealand and shot a 71.
</P>
<P>
   Until his victory Sunday, Browne's best finish had been a tie
for fourth place in a tournament four years ago. Most of his
15-year pro career had been spent on the Nike Tour, where he had
four victories between 1991 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in three days, the course record of
8-under-par 62 was tied, this time by Vijay Singh, the 35-year-old
veteran from Fiji. Singh's 28 on the back nine set a course record
and matched the low for nine holes on the PGA Tour this year. ...
The lone amateur to make the cut, J.J. Henry of Fairfield, Conn.,
who was runner-up in this year's National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament and intends to turn pro later this year,
continued his steady play. Henry, an all-American at Texas
Christian, closed with a par 70 to finish at 2-under-par 278.
</P>
</TEXT>
