<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2461 - JULY 6, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. KILLERS HAVE MORE FUN As players zoom in from around the
world, computer games like 'Ultima Online' are grand social
experiments in community building. There's just one little problem
... By Amy Jo Kim. From Wired magazine. 4,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
THE HIPPOCRATIC WARS The feisty Journal of the American Medical
Association and the staid New England Journal of Medicine are
battling for readers through an unwitting ally : the media. Is
anything being lost in the process? By Ellen Ruppel Shell. From The
New York Times Magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
FROM PROSPECT MAGAZINE (N/A U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  &QR;  HITLER TO HOLDERLIN Much has been written about the great
philosopher Martin Heidegger's involvement with the Nazis. But
Desmond Christy welcomes a new biography which refrains from hasty
judgements, and lets the life speak for itself. Heidegger's real
silence was not about Auschwitz, but about himself. 1,500 words.  &QR;  &QR; 
PORTRAIT : V.S. NAIPAUL To his critics he is an arrogant apologist
for colonialism and a cheerleader for Hindu nationalism. To his
admirers he is the finest writer in the English language and
creator of a new literary form. Jason Cowley talks to the literary
king of rootlessness and finds him content, at last, with life and
England. 4,000 words.  &QR;  &QR;  JEWS AGAINST ISRAEL Israel has reached
mature middle age. Susan Greenberg asks whether the existence of a
Jewish state has been good for the Jews. It is time to think aloud
about costs as well as benefits. Israel was meant to make Jews feel
secure, but it has made them vulnerable. 1,800 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   4. BRUCE BABBITT'S SWAMP U.S. Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt
was supposed to live above Washington's poisonous atmosphere. Now
he finds his once-pristine image contaminated by scandal. By
Charles Siebert. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo :
18h00 GMT Wednesday, July 8.)  &QR;  IS NOT SMOKING BAD FOR YOU? : When
heavy smokers quit smoking, there are many anecdotal reports and
scientific studies showing that mood, the ability to concentrate
and mental agility may be affected. But does performance in an
abstract psychological test in a lab reflect any impairment in real
day-to-day activities? New research now suggests that it does. By
Helen Phillips. 400 words.  &QR;  SIGNALLING A HEART ATTACK The main
cause of heart attacks, stroke and gangrene of the extremities is a
disease of the arteries known as atherosclerosis, where a build-up
of fatty material blocks the arteries and causes clots. Researchers
have worked out how cells communicate with each other to coordinate
plaque formation. By Helen Phillips. 500 words
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
ELLIS ISLAND : A CELEBRATION OF IMMIGRANTS' HOPE When the
immigrants to the United States got off the boat and took their
first tentative steps on Ellis Island, it was impossible to
suppress the thought : The great saga that began on this sacred
rock off New York is America's greatest story. By David M.
Shribman. Boston Globe Magazine. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
From NEW SCIENTIST (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  YOU ARE FEELING VERY, VERY SLEEPY ... Can we believe someone
who claims under hypnosis that they have forgotten their own name,
become colour blind or regressed to childhood? By David Concar.
3,000 words.  &QR;  ECHOES FROM THE DEEP : During the Gulf War, the
Allied forces ruled out a marine invasion of Kuwait because the
coastal waters could not be adequately cleared of mines. Imagine
being able to sense the underwater world as well as a dolphin can.
That's the dream of a man who is building an 'acoustic' camera that
collects sound rather than light. By Ilan Greenberg. 1,500 words.  &QR; 
FROM RUSSIA WITH LOVE : A tale of romance, fiendishly clever
gadgets and dull yellow crystals .... The extraordinary story of
the latest in memory chips. By Bob Johnstone. 1,500 words. 8.
PREDICTING YOUR GARDEN'S FUTURE : GAUGING VEGETABLE YIELDS You may
be growing vegetables - but how many can you expect, and when?
Susan McClure offers a guide to estimate vegetable yields - and
have your predictions come true. 1,400 words + photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
