<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     07-06 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 12.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ANYTHING YOUR LITTLE HEART DESIRES: AN AMERICAN FAMILY STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Bosworth. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Bartley C. Crum, the famous corporate lawyer of
the 1940s and '50s and champion of leftist causes, tracks the
dazzling arc of her father's life, including his undoing by his
personal and political furies. Last year our reviewer, Richard
Lingeman, called this a ``multilayered act of discovery and
reconciliation ... in which redemption comes from the truth of the
telling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNDERWORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Don DeLillo. Scribner, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This sprawling wake for the Cold War explores how people
rearranged their lives around the moral void of Mutual Assured
Destruction, with its attending terror and absurdity. Selected by
the editors of the Book Review as one of the best books of 1997,
the novel spans half a century, from its opening in 1951 at one of
baseball's legendary games to its epilogue in central Asia. The
characters -- both fictional and cultural heroes like Frank Sinatra
and Lenny Bruce -- are psychological fallout victims. ``
`Underworld' surges with magisterial confidence,'' Martin Amis said
here last year. ``It isn't every day, or even every decade, that
one sees the ascension of a great writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESURRECTION: THE STRUGGLE FOR A NEW RUSSIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David Remnick. Vintage, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The author argues that the Russian people have had their fill of
Boris Yeltsin and the oligarchs who gained power after his
re-election in 1996. ``As a gifted journalist, with an eye for the
broad themes as well as the telling details of a story, he provides
us with an amplitude of particulars'' about the miseries that have
occurred during Yeltsin's reign of deception and criminality,
Abraham Brumberg wrote here last year. The thesis of  &UR; PETERSBURG,
CRUCIBLE OF CULTURAL REVOLUTION &LR; , by Katerina Clark (Harvard
University, $18.95), is that the city's idealistic artists and
intellectuals during the tumultuous years between 1913 and 1931
created an atmosphere that made the Great Terror of the late 1930s
possible. This revisionist account is ``a major contribution to the
cultural history of this seminal period,'' Harlow Robinson said in
the Book Review in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BLESSING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Nancy Mitford. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $10.95.
</P>
<P>
   This spirited riff on French-British relations on the highest
social plane pits a beautiful English wife and her charming French
nobleman husband against a diabolical villain: their young son. The
result is a ``cunningly constructed, artfully written ... farce of
the most civilized kind,'' Elizabeth Janeway wrote here in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMAGINING ROBERT. MY BROTHER, MADNESS, AND SURVIVAL: A MEMOIR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jay Neugeboren. Owl/Holt, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   A novelist describes his younger brother's 30-year battle with
mental illness, and his own struggle to navigate the nightmarish
system of mistreatment and inattentive care that dooms many victims
of schizophrenia and manic-depressive disorder. This is a
``powerful story,'' Frederick Busch said in these pages in 1997. In
 &UR; OUT OF THE SHADOWS: CONFRONTING AMERICA'S MENTAL ILLNESS CRISIS &LR; ,
by E. Fuller Torrey (Wiley, $16.95), a psychiatrist reports that
millions of Americans are suffering from severe mental illness
without treatment. ``The crisis he delineates should stir any
halfway sensitive human being to anger,'' Daniel J. Kevles wrote
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNDERGROUND MAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Mick Jackson. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   This first novel focuses on one of Victorian England's most
famous eccentrics, the real-life fifth Duke of Portland, who built
an elaborate network of tunnels beneath his lands to allow him
hidden access to all parts of his realm. ``Jackson has produced a
marvelous study of human foibles,'' Erik Burns said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEAR AND HIS DAUGHtER: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Stone. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The novelist's first collection of short fiction is populated by
men who feel most alive when they are angry. In evoking a kind of
grinding male arrest, ``Stone turns the scraps and figments of
style that we call characters into real people,'' James Wood wrote
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEVER EAT YOUR HEART OUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Judith Moore. North Point, $13.
</P>
<P>
   A California writer and editor expresses her life story through
the food she has prepared, peppering her lively account with
bite-sized essays on everything from the history of the cranberry
to the sex life of turkeys. Last year our reviewer, Susan Cheever,
called this a ``tart, satisfying'' memoir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TEACHINGS OF DON B.: SATIRES, PARODIES, FABLES, ILLUSTRATED
STORIES, AND PLAYS OF DONALD BARTHELME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Kim Herzinger. Vintage International, $15.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a parody of Bret Easton Ellis or a shaggy dog story
about a 4,000-pound Gouda cheese, the 63 pieces collected here
bristle with the author's delight in surprising the reader with his
genre-jumping acrobatics. The result is ``a small education in
laughter, melancholy, and the English language,'' James Marcus
wrote here in 1992.  &UR; A DOG'S HEAD &LR; , by Jean Dutourd, translated by
Robin Chancellor (University of Chicago, $12), is a slender
Barthelmesque fantasy about a middle-class Frenchman born with the
tete of a spaniel. This satirical novel is ``sad-eyed, witty and
often very funny,'' C.J. Rolo wrote here in 1953.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
