<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: Help! A Chevy flashback
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture this. The fate of the republic hangs on it. In the Oval
Office, President Clinton is chatting up the president of Mexico. A
room away, in Mr. Clinton's book-lined study, sits wistful,
trusting Monica Lewinsky, awaiting whatever fate soon to befall
her. Delicately put, that fate seems best visualized as the back
seat of your dad's 1953 Chevy until someone gasps, ``Maybe we
shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   This according to a friend of Lewinsky's who has testified
before Ken Starr's grand jury. There are some _ me among them _ who
will find this both credible and bizarre. You can't quite picture
Rutherford B. Hayes pleading, ``I do too respect you.''
</P>
<P>
   The president says it isn't so, and furthermore it wasn't sex.
Watching Congress solemnly debating these issues will be worth the
gazillions we'll spend for the hilarity value alone. It's like
having a nightmare in which you are put on trial for having been a
teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we elected Mr. Clinton presuming he was beyond his
zit years. Still, it all seems a matter best left to Hillary
Clinton than the House Judiciary Committee. I don't know Mrs.
Clinton well at all, but if I were the Prez and given the choice,
I'd rather face Henry Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
