</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Lure of junk mail too much to pass up
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ I have a cardinal rule when it comes to
sorting mail _ never open window envelopes (unless it's payday) or
anything addressed to Current Resident. It's always junk so why
risk a paper cut?
</P>
<P>
   But today I blew it. Greed got the best of me. This one looked
</P>
<P>
   like a check and who am I to sneeze in the face of fortune? I
ripped it open. Rats! No money _ just another load of hype. Seems
some folks in Mission Viejo, Calif. want to loan me some big bucks
on my house _ and the dummies don't even know if the plumbing
works.
</P>
<P>
   'Dear Elizabeth,' they begin which kind of annoys me. We've
never met and already they're calling me by my first name. They go
on to tellme how pleased they are to inform me that my home has
recently been verified as '...eligible for a low interest trust
deed in the amount shown above.' I check the amount. They've got to
be nuts. Besides, I have no idea what a 'low interest trust deed'
is. I suspect it has to do with, 'Here, little girl, take this nice
money and sign here. We'll be around to grab your house on
Thursday. Don't bother to take the cats or the Steinway - we own
them too.'
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I begin to wonder how somebody all the way out in
</P>
<P>
   California knows my house is worth anything. How do they know it
isn't a falling-down dump with blown-out plastic over the windows?
Or do they care? I read on.
</P>
<P>
   They're telling me that if the amount shown on the pseudo-check
is not enough they'd be happy to boost the ante _ even if (get
this) my property has no equity and my credit's lousy. Golly, gee
whiz! What nice folks.
</P>
<P>
   But I have to hurry. It doesn't say why, only that '...due to
the
</P>
<P>
   large volume we are currently receiving...' It doesn't say
volume of what. Maybe if I don't call right away they'll just be
out of the mood.
</P>
<P>
   After all, giving away large amounts of money is bound to be a
little nerve-wracking.
</P>
<P>
   There's even an example of what their money can do for me. They
tell me that if I'm making monthly credit card payments of $420 and
a car loan payment of $385, for a total of $805, I'm probably in
big trouble and they really want to help me out. They want me to
know I have a 'friend' out there whose sole aim in life is to bail
my backside out of pernicious penury.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on me for being suspicious, but I have a few questions
like:
</P>
<P>
   Where did these clowns get their information? Who sold my
personal life to the vultures? And just how stupid do they think I
am?
</P>
<P>
   In the name of fairness, I've decided to answer their offer:
</P>
<P>
   'Dear Unnamed Moneylender:
</P>
<P>
   You're wasting your time _ and mine.
</P>
<P>
   It may surprise you to know that not everyone in America is up
to his or her hipboots in debt. There are generations of us who
grew up with the old-fashioned work ethic strongly intact: Work for
it _ pay for it _ and if you can't afford it, don't haul it home in
the pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever told us the economy owed us a thing. When our kids
needed braces, we didn't take off for two weeks in Acapulco on the
plastic. And we never bought into the notion that a kid growing up
without a television, a VCR, and a big-buck stereo of his very own
was a candidate for a call from Children's Services.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, we were able to avoid buying into the belief that
without $150 sneakers and designer jeans our kids would become
social outcasts and be forever doomed to a life of tedious
mall-walking.
</P>
<P>
   To a multitude of Americans, credit cards are a convenience _
not a crutch.
</P>
<P>
   So to all of you wannabe Shylocks, strike my name from your
mailing list and get a real job. You don't have to pay my bills for
me and I'm sure as hell not going to pay yours for you.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Not at risk
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
