<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN08-COX     07-06 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: China trip a success, tentatively
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's long trip to China was somehow oddly
distanced, as if the event were unreal, a virtual presidential trip
rather than a palpable one. It was watched at home with seeming
indifference, just another of those occasions of no better than
passing interest that unreel on the nightly news and have type
ladled over them in newspapers mainly out of a vestigial sense of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Has the busy effort to enscandal the Clinton presidency finally
reached the point where the only thing that counts is the latest
tweak in l'affaire Lewinsky or newest arcanum shaken from the
impenetrable muddle of ancient Whitewater and the real business of
the presidency is just time out?
</P>
<P>
   It does not seem to matter that all the -gates have so far
repaid expectations with only a market basket of small potatoes.
The Clinton presidency no longer has much, if anything, to do with
governance. It's just more tabloid TV, a niche production
positioned somewhere between ``Hard Copy'' and ``Entertainment
Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   China is emerging as a major player in world affairs. It is
revving up an economic engine that in time could displace Japan's
as Asia's most powerful. Its military is large and troublesome in
its willingness to hawk technology to other regions' bully boys.
Beijing's geopolitical aims are unclear, probably even to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In short, China matters, a great deal. And Sino-American
relations have been at best shaky since Beijing cruelly quashed a
popular movement for democracy, yet neither nation can afford the
risks of miscalculation that would be inevitable in disengaged
antagonism. The two very different systems must find ways safely to
manage those differences.
</P>
<P>
   In that, President Clinton appears to have succeeded, at least
tentatively. He has carried the bilateral relationship past the
horror of Tiananmen Square but without compromising American
principles. Clinton firmly reiterated U.S. support for human rights
and democracy, emphasized the world's interest in seeing China's
massive pollution brought under control and even spoke up for
Tibet, an especially touchy point with the Chinese autocracy.
</P>
<P>
   No, there were no major breakthroughs, but then none had been
intended or expected. The trip itself was the breakthrough, and all
the more so for President Jiang Zemin's willingness to let the
American president make his points directly to nationwide Chinese
audiences. If that is precedent, the quality of all international
relations with Beijing will have been jumped several places
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the television networks kept their news stars home, as if
the trip were just something White House spinners had cooked up to
take the anchors' eyes off the ball, the mother of all photo ops.
No Gunga Dan this time. No risk Peter Jennings might be caught
abroad _ as he was covering the pope in Cuba _ if another bimbo
erupted. NBC sent Geraldo Rivera, as if to tell the president just
where he stands.
</P>
<P>
   The whole occasion seemed a strange temporal refraction, as if
carried to us from some familiar-seeming but still exotic parallel
universe, one in which Bill Clinton really, really is president. In
their begrudged and sometimes scoffing coverage, the TV networks
made it clear they weren't going to fall for that.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
