<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYSTIC-FIBROSIS-UPDAT     07-06 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYSTIC-FIBROSIS-UPDATE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cystic fibrosis sufferer keeps defying the odds
 &HT;    By Kevin Wishard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Bobby Hogberg was born in 1959, children
like him who had cystic fibrosis were expected to live 10 years.
Little was known about the disease or how to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   Hogberg, 38, has beaten the odds. His fight has required a
rigorous regimen of therapy and repeated hospitalizations. But
Hogberg, who lost two sisters to the childhood disease, never gave
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't be alive today,'' Hogberg said recently. ``But you
can't let those feelings seep in, because if you do, you're halfway
to giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hogberg is in a Houston hospital fighting for his health
once again. This time, he's trying to overcome a stomach blockage
that is symptomatic of cystic fibrosis and hold on to the new lungs
transplanted into his chest in February.
</P>
<P>
   Hogberg, a resident of Georgetown, is among the 6 percent of
cystic fibrosis patients alive today who are 35 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Cystic fibrosis is the most common fatal inherited disease among
whites. In 1970, doctors projected a life expectancy of 18 years
for children diagnosed with the disease, which affects the body's
ability to ward off infections and restricts breathing and
digestion. Victims usually die from lung damage caused by the
buildup of thick mucous and chronic infections.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, scientists discovered a gene that, when defective,
causes cystic fibrosis in 90 percent of cases. The discovery has
led to promising gene research and new treatments that thin mucus
and improve lung function. Those developments and an increased
emphasis on nutrition and diet have resulted in the number of
patients 18 and older nearly doubling in the past 10 years.Today,
the life expectancy for babies born with cystic fibrosis is 45
years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allan Frank, a pediatrician who treats Hogberg and about 70
other cystic fibrosis patients in the Austin area, said Hogberg's
spirit and determination to get better have worked in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tried new therapies . . . and he has not got
discouraged, even though for the past two to three years he's had
one problem after another,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Hogberg was among the first to try a hand-held device called the
Flutter, which sends strong vibrations through his chest cavity,
helping to clear mucus collecting in his lungs. He also was among
the first to benefit from Pulmozyme, which thins mucous.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Food and Drug Administration approved a second
groundbreaking drug, TOBI, an inhaled antibiotic developed from
tobramycin. It delivers a concentrated dose directly to the site of
the lung infections.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, Hogberg was placed on the list of prospective
transplant recipients. In February, just a month after his father's
death, Hogberg was told to get to Houston as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-hour surgery was difficult because Hogberg's lungs were
severely damaged. Scar tissue from previous infections had built up
between the lungs and the bones protecting them. A few days later,
he had more surgery to remove blood clots that were preventing his
lungs from working properly.
</P>
<P>
   Then he faced another problem: His kidneys were damaged during
the prolonged surgery, and he needed dialysis for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he began to recover, believing the prayers offered by
his family and friends had been answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just taking that first breath _ that was what I had fought for
for so long. . . . It was exhilarating,'' Hogberg said after
returning home in April. ``I wasn't wearing oxygen, and my fingers
and my lips were pink.'' amily history
</P>
<P>
   One in 20 people are symptomless carriers of cystic fibrosis,
which strikes children who inherit the defective gene from both
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Barbara Hogberg had three children before they realized
they were carriers of the cystic fibrosis gene. In 1956 the couple
buried their first daughter, Karen, before she was 2, without
knowing she had suffered from cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hogbergs' second daughter, Patti, was diagnosed with
the disease in 1960 at age 2,they realized the illness was probably
responsible for Karen's death. Doctors tested Bobby when he was 3,
discovering that he, too, carried the defective gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I denied it because he was such a healthy child,''
Barbara Hogberg said. ``He was a typical boy who just got into
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years that followed, Patti's health was poor, while Bobby
played sports and kept pace with his peers. His breathing
difficulties didn't surface until puberty. About that time, a month
before her 15th birthday, Patti died.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hogberg began to realize his life would not be normal. His
parents began clapping his chest and back for 30 minutes three
times a day to clear his lungs. But he continued to play baseball
and golf and race motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Hogberg never doubted her son would outlive others
struck by cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's determined and hard-headed and had an attitude that this
was not going to beat him,'' she said. ``And his father always told
him that Hogbergs never quit. Hogbergs don't moan and whine.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, many more cystic fibrosis patients will live as long as
Hogberg has without a lung transplant, which has long been
considered the final treatment option, physicians say.
</P>
<P>
   Older patients
</P>
<P>
   The medical community, which had left the treatment of cystic
fibrosis largely to pediatricians, recently began adapting to the
aging population of cystic fibrosis survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly we looked up and said, `Oh, my God, we've got adults,
and we've got a lot of them,' '' said Linda Ward, clinic
coordinator for the cystic fibrosis care center at Santa Rosa
Children's Hospital in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Now older patients are facing health problems such as high blood
pressure, osteoporosis and back pain.
</P>
<P>
   The transition is challenging for patients who are being asked
to take responsibility for their care and for parents who have
always been involved in their children's health care decisions,
said Dr. Steven Copenhaver of Scott &AMP; White hospital in Temple.
Physicians are trying to integrate the adult care at the 113 care
centers around the nation. In Texas, those centers are in Dallas,
Houston and San Antonio. Satellite care centers are in place at
Brackenridge Children's Hospital in Austin and at Scott &AMP; White in
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most common problems triggered by the complications of
cystic fibrosis in older patients are diabetes and rheumatic
diseases. Pregnancies also are difficult. Men who suffer from
cystic fibrosis are sterile, and about 30 percent of women are
infertile.
</P>
<P>
   Hogberg's outlook
</P>
<P>
   At just over 6 feet tall, Hogberg weighs less than 130 pounds.
He's a proud, independent man who built a courier business that has
suffered during his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at myself in the mirror and thought, `That's me with
no oxygen on, and I'm not winded,' '' he said soon after the
transplant. ``I thought, `God, it worked.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, he was released from the Houston
hospital. He returned the oxygen tanks that had been a virtual
lifeline and began trying to rebuild muscles that had shrunk from
years of inactivity. He hoped he had won a new beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors told him to expect to return to the hospital for
adjustments in the balance of drugs needed to keep his body's
immune system from rejecting his new lungs, which came from a
16-year-old boy who died in a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   He's been in three times, the current stay now extending into
its eighth week .
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said Friday that he had undergone additional
surgery and was having trouble eating.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Westergren, lung transplant coordinator at The Methodist
Hospital, said Hogberg's resilient nature is an inspiration to
those who have worked with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby just shows an enormous amount of raw courage,'' she
said. ``To keep hanging in there, knowing the odds are against him.
There's always the chance that the disease will win, but he's
fought it for so many years and won that I wouldn't put it past him
to fight it for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
