<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Rise and shine, it's vacation time
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ On vacations, there are basically two kinds of
people: those who relax and those who can't.
</P>
<P>
   The first kind arrive at their destination ... and flop. They
sleep in late, eat a leisurely breakfast, take long naps in the
afternoon, sit around reading books, have long, not-very-animated
discussions, eat some more, go to bed. The pace is slow, there are
no schedules, no agendas, no itineraries. No sightseeing, no
tourist attractions, no visits with anyone other than those they
choose.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the other kind of people. The manic ones. They're
up at the crack of dawn, have a moment-by-moment itinerary, go at a
full-out pace the entire day, schedule in just enough hotel time to
shower and change, and then they're off again. No minute is left
unfilled. Every attraction within 100 miles is toured and recorded
in their travel journal with preprinted brochures and vistaview
postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Any relative within driving distance is visited. At 6 a.m. every
morning, they're leaning over your peacefully sleeping face,
saying, ``Ready? We've got a big day ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Each to his own, I say. Unless you're in my family. We are
primarily vacationers of the first ilk. In other words, we go
someplace to do nothing, and we are very happy in our idleness.
Extrememly so.
</P>
<P>
   There is one in our family, however, who is of the other ilk.
He's a go-getter, a rise-and-shine kind of guy, a
what-are-you-waiting-for man. He usually annoys the heck out of us.
</P>
<P>
   We recently returned from a vacation, so the memories of this
difference in styles is fresh in my mind. Drilled into my
subconscious, if you will. Like a root canal.
</P>
<P>
   While four of us sprawl haphazardly in our temporary abode,
reading or sleeping or watching old movies on TV, this son is in
our faces, demanding action.
</P>
<P>
   I understand that there is some expectation that comes with a
vacation. We do plan about one event a day _ a trip to the beach or
pool, a movie, a good restaurant, an amusement park. The usual
stuff. It's just that this son expects us to participate in at
least four major events daily. I don't have that much energy. And
what I do have, I want to save.
</P>
<P>
   He, on the other hand, can become bored quicker than a
two-by-four.
</P>
<P>
   Our recent trip was to my folks' farm in Missouri. There's not a
lot of attractions for the visiting tourist in their little town.
In fact, things are so slow that visiting the new Wal-Mart ranks
right up there with a trip to Disney World. I kid you not.
</P>
<P>
   My folks waited months for this new shopping mecca to rise in
their midst. I got weekly long-distance updates on its progress:
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got the steel shell up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're putting the outside walls on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooh, they're pouring the parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   They hadn't been this excited since their town got a Golden
Corral.
</P>
<P>
   So, for our let's-go son, a daily trip to Wal-Mart was an
absolute must. This, the son who will not step foot in the Wal-Mart
in his own hometown. But when we visit the grandparents, suddent
it's (IT)the(RO) place to go. Actually, it's the only place to go.
</P>
<P>
   He comes back from his daily trips like Magellan reporting to
the queen on the wonders of the New World.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found these great shirts for under $20!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at these neat necklaces, and I couldn't believe the
prices!''
</P>
<P>
   So, when we arrived back home, I thought he would be thrilled
when I pointed out the construction site of our new Super Wal-Mart.
Imagine the departments it will have. A SUPER Wal-Mart, after all,
would be extraordinary. Much better than a regular Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   He idly looked out the window of our car as we drove past and,
once again on his own turf, muttered, ``So?''
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, well. We always take for granted the wonders in our own
back yards, don't we?
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
