<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Mythology and marketing of movie soundtracks
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Featuring new songs by L.L. Cool J, Puff
Daddy, Ice-T and the Lox!''
</P>
<P>
   As a film critic, nothing galls me more than this sort of
screaming pronouncement in a movie trailer. My response, never mind
if I'm a fan of the bands or not, invariably goes like this: Who
gives a $%&AMP;!!
</P>
<P>
   Will I rush to a movie predicated on the hope I will hear a
fleeting splinter of a Smashing Pumpkins song? Is the movie
improved because it's garnished with a nanosecond of the latest
Celine Dion gum drop or even a healthy serving of Red Hot Chili
Peppers? To me, that would be like going to a movie because of the
cozy seats and lovely company.
</P>
<P>
   Piggybacking pop music on a movie is a dicey _ and thoroughly
cynical _ marketing ruse. Dicey because when some of us are tipped
off Will Smith is going to rap in a movie, we want God to tell us
what extravagant sin we're paying for.
</P>
<P>
   Cynical because these pop tunes, unlike a film's original score
_ you know, the instrumental stuff generally performed by a
tuxedo-clad orchestra, not a braying drum machine and a guy with
nouns and serial initials for a name _ are more often than not
irrelevant to the film's craftsmanship. They are songs grafted onto
the completed product, not organic outgrowths of what the film is
trying to say. For instance, please, tell me, what does any Ben
Folds Five song have to do with ``Godzilla''? Anyone? (Besides, I
don't remember hearing any pop songs in ``Godzilla,'' save for Puff
Daddy's ``Come to Me'' blaring over the closing credits, the
crushingly bad movie's highlight.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that pop music can't be responsibly employed. It has, in
fact, been wonderfully used, colorfully enhancing and commenting
upon a film's action. ``The Big Chill,'' ``Goodfellas,'' ``Dazed
and Confused'' and ``Boogie Nights'' are clear examples of pop
music complementing narrative. A more recent instance is the
terrific use of Aerosmith's ``Sweet Emotion'' in ``Armageddon,'' a
film which is in large part a marathon music video, as was the
sensory-throttled ``Top Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   But those films are in a different category. Most of them are
period pieces or the uncamouflaged offspring of MTV. A pop song
becomes a sign-post of place and time. Mass marketing these
soundtracks is a no-brainer. ``Forrest Gump'' was crammed with
period pop that made everybody tingly. So it's not surprising, or
objectionable, that a double-CD of 32 songs from the movie was
released. Gauche and opportunistic, sure, but there are worse
compilations you can own.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm really objecting to is the piecemeal degradation of the
traditional, instrumental movie soundtrack, the nauseating notion
that many so-called ``soundtracks'' are not soundtracks at all.
They are unblushing marketing tools, greedy catalogs of pop music
``inspired by'' a film. It's a hilarious concept to ponder:
Apparently, a bunch of bands have found a movie so darn stirring,
they just had to write a catchy ode to it.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions. ``Dead Man Walking: Music Inspired by the
Motion Picture'' and the ``inspired by'' disc for ``The Horse
Whisperer'' are two rare collections of American roots music whose
songs might never have seen the light of day without the impetus of
Hollywood's slavering marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do with a sickly blunderbuss such as ``Godzilla: The
Album''? And, possibly more offensive, is this desperate example of
marketing avarice: `` `THE PRINCE OF EGYPT' INSPIRES TWO SPECIAL
ALBUMS.'' So reads a press release from DreamWorks Records, which
goes on to detail how the company will release a pair of pop-laden
records ``inspired by'' DreamWorks' animated epic ``The Prince of
Egypt'' _ two months before the movie hits the cineplex in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The albums ``will present songs that are inspired by themes
inherent to the film's story,'' pants the release. ``This marks the
first time that two complete albums from different musical genres
(there will be a country album and an R&AMP;B album) have been created
in support of a film release.''
</P>
<P>
   And hopefully the last.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't all be so unseemly if these pop albums didn't elbow
the film's actual scores into obscurity. Once, many Survivor and
Kenny Loggins movie anthems ago, starchy European-style composers
made music for films, small symphonies that roiled the emotions
hand-in-hand with the story on screen. Max Steiner (``Gone with the
Wind,'' ``Casablanca''), Bernard Herrmann (``Citizen Kane,''
``Vertigo''), Elmer Bernstein (``To Kill a Mockingbird'') and
Alfred Newman (``Wuthering Heights'') scored Hollywood's golden
years.
</P>
<P>
   Today populist classical composers such as Jerry Goldsmith
(``Patton,'' ``Chinatown''), Ennio Morricone (``The Good, the Bad,
and the Ugly,'' ``The Exorcist''), John Williams (``Jaws,'' ``Star
Wars'') and James Horner (``Titanic'') keep the tradition alive
with fitting orchestral bombast. Several former pop stars have
trained their chops on composing classical Hollywood soundtracks,
often with spectacular results. Former Oingo Boingo frontman Danny
Elfman leads the pack with soundtracks for ``The Simpsons,''
``Batman,'' ``Dick Tracy'' and a slew of other blockbusters. You
even can buy a greatest-hits collection of Elfman's theme songs.
Former Police drummer Stewart Copeland provided a beautiful score
for the urban drama ``Fresh,'' which was not released in favor of a
rap-ridden ``inspired by'' disc. Randy Newman and Dire Straits
ax-man Mark Knopfler are old hands at soundtracks. Knopfler's
latest twangy effort was for ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, save for a handful of largely pop-driven titles
(see Top 10 list), soundtracks have never been big business. So
it's not as though this new ``inspired by'' phenomenon is
overshadowing a thriving concern. But it sure doesn't help.
Nowadays we are told, very loudly, what pop acts were hired to
contribute a song to a movie before we hear who wrote and directed
the picture. Movie posters were once art, but increasingly they are
blighted by screaming litanies of bands whose music may or may not
be heard in a film. The person whose name follows ``Music By'' can
be found with binoculars near the bottom of the poster, not far
from the copyright line. In the soundtracks aisle of music shops,
you must be vigilant about what you snatch up, the ``score'' or the
``album.''
</P>
<P>
   Some blame teen-movie maven John Hughes for being the first to
exploit pop music as a powerful movie marketing tool. But where it
started is not half as important as where it could end. Exciting
film composers such as Elfman and Thomas Newman (``The Player'')
may be usurped by crass mercantilism, their scores supplanted by
Tori Amos or Foo Fighters covering a pop oldie, which is happening
more and more.
</P>
<P>
   How thrilling it once was to buy, say, John Williams' grandiose
soundtrack to ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind.'' No Led
Zeppelin cover tunes, just unfettered orchestral bombast,
mini-symphonies with relevant titles such as ``Main Title and
Mountain Visions'' and ``The Appearance of the Visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   And so thank goodness for ``Titanic.'' Say what you will about
the film, James Horner's aggressively traditional, classical score
is smashing records for soundtrack sales. The Academy Award-winning
score currently is catching its breath at No.15 on the Billboard
Top 200 (not the fuddy-duddy classical charts), where it has
resided for an astonishing 28 weeks and has sold 24 million copies,
making it the No. 1 best-selling movie score of all time. Though
people may be buying the disc for Celine Dion's hit (``My Heart
Will Go On''), they wind up being seduced by Horner's richly
evocative score. The album is jostling on the charts with the pop
soundtracks to ``City of Angels,'' ``Hope Floats'' and, yes,
``Godzilla: The Album.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dubiously, a sequel album titled ``Back to Titanic,'' featuring
music performed on the ship in the movie and new compositions by
Horner, will be released next month. So much for a perfect world.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Horner's ``Titanic'' is a beacon of hope in the
dispiriting arena of soundtracks, an S.O.S. flare in the cold night
sky. Perhaps there is hope for the invisible composers and their
overlooked work. Perhaps Megadeth and Fiona Apple won't triumph
after all. And perhaps filmgoers are listening a little closer to a
crucial part of what makes movies what they are.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is a film critic for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
