<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-CARGO07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hartsfield's new air cargo space almost ready
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hartsfield International Airport officials are set to
hand over the keys this month to the first tenants in a major $34.5
million expansion of international air cargo operations.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway Cargo Service will occupy the first of three
104,000-square-foot buildings on the south side of the airport. Two
more buildings are under construction, and a fourth will be bid out
later. When the total project is completed, it will add more than
400,000 square feet, doubling the current space of 352,000 square
feet now operating on the north side of the runways.
</P>
<P>
   The airport also has operated a 42,000-square-foot cold storage
operation for handling perishable food products.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion is aimed at attracting new business to Hartsfield,
where Delta Air Lines is the biggest single cargo hauler with 32
percent of the volume. Delta is not one of the carriers being
courted by the airport for the new space.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are still under way on the lease, but Gateway
Terminal Manager Ray Haulk said he hopes to get in the building by
July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway has 50 to 60 contracts with different airlines to handle
their freight, Haulk said. The new facility will more than double
Gateway's employment from 40 to 100 workers. The operation is
expected to move 500,000 pounds of freight a day.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway operates at 10 U.S. airports and contracts with such
international airlines as KLM, Nippon, Swiss Air and British
Airways, Haulk said.
</P>
<P>
   International air cargo is the single-fastest growing activity
at Hartsfield. Through April, it had increased 32 percent from the
same period last year, up to 78,320 metric tons from 59,272 metric
tons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the airport handled 203,000 metric tons of
international cargo with an estimated value of $7.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic growth is attributable to a booming region, said
Robert Kennedy, who oversees Hartsfield's air cargo operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a diversified manufacturing base in the Southeast that
is the biggest contributor to our growth,'' Kennedy said. ``Now, we
are getting air service that used to be trucked elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield funded the cargo expansion with airport revenues.
Airport officials say they must expand and modernize air cargo
facilities or face the prospect of losing business to other nearby
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, N.C., Columbus, Ga. and Huntsville, Ala., are
considered Hartsfield's closest rivals for cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hendricks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
