A1679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-CHIEF07-COX     07-06 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-CHIEF07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New airport chief puts planning atop itinerary
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Benjamin DeCosta has put completion of a master plan
for Hartsfield International Airport's future and keeping current
construction projects on track among his top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta, who assumed his duties June 29, told his senior staff
those items were atop his list. He was the general manager of
Newark International Airport in New Jersey before replacing Angela
Gittens, whom Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell did not reappoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport is operating at near-capacity,'' DeCosta said in
an interview at the airport. ``It's growing 7 to 8 percent (a
year), and we need to invest in its capacity, if we are to maintain
high levels of customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   Major projects under way include building a fifth runway to land
commuter airplanes, a 400-square-foot expansion of air cargo
operations and putting domestic gates on Concourse E, the
international gateway at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, a Master Plan Coordinating Committee has
been trying to come up with a formula to meet the growth in air
travel through 2015, when annual passenger volume at Hartsfield is
expected to be 121 million, compared to 68 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee _ comprised of 40 members representing the
airlines, business, local governments neighboring the airport and
citizens _ in its only vote opted for a no-build option in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, airport designers have been trying to come up with a
revised expansion scenario the committee could accept. The options
call for a new sixth runway either north or south of the airport
and a new terminal, concourse and cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   The no-build vote was led by Clayton County, Ga. representatives
who have voiced opposition to any new runway construction in the
county and south Fulton County, Ga. residents and business people
who say new runways will destroy their neighborhoods and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta said he is evaluating how to proceed with the Master
Plan process, because of the direction Campbell wants to see the
airport go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has a vision that the airport is key to the success
of Atlanta and the region,'' DeCosta said. Throughout the city
administration, everyone seems to support ``keeping the airport
strong and making its contribution to the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The new general manager spent the first week on the job walking
around introducing himself and trying to give people a feel for his
management style, which boils down to ``just call me Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta said the Southern tradition of using the polite courtesy
title struck him as the biggest cultural difference between the
Northeast and Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I've met here refers to me as Mr. DeCosta,'' DeCosta
said. ``Even at the manager and high levels everywhere, they say
Mr. DeCosta. At Newark, I'm called Ben. I even sign my memos Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta has a straightforward approach to managing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm famous for walking around the airport with a camera,''
DeCosta said. He takes the photos back to staff meetings and hands
them out to the staff with instructions to ``fix that,'' DeCosta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hendricks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
