<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-TRAFFIC07-COX     07-06 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-TRAFFIC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some think Atlanta traveling down the same road as L.A.
 &HT;    By David Goldberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Is traffic-clogged Atlanta the next Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   So asked the headline on a recent story in The Wall Street
Journal, which wondered whether smog and traffic congestion were
harming Greater Atlanta's reputation as a pleasant place to live.
The comparison was inspired in part by comments from Chris
Leinberger, director of the real estate consulting firm Robert
Charles Lesser &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is not in danger of becoming the next Los Angeles,''
Leinberger has said in speeches around the country. ``It is the
next Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous,'' snorts Harry West, director of the Atlanta
Regional Commission, the metro area's planning agency. ``We may be
worse in some ways, but to suggest we're L.A. when they have a
population of 18 million is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to traffic and untrammeled growth, those who
have lived in both places don't find the comparison such a stretch,
based on 100 responses to an Atlanta Journal-Constitution call-in
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous because this place doesn't even have a third
of the people of L.A., but its traffic is as bad or worse in some
ways,'' said caller Adrienne Affleck, who commutes an hour each way
from her home in east Cobb County to work in Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're there. Not almost there -- we're there,'' said Lee
Gilmer of Alpharetta, who recalled moving from L.A. to Atlanta in
1990 and laughing at people who complained about traffic. That has
changed, he said. ``Having to commute on (Ga.) 400 every morning
there's little doubt that Atlanta has achieved the nightmare that
L.A. has been experiencing for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   No one suggests the two regions compare in scale. The L.A.
statistical area encompasses six times as much real estate as
Atlanta's. L.A. has about twice as many miles of freeway as metro
Atlanta. But for all its storied reliance on automobiles, motorists
tally 13 more miles per day per person in Atlanta on average than
those of Los Angeles, and about twice the proportion of commuters
ride transit to work in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Several themes emerged from callers:
</P>
<P>
   -- Although congestion on L.A. freeways is an all-day affair,
Atlanta may be more frustrating because tie-ups can occur almost
anywhere on the area's meandering, often overbuilt arterial roads.
Los Angeles also is ``supported by a large network of grid surface
streets to give you options when the freeway is clogged,'' as one
caller put it.
</P>
<P>
   -- Freeway driving may be more stressful in Atlanta, because the
weather is more erratic and visibility is lower thanks to hillier
terrain, high sound walls and concrete barriers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Atlanta drivers are more aggressive and less courteous.
</P>
<P>
   -- Although vastly more expansive, L.A.'s sprawl allows easier
access to and from freeways and more sidewalks, bikeways and parks.
</P>
<P>
   -- Atlanta has an advantage over L.A. because it has a rapid
rail system in place.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that Southern California's smog is worse.
While Atlanta's ozone problem is labeled ``serious'' according to
federal health standards, L.A. is all alone in the ``extreme''
category. But aggressive measures over the last few years have all
but eliminated L.A.'s ``red alert'' days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people here are taking the air quality situation
as seriously as they are in Los Angeles,'' said Bernie Goldfine of
Acworth. ``Their air is getting better, and ours is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
