A1687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americans consumed by love affair with debt
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Poets and songwriters have long warned us that love
can make people do crazy things. But the lust for bigger kitchens
and designer clothes also can cause people to act as impulsively as
young lovers who can't see beyond the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The good economy has stirred up our consumer hormones to the
point where millions of Americans are falling for the come-on lines
from bankers who promise cheap mortgages and big credit lines.
Instead of rationally evaluating the offers, we swoon and surrender
to lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Our affair with debt began in earnest about five years ago when
credit card issuers started smothering us with letters promising
easy credit. About 2 billion ``pre-approved'' credit card
solicitations are now sent to U.S. consumers each year.
</P>
<P>
   With fresh plastic in their palms, many shoppers make rash
purchases before considering the consequences of their wild moments
in the mall. Since 1993, credit card debt has doubled, while the
savings rate has slid to about half what it was in the early 1980s.
Predictably, record numbers of borrowers are filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, amid our economic boom, another absurdity is developing:
the percentage of homeowners late with their mortgage payments is
rising. The Mortgage Bankers Association of America recently
reported that in the first three months of this year, mortgage
delinquencies rose to 4.47 percent, up from 4.34 percent in late
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Why did mortgage delinquencies increase during a period when
unemployment rates were falling and incomes rising?
</P>
<P>
   Late payments started climbing because many borrowers have begun
getting stung by loans that allowed them to purchase homes beyond
their price range. For example, a borrower might have used a very
low-interest, adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) a few years ago to buy
a big house. But now that the introductory rate has ended, the
monthly payment has moved up, leaving the homeowner struggling to
keep pace. Meanwhile, rising property tax assessments brought on by
a hot real estate market have increased the financial burden of
owning a home.
</P>
<P>
   In some circumstances, of course, ARMs can be useful. A young
couple with freshly minted college degrees might choose an ARM
because they can be fairly certain their incomes will rise fast
enough to keep pace with interest-rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   But too often, people who aren't expecting big jumps in income
are using ARMs to pry their way into pricey homes. In some intown
neighborhoods of Atlanta, housing prices have increased by 30
percent in the past year. Instead of buyers saying, ``Whoa, I'm
just not going to pay $300,000 for a two-bedroom bungalow,'' they
are listening to the real estate agents and lenders who keep
looking for ways to make the deal work.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of years, a sudden jump in interest rates could
drive up monthly mortgage payments and at the same time burst the
real estate price bubble. Today's eager home buyers could find
themselves falling behind on rising loan payments while trying to
hang on to a house with a declining market value.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as late 1997, economists were finding shreds of
evidence that suggested Americans might be slowing their spending
enough to pay down debts and increase savings. But that turned out
to be only a brief breather between trips to the mall. This year,
exuberant spending on housing and consumer goods is taking on an
ardor that could leave millions of Americans broken-hearted in the
next recession.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is a member of The Atlanta Constitution editorial
board.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
