A1688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-AIRPORT07-COX     07-06 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AIRPORT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin-Bergstrom's cargo facilities offer new opportunities,
room to grow
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On a cool, windy day in late October, a FedEx
jumbo jet took off into the overcast Austin sky en route to Japan,
carrying only two human passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the plane housed 80,000 pounds of food belonging to
its exotic cargo _ 156 Texas-bred ostriches. It marked the first
time live cargo left from an Austin airport, and the only time a
local airport has had enough room to land the McDonnell Douglas
MD-11, one of FedEx's largest airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could never have done anything like that at (Robert Mueller
Municipal Airport),'' said Jamy Kazanoff, spokeswoman for
Austin-Bergstrom International Airport. ``There wouldn't have been
enough room for the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Transporting live cargo is just one of many firsts for the
airport cargo facility since it moved to Austin-Bergstrom one year
ago last week. Passengers aren't scheduled to start flying from the
new airport until May 1999, but cargo operations are running at
full throttle out of the new airport, with tonnage hitting record
highs and percent growth in the double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening the 155,000-square-foot warehouse area, almost
four times bigger than Mueller's, carriers have moved 209 million
pounds of cargo _ 33 percent more than was moved during the
previous 12 months at Mueller. Cargo shipments include anything
from letters to fully assembled computers to thoroughbred
racehorses.
</P>
<P>
   Austin CargoPort Development, the private company that owns the
cargo space, spent $20 million to develop the site. Today, eight
national and international carriers lease space there, including
FedEx, Airborne Express and EAGLE USA Airfreight, whose parent
company EAGLE USA has a contract with Round RockAustin-based Dell
Computer Corp. United Parcel Service in March added two planes at
Austin-Bergstrom, citing Austin as one of the fastest-growing cargo
markets in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of ``cargo (handled) now is where we predicted it
would be in 2012,'' Kazanoff said. ``It's been phenomenal. It's
growing at three times the national rate (of 5 percent).''
</P>
<P>
   The boom in Austin's air freight industry is a product of the
large number dearth of technology-related companies in the area,
Kazanoff and others said. Several big companies like Motorola Inc.
make parts that are shipped out-of-state for packaging, and with a
competitive, fast-paced technology market, those companies want
components delivered cheaply and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-tech shipments are driving the market,'' said Holland
Young, an airport planner for the City of Austin. ``Those
high-value components tend to be low-weight, so it pays for those
companies to ship them by air because it's not real expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Since CargoPort's two buildings opened on June 30, 1997, the
surge in cargo activity also has lured more developers to
Austin-Bergstrom's tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, developer Aeroterm U.S. Inc., which owns the
now-vacant Mueller cargo space, broke ground on a $10 million
project at the new airport that will add another 110,000 square
feet of warehouse space by February 1999. Young said a third
developer plans to build a warehouse for use by passenger jets that
haul cargo on their flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aeroterm is hoping to bring to Austin an international (cargo)
carrier that isn't already here,'' said Aeroterm Vice President
Michael Bradley. ``Some of them operate from our building in
Montreal, and we want to bring them here. Austin will be very
competitive with Houston and San Antonio _ it'll be substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Austin's burgeoning air freight industry now
surpasses that of San Antonio International Airport, carrying more
tonnage and occupying more space. Still, the amount of cargo space
at Austin-Bergstrom is half the size of Houston's George Bush
Intercontinental Airport. And it handles substantially less cargo
than Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport, through which
two-thirds of all Texas' cargo passes. At Austin-Bergstrom, bigger
runways and more space have helped cargo carriers, too. At Mueller,
cargo companies struggled to leave on schedule because of the cargo
facility's proximity to the passenger terminal _ delivery trucks
had to maneuver around all the other traffic on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx took advantage of Austin-Bergstrom's warehouse space to
build a mini-hub. With the mini-hub, packages sent across town
remain in the city instead of getting routed through an
out-of-state hub, like they used to at Mueller. In October, Emery
Worldwide will also lease a 25,000-square-foot warehouse at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is money, and the extra space gives us more efficiency,''
said Bruce Dumler, Emery's general manager. ``If you decrease the
amount of time on the ramp (loading area), it makes it easier for
drivers to meet delivery deadlines. There's much more room here,
and it makes a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the new cargo space almost caught airport
planners by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, while drawing the early blueprints for
Austin-Bergstrom, only 20 million pounds of cargo moved through
Mueller Airport, so planners forecast little demand for more space.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in 1993, Young said, prompting the need for more
cargo space. But Mueller was already cramped, so officials decided
to begin seeking developers for Austin-Bergstrom's warehouses with
the goal of moving cargo operations there as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, airport planners gave the cargo industry ample room
to grow with Austin. As high-tech companies expand and the business
climate remains favorable for small start-ups, demand for cargo
shipments can only increase, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand was huge, and we knew if we didn't move soon, we'd be
constraining that demand, which constrains economic growth,'' Young
said. ``It (Mueller) was bad _ it was horrible. It got terribly
congested on the ramp. It was a bad situation altogether. We're
glad to have solved that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Cocks writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
