<HEADER>
A1691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVEACTION-CAS     07-06 1699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVEACTION-CASE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hopwood appeal lawyers take case personally
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's a nearly 40-year-old memory, but it helps
Harry Reasoner explain why his law firm has donated $2 million in
free legal services _ and has pledged more _ to defend affirmative
action at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While in college in the late 1950s, Reasoner took a construction
job and became friends with a helpful foreman, who was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me once, `I would like to have your advice on
something. I need to teach my children that they should step off
the sidewalk when white children walk past. What do you think I
should tell them?' '' Reasoner said.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner, who is white, paused in the retelling. ``I'm still
working on my answer,'' he finally said. ``You'd like to think it
is not true today . . . but we're a long way from a colorblind
society.''
</P>
<P>
   As head of Houston-based Vinson &AMP; Elkins, the law firm
representing UT without charge in the Hopwood affirmative action
case, Reasoner, 58, is not proud of the lack of diversity on his
own legal staff. Without affirmative action in higher education, he
fears it would be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting minorities is very difficult for us, and if the
University of Texas Law School does not have a diverse student
body, that will make it increasingly difficult,'' he said. ``We are
frustrated and unhappy with our efforts in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 442 Vinson &AMP; Elkins lawyers who work in Texas _ another
112 work out-of-state and internationally _ 6 percent are black or
Hispanic, according to the State Bar of Texas. And that's 1 or 2
percentage points higher than the other two largest law firms in
Texas. Forty percent of Vinson &AMP; Elkins' lawyers are UT law
graduates, including the nationally prominent Reasoner.
</P>
<P>
   Self-interest aside, there are other reasons Vinson &AMP; Elkins is
leading UT's fight against Hopwood, a 1996 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals ruling that led to a dismantling of affirmative action
programs in Texas colleges and declines in minority enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   Ties that bind
</P>
<P>
   Although it is unusual for a law firm to do such free work for a
</P>
<P>
   public institution, Reasoner is a big believer in pro bono work,
other Texas lawyers said. He also has deep ties to UT.
</P>
<P>
   A 1962 UT law graduate, Reasoner met his wife, Macey, at the law
school when they were students. He worked as an assistant to her
father, Gus Hodges, a longtime law professor.
</P>
<P>
   The Reasoners' son and daughter are UT Law School graduates, and
Reasoner is president of the school's fund-raising arm, founded in
1952 with help from Charles Francis, then a Vinson &AMP; Elkins
partner.
</P>
<P>
   The firm also does business with the 15-campus UT System.
</P>
<P>
   The system paid Vinson &AMP; Elkins $705,000 in fees and expenses
from Sept. 1, 1993, through May 1998. Except for firms that handle
UT's costlier medical malpractice suits, Vinson &AMP; Elkins' payments
were second only to those of Houston's Arnold, White &AMP; Durkee, UT
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson &AMP; Elkins also represents the UT Investment Management
Co., a private entity that handles UT investments and the Permanent
University Fund. It paid the firm $173,406 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Reasoner said the work his firm does for UT had no bearing
on his decision to take on Hopwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally feel very deeply that giving access to education
to all of our citizens is vital if the state is to survive and
prosper,'' he said. ``I feel also, if the University of Texas
School of Law does not have a diverse student body, the students
who are there will suffer. You can't remain a top-notch law school
without diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The right lawyers?
</P>
<P>
   Vinson &AMP; Elkins will stay in the case as long as it takes,
Reasoner said. UT is appealing to the 5th Circuit and hopes to go
all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court. Reasoner has pledged free
lawyer time and will bill only for expenses, such as copy charges
and travel.
</P>
<P>
   Some civil rights lawyers are not thrilled that a big, white law
firm _ one that often defends corporate clients against minorities
in employment discrimination suits _ is involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the conservative law firms that represents the
status quo,'' said Al Kauffman, regional counsel for the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund. ``All these firms have
been fighting against our interests for years.''
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF and the NAACP Legal Defense Fund are trying to intervene
in the appeal, arguing that they do not believe the firm can
adequately represent minority interests.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the first trial, UT instructed Vinson &AMP; Elkins
lawyers not to attack the validity of the Law School Admissions
Test, even though the test's ability to predict academic
performance is questionable. The minority groups seeking to
intervene in the case ``wanted the LSAT challenged, and the
administration did not,'' Reasoner acknowledged. ``I don't have any
personal expertise to evaluate the LSAT.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier decades, civil rights firms commonly represented
minorities in education discrimination suits. These days, as
universities are sued for reverse discrimination by whites, schools
often are represented by established, predominantly white law firms
assisting the state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Attorney General Dan Morales bowed out of Hopwood,
saying he personally does not support racial considerations and did
not think an appeal could succeed. He agreed, however, to let
outside counsel take over.
</P>
<P>
   Because Vinson &AMP; Elkins had been aiding Morales all along, UT
was eager for it to continue. Reasoner had tried the case before
the federal district court in Austin and argued before the 5th
Circuit. He plans to argue in the second round of appeals. A second
private firm _ Carrington, Coleman, Sloman &AMP; Blumenthal of Dallas _
and three UT law professors also are working on the case for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a remarkable and very positive thing if UT
had hired nationally known minority advocates,'' Kauffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Farabee, UT System general counsel and vice chancellor, said
lawyers for MALDEF and the NAACP Legal Defense Fund represent their
organizations, not the broader interests of a university. Besides,
he said, UT is being sued by MALDEF in an education finance case.
</P>
<P>
   Farabee said UT could not go wrong with Vinson &AMP; Elkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Reasoner is one of the deans of Texas lawyers,'' he
said. ``He is one of the most able trial lawyers in America. We
were extremely fortunate to have nearly $2 million thus far of pro
bono service.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner said that while he would welcome the intervention of
MALDEF and the NAACP Legal Defense Fund, he sees Vinson &AMP; Elkins'
involvement as positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think it's a healthy thing that an establishment
firm that's predominantly white is willing to participate in this
issue,'' Reasoner said. ``We filed a response and said, clearly,
this a momentous public issue; clearly MALDEF and the NAACP
represent people who have a very deep and direct interest in the
matter and . . . in the interest of justice, they ought to be
heard.'' That doesn't mean that Vinson &AMP; Elkins will not fight
hard, Reasoner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a clear understanding with our client that we are to
make every legitimate argument to overturn Hopwood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pro bono pro
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner, who is more active in the courtroom than many managing
partners of other big law firms, last year successfully defended
CBS's ``60 Minutes'' in a libel case over its report on poor living
conditions in certain El Paso colonias, unincorporated rural
subdivisions that often lack basic services. In 1989, he won a
$1.035 billion judgment for a coal slurry pipeline company that
sued the railroads in an antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   After the UT Law School was sued in 1992 by Cheryl Hopwood and
three other white students who contended they were denied admission
so less-qualified blacks and Mexican Americans could get in,
then-Dean Mark Yudof called Reasoner for help. A conservative
Washington firm, the Center for Individual Rights, jumped in to
represent two plaintiffs and was hiring a team of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner said Morales' office would have been hard-pressed to
match those resources, so Vinson &AMP; Elkins agreed to provide free
help some months before the first trial, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson &AMP; Elkins is considered a pro bono leader, said Julie
Oliver, executive director of the Texas Lawyers Care Program, a
legal services support project of the State Bar of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the firm agreed to give its lawyers the same
credit for pro bono work as for hours billed _ a key performance
indicator for lawyers. Most firms give no credit for free hours,
said Scott Atlas, a Vinson &AMP; Elkins attorney who chairs the Law
Firm Pro Bono Project of the Pro Bono Institute and the American
Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put our money where our mouth is,'' said Beverly Reeves, an
Austin Vinson &AMP; Elkins lawyer on the Hopwood team.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the firm's pro bono cases have been highly controversial
_ and costly.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson &AMP; Elkins successfully represented Texas inmates fighting
censorship. Atlas spent years working to free a Mexican national
wrongly convicted of murder at a cost of $2.5 million to Vinson &AMP;
Elkins.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years on death row in Texas, Ricardo Aldape Guerra was
released in April 1997 and got a job acting in a Mexican soap
opera. He died in a car wreck four months later.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson &AMP; Elkins does about $230 million worth of business a
year, and Atlas estimated the firm donated about $5 million in pro
bono work last year.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner said that while some partners and clients aren't happy
the firm is fighting Hopwood, he never wants to shy away from
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a law firm just to make money _ that demeans a great
profession,'' he said. ``Lawyers are obligated to give back. For
me, participating in Hopwood is an opportunity to participate in
one of the great issues of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
