<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYLOR-NOBEARS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baylor University may phase out use of live bears as mascot
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Baylor University is considering phasing out its
tradition of using a live bear as its mascot, according to
spokesman Larry Brumley.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past when we retired bears we found new homes for them
at zoos and wildlife parks,'' Brumley said. ``Now we're running
into challenges finding acceptable places for the bears to retire
to. That's part of what's driving this.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has used live bears as mascots since World War I, when a
bear named Ted was given to the university by the Army's 107th
Engineers after they received orders to leave Camp MacArthur in
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The two bears now acting as mascots are Ginny, 2 1/2, and Bill
Boyd, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Baylor has trotted out the bears at football
games, both at home and away. However, the school's entry into the
far-flung Big 12 conference has restricted the mascots' traveling
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baylor's away games are getting farther and farther away,''
Brumley said. ``It's really become impractical to take a live
mascot along.''
</P>
<P>
   Brumley also said athletic directors are increasingly refusing
to allow live mascots brought into stadiums for liability reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor had planned to bring in a cub this year as a replacement
for Ginny, the younger bear taken to games for the last two years.
However, difficulty in finding a new home for Ginny scotched those
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Placing a bear is not like placing a dog,'' said Rosie
Roegner(NO)cq(RO), nongame permit coordinator for Texas Parks and
Wildlife. ``Black bears require a special diet _ you just can't go
down to the store and get bear chow _ and special facilities.
They're not easy to place.''
</P>
<P>
   Roegner said Baylor's permit allows it to keep its bears on
public display ``for educational purposes.'' The permit is good
until Aug. 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor used to place its former mascots in zoos and wildlife
parks such as the defunct Texas Safari in Clifton. However, Roegner
said such sites are no longer hungry for out-of-work bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black bear is a rare species, but it's not something
people go out of their way to see,'' she said. ``Zoos are not eager
to get them at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, the Baylor Chamber of Commerce, the campus organization
that looks after the mascots, raised $2,500 to build the first
permanent home for the school's bears. The so-called Bear Pit gave
way in 1977 to a plaza across from the student center that features
a large roaming area, a waterfall and a viewing area for
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor bears have marched in homecoming parades, been
photographed with governors and even a president. Ronald Reagan
helped Abner the Bear down a Dr Pepper during a 1980 campaign stop
in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's most famous mascot was a former carnival bear named Joe
College. Yell leader Bill Boyd _ for whom one of the present
mascots was named _ bought the bear, who started the famous routine
of drinking soda water at Baylor games in the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Joe College's popularity endured even after his death. His head
was mounted and hung over the scoreboard at Rena Marrs McLean
Gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   But Baylor's use of a live mascot came under attack in 1991 from
a San Antonio wildlife park director: Lynn Cuny, director of
Wildlife Rescue and Rehabilitation, which had taken in a former
Baylor mascot. Cuny called it inappropriate for a school educating
young people to act responsibly to use an endangered animal as a
mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Brumley said the school still receives correspondence
questioning its practice of having live mascots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't characterize it as an aggressive campaign, but it's
something we're taking into consideration,'' Brumley said.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on whether to keep the tradition of having live
mascots will be made by the Chamber of Commerce and the
administration. Don't look for a decision until at least fall,
Brumley said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is decided, Baylor could continue to have a live mascot
for a number of years to come, said the Chamber of Commerce's
faculty adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the professional trainers tell us Ginny is healthy
and doing well, there's no reason to retire her as mascot,'' said
Steve Sadler, assistant director of the honors program. ``She could
be the mascot for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
