<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-NASCAR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke bottles feature NASCAR drivers
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Coca-Cola Co. is hoping NASCAR fans and Coca-Cola
memorabilia collectors will race out to snap up a series of nine
Coke-Cola Classic bottles featuring some of the sport's most
popular drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-ounce bottles feature Dale Earnhardt, Dale Jarrett, Bobby
Labonte, Bill Elliott, Jeff Burton, Kyle Petty, Todd Bodine and
Ricky Rudd _ all members of ``the Coca-Cola Racing Family.'' A
ninth bottle commemorates Coca-Cola's designation as the official
soft drink of NASCAR. Six-packs of the limited-edition bottles are
now being rolled out, and full national distribution is expected by
the end of the NASCAR season this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this will be one of the most popular limited-edition
bottles series we've ever issued,'' said Andrew Angle, senior vice
president of Coca-Cola USA and general manager of Coca-Cola USA
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company and its bottlers issue between 130 and 150 different
commemorative bottles each year, featuring everything from the
Olympics and the Super Bowl to classic portraits of Santa Claus.
The NASCAR bottles could end up creating a trading frenzy among
fans, because not all of the bottles will be sold in every market,
a Coca-Cola spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's five-year agreement with NASCAR began Jan. 1, when
the company snagged the sponsorship away from rival Pepsico Inc.,
which held it for more than 40 years. Coca-Cola is spending an
estimated $30 million on the sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico, meanwhile, on Thursday renewed its agreement to be the
exclusive soft drink supplier to Daytona International Speedway.
Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Pepsi gained exclusive pouring rights at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway and four Penske Motorsports Inc.
tracks. The company is the title sponsor of four races, including
the Pepsi 400, which was postponed from this weekend until October
because of serious wildfires near Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
