A1694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-NASCAR07-COX     07-06 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-NASCAR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR seeds planted on West Palm Beach track
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Drivers knew it as ``Palm Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Smiling Lee Petty, Fireball Roberts and Banjo Mathews
raced there in the early days of NASCAR, they were driving what
many racing pioneers still refer to as ``the fastest dirt oval in
the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1949, the old Palm Beach Fairgrounds Speedway off
Southern Boulevard was a half-mile racetrack of crushed shellrock
mixed with oil to prevent dust clouds.
</P>
<P>
   There were other dirt tracks around the country. But ``Palm
Beach'' was special because, unlike most tracks, the oval's two
curves banked at 18 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers wearing fighter-plane goggles ``went in hard and came
out fast'' around those curves, catapulting sideways at 65 mph in
cars like a 1952 Oldsmobile that probably had been borrowed a few
hours earlier from a local car-rental lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could really fly around that thing,'' recalled Ted
Sollohub, 60, who watched races there as a teenager. ``The wall was
just plywood, and they'd hit the wall and go right through it and
disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, ``they'd reappear and get back on the track, with
tree limbs sticking out of the car.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly wasn't out of character for a sport historians
say probably started when the second Model T rolled off the line.
According to racing lore, moonshiners transported their product
through the Southern Appalachian mountains in cars with souped-up
engines.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR, formed by Daytona Beach mechanic Bill France, held its
first unofficial race on the hard-packed sand of Daytona Beach in
1948. By 1951, West Palm Beach orchid farmer L.C. Vaughn was
negotiating the first of seven NASCAR races that would be run at
his fairgrounds track over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The track was built just down the road from the Morrison Field
(now Palm Beach International Airport), where oil and equipment
from old World War II planes provided the oil for the race track
and goggles, helmets and seat belts for the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Flock won the first race on Jan. 20, 1952, leading his
Hudson Hornet to the 100-mile mark just ahead of Lee Petty and 25
other cars in NASCAR's Grand National inaugural. Flock raced past
the checkered flag after two hours and ``200 grueling laps,''
according to an account by the late Post-Times sports editor Bob
Balfe.
</P>
<P>
   With 6,500 people in the grandstand, Flock accepted the trophy
from racing buff Eddie Brannick, secretary of the New York Giants
baseball team that had won the National League pennant less than
four months earlier on Bobby Thomson's famous home run.
</P>
<P>
   One of Palm Beach's most memorable races was on Feb. 7, 1954,
when Herb Thomas, near the end of a wild duel with Buck Baker,
slammed into the grandstand retaining wall just five yards from the
checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas still managed to finish first. His four wins and $5,150
in prize money at Palm Beach are records. Thomas, 75, doesn't
remember details of the races, but he knew he enjoyed racing at
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right up there with Darlington. It was a nice track. I
never had any trouble with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pit stops at Palm Beach were common for changing tires or
cleaning the oil-puttied dirt from screens protecting the
radiators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us half a day to clean the mess, but I loved that
dirt,'' recalled Pat Kenney, a retired driver now living in Stuart.
Kenney's mechanic at Palm Beach was Wendell Yarborough, whose
cousin Cale would go on to become one of racing's most famous
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   James Crowe, who would go on to race stock cars, was a faithful
fan at the Palm Beach track thanks to future Indy 500 winner Al
Keller of Greenacres City. ``My dad wouldn't let me go. So I used
to sneak out of the house,'' Crowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he would wait at the corner of Jog and Lake Worth roads
where Keller, driving a truck that was pulling a trailer carrying
his 1954 Hudson, would let the boy into the cab.
</P>
<P>
   Keller was the first to pass the checkered flag at the last
NASCAR Grand National race at Palm Beach on March 4, 1956. He was
later disqualified for ``a little bumping contest we got into,''
recalled Buck Baker, who was named one of NASCAR's top 50 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   That race was the first run on Palm Beach's newly paved track.
Five years later, Keller was killed in a racing accident in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my hero,'' Crowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's NASCAR races moved north with the construction of
Dayton International Speedway in 1959, but the Palm Beach Speedway
still attracted famous names like Bobby Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Also called Southland Speedway, the Palm Beach Speedway hosted
races until it was demolished after closing in 1983. Its legacy
reaches to modern drivers like Jeff Gordon, a graduate of Palm
Beach Speedway driver Buck Baker's racing school.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who drove a city bus in Charlotte, N.C., when he wasn't
racing, laughed about how the sport has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Jeff Gordon the other day, `Jeff, we helped you make
your money.' He smiled and said, `I know it, Mr. Baker. I know
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Capozzi writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
