<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAM-POW07-COX     07-06 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-POW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida man scammed military, friends as longtime lies surface
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On a sunny June Sunday four years ago,
they played the national anthem just for Jay Casenelli.
</P>
<P>
   He stood at attention and cocked a salute as the colors flew
before him.
</P>
<P>
   His friends from the VFW gathered at the 3220th Army Garrison in
West Palm Beach, drawn by the heroic war story he had told them:
</P>
<P>
   How his Cobra helicopter was shot down near the Laotian border
on that awful day, Feb. 23, 1970, during his second tour of duty in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   How his captors beat him after a failed escape attempt and how
they forced him to curl his 6-foot frame into a 3-foot cage atop a
dung heap.
</P>
<P>
   How his weight fell from 200 pounds to 98 pounds as he pawed the
dirt for the few grains of rice the Viet Cong would throw between
the wooden bars.
</P>
<P>
   How, when liberation finally came after six years, he was
haunted by the faces of the other POWs _ the brothers he was forced
to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   The anthem stopped playing on that June Sunday in 1994 and Jay
Casenelli snapped his salute. All around him admired the POW medal
with the bronze eagle that had just been pinned on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll share this with some ghosts,'' he told them.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Jay Casenelli is himself a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about his war story is true _ not a date, not a detail,
not a word.
</P>
<P>
   He flew no helicopter, endured no beating and suffered no
imprisonment in a wooden cage in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Casenelli spent the Vietnam War years well out of the
reach of the Viet Cong gunfire, in Hazlehurst, Ga., and Marathon in
the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very disheartening,'' said Col. Dave Presley, the Army
officer who had helped Casenelli get his POW medal. ``It looks like
he scammed a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army and Defense Department records show that Casenelli was
not in the military during the 1960s and '70s. The National
Personnel Records Center in St. Louis confirmed Casenelli has no
record of Vietnam service.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Greer, a public affairs officer in Washington with the
Department of Defense POW/Missing Personnel Office, said fraudulent
cases of Vietnam internment continue to cross his desk. Casenelli's
is another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to have had a rash of them lately,'' Greer said. ``The
fact is the POW list from Southeast Asia is completely declassified
now. There are no covert operations people who are not on the list.
If you are not on the list, you were not a POW or MIA in Southeast
Asia, and Mr. Casenelli is not on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucratic misadventure and the good wishes of his friends
enabled Casenelli to receive a POW medal he did not deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Coyner, a public affairs officer with the U.S. Army
Reserve Personnel Command in St. Louis, said the POW medal was sent
to Casenelli because of the recommendation of Presley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the word of the local base commanders,'' Coyner said.
``We assume they're not lying. But obviously, this was an honest
mistake. We will ask that the medal be rescinded. This is the first
time I've ever seen a case like this _ when we issued a medal that
didn't belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Presley said he wrote the letter to the Army personnel center
supporting Casenelli four years ago because veterans had encouraged
him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got involved because people from his VFW post asked me to
help,'' said Presley, who organized the medal presentation
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   At the VFW Post 4360 lounge in Palm Springs, a Palm Beach Post
article is framed on the wall. The headline reads ``Vietnam veteran
gets POW medal.'' Friends at the VFW who thought they knew
Casenelli were reeling after finding out they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There cannot be anyone more shocked than myself,'' said Doug
Byrum, the post commander and a retired Navy chief petty officer.
``I never had an inkling anything like this was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   To join the VFW, veterans are required to submit their DD-214
discharge forms. Officers at the post said they do not have
Casenelli's paperwork or know what he submitted some time during
the early '80s to gain membership.
</P>
<P>
   Byrum said he first met Casenelli about 15 years ago when they
worked together in the small engine repair business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just always assumed he was what he said he was,'' Byrum
said. ``This is very devastating to hear, knowing him as personally
as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Manion, the post commander in '94 and a Vietnam vet, said
Casenelli was an engaging and personable member of the VFW
brotherhood. His black pickup truck had POW vanity plates. He had a
pilot's license.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed like what he was supposed to be, his friends said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that he was that great a storyteller _ it's just
that he was so pleasant every time you saw him,'' Manion said. ``He
seemed like the kind of guy you could believe. We took a lot on
faith, I guess. It makes me sick that we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Casenelli's claim was implausible on its face because of the
time line he presented. As late as last week, he steadfastly
maintained he had been freed by the Vietnamese in 1976 _ three
years after the mass release of nearly 600 American POWs after the
signing of the Paris peace accord. Only Marine Pvt. Robert Garwood,
who was repatriated in 1979, has surfaced since the '73 release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe whatever makes you happy,'' Casenelli said last
Tuesday. ``If you want to believe I was in the Florida Keys, then I
guess I was in the Florida Keys.''
</P>
<P>
   After repeated requests for documentation of his military
service, Casenelli sent a fax to The Palm Beach Post that read:
``Can NOT provide documentation you requested. Returned to FLA.
Keys sometime after 1973. (Not sure of date or year). Am returning
medal and certificates to Lt. Col. Dave Presley.''
</P>
<P>
   The medal had not been returned as of last Thursday. In another
faxed statement, Casenelli admitted living in Marathon in 1974, not
in a cage in Vietnam as he once maintained. He would not respond to
questions about why he distorted his record.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the family say Casenelli was not known as
``Jay'' until after he moved to Marathon in '74. Before then, when
he lived in Georgia, he was known as Arnold Byron Casenelli, the
name given him at his birth in Kentucky on May 11, 1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew him as Arnold,'' said Ada Elton, a former neighbor of
the Casenelli family in Hazlehurst, Ga. ``We knew them quite well
in the early '70s. We saw quite a bit of them and he was always
Arnold or A.B. Casenelli.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she and her husband, Dr. Robert Elton, socialized with
Casenelli and his wife, Pat, in Hazlehurst during the years he
claimed to have been held captive in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.B. was not in the Vietnam War,'' Robert Elton said.
</P>
<P>
   Some time during the mid '70s, Arnold Casenelli started going by
the name ``Jay Angelo'' and listing his birth date as June 5, 1933
_ which is the birth date of his younger sister, Joyce Angela
Casenelli.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the family say when Arnold ceased to be, Jay,
the Vietnam war hero, was born.
</P>
<P>
   Casenelli moved to West Palm Beach in 1984. He taught flying at
the Lantana airport and has worked on airplane engines. In 1991,
friends threw him a surprise party in a hangar at the airport. The
celebration was to mark the 15th anniversary of Casenelli's release
by the Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Smith, head of the ladies' auxiliary at the Palm Springs
VFW post, said she has known Casenelli for years and is puzzled his
deception was not uncovered by the veterans he befriended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know how he was able to pull this off,'' Smith
said. ``I can't figure that out. Maybe he was just around people
long enough to tell them his stories and then he backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrum is equally perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I knew him pretty well,'' he said. ``I guess he
fooled me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
