<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-IMMUNITY (San Francisco) _ A mystery factor that protects
some people from HIV infection, despite repeated exposure to the
virus, is under investigation at the University of California at
San Francisco. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-AGRARIANS (Gualala, Calif.) _ Like hundreds of others,
Bonnie Simons and Pat Kelly swapped their suits for sweat shirts,
their mega-mainframe systems for portable word processors _ and
headed to this 80-mile stretch of craggy coastline to work via the
Internet. By ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-MEDICAID (San Francisco) _ A University of California at San
Francisco team has called for expanding Medicaid coverage to
provide anti-AIDS drugs to those who have been infected by the
virus but haven't developed full-blown symptoms of the disease. By
KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIVERMORE-WHISTLEBLOWER (San Francisco) _ The U.S. Occupational
Safety and Health Administration has upheld a Lawrence Livermore
nuclear weapons worker's claim that his employers unfairly
retaliated against him for reporting safety violations. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   TAXES-WAGES (San Antonio) _ Companies now will have to pay seven
of every 10 of their workers at least $9.27 an hour if they want to
ensure they will receive a tax break from the city of San Antonio.
By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS (San Francisco) _ A recent survey by George Mason
University found that nearly half the workers questioned said they
would have chosen a different major, something in science or
technology, if they had it to do over. The survey also found that
40 percent of those in high-tech said they would have chosen a
different major. The other man's path is always greener. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
