   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STRUGGLING-ACTORS (Albany, N.Y.) _ In New York City, they wait
tables. In Los Angeles, they tend bar. In Albany, they sell books.
If you get a monologue along with your purchase at a local
bookstore, don't be alarmed. Alas, poor Yorick, it's just another
aspiring actor. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ALEXIE-PROFILE (Undated) _ Screenwriter Sherman Alexie,
whose novels have the bite of a mad dog but rely on the beauty of
the human spirit, talks about his latest project: ``Smoke
Signals.'' The movie garnered the Audience Award and the Filmmakers
Trophy at the most recent Sundance Film Festival. By ANDY SUMMA.
</P>
<P>
   INCA-GOLD (San Francisco) _ David Ultan and Adam Ballachey were
both 29, struggling to launch careers as documentary filmmakers and
working as house painters when they got The Call. It was an
invitation for the young Berkeley residents to drop their
paintbrushes and take up their cameras. By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-WHITE-PROFILE (Undated) _ Author and commentator Bailey
White's personal style may keep her uneasy in the spotlight, but it
endears her to her fans as well. White wrote ``Quite a Year for
Plums.'' By CAROL RUST.
</P>
