A1853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Three outrageous ones
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever happened to our respect for love and marriage, for
religion and politics? It's outrageous the way we disparage these
righteous institutions, especially in the jokes we tell.
</P>
<P>
   I submit the following as unconscionable examples:
</P>
<P>
   Outrageous joke No. 1:
</P>
<P>
   A fellow was walking alone on the beach when he spied a swimmer
in trouble way out in the surf.
</P>
<P>
   Not thinking twice, he dove in, swam out to him and rescued him.
Once safely on the beach, it was only then that he noticed how tiny
the man was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saved my life!'' the little man gasped. ``I'm a magic elf.
To reward you I will grant you any three wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure,'' the fellow chuckled. ``Well, magic elf, let's
just call it even.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he waved goodbye and started on down the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But the magic elf, who indeed was a magic elf, couldn't let him
go unrewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant him great health and great wealth,'' the magic elf
intoned, conjuring up his powers, ``and also a wonderful sex
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years passed. The magic elf was sitting in a tree in
Central Park, as magic elves routinely do, when lo and behold,
coming down the path was the man who saved his life all those years
before.
</P>
<P>
   Hopping from the tree, the magic elf exclaimed, ``Remember me?''
</P>
<P>
   The man, momentarily startled, broke into a wide grin. ``How
could I ever forget you,'' he said, laughing. ``You're the only
magic elf I ever saved from drowning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So how's life treating you?'' the magic elf said,
nonchalantly. ``You look like you're in good health.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I ever!'' the man said. ``It's as if my health gets better
and better every year that I grow older. The doctors can't explain
it. It's like a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, like a miracle,'' the elf said, smiling to himself. ``And
you look prosperous as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's even more remarkable,'' the man said. ``Every little
investment I've ever made has turned into a fortune. Nowadays I
have to have two full-time accountants just to keep up with my
money. It's a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, indeed,'' the elf said, all the more pleased. ``And how
about the romance department. Has Cupid been kind to you as well?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really wild!'' the man said, waving his arms and
laughing aloud. ``Who'd have ever thought a guy like me would be so
popular with women.'' At this point, he lowered his voice. ``I
don't like to brag, but it's sometimes as often as twice a month.''
</P>
<P>
   The elf frowned. ``Twice a month? That doesn't seem very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The man shrugged. ``For a priest in a small parish,'' he
allowed, ``it's not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Outrageous joke No. 2:
</P>
<P>
   A fellow was out working in his yard when a strange funeral
procession passed in front of his house.
</P>
<P>
   There was a hearse followed by a second hearse followed by a man
with a dog followed by some 200 other men walking single file.
</P>
<P>
   The fellow left his yard work and fell in step with the man and
the dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to intrude,'' he said, ``but I'm curious as to
whose funeral this is.''
</P>
<P>
   The man with the dog nodded solemnly. ``That first hearse is for
my wife,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm sorry to hear that,'' the fellow said. ``What happened
to her?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dog bit her and she died,'' the man said, looking straight
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the second hearse?'' the fellow asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for my mother-in-law,'' the man said. ``The dog bit
her, too, and she died.''
</P>
<P>
   The fellow paused for a moment before speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say,'' he asked, ``could I borrow your dog?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in line,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   Outrageous joke No. 3:
</P>
<P>
   Friday about 2 p.m., the teacher announced to her fourth-grade
class that any of the students who could recite a famous quote and
correctly attribute it would be allowed to leave early.
</P>
<P>
   One little girl immediately jumped to her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A house divided against itself cannot stand. Abraham
Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very good,'' said the teacher. ``You may leave early.''
</P>
<P>
   A second girl stood up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to fear but fear itself. Franklin Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent,'' said the teacher. ``You may leave early, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For a long moment no other child responded. Finally, a
red-haired, freckle-faced boy from the back of the class rose to
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those girls are lying,'' he declared. ``Girls are always
making things up. There's no truth to what they say. Bill Clinton.
See you Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   I only hope you're as outraged as much as I am.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
