<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ALEXIE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT RESERVATIONS: FILMMAKER INTERPRETS MODERN INDIAN LIFE VIA
BUDDIE ROAD MOVIE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDY SUMMA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has a booming voice that fills a room and a dry wit that
crinkles eyebrows. The 6-foot-2-inch Sherman Alexie has a gentle
handshake, as if he's afraid he'll crush your hand, but he has a
choke-hold on the world's social jugular.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's novels have the bite of a mad dog but rely on the
beauty of the human spirit. The Coeur d'Alene Indian screenwriter
of the critically acclaimed ``Smoke Signals'' considers himself a
reclusive artist but is quick to talk about his childhood and his
political views.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is difficult to characterize without using the word
``but.'' Fortunately, his literary stylings are less ambiguous. The
31-year-old author has written nine virtuosic books, each with a
different slant on the oft-stereotyped American Indian experience.
All have been commercial and critical successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' is the first feature film written, directed
and co-produced by Indians. As its screenwriter, Alexie is proud to
be part of cinematic history.
</P>
<P>
   The film already has garnered the Audience Award and the
Filmmakers Trophy at the most recent Sundance Film Festival. The
``Spitfire Grill'' won the Audience Award in 1996, and ``In the
Company of Men,'' a breakout indie hit, nabbed the Filmmakers
Trophy last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' is typical of Alexie's work: rich in
symbolism, peppered with social statements and laced with disarming
humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a movie that challenges the cinematic history of
Indians,'' said Alexie, who grew up on the Spokane Indian
Reservation in Washington state. ``In most films, Indians have been
stoic. That's the stereotype of what Indians are supposed to be _
stoic and alcoholic, depressed poor people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in fact, Indians are the most joyous people in the world.
The two funniest groups of people I've been around have been
Indians and Jews. So I guess there's something to be said about the
inherent humor of genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   It was with such scathing humor that Alexie wrote ``Smoke
Signals,'' based on his 1994 collection of short stories, ``The
Lone Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven'' ($12.50,
HarperPerennial).
</P>
<P>
   Like the man who wrote the script, ``Smoke Signals'' is rough
but gentle, serious, but singed with humor. And it's not exactly
what you'd expect.
</P>
<P>
   As if to announce the film is different from past American
Indian fare, a disc jockey says early in the movie, ``It's a good
day to be indigenous.''
</P>
<P>
   The script's comical overtones and reflective undertones enabled
``Smoke Signals'' to transcend the unseen cage Hollywood has made
for Indian portrayals, Alexie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences aren't stupid,'' the Washington State University
graduate said. ``They want good stories. And I think `Smoke
Signals' has a great story. Who cares that it's about Indians?
People want to see a movie they can relate to, regardless of
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, a recovering alcoholic who has been sober for seven
years, said the film's story is about a precious emotional
resource: forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Its protagonist, Victor Joseph (Adam Beach), hasn't seen his
alcoholic father in more than 10 years. Victor's father, Arnold,
had been given an ultimatum: Quit drinking or leave. He left.
</P>
<P>
   Since his father left him and his mother, Victor has grown into
a strong and athletic ``pseudo-tough'' young man who can't let go
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   He feels partly responsible for his father's absence. Not
helping matters is his unwanted sidekick, Thomas Builds-the-Fire
(Evan Adams), a dorky, compulsive storyteller who continually tells
tales about Victor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Word soon comes to the reservation in Idaho that Arnold has died
in Arizona. Victor needs to pick up some of his father's things,
but can't afford to go.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He'll pay for Victor's trip _ if he can tag along. Victor
reluctantly agrees, and they set out on a journey across the
country _ and across parental divides.
</P>
<P>
   Part buddy film, part drama, ``Smoke Signals'' is a
character-driven movie. Alexie, who lists ``The Graduate'' and
``Midnight Cowboy'' as his favorite films, said this was no
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victor and Thomas are really half of me,'' he said. ``I've
always been a storytelling geek jock. I'm a guy who rambles on,
telling stories and irritating the hell out of people around me.
I'm also large and athletic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a pathological liar,'' he joked. ``But now I
get paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   A self-described ``rags-to-riches'' story, Alexie was born
hydrocephalic and underwent brain surgery when he was 6 months old.
He wasn't expected to survive, and if he did, doctors said, he
would be mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alexie pulled through with no long-term effects. His
condition, however, left him weak and unable to lead an active
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sickly growing up,'' said the Seattle resident. ``I had
seizures and was bedridden. Most little boys use their energy
physically. My energy was used internally. I created imaginary
worlds for myself. I'm a storyteller because I had to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He also buried himself in books. His father, who worked as a
truck driver and as a logger on and off the reservation, was an
avid reader. Alexie followed suit, reading everything he could get
his hands on, from basketball biographies and mechanical handbooks
to cheesy westerns.
</P>
<P>
   But the fraternal influence on Alexie's life goes deeper than
reading habits. As evidenced by the emotionally charged, unspoken
bond between father and son in ``Smoke Signals,'' Alexie's
relationship with his dad is special to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good friends,'' Alexie said, carefully choosing his
words.
</P>
<P>
   But ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had difficulty, mostly when we were younger,'' he said.
``We're at that point where I love him, but I'm pissed off at him.
And I can tell him both things.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, a new parent along with his wife, Diane, who is a member
of the Hidatsa tribe in North Dakota, had to be patient bringing
his paternal movie to the big screen. Before finally collaborating
with first-time director Chris Eyre (a Cheyenne/Arapaho Indian), he
shopped the film around _ with qualified success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have sold this film to studios. They wanted it. They
wanted the screenplay and the book,'' he said. ``But I wanted an
Indian director.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one producer wanted the script _ if he could make one
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to this famous movie producer, he knows who he
is,'' Alexie said, smiling. ``He looked at me and said, `You know,
this is a very interesting story. A very cinematic road trip. Very
touching. Fathers, sons. But do you think we can make these
characters white?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about about 10 seconds to walk out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the film is exactly what he envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals is going to be wildly successful,'' he said,
beaming like a proud papa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be `The Full Monty' with braves and
darker skin.''
</P>
<P>
   But if it's not, it will still destroy a few myths, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumor of the demise of our culture is greatly
exaggerated,'' he said. `` We're very strong, and we're surviving
quite well, thank you.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
