<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXUAL-FREEDOM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DID WOMEN START WEARING SLACKS? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A friend sent me a video cassette of a 69-year-old
Hollywood movie because, he said, it helped put many aspects of
modern life into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The film is called ``The Divorcee,'' and my friend was right. It
demonstrates that there is very little novel happening in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Feminism? Career women? Rebellion against double standards for
the two sexes? Sexual freedom? They are all present in this 1929
movie, one of the first talkies, which, although I'm a cinema buff,
I had never heard of before.
</P>
<P>
   The title role is played by the renowned star Norma Shearer, and
just to make matters clear from the start, she appears in several
early scenes garbed in slacks _ very daring feminine apparel in
1929 even though the other characters seem to take it in their
stride.
</P>
<P>
   This, incidentally, lays to rest the widely believed myth that
slacks were ``invented'' by an exotic European, Marlene Dietrich,
in the mid-1930s and only hesitatingly adopted by American females.
Not so. Here is home-grown Norma Shearer wearing them years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Shearer is a high-salaried career woman who travels
a lot and has a hectic professional life outside of her marriage to
_ heaven help him _ a journalist. Remember, this is 1929, long
before working women, except school teachers, are supposed to have
existed.
</P>
<P>
   But Norma is a faithful wife. When she discovers her husband has
strayed, she divorces him _ by 1929, not as rare an occurence as
one might think. One of her friends has also been divorced and
explains the ``great time'' she has had ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Divorcee'' is full of sex, but there's not a scene or any
language that anyone possibly could object to. As for nudity, there
is not so much as a naked wrist. The result intensifies rather than
diminishes the sexual meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Before splitting with her spouse, Norma also commits adultery _
depicted by a drawn curtain _ and later announces to him that
``I've squared accounts.'' No one could possibly misunderstand her.
</P>
<P>
   The husband had tried to dismiss his own unfaithfulness as ``not
meaning a thing.'' That really infuriates her. Of course, when she
confesses her own transgression, he explodes and walks out. One
must remember that the idea that male infidelity was to be expected
and should be condoned by an all-forgiving wife had long been part
of the social mythology. ``The Divorcee'' reflects how things were
changing.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly an aspect of the contemporary world isn't touched on in
this remarkable film. An example: at one point, a character
announces that his career has received a significant boost by ``the
offer from my company of a big job in the Far East.''
</P>
<P>
   Who says America's global economic expansion began after World
War II?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
