</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADETTRIAL-JUDGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRICT JUDGE TAKES TRIAL OF FORMER CADET IN STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Looming down from one wall of his chambers,
a yellowing flier from 1909 touts a pro wrestling bout featuring
one of Judge Don Leonard's grandfathers.
</P>
<P>
   Across the small office with a view of the Trinity River is an
almost Technicolor-like portrait of John Wayne framed by a pair of
steer horns _ given to the judge only half-jokingly in 1991 after
Leonard wrestled a gun from a murder defendant who was trying to
take him hostage and escape.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, the senior-most district judge in Tarrant County,
doesn't shy away from those old Texas stereotypes but rather
embraces them in a lighthearted way. It's what he grew up with as a
boy in Waco, where he watched Gene Autrey and Roy Rogers films at
the movie house on Saturday afternoons and lived and breathed
sports, high school football in particular.
</P>
<P>
   In his 16th year on the judge's bench, Leonard said the upcoming
trial of former Air Force Academy cadet David Graham will easily
rank as his biggest trial, from a publicity standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The media presence is a necessary headache that helps educate
those who rarely set foot in the courthouse, but it has the power
to disrupt attorneys, jurors and even judges, he said. Leonard
promises he is far beyond getting wrapped up in the media dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more publicity than any case I can remember,'' he said.
``I don't think it's as big as the media does. In the end, it's
still a murder case that has to be tried in a certain way.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard comes from a Central Texas family whose devotion to
criminal justice and public safety stretches back three
generations. The wrestling grandfather with the broad chest and
thick, wavy hair later served as a firefighter in Waco. His father
was a Waco police officer for 25 years who became police chief in
Mexia and only recently retired as a district court bailiff.
</P>
<P>
   The career Leonard really wanted to pursue was football, either
as a player or a coach. He played offensive guard on highly ranked
Waco High School teams and played one year for Tarleton State
University in Stephenville, but he realized he didn't quite have
the swiftness or the size to make a living on the gridiron.
</P>
<P>
   After marrying his wife, Judith, 42 years ago when they were
both freshmen at Tarleton State, they moved to Austin, where
Leonard earned his law degree, and ultimately to Fort Worth, where
he began working in 1961 as an assistant city attorney. They have
two grown daughters and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very rewarding at the end of the day to go home to
somebody who is caring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His friends say Leonard has honed a style that is easygoing and
reliant on humor while conveying a sense that he'll only bend so
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know what my role is supposed to be,'' he said.
``You can push me to a point, but I'm not a daisy when it gets
right down to push and shove.''
</P>
<P>
   If he thinks you're wasting his time, he might look up from his
reading glasses and ask if you're an animal-rights activist intent
on keeping him away from his house on Lake Texoma and the hunting
and fishing he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much unhappiness that comes through here that I try
to be pleasant,'' he said. ``The work can get you down if you let
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The door to his chambers is rarely closed, and the bustle in and
out is so great that he often has to leave his office if he wants
to have a private conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the facade and the homespun sense of humor is a strong
intellect, said Fort Worth defense attorney Jerry Loftin, who met
Leonard 30 years ago when they both had law offices in the Union
Bank building.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a down-to-earth, smart-as-a-whip judge,'' Loftin said.
``He runs a trial very effectively. He controls a trial. He's
intelligent and smart enough to know how everyone can get a fair
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a connoisseur of barbecue, although he has lost 40 pounds
since he agreed to accept the Graham case from his longtime friend,
District Judge Joe Drago, who presided over Diane Zamora's capital
murder trial and chose not to hear Graham's case.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's trial is expected to last a month, with seven days
reserved for questioning prospective jurors. The former Air Force
Academy cadet faces life in prison if convicted of the December
1995 beating and shooting death of 16-year-old Adrianne Jones of
Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora, Graham's former fiancee, was convicted in February for
her role in the slaying and was sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been made big by whatever makes cases big,''
Leonard said. ``I think your reputation as a judge isn't how you
handle the great big cases. It should be on how steady you are
every day. That's what I try to do. It forms good work habits.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
