<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS HOPE HIV RESISTANCE YIELDS CLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Researchers are investigating a mystery factor
that protects some people from HIV infection, despite repeated
exposure to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Studying 60 subjects who engage in high-risk behaviors that
repeatedly expose them to the virus, researchers at the University
of California at San Francisco were amazed when only one was
infected over a 30-month period.
</P>
<P>
   The finding strengthens hopes that, eventually, scientists will
develop a vaccine against the human immunodeficiency virus, which
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Scientist Sharen Stranford and her associates selected 60 people
who seemed to be at high risk of HIV infection, either because they
shared hypodermic needles or had sex numerous times with someone
infected by the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, following the study, only one had been infected by
HIV. The rest showed no sign of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Their CD8+ T cells display an unusual form of immune response.
Therein may lie the secret of the resistance to HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have beat the odds for many years,'' said
Stranford, who prepared her findings for the 12th World AIDS
Congress, which was held last week in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our subjects are gay men who had unprotected sex with
men who (later) died from AIDS, so they assumed they were infected
and later found out they were not,'' Stranford noted.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of T cells, distinguished by different
protein receptors on their surfaces. One type is CD4+ T cells,
which HIV readily attacks.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Stranford's team found that CD8+ T cells in the
study group somehow prevent HIV from copying itself.
</P>
<P>
   Stranford hypothesizes that for these people, and others like
them, low-dose exposure to HIV acts like a natural vaccination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repeated exposures may provide a boost to the immune system
without infecting the cells, like a natural vaccine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, a vaccine for HIV could be possible.
</P>
<P>
   The findings ``provide great encouragement for the ultimate
development of a vaccine to HIV,'' said Jay Levy, a professor of
medicine at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Stranford's colleagues in the study were Dennis Osmond, also of
San Francisco; Joan Skurnick and Donald Louria of New Jersey
Medical School; Sheng-Yung Chang and John Sninsky of Roche
Molecular Systems in Alameda, Calif.; Dr. Guido Ferrari and Kent
Weinhold of Duke University; and Dr. Craig Lindquist of Marin
County Specialty Clinic in Greenbrae, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Stranford team's finding ``has been suspected for some
time,'' said Dr. Michael Horberg, president of the Gay and Lesbian
Medical Association in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   This welcome insensitivity to infection isn't unique to the AIDS
epidemic, Horberg adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back to other epidemics of our time _ the flu
epidemics of the early 1900s, the `great plague' _ there were
people who did not get infected,'' Horberg said.
</P>
<P>
   He speculates that they, too, were blessed with a mysterious
immune resistance to certain types of infections.
</P>
</TEXT>
