<SLUG> BC-HIV-MEDICAID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS URGED EXPANSION OF MEDICAID TO COVER HIV INFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Medicaid program should be expanded to
provide anti-AIDS drugs to those who have been infected by the
virus but have not developed full-blown symptoms of the disease,
experts at the University of California at San Francisco say.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid currently covers drug treatments only for people who
have developed full-blown AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combination therapy using anti-retroviral medications is now
available and for the first time offers real hope for controlling
HIV infection, but not everyone has access to these drugs,'' said
Dr. James G. Kahn of the university's AIDS Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   By expanding Medicaid coverage to those infected by the human
immunodeficiency virus, but not yet afflicted by AIDS, thousands of
deaths could be averted, Kahn said. He prepared findings in
collaboration with Brian Haile for the 12th World AIDS Congress,
which was held last week in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Schatz, executive director of the Gay and Lesbian
Medical Association in San Francisco, said the Medicaid issue is
``another problem those of us on the AIDS Council have had with the
(Clinton) administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President (Al) Gore promised a year ago to get expanded
Medicaid coverage for people with HIV,'' Schatz said. Yet the
expanded coverage has been impeded, Schatz charged, by ``number
crunchers'' at the Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sinking in a quagmire of numbers crunching _ and people
are dying ... This is a national disgrace. It points out glaring
weaknesses in our health care system,'' Schatz said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid is a program funded by the federal and state
governments that helps pay for health care for the needy. In 1996,
state and federal governments spent a combined $160 billion serving
more than 36 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to expand Medicaid coverage reflects larger
political realities, Schatz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have HIV are gay men, drug users and poor
people of color, none of whom are on the top 10 hit parade of the
GOP ...''
</P>
<P>
   There is ``a general hostility toward spending money on the
needy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hopkins, director of federal affairs for the AIDS
Foundation, said: ``I agree with the assessment of the UCSF
researchers that we could reduce the AIDS death rate considerably
if we were able to expand the Medicaid coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the vice president absolutely wanted to
(expand) this. The vice president clearly understands the dilemma
that we're in; you don't want to wait until someone is next to
death before you provide them with care.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately ``the bureaucrats stepped in,'' Hopkins added with
a sigh, ``and once that happens, a lot of really good ideas and
initiatives fall by the wayside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
