A1919 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN04-COX     07-06 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A land ethic for July 4
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My 10-year-old friend in Tiger, Ga., the rural
community that's home on weekends, brought me a tiny jar of
huckleberries recently. ``You can eat 'em,'' he said, with a big
grin. ``They're hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   The small jar of purple-black berries seemed a proper symbol for
my thinking this July Fourth _ my thinking about how hard it is for
most American families, in city and suburbs, to provide their
children with experiences that connect them to America's natural
majesty. Aldo Leopold, who founded the National Wilderness Society,
called a closeness to the land ``the split-rail value.'' He termed
it ``nationalism in the best sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Split-rail values sound very Republican. They could describe
Teddy Roosevelt, the president who decided some of America's
majestic places should belong to all of the people, not just to the
rich. I wish U.S. Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) and some of his GOP
colleagues would study Roosevelt's thinking. Surely one of
Georgia's last undeveloped barrier islands, which lies in
Kingston's district, qualifies as a majestic place. The island's
white sand dunes and wild horses are so breath-taking that John F.
Kennedy,Jr. and Carolyn Bessette chose it as the spot for their
wedding. Congress designated 20,000 acres of Cumberland Island as
wilderness in the 1980s. Now Kingston wants to work a land trade to
give some of the island wilderness back to the wealthy family that
sold it to the park service. Kingston's ``Cumberland Island
Preservation Act'' is enough to make Roosevelt turn over in his
grave.
</P>
<P>
   The island is already listed by the National Wilderness Society
as one of the nation's 17 most endangered wildlands, along with
irreplaceable spots in Colorado, Utah, Alaska and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston's efforts on Cumberland Island might make more sense if
there were not a plan in place to preserve that tract at no expense
to taxpayers _ thanks to the Nature Conservancy and funds earmarked
in the federal Land and Water Conservation Fund. That fund is
financed from royalties paid to the federal government by companies
that hold offshore oil and gas leases, and its purpose is to
preserve environmental treasures as token compensation for
depletion of a finite natural resource that belongs to all of the
people. Some Republicans who are friendly with oil giants_like U.S.
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas)_ hardly out of the Teddy
Roosevelt mold, want to abolish the fund altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing about the Kingston bill is that the land the
Candlers would receive _ the island's highest and most beautiful
cliffs _ would be granted to them in fee-simple ownership, which
means the land wouldn't revert to public ownership, as the family's
current life estate will do when the youngest designated heir is
gone.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the politicians who need to study our historic
land ethic. Some of our corporate giants do, too. Georgia's
Okefenokee Swamp is also on the endangered wildlands list because
the DuPont Company wants to mine titanium dioxide on its edge. Says
DuPont president C.O. Holliday, ``Environmental impact has to be
viewed alongside the total value a company offers society.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think Roosevelt or Leopold would agree that the
irreplaceable plants and wildlife can be given a dollar value.
Maybe it's a philosophical debate worth airing, though.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's nothing philosophical about the
recent remarks of U.S. Rep. Don Young (R-Alaska), chairman of the
House Resources Committee. ``I don't see any justification for the
federal government owning land, other than the Statue of Liberty
and maybe a few parks,'' Young declared.
</P>
<P>
   On July Fourth, what I wish is that some of today's leaders
would spend more time hunting for huckleberries.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
