<SLUG> BC-ROOT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILINGUALISM ALIVE AND WELL IN TEXAS POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Writing about politics these days is becoming
exotic. Or perhaps I should say: ``Escribir sobre la politica llega
a ser exotico.''
</P>
<P>
   As politicians reach out to Latinos, Spanish more than ever is
being sprinkled into political speeches, served up in news releases
and used in interviews on Spanish-language media.
</P>
<P>
   Spicing up your rhetoric with a little ``espanol'' is no
guarantee of success, but it can help your standing with Latino
voters, says Rodolfo de la Garza, vice president of the Tomas
Rivera Policy Institute at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is less that you speak it correctly than you attempt to
speak it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where more than a quarter of the population is Latino,
both candidates in the Land Office race _ Democrat Richard Raymond,
Hispanic despite his Anglo name, and Republican David Dewhurst, a
former CIA officer _ speak Spanish well enough to do TV interviews.
</P>
<P>
   And Republican Gov. George W. Bush has been fearless, if not
fluent like his brother Jeb, as he attempts to communicate directly
with Spanish speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides delivering occasional sound bites to the
Spanish-language press, Bush laid out a bilingual welcome mat to
Hispanics during the Texas Republican Convention last month in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tenemos los mismos valores'' (We have the same values), Bush
told the overwhelmingly Anglo audience.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats _ Spanish-speaking or not _ were quick to grasp
the meaning of Bush's foray into the party's traditional base.
</P>
<P>
   ``While George Bush is delivering part of his GOP convention
speech in Spanish ... we fall further behind the curve,'' San
Augustine County Judge Curt Goetz complained in a flier advertising
his ultimately unsuccessful campaign for chairman of the state
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Goetz also called GOP Texas Railroad Commission candidate Tony
Garza, a fluent Spanish speaker, ``a real threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, one Democrat after another offered up a
Spanish line or two at their own convention last month in San
Antonio. Although Democrats have long peppered their speeches with
Spanish expressions, this year they dropped in full sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nosostros podemos hablar espanol tambien'' (We can speak
Spanish, too), said Paul Hobby, the Democratic candidate for
comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant governor hopeful John Sharp also dropped non-English
words into his speech, although listeners could be forgiven for
thinking his pronunciation of ``educacion'' was an imitation of the
Cajun Man of ``Saturday Night Live'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   Although speaking Spanish can pay political dividends, the
often-hard-earned lesson is to proceed at your own riesgo. U.S.
House Speaker Newt Gingrich learned that the hard way recently when
he issued a seriously flawed Spanish news release. (Among other
things, Gingrich described himself as the ``Hablador de la Casa,''
which could be roughly translated as the ``Blowhard of the
House.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``That made him a fool,'' said UT's de la Garza. ``It did not
generate good will.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is chief of the Star-Telegram's Austin bureau. You can
write him at 1005 Congress Ave., Suite 920, Austin, TX 78701, or at
jroot(at)star-telegram.com, or call him at (512) 476-4294. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
