<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING DOORS AT BERKELEY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB WIEDER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROM: Director of Admissions, University of California at
Berkeley
</P>
<P>
   TO: Application Readers &AMP; Evaluators
</P>
<P>
   As you know, the San Francisco Examiner recently wrote about the
fact that we have begun placing increased emphasis on essays
written by applicants, especially hardship essays, in which the
student recounts any notable obstacles, impediments or adversities
he or she had to overcome to succeed academically, such as
disability or illness, abject poverty, a broken or dysfunctional
home, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   As you also know, our applicants are highly ambitious and
intelligent young Californians, which means they are as crafty,
opportunistic and duplicitous a group as you will find outside the
Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Already, we've seen an increased incidence of hardship claims.
Staff members have asked for some guidelines. Since each case must
be judged on its own unique merits, and because we know a
litigation mine field when we see one, no binding guidelines will
be issued. Instead, here are some illustrative claims.
</P>
<P>
   And our recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANCY: I was pregnant for most of my sophomore year, and
that dragged my grades down overall, especially first-period
chemistry, which I kept missing because I was in the girls' room
blowing chunks every morning.
</P>
<P>
   It's the most frequent question we are asked: Is pregnancy a
hardship, or the natural consequence of a conscious decision, or
just what she gets for being a little tramp?
</P>
<P>
   But the real question is: If we call pregnancy a hardship, will
the right-to-life groups freak out and deluge us with angry e-mail
and petition the Legislature to start jerking us around? The answer
is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, pregnancy is not a hardship but a blessing. (And if
she couldn't manage birth control, she would have flunked chemistry
anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   Rejected.
</P>
<P>
   INCARCERATION: I missed most of the 10th grade because I was
doing 10 months at the San Luis Obispo Youth Facility, where they
sent me for the unwise usage of a shotgun during a convenience
store transaction. This played hell with my grade point average,
because they grade a lot tougher in the SLO Equivalency Program
than they do in high school. Also, I had to send back my NRA Boy of
the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, this is an eminently avoidable hardship. For
another, if we accept the premise that imprisonment for a criminal
offense is a valid hardship, we could ultimately find ourselves
having to admit brilliant sociopaths, compulsive troublemakers and
former government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected.
</P>
<P>
   DEPRIVATION: We didn't have a computer at home until I was
almost 14, and it was this old reconditioned Canon with about as
much memory as a toaster, and even then I could never use it
because my mom was on this Parents Without Partners chat site
trolling for availables like 19 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't even have a used Canon when we were your age. We had
to get by with a damn slide rule! And the winters were colder, too!
</P>
<P>
   Rejected.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN: It isn't just that I grew up in Oakland, and have thus had
to compensate for underfunded and inadequate educational resources.
It's also that I am a Golden State Warriors basketball fan, which
has been a tremendous emotional and intellectual burden.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks it's easy to care about quadratic equations or
concentrate on intermediate Spanish when ESPN is ragging on your
team and Jay Leno is doing Sprewell jokes, that person doesn't know
what hardship is.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, your director is the holder of season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Admit the kid.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Wieder is a free-lance writer in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
