<HEADLINE>
IN NAPLES, HONESTY PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Italy _ Just as animals are said to be able to smell
fear, I've always suspected the world's hustlers, pickpockets and
scam-artists can smell jet lag. Bleary-eyed, bedraggled and 10
times zones from home, we newly arrived travelers make irresistibly
ripe targets for fleecing.
</P>
<P>
   That must have been how the man behind the ticket window at the
Metropolitana subway in Rome saw me as I stood before him, a dazed,
disoriented look on my face and a backpack with fresh airline
luggage tags on my back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due _ Stazione Termini,'' I said, using the sum total of my
Italian, and slid a crisp new 10,000-lire note under the glass.
Without looking up he slid two tickets and two coins back and
gestured for me to step aside for the next customer.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1 in these situations is to know in advance how much
things cost and precisely how much you should be getting back in
change. I knew the subway tickets were 1,500 lire each; even my jet
lag-addled mind could compute that I should have received 7,000
lire back. As I started to turn away I examined the two coins: they
were 1,000 lire each.
</P>
<P>
   I pushed my way back to the window, holding up my tickets and
coins. ``Hey,'' I said, I'm sure I gave you ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Before I could finish, the man gave me an insolent shrug and,
with just the hint of a smirk, slid a 5,000-lire note under the
glass. He didn't even have the decency to pretend that he'd made a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   As Jeri and I rode the jam-packed subway to the train station I
congratulated myself on my savvy. It's rare that I make it through
the first couple days of an overseas trip without being fleeced out
of a tidy little sum by a dishonest taxi driver, street hustler or
would-be guide. I'd never encountered a crooked subway
ticket-seller before, but I'd been up to the challenge. Maybe I was
finally getting the hang of this, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   The worst was yet to come, though: Later that day we'd have to
pass through Naples. Since I was a little boy I'd heard so many
stories that I'd come to fear the city as little more than an
open-air convention of the world's most venial muggers, kidnappers,
robbers, extortionists, assassins, con men, burglars, swindlers and
purse-snatchers. In my overwrought imagination I pictured us
running a gauntlet of sinister gangsters and stubble-faced thugs
picking their teeth with switchblades.
</P>
<P>
   My guidebook tried to be reassuring: ``Violent crime is high,
but it is concentrated mostly among the local Mafia gangs; tourists
are rarely targets for anything more than petty thievery and
pickpocketing.'' That made me feel so much better.
</P>
<P>
   As we made our way through the Naples train station I was as
jumpy as Don Knotts. I kept one hand on my wallet, stuffed deep
into my front pocket, and the other around my passport pouch, worn
under my shirt against my chest. Alert for trouble coming from any
direction, my head swiveled on my neck like Linda Blair in the
``Exorcist.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the only Napoleans we encountered were
friendly and tried to help us find the right track for Sorrento. No
one tried to pick our pockets, hold a knife to our throats or
otherwise live up to Naples' frightful reputation. I began to
wonder whether all those stories were circulated by locals who
didn't want tourists monopolizing the restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the train pulled into Sorrento 90 minutes later, I
felt a palpable sense of relief. We'd survived the crucial first 48
hours of our trip without enriching any pickpockets, larcenous cab
drivers or shortchange artists. It was time to celebrate with a
gelato.
</P>
<P>
   We strolled into the first ``gelateria'' we found and spent a
few delightful minutes working our way up and down the long
counter, smacking our lips lasciviously as we surveyed the
three-dozen flavors: banana, strawberry, blackberry, cherry, lime,
peach, amoretto, chocolate, French vanilla, mint _ it went on and
on, each more tempting than the last. Finally I settled on banana
and chocolate mint; Jeri opted for banana and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Still on alert, I checked that the price was 3,000 lire for each
cone and handed the frowning signora at the cash register a
5,000-lire note and a 1,000-lire coin. ``Prego!'' I said as I
headed for the door.
</P>
<P>
   I was out on the sidewalk and raising my cone to my lips when I
heard the signora yelling at me. She was shaking her fist. I walked
back inside and saw that her fist was full of money. Her other hand
clutched the bank note I gave her _ not a 5,000, as I'd thought,
but a 50,000-lire bill. She counted out my change: 45,000 lire,
about $26. I'd practically begged her to cheat me; frankly, I
wouldn't have blamed her at all if she'd pocketed the money.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a lesson in this little story? I'd say there are two:
One, be ceaselessly alert and vigilant, particularly in the first
jet-lagged day or two of your trip. Even government officials like
the subway ticket vendor in Rome are suspect. And, two, remember
that most people in the world are heartwarmingly honest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
