<HEADER>
A1927 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADETTRIAL-LAWYER-TEX     07-06 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADETTRIAL-LAWYER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CADET'S LAWYER PERCEIVES JOB'S ADVANTAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ The phone call to Dan Cogdell came on a
Friday, the day after David Graham was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the Houston defense attorney said, his knowledge
of the charge against his future client was limited to news
headlines he had scrolled through on his pocket pager: Two military
academy appointees arrested and accused of the love-triangle
slaying of a Mansfield teen. But that alone was enough to make a
decision _ this was not a job that a defense attorney fond of big
trials would turn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shop for criminal lawyers the way they shop for
ambulances _ they call and you better come,'' he said. ``If you
don't come, they'll call another ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial won't fatten his bank account. It will take him away
from Houston and easier, more-lucrative cases for a full month. And
because of the mountain of evidence against his young client _ from
a handgun recovered in his parents' attic to a written confession
and testimony from some of his best friends _ anything short of a
capital murder conviction and a life sentence will be a shock,
legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may well lose this case,'' he said. ``The only thing worse
to me than losing a case is losing a case on the front page of
every newspaper in the country. ... If you do your job right, the
lawyers are going to understand how difficult this case is.''
</P>
<P>
   The promise of nationwide TV and newspaper coverage has a value
of its own, especially for trial attorneys who rely on reputation
to drum up business, said Dick DeGuerin, a prominent Houston
defense attorney who has worked with Cogdell. An aggressive defense
of a case widely regarded as difficult will probably be a winner
for Cogdell regardless of the outcome, DeGuerin said.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell, 41, will not say exactly what his fees are, but he has
said repeatedly that his defense would probably drain the Graham
family's finances. Indeed, he said, the divorced parents even
signed over their modest Mansfield house to pay for their son's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare person who can afford what a lawyer ought to
charge in a case like this,'' said DeGuerin, who has grabbed
headlines representing clients ranging from U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison's acquittal on records-tampering charges to Branch
Davidian leader David Koresh and his followers. ``I don't know of a
good, earnest criminal lawyer who doesn't salivate over a
challenging high-publicity case. It's a business-getter. People
remember your name. When someone gets in trouble, they call you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell's practice is a mixture of high-profile and
bread-and-butter cases. He claimed victory in May after a two-month
federal trial involving five current and former Houston city
officials accused of taking bribes ended with a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   That long trial put his other work on the back burner and
created a backlog of 17 felony cases for Cogdell that Houston-area
judges were itching to resolve before he left for New Braunfels and
the start of Graham's trial. As a result, Cogdell was scheduled for
jury trials _ from DWI misdemeanors to a transsexual client charged
with murder _ every week from the end of the Houston City Council
trial to the start of Graham's trial Monday.
</P>
<P>
   His associate, attorney Rob Swofford, has handled the bulk of
the preparation for Graham's case, while Cogdell wrapped up other
trials. Although this is an especially busy year with two
back-to-back, high-profile trials, he said he likes to spend 10
months out of the year in front of a jury.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom exposure _ even for a misdemeanor
drinking-and-driving charge _ keeps his trial procedures sharp,
such as his knowledge of trial law, reading juries and, of course,
theatrics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 21, is accused of plotting and carrying out a plan with
his former fiancee, Diane Zamora, to kill Adrianne Jones, who was
found beaten and shot to death along a rural southwest Grand
Prairie road in December 1995. After their arrests nine months
later, the two former military academy appointees each gave written
confessions to police, detailing how they agreed to kill the
Mansfield High School sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   The same team of prosecutors that won Zamora's capital murder
conviction will handle Graham's trial, which has been moved to New
Braunfels because of extensive publicity about the case in Tarrant
County. Assistant District Attorney Mike Parrish, the lead
prosecutor, is a former Dallas police officer with 17 years of
experience prosecuting some of the biggest cases in Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   After seven days of jury questioning, opening arguments in the
trial are scheduled to begin July 15. The trial is expected to last
four weeks. District Judge Don Leonard will spend a full week
asking prospective jurors what they have heard or read about the
allegations. Then prosecutors and the defense team will question
individual jurors and try to identify those whom they perceive as
either helpful or antagonistic to their sides.
</P>
<P>
   In legal circles, Hill Country residents are regarded as tough
jurors for the defense, and Cogdell said he had hoped the trial
would be moved instead to a large city with a more worldly
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got the reputation of being a very conservative,
pro-government town, and I'm sure that it is,'' Cogdell said.
``Sometimes very conservative, pro-law-enforcement people are more
sticklers for doing things the right way,'' he said, hinting that
he plans to aggressively question the way Grand Prairie detectives
conducted the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell argued unsuccessfully in pretrial hearings that Grand
Prairie police illegally detained Graham for 36 hours and denied
his repeated requests for an attorney. Although Leonard ruled that
the confession was taken legally, Cogdell will have the opportunity
to make those same arguments in front of the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell won't comment about his defense strategy, but many legal
observers wonder whether he's planning something similar to
Zamora's defense strategy, which was to lash out against Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane Zamora tried to blame it all on David,'' DeGuerin said.
``There's a lot of suspense as to what David's going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he thinks that is bad defense strategy and said
it's against the wishes of Graham's mother, who lives in the
Houston area. She instructed Cogdell early on, he said, to defend
her son vigorously but not at the expense of tarnishing Zamora or
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they want justice for our son but not at the
expense of injustice to other people,'' he said. ``That was sincere
on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
