<P>
   ROY-OHIO _ Roy Rogers' roots were in Ohio: He was born in
Cincinnati and returned to his home state for trap shooting
contests, one of his favorite sports. (Batz, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   AMEX-STATE-EMPLOYEES _ Documents obtained under open records
laws show it is common practice for state employees to use their
state American Express card for personal purchases. Victoria's
Secret. Neiman-Marcus. Macy's. Lord and Taylor. Land's End. Toys R
Us. Also, tanning salon, glamour shots, liquor stores and video
stores. State policy prohibits using the cards for personal use and
employees who do could be prosecuted. So why have state agencies
allowed this to go on? And what are they doing to stop it? (Gamino,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-POW _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The anthem stopped playing
on that June Sunday in 1994 and Jay Casenelli snapped his salute.
All around him admired the POW medal with the bronze eagle that had
just been pinned on his chest. ``I'll share this with some
ghosts,'' he told them. As it turns out, Jay Casenelli is himself a
ghost. Nothing about his war story is true _ not a date, not a
detail, not a word. He flew no helicopter, endured no beating and
suffered no imprisonment in a wooden cage in Southeast Asia. In
fact, Casenelli spent the Vietnam war years well out of the reach
of the Viet Cong gunfire, in Hazlehurst, Ga., and Marathon in the
Florida Keys. ``It is very disheartening,'' said Col. Dave Presley,
the Army officer who had helped Casenelli get his POW medal. ``It
looks like he scammed a lot of people.'' (Moffett, Palm Beach
Post.)
</P>
