<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO IMPROVE RELATIONSHIPS AT HOME, WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Suppose someone makes you an offer, Randy Gibbs
says: If you can foul up your life and make your relationships at
home and work an utter shambles within 30 days, he'll give you $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of cake, right? So, Gibbs asks, why do people think it's
so impossible to improve relationships with their spouses,
co-workers and bosses?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vain of us to think, `There's something wrong in our
relationship _ and I have nothing to do with it,' '' says Gibbs,
author of ``20/20 Insight: 6 Keys to Seeing and Changing the Hidden
Patterns That Control Our Lives and Limit Our Effectiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs says that once a relationship begins to sour _ whether
it's in a family or an office _ it tends to keep getting worse
because each person's behavior brings out the worst in the other
person.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, he gives the example of a wife who was frustrated
because she felt her husband wouldn't do anything around the house
unless she asked, and she felt like she had to ask him all the
time. The husband, though, felt like she was always nagging, and
that made him resist doing anything around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs ran into a similar downward spiral _ or ``dance,'' as he
calls it _ with Bob, a former boss. He believe Bob was too harshly
critical, so he avoided him. Bob felt Gibbs was avoiding him, which
made him more critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in life have a difficult time seeing the patterns we are
creating,'' Gibbs says. ``It's easy to list problems. What is
harder to do is to see the patterns of which they (the people) are
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   When there are problems, he says, it's important to understand
that ``it's not me and it's not you. It's what happens between
us.''
</P>
<P>
   With workplace problems, people often reinforce their own
positions by talking to spouses or friends for support, Gibbs says.
That can create a false sense that you are absolutely right and the
person at work is wrong because your loved ones will naturally side
with you, especially if all they know about your colleague is
information filtered through you.
</P>
<P>
   When there are problems at work or at home, Gibbs suggests these
steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Look at your actions.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, do you approve of how you've acted? Are you trying to
solve the problem or just blame the other person? If you didn't
have a grudge against the person, how would you act?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much admitting I'm wrong; it's admitting that I'm
complicit,'' he says. ``It's the difference between being
emotion-driven and being value-driven. When you're value-driven,
you're pressured to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs says people often spend lots of time trying to convince
others _ or themselves _ of how they've been wronged rather than
solving the problem. ``I cannot simultaneously defend myself and
build a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Examine your past and your beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Gibbs mentions how the vice president of a small
electronics company announces his belief that people only work for
a paycheck. He bases his decisions on that belief, and is confused
when the company has high turnover despite the generous bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   People who lose their jobs often lose confidence, Gibbs says,
which can make them come across as bitter or angry in job
interviews. Then they don't get the job and they lose more
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they affect us very personally, corporate things
aren't personal. How we choose to make sense of a particular
experience has everything to do with future outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Stop dancing.
</P>
<P>
   It takes two to tango, even when it's the dangerous dance that
Gibbs describes in his book. If you know how you're annoying
someone else, quit trying to justify your actions and simply stop
the annoying behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs says that if you keep annoying other people, it gives them
an excuse to keep annoying you. ``We stand between them and their
conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Be open about how you're changing.
</P>
<P>
   If you've had trouble with someone, or you're a boss with
dissatisfied workers, often just changing yourself won't solve the
problem. People are too likely to think you're insincere or have an
ulterior motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lubricate the change process if you let people know what
you're doing,'' Gibbs says. ``They'll cut you all kinds of slack if
they know you're trying.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when he worked with Hewlett-Packard, and managers
would have informal talks with workers every 30 days, letting
people know what changes were being made and why.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Gibbs says, many companies just try to push a
problem aside with a temporary fix rather than actually solving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had managers turn to me and say, `I can't believe we're
talking about this?' Why? `Because we've been talking about it for
a year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Find a good mutual starting point.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs often tells people to read his book or a chapter in it so
they have a mutual experience they can use to start the discussion,
leading in to the difficult points. In work instances, a memo or
film or workshop might be used instead.
</P>
<P>
   If two people can't get along, Gibbs says, it helps if they can
agree on what circumstances or incident led to the problem _ even
though their perspectives on it are obviously different.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can see how it came about, you can see how to go about
changing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
