r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VULGARITY-HNS &LR;      07-06 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VULGARITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VULGARITY REDUX 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NORMA J. SHATTUCK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Equal-opportunity vulgarity has truly taken
root this decade.
</P>
<P>
   If San Francisco's mayor and certain members of Congress and a
New York Times pundit can get away with hurling slurs and gross
expletives; if a mover in San Francisco politics is unapologetic at
sending a hate-mail Christmas card, what is our culture's CQ
(Civility Quotient)?
</P>
<P>
   I began to feel somewhat comforted about this up-turn in
brutishness when I discovered that the poet Horace, born 650 B.C.,
rued the rudeness of his time. It's a gem of distilled exasperation
at creeping crudeness:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hence, ye profane! I hate ye all,
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the great vulgar and the small.''
</P>
<P>
   How, I mused, could Horace have peered so far into the future to
forge a link just as I was fuming about Rosie O'Donnell's polluting
of the Tony Awards? The occasion _ recognition of professional
excellence in Broadway theater _ seemed to call for more high-toned
patter than the rancid jokes and jibes that might've originated at
a Los Angeles venue for fledgling comics who'd fall mute without
the f-word.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing via Horace that vulgarity has always been with us may
have broadened my perspective, but it doesn't quell my queasiness.
Crudity, exhibitionism and disregard for others is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The for-profit tainting of images, attitudes and emotions of
little children strikes me as truly beyond the pale. The
foul-talking kiddie cartoon characters on the television series,
``South Park,'' for instance, are the latest craze in a line of
shows with a kids-as-delegates shtick. Their popularity guarantees
a cynical cadre of older children reconditioned to the profane and
the anti-social.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the young can be shocked at what's being shoved at
them, like the 13-year-old quoted in Time: ``There's sex in the
cartoons and messed-up people on the talk shows ....''
</P>
<P>
   Books can be exploitative too. The victims of the ugly
revelations in Kathryn Harrison's incest memoir ``The Kiss'' will
surely be her own children, doomed to have to come to terms with
Mom's successful marketing of her flings (as consenting adult) with
goatish old Gramps.
</P>
<P>
   What is best-sellerdom worth? I don't think it's worth the
betrayal of privacy of those who played no part in the pathology
she describes.
</P>
<P>
   The nothing's-too-personal-to-share '90s promise other such
bonanzas for voyeurs: Those with a particular bent for obstetrical
peeping were among a possible 7.2 million cable TV viewers to watch
a Florida woman give birth. The mother-to-be claims that she is
``no exhibitionist.''
</P>
<P>
   To such passenger lures as ``more leg-room'' and ``latest
movies,'' shrewd airlines may soon be adding, ``Watch X-rated
onboard antics.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because air travelers have become increasingly drunken
and sometimes literally unbuttoned. While amour aloft used to
consist of couples cramming into lavatories to satisfy personal
urges, crews report recent cases of sex-without-seatbelts within
full view of other passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Many may claim, of course, that we're no more vulgar now than
when Chaucer was capturing human lewdness, lapses and foibles in
``The Canterbury Tales.'' My contention is that Chaucer, seeing the
Jerry Springer show, would be shocked.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Norma J. Shattuck is a writer and reviewer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
