<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTLOOSE AND FANCY: WHAT THE CAVE MAN SHARED WITH TODAY'S TRENDY
DRESSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You know those suede, earth-bound sandals that
are the rage in footwear? It turns out they were fashionable nearly
10,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like your mom said: ``Never throw anything away _ it'll always
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   As Michael J. O'Brien, the Louisiana State University
anthropologist who analyzed 35 specimens of prehistoric shoes
discovered in a cave along the Missouri River and dating back 9,400
years, testifies, ``these shoes were very stylish for the time.''
</P>
<P>
   A report compiled by O'Brien and his co-researchers and
published in Friday's issue of the journal Science found that the
ancient footwear was well-made, having been unearthed nearly whole
in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest sandal in the group was woven from jute much like
that used in footwear today. There also were moccasins, the only
ones crafted in leather, plus sling-backs and slip-ons made from
plant fibers plaited into durable soles and uppers.
</P>
<P>
   Arch support was also a consideration: These primitive cobblers
lined their shoes with cushions of grass, ``like a Dr. Scholl's
foot pad,'' O'Brien says.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a modern version of the Missouri cave shoe, it must
be the sandal that hasn't changed since its invention 101 years
ago, the shoe that shares the salient features of the Flintstonian
flip-flop _ the Birkenstock.
</P>
<P>
   These unrepentant ``hippie'' shoes have soles that mold to the
wearer's foot, just like their historic counterpart, the
straw-filled mocs. That Birkenstock sole is a combination of jute
and cork, biodegradable plant-fibers similar to the yucca-like
plant called ``rattlesnake master'' that was found in that cave.
</P>
<P>
   Icons of the '60s dropout, the neo-Bohemian, and the '90s
style-setter, Birkenstocks hold a kind of reverse status.
Alternative culture types go for their plain practicality and lack
of pretension. A sole of cork, an upper of nubuck straps, two
unshiny buckles: shoes only a mother could love.
</P>
<P>
   Or a Neanderthal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; tth-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      07-06 0179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, July 7, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-DELAYS (Seattle) SEATTLE _ Earlier this year, Russian
authorities arrested several people for stealing hundreds of
thousands of dollars worth of parts specially manufactured for the
International Space Station. The parts had been ordered by the
Energia company, perhaps the most famous name in the Russian rocket
industry. Thieves, who broke into a factory, planned to melt down
the parts and sell the precious metals on the black market. The
parts were recovered before being destroyed. But the embarrassing
incident underscores the decline of the once-proud Russian space
program. It also is symbolic of the problem-plagued partnership
between Russia and the United States on the space station, for
which The Boeing Co. is the prime contractor.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1953 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-DELAYS-SPI &LR;      07-06 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DELAYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH WOES PLAGUE SPACE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Earlier this year, Russian authorities arrested
several people for stealing hundreds of thousands of dollars worth
of parts specially manufactured for the International Space
Station.
</P>
<P>
   The parts had been ordered by the Energia company, perhaps the
most famous name in the Russian rocket industry. Thieves, who broke
into a factory, planned to melt down the parts and sell the
precious metals on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   The parts were recovered before being destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   But the embarrassing incident underscores the decline of the
once-proud Russian space program. It also is symbolic of the
problem-plagued partnership between Russia and the United States on
the space station, for which The Boeing Co. is the prime
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The start of station construction is a year behind schedule
because the Russian Space Agency did not get promised funding from
its cash-starved government. And the country's current economic
problems could mean that it will not be able to launch regular
Progress rocket missions, which will be needed to keep the station
in orbit during construction.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers are saying it's time to drop Russia as a major
station partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The International Space Station program is in trouble,'' two
senior members of the House Science Committee said in a strongly
worded letter to President Clinton last week.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan letter was sent by the committee chairman, Rep.
James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis., and Rep. George Brown of
California, the committee's ranking Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face a situation in which there can be little confidence
that the Russia government will make adequate funding available to
meet its commitments,'' they said in asking that the president
submit within 30 days a plan for the financial rescue of the
station.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing executives involved in the project say Russia should
not be dropped as a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a very big mistake to try and do this without
them,'' said Doug Stone, head of Boeing's space station program in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, Russia is having financial difficulties,'' Stone
said. ``The people in Russia are not happy they are having trouble
getting adequate funding. ... But they have not in any way backed
off from getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Under contract to Boeing, the once top-secret Khrunichev
assembly complex outside Moscow built the first space station
element, known as the functional cargo block, or FGB, for its
Russian acronym. It will provide early station control functions.
</P>
<P>
   The module was funded with $200 million from NASA. Under the
close supervision of Boeing, it was finished in January and shipped
by rail more than 1,200 miles from Moscow to the Baikonur
Cosmodrome launch complex in the republic f Kazakhstan for final
testing.
</P>
<P>
   It is now scheduled to be launched into orbit Nov. 20, to be
followed Dec. 3 by the launch at Kennedy Space Center of Space
Shuttle Endeavour carrying the first U.S. component of the station.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle astronauts will join the two pieces of station in orbit,
marking the start of assembly of the largest and most complex
structure ever built for space.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-built cargo block initially was to have been
launched in December 1997. But the date has been postponed twice
because of delays by Khrunichev in building the critical third
station element known as the service module. That module will
provide early life support to the station crew, as well as
propulsion to keep the station from falling out of orbit and
burning up in the Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The first launch of station hardware cannot take place until
NASA knows for sure that the service module, or an alternative,
will be ready for launch a few months later. After repeated
construction delays caused by inadequate funding from the Russian
government, the service module is nearly finished and NASA is
confident it can go ahead with plans to launch the functional cargo
block Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians did exactly what we asked them to do with the
(cargo block),'' Boeing's Stone said. ``It's at the launch site and
ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Barnes is Boeing's program manager in Houston for the
functional cargo block.
</P>
<P>
   She's known to friends as ``Ginger,'' and likes to joke that FGB
actually is an acronym for ``For Ginger Barnes.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said both Boeing and Khrunichev have benefited from the
partnership, and the success of the functional cargo block
demonstrates that Russia is a valuable member of the space station
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people, as I did on my first trip over there (to Russia),
look for the differences between us,'' she said. ``What I found,
and what most people have found, is there are more similarities
between us than differences. ... The Russians are very humble, very
hospitable, brilliant and caring people, and we have been able to
use those traits to establish lasting bonds. The FGB is a true
bridge between two powerful nations and two powerful companies _
Boeing and Khrunichev.''
</P>
<P>
   The two companies were founded the same year _ 1916. Both
dabbled in areas outside of aerospace at one time. When the early
Boeing Co. was building furniture, for example, Khrunichev was
building children's sleds.
</P>
<P>
   During construction of the functional cargo block, Boeing kept
three full-time employees at the Khrunichev complex. They regularly
visited the factory floor to closely monitor the work and were
impressed at the quality-control system in place, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Khrunichev constructed several physical test stands to emulate
some of the systems on the functional cargo block, said Barnes, who
noted that in this country, those same tests would have been done
by less reliable computer simulation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a public perception in the United States that the
Russians are less technologically advanced, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found just the opposite to be the case,'' she said. ``These
people are experts. They are very proud of their technical
capabilities. They just approach things in different ways than we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Khrunichev completed many of its contract milestones on the
functional cargo block ahead of schedule so its workers could get
paid _ by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of the other station-related programs in
Russia, they have not been as successful because the U.S. has not
funded them,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The critical service module is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the funding shortfalls, the service module is nearly
finished and has been shipped from Khrunichev to the Energia
company for system testing, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are a very confident group of people,'' Stone
said. ``You can depend on them to build a quality piece of
hardware, provided they have the resources necessary to do the job.
Without any reservations, I would say their hardware is just as
good as anything we produce. The difficulty has been making sure we
have an adequate flow of money from the Russian government to the
Russian Space Agency. And that has not been the case. That is
something that we at Boeing, as prime contractor, don't have any
control over. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have proven with the FGB that if the Russians are given
adequate resources to do the job, they will do the job on time, and
not only that, but what they produce will be exactly what they told
you they were going to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial situation, however, continues to look bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Russian participation in the project in 1993
that probably saved the station from the congressional budget ax. A
station funding authorization bill that year survived a house roll
call vote by one vote _ 216-215.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said Russian participation would
</P>
<P>
   accelerate completion of the station by up to two years and save
$2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Congress, including Sensenbrenner, chairman of the House
Science Committee, had argued against making the station project so
dependent on the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   After the breakup of the Soviet empire, Russia's space program,
a symbol of its status as a superpower, fragmented into 38
semiprivate companies coordinated by the Russian Space Agency. Some
of those companies went bankrupt. Others have not been able to pay
workers on time.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, the Russian government realized it would be strapped
for funds and recommended that its Mir station become the hub of
the new International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   NASA refused to change its plans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, NASA asked the U.S. Naval Research Laboratory to begin
building an interim control module that could be sent to the
station should the Russian-built service module be further delayed.
The U.S. module would have the fuel and engine needed to keep the
station in orbit, performing much the same role as the Russian
element.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has indicated it plans to use the Navy hardware even if the
Russian service module goes up as planned next year. It could be
attached to the back of the service module and provide an
additional three years of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, during testimony before Congress, NASA Administrator
Dan Goldin acknowledged that if he had it to do again, he would not
have Russia build the critical service module.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's current assembly schedule has the station ready by
December 2003, which is 18 months later than the original
completion date set in 1993. But a recent NASA-commissioned
independent review of the station project found that completion of
the station is likely to be delayed until 2005 or 2006 because of
Russia's inability to meet financial and hardware commitments to
the project.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, estimated that it costs the United States more
than $100 million for every month the station is delayed.
</P>
<P>
   NASA now says the greatest threat to the station posed by
Russia's economic difficulties is no longer the service module but
the Progress vehicles that will provide additional station reboost.
</P>
<P>
   Progress ships are used to keep the Mir station in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of these Progress flights will be needed during
construction of the station. But Russia may not have the funds.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has asked Boeing to determine the cost of building a
propulsion module from space shuttle components in the event Russia
can't supply the Progress ships. It is one of several options being
considered should Russian participation be further reduced, or
eliminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
