<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE READERS WRITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOCTOR'S NOTE: Engrossed as I am by my intensive research into
the specific molecular composition of the perfect margarita, I
thought I'd step back and let the readers write this week's column.
Don't worry. I'll be right here in italics if you need me. Now,
what happened to all the Triple Sec?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We're always looking for good uses for old CD-ROMs, but this one
is stretching it a bit:
</P>
<P>
   A friend and CEO of a corporation who has been a Microsoft
developer for many years (''And that's supposed to make him
credible?'') takes his CDs and places them in the microwave for
three seconds. The resulting corona flash was amazing, and the
result is the most wonderful crinkle pattern. He then hangs them on
the wall as art. (''No accounting for taste, I guess.'') It's
awesome to enter a room filled with Microsoft CDs burned at the
stake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tron
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have made this next one up even on a good day:
</P>
<P>
   The lapidary world is finding that CDs make GREAT polishing
discs for faceting gems. I'm not kidding! They are coated ever so
slightly with a bit of carnauba wax and then ``charged'' with
diamond dust, and they work great. So, if one were to really want
to recycle the darn things, they could bundle 'em up and donate
them to their local rock and mineral club.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suzette
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is ...
</P>
<P>
   Two words: ``PULL! BLAM!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Frank
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In response to one woman's letter about her husband's snooping
into what she was doing on a chat channel, I recently asked if
anybody knew of a specific way it could be done. These responses
should make everybody a little more paranoid:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hubby'' might be using a key-logger _ a hacker's tool used for
recording keystrokes (usually used for the purposes of obtaining
passwords). Most likely he is using the IRC client's own
logger,.MDBR/.MDNM/ though. Whichever way, the guy's a jerk. (''No
argument about that.'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Spencer
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple script that can be used in mIRC, one of the
popular chat programs out there, and I'm sure that with very little
change it would work with Pirch and many other chats. No, I'm not
anal and don't have such a line in my remotes. (''Sure.'') I am
just responding to your request. (''I'd include the script here,
but it would scare the nongeeks. Besides, I don't want any more
snooping than there already is.'') For more on chat scripting, you
can come to Dalnet, channel \ mIRC4Dummies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ron
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   There are many utilities that will track your every move on the
computer. One of my clients thought his salesman was spending too
much time at Pyro Pete's Porn Page (''not that there's anything
wrong with that'') instead of working on his sales reports, so he
had me install a client that he bought that tracks every keystroke.
But why would you want to? The lady who wrote you left out one
important piece of information. Why does the husband feel it's his
duty to check up on her? Maybe she's caused him no end of grief. I
would suggest that he divorce her, but she'd probably get the
computer. Good women are a dime a dozen, but a good computer, now
that's something worth hanging onto.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Owww. Remember, as you sit down to write your angry letters, I
was busy with the blender and didn't know what was going on or who
was saying what. Hmmm, too much lime, not enough tequila.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
