<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING AWAY FROM IT ALL AT LAKE TAHOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. _ We were seated on a granite terrace
at the brink of Cascade Falls, but it actually felt like we were on
the brink of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Below us, beneath a drop-off literally at our feet, was Cascade
Lake, with sparkling blues and silvers from an afternoon breeze,
surrounded by forest greenness and an azure sky. Beyond to the
east, of course, was Lake Tahoe, cobalt blue and calm, available
for anybody to gaze at for a dose of instant serenity.
</P>
<P>
   To our right, just a few feet away, Cascade Creek went sailing
over the granite rim, creating a 200-foot waterfall, tumbling and
churning, with the cascading water droplets refracting the sunlight
like millions of miniature prisms. To our left, a chipmunk was
perched upright like a statue, begging for a handout like a trained
circus dog. Nobody else was in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Tahoe? This is Tahoe? What about all the people? The tourists
from all over America? Well, yep, this is Tahoe, and the crowds
just plain weren't here.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, I've always made my trips to Tahoe as part of an
expedition, like hiking the Pacific Crest Trail or the Tahoe Rim
Trail or a big story, like last summer when President Clinton
authorized new federal protection of the Tahoe Basin. Not this
time. Like most everybody else visiting Tahoe, I just wanted to
have fun, hiking, biking, maybe boatiny and driving.
</P>
<P>
   What I found was a re-discovery of why Tahoe is like no place
else on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   We started out simple, just to stretch our legs, the same way so
many families approach Tahoe the first day, heading to D.L. Bliss
State Park for two real easy walks. The first is the Balancing Rock
Trail, where after about 40 yards you arrive at this 130-ton,
oblong-shaped granite boulder that is set on this tiny perch and
the whole thing seems to defy gravity. Some day it has to fall,
right? Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Then we switched gears and headed out on the Rubicon Trail, a
meandering path just above the southwest shore of Lake Tahoe,
wandering through pine, cedars and firs, with occasional breaks for
panoramas of the lake. At one perfect lookout point, we took a
lunch stop. In moments, there were a half dozen chipmunks around
us, begging, sitting upright, like a chipmunk circus, hoping for
their nut for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubicon trail runs all the way past Emerald Point to Emerald
Bay, the best spots to soak up the 12-mile expanse of Lake Tahoe,
especially early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The morning air was still cool, mid-30s at dawn, but it warmed
quickly and, by early afternoon, the temperature was in the low
70s, tinged with the scent of pine duff, with light breezes below
puffy cumulus forming over the ridges. Ansel Adams could hardly
have designed a prettier picture.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, you took a bike ride on the paths out of
Richardson's Resort. The bike trail here runs three miles, then
connects to a loop that extends near the lake for another three
miles. If you cross the highway, there are also dirt roads and
routes in Eldorado National Forest where you can extend your trip
for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed so pretty that the only way to see it all was
to drive the loop highway around the lake. Let me tell you, two
years ago, on a Friday, it took me more than an hour to drive just
from Truckee to South Lake, with the roads jammed all the way,
never getting over 30 mph. Last week, to my amazement, with an
early start and so few people here, it was an unpressured and
beautiful cruise all the way.
</P>
<P>
   What could be better? Well, this is what: We turned at the sign
for Fallen Leaf Lake Road, then drove to the trailhead for Angora
Lakes. From here, it is a 15-minute walk uphill, when you reach the
first of a series of three pristine lakes set in Sierra granite.
The last of the Angora Lakes is the biggest, emerald-green and
backed by a high granite wall where there were two dozen waterfalls
running from melting snow, with small rental cabins sprinkled along
the western shore.
</P>
<P>
   The locally famous ``lemonade lady'' still sells lemonade at a
small shop here, and for many visitors, drinking a cup is almost
like being baptized.
</P>
<P>
   This just couldn't be beat, right? But then, at the Glen Alpine
trailhead at the end of Fallen Leaf Lake Road, we hiked into
Desolation Wilderness. We passed a series of small waterfalls, then
climbed up a canyon, finally hitting snow at an elevation of about
8,000 feet, about 3.5 miles in near Gilmore Lake. There was perfect
quiet, with the air warm and sweeping views across miles of the
snow-flecked Sierra crest.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be better than this, right? But then it was off to
Cascade Falls, just sitting there at the brink of the falls,
soaking up dream-like beauty in every direction.
</P>
<P>
   Back in South Lake on Friday, the traffic was just starting to
get gummed up for the weekend at the Y, the intersection of
Highways 89 and 50, smog hovering over the roadway while engines
idled, cars at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   But up there at Cascade Falls, Tahoe has rarely felt so pure,
where with just a short drive and an easy hike we gained entry into
a different world where perfection is still possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
