<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIDER-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING BY `HOUSE RULES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; A curious lad named Homer Wells has just made a
fascinating, frightening discovery. Though his outstretched hands
are empty, his words convey a powerful image: Homer has stumbled
upon a discarded fetus, dumped on the ground outside a ramshackle
Maine orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   This memorable scene, instantly recognizable to readers of John
Irving's novel ``The Cider House Rules,'' also constitutes a
defining moment in the six-hour adaptation of Irving's book that
opens Saturday at the Mark Taper Forum.
</P>
<P>
   As Irving writes it, the incident certainly makes for high
drama. But is that the same thing as great theater?
</P>
<P>
   Actor Tom Hulce thinks so, and he's betting that Southern
California audiences will agree that Irving's best-selling book
deserves to be seen in three dimensions, not just on the printed
page.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is theatrical. It's got a kind of heightened quality to
it,'' says Hulce, an accomplished stage performer probably best
known to movie audiences as Mozart in Milos Forman's ``Amadeus.''
``There's something in the Dickensian influence of this one that it
feels different to me from his other books, in terms of crying out
for a life on the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar to millions of readers as a fat, controversial novel of
the mid-1980s, ``The Cider House Rules'' has spent nine years
making a careful transition to the playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With the author's consent _ though not his active involvement _
Irving's 560-page story of a well-meaning but tortured Maine
country doctor, Wilbur Larch, and his beloved protege Wells, has
been turned into a two-part, six-hour marathon, boiled down from an
eight-hour version that premiered in 1996 at the Seattle Repertory
Theatre. In her review of Part 2, Seattle Times theater critic
Misha Berson noted only one major shortcoming of the time-consuming
production: ``It comes to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   With a plot that revolves around not only abortion but incest,
domestic violence, social inequality and grinding poverty, ``The
Cider House Rules'' isn't what you'd call beach-blanket reading.
But in typical Irving fashion, the novel alternates comedy and
tragedy, often within the same paragraph. Picaresque adventures and
romantic interludes offset grim evocations of primitive
gynecological methods.
</P>
<P>
   Still, turning a work of such Victorian girth into a nimble
piece of stagecraft posed many challenges for its three adapters,
co-directors Hulce and Jane Jones and playwright Peter Parnell, who
devised the script.
</P>
<P>
   Ask why they did it, and the trio becomes nearly as verbose as
Irving's famously expansive prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the fact that it could deal in scope from parts that
are hugely comic to things that are very serious to things that are
deeply eccentric and other things that are just full of true
sentiment,'' says Hulce during an interview at the Mark Taper's
administrative offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I responded to the father-son story at the center of
it, and to the exploration of the abandoned and neglected and
abused, and what our responsibilities are to them.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Jones chimes in with another of the story's
themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Controlling your own destiny,'' she muses.
</P>
<P>
   ``... What your responsibility is to a gift that you may have,''
Hulce counters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living with lies,'' Jones responds. ``I mean, it's just about
life!''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``The Cider House Rules''' is sometimes reductively
described as Irving's ``abortion novel,'' neither the book nor the
play spend much time thrashing out the subject. What attracted
Hulce and company to the novel wasn't that it was issue-driven, but
character- and plot-driven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything Jane and Tom have been saying about their
responses to the novel, I had as well,'' says Parnell, ``and in
addition I felt that I responded to the world of the orphanage as a
Dickensian world, as a world of styles that I felt could work with
both narrative and dialogue, a world that I felt somewhat in its
simplicity reminded me of Thornton Wilder's play-writing, which I
love very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving's admiration for meaty 19th-century novels filled with
long, complicated sentences and tongue-in-cheek asides is
well-known. So is his disdain for what he calls ``the flat,
emotionally inscrutable, spare, modernist and post-modernist
style'' of fiction-writing, the ``grocery list'' prose he
associates with Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``The World According to Garp'' and ``A Prayer for
Owen Meany'' admits he was dubious about the idea of adapting
``Cider House'' for the theater, a literary form for which he
professes little affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was lonely there for a while,'' Jones admits. ``I mean, he
(Irving) was so divorced from the idea of it, because of his
feeling of not being very enamored of the theater. He was very
upfront about it, and yet it felt lonely not to have the father's
blessing. I mean, none of us would be here if it wasn't for John's
story.''
</P>
<P>
   But after talking with Hulce and Parnell, Irving allowed the
project to proceed, provided it didn't interfere with a movie
screenplay he's been working on for years. (A film version is
scheduled to begin shooting this fall with Lasse Hallstrom of ``My
Life as a Dog'' directing.)
</P>
<P>
   When Irving finally sat down to watch Part 2 of the Seattle
production a year and a half ago, he wasn't sure what to expect.
The outcome? A conversion as spectacular as any to be found in
Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just wonderful,'' Irving says. ``I can't wait to see
the production here (in Los Angeles). I've read the six-hour script
of Peter's, and I'm so envious because I've spent 13 years writing
the screenplay for four different directors. And I keep telling
(Parnell and Hulce), I keep saying, `I'm so jealous of you guys
because you have six hours and I only got two! And every time I see
a version of the play, I'm looking at something and thinking, `Oh
(expletive), I took that out, I lost that scene, I lost that
character.' And they've managed to keep most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The germ of the stage production dates to the early 1980s, when
Hulce read a draft of a ``Cider House'' screenplay and met with the
late Phillip Borsos, the director initially assigned to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked his head off,'' Hulce recalls. ``I talked to him for
two hours about this story. I had no idea that I had the kind of
passion for it that I did. And, as I described the moments, I
realized that they were very theatrical moments, they weren't
cinematic moments, because of the way that the stage uses language
and the way that the stage celebrates sentences _ and sentences you
want to say out loud. And also, as there are so many parts of this
that can only live if you use your imagination. When they become
literal, it's not nearly as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulce and Parnell had been friends since 1982, when they worked
together on Parnell's play ``The Rise and Rise of Daniel Rocket.''
Hulce played the title role at Playwrights Horizons in New York and
also on a subsequent PBS broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, another cast member, would go on to found Seattle's
Book-It Repertory Theatre, a company that re-creates books on
stage, word for word. She describes the company's mission as
``celebrating'' books _ not ``interpreting'' them _ by sticking
with an author's original language and immersing audiences in the
world of the book, ``not just the world created within the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a century ago, Broadway was awash in hit plays based on
contemporary fiction, such as Tad Mosel's ``All the Way Home''
(adapted from James Agee's ``A Death in the Family'') and a version
of Nathaniel West's ``Miss Lonelyhearts.'' But as the nonmusical
American theater has grown more marginalized, the novel-as-play has
fallen out of favor. When books get adapted nowadays, they're
likely to be time-tested classics like ``Nicholas Nickleby'' or
``The Grapes of Wrath.''
</P>
<P>
   Its adapters believe that if ``The Cider House Rules'' proves
successful _ a Broadway run still is being discussed _ it could
mean the time has come again for an old-fashioned form of
tale-telling that's too good to keep between the covers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that it is not only so smart and so funny and
so determined to explore difficult territory, it hopefully is the
best of what a huge novel-length story can offer,'' Hulce says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
