<SLUG> BC-LASTGAME-2000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEMIPRO FOOTBALL PLAYER GIVES HIS LIFE FOR HIS DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The day they buried Big Roy, eight of his
teammates from the Dallas Avengers carried his oversized coffin.
</P>
<P>
   They buried him in a cream-colored suit, with a Black-and-Mild
cigar in his pocket and a sweat towel at his side. One at a time,
Roy's teammates laid their big hands on top of his, the way they
did in the huddle, then they swooped their hands in the air and
shouted ``Avengers!''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Lee Woods Jr. died on April 25, with seven minutes and 34
seconds left in the second quarter. He was 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people have heard of Big Roy or his dream. This is
Dallas Cowboys country. Nobody pays much attention to a
semiprofessional team that travels around Texas and Oklahoma
playing games on hot days in high school stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league football is nothing like the farm teams of
major-league baseball. The Avengers are not affiliated with an NFL
team. Their first season was sponsored by the Mid-City
Chrysler-Plymouth body shop. Their home field was a rectangle of
grass behind Nichols Junior High in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   None of these guys is groomed or recruited, and none is paid.
They work full-time jobs, have children and wives, and play in
anonymity. Some play because they love the game. Most play because
this is their last chance at professional ball.
</P>
<P>
   All of his life, Roy dreamed of playing in the NFL. He jumped
off the track that leads to pro ball years ago _ he quit high
school and gave up on college _ but he never gave up on his dream.
He believed a scout might come to a game, though few ever did, and
he still believed, even at 30, that he could make it to the big
time. He died trying.
</P>
<P>
   `MAN, I FEEL WEIRD': The Avengers lumbered from the locker room
across the parking lot and onto their home field to face the Big
Spring Warriors. They were 1-5 going into the seventh game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The first plays were sloppy _ a wide receiver dropped a 50-yard
pass, another guy tripped _ but the Avengers were winning 8-0 by
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A bad punt gave the Warriors the ball. Big Roy usually played on
the offensive line, but this game he was all over the field. He
played like he knew it would be his last.
</P>
<P>
   He slammed into Warrior linemen in a clash of helmets. He
hunched over the line and taunted them with mock introductions and
banter: ``Hello, my name is Roy. Nothing personal but I'm coming
after you. I'll be coming after you all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody doubted Big Roy when he volunteered to play defense and
keep the Warriors out of the end zone. ``Let's stop them,'' he
barked.
</P>
<P>
   With seven minutes and 34 seconds left in the second quarter,
the Warriors called a time out. It happened then: Big Roy's heart
beat out of control. It started beating fast, faster, so fast that
the bottom chamber filled with blood. When his brain demanded
blood, and none came, Roy collapsed. He landed flat on his back,
and he looked up. ``Man, I feel weird'' was the last thing he said.
</P>
<P>
   A fullback shouted toward the stands: ``Call 911!''
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics rushed down to the field, Roy's teammates prayed on
the sideline. ``Lord, let him be OK.'' Roy was big, but he was
healthy. He weighed 300 pounds, stood probably 6 foot 3 or 6 foot
4, but he wasn't fat, it was muscle. He didn't drink or smoke, and
he ate right. ``Please let him be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams decided to call the game. The Avengers followed
the ambulance. Quarterback Tony Naves was entering the emergency
room when a teammate stopped him. ``He's dead.''
</P>
<P>
   A LIFELONG DREAM: It was Roy's best friend on the team, Darril
``Scooter'' Warren, who drove from the hospital in Arlington west
to south Dallas to tell Roy Sr. He stopped at a house with sheets
on the windows and a broken air conditioner on the porch. Roy's
father was home.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I didn't hear him right. I say, `OK, I'll be right
there. What hospital he at? I'll go to the hospital. He'll be all
right.' Then I thought about it. He hugged me. Scooter never hugs
me. He always shakes my hand. He said Roy is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Scooter called Roy's sister, Rose. She was expecting Roy to come
to her house after the game. His birthday was four days away, and
she planned a barbecue. She was putting ribs on the grill when the
telephone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy always wanted to be somebody,'' Rose said. As soon as he
was able to wrap his fingers around a football, Roy Jr. had one in
his hands. ```Daddy, you just wait. You gonna be so proud of me
when I make it big.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 12 or 13, his sisters were his teammates, Linda his
receiver, Rose his offensive line. They were a few years behind
him, and they did whatever he did. Rose wore the red helmet, he
wore the gray, and after plays, he inspected his for flecks of red
paint. That meant he hit her good.
</P>
<P>
   Roy thought he was tough in his 13 1/2-sized shoes and his
XXX-large jersey and pants. Rose looks at his Spruce High photos.
He thought football players should look tough, so the boy with the
high cheeks and the lazy left eye and the thick neck doesn't smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, bless his heart,'' Roy's daddy said. ``He did all he
could to be somebody, to get somewhere in life.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
