</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-NOTES (Undated) _ Short items from the world of music
and the arts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EASTER-ISLAND (Undated) _ Archeologists are at last making
progress in recovering the history of Easter Island and its 900
stone statues, the island, the people themselves and their
indigenous language. The scientists also are gaining a better
understanding of the motivations, practices and economic
foundations of the statue builders. But the place is in danger of
losing its alluring air of mystery. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PENILE-MORPHOLOGY (Undated) _ Among insects, male
reproductive organs differ so dramatically from one species to
another that entomologists rely on the particulars of the cerci,
epiprocts and other bits of arthropod genitalia to distinguish
between species that otherwise look alike. Scientists have long
debated the reasons for such ornateness of penile shape, or
morphology. Now, a Swedish researcher has given the morphology a
new spin, contending that male reproductive organs are the pelvic
equivalent of peacock feathers _ the fruit of sexual selection. By
Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANCIENT-SHOES (Undated) _ One of the longest chapters in the
history of fashion has emerged from an unlikely hiding place _ a
cave overlooking the Missouri River in Calloway County, Mo. From an
ancient garbage dump in the cave, archeologists have retrieved a
series of discarded shoes that range in age from 8,000 to 800 years
ago. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ICE-SHEET (Undated) _ If the earth's temperature heats up as
mainstream scientists predict it will over the next century, the
average level of the world's oceans could rise by about a foot and
a half by 2100, and somewhat more after that, as glaciers partly
melt and the heating makes sea water expand, inundating many
low-lying coastal areas. But it would be trivial compared with the
melting or collapse of the huge West Antarctic ice sheet, the
Godzilla of the game of rising seas. This would loose so much water
into the oceans that they would rise by a truly catastrophic 16 to
20 feet. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-DIABETES (Undated) _ As disturbing and devastating as
the disfigurement may be to some people taking a protease inhibitor
for HIV, the cosmetic changes may be the least worrisome part.
Doctors are worried about more serious, even potentially fatal,
changes in fat metabolism. A small but growing number of studies
find that many such individuals have high levels of cholesterol and
lipids in the blood and other metabolic changes that may increase
the risk of diabetes. The findings are among those revealed at the
12th World AIDS Conference in Geneva. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (New York) _ The largest gathering of Apple
Macintosh fans on the East Coast begins Tuesday in Manhattan, and
they have several reasons to be optimistic after more than a year
of darkness and turmoil. Led by co-founder Steve Jobs, Apple
appears to have stabilized its management team, cut costs, made
some money, halted a precipitous decline in market share, outlined
(at last) a clear path for its Mac operating system, and
streamlined and reinvigorated its product lineup. By Peter H.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Your science questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Insect
repellents for children abound, but now consumers can get help from
a new study giving the pros and cons of particular products. What
may be safe for adults is not necessarily safe for children. By
Jane E. Brody. (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNS-HEALTH (Undated) _ This is New Year's week at your local
hospital, where July 1 marks a new beginning just as fraught with
symbolism and expectation as Jan. 1 elsewhere. Medical schools end
in June and hospital training programs start in July; last week
everyone in them lurched a step forward. Studies show the month is
no more dangerous than any others, but memories of the grueling
training linger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Denver) _ Sports of The Times column on the
All-Star Game. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
