<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASTGAME-2ndTake-TEX     07-06 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASTGAME-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
ARLINGTON, Texas: in life.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Football. Football. Football. How many times did his ex-wife,
Arvillia Johnson, go to bed hearing him talk about the game? ``I
just knew that Roy Junior was going to be on TV. I think as old as
Roy Junior was he was not going to quit. I think he would have went
till he was 50.''
</P>
<P>
   How many games had she seen when they were married? She sat in
the bleachers, hot and mostly empty, with a baby on her lap and
watched him play.
</P>
<P>
   Brionne, who's now 8, and Isaac, who is 6, thought their daddy
could do no wrong. Little Isaac misses him so much he dropped to
his knees at the grave and started digging with little hands.
``Mama, mama, he's not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Football didn't break up their marriage, Arvillia said. They
grew apart. She kept the children; he came for them on weekends.
Roy filled the bedroom closet of his apartment with their clothes,
and stuffed all of his things into a coat closet.
</P>
<P>
   Roy always looked sharp and smelled nice. He was not the most
handsome man, but Arvillia said his personality was what people
loved, not his looks. They stayed friends after the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Roy dropped out of the 11th grade to cook at a Grandy's, and
nobody can remember why. Maybe it was to %a{n money. His daddy was
a contract worker who mowed grass, laid brick and built fences, and
Roy told Arvillia he didn't want to live like that. He had a dream.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he could reach the NFL if he went through the
football leagues overseas. Rose typed his resume, and he promised
he'd send a jersey when he tried out. He never got the chance.
</P>
<P>
   IN MEMORY OF BIG ROY: They buried Big Roy beside a creek, in the
back corner of a cemetery, where the paved road ends. He wanted to
be buried beside his mama.
</P>
<P>
   Bertha Woods was 47 when she died. She was working at a
hospital, cleaning, when she bumped her leg on a file cabinet.
Nobody knew she had a blood clot. She was in the bathroom when she
hollered out to Roy _ ``Junior!'' He rushed in, and she was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Big Roy had started a new job, selling used cars, one week
before he died. His sister Rose couldn't find any insurance papers
at his apartment, so the team paid for the burial.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates cried the day they buried him. They cried so hard
that Roy's family felt sorry for them. ``Those white men sure loved
Roy,'' his daddy said.
</P>
<P>
   They won together and lost together. Remember the game where the
referee clocked the time wrong and stopped them a minute-and-a-half
short? What about the one they lost 28-0? Or the game where 15
players showed up, and they faced a squad twice their size?
</P>
<P>
   They got to know each other in the rented van on road trips.
They stayed up late in motels talking about plays and game plans.
They talked about kids and jobs over interstate buffets. They
prayed together. They dreamed the same dream.
</P>
<P>
   Big Roy could have played in the NFL, said Tony, the
quarterback. Roy was that good. He knew how to save Tony from
sacks, he knew who to shove and which way to push to make a hole
big enough so Tony could run the ball.
</P>
<P>
   If Roy had heart problems, he never told his team or his family.
The Avengers didn't have a team doctor, and they didn't require a
physical, so no one knew about Roy's enlarged heart.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players didn't see the paramedics use paddles to try
to restart Big Roy's heart. The team had called for an ambulance
three or four times before that game, but every time, the guy had
come out OK.
</P>
<P>
   Big Roy didn't feel any pain. That's how it happens, doctors
say. It takes months, maybe years, for the heart to enlarge. Roy
had high blood pressure, which tightened his arteries and put more
pressure on his heart.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what triggered his heart beating too fast. It's
like a car engine that floods; there's so much blood so fast the
heart can't complete the cycle. Doctors say it can happen anywhere,
doing anything. Most people with enlarged hearts don't know they
have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his teammates cried because they saw themselves in that
casket.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Marcus Stewart bought life insurance for his family.
Tony thought about all the times his wife _ and his parents _ said,
``Aren't you getting too old for this?'' Tony is 28. Big Roy was
30. Tony has kids, so did Roy. Tony is healthy, and if a scout
called tomorrow, he'd go. Roy would have gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain football to people who don't play,'' Tony
said. ``It can be like an addiction _ that's how my wife would put
it. Once you start playing and understand the intricacies of
football, it becomes like a life.''
</P>
<P>
   After they buried Big Roy, the Avengers decided he would want
them to play. ``We went out and played in his memory, and we played
like he was there with us,'' said John, the team owner. ``We drove
six hours and played 38 guys _ 15 of us _ and we totally destroyed
them. It felt like he was there with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The last game of the season, a 40-foot field goal was spiraling
right off the goal post when it veered at the last minute and
sailed through _ like a dream.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
