<HEADLINE>
BAMBI BE GONE: KEEP DEER FROM EATING YOUR YARD 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a photo of deer-fencing and a 100-word sidebar. 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By SUSAN McCLURE  
 c.1998  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My children were delighted; I was appalled! There, standing
knee-deep in snow in my front yard was a herd of deer.
</P>
<P>
   They were munching away at the tips of my maple tree and nosing
around my junipers. In summer, I see them in early morning milling
around the Austin roses and lettuces. They once nibbled the tops
off every pea vine and tramped through the bean beds.
</P>
<P>
   Deer populations continue to grow, unhindered by any predator
except mankind and a few coyotes, causing untold damage to
landscapes in suburban and rural settings.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any community blessed with some woodlands and open fields
is likely to have a hungry population of deer. The same can be said
for arboreta and park systems, which often have to battle deer to
save valuable plant life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a massive overpopulation of deer,'' said John O'Lear,
landscape architect with the Forest Preserve District of Cook
County, Ill. ``Spring ephemerals such as trillium, bloodroot, and
especially wild hyacinths, are being decimated in some areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Public gardens, horticultural and botanical research
institutions, natural areas preservationists and concerned
individuals have been focusing on developing systems for keeping
deer away from prized specimens, methods that could work at your
yard.
</P>
<P>
   If you are dealing with deer damage, educate yourself about
their habits, recommends a Cornell University spokesman. A variety
of deer control methods are discussed in the helpful brochure,
``Reducing Deer Damage to Home Gardens and Landscape Plantings''.
It is available by writing to the Department of Natural Resources,
Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853.
</P>
<P>
   Deer are selective feeders. They move along traditional routes
-- through tiny deer trails that slip through woodland openings and
over gaps in fences -- eating as they go.
</P>
<P>
   While they tend to follow familiar routes, they are capable of
learning to stay away from your yard if the way is fenced or made
impassable.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the yard or garden with an 8-foot wooden fence deer
can't jump is one surefire deterrent. But not everyone wants to go
to this expense.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative that has worked well for deer-plagued Holden
Arboretum in Kirtland, Ohio is a nearly invisible mesh barrier
carried by Benner's Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was developed by Dr. David Benner, retired professor
of ornamental horticulture, who searched long and hard for ways to
keep deer from destroying his rare plant collection. After many
unsuccessful efforts, he devised a fine polypropylene mesh fence
almost 8 feet high that he used to enclose his entire yard.
Although nearly invisible from a distance, it should be hung with
12-inch long white streamers for two months to warn deer not to try
to trespass.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use the 8-foot high fence around vegetable gardens or
to edge woodlands,'' said Benner, of Benner's Gardens. ``Shorter
fencing about 5 feet high can be adequate for surrounding smaller
beds like foundation plantings.''
</P>
<P>
   Benner's Gardens, in New Hope, Pa.(1-800-753-4660), also has
deer-barriers for driveways -- deerproof gates or in-ground grids
you can drive over but deer won't walk across.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy recommended by the Indiana Department of
Natural Resources is to surround gardens with a polytape electric
fence. This is a single strand of bright plastic ribbon interwoven
with wire that transmits a shock when touched. Set the polywire
about 2 1/2 feet above the ground, a height deer could easily jump.
But they don't. They investigate it first -- nosing it and getting
a shock that teaches them to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   If fencing is not an option for you, you can try to avoid damage
by planting species deer find less palatable. Deer prefer to nibble
on well fertilized and new plantings with tender young growth, but
when the pickings are lean, they can eat almost anything. Fruit
trees, flower buds and evergreens tend to be among their favorites.
Look at the woods and fields near you for species that are thriving
without major deer damage. You can also ask your local cooperative
extension agent for his recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Repellents can discourage browsing, although they need
re-application at least every three weeks or after a heavy rain. If
the repellents wear off, even for just one night, deer may return
and cause untold damage.
</P>
<P>
   At Holden Arboretum, the most effective products have been
Bobex, Hinder (which can be used on edible crops), and Deeraway
(with an unappealing favor and smell). You also can purchase coyote
and other predator urines, using natural territory markers to
frighten deer away.
</P>
<P>
   Deer pose another problem, in addition to their feeding. During
mating season, from September to December, bucks mark their
territories by rubbing off tree bark. Because this can be enough to
kill small trees, wrap their trunks in 4-foot tall cylinders such
as plastic fencing or trunk guards to protect vulnerable bark. &QL; 
 &UR; (SUSAN McCLURE is a free-lance writer based in Valparaiso, Ind.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
