<HEADLINE>
HELPING KIDS COPE WITH MOVING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By LIZA N. BURBY  
 c.1998 Child  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time my husband and I moved, our youngest child,
Laura, was only 4 months old. As long as we soothed her cries with
gentle words, she couldn't have cared less where we lived.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with her big sister, 1-year-old Danielle. She hated the
whole process, had tantrums anytime we looked at a prospective home
and complained that she saw no reason why we had to move, even
though we explained it to her. But when we found a house on three
wooded acres, the excitement of exploring the expansive landscape
captured her sense of adventure, and her resistance slowly melted
away.
</P>
<P>
   For the first month, Danielle seemed unfazed by her new
surroundings. Then, as we were about to congratulate ourselves on
how well she'd adapted, her mood changed: She began sobbing, for no
apparent reason, at the most unpredictable moments. When pressed,
she burst out, ``I hate this house! I want to go home.'' Stunned,
we tried pinpointing what upset her. Talking about it seemed to
help alleviate her concerns. And gradually she returned to her old
self.
</P>
<P>
   About two years later, we moved again. This time it was
3-year-old Laura who had trouble adjusting. It was the strain of
change they were responding to, however belated their reactions
seemed to be, and we hadn't prepared them well enough for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's across town or across the country, moving ranks
right up there behind divorce and parental death in terms of stress
on kids,'' says Thomas Olkowski, a clinical psychologist in Denver
and co-author of ``Moving With Children.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's a lot of them on the move. According to the U.S.
Census Bureau, of the 41 million Americans who move every year, 10
million are children under age 14. For kids, who often don't
understand why they have to move and who have little control over
the situation, moving can be a traumatic experience. There are ways
to make it easier, however.
</P>
<P>
   While you may not be able to anticipate every twist and turn,
here are steps to help pave the way:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``We're Moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Spare your child unnecessary anxiety: Don't break the news about
a move until you have concrete details about the date and location.
How you tell your child depends on her age. Too much notice invites
the incessant question ``Is today the day we're moving?'' Ann
Deaton, the director of psychology at Children's Hospital in
Richmond, Va., and co-author of ``Moving Survival Kit,'' recommends
giving preschoolers no more than two or three weeks' warning.
``Kids under 5 have a limited sense of time, so waiting for
something to happen can be hard,'' she explains. Help them by
circling the move date on the calendar and marking off the days as
they go by.
</P>
<P>
   Give school-age children, who have a better sense of time, at
least one month's notice before a move. Three months is appropriate
for an 8- to 12-year-old who may want time to break the news to her
friends. However, Deaton warns, more than that is a long time for a
youngster to deal with the anticipation of change.
</P>
<P>
   Older children may worry about losing contact with their
friends, says Olkowski. Help gather the addresses and phone numbers
of your child's friends, and encourage correspondence by
distributing pre-addressed postcards to the other children.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to your child's questions can help ease anxiety. ``At
any age, your children want to be reassured that they will be safe,
and they want to know what to expect,'' says Deaton. Preschoolers
will ask concrete questions that need specific answers, as Jean
Currie of Huntington, N.Y., learned. Her daughter, Jessica, was 3
when the family moved from New York City to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told her all about the new house -- she even took a trip
with us to see it,'' Currie relates. ``But we never defined who was
moving. One day, she asked, ``Mommy, will I be going, too?' We
hadn't realized -- she was worried! Quickly, we explained that all
of us were moving together.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the move, we thought it was wonderful the way that
Jessica was adjusting to our new home,'' Currie continues. ``But
two weeks later, she asked, `When are we going back?' Then we
realized why she had responded so well: She thought it was just a
trip! You can't underestimate the need to define everything
clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   2. House Hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Asking a friend to watch your children as you house-hunt
eliminates the stress of having your attention divided, Deaton
notes. It will be easier on toddlers and preschoolers as well, who
often have difficulty understanding how much things cost or what
might be wrong with the roof. According to Deaton: ``Kids may
decide on the spot which bedroom will be theirs in a house you know
won't work, and your negative response can confuse them.''
</P>
<P>
   Children over the age of 8 may actually benefit from
accompanying you, however. ``Voicing their input helps them feel
like an important part of the move,'' remarks Jill Schneiderman, an
early childhood specialist at Work/Family Directions in Boston, a
consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've chosen a new home, show the kids pictures not only
of the house but also of the neighborhood, schools and playgrounds.
If possible, take your kids on a walking tour -- the more familiar
they are with the area, the easier the adjustment will be.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pack It Up, Ship It Out.
</P>
<P>
   Enlist your children's help in packing, no matter how young they
are. Toddlers as young as 2 years old can help gather their toys.
Put your preschooler in charge of packing her favorite books. Older
kids will probably want to sort through and pack a lot of their own
belongings. Provide your child with a ``premove kit,'' suggests
Olkowski. The kit -- which might contain packing supplies like
markers and stickers to decorate boxes, sandwich bags for loose
items and rubber bands to secure such things as baseball cards --
lets your child participate in a fun and useful way.
</P>
<P>
   After all the anticipation, moving day itself can be almost a
relief. If you have movers, let one parent direct the furniture
arranging while the other concentrates on the kids' needs. Doing
the move yourself? Either use off-site child care or have someone
present at the move just to watch your children.
</P>
<P>
   Set up the kids' bedrooms first, advises Robert Butterworth, a
Los Angeles-based clinical psychologist. For children ages 2 to 8,
arrange their furniture as it was in the old house. ``You're
already changing their house and environment,'' comments
Butterworth. ``They need a little familiarity, especially for
sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk through your old house one last time with your child. Sally
Malech, mom of 2-year-old Asher in West Hartford, Conn., found that
when her family moved down the street, her son kept asking to go
``home.'' ``I finally walked through the empty house with him and
pointed out that his toys and bed were no longer there,'' Malech
says. ``He was reluctant to go in, but it really provided
tremendous closure for him. Now, every time we walk by he says,
`That's not our house. That's our old house.'''
</P>
<P>
   4. Life After the Move.
</P>
<P>
   In those first few days after a move, concentrate on listening
to your child's concerns, says Butterworth. Keeping an upbeat
attitude can defuse some of his fears. A picnic dinner on the
living room floor, complete with tablecloth, candles and take-out
food, will give him a sense of celebration and give you a
much-needed break.
</P>
<P>
   Walk around the new neighborhood together and point out
landmarks. Back at home, draw a map showing the location of the
playground, grocery store, library and school. Make sure your child
knows or carries his new phone number and address with him.
</P>
<P>
   Your child may regress in some way after the move. For example,
it's common, says Schneiderman, for a potty-trained child to start
having accidents. Your toddler may suddenly have difficulty
sleeping through the night. Older kids may develop behavioral
problems in school. You may be tempted to smooth over a rough
transition by offering your child rewards for good behavior, but
sticking to the routines that he's used to actually makes it easier
to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regular discussion time with you so that your child can talk
about how he feels may help ease his anxiety,'' says Butterworth.
If this behavior continues for more than a month, however, you
should contact your pediatrician or family doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of kids will adjust within six to 18 months. ``Most
moves turn out OK, given enough time,'' notes Olkowski. ``Even a
move under the worst conditions can turn out to be a learning and
growing experience for the whole family.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, my daughters, now 8 and 4, will move once again --
to a house eight blocks away from where we now live. They've begun
packing already, and while they consider themselves little pros at
this, I'm not taking any chances -- I've been preparing them for
weeks. Still, the other day I realized I may have fortified them a
little too well. As I was explaining that we would be saying
good-bye to our old house but would live close enough to visit it,
Danielle turned to me and said, ``Mom, don't worry so much --
you're going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
 &UR; (Liza N. Burby is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
