<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-BACK-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S GOOD FOR YOUR BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By KEN McALPINE  
 c.1998  Spirit 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you come to the Texas Back Institute looking to be
mollycoddled, you've come to the wrong place. The largest of the
country's new breed of comprehensive treatment centers for back
care, fat with cutting-edge technology and highly trained
specialists, the Dallas-based Institute seems the ideal place to
indulge America's credo -- fix me, bill me, and send me on my way.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Americans give short shrift to back pain. No, they
care deeply, spending an estimated $50 billion a year on surgery,
drugs and rehab for their back pain, which doesn't sound like
nearly enough to anyone who has had passing acquaintance with the
molten-jolt sensations back-pain sufferers are privy to.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hochschuler is perfectly positioned to take advantage of
this windfall. Chairman of the Texas Back Institute, Hochschuler is
a spine surgeon. But Hochschuler, an affable fellow with a special
kinship with his patients (``I have a back problem, and my patients
are thrilled to hear it''), sees surgery as a last resort, and not
an infallible one. ``Surgery isn't going to make you 100 percent
better,'' states Hochschuler. ``Doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both to his patients and through seminars, videotapes
and books such as ``Back in Shape'' (Houghton Mifflin) and ``Treat
Your Back Without Surgery'' (Hunter House), Hochschuler tirelessly
trumpets a simple message.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to rely on the quick fix, but what they really
have to do is take ownership,'' he says. ``Back pain is a major
health problem. But most of it could be prevented if people took
responsibility for their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Hochschuler would be just as happy if you read his
books and left him alone. Many of his fellow back experts agree,
and they aren't adopting this tack because they want to play more
golf. ``With all the research, we're coming back to the same old
thing every time,'' says Roger Minkow, a Petaluma, Calif., back
specialist and former co-medical director of the San Francisco
Spine Center. ``When it comes to preventing or treating back
problems, it's exercise and lifestyle changes that are going to
make the major difference for most people.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently four out of five people suffer some kind of back pain
at some point in their lives. The back is partly to blame. The
spine is highly complex, an anatomical marvel that is the
centerpiece of movement. But, for reasons only God and back
specialists can understand, the back's heyday is short. After about
20 years, the back begins eagerly hustling toward infirmity --
muscles stiffen; bones weaken; discs harden, bulge, fissure and
burst.
</P>
<P>
   And no one escapes. In a study published in the New England
Journal of Medicine in 1994, researchers found that two-thirds of a
test group of healthy adults with no back pain had abnormalities in
their spinal discs. This explains, in part, why three three nurse
clinicians manning the Texas Back Institute's toll-free hotline,
(800-247-BACK) field some 3,000 calls a month, many of them from
frantic weepy folk convinced their lives are now confined to
hospital gelatin and bedsores.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that, for many of these callers, picking up
the phone is the first thing they've ever done for their backs.
Don't fear the back's inherent de composition, says Hochschuler.
Address it. ``Back pain rarely occurs out of the blue,'' says
Hochschuler. ``Usually, when people develop back pain it's an
accumulation of insults that has led to their back problem. Bending
wrong, lifting wrong, not keeping in shape -- it all adds up. If
you address these things, there's a good chance you can prevent
back pain entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are willing to do what they can, they can avoid all
the medical practitioners,'' says Minkow. ``Unless they're one of
the unfortunate 5 percent that's going to actually need surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there are plenty of things you can do to help your back
exercise tops the list. But, as experts point out, it's not just
about exercising the back. Yes, there are terrific strengthening
and stretching exercises that specifically target the back, and
they're important, which is why you'll find plenty of them
diagrammed in books such as Hochschuler's.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all you need. Shoring up the back means taking
care of the back's supporting cast -- namely almost everything from
head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that old song, 'The hip bone's connected to the leg
bone'?'' says Hochschuler. ``Well, the spine connects to
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is that strong legs -- hamstrings, quadriceps and glutes
-- help take pressure off the back. Ditto for strong abdominal
muscles --weak stomach muscles pull you forward, a disalignment
that puts strain on the spine (witness the aching backs of pregnant
women and potbellied men).
</P>
<P>
   Whole-body flexibility and aerobic conditioning are critical,
too: flexibility because tight muscles don't flex to life's
strains; aerobic conditioning because exercise on the move helps
your body deliver critical nutrients to the spine and builds a
degree of muscle strength.
</P>
<P>
   Spine types can discourse for hours on the physiology. Here's
what concerns the rest of us: ``How much time does a solid
preventive back program take?'' says Minkow. ``Three hours a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, prescribing specific exercises and sports is
difficult. ``Problem is, not all back problems are the same,'' says
Hochschuler. ``Some exercises feel good for some people, and bad
for others. The key point is, if an exercise hurts, stop doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hochschuler and Minkow do offer some general guidelines to shore
up and protect your back. As a rule, twisting, bending sports can
be a problem; witness the conga line of golfers, racquetball,
softball and tennis players that marches through their offices.
Golf is particularly bad (``About the worst thing you can do,''
says Hochschuler). Not that these sports are out. It's just that
some kind of exercise program has to be sandwiched between weekends
so your back can handle the game.
</P>
<P>
   You also might consider some changes when you play. Hochschuler
has his golfers warm up before they start whacking balls, asks them
to bend at the knees when picking balls up and often has them
modify their swing, not much of a sacrifice given the state of most
golfers' games.
</P>
<P>
   Though cycling is generally great for backs (taking the weight
off the spine while strengthening the legs), Minkow has cyclists
with back problems raise their handlebars (``You don't want the
handlebars any lower than the seat'').
</P>
<P>
   Swimming also is good for the back. Again, the spine is freed of
the effects of gravity, and the back and critical support muscles
are strengthened. But swimmers with back problems, says
Hochschuler, should consider avoiding the butterfly stroke (it
requires hyperextension of both the back and the neck). Freestyle
can be a problem, too, constantly turning the head to breathe can
strain the neck and spine (a solution: Wear a mask and snorkel --
or try water aerobics).
</P>
<P>
   Even running, despite its inherent pounding, can work.
Hochschuler just asks his runners to buy shoes with good support
and cushioning and to avoid doing sudden stressful changes such as
upping the distance and speed of workouts simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is detail. Mostly, your aim is simple. ``The
important thing is to do something regularly,'' says Minkow. ``And
if it's a sport you like, odds are better that you will.''
</P>
<P>
   But sports don't strengthen and stretch like weight training and
stretching do, so both disciplines are critical to a healthy back.
Whole books have been written on both topics. Your best bet: Find a
good one and try the stretches and lifts they recommend -- allowing
Hochschuler's ``no pain'' dictum to be your guiding light.
</P>
<P>
   Weight training merits an additional word. Left untended, our
muscles weaken and our bones lose density, bad news for a piece of
anatomy built on these two blocks. Weight training targets both
slides in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   But done improperly it also can level the best of backs
lickety-split. Consider this: Perform a bent-over barbell row
(bending at the waist and pulling the barbell up to your chest)
with 60 pounds. The leverage places roughly 600 pounds of pressure
square on your low back.
</P>
<P>
   Minkow recommends avoiding overhead free-weight lifts such as
the clean and jerk, as they heavily compress an unsupported spine
(overhead lifts are okay on a well-designed machine with a bench
that supports your spine). In the interest of long-term back
health. He also advises skipping heavy weights altogether. If you
can't lift a weight 10 times, says Minkow, it's too heavy for your
back.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, when it comes to preventing back pain the
most important muscle may be your mind. ``No doubt, back pain can
put the fear of God in you,'' says Hochschuler. ``But most back
pain is not dangerous. And, if you stay disciplined, you can work
your way out of it.''
 &UR; (KEN McALPINE is a Ventura, Calif.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
</P>
<P>
