<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINN-BOOKS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTH STEIN TAKES AN UNEXPECTED PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not too long ago, Garth Stein won an Academy Award for his short
film ``The Lunch Date.'' Making it in the movie business requires a
combination of luck and talent. I believe the only harder industry
to crack is the book biz.
</P>
<P>
   Now Stein has made it to the printed page, too. His first novel,
``Raven Stole the Moon,'' (Pocket Books, $22) may not win any
prestigious awards, but it serves notice that Stein is a rare
talent whether on the screen or in books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies and books both require creativity, but I'm learning
fast how different they are, too,'' Stein said recently when
reached by phone at his home in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do a film, there's opening night in the movie theater
or broadcast night on TV, and then you get feedback instantly. The
viewers loved it, the critics have this to say about it, you work
hard on the project for a long time, and then there's the immediate
response. With books, it's more trickle-down. I'm constantly
looking in the paper and doing searches online to see if there are
any reviews of `Raven Stole the Moon,' any hints that someone has
read it and is responding to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Stein always planned to become an author. Life has a
habit of introducing unexpected career turns, and Stein eventually
found himself eking out a living producing documentaries.
Eventually, ``The Lunch Date'' earned him the highest film-industry
award. Being a contrary (if pleasant) sort, this encouraged Stein
to finally write a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed teachers who stressed, `Write about what
you know,''' Stein said. ``Well, I'm only one-eighth Tlinget
Indian, but I knew the legends and beliefs. There aren't many
Tlinget authors on the market, so I thought the subject matter
might be a little unique.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is that. Deftly, Stein tells the tale of Jenna
Rosen, a mother returning to Wrangell, Alaska, where two years
earlier her young son disappeared. Herself a descendent of the
Tlingets, Jenna's attempt to find out what really happened to her
child is colored by ancestral spiritual tenets she had never fully
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Even in those passages where it's obvious fledgling writer Stein
is straining a bit too much to impress, ``Raven Stole the Moon'' is
entertaining reading. Stein's already good, and as he writes more,
he'll only get better.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is associate books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
