<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEA IS TO STOP CHILDREN FROM LIGHTING UP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With a little luck, the political sideshow over
lawyers' fees, which muscled its way onto center stage in Texas'
tobacco drama, will be resolved before Attorney General Dan Morales
and Gov. George W. Bush become merely names in the history books.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes rose with recent reports that the antagonists may be at
least nearing a truce, if a small army of (what else?) lawyers
involved in negotiations can ever agree on all the devilish
details.
</P>
<P>
   The fee fight, unfortunately, has obscured the bottom line of
the lawsuit settlement with cigarette makers, and I don't mean the
25-year, $15.3 billion agreed payout to the state. You can't hide
$15.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The real bottom line is health care.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said he sued the tobacco companies two years ago for two
main reasons _ to recover public health-care costs associated with
smoking and to attack the industry for marketing its
health-damaging products to children.
</P>
<P>
   And he has urged the Legislature to spend the tobacco payments,
especially the $1.2 billion anticipated the first year, on
anti-smoking and other health-care programs.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the settlement becomes final by the time lawmakers
convene in January, the Legislature's chief budget writers have
agreed to sponsor Morales' priorities for the first year's
settlement proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for the tobacco jackpot, nevertheless, will be
keen. Politicians already are scrambling to propose alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Keeton Rylander, the Republican nominee for state
comptroller, advocates using part of the tobacco money for a
teacher pay raise. And John Sharp, the Democratic candidate for
lieutenant governor, wants to spend some of the funds to build new
classrooms for the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be more opportunistic, although worthy, spending
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Health-care advocates may have their hands full trying to snag a
lion's share of the tobacco money, particularly since Morales, who
is stepping down in January, won't be lobbying as an incumbent
officeholder.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, in the long run, than the tobacco money the
Legislature may use to treat cancer and other smoking-related
illnesses will be any funds set aside to discourage young Texans
from beginning to smoke in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Educating youths about the dangers of tobacco is a difficult
task, and money alone can't guarantee any appreciable success. But
youth is where the focus must be because most smokers start smoking
as teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   And smoking has been increasing among Texas teens. In 1996, the
most recent data available, 55 percent of all secondary students in
the state reported having used a tobacco product during their
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Morales negotiated Texas' agreement with cigarette
makers, the Legislature already had taken steps to crack down on
teen smoking. One key feature of a new law, which went into effect
in January, provides that people younger than 18 caught smoking or
possessing tobacco products can have their driver's licenses
suspended for as long as six months.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials hope that penalty, which may be the first of
its kind in the nation, will be a strong deterrent to teen smoking,
at least stronger than lectures and television ads have proved to
be in some other states.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of the driver's license sanction will largely
depend on how often it is used and how strongly the law against
teen smoking is enforced. And it is too early to know either of
those factors.
</P>
<P>
   The same law also provides for tobacco education courses for
young smokers and an ad campaign. Ad campaigns, even when adquately
funded, aren't a sure way to change people's behavior, particularly
the behavior of teen-agers, most of whom seem to think they will
live forever and resist sermons.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texas ad campaign isn't anywhere near being adequately
funded. The Texas Department of Health has only $300,000 this year
for the entire anti-tobacco public awareness program.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few spots on radio and television, warning
teens of the driver's license suspension penalty. And the health
department plans to convey the same message on six donated
billboards _ that's right, only six _ in the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   That compares to hundreds of tobacco industry billboards that
have promoted smoking throughout teen-agers' lives. Those
billboards are finally coming down under the lawsuit settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has asked the Legislature to set aside $200 million of
the first-year tobacco proceeds for an anti-smoking and tobacco
awareness campaign aimed primarily at young people. Such a large
figure boggles the minds of underfunded health officials. Let us
hope, if they actually get it, that the sum doesn't boggle their
imaginations, because more creativity may be needed to curb teen
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   What good would the much-ballyhooed anti-tobacco effort of today
_ including Texas' impressive tobacco settlement _ have really
accomplished if significantly fewer people aren't smoking 10 or 20
years from now?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clay Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
