<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTONIO-BANDERAS-IN-THE-MASK-OF-ZORRO-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTONIO BANDERAS TAKES A STAB AT `ZORRO' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Antonio Banderas in a scene from ``The
Mask of Zorro.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Ask any of his fans _ Antonio Banderas was born to play Zorro.
 &HT;    ``I probably should just follow the remarks of the people who
believe that,'' Banderas says with a laugh. ``Maybe in three or
four years, when I'm really removed from the film, I can be a
better judge.
 &HT;    ``I suppose it may work, me as Zorro,'' he allows. ``People
don't give you gifts for no reason. If someone thought I was right
to play Zorro, then I respect that and say, `Thank you,' because
here I am.''
 &HT;    Directed by Martin Campbell, ``The Mask of Zorro'' opens
nationwide on July 17. It's a fresh spin on the oft-told tale,
picking up decades after the old-Mexican saga normally ends. In
this version, an aging Zorro (Anthony Hopkins), escaping after 20
years' imprisonment, takes a young thief (Banderas) under his wing
and grooms him to assume the mask and the legend.
 &HT;    Complicating matters are Catherine Zeta Jones as Hopkins'
daughter and Banderas' love interest, and two hissable villains,
the corrupt Don Rafael Montero (Stuart Wilson) and his henchman,
Capt. Harrison Love (Matt Letscher).
 &HT;    ``These five people, really, are the engine of the movie,''
Banderas says, relaxing at Los Angeles' posh Four Seasons Hotel.
``Even with all the adventure you see, you're always with these
interesting characters, and it's always about how the adventure
affects them.''
 &HT;    Banderas steps into some intimidating boots in donning Zorro's
mask. Douglas Fairbanks Sr., Tyrone Power, Alain Delon and even
George Hamilton swashbuckled through earlier big-screen
incarnations, while Guy Williams achieved stardom in the 1960s
television series, ``Zorro,'' which aired on Spain's lone station
during Banderas' youth.
 &HT;    ``All of them brought something new to the Zorro legend,'' the
38-year-old actor says. ``Our movie has bits and pieces of the
styles of all the films those gentlemen made.
 &HT;    ```Mask of Zorro' is a comedy, a drama, a romance and an epic at
the end,'' he says. ``I think the balance and that combination of
styles make our movie special.''
 &HT;    Though ``Zorro'' features A-list talent on screen and bears the
golden touch of a producer named Spielberg, Banderas isn't sure if
audiences accustomed to special-effects-laden spectacles will turn
out for an old-fashioned adventure in which the ultimate weapon is
a fine Toledo blade.
 &HT;    ``That's a mystery,'' Banderas says. ``Children, especially, may
not know what to make of it. I can speak for myself here, because
my stepson is 12 now, and he's pretty much into lasers, computers
and movies with spaceships.
 &HT;    ``I don't know how kids who like what he does, and there are
lots of them, will relate to a guy with a sword, to a film where
characters get around on horses, where there are no special
effects,'' he admits.
 &HT;    ``Will people go? I don't know. I hope so,'' he says. ``We'll
all find out on July 17. We'll see if Zorro is a character who can
help close out the end of a century of movies.''
 &HT;    If Zorro is a fusion of Spanish culture and American show
business, Banderas may be the right man for the job. Born in
Malaga, the actor first performed in Spanish theater productions
and later in three dozen Spanish feature films, including three of
director Pedro Almodovar's best, ``Labyrinth of Passion'' (1982),
``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown'' (1988) and ``Tie Me
Up! Tie Me Down!'' (1990).
 &HT;    Banderas' ambitions always reached beyond Spain, however. In
1992 he came to America to co-star in ``The Mambo Kings'' as a
Cuban musician, a role for which he learned to speak English
phonetically.
 &HT;    Since then, Banderas has popped up in his share of hits and
flops, including ``Philadelphia'' (1993), ``Interview with the
Vampire'' (1994), ``Assassins'' (1995), ``Evita'' (1996) and ``Two
Much'' (1996), the last of which is best remembered _ if it is
remembered at all _ as the film during which Banderas met and fell
in love with Melanie Griffith. They married the next year.
 &HT;    ``I feel lucky and, against what some people might think, I feel
that I opened my range of possibilities when I came to America,''
Banderas says. ``I'd done 34 movies in Spain, and was getting
trapped into playing the same characters again and again.
 &HT;    ``When I got here, I got a new start,'' he says. ``I went from
action movie to horror movie, from musicals to psychological
thrillers and comedies. I've done every style of movie, which is
more than some really big superstars get to do.
 &HT;    ``I know I've gotten to do more here than I ever would've been
able to do in Europe,'' he concludes, ``and I feel very good about
that.''
 &HT;    Next up for Banderas are two more distinctly different projects.
In ``The 13th Warrior,'' a late-fall release, Banderas stars as an
Arab who reluctantly joins Vikings heading to northern Europe to
fight an unknown enemy.
 &HT;    Stretching in another direction, he will make his directing
debut with ``Crazy in Alabama,'' a black comedy in which he appears
with his wife.
 &HT;    ``Directing comes naturally to me,'' Banderas says offhandedly.
``After acting in so many films, I suddenly felt the need to go
behind the camera so I could tell people how I see the world, how I
see events, how I'd put together a movie as a director, a
storyteller.
 &HT;    ``It has been a good experience for me, very revealing from so
many aspects.''
 &HT;    Not every novice director would want his wife in the cast of his
first venture, but Banderas says that the experience only made him
appreciate her more.
 &HT;    ``I did, I did,'' he says, laughing. ``I loved having Melanie on
the set, and I felt more than love. I felt admiration.
 &HT;    ``Melanie is a gorgeous actress,'' he adds, ``and she gave me a
lot in the movie. She's beautiful to watch working, and I hope that
will come across on the screen.''
 &HT;    When Banderas and Griffith first hooked up, it was the stuff of
tabloid dreams. ``LATIN LOVER DUMPS WIFE FOR DON JOHNSON'S TWO-TIME
EX,'' the tabloids raved.
 &HT;    At the time, Banderas kept up a stoic front, smiling for the
cameras and ignoring the insinuations. Now, happily married and the
father of a child with Griffith, the Spaniard is willing to admit
that the feeding frenzy caused great pain for himself and for
Griffith.
 &HT;    ``It hurt us personally and professionally,'' says Banderas, who
splits his time between homes in Los Angeles and Spain.
``Fortunately, we are a bit away from all that.
 &HT;    ``Once in a while somebody has to say something about us,'' he
adds with a touch of bitterness, ``so they'll invent some news and
just throw it in there. But it's not traumatic _ I don't care
anymore.
 &HT;    ``We had to pay a price to be together and we did it,'' he says
flatly. ``Now, because we don't do anything strange or scandalous,
because we have a close family, they're getting bored with us.''
 &HT;    After whetting his musical chops in ``Evita,'' the adaptation of
the Tim Rice-Andrew Lloyd Webber stage musical, Banderas has been
lobbying for the lead in the long-delayed film version of Webber's
Broadway hit, ``Phantom of the Opera.'' Also in the works is a film
biography of the Cuban baseball star Orlando ``El Duque''
Hernandez, now with the New York Yankees, which would co-star Cuba
Gooding Jr.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Banderas aims to slow his professional pace.
 &HT;    ``I want to balance my life, my family and my work,'' he says.
``Also, in 1995 I had six movies out almost at the same time, and I
thought I was completely overexposed.
 &HT;    ``I was following the same pattern I did in Spain,'' he says,
``and that doesn't work here. I reflected on that, and now I'm
working less and, I think, doing better work.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
