<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATT-DILLON-IN-THERES-SOMETHING-ABOUT-MARY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING ABOUT MATT DILLON 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Matt Dillon with Cameron Diaz and Lin
Shaye in a scene from ``There's Something About Mary.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    There's something rather goofy and endearing about Matt Dillon.
 &HT;    You have to get past the caginess inevitably engendered by a
decade in Hollywood. Heaven knows, you have to get past the dark,
brooding good looks and the haunted, deep-set eyes.
 &HT;    But behind them lurks ... a Chevy Chase fan?
 &HT;    ``Anything with Chevy Chase, I'm there,'' Dillon says, relaxing
in Beverly Hills' swank Four Seasons Hotel. ``I love all those
`Vacation' movies. Years from now, people will look back on the
movies of Chevy and finally show some respect. These are comedy
classics.''
 &HT;    Dillon is thinking a lot about comedy these days, because his
latest film, ``There's Something About Mary,'' opening July 15, is
a freewheeling farce from the Farrelly brothers, writers/directors
of ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber'' (1994) and ``Kingpin'' (1996).
 &HT;    It was the offbeat script that sold him on the project, he says.
 &HT;    ``I didn't know where it was going,'' the actor says. ``Finally,
it was a script with a few surprises. I also think it's one of
those movies that's a little gross. People are just going to have a
good time and laugh.''
 &HT;    ``A little gross'' may be understating it. In one scene _
disgusting or hilarious, depending on your sense of humor _ Cameron
Diaz, Dillon's co-star and real-life girlfriend, unwittingly ends
up using some bodily fluids as hair gel.
 &HT;    ``I do have one of those sick senses of humor,'' Dillon says,
``so this stuff just ... ''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``You just have to go with it,'' he says. ``This was one of the
funniest scripts I've ever read.''
 &HT;    Dillon is best known for dramatic roles, but he says he loves
comedy _ and, indeed, he turned in an underappreciated performance
as a vain Hollywood idol in last year's ``In &AMP; Out.''
 &HT;    ``I think comedy is the hardest thing to write,'' he says. ``I
don't get offered a lot of comedies, which is a shame, because I
think I'm fairly good at it.''
 &HT;    Dillon also welcomed the chance to make a film with Diaz.
 &HT;    ``There's no denying that we have screen chemistry,'' he says.
``You can't fake what we have up there. You can't reproduce it with
other people _ it's real. You know, we like each other a little
bit.''
 &HT;    Ever since Dillon and Diaz met two years ago, he says, they've
been looking for a project they could do together.
 &HT;    ``I'm sure everybody expected that we would do a big, sweeping
romance or some serious drama,'' he says. ``We love the idea that
we went in the opposite direction and did this off-the-wall
thing.''
 &HT;   Dillon knows off-the-wall. Earlier this year, he shocked
audiences with ``Wild Things,'' a twisty, erotic thriller in which
he played an unethical high-school guidance counselor enmeshed in a
complex fraud scheme _ and steamy group sex _ with two of his
students, played by Neve Campbell and Denise Richards.
 &HT;    ``People are still talking about the sex scene with me, Neve and
Denise,'' Dillon says, shaking his head.
 &HT;    Campbell and Richards reportedly made it through their
eight-hour threesome scene with the aid of a shot of tequila
apiece.
 &HT;    ``Hey, I didn't drink,'' Dillon says, rolling his eyes.
``Generally, I don't think it's a good idea to drink on the job.
 &HT;    ``It really was a tough gig,'' he adds with a laugh. ``All those
hours of pure sleaze.''
 &HT;    Dillon scorns critics who questioned ``Wild Things'' for its
highly charged sex scenes.
 &HT;    ``You know what? I'm glad I did a movie with just pure, raw sex
scenes'' he says defiantly. ``In a lot of movies these days,
people's sex drives are played down. It used to be there was more
sexuality in films. I think films are much too tame now.
 &HT;    ``I guess we're just reacting to the times,'' he adds, ``but I
still wish we could loosen up a bit.''
 &HT;    Dillon grew up in New York's affluent Westchester County, where
he lived a typical teen-age life, playing football and listening to
music. He was discovered in a junior-high-school hallway by a
visiting talent scout.
 &HT;    ``I was cutting a class,'' he recalls, ``and these two guys
approached me in the school hallway and asked, `Do you want to
audition for a movie?' I thought it was some scam.''
 &HT;    It wasn't. Dillon made his movie debut in Jonathan Kaplan's
``Over the Edge'' (1979), and soon was Hollywood's teen-idol flavor
of the month. One magazine proclaimed him ``a breathing tribute to
the American gene pool.''
 &HT;    Dillon became a latter-day James Dean, brooding his way through
teen films such as ``My Bodyguard'' (1980), ``The Outsiders''
(1983) and ``Rumble Fish'' (1983).
 &HT;    ``People always ask if I missed my teen years,'' he says. ``I
don't think I missed anything. Do I wish I went to high school and
then some college, as opposed to going off and making films? The
answer is no. I think my life is much richer and more interesting.
If I had to do it all over again, I wouldn't change a thing.''
 &HT;    The same applies to his post-teen career, which has mixed
occasional hits such as ``Drugstore Cowboy'' (1989) with copious
flops, from ``Rebel'' (1985) to ``Mr. Wonderful'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``What has kept me sane is that I look at this business with a
sense of humor,'' he says. ``Hollywood is really a pretty funny
place.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes it's hard to keep your perspective,'' he adds,
``because you can get caught up in all the hype and the fame.
Bottom line: This is a tough racket, but I just try to have fun
with it.''
 &HT;    Currently, his idea of fun is a script he's working on, one
which he hopes to direct and star in.
 &HT;    ``I don't really want to go into the details, but I will say
it's a fairly ambitious project,'' he says evasively. ``I guess
when you write your first script and direct your first movie,
you're suppose to think small, but mine is an international type of
story with a lot of guys.''
 &HT;    Why not entrust it to a more experienced director, then, the way
Matt Damon and Ben Affleck gave ``Good Will Hunting'' (1997) to Gus
Van Sant, or perhaps find someone else to star, as Robert Redford
did with ``Ordinary People'' (1980)?
 &HT;    ``I just can't give it to anyone else,'' Dillon says. ``Plus I
don't want to drive some other guy crazy. My second problem is that
I wrote one of the parts with myself in mind. Now, what am I going
to do but do both?''
 &HT;    Diaz won't appear, though.
 &HT;    ``There really isn't a part for her,'' Dillon says regretfully.
 &HT;    Besides, he says, the two usually don't mix business and
pleasure. And, no, though they're both actors, they aren't
competitive with one another.
 &HT;    ``Sure, jealousy is part of human nature,'' he says, ``but it's
an immature emotion that you should just acknowledge and then let
go. It's when you hang onto it that you get in trouble.
 &HT;    ``I wondered if the business would add extra stress,'' Dillon
admits. ``But there is the whole other side: It's an advantage to
date someone who understands exactly what's going on in your life.
 &HT;    ``Listen, the most difficult thing about being in a relationship
with someone in the film business is that you both have crazy
schedules,'' he says. ``That's complicated. But there is also
someone right there who can sympathize and empathize when you tell
them, `We had to do 25 takes.'''
 &HT;    Even on those days, though, Dillon says he still loves his work:
 &HT;    ``Every time the camera rolls, it's still magic.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
