 FRANCES McDORMAND TAKES A SHINE TO MADELINE  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Frances McDormand and numerous little
girls in a scene from ``Madeline.'' 
 By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The last time most of us saw Frances McDormand, she was
reasoning with a man who was feeding a body into a wood chipper.
 &HT;    Those who passed through Dublin during May and June may have
caught her going stark, staring mad at the Gate Theatre.
 &HT;    Is this someone you'd trust with little girls?
 &HT;    Actually, the real Frances McDormand is nothing like the very
pregnant Sheriff Marge Gunderson, the role that won her a Best
Actress Oscar in ``Fargo'' (1996) and included the wood-chipper
scene. And she doesn't much resemble Blanche DuBois in Tennessee
Williams' ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' which she was playing in
Dublin.
 &HT;    Actually, she's a sharp, funny and very fast-talking woman whom
you'd have no problem entrusting with your little girl _ which is
good, because on July 10 she's opening in theaters everywhere as
the saintly, if occasionally exasperated, Miss Clavel in the film
adaptation of the children's classic, ``Madeline.''
 &HT;    Yes, that Miss Clavel, who lives ``in an old house in Paris all
covered with vines'' and oversees ``12 little girls in two straight
lines.''
 &HT;    ```Madeline' came at the perfect time,'' McDormand says
brightly, speaking on a car telephone somewhere in London. ``I had
committed to doing `Streetcar' in Dublin and the stage play
`Oedipus' in New York this fall. Since I was spending the majority
of my time working in the theater, I was hoping to do another film.
 &HT;    ```Madeline' was perfect because it was a character I really
wanted to play,'' she adds. ``I love Miss Clavel. I've been reading
the books to my son for two years, acting the part out every time I
read it, and the chance to do it on film was wonderful.''
 &HT;    Besides which, the filming required her to spend three months in
Paris _ hardly an imposition.
 &HT;    ``Oh, the food!'' she exclaims unabashedly.
 &HT;    McDormand's exuberant, chatty demeanor comes as a surprise.
She's so well known for intelligent, intense dramatic performances
_ from Alan Parker's ``Mississippi Burning'' (1988) and Ken Loach's
``Hidden Agenda'' (1990) to ``Paradise Road'' (1997) _ that one
expects the actress to be as serious and self-contained as the
parts she plays.
 &HT;    By rights, perhaps she should be. Born in Illinois, she was the
youngest of a minister's three children. Her father's duties
required the family to move every few years, except for a
seven-year stretch in Pennsylvania when Fran, as her friends call
her, was in high school.
 &HT;    ``We moved around, but I had a really solid family,'' she says.
``And the denomination my father was involved with emphasized
community outreach. Outside of having a congregation, my dad was
very involved with youth organizations and food banks.''
 &HT;    This doubtless explains McDormand's own sense of commitment to
helping those less fortunate. For the past 13 years she has been
involved with the 52nd Street Project in New York, a theater-based
recreational program for underprivileged kids.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I'm sure that's the values my parents gave me,'' she says,
``making sure I gave some back and didn't just take.''
 &HT;    The other big influence on McDormand was books. Even as a child
she was an avid reader. One of the things she enjoyed most about
doing ``Streetcar'' was the chance to spend three months in
Ireland, with its strong literary tradition.
 &HT;    ``The Irish have a cultural relationship with literature,'' she
says. ``Everybody reads books there, and everybody can recite
poetry. Writers are given cultural tax exemptions in Ireland. They
are seen as something that needs to be fostered!''
 &HT;    Every day during her stay, the actress would take a commuter
train from outside Dublin, where she, her husband and their son
were living, to the theater.
 &HT;    ``And everybody on the train was reading,'' she marvels. ``Sure,
some had magazines and newspapers, but the majority were reading
books.''
 &HT;    That love of the written word is something she finds sadly
lacking in the United States.
 &HT;    ``I can't tell you the number of kids in the projects who reach
the age of 14 and cannot read,'' she says sadly. ``To me, the idea
of not being able to read or not having a love of books is ... ''
 &HT;    Her voice trails off.
 &HT;    ``We're known for movies, not for literature,'' she continues.
``I think the electronic and media age is attached to the American
culture: television, film, video.''
 &HT;    McDormand discovered acting in high school, when she performed a
scene from ``Macbeth'' in English class. She studied drama at
Bethany College, a small school in West Virginia _ she was the only
theater major in her class _ before heading to the Yale School of
Drama for graduate study.
 &HT;    Then it was on to New York, where she roomed for awhile with
another struggling thespian, Holly Hunter.
 &HT;    Her first professional job took her to Trinidad, where she
performed in a production organized by the poet Derek Walcott. Her
second was an independent movie called ``Blood Simple'' (1984),
which put its director/producer team of Ethan and Joel Coen on the
map.
 &HT;    The part had actually been written with Hunter in mind, but when
the actress couldn't wriggle out of a prior theatrical commitment,
the brothers cast McDormand instead.
 &HT;    More than her performance clicked: Soon thereafter, McDormand
and Joel Coen were married. Their son, Pedro, is now 3 years old.
 &HT;    Pedro was one reason McDormand wanted to do ``Madeline.''
Another big thrill was appearing in a ``Sesame Street'' video with
Big Bird last year.
 &HT;    ``It was one of the best things that came out of getting the
Academy Award,'' she says with a laugh. ``I was a nervous wreck. I
kept forgetting my lines because I was working with Big Bird. He's
such an icon! It was all too much for me.''
 &HT;    Unlike many actors, who break into the movies and never look
back, McDormand relishes the stage and was pleased to be able to
return after a five-year absence, caused in part by the adoption of
Pedro and in part by the demands of her husband's film career.
 &HT;    She admits to some worries prior to ``Streetcar,'' however.
 &HT;    ``One was the stamina: being able to get through two and a half
hours, six evenings a week,'' she says. ``The other was my voice. I
haven't been the most conscientious of actors _ I don't do vocal
exercises and I do smoke. I had some trouble with my voice every
now and again, but never to the point that I wasn't able.''
 &HT;    Audience response to the Dublin production was varied but always
gratifying, McDormand says. Overall she considers it a great
success, and a great experience for her.
 &HT;    The same goes for ``Madeline,'' her token journey away from the
weird worlds she normally inhabits professionally.
 &HT;    But devotees of her intense characterizations should take heart.
She isn't considering Julie Andrews as a role model. In August, she
begins rehearsals for her next project: ``Oedipus,'' on the New
York stage.
 &HT;    Expect murders, incest, wars, eye-gouging and a lot of anguished
soliloquies.
 &HT;    And not a pigtail in sight.
 c.1998 Jean Oppenheimer  
