<SLUG> BC-KEVIN-NEWMAN-OF-GOOD-MORNING-AMERICA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN NEWMAN SAYS `GOOD MORNING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kevin Newman on the set of ``Good Morning
America.'' 
 By JILL GERSTON  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Kevin Newman was called into the office of David Westin,
the president of ABC News, in March, he thought he was going to be
admonished for some gaffe he might have made as the news anchor of
``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was offered the plum assignment of co-host for the
network's morning show. He took over with Lisa McRee on May 4, when
``Good Morning America'' introduced a citified set and new theme
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the host is very different from being the news anchor,''
Newman says. ``You have to reveal yourself, because there is almost
no script _ it's all out of your head. It's all about how
comfortable you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the high-profile job has sent his anxiety level
``way up there.'' On camera the 38-year-old Newman appears totally
at ease. More important to viewers, who are finicky about whom they
share their morning coffee with, he seems like a regular guy,
someone you'd see standing in line at The Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very unassuming in a lot of ways,'' says Shelley Lewis,
the executive producer of ``Good Morning America.'' ``He doesn't
see himself as some big star.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-night news buffs became acquainted with Newman when he
served as the anchor of ABC's overnight news programs, ``World News
Now'' and ``World News This Morning,'' from 1994 to 1996. His next
stint was as a correspondent for ``World News Tonight'' and
co-anchor of ``Good Morning America Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Newman's star-making turn came in August 1997, when the
Princess of Wales died in a Paris car crash. For four nonstop
hours, Newman held the fort as anchor for ABC's coverage of that
breaking news story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a holiday weekend, so the A-string folks weren't as
close as I was to be called in,'' says Newman, who was at home in
New Jersey with his family when the call came. ``As we began
chasing the story, it was apparent it was much more serious than a
car accident. I assumed that someone else would be brought in to
take over, but they hung with me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was no random decision, Lewis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin never loses his place or his cool during a breaking news
story,'' she says. ``He has that key gift for live television of
being very organized in his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Toronto, Newman graduated from the University of Western
Ontario and began his career ``carrying coffee cups'' in the
newsroom of a regional Canadian television station. He eventually
became the parliamentary correspondent for the Canadian
Broadcasting Corporation and the anchor of ``Midday,'' a show
similar to ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, he left that star post for ABC and a low-profile
job as a news anchor in the wee hours of the morning. Some
observers, particularly in Canada, found his decision baffling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television in Canada was becoming a shrinking thing,'' he
explains. ``There were more challenges here.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman has found a challenge with ``Good Morning America,''
whose declining ratings have put it far behind NBC's ``Today''
show.
</P>
<P>
   By giving ``Good Morning America'' a new pair of anchors, a new
set, new music and looser pacing, the network is trying to
reinvigorate a program that had become somewhat predictable with
longtime hosts Joan Lunden and Charles Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of feel we're like `Star Trek, the Next Generation,'''
Newman says, citing a show that is famous for having taken awhile
to find its footing after a complete cast change before becoming a
smash hit.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the network expected an instant turnaround in ratings,
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `Don't worry, it's a marathon,''' he says, ``and I
take them at their word.''
</P>
<P>
   Before accepting his newest post, Newman says, he discussed it
with his wife Cathy and their children, 12-year-old Alex and
8-year-old Erica.
</P>
<P>
   ``With most other promotions it has been, `Thanks, great, when
do I start?,' but this is a very public job that, as Charlie Gibson
told me, is all-consuming,'' he says. ``I wasn't sure I wanted that
for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   His family urged him to grab ABC's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They focused me on how I felt about the challenge,'' he says.
``Ultimately, I thought, `I don't want anybody else taking it. It's
too good a job.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jill Gerston is a Grosse Point, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
