<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-WAGES-HNS &LR;      07-06 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-WAGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO COUNCIL LINKS `LIVING WAGE' TO TAX INCENTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Companies hoping to get a tax break from the city
of San Antonio will have to pay the majority of their workers at
least $9.27 per hour under a ``living wage'' ordinance approved by
the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   After much debate and jostling among elected officials and
business leaders, the council voted 7-4 Thursday to link the living
wage to the city's principal economic development tool.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ordinance, companies will have to pay seven of every
10 of their workers at least $9.27 per hour to qualify for tax
breaks in this South Texas city of more than 1 million people. The
U.S. minimum wage is $5.15 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio is the first major city in Texas to include a wage
criteria in its tax phase-in guidelines, according to the San
Antonio Economic Development Foundation, which vigorously opposed
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Metro Alliance and Communities Organized for Public
Service hailed the decision as a major victory for city workers and
a big step toward reversing the perception of San Antonio as a
low-wage city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, we thank those council people who had the courage to
stay with us,'' said Sister Gabriella Lohan, a Metro Alliance
executive committee member. ``Unfortunately, some business leaders
were afraid of risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater San Antonio Chamber of Commerce executives argued for a
lower wage level, contending that a higher minimum could hurt the
city's ability to attract jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The higher wage represents the average hourly earnings in the
San Antonio Metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Howard Peak, who voted against the measure, said the new
standard was too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can wish for wings, but our butts are going to hit the
ground when we try to fly. I think we need to be more realistic,''
Peak said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new abatement rules, durable manufacturing companies
would have to pay $10.13 per hour, while all other jobs, such as
aviation, technology, hotels, and warehouses would have to pay at
least $9.27 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   For the first year of their abatement period, companies would
have to pay only 80 percent of the new wage standards. The idea is
to give them time to ``ramp-up'' and train new workers.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Debra Guerrero's amendment to set the number of
jobs for the new wage standard at 70 percent was seen as crucial in
deciding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular issue becomes a balance between trying to
continue to attract economic development and jobs to this city and
making sure it benefits a whole host of people and provides a
higher standard of living,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Hernandez, president of the Economic Development
Foundation, said the living wage could create a disincentive for
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be effectively eliminating the only financial
incentive tool if we mandate a high minimum wage to this critical
program,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
