<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-06 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINCH BUGS THRIVE IN HOT, DRY WEATHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Large areas of my lawn are yellowish and stunted. Is this
caused by an insect or disease?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A: I suspect chinch bugs may be your problem. Hot, dry summer
conditions are an invitation to these insects, and the typically
hot and dry areas of the lawn near the drive and street are
especially vulnerable. Chinch bugs suck the sap from grass blades
and make them wilt, then die. Irregular, yellowish patches appear,
or the grass turns yellow, then brown. If you try to pull the
affected grass and it remains attached to the roots, then it is
likely that chinch bugs are at work. To be sure, push a bottomless
can into the affected lawn, fill with water, wait a few minutes
and, if they are present, the chinch bugs will soon be swimming
around in the water. The insects are about an 1/8-inch long.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage chinch bugs, water the lawn deeply during hot, dry
spells. There are insecticides such as Dursban that can be used,
but use chemicals as a last resort. Milky white grubs also damage
lawns, but these soil insects, the babies of the June bug beetle,
eat the roots of the grass, and if you tug on the blades the grass
pulls up like a carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In my quest for unusual, hardy perennials, I came across a
wormwood plant. I planted it about two feet from a mock orange. I
later heard that wormwood is disliked by most other plants and my
mock orange likely will not thrive because of this. Can you tell me
if this is true? If so, I'll relocate the wormwood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A: Wormwood is a common name given to various members of the
genus Artemisia, and I'm not sure which you have, but I have never
heard any local gardeners complain that wormwood discourages the
growth of surrounding plants. I would welcome any knowledge
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   There are artemisias, or wormwoods, that struggle in our heat
and humidity. Artemisia schmidtiana, `Silver Mound,' is one. But I
use Southernwood, A. arbrotanum, as a billowy, evergreen border
around old roses, irises, rudbeckias and purple coneflowers and
have never experienced any problems. I do have to cut it back a
couple of times each year. I also grow and enjoy`Powis
Castle'artemisia. This finely cut, silver-gray perennial is a great
foliage accent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give reasons why it is not a good idea to empty the
cat's litter box into my flower beds? I have a lot of kalanchoes,
but the leaves of the large plants are turning yellow and brown.
Should I cut these off? Does one usually cut the stems off after
the flowers are gone?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cat feces and/or cat litter are always listed as materials
that should not be added to compost piles because they attract
rodents and other animals. The same would hold true, of course, in
adding them to a flower bed. These materials also smell and would
be unsightly in a flower bed, unless buried. In addition, it is
unadvisable to use the feces/litter due to possible harmful
pathogens. I would think, too, that continuous dumping in the same
place would create a soil imbalance. I would remove damaged
kalanchoe leaves and monitor the watering. Water well, then allow
the soil to dry before watering again. Overwatering and
underwatering can cause leaves to yellow. Remove the spent flower
stems to tidy the plants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q: What conditions does my hoya need?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several species of hoya. One, Hoya carnosa, or wax
plant, likes strong indirect light or morning sun and afternoon
shade and a well-draining soil. Night temperatures in the 60s and
day temperatures 70 and up are ideal.
</P>
<P>
   If you grow the plant indoors, do not overwater; instead, keep
the soil barely moist during the growing period. Keep the humidity
level at about 50 percent. You may want to rest the plant on a tray
of moist pebbles. Apply a balanced fertilizer such as a 10-10-10
every two months during that period. If the plant is grown
outdoors, you will likely need to water and fertilize more often.
Keep the soil moist. In both cases, let the plant rest in winter.
Stop fertilizing and slow watering.
</P>
<P>
   The wax plant produces clusters of waxy, fragrant, star-shaped
flowers that are borne each year on the same short spurs, so do not
remove these or you'll lose the next round of blooms. The succulent
young stems become woody as the plant ages, and the hoya is
suitable for hanging baskets or training on a short trellis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
