<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2234 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-DIABETES-2TA     07-06 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-DIABETES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLING SIDE EFFECTS ARE LINKED TO EFFECTIVE AIDS DRUG THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ Imagine lying on your death bed exhausted
and wasted, just a shell of your former self. Suddenly, a new
therapy lets you gain weight and strength. You resume your daily
activities, if not return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Then about a year later, you learn that your miracle new therapy
unexpectedly produces bizarre side effects. Your body changes shape
in peculiar ways and blood tests indicate you cannot properly
metabolize fat, perhaps increasing your risk of a fatal heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Do you stop the very therapy that has brought you back to life?
Or do you continue it, trading your new found well-being for
unknown long-term risks?
</P>
<P>
   What if you are in the early stages of the disease and feel
fine? What if national guidelines suggest you should start the
therapy? Do you accept the unknown risks? Or demand another
therapy?
</P>
<P>
   Troubling questions like these have filled medical history when
promising new therapies have gone sour. The questions come up now
in a dramatic way in AIDS because of a recently recognized
constellation of findings known as the lipodystrophy syndrome. It
produces a different pattern from the wasting syndrome long known
as a part of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the lipodystrophy syndrome, the face, arms, and legs become
thin. The skin becomes dry, the lips cracked. Weight drops. Veins
stick out as cords, and although normal, may be mistaken for
varicose veins.
</P>
<P>
   While fat disappears from some areas, for unknown reasons it
redistributes to build up in others. The back of the neck resembles
a buffalo hump. Breasts enlarge. A woman may have to buy a bra that
is two sizes larger than the last one. The abdomen swells producing
a sometimes painful pot belly that is dubbed ``a protease paunch.''
A woman may look pregnant when she is not. Exercise may not work it
off.
</P>
<P>
   Several published reports have linked the syndrome to the drug
cocktails that contain one of the powerful protease inhibitor drugs
that were introduced in the last two and a half years. Many
discussions at the 12th World AIDS Conference that ended here last
week focused on the syndrome as experts from several countries
reported new cases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David A. Cooper, of Sydney, Australia, an international
leader in AIDS research, and Dr. Andrew Carr expanded on their
earlier published findings that 74 out of 116 or about 64 percent
of patients taking protease inhibitors developed the syndrome,
compared to 1 out of 132 who did not.
</P>
<P>
   Two other published reports from France and Hong Kong put the
incidence at about 25 percent and others have reported lower
figures.
</P>
<P>
   The wide variation in incidence figures was attributed to
different factors. One factor is the tendency of many doctors to
deny existence of the side effects, Cooper said. A second factor is
variations in research methods. Researchers who have asked the
patients directly about the problem in a questionnaire have
reported higher rates than researchers who reported only their
observations.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are as likely as anyone to deny a troubling new problem.
Like patients, doctors can become as frustrated when they have no
effective therapy to offer and as enthusiastic as patients when a
new therapy suddenly offers dramatic improvement. That development
contributed to the euphoric mood at the AIDS meeting in Vancouver
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As devastating as the disfigurement may be to some people, the
cosmetic changes may be the least worrisome part of the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are worried about more serious, even potentially fatal,
changes in fat metabolism. A small but growing number of studies
find that many individuals who are taking the drug cocktail have
high levels of cholesterol and lipids in the blood and other
metabolic changes that may increase the risk of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has warned about a possible
link between the protease inhibitors and diabetes, though a causal
link has not been established.
</P>
<P>
   The warning about diabetes was particularly arresting because at
the AIDS meeting two years ago, an exuberant speaker said that the
then-new protease inhibitors had made AIDS ``a chronic manageable
disease just like diabetes.'' At the meeting here, speakers played
on the twist in meaning due to development of diabetes as a
possible complication of the drug and repeated the statement to
caution against further hubris.
</P>
<P>
   Although changes in body shape may not be life threatening, they
greatly concern patients. Doctors from Spain and other countries
reported that patients have stopped taking protease inhibitors
because of psychological problems resulting from the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many people have stopped the drugs or switched
to different combinations because drug therapies are not routinely
monitored in practice. Some AIDS doctors estimated that at least
one-third of people who started drug cocktails have stopped them
after two years because of side-effects or inability to adhere to
the rigid regimen of taking up to 20 pills a day.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The lipodystrophy syndrome has caught AIDS experts by surprise.
There were disturbing warning signs in early scientific reports of
increased blood levels of cholesterol, triglycerides, and glucose.
But they were disregarded amid the excitement over the dramatic
developments.
</P>
<P>
   Now the side effects have become ``a very large problem,'' said
Cooper, who was one of the first to raise a yellow flag about the
lipodystrophy syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the percentage of individuals who develop the
syndrome may vary with the different drugs within the class of
protease inhibitors and that it was not known whether newer drugs
in the pipeline will also cause the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Although the drug cocktails are helping tens of thousands of
infected people live longer and better, there is uncertainty about
their long-term safety. The uneasiness creates a problem for
doctors and patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Hirschel, who treats many AIDS patients in Geneva
and was conference chairman, said doctors and patients must weigh
the disfigurement and the unknown longer-term risks of protease
inhibitors against the possibility of a steady decline in the
patient's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that ``many of the patients in Sydney were about to
check out, and the drugs saved their lives.'' Thus, he said he was
reluctant to switch drugs among people with advanced AIDS. But ``in
asymptomatic infection, the risk-benefit ratio is not known,''
Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald P. Kotler's team from St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital
Center, in New York City, doubted a link between the lipodystrophy
syndrome and protease inhibitors, saying that the syndrome occurred
before the widespread use of drug cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   But if so, doctors would have reported the syndrome earlier,
many other AIDS experts said in disagreeing with Kotler's report.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS researchers did agree on the need to expand and standardize
studies of the side-effects of the drug cocktails to make it easier
to compare findings to try to answer such important questions about
whether the fat deposits creating buffalo humps are permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Medical journal articles sometimes pay little attention to side
effects. For example, in the July 1 issue of Journal of the
American Medical Association, Dr. Roy M. Gulick of New York
Hospital-Cornell Medical Center, in New York City, did not include
such data in a report that stressed the long-term effectiveness of
a cocktail including the protease inhibitor, indinavir.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference that the AMA held here and partly paid for
by indinavir's manufacturer, Merck, Gulick said few side effects
were seen in the study. But Gulick said findings from triglyceride
tests were not available and that he did not test for cholesterol
because he began the study before the lipodystrophy problem arose.
</P>
<P>
   Merck said the incidence of high triglyceride levels was
comparable in other studies of the drug except for one in which it
was inexplicably high. In it, 26 of 352 recipients, or 7.4 percent,
had high triglyceride levels compared with none of 105 in a group
that did not receive it.
</P>
<P>
   American and European doctors plan to begin trials later this
year to test drug combinations that exclude protease inhibitors to
determine if they could become first line therapy, replacing those
combinations that include protease inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Even if newer combinations work, participants said the side
effects of protease inhibitors highlight the need for new and safer
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the side effects of AIDS drugs are leading metabolic
researchers to begin studying them to see if they can shed light on
the way heart disease developed.
</P>
<P>
   Drug cocktail users who develop high blood levels of cholesterol
and triglycerides may be advised to take additional drugs to lower
their risk of a heart attack. If so, the extra pills would add to
the complexity of their daily pill burden.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Keith Henry of St. Paul, Minn., said it was unclear
whether such therapies will be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Krista Dong, of Brown University in Providence, R.I., found
that changes in body shape was a common side-effect among women
taking such drugs. Of 116 women in Dr. Dong's study, 21 expressed
concern over the change in their body. The changes were noted as
early as six weeks, but most were observed at about a year. Ninety
percent reported an increase in abdominal girth and 70 percent in
breast size. ``Regular aerobic exercise had minimal effect on body
shape,'' Dr. Dong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
