<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROY-OHIO07-COX     07-06 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROY-OHIO07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (ATTN: National, feature editors)
 &HT;    Rogers touched Ohio fans
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON _ When Roy Rogers died Monday, memories of the ``King of
the Cowboys'' came galloping back across the years to Tim Spiller,
Lana Rhoads and other residents of Ohio's Miami Valley who were
fans of the actor's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1950s and 1960s, Roy Rogers was a symbol for kids who
wanted a cowboy hero, and he was always there for us on the radio,
the television and in the movie theater,'' says Spiller, 42, of
Dayton, a longtime admirer of the singing cowboy and a collector of
TV-related memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoads, 54, of Brookville, liked the fact that Rogers was always
the good guy. ``I never met Roy, but I wrote him a letter when I
was 12 and, as I recall, it was pretty gushy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The actor's death won't affect the Roy Rogers Festival that's
held every June in Portsmouth, Ohio, where Rogers lived for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for the whole world, but the festival will
go on because people want it that way,'' festival chairwoman Nancy
Horsley said Monday. This year's festival, held June 4-6, attracted
about 3,000 people to the small Ohio River city.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers made at least two visits to the Dayton area. In 1950, the
actor, his wife Dale Evans and his horse Trigger, performed with a
Western variety show at Hobart Arena in Troy. Six years later,
Rogers competed in the Grand American Trap Shoot in Vandalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't win any prizes, but Roy was a very good shot,'' said
Dayton Daily News columnist Jim Nichols, who covered the trapshoot
for the newspaper that year.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' death probably won't boost prices of Roy Rogers
memorabilia, Spiller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff is already more popular than that of any other
cowboy star, including Hopalong Cassidy and Gene Autry,'' he said.
``The hottest items include lamps, lunch boxes and cap guns. A
double-holster Roy Rogers toy gun set brings $200 to $1,500, and a
dome-shaped Roy Rogers Chuckwagon lunch box that's in good
condition is worth $200 to $300.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Johnson of Cincinnati, whose personal collection of Roy
Rogers memorabilia consists of thousands of items, agreed. ``They
are in demand because so many 40- and 50-year-olds had those things
when they were kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was born Leonard Franklin Slye (some references say Sly)
in Cincinnati on Nov. 5, 1911. When Leonard was a year old, his
parents, Andy and Mattie Slye, packed their four children and all
of their belongings onto a houseboat and made the 100-mile trip up
the Ohio River to Portsmouth.
</P>
<P>
   When they got there, they tied the boat at the foot of Mill
Street and lived aboard the boat until they were displaced by the
1913 flood (the same flood that devastated Dayton). After Andy used
the houseboat to rescue Portsmouth residents stranded by the
floodwaters, he pulled the craft ashore and built a foundation
under it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1919, the Slyes relocated to 20 rock-strewn acres at Duck
Run, a hilly, wooded rural area a few miles north of Portsmouth,
where they lived until moving to California in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, while singing with a Western band and using the
name Dick Weston, Rogers signed his first movie contract with
Republic Studios. After changing his name _ he chose Rogers because
he was a fan of Will Rogers, and added Roy after someone suggested
Leroy _ he made the first of his 87 films, Under Western Stars, in
1938. His is career was off and running.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers never lost sight of his Portsmouth-area roots, Horsley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy came back to visit many times over the years and he always
had a good time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Portsmouth responded by starting the Roy Rogers Festival in 1983
and erecting a small display of Roy Rogers memorabilia at the
downtown post office.
</P>
<P>
   Horsley, 58, met the actor in 1981 at the home of Cleda
Willoughby, Rogers' sister. Willoughby died three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy threw an arm around me, and it was honey this and honey
that. He was a sweet, caring person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
