<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GREENEST MONTH IN HOSPITALS, BUT DON'T PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is New Year's week at your local hospital, where
July 1 marks a beginning just as fraught with symbolism and
expectation as Jan. 1 is elsewhere. Medical schools end in June and
hospital training programs start in July; last week everyone in
them lurched a step forward.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, thousands of medical workers at hospitals across
the United States _ from new interns to seventh-year surgical
fellows _ have been at their present jobs for less than the blink
of an eye.
</P>
<P>
   Should you try very hard not to get sick this month?
</P>
<P>
   Three studies over the last 10 years say not to worry. One found
that hospital charts were sloppier in the summer, and another that
some hospital stays were a little more expensive, but none found
any evidence that more medical errors occur in July and August,
that patients stay any longer in the hospital, or that death rates
are any higher.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the atmosphere in a hospital in July can be quite heady
and invigorating, as full of good intentions and valiant
resolutions as any shiny New Year's morning. Residents and
supervisors alike are on their best behavior. Rules are enunciated,
examples are set, routines are still new enough that everyone pays
more attention to what they are doing _ and also considerably more
attention to what their trainees are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, then, July might actually be the best month to get
sick?
</P>
<P>
   The studies don't comment on that and, frankly, I would have a
hard time supporting it myself. Out of training now for many years,
I still get a little chill of memory down my spine every July 1,
followed by a surge of deep gratitude to the laws of the universe
that time will never cycle me backward to work in a hospital as a
July intern again.
</P>
<P>
   I did my time in the early 1980s, just before a wave of reform
swept through hospital training programs and eased the work
schedules a little. Back then, we were on duty in the hospital
every third night. As the year wore on, we became efficient enough
to get a little sleep during those nights, but not during July.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are unquestionably dangerous places year-round, but I
think the studies are probably right _ no ``July phenomenon'' put
our patients at unusual risk while we were still getting used to
what we were doing. This is powerful testament to the fact that
terror, adrenaline and very good intentions can sometimes
compensate for inexperience and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   But while our patients survived the month, my colleagues and I
emerged somewhat the worse for wear _ a different kind of July
phenomenon at work.
</P>
<P>
   On the night before my single day off that month, I made the
last train out of Penn Station to eastern Long Island _ and woke up
in a pitch-black railroad car at midnight at the end of the line,
scaring a conductor out of his skin. I nodded at him, turned over
and went back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   On one of her free July evenings, my friend Nancy went out for
dinner with friends, excused herself to go to the ladies' room, and
never came back. Forty-five minutes later they found her snoozing
in a stall.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a true July classic, Arthur was chatting with his mother
on the phone one night, when his doorbell began to ring. He put the
phone down and went to answer it. At the door was his mother. He
had fallen asleep on the phone; she thought an intruder must have
gotten into his apartment, and took a taxi over to rescue him.
</P>
<P>
   No lasting damage was done to any of us, but July still gets us
all in the gut.
</P>
<P>
   Whether by accident or design, hospitals seem to be configured
cannily enough to protect patients from a July phenomenon.
Reconfigurations in medical training are now starting to protect
doctors, too. The kind of brain-numbing fatigue that sent us all to
sleep far from our beds is less common than it was. The month is a
little less dramatic all around.
</P>
<P>
   However, like the restaurant sous-chef who knows that his
kitchen is now entirely up to code but continues to take his meals
elsewhere, I don't yet have it in me to wholeheartedly endorse a
July in the hospital for anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
