<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-N     07-06 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGERS IN THEIR HOMELAND, FRANCE SEEKS WORLD CUP GLORY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France is the home team in this World Cup, and yet much
of that team is seldom at home. Like French wines and designs,
French soccer players are a popular export as the twentieth century
draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Look in any direction. East to Italy, where Zinedine Zidane is
the creative spark and Didier Deschamps the defensive heart of
Juventus' midfield. South to Spain, where Christian Karembeu scored
crucial goals for Real Madrid in its run to the European club
championship in May. West to England, where Arsenal's French coach
Arsene Wenger and his French and foreign recruits won last season's
Premier League title and FA Cup. Or much further west to the United
States, where the world's only superpower went out of its way in
May to expedite the naturalization of a defender named David Regis
who wasn't considered good enough for France's national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``France figured out how to modernize its system of player
development in the '70s and '80s,'' said Wenger, ``and now it is
reaping the rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   But can France, the nation that essentially created the World
Cup in 1930, finally reap the ultimate reward on the field? It has
been to the semifinals on three other occasions, losing to Brazil
in 1958; to Germany in 1982 and again in 1986. This time, their
semifinal opponent is a titan-killer, Croatia, which is competing
in its first World Cup and fresh off a 3-0 victory over the Germans
in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the grudge match that Zidane and his teammates were
anticipating, this semifinal will be an introduction. Croatia and
France never have played, but that does not change the French
objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have equaled what the previous generations have done; now
we need to do better than the previous generations,'' Zidane said.
``I know that winning this World Cup would be the greatest feeling
I ever could have in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Zidane, 26, is the best French player of his generation, and if
his talent is hardly typical, his career choices and personal
history are. Born in Marseille, he left home for Cannes at age 13
for a soccer boarding school where he was given a solid base in
soccer tactics and technique. Zidane's innate touch and
determination did the rest, and after several seasons in the French
first division, he left for Italy and a large contract with
Juventus of Turin in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   His fellow Frenchman, national team captain Didier Deschamps,
was already there. The ruling in 1995 that ushered in an era of
American-style free agency in Europe has led to an exodus from
France, where taxes are high and television and gate receipts too
low to compete consistently with offers from Spanish, Italian and
English teams. Though some Frenchmen with high profiles have
returned _ defender Laurent Blanc from Barcelona to Marseille _
they are exceptions, and nine of the 11 players who started against
Italy in the quarterfinals are under contract with clubs outside
the country.
</P>
<P>
   This talent drain has hardly done wonders for the prestige of
the French domestic league, nor for Jacquet's telephone bills or
peace of mind. ``I've been in Italy more than I've been in
France,'' he said recently. The slender, self-made son of a
butcher, Jacquet was not supposed to be France's supreme leader for
the most important soccer tournament in its history.
</P>
<P>
   It took a stunning collapse to give him the opportunity. With
two qualifying matches remaining before the 1994 World Cup finals,
France needed only to defeat a relatively weak Israeli team or draw
with Bulgaria to secure its spot for the United States. The fact
that both matches were at home only made qualification appear even
more certain, and before hosting Israel, French newspapers reported
that coach Gerard Houillier already was discussing a lengthy
contract extension. Champagne was waiting in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But Houillier's team proceeded to surrender a 2-1 lead against
Israel in the final 10 minutes and lose. Against Bulgaria, the
score was tied at 1 when, with only seconds remaining, Emil
Kostadinov scored off a counterattack. Those two
stranger-than-fiction failures cost Houillier and the president of
the French soccer federation, Jean-Fournet Fayard, their jobs and
presumably some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquet, who had spent nine largely successful seasons coaching
Bordeaux in the 1980s, was named Houillier's interim replacement,
but he would soon become a fixture as France embarked on a
record-setting, 30-match unbeaten streak with a new group of
players, including Youri Djorkaeff, Karembeu and the gifted
playmaker Zidane. The streak ended against Denmark in September
1996, but it ended unofficially in the semifinals of the European
Championships two months earlier when the Czech Republic won on
penalty kicks after a scoreless draw that was an accurate
reflection of France's defensive-minded approach to soccer.
</P>
<P>
   That conservative approach earned Jacquet some vocal enemies at
home, but what mattered more to Jean-Marie Le Pen, the leader of
France's far right wing party, the National Front, was that
Jacquet's team did not look French.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit artificial to bring players from abroad and call it
the French team,'' Le Pen said during the championships.
</P>
<P>
   That comment drew quick condemnation from various quarters and a
quick clarification from Le Pen's party, which said he meant only
to complain that foreign players had been naturalized quickly to
make them eligible. This proved wildly inaccurate, but what is true
is that France's rainbow soccer coalition reflects both recent
immigration patterns and the far-flung places _ French Guiana, New
Caledonia and the Caribbean islands of Guadeloupe and Martinique _
that remain French territories or ``departements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team gives you a sense of the socio-cultural mix that is
France today,'' said goalkeeper Bernard Lama, who was born in
Guiana and did not come to mainland France until he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Desailly, the powerful AC Milan defender, was born in
Ghana; Karembeu in New Caledonia. Lilian Thuram, Trezeguet and
Zidane were all born on the French mainland, but Thuram's mother is
from Guadeloupe; Trezeguet's parents from Argentina and Zidane's
from Algeria (they are Kabyles). Djorkaeff's mother is Armenian and
his father Jean of Polish and Kalmuck descent.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Djorkaeff also played soccer for France, which is proof
that diversity is hardly new on this national team. Platini, after
all, was the son of Italian immigrants, and Raymond Kopa, another
all-time French great, was of Polish descent. For the most part,
France's team, like the nation it represents, has been more melting
pot than mosaic over the years. The only member of the current
group to break ranks has been Karembeu, who advocates independence
for New Caledonia and has left little mystery about where his
allegiance lies.
</P>
<P>
   Le Pen was not the last Frenchman to bemoan the team's racial
mix. ``I receive incredibly nasty letters that reproach me for
having a team of blacks and foreigners who don't know how to sing
La Marseillaise,'' Jacquet told the newspaper Le Monde last month.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacquet and his team, often criticized in a critical nation,
have managed to become immensely popular figures in the last four
weeks. Booed by the fans in Marseille during introductions before
the opening match against South Africa, Jacquet has been cheered
ever since. The lost generation has come home, and it defends like
no other team on earth. Though Jacquet's team, so offensive against
weaker opposition in group play, has again stopped scoring goals
because of its lack of a proven striker, the sound of nitpicking
has been overwhelmed by the sound automobile horns sounding off
late into the night in cities all over the country after the
victories over Paraguay and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more noise in the streets if the Croatians are the
next victims, and though Brazil or the Netherlands would be waiting
in the final, France, a nation with a remarkably rich past, already
has history on its side. The last major soccer event it hosted was
the 1984 European Championships. It won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
