<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 12)  
 (JT)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Chateau Country &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for a package tour of the chateau country, for
the late fall or midspring. Can you suggest any? _ Charles Walter,
Seal Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. The banks of the Loire between Sancerre and Nantes are
studded with 15th- and 16th-century castles. Among the must-see
chateaus are Angers, Azay-le-Rideau, Chenonceau, Blois and
Chambord.
</P>
<P>
   You have a choice of tours that leave from Paris (including day
trips and multiday excursions), a self-drive tour or a complete
program from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Vision, 214 Rue de Rivoli; telephone (33-1) 42.60.30.01,
fax (33-1) 42.86.95.36, Web parisvision.com, has a pair of day
trips from Paris, each stopping at the 440-room Chambord (the
largest chateau), the 17th-century Cheverny chateau and Chenonceau,
the famous castle over the River Cher. A trip by bus, on Tuesday,
Thursday and Sunday in winter and spring, costs $145 (at 5.88
francs to $1). It leaves from the Paris Vision office (Metro:
Tuileries) at 7:15 a.m., returning 7:30 p.m. A tour by
eight-passenger van on Tuesday and Thursday provides pickup at your
hotel; $182. Leave about 6:45 a.m. and return 8 p.m. Both trips
include tickets, guide and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Cityrama, Suite 500, 45 East 34th Street, New York, N.Y. 10016;
(212) 683-8120, fax (800) 320-0417, Web site
cityrama.com/province.htm, gives you a choice of anything from one
to four days, originating from Paris. A day trip to Chambord,
Chenonceau and the remains of the 16th-century Amboise chateau
(7:15 a.m. departure, 7:30 p.m. return, Wednesday and Sunday) costs
$89 a person, without a guide. With a guide, there is a tour to
Blois, Chenonceau and either Cheverny or Chambord, every day except
Wednesday. It leaves 7:15 a.m. and returns at 8 p.m. Cost: $136. A
two-day tour with stops in Blois, Azay-le-Rideau, the formal
16th-century gardens at Villandry and the castles of Chenonceau,
Cheverny and Chambord is $340 a person, double occupancy, including
two meals and a night in a hotel. A four-day tour, including
Normandy, is $722 a person, double occupancy. Tours leave from 4
Place des Pyramides, across from the Louvre (Metro: Palais Royal).
</P>
<P>
   EC Tours offers an eight-day Normandy Landing Beaches and Loire
Castles package out of Paris with Angers, Azay-le-Rideau, Amboise,
Villandry, Chenonceau and Blois as well as Rouen, Deauville,
Mont-St.-Michel, Tours, Orleans and Chartres. The price includes
accommodations (the Hotel Le Bordeaux or Jean Bardet in Tours, for
example), transportation in an eight-passenger van, a guide,
sightseeing, six breakfasts and five other meals; air fare is
extra. Four departures a week from mid-April to mid-October, for
$1,795 a person, double occupancy, or $2,495 for an upgrade with
rooms in chateaus. Call (800) 388-0877.
</P>
<P>
   TWA Getaway Vacations' nine-night Paris Chateaux and Countryside
visits Angers, Blois, Chenonceau and Villandry, with photo stops at
Chambord and Amboise. Other destinations on this tour include
Mont-St.-Michel, Rouen and the D-Day beaches. Departures are Sept.
26, Oct. 3 and Oct. 17. With air fare, accommodations, daily buffet
breakfast, four other meals and guide, it's $1,739 a person,
double. Call (800) 438-2929.
</P>
<P>
   Jet Vacations, (800) 538-0999, Web jetvacations.com, offers
Freewheeling Loire Valley, with five nights' accommodations in
hotels like the Renaudiere in Chenonceaux and the Alliance Trois
Rivieres in Tours, a six-day rental of a car (with automatic),
daily breakfast and three dinners. You decide departure date and
which chateaus to see. Price: $529 a person, double.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Isle of Islay &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be in Scotland in November and want to visit the Isle
of Islay to trace our genealogy. Can you give us information about
weather, ferry crossings, rooms and genealogical research? _
Susette Graham, Fairport, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Islay (pronounced EYE-lah), at the southern end of the Inner
Hebrides, is about 235 square miles, making it one of the larger of
the Hebrides, the 500-island archipelago off western Scotland. It
is known for single-malt whiskey, and you can visit any of six
distilleries. The capital, Bowmore, has the Round Church (1767),
designed so the devil wouldn't have a corner to hide in. The
eighth-century cross at Kildalton Chapel, northeast of Port Ellen,
is a prime example of Celtic crosses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the climate is relatively mild, Pat Carmichael of the
Argyll, The Isles, Loch Lomond, Stirling and Trossachs Tourist
Board, (44-1496) 810254, fax 810363, suggests being ready for chill
and rain that month.
</P>
<P>
   For genealogical research, contact Eleanor McNab at the Islay
Family History Society, Highfield, High Street, Bowmore, Isle of
Islay, PA43 7JE, (44-1496) 840675, fax 810743. She needs the
earliest accurate documentation of an ancestor on Islay. Its
population has dropped from 14,000 in 1831 to 3,200 today, she
said, because of an exodus to Canada and the United States in the
19th century.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the island, you can take a ferry from Kennacraig on
the Kintyre Peninsula, about a two-and-a-half-hour drive from
Glasgow, to Port Askaig or Port Ellen (the prettier of the two
ports). In winter there are two crossings daily. The crossing to
Port Ellen takes about 2 hours 10 minutes; to Port Askaig, 2 hours.
Round-trip fares are $17.50 (at $1.71 to a pound) for passengers in
the summer high season, lower after October. Call Caledonian
MacBrayne, (44-1496) 302209.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry also takes cars, but you probably won't need one to
explore the island. Strathclyde Passenger Transport operates buses
that link all the major towns on the island. A one-day fare card
costs $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   Lodging choices on the island include the following inns and
hotels, most of which are family run and all of which are open
year-round (rates are double, with full breakfast):
</P>
<P>
   Harbour Inn, Bowmore, (44-1496) 810330, fax 810990. Four rooms
with bath; $94.
</P>
<P>
   Lochside Hotel, Shore Street, Bowmore, (44-1496) 810244, fax
810390. Eight rooms with bath; $108.
</P>
<P>
   Hachrie Hotel, Port Ellen, (44-1496) 302310, fax 302404. All 20
rooms and 16 cottages have private bath; $127.
</P>
<P>
   Ballygrant Inn, Ballygrant, telephone and fax (44-1496) 840277.
Three rooms with shared bath; $94.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgend Hotel, Bridgend, (44-1496) 810212, fax 810960. All 10
rooms have private bath; $140.
</P>
<P>
   Port Askaig Hotel, Port Askaig, (44-1496) 840245, fax 840295.
There are 10 rooms, 8 with bath; $123.
</P>
<P>
   Port Charlotte Hotel, Port Charlotte. (44-1496) 850360, fax
850361. Ten rooms, with private bath; $155.
</P>
<P>
