<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR FARAWAY PLACES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one recent journey I visited Sedona, Ariz., and San Diego.
And for a reason that struck me only in retrospect, they made a
perfect combination.
</P>
<P>
   The co-pilot and I are forever debating _ on friendly terms, of
course _ the merits of spending time in familiar destinations vs.
exploring the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Each has its rewards:
</P>
<P>
   There is a comfort level in returning to a favorite haunt.
Logistics are simplified: You already know the way to restaurants,
shops, scenic attractions and recreational pursuits. And chances
are you've formed friendships and eagerly anticipate a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   And yet one of the main joys of travel _ from the initial
planning phase to arrival, even to subsequent discussions with
family and neighbors back home _ is the thrill of discovering new
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular trip, Sedona represented first-time
excitement; I had fantasized about seeing those beautiful,
brilliant red rocks up close, and they didn't disappoint. By
contrast, ever since my first among dozens of visits to San Diego
as a baseball and football reporter before becoming travel editor,
it's occupied a soft spot in my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I found myself focusing on other places that have
inspired me to want to return.
</P>
<P>
   I've made an arbitrary list of 10 destinations I aim to visit
again. And 10 to which I yearn to travel. I've made a promise to
myself, too, that as time permits, I'll find a way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOND MEMORIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Oregon coast. I hope I never erase the image of a spectacular
sunset over the Pacific Ocean from a balcony at the Channel House
Inn in Depoe Bay.
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington, D.C. As a 16-year-old, I rode the train _ I even
remember its name, the Crescent _ from Bay St. Louis, Miss., to
Washington, and spent a week touring every landmark. I've returned
many times, but there was always another purpose, always a reason
to hurry. I covet the luxury of lingering again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Estes Park, Colo. When the toughest decision involves whether
to spy for wildlife in Rocky Mountain National Park, take an
idyllic stroll amid wondrous scenery or languish in a rocking chair
on the patio of your private cabin beside a babbling brook, you
know you're in God's country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kauai, Hawaii. The Garden Island's beauty and tranquility
first captivated me 20 years ago, and witnessing the destruction
inflicted by Hurricane Iniki in this decade brought tears. Now,
Kauai is recovered.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York City. There was a time I never imagined I'd write
those words. I've been to the Big Apple maybe 50 times and _ hush,
don't tell the tourism bureau _ dreaded every visit. But I
recognize now that my frustration occurred largely because the New
York I knew revolved around ballparks and arenas and reporting
deadlines. While I treasure my evenings spent in ``The House That
Ruth Built,'' there was precious little time to soak in countless
other enticements. I'm primed to play Joe Tourist on Broadway, at
the Metropolitan Museum of Art, at the Statue of Liberty. Hmmm,
wonder when the Yankees are playing. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Big Sur, Calif. All factors considered _ the setting,
accommodations, cuisine and service _ the Post Ranch Inn is my idea
of Hotel Heaven. I couldn't afford it the first time I visited; I
can't afford it now. But when I win the lottery ...
</P>
<P>
   _ South Bend, Ind. I'm not Catholic. I'm not even a Notre Dame
fan. But nothing invigorates me _ or makes me feel young again if
only for an instant _ more than a genuine college atmosphere. Spend
an autumn Saturday afternoon here, and you'll never forget the
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco. Anyone who has been there understands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seaside, Fla. Not because of ``The Truman Show.'' I've yet to
see the movie. But what a picture-perfect village! Perhaps Seaside
is artificial, perhaps not. My brief forays haven't uncovered its
real personality. I figure I may need a month there to find out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alaska. Sorry I can't be more definitive. From Ketchikan to
Fairbanks _ with ample time to get reacquainted with Denali
National Park _ this state is filled with wonders. Besides, what
better excuse to take a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A WISH LIST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Vermont. A country inn. Autumn leaves. Whistling wind. A
fireplace. Especially if Larry, Darryl and Darryl stop by.
</P>
<P>
   _ Minnesota's lakes. I've spent many happy days in Minneapolis,
but haven't ventured into the countryside. Friends say this land of
a thousand lakes is marvelous. And it's long past time I learned to
fish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yellowstone National Park. I know, shame on me. In truth, I
did visit as a child. The sight of that 25-foot bear _ or was it 50
feet? _ picking at the garbage outside our cabin still torments me.
I'm ready for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cooperstown, N.Y. I've seen about 3,000 major-league baseball
games. I'm on the Hall of Fame selection committee. And yet I've
never visited the sport's shrine. This is a beautiful part of the
country, too. When pitcher Nolan Ryan is inducted ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Cape Cod, Mass. But only if I can stay in the clapboard house
of my dreams beside the ocean. Maybe for three months. Just long
enough to finish the mystery novel swirling about in my head.
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington state wine region. I figure I owe it to myself to
trace the roots of some of my favorite beverages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Williamsburg, Va. I've yet to meet a person who wasn't touched
by a visit here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blue Ridge Parkway. I never imagined I would enjoy a leisurely
drive along the Natchez Trace Parkway as much as I did last year.
This looms as the perfect follow-up. All-American Road honors don't
come by chance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Augusta, Ga. But only in early April. As a sportswriter, I
covered Olympics, Super Bowls, World Series and other major
championships, but one regret is never seeing the Masters. Wonder
if Tiger Woods needs a caddy.
</P>
<P>
   _ St. John. Yes, I know, it's in the Caribbean. The Virgin
Islands. The U.S. Virgin Islands. I've watched in dismay as
overzealous natives tugging at my shirtsleeves and begging for
quarters spoiled the fun on neighboring St. Thomas. I'm told St.
John is unspoiled and romantic. I figure it's my duty to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts merely scratch the surface. But this is, after
all, America. And no surface is grander.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
