<HEADLINE>
WHISTLE-BLOWER WINS CASE AGAINST FEDERAL LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S. Occupational Safety and Health
Administration has upheld a federal worker's claim that his
employers unfairly retaliated against him for reporting safety
violations at a nuclear weapons laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Lappa, a 19-year employee of the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory who reported the safety violations in the
plutonium laboratory, deserves $15,000 in compensatory damages,
OSHA regional administrator Frank Strasheim ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Strasheim's two-page ruling also ordered Lawrence Livermore
officials to pay Lappa's legal and other costs, and to expunge
``negative references'' from his personnel files dating from June
1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is ``a hands-down, 100 percent victory,'' Lappa's
lawyer, Tom Carpenter of the Government Accountability Project's
office in Seattle. He noted that federal law prohibits officials at
nuclear weapons facilities from retaliating against whistle-blowers
who report wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly found in David's favor and ordered the laboratory
to remedy the violation,'' Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have not decided whether to appeal the OSHA ruling,
Lawrence Livermore spokesman David Schwoegler said. The laboratory,
a part of the Department of Energy, is located in Livermore, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Schwoegler acknowledged that safety violations had occurred in
the plutonium building. But they never threatened public safety, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA issued the ruling June 29 in the form of a letter from
Strasheim to lab director Bruce Tarter. The Accountability Project
announced the ruling last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1997, while serving on an internal committee
investigating the plutonium lab, Lappa accused the employees of
deliberately allowing the violations. Lappa refused to sign the lab
committee's report on the grounds that it did not adequately
discuss deliberate safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   He accused employees of deliberately allowing excess amounts of
plutonium to concentrate into small spaces. The condition is
technically known as ``overmass.'' He claimed the employees
violated the rules in order to meet work schedules.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, excessive concentration of plutonium could trigger a
``criticality event,'' causing a fire or, at worst, a small nuclear
blast.
</P>
<P>
   Schwoegler said even a small nuclear blast ``was technically
impossible under the conditions that existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwoegler said lab officials have responded to the violations
by launching an intensive training program for employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take plutonium handling very seriously,'' Schwoegler said.
Plutonium is the prime fissionable component in most nuclear
weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1649EDT &QL; 
