<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANCIENT-SHOES-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOES THAT WALKED THE EARTH 8,000 YEARS AGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the longest chapters in the history of fashion has
emerged from an unlikely hiding place _ a cave overlooking the
Missouri River in Calloway County, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   From an ancient garbage dump in the cave, archeologists have
retrieved a number of discarded shoes that range in age from 800 to
8,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes include sandals and slip-ons in a variety of styles.
Their design follows no particular pattern from century to century.
``Things came in style, went out of style, like what happens
today,'' said Michael J. O'Brien, an archeologist at the University
of Missouri who has studied the shoes. His findings are published
in the current issue of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the shoes are woven from the leaves of a yucca-like
plant known as rattlesnake master because it is supposed to be an
antidote to snake venom. The two youngest items in the collection,
however, are moccasins made of deerskin.
</P>
<P>
   Though these materials are perishable, the shoes survived
because of the dry and constant conditions in the cave, known as
the Arnold Research Cave.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes were excavated many years ago but dated only recently.
Previous methods of carbon-based dating required that a large
sample of the material be analyzed. O'Brien was unwilling to cut
large pieces from the shoes and decided to wait for a better dating
method to turn up.
</P>
<P>
   Because of renewed interest in the Shroud of Turin, a cloth said
by its devotees to be the original winding sheet that bound the
body of Jesus, scientists at the University of Arizona developed a
carbon-based dating method that required only a few threads of the
original material, the maximum that church authorities would allow
to be taken.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien and a colleague who is a textile expert, Jenna Kuttruff
of Louisiana State University, had the shoes sent off to be dated
by the new method. The footwear turned out to be much older than
they had expected and to cover a much larger expanse of time.
Sagebrush bark shoes found in Oregon are even older, dating back
9,000 years, but the Arnold Research Cave shoes include the oldest
ones found east of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kuttruff said she planned to grow some rattlesnake master in
order to weave some shoes for herself. It was probably a day's work
to make a pair of such shoes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arnold Research Cave was first inhabited about 11,000 years
ago. For most of its occupancy, its inhabitants seem to have been
hunters and gatherers, according to the evidence of the many animal
bones found there. There are signs that at the end of the
occupancy, about 1,000 years ago, the cave dwellers had started to
grow squash.
</P>
<P>
   Besides shoes, the only other fabric found in the cave came from
bags, including one with a squarish shape and a braided top.
</P>
<P>
   Could the inhabitants have worn just shoes and shoulder bags?
``I think not,'' Dr. Kuttruff said. Clothes may be absent from the
remains, she said, because their fabrics were more likely to be
reused until they wore out, whereas shoes were more likely to be
abandoned. And, some of the fabrics worn by American Indians,
including feathers and rabbit fur, are very perishable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Missouri cave collection contains only odd shoes, no pairs.
There are left shoes, right shoes and shoes that fit either foot.
Many show signs of wear at the heel or toe, just like modern shoes.
Some have been repaired, and one has scorch marks suggesting that
its wearer got too close to a fire. Several are padded with the
contemporary equivalent of today's foot pads _ wads of grass.
</P>
<P>
   There is something special in the relationship between people
and their shoes. No other item of clothing must mold itself more
closely to the wearer, or can punish so agonizingly if it fails to
fit. Perhaps shoes were the first item of clothing that had to be
acquired when human beings first learned to walk upright.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, however, noted that the foot grows calluses to protect
itself, enabling people to cross rugged terrain _ although shoes
are useful against frostbite.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,300-year-old ice man retrieved in 1994 from the Italian
Alps was wearing shoes of calfskin, much repaired and stuffed with
grasses for insulation. European settlers noted that the American
Indian tribes they met wore leather shoes, Dr. Kuttruff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2309 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BLACK-REGIMENT     07-06 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BLACK-REGIMENT-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CIVIL WAR REGIMENT RESTORED TO GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 12)  
 (JT)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a young civil-rights worker in Mississippi
during the 1960s, Frank Smith Jr. developed an interest in the
little-known story of the black soldiers who fought for the Union
during the Civil War. As a City Councilman in recent years in
Washington's Shaw neighborhood _ named after Robert Gould Shaw, the
white commander of a black Civil War regiment, portrayed in the
1989 movie ``Glory'' _ Smith has pushed to bring that slice of
history to broader public attention.
</P>
<P>
   Out of his efforts has arisen the African-American Civil War
Memorial, which will be formally unveiled in the heart of the Shaw
district, about 20 blocks north of downtown Washington, on
Saturday, July 18.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is near the intersection of Vermont Avenue and U
Street, N.W., outside the U Street Metro station. Using the same
basic concept as the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, it features a
bronze statue of black soldiers in front of three low semicircular
granite walls covered with stainless-steel plaques listing 208,943
names _ all of the black soldiers who served in the war between the
states plus the 7,000 white officers they served under. The
pie-shaped site, about a block long, was designed by Paul Devrouax
and the landscape architect Edward Dunson; the sculpture, called
``Spirit of Freedom,'' is by Ed Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   The project will eventually include a heritage center, adjacent
to the memorial in the Masonic Temple Lodge on U Street. It is
intended to complement the memorial with historical displays and
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the $2.5 million project, Smith took advantage of the
memorial's site outside the Metro stop. With the help of other
local officials, including Eleanor Holmes Norton, the District of
Columbia's representative in Congress, he persuaded the District
and the U.S. Transportation Department each to provide $1 million.
The remainder came from foundations and private donations.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing to build the memorial, Smith said he was partly
inspired by ``Glory,'' which told the story of the 54th
Massachusetts Regiment. Saturday's unveiling will come on the 135th
anniversary of the regiment's doomed assault on Fort Wagner, S.C.,
when most of the regiment was wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   The 54th was only one of 166 regiments raised for the United
States Colored Troops, as they were officially known. Indeed, Smith
said, a significant proportion of all able-bodied black males ended
up fighting for the Union.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their sacrifice in the cause of the Union and ending
slavery, the black soldiers and sailors won little public
recognition after the war. The African-American Civil War Memorial
Freedom Foundation, set up by Smith to build the memorial, cites an
incident immediately following the Confederacy's surrender at
Appomattox, when 200,000 Union soldiers _ but not one of the black
regiments _ were invited to a victory march down Pennsylvania
Avenue in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it a grave oversight in American history that very
little is known about the heroic contribution of these brave
soldiers in ending slavery and keeping this country united under
one flag,'' Smith said. ``This is an effort to build a focal point
here in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   The unveiling will be preceded by several days of related
events. On Wednesday, the African-American Civil War Memorial
Freedom Foundation will be host to a symposium and reception for
descendants of United States Colored Troops and Sailors at the
Hyatt Regency on Capitol Hill, 400 New Jersey Ave., N.W.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16 at 8:30 a.m. there will be a memorial service at
Arlington National Cemetery, and at 5 p.m. at Capitol Hill there
will be a commemorative program titled ``Their Time Has Finally
Come'' celebrating the troops.
</P>
<P>
   A symposium about the abolitionist movement and the Civil War,
with John Hope Franklin, chairman of the Presidential Commission on
Race, among others, will be held July 17 at 10 a.m. at Howard
University's Blackburn Center (2400 Sixth Street, N.W.). At 2 p.m.
the National Park Service, which will operate the memorial, will
hold a ceremony at Ford's Theater (511 10th St., N.W.) to thank the
volunteers who helped create the data base with the names of all
the black soldiers who served in the Civil War. Seating is limited
for some events. For information, call (202) 667-2667 or toll-free
(888) 648-8728. More information about the memorial is available on
the Web at www.afroamcivilwarmemorial.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
