<HEADLINE>
THE WRITE DIET?  
 KIDS AND SMOKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.C.)   (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If barbecues are your dieting downfall, take a notebook along
with the potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   Self-monitoring _ systematically recording your every bite _ has
long been established as a useful technique in weight loss. To find
out how effective it is, two researchers decided to test it in the
toughest time of the year, the year-end holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the July issue of the journal Health Psychology,
Raymond Baker of OSF-St. Francis Medical Center in Peoria, Ill.,
and Daniel S. Kirschenbaum of the Center for Behavioral Medicine in
Chicago reported following 38 subjects _ mostly women in a
long-term behavioral program for treatment of obesity _ through 10
weeks that included Thanksgiving to New Year's feasts.
</P>
<P>
   Before the study period, the participants had lost an average of
21 pounds over 50 weeks. After that, things went downhill for
almost everybody: Three-quarters of the dieters gained weight
during holiday weeks. The only exceptions were the 25 percent who
were identified as the most rigorous self-monitors, those keeping
track of just about every crumb, who actually lost additional
weight at holiday time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take nearly perfect self-monitoring to buffer the
effects of certain high-risk situational challenges,'' the authors
wrote. _ JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
<P>
   Kids and Smoking
</P>
<P>
   Every day as many as 3,000 youngsters begin smoking, with the
average teen smoker picking up the habit at age 14.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics like these have proved alarming to researchers who,
writing in an upcoming issue of the journal Health Education and
Behavior, called for anti-smoking programs to begin ``at least as
early as primary grades and to target the influence of parental
smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Christine Jackson and her colleagues at the University of
North Carolina, Chapel Hill, looked at smoking in 401 students
while they were in fifth, sixth and seventh grades. More than half
had tried smoking by seventh grade, the researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with children who never smoked, those who did were more
likely to have a parent who smoked, have best friends who smoked,
believe cigarettes were easily available, and doubt that their
parents monitored their smoking or would punish them for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interventions need to focus as much on countering the
influence of parent smoking as on countering the influence of peer
smoking,'' Dr. Jackson said. _ LINDA VILLAROSA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
