<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Yorker delivers on poet Dickey
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the New Yorker ($3), a fascinating excerpt from Christopher
Dickey's upcoming memoir, ``Summer of Deliverance,'' eloquently
describes the troubled relationship with his famous father, James
Dickey, and their eventual reconciliation. The poet promoted
himself as a two-fisted intellectual who excelled in sports, combat
and literature. In reality, his son writes, he was a weaver of
lies, an alcoholic and a tyrant. The turning point in the family's
life was the summer that ``Deliverance'' was filmed in North
Georgia, says Dickey, now a Newsweek foreign correspondent. ``And
after that nothing good was the same.'' Dickey recounts the tension
on the set between his father and the actors. In the end, it was a
battle of egos between Dickey and Burt Reynolds, and Reynolds won.
Dickey was asked to stay off the set.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENTIAL ADMIRER: So much for sexual harassment. In a
Mirabella ($3) essay, a former Time correspondent confesses that
she was ``quite willing to let myself be ravished'' by President
Clinton after an encounter on Air Force One. Nina Burleigh
describes her experience during a game of hearts with Clinton and
aide Bruce Lindsey last year. ``The president's foot lightly, and
presumably accidentally, brushed mine once under the table,''
Burleigh writes. ``His hand touched my wrist while he was dealing
the cards. When I got up and shook his hand at the end of the game,
his eyes wandered over to my bike-wrecked, naked legs. And slowly
it dawned on me as I walked away: He found me attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh, now a New York free-lance journalist, said she did not
feel harassed or pressured by the president. ``If he had asked me
to continue the game of hearts back in his room at the Jasper
Holiday Inn, I would have been happy to go there and see what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG ONE: This summer, World War II is coming to a theater
near you. The big movie, of course, is Steven Spielberg's ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' but six other films are also in the works,
including Terrence Malick's version of James Jones' ``The Thin Red
Line.'' In its cover package, ``War Is Hell,'' Newsweek ($2.95)
explores how ``Saving Private Ryan'' will change the image of World
War II commonly depicted in John Wayne patriotic films. In
Spielberg's film, as in war, says one of the men who fought at
Normandy, ``good guys get killed, too.''
</P>
<P>
   UNHEALTHY PLANS: Managed care was once touted as the cure-all
for the nation's health insurance ills. Now, says Time ($2.95),
after five years of horror stories and the refusal of some HMOs to
pay for Viagra, Americans are pressuring politicians to come up
with new plans. Time correspondent Karen Tumulty looks at proposals
by Democrats and Republicans. In a more lighthearted article, Time
visits America's secret capitals, including Dalton, Ga. (the carpet
capital) and Albertville, Ala. (the fire hydrant capital).
</P>
<P>
   UNSPORTSMANLIKE CONDUCT: Greedy players, fickle owners and the
increased commercialization of sports are taking its toll on fan
loyalty, says U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95). No one expects
die-hard fans to quit watching, but there are signs of a shifting
allegiance away from big-money sports. Minor-league baseball, for
example, has the highest attendance levels since the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILER TRASH: Have you noticed that movie trailers seem to show
more about the film than you want to know? Well, it's not your
imagination. Entertainment Weekly ($2.95) explains why audiences
are becoming increasingly irate at previews that reveal too many
surprises. ``Everything is quick cut a la MTV,'' says trailer maker
Gary Kanew. ``Because of this rat-a-tat-tat formula, trailers show
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
