<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A brief look at the life of Roy Rogers
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roy Rogers
</P>
<P>
   1911 - 1998
</P>
<P>
   -- Born: Leonard Slye, Nov. 5, 1911 in Cincinnati. Legend has it
his home stood where second base at Riverfront Stadium now rests.
</P>
<P>
   -- Early days: After the Depression forced the family to move to
California in 1930, Rogers worked as a peach picker and a truck
driver. In the mid-30's, he formed the cowboy singing group the
Pioneer Trio, renamed Sons of the Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Music: The trio, fronted by Rogers' distinctive yodel,
scored hits with ``Tumbling Tumbleweeds'' and ``Cool Water.'' He is
generally considered one of America's best cowboy singers, but his
musical career quickly became overshadowed by his film and
television work.
</P>
<P>
   -- His movies: Rogers made more than 30 films, including
``Tumbling Tumbleweeds'' (1935), ``Under Western Stars'' (1936),
``King of the Cowboys'' (1943), ``The Cowboy and Senorita'' (1944),
``The Yellow Rose of Texas'' (1944), ``My Pal Trigger'' (1946)
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Rogers married his film co-star, Dale Evans in 1947,
fourteen months after his first wife, Arlene, died. They had nine
children _ two by Roy's previous marriage, one by Dale's, one of
their own, four by adoption and one by foster parenthood. Their
only biological child, Robin, was born retarded and died shortly
before her second birthday in 1952. Dale wrote a book about the
experience, called ``Angel Unaware,'' which became a bestseller.
Rogers is survived by Evans, five children, 15 grandchildren and 33
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   -- What About Trigger?: Rogers's horse Trigger appeared in all
his films and TV shows. Trigger died in 1965, at age 33. He was
stuffed and remained a fixture at Rogers' museum in Apple Valley.
</P>
<P>
   -- Honors: In 1988, Rogers was elected to the Country Music Hall
of Fame. In 1991, he participated in the recording of ``Tribute,''
a CD honoring his music from stars such as Clint Black, Lorrie
Morgan and Riders in the Sky.
</P>
<P>
   -- Other news services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
