<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROY-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History of Roy Rogers on big and small screens
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROY ROGERS ON TV ...
</P>
<P>
   American Movie Classics is saddling up two Roy Rogers programs
for Wednesday night. The documentary ``Roy Rogers: King of the
Cowboys'' will air at 6:30 p.m. EDT followed at 7:30 p.m. EDT by
the 1950 film ``Trail of Robin Hood,'' in which Rogers and other
Western stars (including Rex Allen and Monte Hale) help Jack Holt
(playing himself) get Christmas trees to needy families in time for
the holidays. Both shows repeat starting at 8 p.m. EDT Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ... AND HIS SMALL-SCREEN LEGACY
</P>
<P>
   From 1951-57, Rogers produced 101 episodes of ``The Roy Rogers
Show,'' an early forerunner of TV's great Western era. The show
featured Rogers and Dale Evans as themselves in modern-day Western
stories. Rogers, of course, rode Trigger and Evans rode Buttermilk.
Their sidekick Pat Brady drove a Jeep they called Nellybelle. And,
not to be forgotten, was Bullet, a fast-on-his-paws German
shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and Evans later starred in ``The Roy Rogers and Dale
Evans Show'' (1962-63), a variety series also featuring the Sons of
the Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable early TV Westerns in the Rogers' vein included:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Lone Ranger'' (1949-57): Clayton Moore and John Hart
played the masked hero, created for radio in 1933, with the late
Jay Silverheels as sidekick Tonto. Their theme song: Rossini's
``William Tell Overture.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Hopalong Cassidy'' (1949-51): William Boyd, who died in
1972, played the black-clad good guy (he rode a white horse) and
edited some of his 66 movies into 30- and 60-minute TV shows. Some
52 new episodes were made for the final TV season.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Gene Autry Show'' (1950-56): Autry is the great movie
cowboy who rode his horse Champion on this series for six years,
singing ``Back in the Saddle Again'' and seeing pal Pat Buttram get
into silly situations.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Annie Oakley'' (1953-56): Autrey discovered Gail Davis and
cast her as the sharp-shooting rancher. She did most of her own
stunt work, including hanging off her running horse Target while
demonstrating her shooting prowress. Davis died in 1997 of cancer
in California.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Sky King'' (1953-54): Kirby Grant played Schuyler J. King,
owner of the Flying Crown Ranch and pilot of a twin Cessna dubbed
The Songbird. He used to plane to rescue the meek and seek out
evildoers.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Adventures of Rin Tin Tin'' (1954-59). Call him the
testosterone Lassie. On this show, the German shepherd Rin Tin Tin
and his human pal Rusty (Lee Aaker), were sole survivors of an
Indian raid taken in by the 101st Cavalry. Rusty was commissioned a
corporal; Rin Tin Tin was made a private.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, ``Gunsmoke'' debuted. And the Western lore introduced
to the small screen by Rogers, Evans and others really took off.
Over the next four years, audiences were introduced to ``The Life
and Legend of Wyatt Earp'' with Hugh O'Brien, ``Zane Grey Theater''
with Dick Powell, ``Wagon Train,'' ``Have Gun Will Travel,''
``Cheyenne,'' ``Rawhide,'' ``Sugarfoot,'' ``Maverick,'' ``The
Restless Gun,'' ``The Texan,'' ``Wanted: Dead or Alive,'' ``Tales
of Wells Fargo'' and, of course, ``Bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
