A2345 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRUGGLING-ACTORS-HNS     07-06 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRUGGLING-ACTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THE WORLD'S A STAGE AND ALL THE MEN AND WOMEN MERELY ...
BOOKSTORE CLERKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In New York City, they wait tables.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, they tend bar.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, N.Y., they sell books.
</P>
<P>
   If you get a monologue along with your purchase at a bookstore
here, don't be alarmed. Alas, poor Yorick, it's just another
aspiring actor.
</P>
<P>
   And if these thespians-turned-booksellers in their 20s and 30s
happen to be developing a character during play rehearsals, beware.
It could be a three-act ordeal at the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to be an actress if you're trying to sell a book you
don't really like,'' said Kathleen Carey, manager of the children's
section, Little Book House, at Book House. ``Being able to play a
role went a long way when I was just starting out at Waldenbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey, who has a degree in elementary education, recently
shuttled to New York City to perform an experimental theater work,
``Bruised Reeds,'' in a SoHo art gallery. She's been squeezing in
roles since graduating from high school. At the same time, she
started working in bookstores and the two jobs have complemented
each other ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all flirt with the idea of trying to make a living
as an actor, but I'm happy working in a bookstore and juggling work
with acting,'' Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sense of shared lunacy among the hard-core theater
corps at bookstores. They've been there, done that. They run lines
together. Discuss insights into characters. Trade bad puns. Traffic
in insider analogies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this typical theater person's sense of humor,'' said
David M. Girard, formerly of Lauriat's Bookstore by way of Barnes &AMP;
Noble and B. Dalton. ``Our jokes are very dry and cynical, a little
sick. We like trying out characters. Then another person works off
that. It's like an improv scene. It keeps things interesting at
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Girard now works at Dorian Group Ltd., a classical recording
company in nearby Troy. He said he missed the theatricality of
Lauriat's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I switch dialects a lot at work,'' said Amanda Ennis,
assistant manager of Lauriat's Bookstore at Crossgates Mall here.
``I was raised in Alabama, so I do a Southern drawl. But I also let
the `Fargo' lady from Minnesota dialect slip out. It's a
minute-to-minute situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ennis' boss lends an empathetic ear. That's because he's
infected with the stage bug, too. ``If someone gets cast, we help
each other out and switch schedules so that person can rehearse,''
said Patrick White, manager at Lauriat's, where the staff has done
play readings and Ennis' window displays look like stage sets.
</P>
<P>
   While it may not register as a dramatic development, this bit of
regional quirkiness can be seen in the ever-shifting schedules of
bookstore employees, especially at actor-saturated Lauriat's. They
need time off to audition, to rehearse and to perform. Those not
currently in a production pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   White was drawn to the stage from the written word. He was
inspired to begin acting as a high school student after reading the
plays of Tennessee Williams and Sam Shepard. He's been a voracious
reader of drama ever since. His job feeds the habit. ``Working in a
bookstore is like being a kid in a candy shop for me,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Albany Civic Theater production of Terrence McNally's
``Love! Valour! Compassion!'' could have passed as a bookseller's
convention.
</P>
<P>
   In the Albany Civic Theater show, Girard was cast as Bobby
Brahms, the lover of dancer Gregory Mitchell, played by White.
Carey was assistant director for the show and acted as a stand-in
for a performance after White broke his toe and was detained at a
hospital emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you could say the Albany theater community is very
small,'' said John A. Nickles, another member of the Lauriat's
staff and an actor in local community theater. ``The nice thing is
that our manager (White) is a theater person and he'll work around
our rehearsal schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickles started acting as a youngster. He pursued playwriting at
Purdue University, where he got a master's degree in English
literature and wrote a play called ``Judas'' that was given a
showcase performance at the Albany Civic Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles' mall job produced an unexpected collaboration. Warren
Raboy, who works at a deli in Crossgates, has written a play,
``Scenes From A Wicked World,'' that Nickles hopes to direct in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   White, who graduated from the American Academy of Dramatic Arts
in New York City, spent several years acting in showcase
productions and auditioning in the city for stage and film parts.
His success was modest, although recurring roles in soap operas
earned him union memberships in Screen Actors Guild and Actor's
Equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I avoided waiting tables in New York as long as I could,''
White said. He worked as an overnight bellhop at the
Waldorf-Astoria for a time. Eventually, White took a job as a
waiter at Hamburger Harry's near Times Square and was in the
company of many theater people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, you wait tables for the tips because rents are
high and you can't support yourself in a job like a bookstore,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   When he moved back to Albany in 1994, White waited tables before
he took his father's advice and applied for a bookstore job. He
joined the staff of Lauriat's, eventually getting promoted to
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked reading and hanging out in bookstores and my
dad said it would be a perfect job for me,'' White said. ``The
bookstore is a great place to research characters. You're always
around people, too, so you can pick up on a lot of stuff you can
use in roles.''
</P>
<P>
   All the world's a stage. It just happens to be arranged in
narrow aisles that are lined with shelves of books for these
dramatis personae.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEZELL-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEZELL-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mutual fund titans on way to help investors
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mutual fund pioneer John C. Bogle Sr. will headline an
investment and personal finance conference Sept. 26 sponsored by
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle, founder of the Vanguard Group and originator of the first
index mutual fund, will join other money managers and experts to
show 5,000 members of the public how to improve their financial and
investing skills.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper and the Georgia Society of the Institute of
Certified Financial Planners are partners in providing a full day
of hands-on seminars on topics ranging from family finances to
advanced investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This conference will give our readers dynamic and robust
presentations of trends and opportunities from very savvy people
who are almost never available to the public in one place, at one
time,'' said Roger Kintzel, publisher of the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Other headliners include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Don Phillips, the 36-year-old chief executive officer and
president of Morningstar. The Chicago firm is a major tracker and
analyst of mutual funds. Phillips has made a name with his
outspoken criticism of funds that skimp on customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Phillips and Bogle were ranked among the four most
powerful people in the mutual fund industry by Smart Money, a
personal finance magazine published by The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nationally syndicated columnist Kathy Kristof, author of
``Kathy Kristof's Complete Book of Dollars and Sense,'' a personal
finance guidebook. She writes frequently for these and other
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Donald Ratajczak, the nationally respected economist and
forecaster who heads the Economic Forecasting Center at Georgia
State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique opportunity for Atlantans to learn from some
of the best minds, both locally and nationally,'' said Michael
Smith, the president of the Georgia group of certified financial
planners.
</P>
<P>
   The conference will be held in the Georgia World Congress
Center. Attendance will be limited to 5,000. You can register for
the conference by calling 404-653-0419. For more information, visit
our Web site: http://www.accessatlanta
</P>
<P>
   .com/business/money&AMP;more/
</P>
<P>
   Seminars will cover 20 topics dealing with investment tools and
strategies, retirement and family-oriented financial topics.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of investment strategies, for example, there will be
sessions on building sturdy portfolios in an uncertain market,
tax-efficient investing, global investing and techniques for
picking hometown investments.
</P>
<P>
   Also, an exhibit hall will be staffed by financial service
companies and by nonprofit organizations. An ``Ask the Adviser''
room, where attendees can discuss individual issues with certified
financial planners, also will be open all day.
</P>
<P>
