A2372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEY-ASIA-COX     07-06 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-ASIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Asia is still muddying the waters when it comes to profit
outlook
 &HT;    By Tom Walke--
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asia's worsening economic situation guarantees U.S. corporate
profit growth will suffer well into the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, will affect Wall Street, since earnings growth is
regarded by analysts as the prime mover of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the impact isn't clear, but First Call, which
tracks analysts' earnings estimates, counts a ``greater than
normal'' number of advance announcements from companies on
second-quarter expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A greater percentage'' than usual have been negative,
according to First Call Research Director Charles ``Chuck'' Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's worrisome, coupled as it is with an acceleration of
downward revisions in the last couple of weeks of the quarter,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to tell if the April-June quarter will be a
carbon copy of the first. But Hill said the consensus forecast is
for year-over-year growth of 3.2 percent. The first quarter showed
a 3.8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, first-quarter profit growth has been as high as
15.1 percent (1997) and 23.3 percent (1995).
</P>
<P>
   The drop in demand from Asian markets and the restraining
effects of a surging dollar are already hurting companies with
operations there, as well as exporters who count on foreign buyers
for a large share of sales and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a record-setting increase in inventory buildup of
$105.7 billion in the robust first quarter put more pressure on
companies.
</P>
<P>
   They must now find a way to sell all those goods stored in
warehouses and on store shelves in the face of falling import
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's problems have created a two-tier market for U.S.
investors: those stocks directly affected, and those immune to
Asia's problems or that benefit from side effects such as low
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Cases in point include Coca-Cola, IBM and Hewlett-Packard.
Merrill Lynch analysts trimmed second-quarter estimates for the
beverage company and its ratings for the two computer firms because
of the changes in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Other casualties that will suffer from Asian market weakness
include producers of heavy machinery, and of basic materials such
as chemicals, paper, steel and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, banks and insurance companies generally have
benefited from the decline of U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions are some money center banks such as Citicorp and
Chase Manhattan, big creditors to Asian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners include retailers, benefiting from cheaper Asian
products, and travel-related businesses such as luxury hotels and
airlines. Home building also has been stimulated by falling
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Oil is a ``wild card,'' according to Hill. It could go either
way depending on the price, which fell to as low as $12 a barrel in
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At those prices, oil companies cut back, drying up business for
the drillers and equipment providers, and crimping earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
