<SLUG> BC-MONEY-ECONOMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORLDS APART: Japan will have big hand in shaping Wall Street's
fortunes
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Asian miracle'' is suddenly less miraculous, if not
downright threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Japan _ in recession _ and the rest of Asia _ in some cases in
worse shape _ will have a big say in how much the U.S. economy
weakens in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   That means Asia will help decide which way the U.S. stock market
goes: up, down or sideways.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is expected to be affected, too, but not as seriously. In
fact, some analysts believe European growth will surpass that of
the United States by as early as the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say right now that Europe is the ld Ratajczak.
</P>
<P>
   That represents products not sold, sales not gained and profits
not earned by U.S. manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   At Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, economist David A. Wyss said he
expects Asia ``will subtract about half a percentage point from
real GDP (gross domestic product) growth in both 1998 and 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strong headwind for the U.S. economy to fight
against, but it is not insurmountable,'' Wyss added.
</P>
<P>
   The full impact from Asia won't be known for months, but some
early returns are in:
</P>
<P>
   -- Orders for big-ticket U.S.-made durable goods dropped 2.6
percent in May, the biggest decline in five months, as the Asian
crisis hit home.
</P>
<P>
   -- The strong dollar hurts exports and stimulates imports,
fueling record U.S. trade deficits of $13.2 billion in March and
$14.5 billion in April.
</P>
<P>
   -- U.S. exports declined 3 percent in the first quarter as
shipments to the Pacific Rim weakened, the biggest drop since the
third quarter of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   -- On the plus side, the deflationary impact of Asian imports is
thought by some analysts to have been a factor in the Federal
Reserve's decision not to raise short-term interest rates this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's role in the Far East explains why tns have put constant
pressure on that nation's government to reform its economy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said the falling yen
reflects economic weakness ``and can only be remedied by restoring
economic strength to Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say the solution to Japan's problems won't be easy
or quick. The Japanese economy shrank 1.3 percent in the first
quarter, putting it in its second recession in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Japan took several steps. The government announced a
plan to deal with its banking crisis, and officials indicated they
are ready to use a permanent tax cut to help boost the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Still uncertain, even assuming Asia's full cooperation in rescue
efforts, is how much the financial crisis will hurt the U.S.
economy. Most analysts look for it to restrain, but not stop the
U.S. economy in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started this year at a spectacular (5.4 percent) growth
rate in the first quarter. We may be lucky to be growing at 1
percent or 1.5 per16.8 percent and the Nasdaq composite 20.7
percent _ increases some forecasters thought would represent gains
for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those gains were in the first quarter. Since then,
the major stock averages have experienced corrections as modest as
5 percent for the Dow Jones industrial average and Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 averages, but 10 percent to 12 percent for technology
and smaller stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The corrections occurred because the market could not withstand
a renewed barrage of earnings warnings and bad news from Asia,
accompanied by a sharp rise in the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, most mainstream analysts regard the chances of a bear
market _ a decline of 20 percent _ as minimal at best.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario for most analysts is another correction
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Robbins, market strategist for Robinson-Humphrey in
Atlanta, assigns ``a below average probability'' to a correction of
as much as 11 percent. He continues to stand by his mid-April
forecast that the Dow has a 50-50 chance of reaching 9,875 this
year. That would be 923 points above the Dow's second-quarter
close.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs strategist Abby Joseph Cohen, one of the most
accurate forecasters of recent years, has reiterated her bullish
outlook based on the strength of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   She said there are important forces that offset the effects of
Asian's problems on the United States. For the most part, she
contends weak growth in Asia is a ``moderate negative'' for U.S.
economic growth and for corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   And analysts at Standard &AMP; Poor's look for ``a flat second half,
then modest gains in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forecast is that the S&AMP;P 500 index will end 1998 around
the current level, then work its way modestly higher in the first
half of next year,'' said Vice President Arnold Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
