<SLUG> BC-BENNETT-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WB LAUNCHING `INVASION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Harve Bennett, who has Hollywood staying power to
rival anyone, began his show-business career in radio on a show
called ``Quiz Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the 66-year-old Emmy-Award-winning producer sees it, his
latest _ and most cutting-edge project _ is a return to his roots.
</P>
<P>
   As executive producer of ``Invasion America,'' a prime-time
animated/computer-generated drama, which premieres tonight on the
WB (KTLA, Channel 5), Bennett said that he feels as if he were back
in radio days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a radio director, but I grew up and radio
disappeared,'' Bennett said. ``In animation, it's like you are a
radio writer and director. It's an illustrated version of a radio
show.''
</P>
<P>
   The first season, or book as Bennett calls it, will air at 8
tonight as a 90-minute presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The series follows the life of teen-ager David Carter,
half-human, half from another planet (Tyrus) and his growth to
manhood while trying to protect himself from goons from his
father's planet. His father, Cale, meanwhile is trying to win back
his power on Tyrus.
</P>
<P>
   The finale will take Carter to his life's first plateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of Book One,'' he said, ``he will have climbed a
foothill, but still has a mountain to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The WB network is extremely high on the series, which is also
executive-produced by Steven Spielberg. And, Bennett feels that the
story can sustain a five-year arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has to be a stopping point,'' he said. ``Sooner
or later you have to beat the bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who has been a network programmer and producer and
feature-film writer (most notably the ``Star Trek'' movies), has
found new ways to do audience research.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his two ``uncredited creative consultants,''
(daughters Callie, 13, and Samantha, 9), he has found a wealth of
information from fans on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered a world I was illiterate to, and that's the
cyberworld,'' he said. ``I have been running around to fully
understand that universe. When we did the `Star Trek' movies
throughout the '80s, there was a network called fanzines. They were
the same people, just doing it slower and through the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that he is enjoying his latest project, and in
addition to executive producer, he has compiled another impressive
title for his resume _ voice-over artist. Bennett supplies the
voice for the president of the United States in ``Invasion
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to cross the hall from the control room to the
recording studio to be with my fellow actors,'' he said. ``The
first time I did, they all sang `Hail to the Chief,' which makes a
man feel pretty tall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
