 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, July 7, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE _ Inspired by strong Mac sales, a superfast chip designed
in Austin, and the imminent arrival of the iMac, Macintosh users
are euphoric heading into Macworld expo in New York. It is a
complete turnaround from one year ago, when Apple was bogged down
in losses, saddled with mediocre products and distracted by a nasty
fight with Power Computing. While they have given up hope that the
Mac will ever have more than a fraction of the personal computer
marketplace, they're convinced it's still the best system.
``Mercedes Benz would be very happy with 4 percent of the
automobile business,'' said Mac evangelist Bob Levitus. (Mahoney,
Austin American-Statesman). ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SAKS _ Follow on the sale of Saks Fifth Avenue to Profits, which
is moving its headquarters to Birmingham. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-TECH _ ATLANTA _Lycos stock splits. We ask analysts why
internet stocks continue to split and go up. The wild ride of
Internet stocks. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SMALLBUSINESS _ ATLANTA _ Southern small businesses_
considered the leader among small businesses _ had the slowest
growth rate in the nation during the first quarter. One reason: the
tight labor market, according to a national quarterly survey.
(Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-NASCAR _ ATLANTA _ The Coca-Cola Co. is hoping NASCAR fans
and Coca-Cola memorabilia collectors will race out to snap up a
series of nine Coke-Cola classic bottles featuring some of the
sport's most popular drivers. (Gramig, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Also moving in (s) Sports category.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-CARGO _ ATLANTA _ Hartsfield International Airport
officials are set to hand over the keys this month to the first
tenants in a major $34.5 million expansion of international air
cargo operations. Gateway Cargo Service will occupy the first of
three 104,000-square-foot buildings on the south side of the
airport. Two more buildings are under construction, and a fourth
will be bid out later. When the total project is completed, it will
add more than 400,000 square feet, doubling the current space of
352,000 square feet now operating on the north side of the runways.
(Hendricks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-CHIEF _ ATLANTA _ Benjamin DeCosta has put completion of
a master plan for Hartsfield International Airport's future and
keeping current construction projects on track among his top
priorities. DeCosta, who assumed his duties June 29, told his
senior staff those items were atop his list. He was the general
manager of Newark International Airport in New Jersey before
replacing Angela Gittens, whom Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell did not
reappoint. (Hendricks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-AIRPORT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ On a cool, windy day in late
October, a FedEx jumbo jet took off into the overcast Austin sky en
route to Japan, carrying only two human passengers. The rest of the
plane housed 80,000 pounds of food belonging to its exotic cargo _
156 Texas-bred ostriches. It marked the first time live cargo left
from an Austin airport, and the only time a local airport has had
enough room to land the McDonnell Douglas MD-11, one of FedEx's
largest airplanes. ``We could never have done anything like that at
(Robert Mueller Municipal Airport),'' said Jamy Kazanoff,
spokeswoman for Austin-Bergstrom International Airport. ``There
wouldn't have been enough room for the plane.'' (Cocks, Austin
American-Statesman.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVEACTION-CASE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As head of
Houston-based Vinson &AMP; Elkins, the law firm representing the
University of Texas without charge in the Hopwood affirmative
action case, Harry Reasoner, 58, is not proud of the lack of
diversity on his own legal staff. Without affirmative action in
higher education, he fears it would be even worse. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ The good economy has stirred up our consumer
hormones to the point where millions of Americans are falling for
the come-on lines from bankers who promise cheap mortgages and big
credit lines. Instead of rationally evaluating the offers, we swoon
and surrender to lenders. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(k, f) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ A guide you to places where you can get the
software you need to chat on the Internet, sites that offer
instruction on how to use chat, and even offer a brief course in
chat etiquette. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ ATLANTA _ Sweet and single Teresa is really a
burly truck driver named David from Montana, married, with tattoos
and kids. And the wealthy neurosurgeon you met last night is a
lonely schoolteacher in Vermont. Let's chat about chat and the
people you meet there. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
