<P>
   FLA-NASCAR _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Drivers knew it as ``Palm
Beach.'' And when Smiling Lee Petty, Fireball Roberts and Banjo
Mathews raced there in the early days of NASCAR, they were driving
what many racing pioneers still refer to as ``the fastest dirt oval
in the South.'' Built in 1949, the old Palm Beach Fairgrounds
Speedway off Southern Boulevard was a half-mile racetrack of
crushed shellrock mixed with oil to prevent dust clouds. There were
other dirt tracks around the country. But ``Palm Beach'' was
special because, unlike most tracks, the oval's two curves banked
at 18 degrees. We take a look back at the good old days of NASCAR
in Florida. (Capozzi, Palm Beach Post.) MOVED.
</P>
