<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUMMER WRAP PROVES ITS VERSATILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (fb)  
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Consider the pareo. Wrapped around the chest, it is a
swimsuit cover-up. Tied around the waist, a sarong skirt. Tossed
over the shoulders, a shawl.
</P>
<P>
   Lord &AMP; Taylor has pareos by A. Brod in animal-print cotton ($20)
and self-embroidered rayon ($18), and by Page D. in cotton batik
($25).
</P>
<P>
   Chanel's signature-print pareos are $190, and Cejon's mixed
patterns are $24, all at Bloomingdale's. Alecca Carrano's
iridescent black striped silk is $124 at Barneys New York. Henri
Bendel's cotton pareos come in a variety of prints ($48). Nieman
Marcus has Balinese prints by Cool Change ($58) and a burnout
velvet by Gottex ($155).
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue has stretch nylon pareos in stripes or color
blocks by Baja Blue ($54), red silk with a flowered border by
Plenty ($75), cotton florals by Manuel Canovas ($180), multicolored
zigzags by Missoni ($185) and Hawaiian prints from Oscar by Oscar
de la Renta ($98). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2412 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT     07-06 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE WATCH: GENE ORACLE HAS ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The book of evolution, as recorded in the genomes of living
things, is not a comprehensive history of life on earth, complete
with names, dates and places. It is more like an oracle, providing
rich but cryptic answers if asked the right questions.
</P>
<P>
   You can ask, for example, ``Where did malaria originate?'' By
analyzing the DNA of a particular gene in the various species of
malaria parasites that infect apes and monkeys, Ananias Escalante
and colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta have been able to draw up the gene's family tree.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the tree, marking the earliest ancestor of today's
malarial parasites, shows that malaria originated among the monkeys
of Africa, placing its center of origin in that continent and not
in Southeast Asia as is widely believed. The finding is reported in
the current issue of the Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   A second, more adventurous question, is ``Where is the site of
the original human population expansion from which the rest of the
globe was peopled?'' Two biologists at the University of Oxford in
England, David Reich and David Goldstein, posed that question and
got the same answer as to the first: Africa. By analyzing genetic
variations in aboriginal populations from throughout the world,
they found the marks of an early, pre-agricultural expansion only
among Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing their luck, they then asked, ``When did this population
expansion occur?'' But the great Delphic DNA oracle, perhaps
fearing the next question would be something quite impossible, like
``And just why were we expelled from the Garden of Eden?''
retreated into gnomic vagueness: Between 49,000 and 640,000 years
ago, it told them. Thanks, we knew that already.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists do not give up so easily. The next question put
to the oracle, also reported in the current Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences, came at the Garden of Eden problem
from another direction. ``When did sex begin?'' was the poser from
a group led by Anna-Karin Fridolfsson of the Swedish University of
Agricultural Sciences in Uppsala, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of the question is that the sex chromosomes, denoted X
and Y in humans and other mammals, are thought originally to have
been just like one another except that the Y carried the
sex-determining gene and the X did not. At first the two
chromosomes formed a twin-like pair, as do the other pairs of
chromosomes, which are known as autosomes (human cells have 22
pairs of autosomes and the X and Y pair). But in the course of
evolution the X and Y stopped exchanging genetic material with each
other, as the autosomes do at each generation, and thus followed
such different evolutionary paths that they can now be told apart
just by their shapes, an X and a Y.
</P>
<P>
   The sex mechanism in mammals is known to be extremely ancient _
so ancient, some biologists believed, that it might even have
predated the split between mammals and birds. If so, the sex
chromosomes of birds and of mammals should share a common
chromosomal ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Fridolfsson's team has found evidence that the sex chromosomes
of birds are indeed descended from an ancestral pair of autosomes.
But the pair was different from the autosomal pair that led to the
X and Y chromosomes in mammals. The evolution of the sex
chromosomes has thus occurred independently in birds and in
mammals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INCA-GOLD-HNS &LR;      07-06 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCA-GOLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ADVENTURERS HEAD TO ECUADOR IN SEARCH OF INCAN TREASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ David Ultan and Adam Ballachey were both 29,
struggling to launch careers as documentary filmmakers and working
as house painters when they got The Call.
</P>
<P>
   It was an invitation for the young Berkeley residents to drop
their paintbrushes and take up their cameras, to become cinematic
explorers in a quest that would bring 21st-century technology to
bear on 15th-century Ecuadorean legend, that would cross the paths
of Silicon Valley scientists with long-dead Incan kings and
treasure hunters looking for gold.
</P>
<P>
   Lots and lots of gold.
</P>
<P>
   The call was from Bill Kurtis, a television journalist and host
of ``The New Explorers'' on the A&AMP;E network. He had seen their
pitch for an hour-long segment called ``Search for Inca Gold,'' and
he liked it. So much so that he gave the green light without having
seen any footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bill called, we were both on ladders with paintbrushes in
our hands,'' Ultan says. ``I had to lie: `Yes, I'm in my office.
...' We about fell off our ladders.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ballachey, it was the boost they needed: ``Suddenly, after
shopping this project around all this time, we were credentialed,
we were in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, after two reconnaissance trips to
Ecuador and floppy discs full of research, the two friends and
their scientific team are about to culminate work on the project,
one that will, at the very least, break ground in archaeology. And
one that could, given the best possible outcome, catapult them into
the history books.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, they will go to Quito and fly over the
Andes, carrying recently declassified ground-penetrating radar
developed by Dr. Roger Vickers at Stanford Research Institute. They
will attempt to find traces of the vanished Incan people _ and
their enormous caches of gold. It's a mystery that has lured
treasure hunters and archaeologists to the region, called the
Llanganati, for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-square-mile area of the Andes north of Quito is an
unforgiving land, where heavy rain, earthquakes and jagged cliffs
have claimed the lives of countless treasure hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone agrees on this: An Inca general familiar with this
area took this army and these tons of gold and disappeared,'' says
Ballachey. ``The question is: Did he go into these mountains, and
where did he hide the gold? The radar will be looking for evidence
of Inca infrastructure or pathways that could have led these 15,000
people into this remote area. If they find it, it will raise the
level of discussion to a whole new level.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultan is anxious to get started. ``At the very least, it's a
good yarn and a great adventure,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ballachey and Ultan, friends since childhood, fellow
anthropology majors at California State University, are a study in
opposites. Ballachey, son of a judge, is sharp-witted. Fair and
mercurial, Ballachey is both photographer and journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Ultan is the son of an artist, a painter himself and the protege
of ``60 Minutes'' producer Lowell Bergman. Dark and stocky, the
good-natured, bilingual Ultan is the team's negotiator and
organizer; he's nailed the delicate meetings required by the
Ecuadorean government before the expedition could be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the task of convincing a developing country in a cold
war with its neighbors,'' Ballachey says wryly, ``that we should be
able to bring what amounts to a spy plane into the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultan nods: ``We had more than 100 meetings, with everyone from
the secretary of state on. They never asked us for a bribe, did
everything by the book. We now have a stack of papers giving us
permission. We just had to let them come along and promise to give
them our findings.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: any gold, or any evidence of the gold. This is not
a mission that will make millionaires of the team, they insist.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can imagine, I get calls from treasure hunters all the
time who want to use my technology,'' says Vickers, 60, whose title
is director of the Geoscience and Engineering Center at the
Stanford Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have no interest in that. David was the first person to
approach me about a project where I could see that the treasure was
not the most important thing to them, but the archaeology.''
</P>
<P>
   The only wealth that might be generated from the trip will come
from demand for Ballachey and Ultan's documentary, should it record
some historic discovery; or from future treasure hunts, should this
one prove successful. (The team is forming a company for other
explorations.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1532, the Spanish conquistadors, led by Francisco Pizarro, a
54-year-old illiterate soldier, entered the lowlands of northern
Peru near Cajamarca, capital of the Incan empire. The empire was at
its peak, covering more than 2,500 miles and boasting beautiful
cities and temples filled with golden artifacts. The Incas, who
called themselves Children of the Sun, were led by the young
Emperor Atahualpa.
</P>
<P>
   With visions of gold, but only 183 soldiers compared with tens
of thousands in the Incan army, Pizarro knew treachery was the only
way to conquer. He asked to meet with Atahualpa, who welcomed him
with pomp and ceremony. Atahualpa was surprised by a vicious attack
on his unarmed attendants _ Pizarro himself pulled the emperor from
his gilded throne _ and thousands of Incas were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Now a captive, Atahualpa offered as ransom storage rooms full of
gold and silver, and sent word to neighboring cities to collect the
booty. But after four months, with the ransom only partly
collected, the Spaniards murdered Atahualpa. When word of
Atahualpa's death reached the ends of the empire, the stream of
gold headed for Cajamarca was halted.
</P>
<P>
   One of Atahualpa's generals, named Ruminahui, fled into the
mountains north of Quito with 15,000 soldiers, taking along what
historical accounts estimate as ``70,000 man-loads'' of gold.
Although the pursuing Spaniards tortured and burned alive many
Incas, the gold's location was never revealed.
</P>
<P>
   And what's 70,000 man-loads of gold worth today? Ballachey and
Ultan look uncomfortable. ``That's between two and four, uh ...
billion dollars,'' Ultan stammers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think these mountains are full of treasure
hunters?'' Ballachey says. ``A lot of people think that's worth
dying for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
