<HEADER>
A2420 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WHITE-PROFILE-2T     07-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WHITE-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RURAL RACONTEUR BAILEY WHITE SPINS HER FIRST NOVEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CAROL RUST 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Meeting Bailey White is like having a tall glass of
iced tea with a favorite cousin.
</P>
<P>
   You feel like as if you already know the author and National
Public Radio commentator. You know her mama and the reason her mama
kept a 1958 Porsche speedster parked on the front porch during the
last years of her life. You've heard her read a story about her
cousin Mandon, who lives in Virginia and dreams of one day
reuniting the family's collection of Chippendale chairs scattered
among relatives in a half-dozen states.
</P>
<P>
   You recall the day Uncle Jimbuddy cut off his finger and
couldn't find it in time for doctors to reattach it to his hand,
although it turned up later in a bucket of iced oysters that had
been sitting in his wood shop.
</P>
<P>
   You feel like you've walked the rows of White's garden and know
she planted 20 rose bushes two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   You even know her polite dog, that, at least in the story,
refused to sleep in White's bed the night his owner saw ``Silence
of the Lambs'' because he'd been raised to stay off the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The unpretentious writer and schoolteacher-on-sabbatical who
lives in southwest Georgia expresses herself in such a personal,
homespun manner that readers cannot help but feel a pea-shelling
camaraderie with her.
</P>
<P>
   They're not surprised to learn that the wiry slip of a woman
travels on book tours with just two outfits so she doesn't have to
trust her luggage to the airlines, and that she's a bit intimidated
by snooty waiters in ritzy restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   She's been reading her short essays about everyday Southern life
on NPR since 1991 in a crackly voice that conjures up an image of a
little old lady in a sunbonnet instead of a petite woman who has
bobbed brown hair and wears bluejeans and a long-sleeved,
white-cotton shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel, ``Quite a Year for Plums'' (Knopf, $22), was
released in June. Her two previous books, ``Mama Makes Up Her
Mind'' (Vintage Books, $11) and ``Sleeping at the Starlite Motel''
(Vintage, $12), were anthologies of previously aired essays.
</P>
<P>
   She pulled together the first book, published in 1993, at the
suggestion of a friend. ``Sleeping at the Starlite Motel'' came two
years later.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of writing a novel was somewhat wilting, she said,
mostly because ``I had signed a contract to do the book and I was
worried that I'd said I'd do something I couldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first book I ever wrote,'' she said. ``The other
books were just things I got out of my file folders. Everything had
already been read over the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Her darkly funny slice of Southern life knits together an odd
collection of humanity that features Roger, a plant pathologist who
lectures farmers about tomato spotted wilt virus, thrips and other
enemies of the peanut; and the local women, mostly schoolteachers,
who are preoccupied with his well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled into this group is a devoted collector of electric
desk fans; a maniacal printer committed to preserving near-extinct
typefaces; a wildlife artist who nearly smothers in the
black-and-white feathers of a pair of Dominique hens she's
painting; and a gawky ornithologist tracking the red cockaded
woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   Della, the wildlife artist, finds that the only way to alleviate
her ``painter's block'' with the Dominique hens is by discarding
household items at the dump. Most are accompanied by a personal
note, such as: ``This fan works but it makes a little clicking
sound and will not oscillate.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger is intrigued with the notes and the way Della carefully
places items at the dump, just in case someone else can use them.
Their odd romance is perfect for such odd characters.
</P>
<P>
   Is White happy with the reviews for ``Quite a Year for Plums?''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know. She doesn't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not reading any reviews, and I don't want you to tell
me,'' she said flatly. ``I told my friends, `Don't tell me if
they're good, and don't tell me if they're bad.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't make me write anything better or do anything
different,'' she said. ``I'd rather just not know.''
</P>
<P>
   White smiles tentatively and ducks her head in embarrassment
when presented with praise. She's used to readers feeling like they
know her, and she appreciates the attention, but she doesn't really
know what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   She likes to focus her attention on others. Everywhere she goes,
she is listening to what people have to say. She rarely uses a tape
recorder and takes notes only occasionally, when she wants to be
sure to get something right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a notebook with me that I scribble some things down on
sometimes, like in the bathroom at the airport the other day,'' she
said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Two women had just seen the movie ``The Horse Whisperer'' and
were talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them said, `I start to cry before the crying part even
gets there because I know it's coming.' I knew that feeling so
well. If you see a horse running in slow motion, you just feel the
tears well up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although her trademark is documenting Southern eccentricities,
she doesn't believe they're unique to the South. ``I do not agree
that craziness runs in Southern families,'' she said. ``Families
everywhere are that way. I don't know why the South has gotten a
reputation for being that way unless it's that Southern writers
write about it and Northern writers don't as much. I see the same
thing everywhere I go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White's characters orbit around themes of horticulture and
wildlife. She chose the first because that's what she happened to
be doing when she started the book two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I was interested in myself,'' she said. ``Right
about the time I started writing this book, I stopped teaching
school, which meant I had a whole lot more time. So I mainly did
two things: wrote this book and gardened. It was easy and natural
to write about people and gardens because I'm familiar with those
subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   Research topics for the book included desk fans, peanut
diseases, camellias and birds _ ``I nearly wore out a Peterson's
Guide,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   White, who has taught mostly first-graders for 21 years in
public schools, has a large garden instead of a family, she said.
She calls herself a ``spinster,'' shrugging off the word's negative
connotations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spinster is an unmarried woman, and that's what I am, an
unmarried woman,'' said White, who is in her mid-40s. ``I happen to
like the term.''
</P>
<P>
   First grade is her favorite, she said. ``That's before students
become so wise. And they go so far in that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In second and third grade, they know how to read _ they just
learn to read a little bit better.
</P>
<P>
   ``In first grade, they come in and don't even know the alphabet,
and when they leave they can read. That's why it's an exciting
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also kind of frightening, because it's a huge
responsibility, and I've always worried they won't be ready for
second grade.''
</P>
<P>
   She's taken a two-year leave from teaching to write her book,
but wants to get back into the classroom. It has provided material
for her essays more than once.
</P>
<P>
   In the essay ``Maritime Disasters from Mama Makes Up Her Mind,''
for example, she writes about different methods of teaching
reading. During the years, she has taught her students more old sea
chanteys than stories about Dick and Jane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a man overboard or a good sinking ship, and I can
teach a half-witted gorilla to read,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she feels guilty about using the Titanic as source
material, as if she were desecrating a grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I remind myself that in my whole career the Titanic and I
will teach over a thousand children how to read _ close to the
number of people who lost their lives on that black night. Surely,
for the sake of literacy, the spirits of those poor souls will
forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   White's mother frequently starred in her comic essays and never
minded, White said. ``I think she considered herself a fictional
character.''
</P>
<P>
   She used bits and pieces of people she knows in real life to
fashion the characters in ``Quite a Year for Plums.''
</P>
<P>
   For Louise, who's convinced she's communicating with spacemen,
she used the personality trait of insanity contained in a single
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anyone specifically like that, but I've known
people who were crazy in spots. In most situations, they appear to
be totally normal people, but in one particularly area, they're
just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   White would like to write another novel, she said, but she wants
to keep it a secret until it's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great luxury would be to write a book without having a
contract,'' she said. ``The other scary thing is that they pay you
in advance, and you haven't done this work yet, and it paralyzed me
with worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `What if I get some crippling disease and can't
write the book? I had to pay income tax on (the advance), and I
thought, `if I pay the income tax, I can't even give them the money
back,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her doubts, she continues writing because the
inspiration keeps presenting itself. She is keeping a log of her
book tour so the two-month jaunt won't be an anonymous whirlwind of
places and names when it's over in late July, she said. She keeps
from becoming exhausted by staying organized and limiting her
appearances. She rarely grants interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Fans feel as if they know her because of the personal subjects
she writes about, she said. She knows how they feel because she
does it herself, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that way about people I listen to on the radio, when I
meet them, I'm always surprised that they don't look right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mind is such a strange thing. You can hear somebody and,
just without thinking, get ideas about how tall they are and what
color their hair is.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when you meet them, they're short and dumpy and bald.
They're all wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   She can't recall the particular essay she first read after going
to the office of the NPR affiliate in Tallahassee, Fla., but she
does remember the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous,'' she said. ``The technician was real sweet,
and he said, `Don't worry, I can get anybody to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wrong, but it was encouraging.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
