<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and strong thunderstorms will erupt Tuesday
near a warm front from the Great Lakes to the upper Ohio Valley as
sultry breezes from the south are lifted by a vigorous jet stream
disturbance. Winds changing speed and direction with height will
impart rotation to some of the thunderstorms, heightening the risk
for damaging winds, hail and isolated tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Spotty thunderstorms will also develop from Minnesota through
lower Michigan, while ample clouds and afternoon showers develop in
the interior Northeast. Farther south, a few thunderstorms will
tease the parched Florida peninsula, though no widespread rainfall
is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will explode to the south of a cold front
in the torrid conditions of the late afternoon from Missouri to
central Kansas. Sweltering heat will prevail over the lower
Mississippi Valley and southern Plains as sprawling high pressure
aloft supports bright sunshine. High temperatures will reach 100
degrees in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   High humidity levels associated with the nascent summer monsoon
season will encourage showers and thunderstorms in the Southwest.
Drenching rains will occur in some areas, raising the risk for
flooding in low-lying areas. Meanwhile, high pressure will provide
partial sunshine and seasonable temperatures to the northern
Rockies. The West Coast will be mainly sunny and warm with the
exception of morning coastal clouds and lonely afternoon
thunderstorms over the mountains of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: the Monsoon Begins
</P>
<P>
   The monsoon officially began in southeast Arizona on Friday, and
true to form, a thunderstorm rolled over Tucson on Sunday dumping
nearly an inch of rain. A monsoon is simply a seasonal wind. In the
deserts of the Southwest, the wind blows from the southeast during
the summer monsoon, directing humid air from the Gulfs of Mexico
and California. Technically, climatologists in Arizona define the
start of the summer monsoon as the first 24-hour period when the
dewpoint remains above 55 degrees. The average start of the monsoon
is July 5, and it usually concludes around September 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
