<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT ARRIVAL AT KENNEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 12)  
 (JT)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The all-new Terminal 1 at Kennedy International Airport has
already garnered critics' praise for its architecture. The people
who built this international terminal for the owner airlines, Air
France, Japan Airlines, Lufthansa and Korean Air, and those who
work in it, seem in love with it. They stop frequently to point to
views through certain windows, particular pieces of design, giant
new gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   The departure area is dazzling in its light and loftiness. The
interior balcony offers good people-watching. But how will the
terminal work for passengers at the airport where, as the signs all
over Kennedy say, ``America Greets the World''?
</P>
<P>
   It is usually true that departing passengers see the best of an
international airport, according to William Bodouva, the principal
architect. Arrivals enter on the lower level _ the equivalent of
steerage.
</P>
<P>
   Since the departure level is dictated by the height of the
airplane door, Bodouva said, getting people aboard without climbing
is possible only from an upper level. The baggage removed from the
plane is handled at ground level and so, then, are its owners.
</P>
<P>
   At Terminal 1 passengers still arrive downstairs in the
so-called sterile security-sealed lower corridor. But they do not
set foot on U.S. soil in a windowless wooden-walled corridor with
no light at the end, as has been the case at the old International
Arrivals Building.
</P>
<P>
   The inbound concourse leading to the Immigration and Customs
area at Terminal 1 has a moving sidewalk along one wall, and
windows along the other with a view over runways and the aircraft
parking area. The ceiling is undeniably low _ ``the sterile
corridor is always a squeeze, but we softened it a little,''
Bodouva said, referring to electric-light coves cut into the
ceiling. Then, when passengers turn left toward Immigration
control, the overhead opens into a vast skylight.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration area has 34 booths leading to four luggage
carousels and space for a fifth. This area and the Customs staff at
five channels are designed to handle 2,200 passengers an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidental with the opening of Terminal 1 came a new amenity
for all three New York area airports: On June 15, the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey hired a staff of 235 customer
service agents, suited them up in red jackets or vests and sent
them to the airports, turning a formerly seasonal program into a
year-round project. Five of Kennedy's 82 permanent multi-lingual
greeters are assigned to Terminal 1 seven days a week on two
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew E. Kreek Jr., Kennedy's manager of landside services,
said these helpers had instructions to approach people in
difficulty and to be sure they found what they needed. They are
available to direct people to taxi lines and provide guidance on
fares. Seventy percent of the customer service people speak a
second language, commanding among them at least 30 languages,
including French, German and Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   All terminals at Kennedy but Tower Air's are being redesignated
by numbers. Terminal 1, built on 36 acres formerly used by Eastern
Airlines, is the first major terminal an arriving driver meets
coming off the Van Wyck Expressway; the last ones on the outbound
swing, used by American, are now identified as Terminals 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   Terminal 1 cost $445 million, according to Dieter Bergt, the
chief operating officer. Ground was broken in September 1995,
although the old Eastern terminal was not yet completely
demolished. Terminal 4, formerly International Arrivals, has lost
some of its tenants and is also being renovated.
</P>
<P>
   Terminal 1 has 96 check-in positions and 32 ticketing positions
on four islands on the departure level. Each island bears the logo
of one of the four tenant-owner lines. But Bergt said the computer
systems allowed any airline to use any counter in case passenger
lines backed up. Air Afrique, Olympic Airways, Royal Air Maroc,
Singapore Airlines and Turkish Airlines are moving into the new
terminal, too, and others may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Shore, the project manager for the Terminal 1 Group
Association, particularly admires the features that give the new
terminal the ability to serve several functions in tight quarters.
She pointed to the design of 6 of the 11 plane-entrance ramps,
called lofting bridges. Departing travelers and arriving
international passengers may not be mixed, and this usually
requires using separate gates, or walled-off walkways in the
interior. The adjustable end of the lofting bridges is on the
terminal side: the plane can stay in the same place during its
turnaround, and at the terminal end the gate is lowered to
disembark passengers at the lower level or raised for embarkation
at the upper level.
</P>
<P>
   On a humbler scale, the ATM situation at Terminal 1 is not
optimal. There are to be only two cash machines, according to Kevin
Corrigan, a spokesman for Airport Aviation Professionals. This
organization served as adviser on concessions to the Terminal 1
Group Association. Both machines are provided by American Express.
The one that was working June 22 charges users $1.50 a pop to get
at their bank accounts. It is inside the security barrier, near the
American Express money exchange counters and, naturally, the
stores. The other is on the ground floor, outside the security
barrier, where arriving passengers are met.
</P>
<P>
   The terminal has lots of phones, including a good number on
pedestals in the meet-and-greet area, where they are so often
needed. The wall installations on the departure level, oddly, are
all at wheelchair height, which makes the keypads hard to read for
those who dial standing up.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,000-square-foot duty-free shop, where one may not enter
without a boarding pass, is run by International Shoppes. Because
Terminal 1 is used only by international passengers, this store is
able to hand the merchandise, including cigarettes and liquor, to
the buyers right in the store. The shop emphasizes California
wines, and has a good selection of American whiskies.
</P>
<P>
   Also beyond the barrier are two small bars and snack bars,
Brooklyn Brewery Pub and Napa Valley Wine Bar, and some stores. One
that has just opened is an H.Stern jeweler..
</P>
<P>
   First- and business-class passengers can use spiffy private
lounges run by the individual airlines. The walls facing out are
almost entirely glass, with varying views, some distant, some of
waiting planes. There are plenty of easy chairs, tables with phones
and modem outlets, phone booths or communications carrels, meeting
rooms, and a couple of windowless rooms with recliners for naps.
The host airlines, which serve countries where smoking is
apparently unabated, have encapsulated smoking rooms within their
lounges. V.I.P. rooms, useful for those who crave privacy (rock
stars perhaps), are available on request.
</P>
<P>
   Three lounges have showers: Air France, Lufthansa and Korean
Air. Attendants will fetch towels from well-stocked linen closets.
Japan Airlines has no shower, but provides high-tech bidets with
adjustable water temperature. In addition to the usual coffee,
snacks and alcoholic drinks, Lufthansa and Air France will serve
dinner at tables in the lounge to first-class passengers taking
late-evening flights who want to go straight to sleep once on
board.
</P>
<P>
   Air France has transferred its children's playroom, with a
wooden plane suitable for small children to climb aboard, a fabric
tunnel for floor crawling and other games, from its former terminal
to the corridor near its lounge. To reach the lounge or the
playroom, passengers must go through security. The children's area
may be used by Air France economy passengers, too.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a play area for children of all departing
passengers out in the open on the departure level. It was still
being put together on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   The food court area on the balcony outside the security barrier
is also still being finished, although a self-service counter was
open, selling coffee and small sandwiches and cakes. It's hard to
discern what it will be like when the Greenwich Village Bistro and
the like are up and running, but in spacious unfinished condition,
the balcony revived two vivid memories. One was the Golden Door at
Newark Airport in the 1950s, a restaurant whose name reminded
visitors that America was the place of opportunity, and whose
splendid food endowed the portal itself with romance. Another
feeling, from an even earlier era, overcame me as I stood at the
balcony edge looking over the concourse: the sense one got in the
old Pennsylvania Station _ of purposeful people under a high, high
roof going someplace exciting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
