<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL COACH SEES MATCH WITH DUTCH AS `LION EATING LION'  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France _ There was a time when the Dutch were called
the Brazilians of Europe. Their aggressive offense did not help
them against West Germany in the 1974 World Cup final or against
Argentina in the 1978 final, but now comes their chance against the
Brazilians of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch meet the four-time champions here Tuesday night in one
semifinal of a World Cup that has three semifinalists that have
never won the tournament. France and Croatia meet Wednesday night
in St. Denis.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil and the Netherlands go back a ways. Only six teams have
ever won the World Cup in its 14 sessions, and the Netherlands has
often been regarded as the best football power to never win it.
</P>
<P>
   It charmed soccer fans around the world in the '70s with its
concept of Total Football, as originated by Rinus Michels, the
creative Dutch coach. Michels, now 70 years old, was taken to the
hospital here after Saturday's 2-1 victory over Argentina, and was
in stable condition Monday after being diagnosed as having suffered
a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Under Michels, the Dutch came close twice, eliminating Brazil in
1974. Conversely, Brazil eliminated them in the 1994 World Cup in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the teams that have presented the best football in the
Cup so far,'' said Mario Zagallo, the coach of Brazil, who was also
the head coach in 1974. ``This will be lion eating lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil came into the tournament as the favorite, and have really
not done anything wrong, except to lose to Norway in a first-round
game after they had already won their group.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams come into the semifinal with personnel shortages.
Cafu, the powerful Brazilian defender, received his second yellow
card of the second round during Brazil's quarterfinal victory
against Denmark for delaying play.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement will be Ze Carlos, who is popular among his
teammates for his imitations of various forms of wildlife. Zagallo
said, ``I told Ze Carlos that since he can imitate dogs, parrots
and owls, now he'll imitate Cafu.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch are more severely short-handed, because Arthur Numan,
a starting defender, was tossed out of Saturday's victory as a
result of his second yellow card of the game. The man who would
have replaced him, Winston Bogarde, broke his right fibula during
normal running drills on Sunday. Guus Hiddink, the coach, has not
said who will start in their place. Several other major Dutch
players, Clarence Seedorf and Aaron Winter, missed the Argentina
game because of injuries but are likely to be available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch still like to attack. Their midfielders can drill long
and accurate passes, like the one that Frank DeBoer lofted to
Dennis Bergkamp, who volleyed the winning goal late against
Argentina. Philip Cocu, listed as a midfielder, has been known to
enter striker territory.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Davids, fiery as his nickname, ``Pit Bull,'' knocked off
Yugoslavia in the 93d minute, just before the end of regulation
time, and has been covering the gaps in the defense as his
teammates rush forward.
</P>
<P>
   None of the previous Dutch success may matter much against
Brazil, which has more firepower than any other nation. Ronaldo,
who came into this tournament as the hugely-promoted star of an
equipment company, with billboards everywhere, has been fine.
However, Rivaldo has been the silky offensive star so far, and
Cesar Sampaio has roamed far up front to score important goals, and
Roberto Carlos, the mobile midfielder, has often been the best
player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian goalkeepers are often seen as mere accessories, and
Taffarel fits into that pattern. The Dutch goalkeeper, the lanky
Edwin Van Der Sar, may have given his team a new personality as
fiery as the bright orange outfits its supporters wear.
</P>
<P>
   They call him the ``Ice Rabbit'' back home, but Van Der Sar's
aggressive posture helped the Dutch into the semifinals. He says he
prepares for big games by staring out the window, but Van Der Sar
was far from reflective last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dutch down a man because of an expulsion, Ariel Ortega
of Argentina took a flop near the goal, trying to draw the
official's sympathy. Totally out of character, Van Der Sar came
running up to berate Ortega, who leaped up and head-butted him,
earning a red-card expulsion. With the teams even again, DeBoer and
Bergkamp collaborated on their gorgeous goal. It was a throwback to
Total Football, and it united the Brazilians of two continents for
another round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
