<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-NYT &LR;      07-06 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: GOING ASTRAY ON HIGH-PROFILE REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How could it have happened? How could experienced producers at a
major network have turned out such a mishmash of a report on so
sensitive a subject, little short of the charge of an American war
crime?
</P>
<P>
   After an independent investigation found that last month's CNN
report of U.S. use of lethal nerve gas in Laos in 1970 was not
supported by the evidence, retractions and apologies were properly
made by CNN and by its partner, Time magazine, which may be having
second thoughts about the virtues of journalistic synergy.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN producers who patched together the now exposed expose
were dismissed; the senior executive producer of the new
news-magazine series ``Newsstand: CNN and Time,'' which had come on
with the usual beating of drums, resigned, and Peter Arnett, a
stellar CNN correspondent, who had done some of the program's
interviewing, was reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   All the blemished parties must hope that the episode will go the
way of other quickly forgotten journalistic embarrassments,
allowing them to get back to business as usual. But in business as
usual can be found the elements that propelled them into folly.
</P>
<P>
   It began in hype. With the introduction of ``Newsstand'' last
month, CNN was striving to distinguish itself from the cable-news
clutter that fills the channels and scatters their ratings. And by
associating itself with Time, CNN was acknowledging that the
credentials of print would add potency to its own so-so reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The new series and its initial program _ ``Valley of Death,'' it
was called, in true pulp spirit _ represented a big Time Warner
commitment, both financially and as a show of cable-news muscle.
The pressures were on, the juices were running, and it is easy to
imagine producers being incited to excesses in the interests of a
smashing debut.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism has never been a hype-free line of work, and
television, with its affinities to show business, lays on the
hoopla with particular zest. By now, the reasonably sophisticated
fan takes the standard news-magazine promises of revelations,
breakthroughs and near-miracles with a resigned skepticism; if the
evening's crime story or health story or scandal tends toward
sensationalism, so what's new?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the ``Newsstand'' producers, their subject was
too hot to be accepted with the usual shrug. American veterans, the
Pentagon and Washington's reputation were involved. But any show of
restraint, any muting of the charges would have weakened the punch
of opening night. What sort of expose would it be, hedged in with
maybes?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in The New York Times over the weekend, the
producers _ April Oliver and her immediate superior, Jack Smith _
said they had pressed for an hour of air time instead of the 18
minutes they were allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists, often compelled to pack too much information into
too few minutes, will sympathize, yet an elementary part of the job
is being fair and accurate whatever the constraints of time. In
defending the 18-minute version, Ms. Oliver suggested that she was
sparing her audience from a confusion overload. That excuse can be
applied to many of the thinly reported documentaries that fill the
tube.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains, particularly in regard to the severely
criticized use of sources: Is this the best they could do after an
eight-month investigation? (That's enough without getting into what
the conservative Bill Kristol called the producers' politically
driven motives, an imputation that makes one wonder about his
motives.)
</P>
<P>
   The lure of the subject, American use of poison gas, was further
stimulated by pictures of the Laos raid. They were grabbers,
lending the semblance of documentary verisimilitude to the report.
Such is the camera's power. The pictures provided the smoky,
somewhat sinister drama that television relishes, but they added
nothing to the assertion that nerve gas had been used or that
defectors had been the targets.
</P>
<P>
   There is no novelty in news-magazine producers' relying on
pictures to bolster stories that are short on substance. How were
they to know that this time out, they would be subject to
line-by-line, frame-by-frame scrutiny?
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the presence of Arnett, a Pulitzer Prize
correspondent who found himself working on a story in which by his
own account he had not been deeply involved. He told Reuters:
``Looking at it in retrospect, maybe I could have asked more
questions about the story than I did. But I came into it very
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Arnett's role or predilection, the notion of hauling in
a star correspondent to add credibility does not defy common
practice. Will this affair do anything to stop news magazines from
using high-profile reporters as display pieces for reports to which
they contribute little but their reassuring presences? Don't count
on it. This is show business, where television's news stars earn
their outsize salaries on the backs of producers. It's a continuing
invitation to irresponsibility.
</P>
<P>
   None of television's bad habits can pardon the producers'
performance in their ``Valley of Death,'' but the scene was set.
Whether the experience will do anything to reduce the hype, the
mindlessly punchy use of pictures, the empty celebration of star
performers to which television news is prone, remains to be seen.
There is no reason for optimism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
