A2486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI07-COX     07-06 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI07-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Diane Lore and Virginia Anderson
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Public health officials have identified another case
of E. coli linked to White Water park, bringing the total number of
children infected with the bacteria to 21.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which involves a Gwinnett County, Ga. child, was the
result of exposure on June 17 at the popular Atlanta area water
park, said Peter Lee, a Georgia Department of Human Resources
spokesman. Lee said he had no information about the age of the
child, who did not require hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cases have been linked to exposure June 11-12,
although public officials are now looking at a second wave of
infections tied to June 17.
</P>
<P>
   No more tests that determine the genetic fingerprints of E. coli
O157:H7 have been completed, although public health officials
expect results by mid- to late-week.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Georgia Division of Public Health has conducted 11
genetic tests and all 11 have been linked to White Water, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also said public health officials were still ``looking at a
couple more cases'' that might be linked to the water park.
</P>
<P>
   Of those children who required hospitalization, a critically ill
4-year-old, who has been hospitalized for two weeks, appears to be
getting better, Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's condition was upgraded from critical to serious
Monday, according to Scottish Rite spokeswoman Kim Lathbury. The
hospital will not release the child's name because of patient
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Another child who also has been hospitalized for two weeks, a
2-year-old girl, remains in critical condition at Scottish Rite.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the last remaining E. coli patient at Egleston
Children's Hospital, a 2-year-old boy, has been upgraded to good
condition, said hospital spokeswoman Julie Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
