<HEADLINE>
JURY SELECTION BEGINS IN CAPITAL MURDER TRIAL OF FORMER AIR FORCE
CADET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ A few blocks from the German restaurants
and refreshing spas that make this central Texas town a summertime
tourist haven, lawyers at the Comal County Courthouse on Monday
began the tedious process of selecting a jury to hear the capital
murder case against a former Air Force Academy cadet.
</P>
<P>
   David Graham, 21, is accused of killing Adrianne Jones, a
16-year-old Mansfield girl, in order to please his jealous fiancee
and atone for having a brief sexual relationship with Jones. But
about 500 potential jurors were told nothing specific about the
case, only that this is a murder trial moved from Fort Worth's
Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   No mention was made of former Naval Academy midshipman Diane
Zamora, Graham's former girlfriend, who earlier this year received
a life sentence for her role in the 1995 killing of Jones.
</P>
<P>
   According to Graham's confession in the case, he invited Jones
to go for a drive Dec. 4, 1995. With Zamora hiding in the trunk,
Graham drove to a remote location where, he said, Zamora struck the
first blow by hitting Jones in the head with a barbell weight.
Jones fled the car and collapsed in a field, but Graham said in his
statement that he followed her and shot her twice with his 9 mm
pistol.
</P>
<P>
   The murder remained unsolved until the couple entered their
respective academies and Zamora confessed the crime to her new
friends at the Naval Academy, who turned her in.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jones had gone out voluntarily with Graham on the night
she was slain, she was kept against her will, resulting in a
kidnapping allegation that allowed prosecutors to obtain the most
serious possible indictment _ capital murder. Yet, at the request
of the victim's family, the state is not seeking the death penalty
for Graham. Life in prison is the only possible punishment if he is
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they had never heard of the widely publicized case,
potential jurors couldn't help but notice Monday that Graham's
trial attracted media attention from around the state and nation.
The three- or four-week trial, which is to begin next week, is
expected to involve the same evidence as Zamora's trial last
February in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, &UR;  &LR; wearing gold-rimmed glasses and a dark suit, sat
silently before potential jurors, flashing an occasional smile
during the day's brief proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In the first phase of the winnowing process, Comal County
residents offered reasons why they should not be interrogated in
detail about potential jury service. That depth of questioning
begins Tuesday, with much of the questioning centered on the
jurors' exposure to media coverage of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Don Leonard, urging them to keep an open mind about
Graham, told panelists he wanted them to ``set aside what you may
have heard'' and prepare to decide his case solely on evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Dan Cogdell acknowledged it would be difficult
to win acquittal for Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime there's a case with a confession and a case where the
co-defendant has been convicted on the front page of every
newspaper in the country, it would be folly not to think it was a
difficult case,'' Cogdell said. ``How difficult, time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County prosecutor Mike Parrish, who successfully
prosecuted Zamora, said the pressure is on him to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more difficult for us because everybody expects
David Graham to be convicted. Everybody knows the evidence against
Diane Zamora,'' Parrish said, referring to the couple's confessions
and the discovery of the murder weapon hidden in Graham's attic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real story here will be if David Graham gets off lighter
than capital murder or gets found not guilty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
