<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: GOOD NEWS FOR `THE LION KING'; NOT QUITE AMAZON.COM;
OPERA TRIPLE BILL; FREE CONCERTS IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: South Africa, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the New Amsterdam Theater near Times Square, not
only does the show (``The Lion King'') go on, but so do six South
Africans in the 52-member cast. The South Africans, including
Tsidii Le Loka, who plays the wise baboon Rafiki, and five members
of the ensemble received a waiver from Actors' Equity to appear in
the cast when the show opened last November. But their waiver was
to expire on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after Disney Theatrical Productions argued that they
provided a unique service, and Equity agreed, the actors may remain
in the New York production indefinitely. Chanting and singing, the
performers speak several African dialects, some difficult to learn;
and under the agreement, the actors are offering master classes to
find performers who could play their roles in the future.
</P>
<P>
   History's Pages
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1476 or early 1477, William Caxton, England's earliest
typographer, printed a book about a group of pilgrims. About 300
years later, the book was bought for 6 pounds (about $10 today but
considerably more then) by the fourth Earl Fitzwilliam's family,
where it has remained ever since. On Wednesday, that first edition
of Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales'' will be auctioned at Christie's
in London, where it is expected to fetch as much as $1.1 million.
Although a dozen copies of the volume survive, this first edition
is the last in private hands.
</P>
<P>
   One Act Operas
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With librettos by A.R. Gurney, Terrence McNally and
Wendy Wasserstein and scores by Michael Torke, Robert Beaser and
Deborah Drattell, three one-act operas have been jointly
commissioned by the New York City Opera, the Glimmerglass Opera and
the ``Great Performances'' series, produced by WNET in New York.
Plans call for the operas to be presented as a triple bill under
the title ``Central Park'' because their unifying element will be
the park. The work, directed by Mark Lamos, will be first seen next
summer at the Glimmerglass Opera, in Cooperstown, N.Y., followed by
six performances at the New York City Opera, when it will be
televised on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Play Times
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cuba Gooding (the actor's father) and the Main
Ingredient begin the eighth year of free Concerts in the Park,
Tuesday night at 7 in Fort Greene Park in Brooklyn. This evening of
soulful style is just the appetizer for a summer of classic soul,
rhythm and blues and Latin music not only in Fort Greene Park on
Tuesdays but also in Sternberg/Lindsay Park in Williamsburg on
Wednesdays and in Von King Park in Bedford-Stuyvesant on Thursdays
through the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the scene shifts to Linden Park in East New York on
Tuesdays and Sunset Park in Greenwood on Wednesdays. Attractions in
the series include the Persuasions, the Delfonics, Clarence
(Gatemouth) Brown and Orquesta Broadway.
</P>
</TEXT>
