<SLUG> BC-TV-AFFLUENZA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFFLUENZA': WELL-INTENTIONED BUT HEAVY HANDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The PBS audience was introduced to the dire syndrome of
``affluenza'' last year in an earnestly intentioned yet lightly
delivered documentary that made a case against greed, surfeit,
waste and related ills. Tuesday night brings a sequel, an earnestly
intentioned, earnestly delivered documentary that is heavy-handed
enough to send viewers rushing to the shopping mall to waste some
money.
</P>
<P>
   One of the program's producers, Vivia Boe, announces that ``in
many ways, the American Revolution was a rebellion against
materialism, and seeking independence from stuff is entirely within
the spirit of Independence Day.'' John De Graaf, another producer
of ``Escape From Affluenza,'' announces that consumers are tired of
trying to keep up with the Joneses. It's the sort of hot air that
ought to be recycled for home heating.
</P>
<P>
   It's a case of high-minded messages being drummed in so
relentlessly, so humorlessly and with such an air of
self-satisfaction that you want to hang the messengers, all of whom
have given up the rat race and are devoting themselves to good
works like helping the needy, buying little and wasting nothing.
Some of them run operations like the Money Masters Program for
youngsters and the New Road Map Foundation for the frugally
inclined and the Northwest Earth Institute, which combats, among
other ailments, stress and ``resource exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, alas, is that virtue alone does not invigorating
television make, unless you are entranced by the pleasures of
composting. So while wishing well the apostles of simple, frugal,
environmentally conscientious living celebrated here, and while
admiring anyone who chooses to read to the blind instead of making
a million dollars on Wall Street, I confess I was relieved by the
hour's end just to get away from these people.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ESCAPE FROM AFFLUENZA'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
