<SLUG> BC-TV-AIRPORT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AIRPORT': IN-DEPTH LOOK AT HEATHROW REVEALS LITTLE OF INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The workings of Heathrow Airport in London must be more
interesting than ``Airport,'' the three-part series that begins
Thursday night on PBS with attention to the doings of the official
airport photographer, the unsuccessful efforts of a couple of
customs officers to catch suspected drug traffickers, the training
sessions for flight attendants and incidental activities.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are excited by the sight of a photographer in pursuit
of Melanie Griffith and Joan Collins speeding through the
corridors, the ordeal of some stranded passengers and the arrival
of Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton, you may find your attention
flagging. Except that nobody is peddling souvenirs, this report is
as stimulating as a made-for-cable infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AIRPORT'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Thursday on PBS
</P>
</TEXT>
