<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINESS-CARDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Almost 10 years later, letters to sick boy keep coming
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nun in New York had six bags of cards hand-made by children,
ready to send to the young boy with an inoperable brain tumor who
wanted to hold the world record for the most get-well cards
received.
</P>
<P>
   But that young, ailing boy has recovered and grown up. He set
the world record _ at 33 million cards _ back in May 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It's been nearly a decade since Craig Shergold, then a
9-year-old boy in England, embarked on the world record campaign
with assistance from Atlanta-based Children's Wish Foundation. And
it's about time that it stopped, foundation officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite as chaotic as the early days, but it's still
the same situation,'' said Christy Chappelear Andrews, public
relations director for the Children's Wish Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Well-meaning cards still stream in. Some are addressed to
``Craig Sherwood,'' ``Craig Sherford'' and other similar names.
Cards also have gone to other organizations, and some people send
business cards, the result of chain letters run amok.
</P>
<P>
   After Shergold was diagnosed with a brain tumor in 1989, the
foundation added Shergold's goal to its list of wishes and helped
him receive 16 million get-well cards in 1990, the first time
Shergold set the world record. It also brought him to the attention
of Virginia billionaire John Kluge, who financed an operation at
the University of Virginia Medical Center to remove most of the
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   When Shergold set the world record for the second time, he and
his family asked that people stop sending the cards. Many still
haven't gotten the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for the cards I wouldn't be here today,''
Shergold said. ``The cards give me so much spiritual upliftment.
They make me so happy. But I just wish it would stop now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now healthy and attending college in England, 19-year-old
Shergold remains the world record holder for the most get-well
cards received. According to the 1993 Guinness Book of Records, the
next closest competitor is Jarrod Booth of Salt Spring Island,
British Columbia, Canada, who collected 205,120 Christmas cards in
February 1990. The Guinness Book of World Records, after updating
the number of cards that continued rolling in, retired the category
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone tried to top that, the post office would go
bananas,'' Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the category was closed, volunteers at the Children's
Wish Foundation stopped counting at 100 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the volunteers' jobs are far from done. They come in twice a
week for six hours at a time, and in a warehouse behind the
foundation's headquarters, they sort through the stacks of mail,
open and divide the cards according to paper quality and send them
to a recycling center.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Wish Foundation is the only organization
authorized by the Shergold family to receive and open the mail, but
cards also keep coming to the Phoenix-based Make a Wish Foundation
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Brain Tumor Foundation for Children, a non-profit
organization based in Georgia, has been fielding telephone calls
from well-wishers checking the address before they send a batch of
greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Allman, the executive director of the Brain Tumor
Foundation for Children, told the nun to send the children's
hand-made cards to local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last month, she has had to tell nearly 20
well-wishers, including the Chicago Bulls, that the chain letter _
which now also circulates as a forwarded e-mail _ is no longer
relevant.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
