<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STINKY-FLOWER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visitors at Botancial Garden say stinky flower doesn't smell
that bad
 &HT;    Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As bad smells go, you've had worse elevator rides.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the buildup, the celebrated stinking flower of Atlanta _
the gigantic Amorphophallus titanum, blooming at the Atlanta
Botanical Garden _ didn't rank with the rankest scents you've ever
whiffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smells a little like dirty socks,'' said John Allison, who
dropped by to see the bloom Monday with his wife, Joan. ``We
expected rotting human flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   What many had feared would be an assault on their nostrils
turned out to be a feast for their eyes and titillation to the
other senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question I get most frequently is `What does the stalk
feel like?' '' said Carolyn White, the security officer who'd been
assigned to guard the flower since it bloomed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them the guy that waters it said it feels like
sponge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Garden's titan blossom is only the seventh produced in this
country. The flower is native to Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
   At more than 5 feet tall, Atlanta's bloom may be the largest
ever in the United States. Garden officials think so, anyway. This
week, T-shirts will go on sale with a picture of the flower and
this boast: ``Our Amorphophallus titanum is bigger than yours.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the parking lot was jammed to overflowing on a day
when the Garden normally is closed. Four TV crews showed up, along
with hundreds of paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   The bloom peaked Sunday, and its main stalk will topple any day.
Garden curator of tropical plants Ron Gagliardo, said the bloom
will stay on display through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it topples, we may cut it open and put a mirror above it
so people can see the smaller blooms inside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the plant has become an overnight scentsation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
