A2543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-TECH-COX     07-06 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-TECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As Lycos surges, sky seems to be limit for Net stocks
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lycos, known for its search engine of the same name
(http://www.lycos.com), announced a 2-for-1 stock split Monday and
then saw its stock soar, following a pattern set by other Internet
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos jumped $20.50 to $99.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! Inc., Amazon.com Inc. and other Internet stocks already
at records got a further boost from the Lycos announcement.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no ceiling for Internet stocks lately, with
most of the excitement coming from investor optimism that media
companies will buy them, fueled _ many analysts think _ by NBC's
investment last month in Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic rises in Internet stocks over the past month, with
many hitting all-time highs, left Wall Street analysts looking on
in wonderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet stocks are obviously making moves that are not
based on anybody doing arithmetic,'' said Robert Herwick, president
of Herwick Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the meteoric rise of these stock prices, (the Web
companies) are still small companies compared to the giants who
might want to acquire them,'' said Jeff Sadler, an analyst with
Robinson-Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the speculation has been centered on rumors that Web
navigation companies such as Lycos, Netscape and Excite were prime
targets for acquisition by major media companies. AT&AMP;T (which plans
to merge with Tele-Communications Inc.), Time Warner and CBS are
some of the traditional media companies looking for new
distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler compares the current Web stock frenzy to the early days
of the biotechnology industry. ``In the early stages of biotech,
everybody's stock went up. Some were delivering on their promises,
and others weren't. Then came the retractions. This is not unusual
in the early stages of emerging companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lycos is certainly one portal (trade jargon for a search
engine) that needs a partner and is likely to (be acquired) next,''
predicts Forrester Research analyst Chris Charron. ``Lycos has the
traffic and the strong technology to be an attractive partner. The
investors believe there is media support for this space. Companies
are looking to buy in. Compared to the price of Yahoo!, Lycos may
look attractive. ``
</P>
<P>
   The Lycos stock split is payable to shareholders of record Aug.
14.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
