<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSORSHIP-3800(4Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM AND THE FIG LEAF IN U.S. ARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History proves that freedom of expression does not come easily
to even the greatest artists _ from the Beatles to Michelangelo,
from Mahler to Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, so soon after Independence Day 1998, artists fear the
chill of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than 10 days ago, the Supreme Court ruled that the
National Endowment for the Arts must consider public values in the
process of awarding grants.
</P>
<P>
   Is this tragedy or justice? With Independence Day sentiments
still fresh in mind, we offer a select list of controversial and
censored works. You decide.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   ``Christ Blessing'' (c. 1500) _ The navel in this Giovanni
Bellini work was painted over in the 19th-century Victorian period
after it was deemed to render Christ too human.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Judgment'' (1533-1541) _ Michelangelo's painting on the
east wall of the Sistine Chapel in the Vatican drew criticism even
before it was finished. In 1564, an artist was hired, by order of
the Council of Trent, to paint clothing over the nude figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Armory Show (1913) _ When the infamous show of modern art
traveled to Chicago, professors of the School of the Art Institute
of Chicago told their students to stay away. A group of students
went anyway and became so outraged at Matisse's ``Blue Nude'' that
they threw stale bread rolls at it _ then hung Matisse in effigy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fountain'' (1917) _ Under the pseudonym of ``R. Mutt,'' Marcel
Duchamp submitted a sculpture titled ``Fountain'' _ actually
nothing more than a urinal with a signature on it _ to an open show
produced by a group of avant-garde artists. The group refused to
accept it. (An additional irony: Duchamp was one of the group's
founding members.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mirth and Girth'' (1988) _ A painting of recently deceased
Chicago Mayor Harold Washington wearing women's lingerie was
``arrested'' after being displayed at the School of the Art
Institute of Chicago. The painting, by graduating senior David K.
Nelson, represented the African-American hero figure as effeminate,
said the Chicago aldermen who persuaded police to take it away. The
painting was damaged in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doonesbury'' (1989-present day) _ Various newspaper editors
across the country refused at times to run Garry Trudeau's edgy
political comic strip, deeming it in bad taste or a mistreatment of
controversial issues. Problem topics included Alzheimer's disease,
AIDS, allegations of drug use by then-Vice President Dan Quayle
and, in February of this year, sexual allegations against President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``X Portfolio'' (1992) _ Conservatives raised a stink about U.S.
government funding exhibits that offended them, including Robert
Mapplethorpe's ``X Portfolio'' (which contained gay themes, nudity
and graphic images).
</P>
<P>
   ``P--- Christ'' (1992-1998) _ Conservatives were angered by
Andres Serrano's photo of a crucifix displayed in a jar of human
urine. (Ironically, Serrano later would anger liberals by taking
pictures of members of the Ku Klux Klan.) This year, ``P---
Christ'' was included in a survey of Serrano's work at the National
Museum of Virginia in Melbourne, Australia, where it was destroyed
by two teen-agers with a sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myra'' (1997) _ At Britain's Royal Academy, two angry viewers
threw eggs and ink on a portrait of a well-known British child
killer created from hundreds of imprints of a child's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Age of Innocence, The Last Day of Summer'' and ``Radiant
Identities'' (1998) _ Books by two noted photographers were hidden
from minors in a Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore in Brentwood, Tenn.,
after a controversy that led to three grand jury indictments in
Tennessee and Alabama. The books, by photographers Jock Sturges and
David Hamilton, include pictures of nude children and are
considered by opponents to be child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
