<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2557 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTLESS-BAND-AZR &LR;      07-06 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTLESS-BAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTLESS HEART FINDS HARMONY IN REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDAVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - When country supergroup Restless Heart quietly
stopped beating in 1994, most of the members went off to other
musical ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Drummer John Dittrich formed the band Buffalo Club. Guitarist
Greg Jennings joined Vince Gill's backing band.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Paul Gregg, the group's lanky, gregarious bass
player. He went to work at his family's chain of carwashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in, and they'll do a double take,'' Gregg says.
``The guys from Little Texas came through, and they're looking at
me. I just go, `Would you like your tires cleaned?' It's been
really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg, always the group's quirkiest soul, says it was easy for
him to move into the business that his dad started. On the other
hand, when the call came for him to rejoin his former bandmates,
that was a tougher decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't miss the stage all that much,'' he admits. ``I worked
really hard at my business and trying to improve the spiritual side
of my life. It had been a fight to spend that many years on the
road. I was a little apprehensive to get back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   When the band was on the road, few groups could touch Restless
Heart. The quintet created crystal harmonies that were almost
frighteningly pure. The guys weren't brothers, but they sure
sounded like it.
</P>
<P>
   They had an unerring sense about what made a good song. From
1986 through 1994, they were a mainstay on radio with tunes such as
the spritely ``Why Does It Have to Be (Wrong or Right)'' and the
haunting ``Dancy's Dream,'' a powerful look at a man in spiritual
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   And in the days when crossover was a dirty word, they were
constantly pushing the envelope. ``I'll Still Be Loving You,''
``When She Cries'' and the R&AMP;B-flavored ``Tell Me What You Dream''
all became pop hits without alienating country fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see people like LeAnn Rimes and Trisha Yearwood cross
over, it makes me think,'' Gregg says. ``It's interesting where
country is going and where it's been. It's like it's coming back
around to where it was when we first got in.''
</P>
<P>
   The group started to splinter in 1991. Lead singer Larry Stewart
took his distinctive voice and left for a solo career. The next
year, keyboardist Dave Innis departed.
</P>
<P>
   The group soldiered on, but pressures of the road mounted. It
was tough for Gregg, a married man with two kids. After the disc
``Matters of the Heart'' flopped in '94, the trio called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't no perfect marriages, and there ain't no perfect
bands,'' Gregg says. ``But we've never had a situation where we
haven't been able to communicate with each other. That speaks very
highly of this band _ they're a class bunch of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost instantly, reunion rumors began. They were all gossip
until the guys regrouped two years ago to make a tape for a
terminally ill fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really scary, like, `Been there, done that,' '' Gregg
says. ``But we could tell that there was still something there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, managers, agents and publicists were involved. The
group's old home, RCA Records, signed them to a new deal. It's
almost like the old days. The entire group is back, save for Innis.
Gregg is vague about the reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some issues he has to work out,'' he says. ``We didn't
want to make his life miserable; we didn't want ours to be
miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has out a greatest-hits disc that features three
just-recorded songs. The first single, ``No End to This Road,'' is
rapidly moving its way up the chart. It's like the guys _ older and
wiser _ have climbed back aboard a ``Fast-Movin' Train,'' to quote
one of their standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife never understood how I walked away the first time,''
Gregg says. ``I mean, I took my guitars and locked them in the
closet. For four years, I never touched them. The stench about
knocked me over when I took them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg isn't sure how long this phase of Restless Heart will
last. There are no immediate plans past the reunion tour.
</P>
<P>
   So far, fans have reacted positively. And judging from the
group's new songs, that unmistakable blend of voices is still
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be boastful, but some things just click,''
Gregg says. ``The way our harmonies blend, the way we sing with
each other . . . it's like we never missed a beat. I don't know any
other way to explain it. It's like the planets started to line up,
you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the four join voices for the hushed tones of ``For
Lack of Better Words.'' Gregg is not being boastful. This is one
man who should not spend his days washing cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if the music business would ever come back
around for me,'' he says with a sly chuckle. ``I wanted to make
sure I had something else to fall back on.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
