<P>
   &UR; REVENGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A grizzled old man was eating in a truck stop when three Hell's
Angels bikers walked in. The first walked up to the old man, pushed
his cigarette into the old man's pie and then took a seat at the
counter. The second walked up to the old man, spit into the old
man's milk and then he took a seat at the counter. The third walked
up to the old man, turned over the old man's plate, and then he
took a seat at the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Without a word of protest, the old man quietly left the diner.
Shortly thereafter, one of the bikers said to the waitress, `Humph,
not much of a man, was he?`
</P>
<P>
   The waitress replied, `Not much of a truck driver either. He
just backed his truck over three motorcycles.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELEMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sherlock Holmes and Watson were on a camping and hiking trip.
</P>
<P>
   They had gone to bed and were lying there looking up at the sky.
Holmes said, `Watson, look up. What do you see?`
</P>
<P>
   `Well, I see thousands of stars.`
</P>
<P>
   `And what does that mean to you?`
</P>
<P>
   `Well, I guess it means we will have another nice day tomorrow.
What does it mean to you, Holmes?`
</P>
<P>
   `To me, it means someone has stolen our tent.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIRTY JOKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man walks into a house of ill repute and tells the
madam that he would like a young woman for the night. The madam
gives him a puzzled look and asks, `Just how old are you, mister?`
</P>
<P>
   `Why,` the old patron says, `I'm 98 years old today!`
</P>
<P>
   `Ninety-eight!` the madam exclaims. `Don't you realize you've
had it?`
</P>
<P>
   `Oh,` he says, `then how much do I owe you?`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIFFERENCE BETWEEN A NICKEL AND A DIME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There's a little fellow named Junior who hangs out at Tim
Alley's Grocery Store. The owner Tim doesn't know what Junior's
problem is, but the boys like to tease him. They say he is two
bricks shy of a load, or two pickles shy of a barrel. To prove it,
sometimes they offer Junior his choice between a nickel and a dime.
He always takes the nickel, they say, because it's bigger. One day
after Junior grabbed the nickel, Tim got him off to one side and
said, `Junior, those boys are making fun of you. They think you
don't know the dime is worth more than the nickel. Are you grabbing
the nickel because it's bigger, or what?` Junior said, `Well, if I
took the dime, they'd quit doing it!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I was riding home on the No. 3 train during rush hour when a
mother, babe-in-arms, and a little boy with a bag of potato chips
came into the car. The little boy bounced down next to me and
continued working on the chips. The mother was standing.
</P>
<P>
   I am aged and not inhibited about offering gentle criticism. I
asked the boy whether he didn't think his mother would like to sit.
Without missing a chip, he bellowed: ``Ma, do you want to sit?''
</P>
<P>
   She said ``no'' just as he added, ``cause there's a woman here
who wants to give you her seat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Evelyn A. Mauss
</P>
<P>
   The 60ish man was slightly paunchy but nattily dressed as he
stepped onto the 66th Street crosstown bus. After several tries, he
still couldn't get his Metrocard properly placed in the slot. Trudy
Linfield was sitting behind the driver and enjoyed this exchange:
</P>
<P>
   Driver: ``You have terrible technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger: ``I have to hear that from you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know New York is a tough town,'' writes Richard Donsky, but
this sign in Soho struck him as extreme: ``Unauthorized Parkers:
License plates will be removed, air will be taken out of tires.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you define a New Yorker? Susan Welsher Jereski was in a
restaurant recently sitting next to two women discussing their
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   One said she had a terrace. The other sniffed: ``I wouldn't want
a terrace. I'm not the outdoorsy type.''
</P>
<P>
   The young businessman, busy at his laptop, smelling faintly of
gin, was sprawled over three seats during the rush hour on the E
train. To his left were reference books; to his right, a briefcase
and papers.
</P>
<P>
   As I indicated I would like a seat, he pointed to an elderly
lady, snoozing and occupying two seats and asked, ``Why don't you
sit over there?''
</P>
<P>
   I told him this was a subway and not his office; he gathered his
things and moved over, muttering, ``You should have some common
courtesy when you see people working.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, my eyes wandered to his laptop display which
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York subways are full of jackasses. This 40-45 year
old man just disrupted my work by demanding to sit next to me. What
a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   I took out my notebook and started writing my version of this
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   The man continued typing:
</P>
<P>
   ``The bozo's taken out a notebook and I think he's writing about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been interesting to see where this would have
gone, but I had to get off. Still, he made my day. I'm 58.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jerry Weiss
</P>
<P>
   Dominick Coviello was in a Kmart looking for a good buy in
litter for his ferrets and discovered a brand he had not seen
before. The shape of the bucket was unusual; it held 25 rather than
22 pounds and the price was $1 less than that of the smaller
amount.
</P>
<P>
   He was so pleased with his find that he tried to share it with a
fellow shopper whom he presumed was also in search of a best buy.
Did he get any appreciation? No.
</P>
<P>
   The other litter shopper wasn't interested: ``I'm a little more
concerned with quality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: A TriBeCa restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Judith and Stephen Gutmann, celebrating their 35th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Action: Waiter approaches and asks:``Do you have any
questions?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gutmann: ``Yes, please tell us about the ostrich.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiter: ``Well, it's a very big bird.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother, a psychoanalyst, received a message on her answering
machine that was intended for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The caller, thinking he was leaving a message for ``John,''
announced that he was going to be on television that night and
named the time and channel.
</P>
<P>
   My mother was distressed because he did not leave a return phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so excited about being on television,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what did you do?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   To which she replied: ``What could I do, I went home and
watched.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amy J. Gershenson
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Greenberg was waiting her turn at her favorite hot-dog
vendor on First Avenue and 34th Street when the young man in front
of her asked for mayo on his large spicy sausage.
</P>
<P>
   The vendor picked up a plastic bottle and squirted the pale
dressing along the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greenberg couldn't help it. She looked at the customer and
said: `You're not from New York, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   The man laughed and admitted that he was from California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wasn't I surprised?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The day Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel was on the
East Side of Manhattan, Julia Koenig and Cara Eckert were walking
down Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   They were behind a couple who Ms. Koenig defined as ``clearly
tourists, maps hanging out of their pockets, cameras hung around
their necks and walking much more slowly than the natives.''
</P>
<P>
   The husband said to the wife: ``What do you think all the cement
barriers and wooden horses along the sidewalk are for?''
</P>
<P>
   The wife replied: ``I think they keep the tourists away from the
residences.''
</P>
<P>
   I was walking my Shetland sheepdog in Greenwich Village when she
suddenly lunged for something on the street and started chomping
away.
</P>
<P>
   In exasperation, I shouted, ``What on earth have you picked up
this time?''
</P>
<P>
   Behind me, I heard a childlike high-pitched voice say, ``I don't
know and I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   I turned around to find a young man with a big grin on his face
who had decided to speak for my dog. We laughed. The dog did not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ruth Rosenberg
</P>
<P>
   It was intermission at a Sunday afternoon performance of ``The
Beauty Queen of Leenane.'' As usual, there was a long line for the
ladies' room and a much shorter one for the men's room. Four women
decided to join the men's line, and one was finally admitted when a
chivalrous male announced that a stall was free.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ebert was one of the men who heard her proclaiming loudly
``I'm not looking, I'm not looking,'' as she walked in.
</P>
<P>
   When she emerged, she observed to the one friend still on line,
``I tell you Debby, it's just like I was Ally McBeal.''
</P>
