<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-06 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ABOUT A BOY': AN UNCOMMITTED SLACKER INVENTS COMMITMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So how cool is Will Freeman? Nick Hornby's feckless slacker-hero
is so cool that he scores a daunting 66 in a magazine
questionnaire, a score that officially ranks him as one of the
coolest of the cool: ``sub-zero,'' ``dry ice,'' so cool he could
``die of hypothermia.''
</P>
<P>
   What has Will done to become so cool? Well, in the last three
months he has slept with a woman he didn't know very well; he has
spent more than 300 pounds (about $500) on a jacket; he has taken
Ecstasy in a club (not at home as a sociological exercise); he has
eaten in a restaurant that serves polenta and shaved Parmesan, and
he has both grown a goatee and shaved it off again.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rob, the narrator of Hornby's highly acclaimed first novel,
``High Fidelity'' (1995), Will is another one of those
thirtysomething men who give new meaning to Cyril Connolly's phrase
``perpetual adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   At 36, he has never held a job _ he lives off a comfortable
stipend from his father, who penned a treacly novelty song called
``Santa's Super Sleigh'' _ and he congratulates himself on his
ability to stay afloat on the effluvia of modern life: on movies,
pop songs, magazines and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life took up so much time,'' Will thinks, ``so how could one
work and, say, take a bath on the same day? He suspected that one
or two people he knew were making some pretty unsavory shortcuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``About a Boy'' retraces much of the same comic ground
as ``High Fidelity,'' it's an altogether glibber, slicker
production that lacks the earlier novel's idiosyncratic pop and
sizzle. ``Boy'' feels less anchored in a particular place and time,
perhaps because it boasts fewer knowing references to pop culture,
perhaps because it plows ahead stolidly, like a movie script,
without pausing to glance around.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that ``Boy'' isn't a lot of fun to read. It's
just that Hornby's wonderfully antic sense of humor is employed
here in the service of a contrived story line that forces his
engagingly churlish hero to undergo a series of predictably
transformative _ and redemptive _ adventures.
</P>
<P>
   We pretty much know Will's problems _ defensiveness, emotional
detachment and a fear of commitment _ the moment we meet him, and
we can pretty much guess what's going to happen to him a couple of
beats later.
</P>
<P>
   Will, of course, is a kind of fictional descendant of Kingsley
Amis' Lucky Jim and William Boyd's Morgan Leafy, and he's also a
sort of spiffed-up British version of ``Seinfeld's'' George
Costanza.
</P>
<P>
   He not only embodies just about everything that women like
Bridget Jones (not to mention her real-life counterparts) find so
frustrating about single ``eligible'' men _ namely, a carefully
honed talent for wriggling out of commitment, maturity and honor _
but he's also proud of the maneuvers he has developed for avoiding
unnecessary emotional clutter.
</P>
<P>
   Having dated a gorgeous single mother named Angie (who he thinks
would normally be out of his league), Will comes to the conclusion
that ``children democratized beautiful single women'': Children, he
thinks, ``served as a symbolic blemish, like a birthmark or
obesity, which gave him a chance where previously there would have
been none.''
</P>
<P>
   After his affair with Angie ends, Will decides to seek out other
beautiful single mothers at a local meeting of SPAT (Single Parents
_ Alone Together). Will invents a fictional ex-wife for himself
(her name is Paula, he tells himself) and a fictional 2-year-old
son (his name is Ned, not Ted, he continually reminds himself) and
with these lies, he launches himself in the world of single
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Will does not meet a beautiful single mother, however. He meets
a sweet, troubled 12-year-old named Marcus, who needs a father.
Marcus is worried about his mother, who has tried to kill herself,
and he's worried about his own prospects at school, where he is
tormented by his classmates for being a nerd, a weirdo and a geek.
</P>
<P>
   Since Will is basically a 12-year-old himself, he and Marcus
soon form a bond. This is a little more emotional involvement _ a
little more clutter in his life _ than Will is used to, but he
figures he can use his vast knowledge of pop culture, his cool
quotient as it were, to help keep Marcus from being beaten up at
school.
</P>
<P>
   He buys Marcus some hip new sneakers, persuades him to get a
decent haircut and teaches him about Nirvana and Kurt Cobain.
Meanwhile, he meets a woman who apparently likes him because she
thinks Marcus is his son, a development that, needless to say,
leads to all sorts of further complications.
</P>
<P>
   Hornby uses his familiarity with adolescents and adolescent
behavior to get inside the heads of both Will and Marcus and to
give their lives an appealing specificity. In this novel, unlike
``Fidelity,'' however, he tends to spell out needlessly their
states of mind, rather than simply allowing their actions to speak
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He is constantly telling us things like ``Will had spent his
whole life avoiding real stuff'' or having Will say or think things
like: ``You could shut life out. If you didn't answer the door to
it, how was it going to get in?''
</P>
<P>
   This writerly tic has a way of making ``About a Boy'' feel even
more schematic than it really is. Yet if we can see the novel's
conclusion coming far off down the pike, Hornby's sharp
observations and his quirky comedic instincts ensure that our
journey there is entertaining, funny _ and occasionally affecting.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ABOUT A BOY'
</P>
<P>
   By Nick Hornby
</P>
<P>
   307 pages. Riverhead Books. $22.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
