<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     07-06 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ABOUT RESIDENCE OFF-LIMITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. One of the applicants for a position here has
had many residences over the past few years. His job stability has
been fairly good but I am wondering if his other moves are a sign
of problems.
</P>
<P>
   M.R. &QL; 
A. This is literally an applicant on the move, but the fact is that
his personal residences are literally none of your business. All of
your questions should be job-related, and his tendency to
frequently move from one residence to another not only is unrelated
to the job but is not predictive of any aspect of his future
performance on the job. After all, there are plenty of cases of
people who move around frequently and maintain high levels of
performance as well as cases of those who remain in the same
residence for years and years but whose performance resides
somewhere south of horrible.
</P>
<P>
   If your concern is whether he will be able to be at work during
normal working hours on a regular basis, you should ask him that.
If he has any demands, responsibilities, interests or commitments
that could interfere with his ability to be at work during normal
working hours, you can ask him that, too. Job-related questions are
the best predictors of future job performance.
</P>
<P>
   You indicated that this applicant has had fairly good job
stability. If you are trying to find an indicator of future job
stability, numerous studies have shown that past stability is the
predictor. By asking about an applicant's tendency to change
residences, you are actually asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having serious problems getting along with one of the
people who report to me. She has a difficult and abrasive
personality, and she is always ready to complain about whatever I
do. We have met with management to discuss this but nothing has
worked. What do you suggest in this type of situation?
</P>
<P>
   C.W.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your employee is overlooking an important part of her working
relationship with you: reality. The reality is that you are the
manager. It sounds like you have tried to establish a more cordial
and supportive working relationship with this individual but it is
not happening.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that your employee is entirely to blame. In
fact, she may perceive you as a difficult and abrasive person.
Either way, it is time for both of you to focus on the job that
needs to be done, rather than on personality characteristics. You
and this employee need to come to an arrangement regarding the
objectives, standards and performance expectations for her
position, and she should be evaluated strictly on her effectiveness
in these areas.
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, if her abrasiveness is interfering with her
effectiveness, that should be noted in any formal assessment of her
performance. When she is given feedback, it should be in terms of
specific behaviors and measurable indicators of productivity,
rather than in terms of general descriptors or labels. You should
also provide her with some guidance regarding the kinds of steps
for her to take in order to meet the established standards. She
also needs to understand the reality of the consequences associated
with sub-par performance.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just finished a meeting with my direct supervisor and she
told me that I spend too much time trying to please everyone else
around here and that is ultimately going to hurt my career. Do you
agree and, if so, what can I do about it?
</P>
<P>
   A.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a quote attributed to Benjamin Franklin that fits
your situation: ``I cannot give you a formula for success, but
here's the formula for failure: Try to please everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   As you advance your career, your responsibilities increasingly
will place you in situations in which it will be impossible to
please all who work with you. You will be making decisions in a
myriad of areas that can be potentially upsetting to others,
whether in terms of your availability, priorities, performance
standards or enforcement of established policies.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that by placing excessive emphasis on pleasing
others, you end up pleasing no one, including yourself. Managers
who try to do so can be labeled as weak, pliable, unfair and even
unprofessional.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who have a strong need to please others tend to have
a related need to be well-liked. Although there is nothing wrong
with wanting to be liked, it is not a great objective for people
who want to manage. For managers, the more appropriate objectives
are to be effective, professional, ethical and fair. And, by doing
so, such a manager has a very good chance of being well-liked. The
idea of being well-liked is best viewed as a byproduct of
management, rather than as an objective.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
