<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPARE-PARTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARE-PARTS BUSINESS KEEPS AIRCRAFT FLYING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE KENNEDY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATES CITY, Mo. _ Where you see the twisted propellers and
dented fuselage of a grounded airplane, Phil White sees a business
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Where you see an 180-acre field littered with junk and debris,
White sees a 30-year inventory of engines, electronics and other
valuable parts.
</P>
<P>
   That's why White is in the aircraft salvage business, and you're
not.
</P>
<P>
   On what was once an idle pasture on the eastern fringe of the
metropolitan area, White Industries is a field of dreams for pilots
and plane owners looking for the hard-to-find part to return their
flying machines to the skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't specialize,'' White said. ``We run the entire gamut.
Whatever a pilot is flying, we'll have a part.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is one of the largest airplane salvage operations in
the United States, said a spokesman for the Airplane Owners and
Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   The salvage yard has 2,000 aircraft in various states of
disassembly, but that's not readily evident to the countless
drivers who whiz by the business as they drive on Interstate 70
near Bates City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   All they have seen, most likely, is (begin itals)one(end itals)
plane _ a weathered Lear jet perched along the northern frontage
road of the highway. That's the only clue that an airplane
graveyard lies a few hundred yards north.
</P>
<P>
   The obscure location doesn't hurt business. White said less than
1 percent of his business comes from walk-in customers. Clients
from around the world make their deals by phone, fax or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The company began as a foreign auto-part business that White's
father, Terry White, founded. In the 1960s, it evolved into
aircraft parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a pilot, and he saw how hard it was to find parts for a
plane,'' Phil White said.
</P>
<P>
   The elder White operated the company on a 30-acre site on U.S.
40 in east Kansas City, Mo. Increasing vandalism and the need for
more space sent him out to Lafayette County in the early 1980s. The
site includes a 4,600-foot runway for the occasional fly-in
customer and 200,000 square feet of warehouse and office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't start one this size now,'' Phil White said. ``It
would take too long to build up the inventory. We have 30 years of
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the airplanes have had brushes with fame, but with 2,000
of them to keep track of, the facts can get a little hazy.
</P>
<P>
   One plane that crashed years ago in Alaska may have been owned
by Aristotle Onassis; another was used by Elvis Presley. One
appeared in one of the James Bond movies _ `` `Goldfinger,' I
think,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Phil White began working at the company as a kid. He mowed
grass, swept floors, pulled parts from planes, helped ship parts
and ultimately wound up in sales. In February, his father
``semi-retired'' and chose his son, 34, to run the company as
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he still owns it,'' Phil White said. ``He has the final
say.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's 35 employees constantly have feelers out for
troubled aircraft. Each day, they scour Federal Aviation
Administration damage reports, and work the phones with insurance
companies and dealers looking to unload planes.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 1 percent of the planes at the salvage yard have been
involved in fatal accidents. Most planes end up in salvage for more
mundane reasons: Maybe a hangar falls onto a jet; a plane's landing
gear collapses; a pilot school shuts down and has a clearance sale;
or authorities seize a craft involved in illegal activities. White
buys about 190 aircraft a year.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, White had more than 30 planes scattered
throughout the United States that he had bought, but had not been
brought to the salvage yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to find someone to drive it here,'' he said.
``What's difficult is finding someone qualified to take an airplane
apart, especially a damaged aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases White sells whole planes when they can be repaired
for a reasonable cost and still fly. In most cases, the planes the
business acquires are sold for parts.
</P>
<P>
   Once White has the plane, workers typically strip it of the most
valuable components _ the engine and electronic equipment. Then the
customers come calling.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, plane owners in Florida needed a new nose for a
Fokker commuter plane after the original part was damaged. They got
in touch with White, negotiated a price, and for $15,000, White
sawed off the front of one of his Fokker commuter planes and
shipped it south.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the cockpit-less plane sits in a field waiting
until some other part is needed. Many planes at White Industries
share the same fate. They have been beheaded and their cockpits
sold to businesses needing flight simulators.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts fill the shelves of the warehouses. A collection of
plane noses looks like the wardrobe department of a ``Coneheads''
movie. Engine cowlings and wing tips are stacked to the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   But with so many aircraft taking up space, most of the parts are
left unharvested in planes until a customer comes looking for a
particular item.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could take our phones out of service and do nothing but
inventory all the parts, and it would take a year's time,'' White
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
