<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLOW TIME FOR YOURSELF TO HAVE FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Saturday was the Fourth of July _ a time for
barbecues, homemade ice cream and a chance to defrost my freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds crazy, but you'd be surprised how many women will unplug
the deep freeze the next few weeks. It's part of the ritual we
perform each summer before taking our vacations.
</P>
<P>
   I know it doesn't make sense. Most of us already are overwhelmed
by swim meets, baseball games and the extra load at the office as
the census at work dwindles during the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   So why do we spend valuable time cleaning our homes when we
won't be there? It's probably the same reason we're usually the
ones who pick, plan and prepare for vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Sure I know at least one guy who stopped his mail and mowed his
lawn before taking a vacation, but he's pretty unusual. A lot of
men think they've done a lot if they got the traveler's checks and
bought the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, I realize that part of the problem is our own.
My husband doesn't care if we leave the house spotless. While he'd
rather not come home to a mess, he reasons that most things can
wait until we return.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of women I know don't see it that way. Not only do the
beds need to be made and the carpets vacuumed, the floors need to
be mopped and the laundry folded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if women don't have permission to have fun,'' said
Connie Russell, a licensed social worker and career development
coach. ``By making sure everything is done, women feel they've
earned the right to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she said, women are juggling many roles at
work and at home, and we have a difficult time saying no.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's advice is ``to give yourself permission to have fun
without first climbing Mount Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention to what you're doing,'' said Russell, who
admitted she took the time to clean her office before leaving town.
``Ask yourself: ``Is this necessary to do before I go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is. Most of us want to leave a clean house because
we know how busy we'll be at home and work when we're first back.
But maybe you can wait a few weeks to finish those photo albums.
</P>
<P>
   I'd take Russell's advice a step further. Not only should you
say no, you should lower your standards and ask for help,
especially from other family members.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the children will cram far too many toys and
books in their backpacks, let them do it. Not only will they be
sure to pack at least something they want, it's one fewer thing
you'll have to do.
</P>
<P>
   And while I'm at it, I think I'll ask my husband to help too.
The first thing he can do is pull the plug on the freezer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
