<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSORSHIP-2ndTake-TE     07-06 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSORSHIP-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: child pornography. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LITERATURE
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn'' by Mark Twain (1884) _
The incorrect grammar and phonetic spelling in Huck's first-person
account drew fire from sanctimonious elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Awakening'' by Kate Chopin (1899) _ It's a woman's sexual
awakening, a forbidden subject then and for a long time afterward.
Redeemed by the women's movement of the 1970s, it is now an
acknowledged classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sister Carrie'' by Theodore Dreiser (1900) _ This
groundbreaker in the mode of naturalism was widely suppressed
because the titular heroine was not made to suffer for her
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bertram Cope's Year'' by Henry Blake Fuller (1919) _ Privately
printed after its original publisher capitulated to pressure and
withdrew it, this was the first novel to treat homosexuality
directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Main Street'' by Sinclair Lewis (1920) _ Especially in the
Midwest, libraries refused entry to a work that presented an
unflattering, exposelike view of small-town American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco Road'' (1932) and ``God's Little Acre'' (1933), both
by Erskine Caldwell _ Frank presentation of the depravity of poor
Southern ``white trash'' caused these books to be both censured and
(some printings) censored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grapes of Wrath'' by John Steinbeck (1939) _ Although this
social protest novel took a Pulitzer Prize, pressure from church
and civic groups provoked bans in Boston and elsewhere, again on
grounds of language and depravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoirs of Hecate County'' by Edmund Wilson (1946) _ These
linking short stories by America's foremost literary critic make up
virtually the only book to have been banned nationally on grounds
of sexual explicitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catcher in the Rye'' by J.D. Salinger (1951) _ Although
widely read in high school and junior high classrooms, this exalted
novel has been a perennial target for would-be censors because of
one four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portnoy's Complaint'' by Philip Roth (1969) _ Many works by
this author (the latest Pulitzer winner) have lived with scandal,
none so much as this much-attacked first-person revelation (to a
psychiatrist) of sexual mystery.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   ``Desire Under the Elms'' by Eugene O'Neill (1924) _ This gloomy
drama of stepson/stepmother incest was raided by police when the
production was moved from Greenwich Village to Manhattan. The
publicity improved attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``All God's Chillun Got Wings'' by Eugene O'Neill (1924) _ This
O'Neill opus dealt with interracial marriage. The Ku Klux Klan
threatened the playwright, and city officials tried to shut down
the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Price Glory?'' by Maxwell Anderson (1924) _ The language
of the troops was considered shocking in this realistic depiction
of World War I combat and its emotional toll on the fighting men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cradle Will Rock'' by Marc Blitzstein (1937-1938) _ The
composer/playwright's leftist leanings prompted the WPA to drop the
play as a project. Later, the New York premiere was halted by an
injunction. Cast and audience then trekked more than a mile to an
empty theater where the show went on, sort of. To thwart the
injunction, actors performed from the seats instead of the stage.
The musicians' union honored the injunction, so the only
accompaniment was Blitzstein playing solo piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' (1967) _ The Fort Worth
Theatre's artistic director wanted to stage Edward Albee's drama,
but the group's board said the language was too vulgar. By 1971,
attitudes had changed and the play was staged by FWT, to widespread
acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hair,'' Theatre Arlington, 1991. It wasn't the nude scene that
was the problem. The famous tribal rock, anti-war musical was on
the season calendar when the Persian Gulf War erupted. Not wanting
to be thought unpatriotic, the theater substituted another show.
Theater Arlington eventually produced ``Hair'' in l995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma!'' (1993) _ A wildly unorthodox production at Addison
Centre Theatre north of Dallas was to have been held over. But the
Rodgers &AMP; Hammerstein Library, which controls performance rights to
the show, persuaded them not to. Among the things the R&AMP;H office
objected to was the rigging of a hydraulic lift beneath Aunt
Eller's skirt so that she ``grew'' to a height of about 18 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corpus Christi'' (1998) _ Terrence McNally's new play about 13
gay men who meet to enact the story of Jesus was canceled by the
Manhattan Theater Club after the theater received death threats.
After a firestorm of protest within the theater community, the
Theater Club reversed its decision.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
