<SLUG> BC-FIGHTING-BULLS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN RANCHER BREEDS FIGHTING BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (TRINCHERAS, Sonora, Mexico) _ The spindly bull calves leave the
womb with their legs wobbly but their hearts strong.
</P>
<P>
   And their spirit bred for generations to put the hurt on human
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly the way Dr. Adrian Ortega Fernandez likes it on
his sprawling ranch in the desert of northern Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   This is where he raises ``pura sangre'' _ full blood _ bulls of
Iberian fighting ancestry that are the stars of northern Mexico's
resurgent bullfighting industry.
</P>
<P>
   If bloodlines don't make them mean enough, the cattle disappear
into a patchwork of mesquite thickets, organ pipe cactus and sandy
arroyos, not coming into contact with people for up to a year at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any man could ever tame them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they are 3 days old they start charging,'' says the
70-year-old Ortega, the sole producer of fighting bulls in
northwestern Mexico. ``You never turn your back on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Ortega turned his back on a lucrative career
as a surgeon and bought 70 square miles of this wild, sparsely
populated country.
</P>
<P>
   His friends thought he had lost his mind _ especially given that
era's drop in popularity of the traditional blood sport, in which
the matador sticks a sword through the shoulder blades and severs
the aorta of all but the bravest animals.
</P>
<P>
   There's no water, Ortega's friends protested. So he dug wells.
</P>
<P>
   There's no food, they said. So Ortega began growing fields of
alfalfa, barley, sorghum and wheat for his growing herd.
</P>
<P>
   It's too lonely, they said. Ortega acknowledges that his wife
can only put up with living part time at the isolated ranch house,
15 miles from the nearest paved road.
</P>
<P>
   But that also has its benefits, Ortega wryly notes: The animal
rights people in the United States haven't been able to find him.
Not that they would be able to change him.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega has long had a passion for bullfighting. Paintings,
photographs and publicity materials from the great Mexican and
Spanish ``plazas de toros'' cover the walls of his house.
</P>
<P>
   In one, he poses with the great Mexican matador Silverio Perez.
In another, Ortega has a panorama of the Astrodome in Houston where
45,000 turned out for a bullfight in 1970. The good old days,
Ortega sighs, before bullfighting was banned in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega fought as a novice when he was a student in Nogales,
Sonora, before going off to medical school in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's perfectly positioned to take advantage of the
resurgence of interest in bullfighting in Mexican cities along the
U.S. border, which has led promoters to prolong the seasons in
Tijuana, Mexicali and Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   Two competing entrepreneurs in Nogales also are expected to
bring back the ``corridas'' on a regular basis by the beginning of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega said he sold 60 bulls to the bullrings last year. In
fact, Ortega says he has been selling them as fast as he can raise
them.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good reason for that, says Silviano Tanori, a Nogales,
Ariz., matador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through selective breeding, the doctor has put together the
perfect bull for creating art,'' Tanori said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a huge investment in going way down south and buying
10 seed bulls and 200 cows from fighting stock which was top of the
line. Then, he has culled the lesser animals out and has produced
some real fighting machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanori found that out the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day we were testing the cattle in a pen and I was standing
next to this gate, talking,'' Tanori said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, this little bull, no more than 200 pounds, sees me
through a crack and hits the gate like a bolt of lightning. The
gate came off its hinges, crashed into me and gave me bruises all
over my body.''
</P>
<P>
   His cattle have become so wild, Ortega says, that he has given
up hope of ever trying to herd them again. They attack everything
that moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only control I have over them is water. If we have to move
them by vehicle between ranches, I fill a water trough in a corral
and someone sneaks up and closes the gate behind them,'' Ortega
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it takes the craftiest of cowboys to prod the cattle
through a loading chute and into trailers for the trip to ranch
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five head of the cattle recently have been moved to the
mesquite-wood corral near Ortega's house. As visitors move to
within 50 yards, the cattle kick up a huge cloud of dust as they
stampede along the inner corral wall.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega then walks to a nearby bullring with a shaded spectator
box from which he analyzes his stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give them all a rating from one to 10 depending on their
level of bravery,'' Ortega said. ``I've had several 10's and six of
them have been returned here. Their lives were spared by the
matadors because they were deemed to be so brave.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanori agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you fight one of these bulls, the spectators get their
money's worth,'' Tanori said. ``Plus, the matador gets a free
ticket to the primitive world.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
