<SLUG> BC-JASPER-MASSACHUSETTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN APPARENT RACIAL BEATING OF JASPER NATIVE IN
MASSACHUSETTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Mass.) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a case that in some ways mirrors the Jasper, Texas, murder of
James Byrd Jr., a Massachusetts court Monday began action against a
white man accused of beating a black Jasper native now living in
Lawrence, Mass., with a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Charles Love, 44, who moved to Lawrence about
15 years ago for better jobs, was beaten by three white men in an
apparently racially motivated attack Saturday. Love remained
hospitalized in stable condition Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Charged in the case was Jeffrey Klier, 43, described by an Essex
County, Mass., district attorney's spokesman as a ``career
criminal.'' Klier, who has 13 previous convictions, was accused of
attempted murder, civil rights violations, assault and battery with
a dangerous weapon and lesser offenses. Bond was set Monday at
$75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence police Detective Jack McDonald said authorities are
seeking two additional suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out about this Sunday,'' Love's aunt, Gloria Mays,
said at her home in Jasper, a town of 8,000 about 140 miles
northeast of Houston. ``I have to be very blunt. We felt anger.
This is happening all over again _ what we went through with the
Byrds.''
</P>
<P>
   Love's wife, Brandy, who is white, said the attack grew out of a
Saturday afternoon disturbance as her family celebrated both the
couple's 20th wedding anniversary and a granddaughter's birthday
with a backyard barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the back yard, but they could see us from the
front,'' she said. ``They were drunk. They would drive around and
around, yelling (racial epithets). They would come around every 15
or 20 minutes. This went on for two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   About 7 p.m., Love accosted the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles just told them to to stop and say their piece,'' his
wife said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said, the men beat him on the head with aluminum
bats, cursing him and calling him derogatory racial names. Mrs.
Love said she sought refuge in her automobile, but one of the
suspects smashed all the windows with a bat and appeared ready to
attack her when officers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Although not well-acquainted with the attackers, Mrs. Love said
she had previously seen Klier in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hangs (out) about three houses down the street from us,''
she said. ``He would always say, `Good morning' or `Good afternoon'
when he rode by on his bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Love said her husband, who remodels houses, had no previous
problems with the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles never bothers anyone,'' she said. ``He goes to work,
he comes home. He never goes anywhere unless it's to the store. He
goes to bed at 8 o'clock because he has to drive so far to his job.
Everybody around here knew him; knew he was from Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the couples in this neighborhood are integrated _
black and white, white and Spanish, Cambodian and white. Every
other family you see has dual nationality. People have their
fights, but nothing like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Love said she and her husband met in Little Rock, Ark.,
where he had worked as a construction worker and she had been
living with friends.
</P>
<P>
   They moved to Lawrence, once a decayed textile mill town revived
as part of former Gov. Michael Dukakis' ``Massachusetts Miracle,''
to rejoin her family.
</P>
<P>
   They reared four children from her previous marriage and two
adopted children, Mrs. Love said.
</P>
<P>
   District attorney's spokesman Steve O'Connell said Klier's
criminal record included sentences for burglaries and assaults. He
apparently has no record of previous civil rights violations,
O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
