<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROY-FILM-COX     07-06 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROY-FILM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rogers was always good-guy movie star
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time in the West, movie cowboys wore white hats and
rode golden stallions. When they weren't rounding up rustlers or
saving the ranch from some smoothly crooked banker, they could be
found courting a feisty cowgirl, cutting up with a crusty yet
lovable sidekick or, most likely, strumming a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Rogers wore the white hat in over 90 films. And he wore it
proudly and well, whether galloping through countless B-movie
serials on the Republic backlot or adding some cactus-savvy dash to
an A-list comedy like Bob Hope's ``Son of Paleface.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gene Autry, whom he essentially replaced, or Hopalong
Cassidy or any number of boxoffice buckeroos/singing cowboys who
blossomed in the '40s and '50s, Rogers was a wholesome hero.
Someone little kids could look up to. He didn't drink, smoke or
spit. He was fast with his fists and faster with a gun. And while
he never went looking for a fight, he never backed away from one,
either.
</P>
<P>
   His idea of strong language was an occasional ``aw, shucks.''
His idea of an ideal co-star was a palomino named Trigger who
carried him faithfully through every one of those 90-plus films;
like Roy, a Cincinnatti native, Trigger was originally a
tenderfoot, born in Milwaukee, Wisconson. His idea of a leading
lady was the same on screen as off _ Dale Evans whom he married on
New Year's Eve, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Roy's adventures, especially in the '40s and '50s, when theater
operators voted him the number one western star 12 years straight,
took place in a kind of weird, time-warped West where airplanes and
stagecoaches co-existed. Where the bad guy might well be dressed in
some sort of vaguely western-looking suit _with, say, a string tie
_ while Roy invariably wore gaudy cowboy garb, right down to
hand-tooled boots, colorful neckerchiefs and a silver-trimmed
holster, to match Trigger's slver-trimmed saddle. In fact, Roy was
into name-brand clothing and accessories long before Gloria
Vanderbilt or Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   The West he inhabited was the antithesis of the West imagined by
such contemporaries as John Ford or Howard Hawks who rooted their
mythologizing, such as it was, in a very different reality. As
times changed, Roy Rogers' West was so squeaky clean that it almost
begged to be defiled. And so it was. In '50s psychological westerns
like ''High Noon,'' ''Johnny Guitar'' and ''The Left-handed Gun.''
In the genre-bending spaghetti weterns of Sergio Leone (''Fistful
of Dollars,''''Once Upon a Time in the West''). In the revisionist
westerns of the late '60s and early '70s (''Little Big Man,'' ''The
Wild Bunch''). Even a jolly romp like ''Butch Cassidy and the
Sundance Kid'' had no place for the simplistic morality of a Roy
Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the mythic figure of The Cowboy as embodied by Rogers and
his ilk has never entirely left us. We still can glimpse him as the
``good'' badman in John Wayne's last film, ``The Shootist,'' or
Clint Eastwood's Oscar-winning ``Unforgiven.'' He finds his inner
Sensitive Male in Kevin Costner's ``Dances With Wolves'' and is
re-born as the Brat Pack on horseback in ''Young Guns.'' Or he
simply finds new territory to roam _ Han Solo's space-cowboy in the
''Star Wars'' trilogy or Eastwood, again, as an urban gunslinger in
the Dirty Harry movies.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bruce Willis, Sly Stallone and their endless clones, Roy
Rogers didn't need a billion dollars worth of special effects to
work his heroics. He just needed a horse, a gun and an unerring
sense of what was right.
</P>
<P>
   What's been lost, however, perhaps forever, is Roy's untainted
innocence. His clear-eyed belief in the Code of the West where a
hero always fought fair and was a little shy around ladies. His
legacy reminds us that, not so long ago, it was okay to be a Good
Guy. That, in fact, we were once a nation of Good Guys who saluted
the flag and unquestioningly stood when the national anthem was
played. And though he hadn't made a movie since 1975, his death
somehow makes the trail just a little more lonesome. And a little
less happy.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel is a film critic for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
