<HEADER>
A2578 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSORSHIP-3rdTake-TE     07-06 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSORSHIP-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: its decision. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FILM
</P>
<P>
   ``Song of the South'' (1956) _ A Walt Disney feature that
combined animation and live action to tell the B'rer Fox and B'rer
Rabbit stories. It was re-released as recently as 25 years ago, but
the studio pulled it after conceding that it did indeed feature
racial caricatures. It can now only be found on imported cassettes
and laserdiscs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971) _ This Stanley Kubrick film
prompted an editorial in The Detroit News that said the combination
of sex and violence was so disturbing that the News could no longer
support the rating affixed to such a movie. The X rating fell into
disrepute after most newspapers stopped accepting ads for X-rated
films in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Tango in Paris'' (1972) _ This groundbreaking X-rated
film starred Marlon Brando and was directed by a major European
talent, Bernardo Bertolucci. Brando was nominated for a Best Actor
Oscar for his performance in ``Tango,'' his first role after ``The
Godfather.'' (In France, Bertolucci was prosecuted as a
pornographer for ``Last Tango.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spook Who Sat by the Door'' (1973) _ Ivan Dixon _ the
lovable Kinchloe from ``Hogan's Heroes'' _ directed an adaptation
of the Sam Greenlee novel about a token African-American CIA hire
who quits and uses agency information to start a revolution. It was
withdrawn from release by the studio after fears were raised that
it might stir up trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Warriors'' (1979) _ One of the most influential, and
unheralded, action pictures of the past 20 years caused riots in
several theaters during its run. Paramount Pictures snatched it out
of theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Temptation of Christ'' (1988) _ Nervousness keeps the
Blockbuster chain from stocking Martin Scorsese's controversial
depiction of Christ's imagining his last days as a man who settles
down and raises a family. The subject made its studio release a
rocky affair as well. Protesters camped at theaters playing ``Last
Temptation,'' freely admitting that they hadn't seen it and had no
interest in seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lolita'' (1998) _ Director Adrian Lyne's recent remake of
``Lolita,'' starring Jeremy Irons, is a film that every major
studio was afraid to distribute. It will eventually run on Showtime
_ and it will have theatrical distribution as well _ but none of
the major players wanted the taint of appearing to approve child
molestation. This anxiety makes one wonder whether the 1960 version
of Vladimir Nabokov's novel, directed by Stanley Kubrick, would
ever have been made in the current climate.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour,'' 1967-1969: Co-hosts Tom
and Dick Smothers, comic brothers with political bite, fought
censorship battles with CBS until the network eventually canceled
the variety show. Among the battles lost: Pete Seeger's performance
on the fall 1967 premiere of ``Waist Deep in the Big Muddy,'' a
song with anti-war overtones; Harry Belafonte singing in front of a
filmed montage of disturbances at the 1968 Democratic convention in
Chicago; and an interview with Dr. Benjamin Spock, who had been
convicted of aiding draft evaders. Eventually, CBS took the
then-unusual step of demanding to pre-screen upcoming shows. (This
is now common practice.) When Tom Smothers failed to deliver one
tape until a day before air time, CBS yanked the show and did not
broadcast it until three weeks later. (On that show, Joan Baez
dedicated a song to her husband, David Harris, then serving a jail
sentence for draft evasion. By then, Tom and Dick Smothers knew
they were gone.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Make Room for Daddy,'' 1950s: In one episode, Danny Thomas had
to refer to Sir Winston Churchill as a member of the British House
of Commons, instead of the usual ``member of Parliament'' because
one of his sponsors was a cigarette company that didn't want to
mention, even almost subliminally, a competing brand on the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Hallmark Hall of Fame,'' 1953: In the TV production of
George Bernard Shaw's ``Man and Superman,'' mothers are described
as dreadful harpies who sell their daughters in marriage to the
highest bidders. A man from the ad agency ordered the speech
killed. His argument? Mother's Day was a vital holiday in the
greeting-card business, and the show would antagonize every mom in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue,'' 1993: Bowing to ``family'' group protesters, WFAA
in Dallas/Fort Worth passes on the ABC cop drama ``NYPD Blue'' for
language, violence and nudity the station said would be offensive
to viewers. After a year, WFAA relented to protests from another
side _ those who wanted to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew ``Dice'' Clay, 1990: On the ``Arsenio Hall Show,'' the
comic sobbed when explaining ``the abuse'' received about his
comedy character, a bigoted jerk who felt that women were, at best,
``pigs'' and ``chopped meat.'' His ``Saturday Night Live''
appearance prompted ``SNL'' regular Nora Dunn and musical guest
Sinead O'Connor to refuse to perform. Through the criticism, Clay
metamorphosed into a mild-mannered family guy on a sitcom, which
failed. He has since returned to his tough ``Dice'' character, but
fans now see him as a pathetic sellout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing Sacred,'' 1997: ABC was praised for staying with this
controversial drama despite some Catholic organizations calling the
portrayal of the liberal priest ``anti-Catholic,'' not to mention a
program with a political agenda because the executive producers
were Jewish. But when the series shot an episode dealing with a gay
priest with AIDS, ABC refused to air the episode even as the series
went down in ratings flames.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
