<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSORSHIP-4thTake-TE     07-06 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSORSHIP-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: ratings flames. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   ``Love for Sale'' (1956) _ ABC radio banned the Billie Holiday
song because it deals with prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transfusion'' (1956) _ All three major radio networks (NBC,
ABC and CBS) banned the novelty tune by Dot and Diamond because of
its subject matter, blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   Various songs (1957) _ Rock 'n' roll is banned in Catholic
schools in Chicago; the rhythms are said to goad youngsters into
bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumble'' (1959) _ The famous Link Wray instrumental is banned
from stations around the country _ the title is thought to
encourage gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louie Louie'' (1964) _ The Kingsmen garage-rock classic comes
under fire from Indiana Gov. Matthew Welsh, who says it is
pornographic. Some stations stop playing it, but the song later
becomes a frat-party staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction'' (1965) _ Some radio stations
refuse to play the Rolling Stones song because of its sexually
suggestive content.
</P>
<P>
   Various Beatles songs (1966) _ After John Lennon's famous
comment that the band is bigger than Jesus Christ, some stations
stop playing the group's music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria'' (1966) _ Chicago station WLS quits playing the hit by
the Irish group Them due to the sexual overtones of the lyrics,
specifically the ``she comes in my room'' line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio'' (1970) _ Ohio Gov. James Rhodes orders stations not to
play the Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young tune after the deaths at
Kent State University. Few stations comply, and the song becomes a
huge counterculture anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow Submarine'' and ``Puff the Magic Dragon'' (1971) _ Both
the Beatles song and the children's tune are singled out by
Illinois legislators for their ``drug references.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical'' (1981) _ The Olivia Newton-John hit is dropped from
radio stations in Salt Lake City and Provo, Utah; the lyrics are
deemed unsuitable for the largely Mormon listening audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankenchrist'' CD (1987) _ Copies of this Dead Kennedys
record are seized and destroyed and band leader Jello Biafra is
accused of distributing pornography; the controversy involved the
record's artwork, which includes a work by H.R. Giger. Biafra is
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Nasty as They Wanna Be'' (1990) _ The 2 Live Crew record is
declared obscene by a district judge in Florida, and a store owner
who sold it is charged with obscenity. Three members of the group
(including leader Luther Campbell) are charged with obscenity in
connection with an adults-only club performance.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, two 2 Live Crew CDs, as well as recordings by
Ice-T and Eazy-E and several X-rated videos, are banned in Volusia
County, Fla., by a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is a Good Thing'' (1996) _ Lyrics in the Sheryl Crow song
(''Watch our children as they kill each other/With a gun they
bought at the Wal-Mart discount stores'') lead to the CD it's on,
``Sheryl Crow,'' being taken off the stores' shelves nationwide.
It's estimated that not having the CD available in the chain could
mean 400,000 fewer copies being sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smack My B---- Up'' (1997) _ Protests over the Prodigy song
lead to the CD it's on, ``The Fat of the Land,'' being pulled by
Kmart and Wal-Mart stores.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Verdi's ``Un ballo in maschera'' (A Masked Ball) (1858) _ After
an Italian revolutionary attempted to assassinate French Emperor
Napoleon III in 1858, this work _ based on the 18th-century
assassination of King Gustavus III of Sweden _ was banned in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   The tango (1912) _ Pope Pius X declared the tango a sin; the
Massachusetts Legislature agreed and made dancing the tango a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   German composers (1918) _ At the height of anti-German sentiment
during World War I, the New York Philharmonic banned music of
living German/Austrian composers, including Hindemith, Schoenberg
and Richard Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish composers (1933) _ Nazi Germany banned music by composers
of Jewish descent, as well as ``Negro jazz.'' Anything the Nazis
didn't like was labeled as ``Musical Bolshevism,'' which ultimately
included Hindemith, Stravinsky and other modern composers.
Ironically, the Nazis condemned two composers who represented the
ideal of Austro-German music: Mendelssohn and Mahler. The Nazis
went so far as to commission new music to Shakespeare's ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' from two composers of certified pure
Aryan descent, to replace the familiar, beloved but officially
disfavored music by Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner (1940s-present day) _ Richard Wagner is still banned by
the Israeli Philharmonic because of that composer's identification
with the Nazi cause (although he died long before the birth of
Adolf Hitler). The music of Richard Strauss, who held official
positions in the Nazi cultural establishment, was formerly banned
in Israel but has been introduced in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Child of Our Time'' (1941) _ This oratorio, by British
composer Michael Tippett, was written in sympathetic response to
the Nazis' persecution of the Jews, but was once banned in Israel
because it quotes African-American spirituals with references to
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suor Isabella'' (1982) _ It happens in Texas, too. This opera,
by Dallas-based composer Robert X. Rodriguez, is based on a classic
tale of a nun who brings a secret lover into the convent. A
performance by the San Antonio Symphony was canceled under pressure
from the Roman Catholic archbishop of that city.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
