<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAKS-COX     07-06 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News of Saks buy not exactly good news for Proffitt shareholders
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The steep price tag on the purchase of Saks Holdings
Inc. by Proffitt's Inc. worried some investors that the acquisitive
retailer is forgetting its bargain-buy strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham-based Proffitt's shares fell as much as 13 percent on
Monday after it agreed to buy retail icon Saks Fifth Avenue for
$2.99 billion in stock and assumed debt. That's about 11 times
Saks's estimated cash flow this year, richer than any of Proffitt's
recent purchases of regional department-store chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real happy about it,'' said John Cabell, portfolio
manager at USAA Investment Management, which owned 53,000 shares as
of March. ``There are a lot of small regional chains that I would
have liked to see them do instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's, the country's fourth-largest department store
operator, announced late Sunday it will swap 0.82 share, valued at
$33.36 at Thursday's closing price, for each Saks share _ a 15
percent premium to Saks's closing price of 29. It will also take on
about $890 million in debt. The transaction is expected to be
completed by the end of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's richest purchases before Saks were Carson Pirie Scott
and Parisian, which operates five stores in metro Atlanta.
Proffitt's operates 230 department stores and four furniture stores
in 24 states. The company had about $3.54 billion in sales last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Saks's mainstay business is its 56 department stores. It also
has eight Saks Fifth Avenue Resort Stores, seven Saks Fifth Avenue
Main Street stores and 40 Off 5th discount stores, including one at
North Georgia Premium Outlets in Dawsonville. Saks generated about
$2.19 billion in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Skittish investors had concerns about bringing together the
disparate personalities of toney Saks _ known for designer clothing
by Bill Blass, Chanel and Georgio Armani _ and Proffitt's chains
that market midpriced brands such as Dockers and Jones New York.
</P>
<P>
   Saks's only metro Atlanta department store is at Phipps Plaza,
where it will share the same roost with new corporate cousin
Parisian. But thanks to an ironclad Saks identity and plans to keep
top management intact, shoppers shouldn't see immediate impacts
from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, consumers may see differences to the extent that
Proffitt's chains learn the more sophisticated merchandising
strategies of Saks,'' said Arnold Aronson, managing director of
retail strategies at Kurt Salmon Associates and former Saks chief
executive and chairman. ``Saks gives them clout with manufacturers.
There's a new influence that can elevate the company, substantively
and psychologically.''
</P>
<P>
   Saks also is highly regarded for catering to its loyal shopper
base, which could rub off on Proffitt's stores, said Brenda
Gilpatrick, an Atlanta-based retail marketing consultant. ``Atlanta
consumers will probably see benefits at Parisian, which could
become a stronger store.''
</P>
<P>
   New merchandising savvy at Proffitt's could manifest itself in
stronger private labels as well, Aronson said.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit is that Proffitt's, a dominant regional player,
becomes a national company that can better compete against chains
run by rivals like Federated Department Stores Inc., May Department
Stores Co. and Dillard's Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proffitt's had a good name but not national recognition.
People in San Francisco aren't asking, `When is a Parisian coming
here?' '' said Frederick Marx, a retail consultant in Farmington
Hills, Mich. ``Proffitt's has a real growth vehicle now because
they can hitch the name and identity with Saks and cover North
America _ and probably the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's will change its name to Saks Inc. and move its
headquarters from Alcoa, Tenn. to Birmingham, where the Parisian
chain is based. The merged company will be headed by Proffitt's
Chairman and Chief Executive R. Brad Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The Saks Fifth Avenue chain will become a New York-based
subsidiary that will be managed by Saks Chairman and Chief
Executive Philip Miller and Vice Chairman and Chief Operating
Officer Brian Kendrick.
</P>
<P>
   As with previous acquisitions, Proffitt's will integrate the
inventory, distribution and other daily operations. With Saks, the
companies expect to save about $10 million to $12 million this
year, $60 million to $70 million next year and $75 million to $85
million in 2000 on advertising, property and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Saks likely won't add to Proffitt's earnings as much as or as
quickly as previous acquisitions, investors said. The purchase will
add 1 cent to 2 cents a share to earnings by year-end, according to
Proffitt's, which forecast profit of about 96 cents a share for the
fiscal fourth quarter ending Jan. 30, 1999, and $1.66 for the year.
Next year, it will add about 3 cents to 5 cents a share, resulting
in annual earnings of $2.20 a share. Proffitt's will issue also
about 52.5 million shares for the transaction, adding to the 89.7
million shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the number crunching, though, is a selling point less
quantifiable but still notable for Proffitt's. ``They have some
bragging rights now because they got the pick of the litter,'' Marx
said. ``Another player is coming out of the South, which shows that
not everything (retail) happens on the coasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
