<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIMESTOPPER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PATCH NEIGHBORHOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Alvin Moses is running out of new bullet holes
around his central Phoenix home, and he credits a new
crime-fighting approach by Phoenix police that targets bad places
as much as bad people.
</P>
<P>
   Life has become a lot more peaceful, he said, since officers
started focusing less on arresting individual thugs and more on
attacking the places from which they dealt drugs and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, these three bullet holes in my house, those in my fence
. . . all were done during a two- or three-year period, which ended
last summer,'' said Moses, 72, standing in front of his home in
west-central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the police hit those apartments, the trouble pretty much
stopped,'' he said. ``And the shooting pretty much stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police agree so much that they're expanding their use of
a nationally recognized crime-fighting strategy that they credit
with helping reduce crime in Moses' and other troubled
neighborhoods by as much as one-third.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the ``broken windows'' approach, and many law
enforcement experts call it the key to saving crime-ridden
neighborhoods and preserving those threatened with decline.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Phoenix police and other city agencies took tough
action against landlords who owned an apartment complex and a small
mobile home park _ both infamous for harboring criminals _ near
Moses' home.
</P>
<P>
   The police are so happy with the success of the strategy that
they are expanding the program citywide. And Arizona lawmen in in
Mesa, Tempe and the Maricopa County Sheriff's Office are studying
the approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix City Council recently approved five more detectives
for full-time ``crime abatement'' duties, which include
investigating ``nuisance'' properties blighting neighborhoods with
slumlike or crime-ridden conditions.
</P>
<P>
   South Mountain Precinct Cmdr. Mike McCort and Lt. Suzy Parra
said that, in many crime-plagued neighborhoods, a few properties,
typically rundown rentals, are host to the majority of offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is, you close down the places that are wrecking
neighborhoods, the places with broken windows, couches and old cars
out in front, with crime going on inside and out, and you cut down
on crime throughout the neighborhood,'' Parra said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``broken windows'' phrase comes from a 1982 magazine article
in which criminologists George Kelling and James Q. Wilson argued
that allowing one broken window in a neighborhood home to go
unrepaired meant another would soon be broken. And another. Then an
old couch would appear on a corner, a slum dwelling would
eventually evolve and crime would surely follow.
</P>
<P>
   Stop the broken windows, eliminate the slum properties and crime
decreases, the argument goes.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the theory in the New York City Police Department
credit that city's dramatic drop in crime during the past five
years to the ``broken windows'' approach. In Phoenix, McCort and
Parra decided to develop a program that would target problem
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Police worked with neighbors to learn which properties were the
centers of trouble. The officers then worked with the properties'
landlords to stop the crime and clean up blight.
</P>
<P>
   If the landlord refused to cooperate, legal action would be
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concept we've proved works, with just one detective and
one officer doing it,'' Parra said. ``Now the idea is to have more
detectives and officers doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Arizona Legislature passed a law that makes
knowingly allowing criminal activity continue on one's property a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   In September of that year, Wallace Dossie, 60, was the first
person to plead guilty to ``failing to abate a crime'' at his West
Monroe Street property that Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley
called a crack house.
</P>
<P>
   Police had long known that some properties seemed the center of
a neighborhood's problems, Parra said, but their response had been
saturation patrols, search warrants, ``zero tolerance'' programs
and other traditional policing methods.
</P>
<P>
   But such efforts often simply displaced the problems, McCort
said. And when an individual criminal was identified and arrested,
the activity was not curbed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
