<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PEONY-2TAKES-NY     07-06 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE RIGHT TO PERFORM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With much of Tibetan culture put at risk by actions of the
Chinese government, it may seem petty and impertinent to fret about
the fate of Chinese opera; even more, about one particular corner
of it. But Chinese opera, which has long been the central
manifestation of the performing arts in China, deftly combining
music, drama, poetry, dance, design and acrobatics, is waning. And
Kunqu opera, the revered style that began in Kunshan, near
Shanghai, in the 14th century and gave birth to so many later
varieties, including the dominant Peking opera, appears to be
dying. Really dying, not just wallowing in confusion, as so much of
Western classical music is doing.
</P>
<P>
   That sober reality was hard to credit for a recent visitor to
Shanghai, seeing the remarkable talent, energy, imagination and
love being lavished on rehearsals for the ground-breaking
production of the Kunqu classic ``The Peony Pavilion'' that was to
have formed the crown jewel of the Lincoln Center Festival, which
opens Tuesday evening. As Chen Shi-Zheng, the gifted American
director now at the center of a storm, put the mostly young
performers of the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company through their paces,
the gorgeous costumes arrived bit by bit, handmade in classic
fashion by elderly seamstresses in nearby Suzhou, the site of a
Kunqu museum. Despite the dinginess of the surroundings, on the
fifth floor of a municipal building in the old French quarter of
Shanghai, the process seemed one of growth and vitality.
</P>
<P>
   But it is suddenly easier to comprehend the dire predictions now
that the Shanghai Municipal Bureau of Culture has at the last
minute denied the company permission to travel to New York. And it
seems clear that the final, fatal blows to Kunqu are being
delivered by the very people who proclaim themselves its
protectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a precious piece of Chinese culture,'' Ma Bomin, the
director of the bureau, rightly says of ``The Peony Pavilion,''
written by Tang Xianzu in 1598 and considered one of the great
masterpieces of Chinese literature. Yet that epic drama lay mostly
unperformed for centuries, typically represented by an occasional
presentation of one or two of the most famous of its 55 scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for the Lincoln Center production, which was to have
presented the work at its full 20-hour length, seemingly for the
first time in at least three centuries, came not from China but
from an American, John Rockwell, when he was the director of the
Lincoln Center Festival. Rockwell, who is now the editor of the
Arts and Leisure section of The New York Times, is expert in
Wagnerian opera, and his curiosity about ``The Peony Pavilion'' led
him to conceive the ``Ming Ring,'' as he called it: a presentation
of the complete work in six parts, over six nights or three days.
He was also fascinated by the possibility of applying Western
methods of early-music research and notions of ``authentic''
interpretation to this repertory, and he enlisted Chen, who has
lived in New York since he left his native China in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Here, whatever its origins, was a prime opportunity to inject
new life into Kunqu by giving it unprecedented international
exposure. The production was to be showcased not only in New York
but also at festivals in Paris, Sydney and Hong Kong, and probably
released on audio and video. And this at a time when another
version of ``The Peony Pavilion,'' directed by Peter Sellars in a
truncated and Westernized form, is traveling the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chen's production has been derailed by Ms. Ma, who deemed it
unworthy to represent Kunqu tradition and, significantly, modern
China to the world. No matter that the largely oral tradition has
itself strayed far from whatever Kunqu may originally have been. It
is as if someone had been able to decree early in this century that
Handel's ``Messiah'' should be performed only as it had emerged
from Victorian England, with bloated chorus and orchestra and
perhaps even a few of Thomas Beecham's bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, one issue was the brief appearance of a prop, a
chamber pot, which was alleged to make China appear backward. Yet
as Chen points out, during the Song dynasty, in which the opera is
set, or even the Ming, in which it was written, a chamber pot would
have been anything but backward.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of four scenes the bureau took issue with in a
recent preview. In another, Chen was accused of injecting
superstition by staging a funeral march for the heroine and burning
effigies, in line with Chinese folk tradition. In the two other
scenes, the material objected to _ the ``pornography'' of the scene
in which Sister Stone tells why, anatomically, she could only be a
virgin, and the mocking treatment of a drunken Tartar general _
came directly from the classic text.
</P>
<P>
   After Chen expressed a willingness to make adjustments, the
bureau's censors took the production back into rehearsal and
demanded changes in six more scenes. Even then, Chen said on Friday
on his return to New York, ``if that would get approval for the
performers to leave, I would have done it.'' But when Ms. Ma walked
out on the rehearsal she attended, it became apparent that no
amount of compromise would suffice to liberate the production.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested that the real reason for refusing to permit
the company to travel was a fear of defections. Indeed, the last
time this company visited the United States _ Los Angeles, in 1989
_ eight of the 20 members defected. Several are part of the Kunqu
Society in New York. Those who stayed with the company are now the
wise old masters on whom Chen, whose training was largely in other
forms of Chinese opera, relied for the niceties of Kunqu. ``The
practitioners are the real experts,'' he said, dismissing the
``experts'' who found his work wanting.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the New York trip, the bureau obtained signed
affidavits from the performers' families promising that if an
individual did not return, the family would forfeit $12,000, no
small amount by Chinese standards.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the ultimate reasons for detaining the production and
however great the loss for Western audiences, the real damage has
occurred in China. Eight months of painstaking rehearsal and the
exquisite work of innumerable craftsmen have evidently gone for
naught, and brilliant young performers have been denied brighter
futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their spirits are totally broken down,'' Chen said. If so, it
is a calamity for those were clearly strong and vibrant spirits,
well suited to the lively characters they were to play.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Peony Pavilion,'' Du Liniang, the susceptible teen-age
heroine, finds a dashing lover in a dream and pines to her death
for lack of the reality. But she is resurrected when the embodiment
of that lover, Liu Mengmei, a young scholar, discovers her portrait
and reciprocates her love. Though the work is set in the Song
dynasty (960-1279), its concerns relate at least as much to Tang
Xianzu's era, as Ben Wang, a Kunqu expert in New York, explained in
a captivating series of lectures at the China Institute in
connection with the Lincoln Center Festival. The playwright was
especially intent on espousing freedom and initiative in his
heroine at a time when Neo-Confucianism found young women suited
only to idleness and subservience.
</P>
<P>
   Qian Yi, lovely in a shy and understated way at 22, was to have
played Beautiful Du, as the name can be translated. Zhang Jun, tall
and charismatic at 23, was to have played Mengmei. Both were
members of the last class to have graduated from the Shanghai Kunqu
Opera School: possibly the last class ever. In 1986, they were
among the 60 students accepted from 20,000 applicants for the
eight-year program. When the school recruited for the next class,
recently, there were not enough applicants to form one.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in all forms of Chinese opera has eroded in the last
decade under a wave of American pop culture and Western arts,
including opera. Kunqu, the most refined of the 360 or so types of
Chinese opera, has been especially hard hit. Kunqu melody grows
directly out of the pitch characteristics of Chinese speech, with
its four tones: high, low, rising and falling. And just as speech
is elevated to song, movement is elevated to dance, with special
significance given to curving motion, since, for the Chinese, the
circle represents the perfect union of opposites, the yin and the
yang.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, parents limited by national social policy to
producing a single child are reluctant to consign that child to so
rarefied and uncertain an enterprise. The Shanghai company is one
of six Kunqu troupes surviving in China, and performances are
infrequent and ill attended. The performers are paid less than $100
a month.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Qian and Zhang, obviously the rising stars in the
field, were asked what professional opportunities might await them
after ``The Peony Pavilion,'' neither professed to have any idea.
Both are taking night courses in Chinese cultural administration as
a hedge against unemployment, and Zhang has already made headway as
a pop performer, where prospects are better.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty members of their class have already left the company, but
the rest are an ebullient lot, as adept at belting out choruses as
at tumbling in the battle scenes and even performing acrobatics on
stilts. They work under the continuing tutelage of performers twice
their age, for a generation was lost to Chinese opera during the
Cultural Revolution, when performances were banned. Chen, now 35,
was among the first to emerge after the revolution ended, in 1976.
The members of the company are mostly in their 20s or 50s.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this fragile ecosystem that Ms. Ma took her draconian
action to ``protect'' Kunqu from Chen's incursions. And what did
those incursions finally amount to? Chiefly, attempts to reimagine
the spirit of Kunqu when ``The Peony Pavilion'' was new, before
interpretations and costumes took on their present stiffness.
Within conventions still highly stylized, he wanted a hint of
naturalism.
</P>
<P>
   He also wanted to show the West Chinese folk tradition and, he
said, ``the best of China.'' Thus, not only the hundreds of
glorious costumes but also a magnificent wooden set, modeled after
the famous gardens of Suzhou and the outdoor theater in the museum.
</P>
<P>
   That Chen was able to achieve all of this on a budget of
$500,000 attests to the modest cost of the highest-quality
craftsmanship in China and also to his abilities as producer as
well as director. With cell phone at the ready, he fairly reveled
in detail during those Shanghai rehearsals, fielding crises like
the call from the Shanghai Zoo informing him that it would not
furnish songbirds for the preview performance for fear that the
clangorous Chinese percussion instruments might induce
psychological problems; he would instead have to find birds inured
to street noise.
</P>
<P>
   This splendid production would have established Chen as a star.
On the basis of the Shanghai preview, Le Monde in Paris has already
called it ``one of the major cultural events of the end of the 20th
century.'' No matter; Chen is resourceful enough that he will find
his way another time. One can only wish the same for those
wonderful performers tossed aside back in Shanghai, one of them,
Zhang, wearing the new suit he bought for New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
