<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S BARBARIC DRESS CODE FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: SIDEBAR accompanies IRAN-TOURISTS)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GAIL BENSINGER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For female travelers in Iran, the biggest issue is hijab, the
dress code that requires women to wear dark, shapeless garments and
to cover their hair.
</P>
<P>
   For Western women used to going bare-headed, the sheer
discomfort of fabric around necks and chins _ especially when it's
hot, as it frequently is in Iran _ is relentless.
</P>
<P>
   The most restrictive form of hijab is the chador, the
all-encompassing dark robe that covers a woman from head to toe,
held closed by a hand under the chin or by the teeth if she has her
arms full of children and packages. Such a garment declares a
woman's adherence to the strictest laws of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   For a few especially holy sites, such as the compound that
houses the shrine of the Imam Reza in Mashhad or the mosque of
Shah-E Cheragh in Shiraz, our Iranian tour guide lent us huge,
unwieldy squares of dark printed fabric, leading one of our number
to describe us as a procession of puddings.
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat more relaxed form of hijab is a head-scarf and
manteau, a loose, long overcoat that goes down to mid-shin, even in
summer. Such garments offer more opportunity for stylishness _ and
two free hands, not to mention pockets. The scarves were often
paisley or with flower prints, and women in manteaus tended to wear
them atop fashionable shoes and occasionally jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Dislike of the dress code is one of the most contentious issues
in this politically charged country, where the deposed shah forbade
chadors and the new theocratic rules make hijab mandatory. The most
daring women allow hair and jewelry to peek out from behind scarves
and they wear makeup. When we got on the plane to leave, virtually
all of the Iranian women shed their scarves and made up their
faces, even before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   For foreigners, the rules are a bit more relaxed. We wore
raincoats, loose-fitting jackets or newly purchased manteaus with
scarves, or occasionally just baggy shirts and dark pants or long
skirts. On inter-city bus rides, we shed our scarves until we
reached the various checkpoints, when our English-speaking guide
would announce a ``scarf alert'' and we would scramble to
re-assemble our headgear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
