<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TANGLEWOOD-REVI     07-06 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TANGLEWOOD-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGLEWOOD: STARTING SEASON WITH SERIOUS BUSINESS IN IDYLLIC
SETTING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ It was another eventful off-season at Tanglewood
here, with more contention as to the direction of the Tanglewood
Music Center and changes in its administration. All of that will
take time to shake down and sort out.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Boston Symphony Orchestra opened its own
season on Friday evening and Sunday afternoon, and beautiful
weather for those concerts could lull a listener into thinking, for
the moment, that Tanglewood was its old idyllic self.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the programs set out to lull. As festival fare goes,
they were uncompromising, even challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Seiji Ozawa set the tone for a weekend of serious choral music
on Friday, conducting Berlioz's ``Damnation of Faust,'' a big,
unwieldy work of the sort in which he often excels. Here, the piece
was slow to come together.
</P>
<P>
   Some murky harmonies too weird even for Berlioz in the lower
woodwinds and some frayed edges in the excellent Tanglewood
Festival Chorus suggested under-rehearsal. And in this open space,
Vinson Cole's familiar portrayal of the title role lacked the
claustrophobic immediacy it had a few months ago in a semistaged
performance with the Brooklyn Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the work caught fire only in the drinking
scene, with David Wilson-Johnson providing an excellent lead as
Brander and the men of the chorus contributing fine woozy slides.
The second half proved altogether more compelling, thanks largely
to the steady presence of Frederica von Stade as Marguerite.
Wonderful in her big numbers, she drew like efforts from members of
the orchestra: Steven Ansell, the principal violist, in ``The King
of Thule'' and, especially, Robert Sheena, the English hornist, in
the Romance.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Rouillon seemed slightly miscast as Mephistopheles,
producing beautiful sounds but lacking the needed plangency at the
bottom and any sense of real menace. Ozawa and the orchestra and
chorus all hit their stride in ``The Ride to the Abyss'' and
``Pandemonium,'' producing the kind of excitement one might have
hoped for throughout.
</P>
<P>
   In Bernstein's brief ``Chichester Psalms,'' on Sunday, they did
provide it throughout. Derek Lee Ragin, a countertenor, took the
part of the boy soprano more than satisfactorily, yet the role lost
some of its vulnerability. The concluding chorale was especially
fetching, accompanied only by a bird, which seemed all too eager to
spell the orchestra. Here, Ozawa was substituting for Robert Shaw,
who had canceled because of illness. Other conductors picked up the
other works.
</P>
<P>
   John Oliver, the conductor of the chorus, led Beethoven's Mass
in C briskly and sometimes eventfully. He did not always make a
convincing case for his favored choral setup, with the vocal ranges
shuffled, missing the knifelike clarity needed when a melodic voice
dips or rises a semitone or suspends a dissonance. The fugues
sorted themselves out nicely, however, and made a big impact. The
vocal soloists _ Dominique Labelle, Marietta Simpson, Richard
Clement and Wilson-Johnson _ were generally fine.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Arming, the young cover conductor for the orchestra's
Tanglewood concerts, led Brahms' ``Nanie'' expansively, making the
most of his moment. Although this is not an easy piece with which
to make an effect, everything was pretty much in place, and the
chorus, especially, seemed intent on lending moral support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
