<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICA FETE: MUSICAL IDEAS FROM AFAR
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For African pop musicians, using ideas from other
places has never been a tough decision. Creative assimilation is
part of both the pop process and African tradition. The real
questions are how to use borrowed materials, and how much. Africa
Fete, the package tour that brings African musicians to American
audiences, presented four distinct answers _ from Mali, Senegal,
Somalia and Congo _ at Central Park Summerstage on Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Salif Keita, from Mali, and Cheikh Lo, from Senegal, are both
rooted in the West African griot tradition, with songs that set
incantatory, Islamic-tinged vocals above circular patterns and runs
played on the kora (harp-guitar). Keita's new band, Wanda, mixes
musicians from Mali and New York, and it sets out to mesh African
rock and American funk, wandering musical frontiers with a reckless
enthusiasm. Keita has been concocting African hybrids since the
1980's, but Wanda is his rawest, most exploratory music yet.
</P>
<P>
   The band includes a kora player, Toumani Diabate, alongside two
guitarists steeped in funk and jazz, and it turned its songs into
jams, riding terse vamps wherever they led. There were ethereal,
hypnotic passages dominated by the kora, with intricate patterns of
finger picking; there were stretches where modal chords turned into
jazz harmonies, as Ousmane Kouyate played dizzyingly fast guitar
leads; there was down-and-dirty funk, with the guitarist Freddie
Bryant attached to his wah-wah pedal. And Keita, whose voice has
always been riveting, responded to the band's forays with
heightened fervor, eager to rise above boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Lo maintains an established way of merging griot music and rock;
his band plays Senegalese mbalax, brisk dance music with high
guitar lines and the sputtering cross rhythms of a talking drum.
His international touches included the inevitable reggae tune (sung
in French) and one song with a flamenco tinge, but most of the
songs followed the worthy example of Youssou N'Dour, who produced
Lo's album ``Ne La Thiass'' (World Circuit/Nonesuch). Lo proffered
heartfelt messages above music that was transparent yet propulsive.
</P>
<P>
   Maryam Mursal was Somalia's first female pop star before she
fled its civil war, and she now sings an exile's songs, lamenting
her country's misery and wishing for peace. Her voice is deep and
gutsy, an alto filled with sorrow and determination; her songs have
strong Arab influences, but they are catchy in Western ways, with
forthright melodies that start on the downbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Her band, from Denmark, underlines the hand-drum beat with a
rock rhythm section and connects the songs to current dance music,
using samples of horn sections and pulsating synthesized bass
lines. Diligently recreating the arrangements from Mursal's album
``The Journey'' (Real World), the band was merely competent; its
bass player kept upstaging Mursal. But her voice and songs were
indomitable.
</P>
<P>
   Papa Wemba, from Congo, has one of the most sympathetic voices
in the world, a tenor croon that can take on a penetrating power
without losing any of its sweetness. His new band, Molokai, is his
most Westernized group yet, placing his voice amid the
slow-building dramas of European and American-style pop ballads, as
if he has heard too many Peter Gabriel albums.
</P>
<P>
   Breathy synthesizer chords hovered behind him. His guitarists
played aggressive lead lines. Two women harmonized and sometimes
sang in English, with lyrics like ``Hear the children cry.'' The
songs were flawlessly performed and utterly disheartening as they
embraced Western cliches.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the set, when Papa Wemba sang his older Congolese
dance tunes, with their buoyant rumba beat and gleaming guitars,
the music suddenly sounded vital again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
