<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK HYPE ON INTERNET SNAGS UNWARY INVES TORS 
</HEADLINE>
 OIL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG ANDERSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - The Internet is a valuable tool for private
investors, allowing them access to information once reserved
strictly for brokers and big-stakes players.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more, cyberspace has become a playground for spin
doctors and snake-oil salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, online investors need to face the oncoming wave of
stock solicitations with a high degree of Web-surfer skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing an explosion of hype and promotion of
small-company stocks on the Internet,'' said Marc Beauchamp,
communications director for the North American Securities
Administration Association.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Web is so vast and unregulated, lawmakers have a
tough time keeping up with law-breakers. Unfortunately, many people
are in awe of new technology, and they assume everything they read
online is the gospel truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is being sucked in more than we hoped they would,''
said Michael Burton, director of securities for the Arizona
Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   One common method of reaching undiscriminating investors is
``spamming.''
</P>
<P>
   Spamming is the mass dissemination of unsolicited e-mail, a
highly criticized means of pitching sales. Receiving a spam e-mail
is tantamount to getting a cold call from telemarketers, except
that thousands of messages can be sent out for mere pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's spams were mainly come-ons for X-rated Web sites.
This year, it's penny stocks, small investment opportunities and
credit offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess commerce is replacing the world's oldest profession,''
Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Another common way in which unscrupulous people push stocks is
to enter online financial chat rooms and give ``friendly advice''
about how fast a company is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Since users can choose any name they wish, chat room
communication is essentially anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   And it's free.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the commission tries to stop bogus investment
solicitations when it can, but exponential growth of new Web sites,
free speech issues and jurisdictional problems are outstripping
regulators' ability to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-defense is really the way to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Burton said state and federal agencies are doing what
they can to restrict Internet investment offers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the California Corporations Commission ordered 10
companies to either comply with state securities requirements or
stop offering investment opportunities on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One company on the list is Eventemp Corp., a fledgling
Scottsdale, Ariz., firm that is developing a system to preheat or
precool a car via a remote pager.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Crandall, an attorney in the California commission's
enforcement division, said he followed up on some spam e-mails and
Internet press releases touting Eventemp as a great investment
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The spams contained lines such as: ``Analysts say look for
Eventemp to go as high as $10 by March 1. . . . Analysts predict
that stock could shoot to $6 in the next few days. . . . Get in
while there is still time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Schroeder, Eventemp's president and chief executive
officer, said he was not aware of the spamming until he started
receiving complaints about it.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail campaign ignited a firestorm of online criticism
against Eventemp, spearheaded by Rich Hilgersom, an information
systems analyst from Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Hilgersom said he had received one spam too many when the
Eventemp message landed in his e-mail box.
</P>
<P>
   After doing some research, Hilgersom constructed a Web page
devoted entirely to Eventemp, criticizing the company and its
methods of promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said Eventemp hired Sloane Fitzgerald Inc., a public
relations firm in New York City, to promote the company's product
and was not responsible for the e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said he terminated relations with the firm after
learning of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The phone number for Sloane Fitzgerald, also ordered by the
California Corporations Commission to qualify in California or stop
making investment offers, has been disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall said some online press releases contained false or
misleading statements about Eventemp.
</P>
<P>
   One release announced that Eventemp had signed up Don Massey
Cadillac, a Plymouth, Mich., dealership, ``to purchase and sell our
new product line.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Massey, used car manager at Massey's Plymouth location,
said representatives from Eventemp had promised to send
demonstration units of their air-conditioning system but never
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They promised a product and never showed up,'' Massey said.
``We don't carry it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said criticism Eventemp has received probably caused
the car dealership to deny it ever made the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They backed off. Wouldn't you?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventemp stock, which trades on the largely unregulated OTC
Bulletin Board, peaked at 4 7/8 in early February, at the height of
the PR blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The stock now sits at 1 1/2 with very little activity.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said criticism of Eventemp is to blame for the
plummeting stock value, and he is angry at those who blasted his
company on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand how there can be no accountability for
people on the Internet,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
By following these basic guidelines, Internet users can greatly
reduce their chances of being taken in by investment scams:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spamming is seldom done by reputable companies and should be
reported to your Internet provider, as it usually violates Web
service agreements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not judge a company by how flashy its Web page is. Anyone
can construct a site with fancy graphics and animation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be skeptical of ``friendly'' people offering stock advice in
chat rooms. They could have ulterior motives _ including taking
your money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Before investing, do a little research. Check out the
company's track record with state authorities. The Better Business
Bureau may have a complaint record for the company, although lack
of such a record does not mean the business is reputable. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
