</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIAZZA-THECALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Piazza still fuming over 'ridiculous call'
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denver _ With a bandage on his right thigh covering a gash
caused by Michael Tucker's cleat, Mike Piazza leaned against a wall
Monday and had this message for the Braves right fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was an illegal slide,'' the Mets catcher
said, ``but I'd call it an unethical one.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, starting behind the plate in tonight's All-Star Game, is
still upset about what happened Sunday at Turner Field when Tucker
came sliding across the plate with the winning run in the 11th
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The ball had been hit to short left field, and the Mets appeared
to nail Tucker. Bernard Gilkey's throw to the plate was on target,
and Piazza blocked the plate and held the ball closely to his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   But home-plate umpire Angel Hernandez thought otherwise, setting
off a furious argument from the Mets. Both reliever John Franco and
manager Bobby Valentine bumped Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, once he realized that Tucker had been called safe, also
went crazy, arguing with the umpire and spiking the baseball. A day
later, he was still talking about the play _ and whether Tucker's
slide was legal. Replays clearly show Tucker's right foot up in the
air, heading for Piazza's chest.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball rules don't cover details of sliding or whether a
certain style is illegal. For instance, a player cannot slide out
of the basepaths to break up a double play or beyond the bag. But
nowhere in the rulebook does it say a player cannot slide with his
feet up. However, it's an unwritten rule among players.
</P>
<P>
   But Braves third baseman Chipper Jones said, ``If I thought
Michael did something wrong on that slide, I would have said
something to him. But what does the catcher expect? He had the
plate blocked. It was a just an aggressive play by Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, National League president Leonard Coleman said Monday
that he will wait until after the All-Star Game to review the
incident. Fines and even suspensions could be handed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (Coleman) takes into account what the situation was,''
Piazza said. ``It was a very emotional game for us, and it was a
ridiculous call. And I don't think anything was done out of malice.
I think we were just trying to talk to him, and he was walking off
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
