<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Tuesday, July 7. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CRIMESTOPPER (Phoenix) - Alvin Moses says Phoenix's new
crime-fighting approach has worked in his neighborhood. Since
police stopped arresting drug dealers, gang members, and armed
robbers one-at-a-time and attacked the dens from which they dealt
death and dope, life has become a lot more peaceful. Police say
that, in fact, crime has gone down 31 percent in three central
Phoenix neighborhoods where they fought crime by taking a tough
stance against the apartments from which the crime emanated. It's
part of a nationwide crime-fighting stragegy. By BILL HERMANN.
Story rescheduled from earlier, moved in the ``A'' cateogry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIGHTING BULLS (Trincheras, Sonora, Mexico) _ The spindly bull
calves leave the womb with their legs wobbly but their hearts
strong. And their spirit bred for generations to put the hurt on
human bodies. Which is exactly the way Dr. Adrian Ortega Fernandez
likes it on his sprawling ranch in the desert of northern Sonora.
This is where he raises ``pura sangre'' _ full blood _ bulls of
Iberian fighting ancestry that are the stars of northern Mexico's
resurgent bullfighting industry. By MARK SHAFFER. Story moved in
the ``A'' and ``S'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SNAKEOIL (Undated) - The Internet is a valuable tool for private
investors, allowing them access to information once reserved
strictly for brokers and big-stakes players. But more and more,
cyberspace has become a playground for spin doctors and snakeoil
salesmen, requiring a new degree of Web-surfer skepticism. By CRAIG
ANDERSON. Story moved in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RESTLESS-BAND (Undated) - When country supergroup Restless Heart
quietly stopped beating in 1994, most of the members went off to
other musical ventures. When the band was on the road, few groups
could touch Restless Heart. The quintet created crystal harmonies
that were almost frighteningly pure. Now it's back. The group has
out a greatest-hits disc that features three just-recorded songs.
The first single, ``No End to This Road,'' is rapidly moving its
way up the chart. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E``
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
