<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      07-06 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quiet Days in Paris
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ There has been a sharp falloff in the number of
well-known designers staging men's wear shows in Paris this season.
Among those who had presentations last season and did not show this
past week are Walter van Beirendonck, Emanuel Ungaro, Ozwald
Boateng, Claude Montana, Eric Bergere and Givenchy. Issey Miyake
and Jean Paul Gaultier both opened their collections in Milan,
Italy, instead of Paris, though Gaultier also presented his line
here.
</P>
<P>
   Gaultier has his collections made in Italy and wanted to be
closer to the production. Designers also want maximum exposure, and
by the time the caravan of retailers and fashion media hits Paris,
its numbers have dwindled. Gene Pressman, a co-chairman of Barneys
New York, was the lone senior retailer in Paris. Michael Gould,
chairman of Bloomingdale's, and Stephen Elkin, chairman of Bergdorf
Goodman, left after Milan. This development does not concern the
Chambre Syndicale, the French organizing body for the shows. The
lull is temporary, said Denise Dubois, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Some designers stayed away because they were afraid the World
Cup would make it difficult to secure rooms, Ms. Dubois said,
adding, ``We have nothing to be worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   New Clothes in the Louvre
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Musee de la Mode et du Textile at the Louvre, the
Paris equivalent of New York's Costume Institute at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, will begin a series of twice-a-year
exhibitions that will highlight current commercial fashion. The
first installation of the unusual program, called ``Le Plus de la
Mode'' (``The Height of Fashion''), will run from July 22 through
the first week of September. It will feature about 30 outfits drawn
from the men's and women's collections currently in stores, said
Pamela Golbin, a curator. They will be chosen by the museum's staff
and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to assure the museum a steady supply of clothing for
its archives and to strengthen relationships with the fashion
community, Ms. Golbin said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seems an odd course for a museum to embark upon, but it
should have intriguing results. What constitutes a museum piece
will be contrasted with the requirements of commercial fashion.
``We're here to show not only a garment as clothing to be worn, but
also as an identity to itself, and as a social object,'' Ms. Golbin
said. ``Fashion houses and stores have one object in mind: How they
can sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Golbin, though, will be assessing a garment's importance on
esthetics, technical innovation and quality, and social relevance.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary but Entertaining
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Diffusion, or secondary, collections by definition do
not break ground and are less conceptual than top lines. But
designers insist on giving their secondary lines runway shows, and
they go to great lengths to engage guests.
</P>
<P>
   For her Versus show last week in Milan, Donatella Versace
offered a winning, loose-fitting casual take for the young in batik
pants, overalls and pink shirts. She also offered entertainment _
British singers Jimmy Ray and Catatonia _ and a runway-worthy
entrance by Whitney Houston, trailed to her front-row seat by six
aides-de-camp.
</P>
<P>
   At Emporio Armani, Giorgio Armani created a kind of theater
without walls. More than half the audience was seated in
traditional theater style, in front of the proscenium, looking up
to the stage, which was to be the runway. The remainder of the
guests were seated on the stage on bleachers, making them part of
the show. The likes of Arnold Schwarzenegger and Maria Shriver were
thus forced at least to look as if they were paying attention to
the more than 100 outfits that came down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Gianfranco Ferre's theatrics for GFF had the audience sitting
around a vast public pool and models in sheer aqueous-colored
sportswear and water shoes appearing to walk on water _ actually
stepping across a boardwalk suspended below the water's surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
