<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2610 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE07COX     07-06 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE07COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON MOVES TO RAISE MEDICARE SUPPORT TO LOW-INCOME ELDERLY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton launched a new effort Monday to
inform up to 3.9 million Americans that they are entitled to
federal assistance in paying for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's action, announced at a brief news conference in the
Rose Garden, came in response to a report by Families USA, a
non-partisan health advocacy group, that estimated between 3.3
million and 3.9 million low-income elderly do not take advantage of
federal programs that pay Medicare premiums, and in some cases
deductibles and copayments as well.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, which Families USA had scheduled to release
Tuesday, it found that an estimated $1.7 billion to $2 billion was
improperly being deducted from the Social Security checks of
low-income elderly to pay for Medicare premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The federal effort to reach those eligible for the programs will
include special mailings coordinated by the Social Security
Administration _ which deducts the $43.80 monthly Medicare premium
_ and the Department of Health and Human Services, which
administers Medicare for 38 million elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, case workers, federal and state field offices and
the Internet will all be used to help publicize the programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through this effort, hundreds of thousands of older and
disabled low-income Americans will receive more affordable health
care without any new congressional action,'' Clinton said. ``This
is a duty we owe our parents and our fellow citizens, and we should
honor it. It's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pollack, executive director of Families USA, who joined
Clinton in the Rose Garden, hailed the announcement as an
initiative that could benefit millions of Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steps outlined today by the president will go a long way
to ensuring that low-income Medicare beneficiaries will have a much
better chance to get their Medicare premiums subsidized so that
their meager Social Security checks are no longer deducted,''
Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Congress created two programs to help low-income
elderly beneficiaries pay their Medicare Part B premium, which
covers doctors bills and related services. The programs are
administered through the federal-state Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   One program, known as Qualified Medicare Beneficiaries (QMBs),
covers beneficiaries with incomes at or below the poverty level for
the elderly: $8,292 for an individual and $11,100 for a couple. It
covers the monthly premium as well as deductibles and copayments.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1.9 million to 2.4 million beneficiaries who
qualify for the program nationally do not participate in it, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The other program, known as Specified Low-Income Medicare
Beneficiaries
</P>
<P>
   (SLMBs), covers low-income elderly up to 120 percent of poverty,
or $9,900 for individuals and $13,260 for couples. It covers just
the monthly premiums. An estimated 1.4 million beneficiaries
eligible for this program do not participate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A third program, which began this year, is eligible to pay the
premiums of beneficiaries with incomes between 120 percent and 135
percent of poverty ($11,112 and $14,892, respectively, for
individuals and couples). Almost 500,000 people nationally are
expected to be eligible on a first-come, first-served basis, but
the report said only 4,723 _ less than 1 percent _ had applied as
of last month.
</P>
<P>
   Families USA suggested that participation levels are low for two
reasons: many beneficiaries don't realize they are eligible, and
applying for benefits is cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Although Medicare premium deductions are set when people enroll
at their Social Security office, they must apply for the assistance
programs at state welfare and Medicaid offices.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack urged the Social Security administration to directly
enroll low-income beneficiaries for the programs. A White House
official said the federal government would urge states to
streamline the application process, but shifting the programs to
the Social Security administration would require a change in the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
