<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GENDER-ART-857(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S MUSIC: WHO CAN TELL?
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The right to compose music is one of the last that women have
chosen to claim, which raises an interesting question. But that
right is now being energetically upheld. A fair proportion, if
nothing like 50 percent, of the most talented composers at work in
the United States are women: Joan Tower, Ellen Taaffe Zwilich,
Barbara Kolb, Thea Musgrave, Shulamit Ran and Augusta Read Thomas
are outstanding examples. Abroad, prominent composers include women
like Betsy Jolas, Olga Neuwirth, Kaija Saariaho, Judith Weir and
Sofiya Gubayidulina. The battle for recognition is over. The
question now is, What is women's music or what might it be?
</P>
<P>
   Creative contributions to that discussion are at hand. This week
the Lincoln Center Festival is presenting an opera by Paula M.
Kimper, ``Patience and Sarah.'' And on July 16 a whole evening of
music by women, including a new work by Carol Barnett, will be
performed in Minneapolis to mark the 150th anniversary of the first
women's rights convention, at Seneca Falls, N.Y. If ever those
founding mothers of Seneca Falls gave their attention to music, the
record is silent. There were, to be sure, more pressing issues.
</P>
<P>
   But it is curious that very few women gained important
reputations for their music before the late 1960s, by which time a
good number of women had long been established at the highest level
of painting, to cite another art form with few front-rank women
before the 20th century. Even those earlier women who had produced
fine music, such as Mrs. H.H.A. Beach and Ruth Crawford Seeger,
were not much noticed until two or three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the delay have to do with the fact that change,
when it came, resulted not only from pressure from female composers
but also from a shift in the understanding of music and musical
tradition. Barriers of all kinds were falling. Musicians and
audiences were becoming interested in medieval and Renaissance
music, in the musical cultures of Asia and Africa and in the host
of Western composers who had previously been judged peripheral. All
these adventures made it harder to sustain the idea of a canon
dominated by a dozen great composers, all men and nearly all from
German-speaking Central Europe. And if this central idea of
classical music _ the idea of the core repertory _ was being
questioned by the profession, general audiences were bound to
respond by questioning the value of classical music.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this earthquake in Western musical culture, the
arrival of female composers came at a difficult time. Since the
late 1960s, women have been able to look forward to fully
professional careers as composers and not content themselves, as
women before often did, with the status of a very minor master,
composing domestic songs (Liza Lehmann) or light chamber music
(Cecile Chaminade), and often accepting a role behind the men of
the family (Fanny Mendelssohn, Clara Schumann, Alma Mahler). But
since the late 1960s, too, the prospects of widespread acclaim for
any composer, woman or man, have been receding. It is not
surprising, therefore, that no women have emerged as great
composers during the last three decades. No men have either.
</P>
<P>
   Given that so much has changed, examples from the past are
probably not going to help much. Current enthusiasm for Hildegard
of Bingen _ easily measured by how much her albums outnumber and
outsell those of her troubadour contemporaries _ can be understood
only as part of a re-evaluation of female composers from history.
But it is not at all certain that this re-evaluation is
demonstrating any distinctively female attributes in women's music
or providing anything more than confidence boosting for young women
who compose, important as that may be.
</P>
<P>
   After all, men's music is not particularly male. Down the
centuries from Monteverdi to the present day, most male composers
have favored sopranos above all other kinds of singers and favored
instruments that operate in the soprano register, notably the
violin. The voice of classical music is female. Accordingly, the
female characters in opera are generally more fully drawn,
dramatically dominant and persuasive. It would be hard to say how,
for instance, ``The Marriage of Figaro'' would have been different
if the score had been composed by a woman.
</P>
<P>
   All of this may help explain why women's music is not, so far,
sounding so different from men's music. The lesson may be that sex
is much less important than national origin in influencing a
composer's music. French music, Russian music, American music:
These all have their particular sounds. Women's music does not.
Probably this is because French, Russian and American composers
grow up with different stimuli that have a close bearing on music:
different languages, different musical traditions, both classical
and vernacular, different ideas of music's cultural place and
function.
</P>
<P>
   Female composers, on the other hand, grow up in the same world
as men. To insist otherwise _ to lay claim to a tradition of
women's music going back to Hildegard _ may be tempting but will
probably also be incapacitating. It would be unlikely to help any
musical girl to think that her heritage comprised a remote nun
together with a few salon composers and could not by definition
include Beethoven and Debussy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that women's music is not easily distinguishable from
men's comes from a recent CD of music by 11 American composers who
define themselves as lesbians (Composers Recordings Inc. 780) and
also from Ms. Kimper's ``Patience and Sarah,'' an excerpt from
which is on this record. The CD's program is so diverse that no
common thread is discernible, and none of the tracks stand out as
evidently female, let alone evidently lesbian. ``Patience and
Sarah'' includes love music for two female voices, but this is
nothing new. Such music, at a considerably higher erotic
temperature, can be found throughout the operatic repertory, from
``The Coronation of Poppea'' to ``Der Rosenkavalier.''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion seems inevitable that sexual preference, as well
as sex, is inaudible. And it is not obvious that any contrary
indications come from the music of male composers who identify
themselves or who have been identified as gay. Of course, people
who think they understand Tchaikovsky's sexual inclinations can
start to build theories about the meanings of his operas, his
ballets and even his symphonies. And those theories may well be
convincing and instructive. But they depend on knowledge that the
music itself does not disclose. Shades of sensibility that have
been associated with male homosexual behavior _ performance,
subterfuge, empathy _ are everywhere in music, and it would not be
at all difficult to construct a case for Mozart's homosexuality,
any more than for his womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   This neutrality of music, with respect to sex and sexuality,
goes against the grain. It is hard to believe that a composer's
nationality is vital but not these matters that seem so much deeper
in the personality. How can it be that music, the most erotic of
the arts is indifferent to the source and object of the desires it
manifests?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these instincts are right, and once a sufficient number
of female composers have been working for a sufficient time,
women's music will be a category as particular _ if also as broad
and diffuse _ as American music, Russian or French. When that time
comes, it may also become clear what men really sound like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
