<HEADLINE>
IRAN: IF YOU GO, BRING CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GAIL BENSINGER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tourism was discouraged until recently by the mullahs who won
the revolution, and they still don't make it easy. Solo travel is
nearly impossible for non-Farsi-speakers. So most foreigners join
groups, leaving to travel agencies arrangements for the mandatory
visa as well as hotels and in-country travel.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: Traveling across the interior of Iran is
grueling. It's a big country, with only limited train service, so
you must take buses, private cars or Iran Air, which is not an
airline you would want to accumulate frequent-flier miles on.
Traffic conditions in cities and along the two-lane highways
between them range from scary to terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels: Most Iranian hotels that rise above the fleabag level
date from the shah's era, and the ones we stayed in were clean and
comfortable, if occasionally in need of sprucing up. Each room
offered the usual amenities, including TV and refrigerator. Hotel
bathrooms have Western-style toilets, but in public places most
toilets are of the squat variety.
</P>
<P>
   Food and drink: The water is safe, so we had no worries about
brushing our teeth or eating fresh fruit and salads. The food was
good, if a bit monotonous. Nearly every meal started with barley
soup, and every menu offered a range of kebabs. Rice accompanied
every entree. Chicken and lamb are the usual meats, but fish is
generally available. The bread is terrific, as are the yogurt and
the feta cheese served with fresh herbs. Drinks include soft drinks
and non-alcoholic beer _ booze is strictly forbidden by the
dictates of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Money and shopping: Bring cash, in small denominations. U.S.
credit cards and travelers checks are useless. The official
exchange rate is far below the black market rate. You can get in
serious trouble if the authorities catch you changing money
illegally. There's not a lot to buy, although the bazaar in Isfahan
features good handicrafts _ intricate wooden boxes and picture
frames, jewelry, textiles and the like. U.S. sanctions against Iran
prohibit the import of carpets.
</P>
<P>
   Further reading: ``The Iranians'' by Sandra Mackey is a
comprehensive general history, and the just-published paperback
version contains a useful political update. ``The Mantle of the
Prophet'' by Roy Mottahedeh discusses the role of Shia Islam, while
``Nine Parts of Desire'' by Geraldine Brooks looks at women's
issues throughout the Muslim world. ``The Art and Architecture of
Islam'' and ``Islamic Arts,'' both by Sheila Blair and Jonathan
Bloom, are informative. The only easily available guidebook is
Lonely Planet's 1997 edition of ``Iran.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
