<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LANIER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-HOUSTON MAYOR LATEST DEMOCRAT TO ENDORSE REPUBLICAN BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional ending) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Former Mayor Bob Lanier once told a convention of
radio talk-show hosts that he votes Democratic about three fourths
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   This year's governor's race apparently will be one of the
exceptions. Lanier plans to endorse Republican Gov. George W. Bush
on Tuesday in a gathering at Lanier's Houston condominium.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier did not return calls about the event Monday. But a
spokeswoman for Bush's campaign confirmed the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier is the latest in a string of Democrats to endorse the
Republican governor, including Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, state Rep. Rob
Junell of San Angelo and other state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time that Lanier helped a GOP
candidate. But his backing of a contender from the Bush clan is
rare.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier helped raise campaign money for Democratic presidential
candidates Michael Dukakis in 1988 and Bill Clinton in 1992. The
Republican candidate both times was George Bush, father of the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 gubernatorial contest, Lanier introduced Democratic
Gov. Ann Richards at a campaign event in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a word, she's a leader,'' he said, citing her work to
reduce crime and provide the city with transportation funds.
</P>
<P>
   She lost the election to George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are also political connections between Lanier and Bush,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Austin political consultant Mark McKinnon produced television
commercials for Lanier's campaigns and is doing the same for Bush
now.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McKinnon reportedly discussed the governor's race with
Lanier at a meeting in Houston a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush is being challenged by Democratic land commissioner Garry
Mauro, who is trailing by more than 50 percentage points in the
latest poll.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Lanier were on the same side last year when Bush signed
a bill clearing the way for the use of public funds on the
construction of a downtown Houston baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But when Lanier's backers pushed a bill that would override
Houston's term limits and allow Lanier to run for mayor again, Bush
said the Legislature would never approve because it believes in
``local control.'' The proposal died in committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
