<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-HNS &LR;      07-06 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Netherlands tries to escape shadow
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MARSEILLE, France _ It's about the team that casts the longest
shadow in the world of soccer.
</P>
<P>
   And the team that stands in it.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil wins big games; the Netherlands loses them. Brazil
somehow always brings its diverse and often voluminous egos
together at just the right time. The Netherlands always manages to
strip itself apart.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has spent the last 40 years building a reputation for
greatness. The Netherlands has spent the last 20 helping others
achieve greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil vs. the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a painful history for us at the World Cup,'' Dutch
coach Guus Hiddink said. ``We have had many disappointments.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the contrasting fates of these multitalented teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Brazil,'' defender Cafu said. ``That means we are
obligated to win. And not just win, but win with style and playing
beautiful soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, these are different times and different players from the
ones that spawned the travels of these soccer-loving nations _ the
likes of Brazil's Pele and Garrincha and the hard-luck Holland
heroes Johan Cruyff and Robbie Rensenbrink.
</P>
<P>
   But until something happens to change the course these teams
have taken, with Brazil having won four World Cup championships and
the Netherlands having fallen short twice, both nations realize the
shadows will remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the first memory I have of the Dutch national team
was when it lost the championship,'' Dutch forward Dennis Bergkamp,
29, said, referring to the 1974 World Cup title game in which the
Dutch were heavily favored but lost to West Germany. ``I was very
upset. We want to win this World Cup and give our country what it
has wanted for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1974 and 1978 Dutch teams lost in the World Cup
finals has there been a better chance.
</P>
<P>
   But making today's World Cup semifinal at Stade Velodrome all
the more intriguing is the opponent, Brazil. It will be trying to
add to its great World Cup legacy in this game that promises much
excitement, considering the offensive-mindedness of both teams, and
is meaningful in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians could be on their way to an unprecedented fifth
Cup championship. The Dutch could be stepping out of the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a destiny that we had to play the Dutch,'' said
Brazil coach Mario Zagallo, who has faced the Netherlands as a
player, assistant coach and head coach. ``We cannot fight it. They
are a team that we should play. Our destiny is the Netherlands.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Zagallo was on the bench coaching when the Cruyff-led
Dutch defeated Brazil 2-0 in the Cup semifinals. Zagallo saw his
squad lose to an unforgettable side.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the best team in the (1974) tournament,'' Zagallo
said. ``They played artful football. It was beautiful to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was agonizing for the Netherlands. That 1974
Netherlands team recently was ranked among the top five best soccer
teams in history. But it is the only one among the five that didn't
win the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 years later, it was agonizing again for the Dutch when
in Dallas the Netherlands fought back from a 2-0 deficit against
Brazil to tie the score, only to give up a free kick and lose 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game is still painful to remember,'' Dutch defender Jaap
Stam said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 Netherlands team was quite similar to this one, with
the likes of Bergkamp and the de Boer twins, Frank and Ronald. It
was an extremely talented Dutch team, much like the 1974 and 1978
teams.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was a self-destructive team, with apparent racial
tensions adding to its demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Dutch tradition to fall apart from the inside,''
Hiddink said. ``It is very disappointing and frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   But this team promises more.
</P>
<P>
   There is apparent harmony both on the field and in the locker
room. Race issues have long been resolved, said midfielder Edgar
Davids, who is black and was at the center of the 1994 controversy.
The tensions came from a lack of getting to know one another on a
social level, Davids said.
</P>
<P>
   And on the field, everything is smooth. Twice already in
elimination games, the Dutch have scored in the final minute to
win, with Bergkamp's winning goal against Argentina last week among
the more memorable goals to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously have grown in power,'' Brazil defender Leonardo
said of the Dutch. ``I'm impressed by the way in which some very
strong individuals have managed to adapt to a collective mentality.
I'm also a little surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, it hasn't been the Dutch way to funnel formidable
talents together in such a way. When asked to name the last time he
saw a Dutch national team perform as cohesively and in such a
clutch fashion as this one has, Hiddink responded, ``I don't
remember when.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we are a team that can prove to be the best,''
Bergkamp said. ``The only way to prove that is to play Brazil.
We've tasted a bit of success, and we want more.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brazil has drunk from the Cup so many times its nation is
addicted. It is expected to win today. And always.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Dutch tradition, the Brazilians traditionally
are individual and often egotistical superstars away from the
national team who somehow find a way to become one once they pull
on the yellow jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, there were persistent rumors and reports about
squabbles within the Brazilian team, most notably between forwards
Romario and Bebeto. But by the end of the tournament, Brazil was
happy and lofting the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The image of Bebeto and Romario standing side-by-side, rocking
their arms back and forth in celebration of a key goal on the way
to the championship continues to be played over and over on the
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The game in which that celebration took place was against the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope history repeats itself,'' Brazil's Ronaldo said. ``We
are playing much better as a team with every game in this
tournament. We are ready to win the Cup. We are ready to defend our
championship, and we know we are good enough to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
