<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-MENS-FASHION-AR     07-06 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-MENS-FASHION-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MILAN, TOM FORD LIGHTENS UP THE GUCCI MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ The trendy designer, embodied by Tom Ford at
Gucci, and the unapologetic industrialist, represented by Giorgio
Armani, now define fashion in Milan, and it speaks well of the city
that both can thrive in such a hothouse. Seemingly overnight, Milan
has become the magnet for designers from around the globe showing
their menswear for next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the clamor, designers can attract attention in two ways.
They can, like Armani, command it with vast reserves of
professional esteem born of creating fashion history, like Robert
De Niro's luring movie audiences with the same role. Otherwise,
like Leonardo di Caprio, they had better offer something new, and
it should preferably be young.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet able to take the first path, Ford went with the
alternative. After four years of creating the image of the Gucci
man as cynical sexpot, he has recast him as the dreamy romantic.
The startling transformation made Gucci the show of this round,
which ended Thursday with Ford capturing an emerging quixotic
spirit in menswear.
</P>
<P>
   It's axiomatic that fashion is about change, but how and when a
design house should change has become an urgent question as
companies have expended and fashion has become a tentacle of global
entertainment. Once a designer establishes a successful image, does
he move on and risk millions in sales? Or does he hold fast to his
concept and possibly lose relevance? That Milan had strong
contenders for both positions indicates there are no easy answers.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek Gucci look of sullen sophistication was in danger of
growing stale. Ford replaced it with clothes that reeked of giddy
delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted things to be less perfect, less matched,'' Ford said.
``Suits were not as important.'' The show, he said, was about mood.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts, in gauzy pink or military khaki, will look familiar
to baby boomers, who came of age in the 1970s, and almost everyone
will recognize the hip-hop drop-crotch trousers. But there were new
twists everywhere, like an extraordinary khaki shirt sequined and
beaded in cobalt-blue flowers, baggy pants in hot pink and the new
Gucci shoe _ a sneaker with Velcro straps and the old double-G
Gucci canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Ford juxtaposed a pristine white zip-front shirt with Velcro
snap at the collar with distressed white baggy trousers. A simple
gray sleeveless T-shirt topped gray flannel pants awash in enough
crystals and embroidery to raise Liberace from the dead. And the
Gucci suit itself was tamed with a looser shape and plainer-looking
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Stockholders will be watching to see if Ford wins his crapshoot.
The most prominent among them, Miuccia Prada and her husband,
Patrizio Bertelli, owners of Prada, in two transactions last month
acquired a 9.5 percent stake in Gucci, a publicly traded company.
None of the principals in the two companies, including Ford, the
creative director and a stockholder, will say much about the
investment, which was unsolicited by Gucci and is extraordinary in
fashion circles.
</P>
<P>
   The distraction obviously did not dampen Ford's creativity, nor
that of Ms. Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Her white, sheer nylon shirt slipped easily over gray trouser
shorts, which ended midcalf in the gather characteristic of sweat
pants. Shirt jackets in breezy fabrics had the boxiness of a jacket
but the cuffs of a shirt. The collars on summer coats and suits _
less boyish than last season's _ were left raw.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Prada notwithstanding, Italy owes its reputation to
industrialization. There is now plenty of creativity, partly
because of a cosmopolitan atmosphere typical of Paris. Americans
show in Milan. New, too, are the formidable Belgians, the Japanese,
the Canadians and the English.
</P>
<P>
   American designer John Bartlett, in his first presentation for
Byblos, drew upon ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' the moody cult film
starring Steve McQueen. Bartlett used the movie as a reference
point for his own men's line, shown this year in New York with more
success. But his touch was assured, and polished-denim two-button
suits with orange zippered body shirt, bold geometrically striped
knits and slim white leather jeans refreshed the parade of
nonchalant, athletic fashion on some runways around town.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Edwards, the American collection designed by Richard
Bengstrom and Edward Pavelik, was handsome, with a visible
improvement in quality. The designers put an easy hand to anoraks
with drawstrings above the waist, loose trousers, pinstripe jeans,
and knit polos with quilting on the sleeves, all in quenching
shades of white, blue and khaki.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein has the might of an industrialist, but he has
chosen to dance aggressively at fashion's edge. His unlined and
unconstructed jackets fell over wide pants with a drawstring at the
waist. A honey-color leather pullover or a white or gray cotton
drawstring shirt was paired with nonchalant drop-crotch trousers,
also in white and gray.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Paul Gaultier's image is rooted in challenging status-quo
sensibilities. The humor of his show made it perfect for customers
cruising for fun pieces. Low culture has become an endless source
of inspiration for the intelligentsia, designers included. Suburban
summers spent guzzling bear in washed-out jeans came to life on
Gaultier's sand-covered runway. Knit tops strained against models'
pectorals, softened by roomy trousers, and when cool nights call
for a cover-up, there are blouson jackets with ribbed-knit trim for
men nostalgic for Members Only.
</P>
<P>
   Designers like Dirk Bikkembergs, Alessandro Dell'Acqua and Ennio
Capasa for Costume National have built their reputations on change.
Bikkembergs invited his audience to the source of his inspiration,
an ice-skating rink. As guests took their seats at the center of
the ice, about a dozen speed skaters in red unitards zoomed around
the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   The show explored the theme with strong fitted sweaters, piped
in the elliptical shape of a skating rink, worn with baggy
trousers. There were red leggings with a navy stripe down the side
under tailored jackets, pinstripe suits with large shoulders and
flapping pants and loose tunic tops with deep scooped necklines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dell'Acqua was not able to make his creations work so smoothly.
His sheer fitted Champagne-tone nylon tops with raised seams down
the front and straight-leg pants with fraying seams provided
interesting touches, but many of the clothes were oversimplistic
or, like over-the-knee shorts, unflattering.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly or uncomfortable clothes are no longer interesting. Even
designers like Capasa, who just two years ago was contributing his
share of them, is adding elegant touches and softening his approach
with wonderful results. It began with reversible leather shirt
jackets in black and stone, supple and relaxed. The most casual of
spring garments, the khaki-color jacket, came in double-faced
cotton. Capasa's mixes of paler khaki with mushroom-brown were
appealing, and several jackets were made from paperlike cotton. And
while many designers ease their suits with knitwear, Capasa has
suddenly gone back to shirts. This kind of about-face separates
designers who set trends again and again from those stuck in a
mold.
</P>
<P>
   Armani defiantly calls himself ``an industrialist,'' in
explanation of the small changes he has made in his line each
season. ``It's a slow process because you've got to sell your
collection at the end of the day,'' he said. ``You have to educate
the consumer. Men don't want a big revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Within his collection of fluid drapey signature suits, Armani
did offer some novelty, like loose Chinese worker jackets with
matching pants. Although Armani says he is restlessly in search of
a new silhouette, he could do much to refresh his benchmark look by
casting some of his designs in crisp or modern synthetic fabrics,
rather than putting see-through tops under suits.
</P>
<P>
   Like Armani, Valentino and Gianfranco Ferre approach menswear
with familiarity in mind. Such designers, swaddled in the blanket
of success and acclaim, risk missing the cues that it is time to
move on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
