<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-STOLEN-ART-470&AMP;     07-06 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-STOLEN-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY RECOVERS THREE STOLEN PAINTINGS _ AND ITS WOUNDED PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By ALESSANDRA STANLEY  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Bursting into apartments in Turin and Rome in pre-dawn
raids, the Italian police on Monday recovered two Van Goghs and a
Cezanne stolen from the National Gallery of Modern Art. The raids
ended a seven-week search for the paintings, among Italy's most
valuable post-Impressionist works.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, three armed robbers hid inside the museum until
closing time, then tied up three guards, turned off the alarm and
walked out with the paintings, a brazen theft that was deeply
humiliating to the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a bleeding wound that Italy didn't deserve,'' Deputy
Prime Minister Walter Veltroni said at a news conference to
announce the recovery and the arrest of eight Italian suspects,
including a museum employee. ``Today, the wound is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Veltroni, who is also the minister of culture, described the
theft as the work of professional robbers. Police investigators,
who traced the gang members through the museum employee with
wiretaps and surveillance, said they identified the suspects more
than a month ago but moved slowly for fear the artworks could be
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult and risky operation because we had to make
sure we didn't endanger the paintings,'' said Italo Ormanni, the
prosecutor who led the investigation. ``It was more important to
recover them than make the arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the paintings _ ``Le Jardinier,'' by Van Gogh, and ``Le
Cabenon de Jourdan,'' by Cezanne _ were found unharmed and wrapped
in blankets and cardboard under a bed and on top of a wardrobe in
an apartment in a working-class neighborhood on the outskirts of
Rome. The other Van Gogh _ ``L'Arlesienne'' _ was found in Turin in
an apartment that also held guns, rifles, masks, false beards and
material that could be used to make bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Italy overflows with Renaissance treasures, but it has very few
post-Impressionist and Modernist works. The Van Goghs were the only
oil paintings by the artist in Italy. ``Le Cabenon de Jourdan'' was
the country's only major work by Cezanne.
</P>
<P>
   Italy is also rich in art thefts. The police estimate that more
than 4,000 valuable works have been stolen in the last 30 years. In
1992 thieves stole 13 paintings, including a Velasquez, from a
museum in Modena. All were later recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Crime prevention has improved in recent years. Veltroni said
that art theft was 50 percent lower this year than last year, and
that half the stolen works are recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Veltroni said all three paintings would be back on display on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the suspected robbers, the police said, had previously
served jail sentences for armed robbery in Belgium. While tracing
the paintings, the investigators said, they overheard the suspects
plotting robberies in France and Belgium, and tipped off their
European counterparts about the plans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than 100 Italian law-enforcement officers worked the case.
They investigated all 160 museum employees, eventually focusing on
one woman, a guard, who had contacts with people with criminal
records, and who is accused of helping the robbers plan their
break-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately the question of whether there was an inside
connection was confirmed, and this for me ruins the joy of the
recovery,'' said Alessandra Pinto, director of the National Gallery
of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   But she also saw a bright side: ``At the same time, the fact
that someone inside the gallery assisted the criminals dismantles
the charges that our security system was inefficient. It is much
more difficult to protect things if it is an inside job.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said the robbers had hoped to make $18 million by
selling the paintings abroad to private collectors, a plan that art
experts found preposterous. Officials said the suspects had
contacted one art trafficker to fence the stolen paintings, and
were turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had been experts in art theft, they would never have
chosen these three paintings,'' said Francesco Maria Benedetti,
director of operations of the art theft squad of Italy's military
police. ``They are too well known and too difficult to sell. These
people were bank robbers and very dangerous people, but they did
not know much about art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
