<P>
   ROY-ROGERTOWN (Los Angeles) _ To the folks in the Los Angeles
community of Chatsworth, Roy Rogers was more than America's
favorite cowboy. The singing cowboy WAS Chatsworth, the man who
lived in the ranch house on Trigger Street. All around town, from
the commuter train station he and Dale dedicated three years ago to
the chamber of commerce, where they're working up plans to give the
town a Western makeover, people reminisced about the man's goodness
in the place where Rogers and his wife Dale Evans spent their
working years and made many of their Western movies. Rogers and
Evans, who lived in a six-bedroom ranch house in the Chatsworth
neighborhood, later developed many homes in the area, plotting them
on streets like Trigger and Dale. The singing cowboy died Monday of
congestive heart failure at his Apple Valley home. He was 86. By
Sharline Chiang. (Will move in the ``e'' entertainment and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
