<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLSTAR-ADVANCE-COX     07-06 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How will great pitching from Maddux, Wells stand up in Coors
Field?
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Tonight's pitching matchup in the All-Star Game
represents two players from different worlds.
</P>
<P>
   There's Atlanta's Greg Maddux, a perfectionist on the mound who
lives on his control and away from the game he's quiet, almost
transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's David Wells of the Yankees, who relies on a hard
fastball and curve, his delivery a bunch of arms and legs and off
the field he argues with his owner and counts O.J. detective Mark
Fuhrman as one of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be interesting,'' said National League manager Jim
Leyland of the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   It could be more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux and Wells could find themselves paired against each other
come the World Series as their teams went into the break with the
best records in the their respective leagues.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, it's probably two innings apiece as Maddux is
on his seventh All-Star team, his third start while Wells is making
his second appearance.
</P>
<P>
   And Coors Field has never been very friendly to Maddux. He has
allowed 14 earned runs in 18 innings here and when asked what the
difference was between Coors and other parks he said, ``Slider
doesn't slide as much, curve doesn't curve as much. But you can
still pitch here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has pitched just once in Denver, back in 1995 when he was
playing for Cincinnati and when asked what his strategy would be in
a park where balls travel 10 percent further a major league record
222 homers were hit last season, he said, ``Duck.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells went on to add, ``You just have to create something. I
think hopefully I have a vision of a high-scoring game, but
hopefully not when I'm in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the game is at Coors and because of all the home runs
that have been hit throughout baseball this season, there are a lot
of offensive expectations when such players as Mark McGwire and Ken
Griffey Jr. walk up to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But said Griffey, ``The two starting pitchers that will be
starting, I don't know if it's going to be a high scoring game ...
maybe a quick game. But hopefully it's a lot of fun. Hopefully the
fans get what they want: A couple of guys get some home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, the game could turn out to be a power classic like
there was back in 1971 at Tiger Stadium when six future Hall of
Famers hit homers, a group that included Hank Aaron and Roberto
Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NL leads the series 40-27-1 though last year the
AL won 3-1 in Cleveland, the NL's only run coming on a homer by
Javier Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will have three players in tonight's starting lineup.
In addition to Maddux, there is Chipper Jones at third and Walt
Weiss at second. Lopez will likely come on in the fourth inning and
replace Mike Piazza behind the plate while Andres Galarraga goes to
first after McGwire gets at least two at-bats. Also, Tom Glavine
will pitch, probably behind San Diego's Kevin Brown who is expected
to replace Maddux after two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is always a good time,'' said Glavine, who is on his
sixth All-Star team. ``There have been a couple of times where I
haven't pitched, but I want to this time because I have had some
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lopez, ``I sort of feel like this is my first All-Star
Game, I guess I will always feel that way no matter how many times
I come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Maddux, ``These games are great to play in. You know, you
just play. It's almost like spring training. You really enjoy the
game. There is no pressure to win or anything like that. You have
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
