<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2684 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHCAROLINA-GAYS-2T     07-06 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHCAROLINA-GAYS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY RIGHTS DRIVE MEETS FIERCE RESISTANCE IN SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ It was not by accident that the first shot of
the Civil War was fired in this tradition-bound state, where few
things are viewed so seriously as an assault on the inherited
culture. It is a place where lawmakers still scoff at suggestions
that the Confederate flag be removed from the Capitol dome and
where only a federal court order enabled women to enroll at the
Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with increasing vigor, the resistance to change
extends to another perceived threat: homosexuality. For more than
two years, leaders of this state's churches, governments and
schools have erected barrier after barrier against a cultural
invasion that many view as an affront to their most cherished
values.
</P>
<P>
   In an election year with little economic discontent, Senate
majority leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., brought new focus to the
politics of morality when he declared in a television interview in
June that homosexuality is a sin. But if Lott was trying to
escalate a rhetorical war on homosexuality, the battle was joined
some time ago here in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   It began in May 1996, when the Greenville County Council adopted
a resolution declaring homosexuality incompatible with community
standards. The decision, on a vote of 9-3, prompted organizers of
the run carrying the Olympic torch to Atlanta to shelter the flame
in a van as it moved through the rapidly growing county.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months alone, the mayor of Myrtle Beach has
joined business and religious leaders in opposing a gay-pride rally
there (it took place anyway), a high school principal has canceled
a free concert by the Indigo Girls, at least partly because parents
complained that the rock singers, Amy Ray and Emily Saliers, are
lesbians, and a Republican candidate for state agriculture
commissioner has vowed to protect the family farm from the
``homosexual movement.''
</P>
<P>
   While a recent report by the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force
asserts that a growing majority of Americans support equality for
homosexuals, gay rights leaders acknowledge that South Carolina may
be a microcosm of much of nonurban America. The state is inherently
conservative in its politics, religion and social practices, and
many here regard the increasing openness of gay life as emblematic
of a broader moral decay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just homosexuality,'' said the Rev. Steve R. Hubbard,
a 37-year-old Baptist minister from Myrtle Beach who organized a
family-values coalition in response to this year's gay-pride rally.
``We've got a 60 percent divorce rate. We've got kids killing kids
in our schools. We've got prostitution. We've got sexually
transmitted diseases at an all-time high. We've got gambling that
is destroying families. And in the end, what is always hurt is the
traditional family, which provides for a community and a
civilization what no other unit can provide.''
</P>
<P>
   But gay rights leaders, political scientists and government
officials also agree that a distinct confluence of factors has
contributed to the rawness of gay rights conflicts here: the
pervasiveness of fundamentalist Christianity, which interprets
scriptural warnings against homosexuality as God-given truth; the
ties between religious conservatives and the state's surging
Republican Party; the increasing activism of the state's gay
community; the South's history of bigotry, and the state's
resistance to cultural change, racial and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here perceive themselves on the defensive, defending
their culture, their religion, their communities, against outside
forces,'' said Charles W. Dunn, a political scientist at Clemson
University. ``They see these changes, such as homosexuality, and
they rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's gay leaders say homosexuals have been energized
by the attacks, with more taking an active stand on political
issues. Gay rights organizations have been established in all the
state's major cities. Columbia has a gay community center that
advertises itself with a pink triangle on its sign. The gay-pride
march in Myrtle Beach this year, the ninth annual event in the
state, attracted an estimated total of 5,000 to 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Gay leaders depict their victimization as in keeping with a
legacy of Southern hate. While public expressions of racism are no
longer acceptable in the region, they say, there is no such taboo
against homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be discrimination against gays and lesbians
everywhere, but here the gay-baiting is so open,'' said Harriet D.
Hancock, a mother of three, including a gay son, and co-chairwoman
of the South Carolina chapter of Parents, Families and Friends of
Lesbians and Gays. ``It used to be race-baiting. Now it's
gay-baiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Snell, co-chairman of the South Carolina Gay and Lesbian
Pride Movement, which has a mailing list of 8,000 to 10,000, said
the state's homosexuals were ``the scapegoat du jour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've sent a message here,'' Snell said of antigay forces,
``that it's OK to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   But church leaders depict their message as one of hate for the
sin and love for the sinner.
</P>
<P>
   Like many fellow clerics, the Rev. Stan Y. Craig, the pastor of
Choice Hills Baptist Church in Greenville and an organizer of his
city's Citizens for Traditional Family Values, cites the Bible as
the foundation of his approach to gay issues.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said he believed that homosexuality was ``demonic'' and
``a stench in the nostrils of God.'' His organization's blue and
white placards proclaim that homosexuality is ``Satan's plot for
our children'' and that ``sodomy is not a family value.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade C. Cleveland, one of the three members of the Greenville
County Council who opposed its resolution against homosexuality,
said that homophobia might not be more prevalent in South Carolina
than elsewhere but that it might be more virulent, ``because we get
it so honestly from the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's justified by God,'' Cleveland said, ``you can do a
whole lot more through a jihad than through normal dislikes.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Snell and Ms. Hancock argue that fundamentalist zeal has
influenced policy and political rhetoric because of the dependency
of Republican politicians on the votes of religious conservatives.
The state GOP is certain enough of its constituents' views on
homosexuality that it does not even poll on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like asking everybody if they're for free ice
cream,'' said Trey Walker, a party spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a state like South Carolina, pollsters warn,
Republican candidates can expect a backlash if they attack
homosexuals with malice. And recent elections here have shown that
the most socially conservative candidate does not always win
Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, in the last 14 months, Gov. David M. Beasley,
Lieut. Gov. Robert L. Peeler, Attorney General Charles M. Condon
and Rep. Bob Inglis, who is running for the U.S. Senate this year
against longtime Democratic incumbent Ernest F. Hollings, have all
attended family-values rallies that were organized in reaction to
gay rights marches.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's Senate race, state Republican chairman Henry
McMaster has already derided Hollings' sponsorship of a 1983 bill
to protect homosexuals from employment discrimination. At the state
Republican convention in May, David Eckstrom, who later won the
party's nomination for state education superintendent, spent more
than a third of his speech touting his support for the cancellation
of the Indigo Girls concert at Irmo High School, near Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to take a stand,'' said Eckstrom, who is
chairman of the school board that governs Irmo High. ``If the
Indigo Girls got their feelings hurt, that's too bad.'' Eckstrom
later mailed text of his remarks to religious conservatives around
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the political use of gay issues a step farther, Jim
Gordon, a Republican candidate for state agriculture commissioner,
declared last month that ``we can't have farming based on Bob and
Bob being married and a new definition of marriage.'' Gordon won 31
percent of the vote in a three-way primary on June 9, finishing
second to the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, gay rights leaders find much wanting in South
Carolina's legal code. It is one of 14 states that outlaw sodomy,
both homosexual and heterosexual, according to the National Gay and
Lesbian Task Force. It is one of 29 states with laws prohibiting
same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   When the Legislature, which has a Republican-controlled House
and a Democratic-majority Senate, banned same-sex marriages in
1996, Gov. Beasley said that ``America is in a moral meltdown today
because its leaders, under pressure from special interest groups,
want to always appear tolerant.'' Beasley declined to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is also one of nine states without a hate crime
law of any kind. After a racial shooting in 1997, Condon, the
Attorney General, proposed hate crime legislation that would have
assigned special penalties to those convicted of crimes motivated
by racial bigotry. But when lawmakers introduced a competing bill
that would have expanded the definition of a hate crime to include
bias attacks against women and homosexuals, Condon dropped his
support, saying it would be impossible to gain passage for such
legislation. He also declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Some gay leaders blame Condon and others for contributing to a
climate that encourages anti-gay violence. Twice in the last seven
months, they point out, a lesbian named Regan Wolf has been
brutally whipped at her home near Lancaster, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   In both incidents, Ms. Wolf was knocked unconscious at her home
and strung up spread-eagle on a porch. The beatings left horizontal
red stripes across her back, as if she had lain on a sizzling
grill. In the first incident, a message was left in spray paint on
the steps: ``Jesus weren't born for you, faggot.'' State and local
law enforcement officials have made no arrests and decline to say
whether they regard the attacks as homophobic.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who are leading the fight against gay rights here
make it clear that they feel that their state and their values are
under seige.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, the Greenville minister, said he had grown increasingly
disturbed as President Clinton liberalized the country's policy on
gays in the military, as television sitcoms began to feature openly
gay characters, and as gays and lesbians marched through Greenville
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is about to happen in Greenville has already happened in
places like San Francisco and New York City,'' said Craig. ``We
really believe this is the last bastion of moral decency left in
America, and they're trying to push their agenda into this part of
the country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The same sentiment led Mark S. McBride, a city councilman in
Myrtle Beach, to speak out last year against the opening of a gay
bar in the resort town's Pavilion area, a gaudy boardwalk of roller
coasters, video arcades and T-shirt shops. The gay bar, which he
said would attract ``transvestites and drag queens and people being
led around on leashes in dog collars,'' did not blend with the
family-friendly image that Myrtle Beach has long tried to promote,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His stand against the bar gave McBride a platform from which to
run for mayor, and he narrowly defeated a longtime incumbent in
November. In tribute, the gay pride movement announced that it
would hold its May 1998 march in Myrtle Beach. McBride again made
his displeasure known, and the city's largest developer, Burroughs
&AMP; Chapin Co., killed plans by several nightclubs in one of its
developments to hold an outdoor concert by the Village People that
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not going to allow our company's facilities to be used
to further a cause that we felt was a negative influence on our
community,'' said company president Douglas P. Wendel.
</P>
<P>
   Although the gay bar opened and the march was held (McBride sent
his wife and two children to Greenville for the weekend), the
34-year-old Mayor still hopes to preserve the traditional family
orientation of his town.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've built ourselves on over the last 60 years is the
traditional family base,'' he said. ``People don't come here to be
subjugated to all the progressiveness, all the sophistication, all
the enlightenment of big city life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
