<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-TALKS-COX     07-06 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-TALKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talks aimed at averting yet another UAW/GM strike
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ General Motors Corp. and United Auto Workers in
Dayton started high-level negotiations Monday in hope of saving two
local brake plants and avoiding another devastating labor strike.
</P>
<P>
   The local talks begin at a time when GM and the UAW are
negotiating to end two crippling strikes in Flint, Mich., that have
dragged on into their second month.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders for UAW Local 696, which represents 3,400 hourly workers
at the brake plants, confirmed that GM and International UAW
officials began a new round of talks in a Moraine hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to the talks said ``no progress'' was made
Monday towards settling job and outsourcing issues that have split
GM and Local 696 for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all in the same room, but nothing is happening right
now,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   GM and UAW officials both declined comment on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The brake plants produce anti-braking system parts used in many
GM cars and light trucks built in North America. A 17-day strike in
1996 at the brake plants virtually shut down GM's North American
production within days and cost the automaker $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   The current negotiations were prompted by the threat of another
strike at the plants. Last week, Local 696 leaders received
approval from members to organize a possible strike against GM
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   If the local talks fail, Dayton could be the site of another
strike by the UAW. The Flint strikes have closed 26 of GM's 29
North American assembly plants, idling more than 7,000 GM workers
in the Miami Valley and 162,000 auto workers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The main issue splitting the UAW and GM in Dayton continues to
be the plants employment level. Company documents show GM wants to
slash about 1,800 jobs at the brake plants and combine the
operations into the Needmore Road factory. The union says GM agreed
in the local contract to employ about 2,900 workers at the plants
until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   GM also wants to eliminate 'make out and quit,' a quota clause
that requires workers to produce certain number of parts in an
8-hour workday. Workers sometimes complete the work in five or six
hours, but get paid for a full shift. Because of the quota clause,
company officials say the brake plants have the lowest productivity
rating among any of GM's parts plants.
</P>
<P>
   The two brake plants have been facing the threat of sale or
shutdown because of massive financial losses over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, GM and the UAW are under intense pressure to settle
the strikes in Flint before the costly walkouts cause permanent
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Flint strikes plants began a month ago and have cost the
automaker more than $1.2 billion in second-quarter profit from lost
output of cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement this week would allow GM to begin the complex
process of restarting plants by Monday, the end of its annual
two-week summer vacation. It's an important target for negotiators,
who in the past have responded to deadlines. Without a settlement
soon, GM risks fouling a $4 billion truck rollout and surrendering
hard-to-regain market share to rivals such as Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ford and Chrysler will have better chances to grab
GM customers the longer the strike lasts. GM dealers' inventories
have been shrinking because of the lost production. The automaker
has already said it expects poor sales in July, as much as 40
percent below the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the Flint strikes last, the more difficult it is for
each side to sell the agreement as a victory, analysts said. GM
needs to show Wall Street and investors that it gained the right to
lower its manufacturing costs or improve efficiency. GM executives
are under pressure to win concessions the longer the strike lasts,
and their careers could be hurt if they don't, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW needs to show it will protect jobs at the world's
largest automaker. Union members at the two plants must ratify the
agreement before they return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Business News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
