<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELOQUENT TRIBUTES TO THE DEAD PRINCESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every remark can be etched in stone, or even margarine, so
Diana-watchers everywhere will be grateful for ``Remembering Diana:
The People's Tribute to Their Princess.''  &UR; Rick Blalock &LR;  and  &UR; K.
Thomas Oglesby &LR;  of Georgia have compiled and edited some of the
millions of tributes to the princess that appeared, in print or on
the Internet, after her death. Among the world leaders who weighed
in:
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a toucher. I appreciated that in her,'' said  &UR; Diana &LR; 
 &UR; Ross &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana was loved by the people of Russia,'' said  &UR; Boris &LR; 
 &UR; Yeltsin &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been hard for me,'' said  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Through her commitment to organizations that help people in
need, Diana embodied the true spirit of volunteerism, transcending
stations in life and wealth. She reached out a helping hand to
those who most needed one, and that is the true meaning of
community,'' said &UR; Liane Levetan &LR; , chief executive officer of DeKalb
County, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Archbishop of York &UR; David Hope &LR; , second banana in the Church
of England only to the Archbishop of Canterbury, told the Sunday
Times of London that the Diana museum  &UR; Earl Spencer  &LR; opened last
week was inappropriate. ``It's the last thing she would have
wanted,'' he said, suggesting that a more appropriate memorial
would be remembrance of ``lives changed, wounds healed, bodies
remodeled and remade. ... We need to beware of clinging to the
icon. There is some element of wallowing in her death.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. The postal service of New Zealand has canceled plans to
issue a set of stamps commemorating the September anniversary of
Diana's death because it couldn't get approval from the Princess of
Wales Memorial Trust in time, and (having missed the bandwagon) it
was worried about ``over-commercialization.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE LEGACIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Milton Berle &LR; 's estranged son,  &UR; Bill &LR; , is peddling to
publishers ``Near You,'' a tell-all memoir that describes his
father's affairs with &UR; Lucille Ball &LR; ,  &UR; Marilyn Monroe &LR; ,  &UR; Veronica &LR; 
 &UR; Lake &LR; ,  &UR; Betty Hutton &LR; ,  &UR; Lana Turner &LR; ,  &UR; Hedy Lamarr &LR; ,  &UR; Aimee Semple &LR; 
 &UR; McPherson &LR;  and (drum roll)  &UR; Nancy Reagan &LR; . The book also claims
that Berle was an absentee father and ``domestic tyrant,'' says the
New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   Berle's 90th birthday is on the horizon, and Bill, 36, is not
invited to any of the parties.
</P>
<P>
