</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-U.S.-POLICY-390-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO POLICY CHANGE, U.S. ASSURES TAIWAN AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration sought to reassure the
Taiwan government on Monday that there had been no change in
American policy toward Taiwan despite Clinton's declaration in
China that the United States would not support Taiwan's
independence from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's comments about Taiwan last week duplicated
statements made in the past by other administration officials, it
was the first time that the president had articulated the policy
himself.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks set off alarms in Taiwan, which Beijing considers a
breakaway province, and on Capitol Hill, where Taiwan has many
supporters. A statement today by President Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan
suggested that the island's fears would not be quickly allayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, your country should negotiate directly with us
about any matters involving Taiwan,'' Lee said after meeting in
Taipei, the Taiwan capital, with an American official who had been
sent there to provide reassurances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should not have to _ and should not _ hold bilateral talks
with the Chinese Communists'' about Taiwan's sovereignty, he told
the American official, Richard Bush, the Washington-based chairman
of the American Institute in Taiwan. The institute is a nominally
private organization that handles American relations with Taiwan in
the absence of formal diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters in Taiwan that Clinton's trip to the
mainland and his comments there did not indicate that Washington
was trying to bolster China's demands for reunification with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``United States policy toward Taiwan has not changed,'' he said.
``In all its elements, it is exactly the same as before President
Clinton's trip.''
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting in Shanghai last week, Clinton appeared to make
a concession to his Chinese hosts by making a public declaration of
a policy known as the ``three no's'' _ no American support for an
independent Taiwan, no recognition for a separate Taiwan
government, and no support for Taiwan's entry into international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that the president said in China changes our
relationship with Taiwan,'' said P.J. Crowley, a White House
spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
