<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2700 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RUSSIA-NYT     07-06 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACCEPTS YELTSIN'S INVITATION FOR SEPTEMBER SUMMIT TALKS IN
MOSCOW
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has agreed to travel to Russia in
early September to meet with President Boris Yeltsin, although the
Russian legislature has not fulfilled a request to ratify an
important arms control treaty signed with the United States, the
White House announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents have made a practice of annual summit
meetings, but for more than a year the White House had postponed
responding to Yeltsin's invitation to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton never said that ratification of the treaty, known as
START-2, which was signed five years ago, was a requirement for his
visit, but he indicated that it was his strong preference. The
president had said he hoped to move on to discussing further arms
reductions, a topic that White House officials now say will be on
the agenda this fall even without approval of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, they just felt that the issues we have
to discuss were more important than waiting for the Duma,'' an
administration official said, referring to the lower house of the
Russian Parliament. In describing those issues, he listed the
ethnic violence in Kosovo and the state of the Russian economy,
badly shaken by the financial turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate ratified the arms control treaty in 1996. But despite
pleas from Yeltsin, the Communists, and nationalists who dominate
the Russian Parliament have dragged their feet over ratification of
the treaty, which would cut Russian and American nuclear arsenals
to about 3,500 warheads apiece, citing security concerns and the
high cost of destroying the weapons. The Parliament plans to take
up the issue in September.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that Vice President Al Gore would meet in
Moscow later this month with the Russian prime minister, Sergei
Kiriyenko, to help prepare the agenda for the summit meeting. The
precise dates for the president's trip, as well the site of his
meeting with Yeltsin, have not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also anxious to visit Ireland and Northern Ireland
this year to celebrate the recently approved peace agreement there.
He may make those stops as part of his Russia trip, one aide said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House squeezed the Russia trip into a presidential
schedule already jammed with foreign travel. Clinton just returned
on Saturday from a nine-day trip to China. Earlier this spring, he
spent almost two weeks in Africa. In April, he attended a summit
meeting in Santiago, Chile, and in May he attended one in
Birmingham, England, making stops in Germany and Switzerland along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   The president is still scheduled to visit India, Pakistan, and
Bangladesh in November, although the White House is weighing a
change of schedule because of the nuclear tests conducted this
spring by India and Pakistan. Regardless, Clinton will be in Asia
that month, for a summit meeting in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with Yeltsin during the Birmingham summit, Clinton
urged him to seek ratification of the arms control treaty to help
persuade budding nuclear powers like India and Pakistan that they
were moving in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Clinton's travel was scheduled long before the
disclosure in January that Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel,
had broadened his investigation of the Whitewater land deal to
include the president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a former
intern. But the White House has welcomed the busy foreign travel as
an opportunity to escape Washington and to display the president as
a global leader.
</P>
<P>
   The packed foreign schedule is also coming in a year when the
administration is struggling to accomplish its legislative agenda.
With congressional elections looming in November, a comprehensive
tobacco agreement has eluded Clinton, and some presidential aides
have all but given up on a budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton appeared in the Rose Garden to lay out his
agenda, pressing Congress to act in what he called ``the remaining
38 working days'' of this legislative session. He called on
Congress to approve new money for the International Monetary Fund,
a juvenile crime bill and bills to change the campaign finance
system and the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has a choice to make in writing this chapter of our
history,'' the president said. ``It can choose partisanship, or it
can choose progress. Congress must decide.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president is trying to avoid a vote on another matter
once central to his agenda. House Speaker Newt Gingrich said
recently that he may bring up so-called fast track trade
legislation this fall to give Clinton enhanced authority in
negotiating trade deals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the White House lost a bruising fight for the
legislation, as Democrats deserted Clinton over fears of a backlash
by organized labor and environmental groups against trade deals.
The White House regards Gingrich's proposal as a political ploy,
and on Monday, Clinton made clear that he was in no hurry to see
such a vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
