<HEADER>
A2708 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES-670&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-06 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY EVACUEES RETURN HOME AS FIRES BEGIN TO SUBSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUNNELL, Fla. _ For an excruciating three days, an estimated
35,000 people waited in shelters and hotel rooms just outside
Flagler County, as a result of a mandatory evacuation while
firefighters battled the worst wildfires in Florida's history. On
Monday morning, evacuees collected their photo albums, cats, dogs
and other belongings and came home, most of them, to relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my house was gone,'' said Donna Kerney of Bunnell,
who had thrown a hose and running sprinkler on her roof and fled as
flames neared her neighborhood on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the vast majority of the evacuees, she went home
Monday and found that though parts of her house were burned and
smoke-damaged, it was still habitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the grace of God, it stood,'' said Ms. Kerney, a
37-year-old administrative assistant for the city of Bunnell.
</P>
<P>
   Flagler County's worst-case scenario, that three wildfires
burning out of control would merge and race eastward through the
county all the way to the Atlantic, evaporated in the last few
days. The residents' fear was washed away first by firefighters'
hoses and then by much-anticipated rain.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as the thousands of residents returned to their homes
after cancellation of the mandatory evacuation, some of them
driving through the rain they had prayed for, talk was more about
what might have happened than about what did. Only about 40 homes
were destroyed or damaged in Flagler County, officials said, by
wildfires that consumed almost 50,000 acres, most of it scrub and
forest.
</P>
<P>
   Several families lost everything when their homes went up in
flames, including Beatrice and Gerald Snyder, who celebrated their
47th wedding anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
   Their home in Bunnell was reduced to ashes, along with memories
that spanned a half-century. They can rebuild their home, but
``that isn't going to bring back 47 years of stuff,'' said Mrs.
Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   But the news in most neighborhoods around northern and east
central Florida was better Monday morning, as firefighters and rain
continued to beat back wildfires _ though flare-ups continued in
some places, triggered by lightning strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tide has turned to some extent, at least temporarily,''
said Lt. Gov. Buddy McKay.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 95 and U.S. 1, the main north-south travel routes,
were reopened, though plumes of smoke from new and dwindling fires
continued to rise into the air in Flagler, Volusia and Brevard
counties.
</P>
<P>
   What the parched region had needed most, as wildfires raged
through palmettos, pines and sometimes homes, was rain. ``Every
little bit helps,'' said Ms. Kerney about the brief downpours on
Monday. ``But we need much more than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters have said there is a 50 percent chance of
thundershowers for the region, and more rain is needed if
firefighters are to continue gaining ground. Less than 2 inches
fell in the region. Firefighters said it would take a downpour of
more than 10 inches to put out the remaining fires.
</P>
<P>
   But for many residents here, who had previously been ordered
from their homes by state officials, any good news was welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The past few days ``have been pretty rough,'' said Tom Hubbard,
who manages the Bunnell Thriftway, the town's only supermarket, as
returning residents filled his store, going about the business of
living.
</P>
<P>
   But now the emergencies seemed smaller. The worries were more
about having enough groceries in stock than about whether the
store, which was not damaged, would fall victim to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far,'' he said, ``we've been able to supply everything they
need.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials took time, during the respite, to count the cost
of the wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday evening, 58 fires still burned in Florida, pushing
the total of wildfires to more than 2,000 since May, and the number
of acres burned to 474,462.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag, in property losses has reached $276 million.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 101 people have been injured, almost all of them
firefighters, and 161 homes have been gutted or badly damaged.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Only one person has died. An elderly man in a Flagler County
nursing home died from an apparent heart attack as he was being
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's miraculous that there haven't been more
deaths,'' said McKay.
</P>
<P>
   In Flagler County, people with ruined and damaged houses
wondered how they would pay for the repairs that insurance did not
cover.
</P>
<P>
   John Livingston, 36, came home to find his house damaged but
standing. The heat around the house was so intense that the roof
warped and now leaks.
</P>
<P>
   But he found out Monday that he might qualify for a low-interest
loan from the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a godsend,'' he said. ``I'm glad they're here
for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kerney, like many residents here, is accustomed to wild
weather and even wildfires. But this time was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through the fires in 1985, and I was pretty much used
to it,'' she said. This time, ``we didn't have much time to get
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
