<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARIS-MENS-FASHION-AR     07-06 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-MENS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PERSONAL IN PARIS WITH ROMANTIC VISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Designers working in Paris create such highly personal
collections that it is somewhat surprising that they find an
audience at all for their men's wear collections, which were shown
here last weekend. But they do, because within their peculiarities
often lie the seeds of many fashion visions. It was impossible to
ignore the free and gentle breeze wafting through Paris as
designers led by Yohji Yamamoto and Rei Kawakubo crystallized the
romantic theme shown earlier in Milan, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   For these designers the boundaries between the genders have
always been porous, and the result is an unforced quality to their
artistic designs.
</P>
<P>
   Men, of course, began to be outdressed by women only in the 19th
century with the advent of the suit. In certain tribal societies,
it is perfectly acceptable for male citizens to adorn themselves
fancifully. And to be a romantically dressed 1970s-style rock star
was a powerful fantasy that still resonates strongly for many men.
</P>
<P>
   Yamamoto's graceful collection did not ask men to suspend
reality to that extent. He made the imaginary tangible with hooded
black zippered nylon tunics and trousers that bloused softly at the
narrow ankle, and with crushed suits in stark white or faintly
metallic black in a soft fabric of acrylic and metal. Gently faded
floral jackets skimmed over earthy black pants.
</P>
<P>
   Models, mostly nonprofessionals with emotional ties to each
other _ husband and wife, brother and sister, best friends, all in
men's clothes _ took to the runway as couples, underlining
Yamamoto's theme.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kawakubo, too, chose her models in the Comme des Garcons
show with deliberation, putting the entire line on sweet-faced
young boys, none of whom appeared older than 16. ``Hidden jewels or
secret treasures'' are what she called the striped jackets
imaginatively lined in row upon row of red or teal ruffles.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffles down the front of unblemished white shirts peeked from
beneath jackets and trousers, as it seemed as if the wearer, in a
rush toward something exciting, had pulled them on without
bothering to iron them.
</P>
<P>
   Like any sincere romantic, Ms. Kawakubo sometimes was swept
away, tacking ruffles hither and yon on the outside of jackets that
looked as if they were worn inside out.
</P>
<P>
   The flowering of romantic design has shunted aside minimalism
and pushed dour sub-styles like Goth back underground. The work of
Raf Simons could not truly be said to be emblematic of the
development, but like almost everything in Paris, it was fashion
fantasia. Simons abandoned his Gothic creed and revealed more
clearly how close he had come to his quest for impeccably tailored
jackets and pants that are fit for a raver.
</P>
<P>
   He heightened the experience of viewing his awesome tailoring of
floor-dragging trousers with an inverted pleat down the leg and
long sleeveless jackets by staging a breathtaking show at the Cite
des Sciences et de l'Industrie. The building is mostly glass. More
than 50 models slowly traversed one of the building's high
breezeways, their thin bodies outlined against the Paris skyline,
as the audience, seated on a lower breezeway, viewed them across an
expanse of air.
</P>
<P>
   The collection of the unheralded Joe Casely-Hayford was also
streetwise and individualistic. Few designers were able to make
trouser shorts an alternative as convincingly as Casely-Hayford
did. With elegant sweaters with asymmetrical neckline, wide-leg
wrap-waist trousers in ecru-colored canvas and narrow jeans with
seams that curved in toward the front of the leg, he proved that he
deserves more attention.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment of the season was Dries van Noten, with his
offhand assemblage of indistinct T-shirts, shapeless pants and a
dour green palette. If there was a point to the collection, it was
a dull one, and it was painful that in this, of all seasons, there
was no sign of Van Noten's original romantic vision.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Paul Smith, John Rocha and Hedi Slimane for
Yves Saint Laurent warmed to the moment. Smith mixed embroidered
and floral jackets with jeans and funky drooping trousers, and
Rocha adorned cotton summer jackets with flashes of embroidery and
decorative feather appliques. Slimane evolved the look he began
developing last season, a fluid rarefied approach to men's wear,
with slim-fitting trench coats over languid pants and with refined
tunic shirts open at the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Even Paris' indulgent show of flesh spoke to the kind of
libertine romanticism that the city has encouraged among artists
for generations. Both Thierry Mugler and Shirtology, a company that
plans to open a store in Paris this month, brought their separate
fashion visions to men's swimwear and lingerie _ and, yes, that is
the correct word. In case anyone asks, two-tone swim briefs and
trunks with vertical slashes at the hip are the way to hit the
beach next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Paris could a design company named Shirtology, without a
smidgeon of irony, stage a runway show that included about three
shirts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
