<SLUG> BC-SCI-COW-CLONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE SCIENTISTS SAY THEY'VE CLONED ADULT COWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japanese scientists announced Monday that they had created two
calves that are clones of adult cows. If their claims are correct,
the two calves born on Sunday would be the first clones of adults
after Dolly the sheep, whose birth was announced last year.
</P>
<P>
   But cloning experts were cautious, saying that they had no
reason to doubt the Japanese researchers but that the scientists
have not yet offered evidence that they have cloned adult cows.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitsuo Kita, a senior researcher at the Ishikawa Prefectural
Livestock Research Center in Japan, reported that his group used
much the same method as Dr. Ian Wilmut of the Roslin Institute in
Scotland used to clone Dolly the sheep. They slipped adult cow
cells _ taken, Kita reported, from the uterine tube of a cow _ into
unfertilized cow's eggs whose own genetic material had been
removed. The genes from the adult cells took over and directed the
cells to develop into calves that are genetic identical twins of
the cows whose cells were used for cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Kita's group said they had created pregnancies in five cows. One
gave birth to twins prematurely on Sunday. The others are due to
deliver in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``This method will make it possible to breed a large number of
cattle with high-quality beef of larger milk production,'' Kita
told Agence-France Presse.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dolly was born, a few researchers have questioned whether
she was really cloned from an adult cell, noting that the feat had
not been duplicated. Several calves have been born that were cloned
from fetal cells, but this is considered easier than cloning from
cells of an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Robl, a cloning expert at the University of
Massachusetts in Amherst, who has cloned from calf fetuses but not
yet from adult cows, said that he would like to see more data
before commenting on the Japanese feat. The announcement did not
provide details that are necessary for investigators to assure
themselves that cloning took place. In particular, there is no
evidence that the Japanese have yet done the extensive DNA analysis
of the calves that would prove their genes are exactly the same as
the genes of the cow that was cloned.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Seidel, a cloning expert at the Colorado State
University in Fort Collins, said he was inclined to believe the
announcement. ``The Japanese are pretty careful about the claims
they make and they can muster the resources to do these types of
experiments,'' he said. On the other hand, he said, it is hard to
know how to assess claims published only in a press report.
</P>
<P>
   But, Seidel and others noted, whether or not this particular
announcement stands up, they expect to see more clones of adults in
the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
