<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Men's tour adopts points race for 2000
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men's tennis and stock car racing are on opposite ends of the
sports universe, but the ATP Tour is borrowing from the Winston Cup
circuit to enhance the sport's popularity in the next century. In
2000, there will be an ATP Tour points race and nine
``mini-majors'' to bring the top players together.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans think the ATP's current ranking system is too
complicated, especially when Marcelo Rios loses in the first round
of Wimbledon but could have ascended to No. 1 had Pete Sampras lost
in the Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   The standings approach, approved last week, will be based on
points earned to date in a calendar year. The 12-month rankings
will be maintained for seeding purposes only.
</P>
<P>
   If a standings format were in effect this year, it would bring
to life Sampras' quest for a record sixth straight final No. 1
ranking. The record is the five in a row held by Sampras and Jimmy
Connors (1974-78). In the ``standings,'' Sampras broke the top 10
this week only after winning Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Another change announced by the ATP Tour last week is the
requirement that all players who qualify for the four majors and
the Super 9 events must play them or receive a mandatory zero in
their ``best 14'' results that count toward rankings. Under the
current system, Rios' first-round loss isn't figured into his
ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't play, he doesn't score,'' ATP Tour CEO Mark
Miles said about the new plan. ``I don't think that's an odd
concept in sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuveen wins for Pernfors
</P>
<P>
   Mikael Pernfors got his first victories on the Nuveen Tour last
week in Finland, beating Guillermo Vilas and Veli Paloheimo.
Pernfors, along with Bjorn Borg and Connors, plans to play in
Atlanta's Nuveen Tour stop Sept. 30-Oct. 4 at Atlanta Athletic
Club. ... Tough loss for Atlanta's Ellis Ferreira at Wimbledon. He
and Rick Leach lost in the doubles quarterfinals to Jonas Bjorkman
and Patrick Rafter 5-7, 7-5, 6-3, 6-4, 11-9.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson rushes home
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Davis Cup captain Tom Gullikson pulled out of the
45-and-over doubles final Sunday at Wimbledon to rush home to
Florida, where his home is threatened by wildfires. Gullikson's
family lives in Flagler County. ... Little chance it will happen,
but Todd Martin should be considered the No. 2 singles player for
the U.S. team's Davis Cup match against Belgium. Martin is up to
No. 30 while Jim Courier is floundering at No. 45. It's assumed
Andre Agassi will play No. 1 singles and that Martin and Richey
Reneberg will be the doubles team in the July 17-19 match in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Tim Henman gets a $3.3 million bonus from his equipment sponsor,
Slazenger, if he reaches the top 10. His semifinal loss to Sampras
prevented that this week, but he did improve five spots to a
career-high No. 13. ... Jana Novotna moved up a spot to No. 2 in
the rankings, matching her career high. Nathalie Tauziat is No. 10,
also matching her best. Anna Kournikova dropped out of the top 10
to No. 15 after withdrawing because of a thumb injury. ...
Wimbledon's total attendance was down almost 12,000 this year.
World Cup soccer and the early loss of such stars as Steffi Graf,
Serena Williams, Kournikova, Greg Rusedski and Agassi didn't help.
... In the Sampras-Goran Ivanisevic final, there were 182 points
ended on serve _ 44 aces, 110 service winners and 28 double faults
_ an average of 3.4 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
