<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pressure Pak ending at the Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ The Open That Wouldn't Close finally became
another major championship for 20-year-old Se Ri Pak Monday. It
took 92 holes and five days. It took the South Korean making bogey
from ankle deep water. It took Duke senior-to-be Jenny
Chuasiriporn, despite the loss, to the pinnacle of her athletic
life.
</P>
<P>
   It even took Pak, who on the course is icy and emotionless, to
tears when her 18-foot putt found the cup for birdie on the second
hole of the first sudden-death playoff in tournament history,
giving her the U.S. Women's Open title at the Blackwolf Run Golf
Course.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, the first Asian to win the title, became the youngest
champion (20) in U.S. Women's Open history; the first LPGA rookie
to win two majors in a season since Juli Inkster in 1984; and the
first since Meg Mallon in 1991 to win consecutive majors. With
Chuasiriporn an amateur, Pak already had secured the professional
winner's check of $267,500 before the start of Monday's 18-hole
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really surprise myself because this is my first year and I
just really start,'' Pak said. ``The first time I win a major (the
McDonald's LPGA Championship in May), I surprise myself. Maybe some
people thinking I am lucky. Now I win the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my trophy here. Now the dream is true. It's come to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak came back after trailing Chuasiriporn by four shots through
five holes of the playoff. Chuasiriporn, also 20, was foiled by a
triple-bogey at the 6th hole that allowed Pak to get back into the
match. After the stunning 45-foot putt Sunday that pushed her into
the playoff, Chuasiriporn displayed a carryover of momentum,
chipping in for birdie at the first hole and sinking an 8-footer
for birdie at No. 2. But at the par-3 6th, when her pulled 9-iron
wound up in unplayable high grass, the story changed. She re-teed,
made a wild approach putt and finally made 6. Pak parred for a
three-shot swing. The Korean finally tied the match at the 12th
with a 15-foot birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Although No. 11, the 92nd hole, offically decided the
tournament, the difficult, 421-yard 18th was as crucial. Pak only
made the most important bogey of her life there.
</P>
<P>
   After driving into high grass in the hazard area next to the
Sheboygan River, Pak, after about 10 minutes of studying the
situation, hit out cleanly with a sand wedge, but into the right
rough. Hitting to the green in three with an 8-iron, Pak two-putted
for bogey. Chuasiriporn smartly hit her second shot away from the
water hazard, but then chipped too strong to the right fringe, 15
feet past the cup. Admitting that her hands were shaking,
Chuasiriporn pushed the putt slightly and missed, giving both
players 2-over 73's and pushing the match to extra holes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
