<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR, TRUCK SALES IN U.S. AT HIGHEST RATE IN 10 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic on auto sales in June is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. on Monday reported a 9.8 percent increase in June
car and light-truck sales from June 1997, pushing total U.S. car
and truck sales last month to a seasonally adjusted annual selling
rate of 16.7 million, its highest rate in more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. vehicle sales for the month totaled 1,570,355 cars and
light trucks, a 14.1 percent increase from June 1997, the best
month since September 1986, according to Ward's Automotive Reports,
which calculates percentage changes on a daily selling rate. Last
month had one more selling day than did June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of both cars and trucks increased, though truck sales were
substantially higher. Car sales totaled 818,604 units, up 6.4
percent from June 1997; light-truck sales were 751,751 units, up
23.9 percent. The seasonally adjusted annual selling rate of 16.7
million cars and trucks was the highest level since August 1987,
when the rate was 16.8 million cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Ford reported that its Ford, Mercury, Lincoln and Jaguar
divisions sold 406,991 cars and light trucks in June, a 9.8 percent
increase from June 1997. Ford's car sales totaled 169,278 vehicles,
up two-tenths of 1 percent from a year earlier. Ford's light-truck
sales were 237,713 units, up 17.9 percent. Ford's total truck sales
set an all-time monthly record for any manufacturer and beat
General Motors Corp.'s truck sales by a scant 1,346 units.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of GM's North American assembly operations are closed
because of two strikes by the United Automobile Workers union at
parts-making operations in Flint, Mich. In addition, three of its
North American truck plants are in the process of being converted
to produce a new version of its full-size pickup truck, which is
scheduled for release in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was the last automaker to report sales. Nearly every major
vehicle manufacturer, most of which reported sales last week,
experienced higher sales in June compared with the month a year
earlier. The Chrysler Corp. set a new monthly sales record, selling
252,485 cars and trucks, a 10.5 percent increase. Toyota sales
totaled 117,043 cars and trucks, up 17.2 percent, setting a new
June record. Honda also set a new June record, with 88,928 vehicles
sold, an increase of 7.7 percent. Also reporting higher sales for
June were Isuzu, Kia Motors, Mercedes-Benz, Mitsubishi, Porsche,
Subaru of America, Suzuki, Volkswagen and Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Only Saab (which includes its sales in GM's total), Nissan,
Hyundai and BMW had lower sales this June compared with June 1997;
BMW had higher car sales but lower sales of sports utility vehicles
at its Land Rover division.
</P>
<P>
   The extremely strong sales in May and June, however, may be
short-lived, according to analysts. ``July sales will collapse,''
predicted David Healy, an analyst with Burnham Securities Inc. in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   GM sales are expected to drop between 30 percent and 40 percent
this month compared with July 1997 because of the strikes, Ronald
L. Zarrella, vice president in charge of GM's North American
Vehicle Sales, Service and Marketing Group, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle sales in May and June were partly fueled by attractive
incentives, some of which ended this month. GM has announced that
it will not renew its customer loyalty program. In mid-April, GM
sent former GM buyers certificates of $500 to $1,000 to use toward
the purchase of specific GM vehicles, above and beyond other cash
rebates and low-financing charges as incentives. The highly
successful program was an effort to rebuild GM's U.S. market share,
which had fallen below 30 percent early in the year; the program
pushed it over the 30 percent mark. Now, GM does not need
incentives because its inventory on dealership lots is running out
because of the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Chrysler had matched GM's program with their own
customer loyalty plans, which included acceptance of GM
certificates. Chrysler's program was to expire Monday at midnight,
and the automaker is expected to announce its future incentive plan
on Tuesday. Ford's program also expires Tuesday and the company is
expected to announce if it plans to renew the incentive program.
Analysts, however, expect both companies to follow GM's lead and
end the loyalty programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
