<HEADLINE>
WORRIES OVER JAPAN AND U.S. SEND TREASURIES HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Concerns about Japan and signs of a slowdown in the
United States sent Treasury prices higher Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 12/32, to 107 31/32.
The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, fell to 5.57 percent, from 5.60 percent Thursday, matching
the low set on June 15 _ the lowest it has been since the
government began regular sales of securities in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Monday's gains came from overnight weakness in the
Japanese yen compared with the dollar, amid speculation that Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto of Japan was not promising permanent tax
cuts. Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of the
fixed-income department at J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca
Raton, Fla., called Monday's session extremely quiet with light
trading after the July 4 holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bias is toward higher prices,'' he said, ``especially with
all the positive information about inflation. The market's positive
tone has a lot to do with foreign buying and the strength of the
dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about $32.9 billion of bills, notes and bonds were traded
by the major brokerage firms by late in the day, down 35.1 percent
from the average Monday during the third quarter of 1997, according
to GovPx, the bond-pricing service.
</P>
<P>
   Pugliese does not expect anything to rock the market in the near
term, with the exception perhaps of a few reactions to news
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally the market is strong, and many believe there are
more than a half-dozen reasons why the market will continue to do
well,'' he said. ``Yields are probably where they should be, based
on the present scenario. So we should be in a trading range this
week with an upward bias on prices. Any new type of negative news
is going to bring in buyers at any level.''
</P>
<P>
   The only major economic data expected this week are Friday's
Producer Price Index for June, which some analysts expect to be
unchanged for both the overall and the core numbers.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp increase in drug prices in May contributed to the 0.2
percent gain in the overall and core indexes, and some analysts
believe that prescription prices could continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's regular weekly bill auction of new three-month and
six-month bills was uneventful, with the average rate for a
three-month maturity 4.960 percent. The six-month bill produced an
average rate of 5.010 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
