<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-ROGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROY ROGERS, 86, KING OF THE COWBOYS, OF HEART FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roy Rogers, the singing ``King of the Cowboys'' whose straight
shooting in movies and, particularly, in television made him a hero
to generations of young fans, died Monday at his home in Apple
Valley, Calif., at the age of 86.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rogers died of congestive heart failure, according to a
spokeswoman, Jane Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   Born Leonard Slye on Nov. 5., 1911, in Cincinnati, Mr. Rogers
drove a truck and picked peaches during the Depression to make ends
meet. Eventually, he entered show business as a country singer with
the Sons of the Pioneers, before he landed a $75-a-week job in 1937
as singing cowboy at Hollywood's Republic Studio. Armed with a
guitar, six-shooters, and charm, he was the No.1 Western star at
the box office from 1943 until 1954. He made 87 Westerns in all,
and in them, he was the cowboy who fought fair, never killed the
bad guys but only shot the gun out of their hands and lived to sing
about it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But it was in television that Mr. Rogers made his biggest
mark, and where the twinkle in his eyes and his good-guy smile had
the most impact. Following Gene Autry and ``The Lone Ranger'' onto
network TV, ``The Roy Rogers Show,'' ran on Sundays at 6:30 p.m.
from 1951 to 1957 on NBC. It inspired a following of boys and girls
to dress in cowboy and cowgirl garb and send away for all kinds of
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   In many films and in the television series, he costarred with
Dale Evans, whom he married in 1947. She was the co-writer of
``Happy Trails to You,'' which became their theme song. Featured
were his famous palomino horse, Trigger &UR;  &LR; (who was later stuffed and
placed in Rogers's museum), his dog, Bullet, and Evans's horse,
Buttermilk. His sidekick in films was the bewhisk-ered Gabby Hayes,
in television, Pat Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a blessing to have shared my life together with him for
almost 51 years,'' said Evans. She and Mr. Rogers married 14 months
after his first wife, Arlene, died. Evans, born Frances Octavia
Smith in Uvalde, Texas, became known as ``Queen of the Cowgirls.''
</P>
<P>
   Others paid their tributes to Mr. Rogers as well. President
Clinton said, ``I really appreciate what he stood for, the movies
he made, and the kind of values they embodied. Today there will be
a lot of sad and grateful Americans, especially of my generation,
because of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible loss for me,'' said cowboy crooner Gene
Autry, 90. ``I had tremendous respect for Roy and considered him a
great humanitarian and an outstanding American. He was, and will
always be, a true Western hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Moore, the 83-year-old actor who played the Lone Ranger,
said: ``He certainly was a role model for people all over the
world. Just a good, straightforward man. He always treated people
with kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an introvert at heart,'' Mr. Rogers once said. ``And show
business _ even though I've loved it so much _ has always been hard
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rogers was a co-founder of Sons of the Pioneers, which had a
couple of radio hits in the '30s, ``Tumbling Tumbleweeds'' and
``Cool Water.'' Mr. Rogers kept up his musical career in recent
years, releasing an album of old and new songs, ``Tribute,'' in
1991. The album featured country superstar Clint Black (a Rogers
lookalike) as a guest singer on one cut, ``Hold On Partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rogers and Evans became well known for their Christian
beliefs and spoke at many religious gatherings, including some of
evangelist Billy Graham's revivals.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had nine children, which brought pain as well as
happiness to their lives. Their daughter Robin, who was mentally
retarded, died of complications of the mumps shortly before her
second birthday in 1952. Korean-born Debbie, one of the couple's
adopted children, was killed with seven others in a 1964 church bus
crash, and the following year, their adopted son John choked to
death while serving in the Army in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Bible, it doesn't say you're going to get by without
having troubles,'' Mr. Rogers once said. ``I'm not a fanatic about
religion. I think it's a practical way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   His sense of fairness was tested when Herbert Yates, then
president of Republic Pictures, sold some of Mr. Rogers's movies to
television in the early '50s. Mr. Rogers thought he was due
residuals and took Republic to court. Mr. Rogers lost the battle in
the US Supreme Court, but he fired an important salvo for the
rights of actors regarding ancillary rights.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rogers also pioneered marketing. He and a fellow TV cowboy,
Hop-along Cassidy, realized that their names meant something in the
open market. Eventually, Mr. Rogers had his name on everything from
clocks and bedspreads to wristwatches and lunch boxes, but said he
never put his name on a product he didn't believe in.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rogers leaves is wife, Evans; Roy Rogers Jr., his son from
his first marriage; Linda Lou Johnson, a daughter from his first
marriage; Cheryl Barnett, an adopted daughter from his first
marriage; Dodie Sailors, an adopted daughter from his marriage to
Evans; 15 grandchildren and 33 great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2036EDT &QL; 
