<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM LIFTS S&AMP;P 500 TO A HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investor optimism that corporate earnings would
continue to grow and interest rates would remain near historic lows
lifted stocks higher Monday, with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index reaching another closing record.
</P>
<P>
   Led by gains in shares of Lucent Technologies, Home Depot,
Coca-Cola and Merck, the S&AMP;P 500 index rose 10.89 points, to
1,157.31.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are thinking there won't be too many disasters out
there,'' Jim Benning, a trader at Bankers Trust, said of the
quarterly profit reports, which are to begin appearing in earnest
next week.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, investors are not likely to be disappointed.
Traditionally, most companies that anticipate earnings shortfalls
soften the blow by warning investors well in advance of the actual
earnings reports. Stocks then are likely to fall on the forecast,
but may rise if actual earnings are no worse than expected.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, actual earnings normally beat expectations by about
2 percent to 3 percent, according to First Call Corp., which
compiles analysts' forecasts. Therefore, near-term, beating the
estimates should only be bullish if 4 percent or more of the
companies in the S&AMP;P 500 do so, First Call said in a recent market
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   A large amount of the investor euphoria on Monday also was
fueled by a decline in long-term interest rates. On Monday, the
yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.57 percent. That
matched its level on June 15, which was the lowest yield on the
security since the Treasury began issuing bonds on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Lower yields enable companies to borrow at lower rates and are
expected to increase capital expenditures and to aid in lifting
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not expecting much pricing power, so you're just
going to have to act smarter and build smarter'' in order to lift
corporate profits, Benning said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average increased 66.51
points, to 9,091.77, marking its third consecutive close above
9,000 since early June. The Nasdaq composite index, which is
heavily laden with technology issues, rose 15.47 points, to
1,909.47, and is just 8.14 points away from its April 22 record.
Microsoft, Ericsson and Compuware led the charge.
</P>
<P>
   In one sign of slowing economic growth, the National Association
of Purchasing Management said its index of nonmanufacturing
business activity fell to 61.5 in June from 64 in May. Readings
above 50 mean business is still expanding, thus investors viewed
the moderate June decline as positive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
