</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-GERMANY-DRUG-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST GERMAN SPORTS DOCTOR TELLS OF ISSUING STEROIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A former East German sports doctor admitted Monday in a
Berlin court that he handed out anabolic steroids for use by young
female swimmers, the first formal confession of such practices by
an official of the Communist state that once churned out
gold-medal-winning athletes with bizarre consistency.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, Dieter Binus said that the doses of the
steroids never exceeded 1,000 milligrams a year, an amount that he
contended was too small to harm the young swimmers. He denied
giving testosterone injections or other drugs to the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Binus, a 59-year-old Berlin physician, was testifying at a trial
in which he, another doctor and four coaches are accused of
seriously injuring 19 athletes through the forced use of steroids.
Despite his disclaimers, the doctor's admission that steroids were
used amounted to an extraordinary breakthrough for prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   All of the defendants at the trial, which opened in March, had
denied the charges. But last week, Binus reached an agreement with
the state prosecutor, Rudiger Hillebrand, in which he agreed to
testify about the use of steroids in return for a lighter sentence
if convicted. The maximum sentence he faces is a fine.
</P>
<P>
   The trial amounts to the culmination of a long and divisive
investigation into what prosecutors believe was the state-sponsored
use of steroids by the former East Germany as part of a campaign to
attain athletic excellence that would reflect favorably on the
former Communist state.
</P>
<P>
   For many years before the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, East
Germany, with only 16 million inhabitants, consistently won an
extraordinary number of gold medals in swimming and track events.
But suspicions that drugs were behind the glory were never
definitively proved.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1976 Olympics in Montreal, when the U.S. men won 12 of
their 13 events, the U.S. women, despite breaking eight U.S.
records, won only one of 13 events. East Germans won 11 events and
a Russian won the other.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Monday's testimony, Jack Nelson, the head coach of
the 1976 U.S. women's Olympic team, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is glorious. It's all sad, but it's also great because
our women who did so fantastically well in 1976 may not get their
rightful reward. It doesn't matter who gave the German doctors the
orders to use steroids. It was wrong. It just breaks my heart that
the United States has never saluted the greatest women's swimming
team it's ever had. Shirley Babashoff would have won four gold
medals and would have broken four world records if it was a level
playing field. It just surprises me how long it's taken for this to
come out and how long our own representatives in the United States
haven't gone to bat for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Weilgus, executive director of U.S. Swimming, the national
governing body, said that ``once this is settled in the German
court system we'd like to find an appropriate way, and I'm not sure
what that is yet, to recognize these American athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean asking the International Olympic Committee to
give gold medals to those swimmers from the United States and
elsewhere who were denied them because of drug use by East Germans?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our board has talked about that,'' he said. ``We have no
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the 19 female athletes called as witnesses at the
Berlin trial have said their bodies became more masculine as a
result of ``little blue pills'' they were made to take. They said
they suffered unnatural body hair, voice changes, severe acne and
abnormal muscle growth.
</P>
<P>
   According to secret files recovered from the Stasi, the East
German secret police, some women were ordered to abort fetuses that
might have been deformed by the drugs. Rica Reinisch, an Olympic
gold-medal swimmer, has said she was given steroids at age 12
without knowing what they were and now suffers from ovarian cysts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reading a statement, Binus said he did not give the pills to the
athletes himself, but would hand them to coaches who were charged
with making sure the swimmers took what were then known as the
``supporting means.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that as a doctor for the Dynamo Berlin team from 1969
to 1986, he did not have the authority to decide whether the
performance-enhancing drugs should be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only an official carrying out orders,'' Binus said,
suggesting that the orders came from the doctors' commission in the
national swimming association.
</P>
<P>
   He added that his co-defendant, Dr. Bernd Pansold, who was one
of the association's doctors, decided which athletes should receive
the drugs. Pansold, who continues to deny the charges, did not
testify Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It seems clear that Binus' confession will bolster a case that
the prosecution hopes will eventually lead to the trial of senior
former East German officials.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the use of steroids, begun in 1993, has
already caused anger among former East German leaders. Egon Krenz,
East Germany's last Communist leader, has said the trial is ``about
revenge because East Germany was better at sport than West
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes from many other countries, including the United States,
have been found to have taken steroids, but the apparently
systematic nature of the East German program, and its extent,
remain without obvious parallel.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Venedey, Binus' lawyer, said in a telephone interview
that it was very difficult to say where the real responsibility for
the policy of using steroids lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several levels of the authority in the former East
Germany, and my client will not attempt to say where orders
ultimately came from,'' Venedey said.
</P>
<P>
   Binus is scheduled to testify again on Monday and a verdict is
expected before the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LIABILITY-NYT &LR;      07-06 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LIABILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN-CONTROL ADVOCATES THREATENING TO DERAIL DAMAGE-CAP
LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., W.Va., N.J., Calif., Mo.)  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gun control advocates who want the firearms
industry to be held responsible for gun-related injuries or deaths
are threatening a fragile agreement on broad legislation that would
affect lawsuits against manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, scheduled for debate in the Senate this week,
would place a cap of $250,000 on the punitive damages that small
businesses would have to pay in cases involving faulty products.
The limit on damages, opposed by consumers, is part of a broader
product-liability bill that businesses have been seeking for nearly
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The White House helped negotiate the bill after President
Clinton two years ago vetoed an earlier version that would have
capped damages paid by companies of all sizes. The pending version
defines small businesses as those that employ fewer than 25 people
and have annual revenues of less than $5 million a year.
Gun-control advocates say that nearly one in five guns sold in the
United States is made by a small company, and that two of the guns
manufactured by small companies rank among the top 10 weapons found
at crime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gun forces fear that the punitive damage limits on small
businesses would derail their larger efforts to hold the gun
industry accountable, in much the same way as the anti-smoking
forces have stepped up pressure on the tobacco industry. Just as
those forces found their voice in the state attorneys general, the
gun control advocates hope that big-city mayors can carry their
banner with lawsuits against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Their concerns have persuaded two Democratic senators, normally
allies of Clinton, to propose exempting the gun makers from the
protections offered by the bill. That proposal could drive away
supporters of the broader liability legislation, vastly
complicating propsects for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Reilly, a spokeswoman for the National Federation of
Small Business, said that any changes in the language of the bill
could scuttle the entire legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for gun manufacturers say that the caps on damages
would affect only a small percentage of firearms makers and is
irrelevant because these companies routinely win lawsuits
contending that they have negligently marketed their products. The
manufacturers support the product-liability bill as part of what
they say is a much-needed overhaul of the litigation process.
</P>
<P>
   While consumer advocates, including Ralph Nader, oppose the bill
on grounds that the measure makes it more difficult for consumers
to recover damages, the business community is split.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses view the proposed legislation as a relief from
excessive litigation. Even for larger companies, the bill would
raise the standards of proof for a consumer to be eligible to
recoup damages. But some large companies _ like chemical producers
and automobile manufacturers, which have substantial liability
exposure _ wanted the same protection against high punitive damages
that smaller businesses would receive.
</P>
<P>
   The bill could pose a political dilemma for many Democrats and
some suburban Republicans who want to be responsive to the concerns
of small businesses but whose support for gun control can be an
important distinction in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Blurring the picture further are the competing interests behind
the bill: It is strongly backed by the National Federation of
Independent Business, a powerful lobbying group for small business,
while it is strongly opposed by the trial lawyers, who tend to make
large financial donations to Democrats. (Trial lawyers have been
particularly generous to Clinton, who in this case is going against
their wishes.)
</P>
<P>
   The White House helped hammer out the bill in an agreement with
Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and John Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va. Nader
said the White House ``bollixed'' the bill by making proposals that
it did not expect Gorton to accept. And two Democratic senators _
Robert Torricelli of New Jersey and Dianne Feinstein of California
_ expect to sponsor an amendment that would exempt the entire gun
industry from the limits. The bill already exempts tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Those 12 firearms companies made 17 percent of all guns sold in
the United States between 1990 and 1995, according to an analysis
by the Violence Policy Center, a nonprofit group in Washington that
promotes gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In that same period, the 12 companies made 23 percent of all
.38-caliber pistols, which are the most popular caliber. And they
made two of the top 10 guns that are found at crime scenes, the
center said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official conceded that the bill's failure to
exempt the gun industry ``complicates things because the president
has been so strong on guns,'' but insisted this was not an
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   And other backers of the bill asserted that it offered no
substantive protection for gun makers. ``These are just folks who
don't like this bill and are looking for ways to tear it down,''
said Victor Schwartz, counsel for the Product Liability
Coordinating Committee, which has been seeking similar, if
stronger, legislation for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no situation where any of these gun manufacturers have
paid punitive damages anywhere near the cap,'' he said. ``It's a
completely bogus argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats in both the Senate and the House already oppose
the larger bill but on other grounds _ they see it as
anti-consumer. Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic
leader, told Clinton in a recent letter that the bill was a ``grave
mistake'' and would limit consumer rights for the sake of a myth
that businesses are burdened by an excess of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, director of federal policy for the Violence Policy
Center, said that gun-control advocates are trying to formulate a
new legal line based on the tobacco cases _ not that guns are
defective but that the manufacturers are knowingly marketing a
dangerous product. Although the bill deals only with product
liability, she said that even this limit on lawsuits against gun
manufacturers would be a setback to the anti-gun movement.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Feldman, executive director of the American Shooting
Sports Council, which represents the gun industry, said that the
bill would have little effect. And he dismissed the attempt to
mimic the success of anti-tobacco groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very important distinction between tobacco and
firearms,'' he said. ``When you use tobacco as it is intended to be
used, it is harmful; when you use a firearm as intended, not only
is it not harmful to the user, it can save the user's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
