<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEEN ACCUSED OF SETTING BOY, 8, ON FIRE SOBS IN COURT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAUL McKAY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONROE, Texas _ A 13-year-old boy accused of setting an
8-year-old neighbor on fire sobbed Monday when a judge announced
that he will remain in custody on allegations of aggravated
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Retired state District Judge John Martin also said in a court
hearing that Don W. Collins will be detained for at least a week on
related accusations of injury to a child in the June 28 attack on
Robert Ray Middleton.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Robert has named Collins as the
one who attacked him on a wooded trail in the east Montgomery
County subdivision where the boys are next-door neighbors. Sources
have said that Collins had threatened to hurt Robert after the
younger boy told his father that Collins had stolen his fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   About a month earlier, Robert reportedly had told people that he
had seen Collins molest a child in the woods in their neighborhood
near Splendora, about 30 miles north of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Robert was listed in critical but stable condition Monday at the
Shriners Burns Hospital-Galveston after undergoing one of the
numerous skin-graft surgeries that doctors say he will need in a
recovery that will take years.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered third-degree burns over 99 percent of his body after
being doused with a flammable liquid and set afire on his 8th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked in Monday's court hearing by two sisters and an uncle,
who massaged his shoulders as he stood before the judge, Collins
lowered his head and wept as Martin announced that he had appointed
Conroe lawyer William ``Bill'' Hall, who was unable to attend the
hearing, to defend him. Martin set another hearing for July 14.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his age, Collins cannot be certified to stand trial
as an adult, Montgomery County prosecutor Bill Pattillo said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that Collins will be prosecuted under the
Determinate Sentencing Act. That means that if he is convicted of
aggravated assault, which carries a maximum sentence of 20 years,
or of injury to a child and given a maximum sentence of 40 years, a
judge would determine when he turns 18 whether he should serve out
the full sentence in an adult prison.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Collins has admitted being present when
Robert, who was headed down the wooded trail to meet a 9-year-old
friend, was doused with a flammable liquid _ presumed to be
gasoline _ and set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Collins reportedly has tried to place at least some of the blame
on a younger boy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether any others are considered suspects at this point,
prosecutor Mike Valdez said, ``We anticipate that Robert is going
to be able to give us the whole story eventually, so the
investigation will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   According to probable-cause documents, Robert was asked who had
set him on fire when he regained consciousness and was taken off a
ventilator Thursday morning. According to the documents, he told
his mother and two nurses at the Galveston hospital that ``Don did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents note that investigators last week were seeking a
warrant to search the home of a relative where Collins has been
living for ``a gasoline can or other devices'' capable of
containing flammable liquids.
</P>
<P>
   No such container has been found either at the home where
Collins was staying or in the woods where Robert was burned,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, meanwhile, advised Collins' half sister, April Collins,
and an uncle, John Horn, to have someone in the family pursue legal
custody of the teen-ager, who currently has no legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   April Collins, 24, said her mother died about three years ago.
Her half brother's father, she said, is ``nowhere to be found.''
</P>
<P>
   Horn, who owns a glass business in Cleveland, Texas, and April
Collins insist that the teen is not responsible for the crime. Horn
complained Monday that authorities have not allowed him and the
other relatives to see the teen, telling reporters that ``you seem
to know more about everything than we ever thought about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
