<SLUG> BC-OPENSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This time, hole keeps Pak's hopes alive
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Jenny Chuasiriporn knows a comfort zone when she
sees one. She had a feeling that the 18th hole, which had allowed
her a 45-foot bomb the day before, would be her spot to either win
the U.S. Women's Open in Monday's playoff or see it slide away on
the holes of sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   These Duke kids are usually pretty smart. Indeed, the 18th
proved clean out of miracles for the 20-year-old amateur. When it
looked like Chuasiriporn had a par wrapped up on Blackwolf Run's
421-yard 18th, it became a bogey. When it looked like Se Ri Pak was
doomed there, hitting from the bank of the water hazard, she
somehow manufactured a bogey to tie.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour later, with experience becoming a larger factor with
each passing moment, Pak sank an 18-foot putt on the second playoff
hole to secure the U.S. Women's Open title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to watch,'' Chuasiriporn said. ``I really had
a sixth sense she was going to make that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chuasiriporn's 15-foot par try at the 18th curled just
above the hole, she knew the magnitude of the opportunity that had
just gotten away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had the putt, but my hands were shaking a lot,''
Chuasiriporn said. ``I thought that was going to be it, but it
didn't turn out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The final result notwithstanding, Chuasiriporn left Wisconsin
with no regrets. Barely noticede when the week started, she nearly
left with the USGA hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty satisfied with the way I handled it,'' she said.
``I mean, it was so stressful at times this week. This is just
another thing to build my confidence and my mental game. Everything
is just a big plus coming out of this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, a psychology major, said she probably will turn
pro after she graduates. The big surprise would be if she didn't.
Especially now that she's gained some Matt Kuchar-like notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as though in a year's time I'll probably give it a
chance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Chuasiriporn had desired to play the Women's Open as a
pro, she could not have done so. Because her spot was earned as a
member of the Curtis Cup team, she was only eligible as an amateur.
Several of her Curtis Cup team members followed her in the gallery,
along with her parents, brother Jimmy, 10, and Duke coach Dan
Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn played with golf balls bearing a University of
Virginia Cavalier logo. A friend of Virginia's Louis Chitengwa, she
lost a putting contest with him at a UVA golf camp last week and,
according to the wager, had to display his logo instead of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance record
</P>
<P>
   The tournament set a U.S. Women's Open for attendance, drawing
115,000 over four days at Blackwolf Run, breaking last year's mark
of 109,000 at Pumpkin Ridge near Portland, Ore. ``On a scale of
10,'' said past USGA president Judy Bell, ``it (the event) was a
60.''... About 10,000 people attended Monday's playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
