<SLUG> BC-AIR-NAVIGATION-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA SEEKING TO INSTALL NEW NETWORK OF NAVIGATION AIDS TO REPLACE
RADIO BEACONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration is trying to
replace its aging nationwide network of radio beacons and other
navigation aids with a satellite-based system that is simpler, more
accurate, and less expensive to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   But it is running into a problem: some aviation experts think
that the new system will not be reliable, and they want the
government to maintain both the new and the old.
</P>
<P>
   The old system is a network of more than a thousand radio
beacons, used like lighthouses, in long-distance navigation, a
similar number of radio aids that help airplanes approach runways,
and about 100 long-distance radars, used to help controllers on the
ground determine the location of planes.
</P>
<P>
   The existing equipment costs more than $100 million a year to
maintain. Much of it, though, will reach the end of its useful life
in the next few years, and would cost billions of dollars to
replace.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the aviation agency wants to replace its beacons and
radars with an enhanced version of the Global Positioning System, a
network of satellites launched by the Pentagon that sends location
signals. Inexpensive receivers sold at electronics stores can
pinpoint a position to within a few yards, and the receivers are in
wide use in pleasure boats, trucks, and even farm tractors.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA is spending $475 million on a supplemental system that
would let airplanes use the signal to find their way to within a
few hundred feet of runways. If the new system cuts delays, it
could save the airlines hundreds of millions of dollars a year.
Proponents say it will let planes fly closer together and land
safely in low-visibility weather, because of greater certainty
about where they are.
</P>
<P>
   But some air traffic experts say that the older, less
sophisticated system has an advantage. Decentralized, strong, and
simple, it can withstand the loss of several radio beacons or
radars. On most days, in fact, it does.
</P>
<P>
   Langhorne Bond, the administrator of the FAA from 1977 to 1981,
said at a recent conference that the Global Positioning System,
although accurate and cheap, could easily be jammed by a terrorist
or a hostile power, and could even be subject to inadvertent
interference, partly because it uses low-power signals.
</P>
<P>
   Bond also expressed concern that moving to the GPS would mean
that a single method would tell an airplane and controllers where
the plane is, tasks now accomplished by separate systems. ``They're
creating the mother of all single-thread systems there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cluster of jammers, some floated in weather balloons, would
destroy all GPS navigation and approach-guidance for hundreds of
airliners'' as well as private aircraft, Bond said. When visibility
was poor, he said, ``many of them, perhaps most of them, would
crash without back-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials agree that radio interference, deliberate or
accidental, could be a hazard. They said they are already studying
what backup system they should retain.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA wants to eventually abandon radio beacons, called VHF
omnidirectional radios, which send a radio signal to each degree on
the compass. The FAA would also like to abandon 1,100 instrument
landing systems, which guide aircraft approaching runways.
</P>
<P>
   By next March, the FAA plans to accept delivery of a network of
receivers on the ground that will be used to help reduce the margin
of error in the Global Positioning System. The system should start
in about a year and be fully operational by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That system, accurate to about 20 feet over the continental
United States, is called the Wide Area Augmentation System. Later,
the FAA plans a Local Area Augmentation System, with ground-based
receivers calculating errors and broadcasting a correction factor
over an area of a few square miles, that would be accurate enough
to guide planes to runways in near-zero visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The local augmentation system would be far cheaper than existing
instrument landing systems, and a single unit could provide
guidance for all the runways within several miles. Existing
instrument landing systems are good for only a single runway.
</P>
<P>
   Global positioning would also eventually replace radar. Planes
carrying GPS receivers would know their location to within a few
feet, and broadcast that to all other planes and to controllers on
the ground. And it is a crucial part of a new system for avoiding
crashes into mountains, with an instrument that continuously
compares the plane's position and route against a database of the
world's mountains.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 planes, most of them small private aircraft,
already use GPS for navigation. The FAA has given only limited
approval for the system's use in airliners, mostly over ocean
routes, where there is no ground-based beacon system.
</P>
<P>
   One possible back-up is a radio-based navigation system called
Loran-C, maintained by the Coast Guard for ships and widely used by
private planes, but the Transportation Department is planning to
replace that, with GPS. Congress has directed the Transportation
Department to study Loran's future.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Joseph Canny, the deputy assistant secretary for transportation
policy at the Transportation Department, said in a telephone
interview that when the FAA decided to pursue the wide area
augmentation system, ``an important part of the cost justification
is that they would expect when that system is in place, to be able
to phase out a substantial part of the ground-based systems.
</P>
<P>
   But officials are now saying that they may, in fact, have to
maintain at least part of the existing system, or develop an
entirely new back-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues on the table is whether we would need some
sort of backup system,'' said Daniel Salvano, the FAA's acting
director for the Office of Communication, Navigation and
Surveillance Systems. ``We haven't finalized our position.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, even if GPS cannot suffice alone, it must be
installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of countries are moving towards satellite systems,'' he
said, and if the Untied States does not do the same, ``we will have
the potential of having different types of equipment on board our
aircraft that fly internationally, and when they fly into our
airspace, they will have to have different equipment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
