<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-AD-COLUMN-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SELLING BASEBALL _ WITH A SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As major-league baseball heads into the All-Star Game on Tuesday
night, an agency that specializes in selling with a smile is
seeking to help the sport improve its image.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners, the New York shop that is expert in
humorous campaigns, has introduced a series of offbeat commercials
for the ``Game of the Week'' baseball broadcasts on Saturday
afternoons on the Fox network. The slapstick spots _ infused with
the wacky perspective and odd, cartoon-like characters that are
Freeman mainstays _ come after the agency won several prestigious
awards for an off-kilter television campaign to promote Fox's
coverage of National Hockey League games.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign attempting to ``Freemanize'' baseball is appearing
amid indications that the sport's imperiled state may be improving
after years of labor problems and diminished interest among younger
fans. The trade publication Mediaweek reported this week that
ratings for national broadcast and cable TV baseball games were
rising, fueled by growing interest in interleague play, the race to
break Roger Maris' single-season home run record and strong
performances by widely followed teams like the Atlanta Braves and
New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game now has some momentum behind it,'' said Neal Tiles,
senior vice president for marketing at the Fox Sports division of
Fox Broadcasting Co., a unit of News Corp. in Century City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task for hockey was to position it as a sports fan's kind
of sport,'' he added, while for baseball the goals are to ``break
through with a highly creative message'' and ``differentiate the
Fox Saturday game to make it seem special.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman was selected for the assignment, Tiles said, because the
agency, by taking ``creative risks in a strategic way,'' produces
results for marketers like Little Caesars pizza and Staples that
``are not tremendous advertising spenders.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the awards that Freeman won for the NHL campaign haven't
hurt. Those honors included a Gold Lion at the 45th annual
International Advertising Festival in Cannes, France; the Grand
Clio for television work at the 39th Clio Awards presentation, and
two silvers at the D&AMP;AD show in London, rare kudos for an American
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The hockey commercials presented hilarious glimpses into a
parallel universe where basketball, squash, bowling, billiards and
golf ``would be better'' if they were played like hockey. For
instance, the basketball spot featured play-by-play coverage of a
college game in which a goalie was perched atop the net to prevent
rival players from sinking baskets. And the bowling spot showed a
bowler knocking down an opponent before he could make game-winning
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Fox gave us a whole lot of instruction in
creating the hockey commercials,'' said Cliff Freeman, chairman and
chief creative officer at Freeman, a unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC,
other than ``to try to get hockey fans to be more aware of the
broadcasts on Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   For baseball, he added, the assignment was ``a little more
specific,'' promoting such features of the Fox coverage as camera
shots from the catcher's perspective and enhanced sound, which
``give a visceral feeling of being inside the game'' in order to
``heighten the drama'' _ an attribute that many fans have believed
was sorely lacking during recent seasons plagued by strikes and
instances of what were widely perceived as player and owner greed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the idea was to make baseball more exciting, Freeman
replied: ``I'm not sure how much that was in the back of our minds,
but it probably was. The Fox broadcast features have juiced up the
whole experience of the game, to make it more like you're there.
Baseball at its best is very exciting, but people say that a lot of
the time there isn't that feeling.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And feeling is at the center of the Freeman baseball
commercials, as in feeling sore, dazed or battered. Each spot shows
baseball fans performing dangerous stunts meant to duplicate plays
by stars like Brady Anderson, Bernie Williams and Randy Johnson.
Though the action is clearly in the vein of the Three Stooges or
``Dumb and Dumber,'' as a cautionary note each commercial ends with
the words ``Don't try it at home'' superimposed on screen.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, a man climbs a ladder to reach a rope that he uses
to swing into the side of a barn. After he grunts in pain, his
friend declares, ``That sounded like Anderson.'' At that point,
footage from a Fox baseball broadcast appears, presenting Anderson,
a Baltimore Orioles outfielder, crashing into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   In a second spot, a man crouches behind a horse as his friend
slaps the horse on the rump. The horse, being a horse, knocks the
first man down, of course, at which point the friend says, ``That,
uh, looked like the foul tip into Rodriguez.'' The spot then cuts
to footage from a game in which Ivan Rodriguez, the Texas Rangers
catcher, is dinged by a batter.
</P>
<P>
   The other stunts include a man falling after being hit by a
shopping cart filled with cement blocks, to duplicate how a catcher
feels when Williams, the Yankee outfielder, knocks him down at home
plate, and a man falling after being hit by a baseball thrown from
a moving pickup truck, to duplicate the force of a fastball tossed
by Johnson, the Seattle Mariners pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so over the top,'' Freeman says of the simulated
violent acts in each commercial, which were produced by using stunt
performers ``and some camera tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiles said that the spots would run during various Fox prime
time, sports and children's programs as well as on a cable sibling,
the Fox Sports Network.
</P>
<P>
   More commercials are planned, he added, as Fox is ``working with
Cliff again for postseason baseball coverage, straight on through
to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like extra innings for the stunt performers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
