<SLUG> BC-JASPER-JURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER GRAND JURY INDICTS WHITE SUSPECTS IN DRAGGING DEATH OF BLACK
MAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Three white men were indicted Monday on capital
murder charges alleging they kidnapped a 49-year-old black man and
dragged him to his death behind a pickup.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying of James Byrd Jr. early June 7 brought international
attention to this East Texas town of 8,000. On Monday, the Jasper
County grand jury issued two indictments, one naming Bill King, 23,
of Jasper and Russell Brewer Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs, the other
naming Shawn Berry, 23, of Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray said it is ``pretty likely''
prosecutors will seek a death sentence for King and Brewer. He said
Berry may be spared in exchange for his testimony against the other
two. Capital murder carries a sentence of either death or life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In chilling affidavits filed in the case so far, investigators
have said Berry told them that Brewer and King beat Byrd, kicked
him, sprayed his face with black paint and chained him by the
ankles to the back of Berry's pickup, then dragged him almost three
miles along country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Byrd's head and right arm were ripped from his
body.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said Monday that reports from the FBI lab in Washington
backed up ``some parts'' of Berry's story.
</P>
<P>
   No trial date was set, but Gray said it would likely be early
next year by the time defense attorneys finish having their experts
look at the mounds of forensic evidence police have gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer and King could be tried together, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The three men have been held without bond in the Jasper County
Jail since they were arrested the night after Byrd was killed.
State District Judge Joe Bob Golden is expected to appoint new
attorneys for King and Brewer because earlier court-appointed
attorneys aren't certified to try capital cases. No Jasper County
attorneys are certified to try capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   Beaumont attorney Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn said Berry hired
him Friday to represent him.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said that although Byrd was dragged behind Berry's
truck, Berry ``had nothing to do'' with the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just there,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said he would like Berry to be tried in Jasper, adding
that Berry's friends and relatives raised the money to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an excellent chance of him being found not
guilty,'' Hawthorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who early on said Berry's testimony against the other two
men would be important to the cases against them, said Monday that
he wants to look at more forensic lab results before considering if
he will seek the death penalty for Berry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very pleased with the results we've gotten so
far,'' Gray said of the lab results. ``Obviously, our evidence has
improved significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   A multi-agency task force headed by the FBI has been
investigating the crime and is still at work, Sheriff Billy Rowles
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one FBI agent appeared before the grand jury Monday.
Rowles and several of his investigators also appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury of four men and eight women _ two of them black _
spent less than three hours hearing testimony before voting to
indict the three men.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of local black citizens joined reporters at the
courthouse waiting for the grand jury to return the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to see that justice is done,'' said Paul Beaty,
44, who added that he doesn't think African-Americans always get
justice in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``A jury trial will show if there's justice in Jasper,''
District Attorney Gray said later.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities earlier said they hoped to file federal
charges on the suspects. But Gray said that as the cases evolved it
became apparent that it would be better to charge them under state
capital murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors will assist him during the trials, Gray
said, adding that if any one of the trio is acquitted, federal
charges may be filed later.
</P>
<P>
   The trials, along with that of another Jasper man indicted for
capital murder Monday in an unrelated case, could cost Jasper
County a total of $1 million, Gray said. The cost would go up
significantly if pretrial publicity causes the trials to be moved
out of Jasper, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there will have to be an increase in taxes,'' Gray
said. ``We'll do what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray hopes the trials will be in Jasper, but he said defense
attorneys may try to have them moved. Judge Golden will make the
final decision.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying's massive publicity has been a ``distraction,'' but
the case has otherwise been handled like other capital murder cases
in Jasper County, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators and Gray have been deluged with calls and
interview requests by hundreds of news agencies, including
reporters from as far away as New Zealand and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   When 25 members of various Ku Klux Klan groups and 50 members of
New Black Panther and other black dissident organizations appeared
in Jasper on June 27, they were surrounded by at least 200
reporters and cameramen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
