<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S RULING PARTY RETAKES CHIHUAHUA IN SYMBOLIC VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: Subs 5th and 6th graphs to add name of the PRD candidate in
Zacatecas, Ricardo Monreal Avila, and background about him, and the
Chihuahua race.)   (fb) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIHUAHUA, Mexico _ Mexico's governing party, which has seemed
in retreat before a rising opposition tide, has swept to one of its
most important triumphs, electing a former businessman to the
governorship of Chihuahua and for the first time recovering a state
that had been controlled by rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The result of Sunday's Chihuahua elections, announced on Monday,
was the second stinging defeat in a year for National Action, the
pro-business party known as the PA, which had governed Chihuahua
since 1992 and which some had seen as the opposition's best chance
to win the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission accomplished!'' Patricio Martinez Garcia, Chihuahua's
governor-elect from President Ernesto Zedillo's party, known as the
PRI, said in a victory news conference on Monday. ``We've
triumphed. We've recovered Chihuahua.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI split the results in two other northern states where
there was gubernatorial balloting, winning easily in Durango, where
the opposition vote was divided among three candidates, and losing
in a more closely-watched election in neighboring Zacatecas.
</P>
<P>
   The Zacatecas vote gave an important lift to Mexico's leftist
opposition party, whose victorious candidate, Ricardo Monreal
Avila, was a PRI legislative leader who defected to the Party of
the Democratic Revolution, or PRD, this year after having been
passed over for the governing party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Monreal, 41, owes little to the PRD. He won election largely as
a result of his own carefully constructed personal political
organization, and how closely he will work with PRD leaders in
governing his state remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In Chihuahua, Martinez, 50, a real estate executive who first
ran for office in 1992, winning election as mayor of the state's
capital, also appears quite likely to develop an unusually
independent relationship with the PRI, whose governors have until
recently been handpicked by successive Mexican presidents.
</P>
<P>
   But his victory more than compensated for the governing party's
loss in Zacatecas. Chihuahua, which borders western Texas and New
Mexico, is one of the fastest-growing industrial states in Mexico.
The governing party's victory there is laden with extra
significance, because the state has often functioned as a
Californi-esque harbinger of political experimentation and change
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The PAN's rise from a marginal party of conservative Catholic
ideologues began with victories in Chihuahua towns and cities in
the early 1980s, including the election of Francisco Barrio as
Ciudad Juarez's mayor in 1983. In 1992 gubernatorial voting here,
Barrio became only the second opposition figure ever to win control
of a Mexican statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Now the PRI's victory here has reversed Chihuahua's symbolism.
Making the damage worse, the PAN candidate, Ramon Galindo, said
repeatedly during the campaign that ``the battle for Chihuahua is
the battle for Mexico,'' suggesting that a victory by the PRI here
would complicate the opposition's quest to wrest the presidency
from the PRI for the first time in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Galindo acknowledged his defeat on Monday in a moist-eyed news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Corral, a federal congressman from Chihuahua who is the
spokesman for the PAN's national executive committee and who
accompanied Galindo in his news conference, laid his party's defeat
to a slander campaign in which the PRI told voters that the PAN
intended to dismantle Chihuahua's public schools, forcing poor
families to pay for private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI waged a dirty war, systematically distorting our
party's image through a campaign of insults and false
accusations,'' Corral said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For his part, Barrio, now a lame-duck governor, took a more
philosophical approach in a meeting with reporters in the Chihuahua
governor's palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even defeats can be opportunities if you know how to take
advantage of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The PAN's defeat appears to end any chance that Barrio might run
for president. Instead, the Chihuahua elections strengthen the
likelihood that the PAN will pick as its presidential candidate
Vicente Fox, the governor of the central state of Guanajuato, who
began campaigning in earnest for the job early this year. But
Barrio refused to rule anything out of his own future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to identify things to improve and change about our
party,'' Barrio said. ``Today's defeats can be the germs of
tomorrow's victories.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Aziz Nassif, a professor who has written two books about
Chihuahua politics, seconded Barrio's call for introspection within
the PAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PAN needs to do some self-criticism,'' Aziz said,
describing Galindo as a lackluster candidate with a weak record as
Mayor of Ciudad Juarez. ``They need to seriously examine how they
pick their candidates and how they develop their image.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, Aziz said, ``has shown they are capable of learning
from their mistakes and adapting to new situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Zarate Flores, the editor of a Mexican political
newsletter, agreed. ``These elections prove that its too early to
announce the PRI's funeral,'' Zarate said. ``Now we see that when
the PRI combines an attractive candidate and good marketing with
its efficient political machinery, they can win elections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
