<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 92 HOLES, PAK WINS HER SECOND MAJOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ It finally ended on the 20th playoff hole. It was
the longest U.S. Women's Open ever, and one of the most dramatic, a
compelling championship duel between two remarkable 20-year-olds
seeking their place in their sport's history. And while Se Ri Pak's
victory firmly established her as a new force in women's golf, the
performance of Jenny Chuasiriporn, who nearly became the second
amateur to win the Women's Open, was extraordinary in its own
right.
</P>
<P>
   Making an 18-foot birdie putt on the second hole of sudden
death, Pak finally vanquished Chuasiriporn to become the youngest
Women's Open champion ever. After the winning putt dropped,
breaking a tie at 2 over par through 19 playoff holes, the normally
stoic Pak burst into tears, as her father, Joon-Chul Pak, ran onto
the 11th green to embrace her.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional victory lifted Pak, a South Korean who is the
fourth straight foreign winner of the Open, into lofty company.
Having won the McDonald's LPGA Championship in May, Pak became the
first rookie to win two majors in the same year since Juli Inkster
in 1984. Pak is the first woman to win back-to-back majors since
Meg Mallon in 1991, and the first woman to win two majors in the
same year since Laura Davies in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she believed that she was the No. 1 player in the
world, Pak laughed and said: ``No, not yet. But good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could argue? In her rookie season on the LPGA tour, Pak
moved to fourth on the money list ($525,170) with Monday's $267,500
first-place check. With accurate driving, superb iron play and
admirable cool under pressure, Pak has arrived as someone capable
of winning major championships far more quickly than even she
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Pak did not start playing golf until 1989, but she developed
rapidly, winning numerous tournaments in South Korea before moving
to Orlando, Fla., last year to work with renowned golf teacher
David Leadbetter. Pak earned her tour card at qualifying school
last fall, and she has already earned a reputation as one of the
tour's hardest-working players, often spending hours on the
practice range after her round is over.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when Pak struggles to understand questions
during interviews, but her command of English has improved greatly
since last year. And when asked if winning two majors in the same
year put her ahead of schedule, Pak gave an insightful answer. ``My
sponsor, they, like, really surprised,'' she said. ``Maybe they get
me more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chuasiriporn, who will turn 21 on Thursday, delivered
an admirable performance, nearly joining Catherine LaCoste, won won
the Open as an amateur in 1967. Chuasiriporn, whose parents are
originally from Thailand, was gracious in defeat, but as she
prepares for her senior year at Duke University, she will remember
two key miscues from Monday: a triple bogey on No. 6 after she had
built a four-stroke lead, and then a missed 15-foot putt for par on
No. 18 that could have won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt it slip away there,'' Chuasiriporn said of her
putt for par at No. 18. ``I thought I was going to do it there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another thing to build my game and my confidence.
I am pretty satisfied with the way I handled it. I guess I really
feel like I am going to win one, so I am really not too
disappointed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though Pak looks like a player who will have other titles in her
future, none may test her more than Monday's. She survived 92 holes
of grueling golf _ four 18-hole rounds, an 18-hole playoff and two
sudden-death holes _ on a challenging Blackwolf Run course that was
among the toughest layouts in Open history. And Monday, she
overcame a four-stroke deficit after five holes, as well as a poor
tee shot on the par-4 18th hole that forced her to remove her socks
and shoes and hit her second shot off a steep bank while standing
in a water hazard.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, that recovery shot typified Pak's determination,
and it was a turning point. Pak and Chuasiriporn reached the 18th
green tied at one over par, but after Pak pulled her tee shot into
the hazard, Chuasiriporn hit her second shot onto the fringe of the
green, only about 50 feet from the hole. Pak was in deep trouble,
with no chance to reach the green from the bank, while Chuasiriporn
was in solid position to make a par. So instead of opting to take a
drop out of the water hazard, which would have cost her a penalty
stroke, Pak elected to play the ball from where it was, even though
she faced an extremely difficult shot.
</P>
<P>
   The gamble paid off. The crowd cheered when Pak removed her
shoes, cheered again when she removed her socks, and cheered again
when she hit a difficult wedge shot, over the 6-foot-high bank,
across the fairway and into the rough on the right-hand side. Still
about 138 yards from the green, Pak then hit a solid 8-iron to
within about 17 feet of the pin. But Chuasiriporn still had the
edge. From the fringe, she hit a chip shot about 15 feet past the
hole, and then Pak left her 17-foot putt for par more than a foot
short.
</P>
<P>
   That left Chuasiriporn with a 15-foot putt at No. 18 for the
victory. After the sensational 35-foot putt she made at No. 18 on
Sunday to get into the playoff, most people expected her to make
this one, including Pak. ``I thought she make that par putt,'' Pak
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuasiriporn pushed the putt just a little, and it slid past
the hole. ``I thought I had that putt, but my hands were shaking a
lot,'' Chuasiriporn said.
</P>
<P>
   So the battle continued, the first time a Women's Open had ever
reached sudden death. Both players made par at the first sudden
death hole, the par-5, 564-yard No. 10, as they both missed birdie
attempts of more than 20 feet. But at the par-4, 374-yard No. 11,
it finally ended.
</P>
<P>
   After both players reached the green in two shots, Chuasiriporn
missed a birdie attempt from about 18 feet, then watched helplessly
as Pak lined up her final putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had a sixth-sense feeling she would make it,''
Chuasiriporn said.
</P>
<P>
   So after many holes, and many anxious moments, Pak had won
another major, and there was no doubt she had earned it. ``I am
really happy,'' Pak said. ``That is why I cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
