<HEADLINE>
OUTBREAK OF TAINTED OYSTERS SHOWS SIGNS OF TAPERING OFF AS FIGURE
HITS 316 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Fla., Okla. and Tenn.) 
(See optional ending) 
 
By CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Only 16 new cases of people sickened by eating raw
Galveston Bay oysters were reported over the weekend, leading
health officials to hope the record-setting outbreak is tapering
off.
</P>
<P>
   The latest count showed 316 cases of the flulike diarrheal
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Though harvesting of oysters in Galveston Bay stopped June 25
after illnesses were first linked to the shell fish contaminated by
the bacteria, ``Vibrio parahaemolyticus,'' the count had been
leaping upward by more than 50 new cases a day.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Health spokesman Doug McBride said Monday
that he thought the voluntary recall by oyster houses may be
starting to have an effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we're no longer accepting illness reports over our
800-telephone number in Austin,'' he said. ``Instead, we're
directing those who think a raw oyster made them sick to call their
local health department who will then report it to us. I'm sure
we'll probably get a few more calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak last week surpassed the national record of 209 set
last summer by illnesses from contaminated oysters harvested in
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking kills the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Texas supplies more than half the oysters eaten raw in the
nation, and the reports of illnesses from Galveston Bay oysters
came from three states in addition to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In the 316 total are 248 cases from Texas, 53 from Florida, 12
from Oklahoma and three from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   One fatality was reported in the Pacific Northwest outbreak last
year. None has been recorded so far from the Galveston Bay outbreak
although ``three or four people have been hospitalized,'' McBride
said.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the bacteria causes flulike symptoms that last up
to seven days and are not life-threatening unless the sick person
has an immune-deficiency disorder. Symptoms include diarrhea,
abdominal cramps, nausea, fever, vomiting and headache.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oyster fishermen are awaiting lab reports on water, soil and
meat samples taken from the oyster reefs in Galveston Bay to
determine the cause of the trouble and how long it might last.
</P>
<P>
   The health department hopes to have those results by Wednesday,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria is always present, even in the cleanest waters of
the world, but usually not in quantities that would make anyone
sick. Because of that, state officials want to know what triggered
the outbreak, McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that the extreme heat and drought conditions in
Texas caused the bacteria to become more plentiful, while another
is that a heartier, more virulent strain of that bacteria has
developed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
