<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 12)  
 &HT;     
 A Milelong Bridge Links Danish Islands  
 Swollen Rivers Prompt Concern in California   
 Music and Dance Staged in Paris Parks  
 Historic Lighthouse To Open in Atlantic City  
 Rethinking a Landmark in Marrakesh  
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In English, it is called the Great Belt. In Danish, it is
Storebaelt. It opened on June 14, incorporating the second-longest
suspension bridge in the world and linking east and west Denmark by
automobile, replacing ferry services that once carried visitors
between Halsskov on the island of Sealand and Knudshoved on Funen
and cutting travel time by approximately an hour, not counting
waiting for a ferry.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 5,350 feet, the East Bridge, which is part of an 11-mile
bridge and tunnel, is surpassed only by the 6,500-foot-long
Akashi-Kaikyo Bridge in Japan, which opened in April. The Golden
Gate Bridge, now ranked seventh in the world, spans 4,200 feet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rail link across the Great Belt opened a year ago; about
20,000 train passengers a day now make the trip. The project took
10 years to complete at a cost of about $4.3 billion. Automobile
traffic is expected to begin at about 10,000 cars a day, rising to
17,000 in 2001. The one-way toll for a car is about $31. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 9.3-mile connection for trains and cars, called the Oresund
Fixed Link, is under construction between Copenhagen and Malmo,
Sweden, and is scheduled to open in 2000. It will consist of a
4.8-mile bridge, a 2.5-mile artificial island and a 2-mile tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another example of El Nino's lingering ill effects, the
California Department of Boating and Waterways issued a safety
advisory on June 22 warning that the state's rivers are colder,
faster and carrying more debris than normal this summer because of
the melting of a record Sierra Nevada snowpack.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory was prompted by the deaths of nine rafters on
swollen central and northern California rivers _ including the
American, Cosumnes and Yuba Rivers _ in a one-week period. Three
were on commercial trips accompanied by trained whitewater guides
and six on private outings without professional assistance. (Two
rafters on air mattresses were also killed last month, and a
kayaker drowned in February.)
</P>
<P>
   The highest number of California whitewater deaths for an entire
season is 12, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Standard, a department spokeswoman, said some California
rivers were carrying up to seven times the normal volume of water
for this time of year. Additionally, cool spring weather delayed
the snow melt, causing water temperatures to be much colder than
usual and increasing the chance of hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   Although state water officials believe the Sierra runoff has
peaked, this year's massive snowpack means that full rivers, and
the need for extra caution, will extend well into the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're at the most expert level,'' said James Bailey, a
state hydrologist and experienced river kayaker and rafter, ``take
lessons or go with a guide. It's a great year for rafting, but do
it with a pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Every summer the Paris Quartier d'Ete performing-arts festival
peppers the city's monuments and gardens with music, dance and
theater performances. The festival's ninth edition begins on Sunday
at 7 p.m. with a free concert by Ju Percussions from Taiwan in the
Jardin des Tuileries. On July 25 at 6 p.m., the Tuileries will be
the site of a Jidai-Matsuri, a traditional parade from Kyoto with a
display of kimonos and re-enactments of events in Japan's history.
</P>
<P>
   The Palais Royal will be the venue for dance on July 20 to 23,
including the contemporary French choreographer Jean-Claude
Gallota, at 10 p.m. Tickets are $17.75.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15th arrondissement's futuristic Parc Andre Citroen,
France's Orchestre National will give a free performance of
Beethoven's Seventh Symphony on July 25 at 9 p.m. Pierre Henry, the
French composer and interpreter of ``musique concrete,''
inaugurates a series of performances on July 21 with his ``Symphony
for a Lone Man'' at the Thermes de Cluny.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz will take over the 16th-century Hotel d'Albret on the Rue
des Francs-Bourgeois from July 27 to Aug. 2, including performances
by the saxophonist Michael Brecker July 27, and the accordionist
Richard Galliano with Michel Portal, clarinetist, July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Jardin du Luxembourg will rock to the sound of world music
groups such as Ongo Trogode, who play huge Banda horns from the
Central African Republic July 23 to 25, Cuarteto Cedron from
Argentina July 27 to 29, Burundi Drums Aug. 9; all at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A giant tepee built in front of the Centre Georges Pompidou for
the duration of its renovation will be the setting for theater
performances including ``Barboni'' by Pippo Delbono, an Italian
Teatro Commedia dell'Arte company.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the Paris Quartier d'Ete, call (33-1)
44.94.98.00. For tickets, which range from $8.50 to $20.75, call
(33-1) 49.87.50.50. Concerts in the parks are free.
</P>
<P>
   The 170-foot-tall Absecon Lighthouse in Atlantic City, which was
first lighted in 1857, is scheduled to reopen by the end of the
month (the exact date has not yet been determined). Visitors will
be able to climb the tower's 228 steps and walk outside on the
balcony (or gallery, in the lighthouse lexicon) to view the city
and nearby Brigantine beach.
</P>
<P>
   The lighthouse's original first-order Fresnel lens, the most
powerful of the French-manufactured lighthouse lenses, will be on
display at the top of the tower. The lens was powerful enough to
project the light up to 20 nautical miles.
</P>
<P>
   The Inlet Public-Private Association, a nonprofit corporation,
directed the $2.6-million restoration of the lighthouse, which had
been closed for 15 years. The tower's exterior has been repainted
yellow and black to reflect its appearance from 1925 to 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be able to tour the interior of the newly
reconstructed lighthouse keeper's house, rebuilt on the foundations
of the original residence. Plans for the keeper's house include a
visitor center with exhibits and a museum shop. The lighthouse and
keeper's house, on Pacific Avenue between Rhode Island and Vermont
Avenues, will be open Thursday through Monday, 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.,
year round. Admission is $4 for adults (including admission for one
child), $1 for children. Information: (609) 449-1360.
</P>
<P>
   La Maison Arabe in Marrakesh, a near-legendary restaurant that
closed a decade ago, was reborn this year. But this time it's a
hotel. A charming and beautifully decorated collection of 11 rooms
meanders through the two buildings that housed the restaurant on a
side street in the Medina (old city). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The accommodations, all different, range from a small room with
a queen-size bed and a private patio to large bedrooms with living
room and terrace dripping oleander and bougainvillea on the top
floor, affording a view of the city. All have sleek marble
bathrooms furnished with thick towels and bathrobes.
</P>
<P>
   The public areas, filled with antiques and artifacts, are
ornamented with carved cedar and plaster in typical Moroccan style.
The staff members wear traditional Moroccan dress. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new hotel is more elaborate than the famous namesake
restaurant, which was the first in the Medina to serve fine
Moroccan food while catering to Europeans when it opened in 1947.
The restaurant was owned by Suzy Larochette, who came to Marrakesh
for health reasons with her mother and sister in 1938; they were
stranded there when World War II broke out. Through her well-placed
contacts, she got the pasha of Marrakesh, Si Thami el Glaoui, to
provide a chef for the restaurant from his entourage. In its
heyday, the restaurant welcomed such notables as Winston Churchill
and the Aga Khan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a French-Italian entrepreneur, Fabrizio
Ruspoli, and his partner, Philippe Cluzel, started talking with Ms.
Larochette who, though nearly 90, is as feisty, opinionated and
stylish as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed classy,'' Ms. Larochette said of Ruspoli.
</P>
<P>
   She sold them the two houses but made them agree not to put in a
restaurant because she lives in an adjacent house and did not want
the noise.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, those who stay at La Maison Arabe will get an early
wake-up from the 5 a.m. call to prayer over loudspeakers from the
Bab Doukkala mosque across the alley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   La Maison Arabe, 1 Derb Assehbe-Bab Doukkala, Marrakesh;
telephone (212-4) 39-12-33, fax (212-4) 44-37-15. Rooms range from
$139 to $266 from June 14 through Dec. 9 and $181 to $320 the rest
of the year, including breakfast and afternoon Moroccan tea.
</P>
<P>
   Most rooms are air-conditioned; all have heating and cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
