<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-PORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HASTEN APPEAL, REPORTER ADMITS VIOLATING CHILD-PORN LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A veteran radio reporter pleaded guilty in federal
court on Monday to violating the nation's child pornography laws,
saying he did so to hasten his appeal that he was trafficking in
lewd photos of minors on the Internet as part of his First
Amendment right to research an article on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter, Larry Matthews, a freelance journalist who works
for National Public Radio and public television in Maryland, was
scheduled to go on trial in suburban Maryland on Tuesday on 15
counts of using his computer to trade images of under-age girls
engaged in various sexual acts with other minors and adults. But
his lawyer, Michael V. Statham, said that a ruling by the trial
judge last week dealt a fatal blow to Matthews' chances and made it
pointless to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Alexander Williams Jr. ruled that Matthews could not use
the First Amendment's guarantee of an unfettered press as a
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A press pass is not a license to break the law,'' Williams
ruled, adding that Matthews would not even be allowed to suggest to
the jury that he was a journalist whose motive was to expose
aspects of the child pornography trade on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Matthews had broadcast a three-part series on the
subject of Internet child pornography on a local Washington radio
station. He said in court papers that he had hoped to use the
information he was acquiring to write a magazine article, although
he did not offer evidence that he had communicated with any
publication about arranging to sell such an article.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, 54, pleaded guilty to one count of receiving lewd
images of minors and one count of transmitting such images; the
plea came in an agreement with prosecutors that allowed him to
appeal. He is scheduled to be sentenced on Dec. 11, after which his
lawyers may seek to have Williams' ruling overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews' lawyers had argued that the only way for their client
to penetrate the secretive world of fanciers of child-pornography
was to pretend to be one himself. Many transactions in that world,
they argued, occur in private chat rooms where people are
hard-pressed to win the confidence of suspicious players. Williams
said, however, that there were ways to scrutinize the world of
child pornography without breaking the law including interviewing
law-enforcement officials. Matthews' lawyers had argued that such a
method would only provide a government-approved version of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the second half of 1996, Matthews engaged in a brisk
trade of child pornography over the Internet. As often happens in
such cases, one of the people with whom Matthews corresponded was
not a child pornography trader as advertised but a federal agent
trolling cyberspace to snare people who were violating the federal
law against such traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, then under investigation, declared he also was not
what he seemed. He was, he said, just researching an article he
hoped to write about whether child pornography was as easily
available as its critics contended and how well it was policed. The
Justice Department said that such an explanation did not matter and
Matthews was indicted in July 1997. Moreover, the prosecutors in
suburban Maryland asserted that they were convinced that Matthews
was not researching a news article but was just using that as an
excuse to send and receive illicit materials.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews operated under such Web names as ``Mr. Mature'' and
``Dd4SubFem.'' When FBI agents raided his home in Silver Spring,
Md., in 1996, they found two images of prepubescent girls on his
computer's hard drive. They then subjected Matthews' computer to a
sophisticated search and found many more such images he had tried
to delete.
</P>
<P>
   The federal child pornography laws are themselves an unusual
exception to traditional First Amendment theory and practice that
generally allows people to possess and consume any information no
matter how offensive it may be to the government or others. In the
case of child pornography, however, the Supreme Court has ruled
that there is a legitimate government interest in outlawing its
possession because it creates a market that inevitably requires the
exploitation of children.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1982 ruling upholding a New York state law, the court
raised the possibility that there might be legitimate exceptions of
``serious literary, scientific, or educational value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
