<HEADER>
A2771 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYROGERS-TEX     07-06 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYROGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF ROY ROGERS IS EVERYBODY'S LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
And LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He shined shoes in Ohio, sold magazines in Missouri and chopped
cotton in Texas while working his way toward Hollywood and the slim
chance of stardom. But Roy Rogers more than made it. When he died
on Monday at the age of 86, the nation mourned the loss of a
straight-shooting, singing cowboy legend who embodied everything
decent about the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``He influenced several generations of Americans,'' said Red
Steagall, a cowboy poet and troubadour from Fort Worth, Texas, who
came to know Rogers and his family. ``He was one of those people
who taught us the difference between right and wrong because he
always wore the white hat and he was always in conflict with the
guys in the black hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he always defeated them,'' Steagall said, growing
husky-voiced with emotion as he spoke. ``Good always defeated evil
in all of Roy's productions. It's too bad that so much of our
society today wears gray hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar tributes poured in as news spread about Rogers' death of
congestive heart failure at the California home that he shared with
wife and co-star, Dale Evans.
</P>
<P>
   In a career spanning six decades in movies, television and
recordings, Rogers was the singing ``King of the Cowboys.'' Rogers
and Evans were among the nation's most recognized and admired
couples, their anthem, Happy Trails to You, among the century's
most beloved songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today there will be a lot of sad and grateful Americans,
especially of my generation, because of his career,'' President
Clinton said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rogers' movies that most inspired a teen-ager named Don
Edwards, who eventually followed in the Ohio native's footsteps as
a cowboy singer, and in later years became Rogers' friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy was bigger than life,'' said Edwards, a Weatherford,
Texas, resident who appeared in the recent movie The Horse
Whisperer. ``He had a big influence. He was an icon. My mom and dad
would drop me off at the movie house and they didn't have a problem
with that, me staying all day, because Roy Rogers was preaching the
same things that they were. You were in good hands with Roy in the
movie house...''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really makes you kind of sad that he's not here anymore,''
said Edwards, also a country singer based in Fort Worth. ``But
there are a lot of memories, a lot of things on my walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also worked as a Depression-era truck driver and peach
picker, then was a successful country singer with the Sons of the
Pioneers that he helped organize before he landed a $75-a-week job
in 1937 as a singing cowboy at Hollywood's Republic Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a guitar, six-shooter, crinkly-eyed good looks and
shy country charm, Rogers rose in salary and popularity. From 1943
to 1954, he was the top western star at the box office in a
magazine poll of theater operators.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who survives her husband, shared the screen in many of
Rogers' 87 films and a long-running TV series. Rogers' palomino,
Trigger, became a household name. In his performances, Rogers
fought often, but always fairly, and usually shot the gun from the
bad guy's hand, not the bad guy himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was and will always be a true western hero,'' said Gene
Autry, Rogers' friend and longtime cowboy rival.
</P>
<P>
   Off-screen, Rogers was described by friends as a gracious and
deeply religious man, someone keenly aware of his straight-shooting
image and ability to influence young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never showed anything on screen that wasn't part of his
personal life,'' Steagall said. ``He was absolutely the most
outstanding person you could imagine. He was very dedicated to his
family, he was strongly convicted in his faith in God, and he
wasn't afraid to tell that to anyone who would listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Steagall, like many others who knew Rogers, on Monday recalled
favorite memories of the cowboy star. Steagall took Rogers goose
hunting on his 80th birthday, and a few years ago visited Rogers at
the California museum he and his wife had created near their
California home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he was able, he would greet everyone down in the
lobby of that museum,'' Steagall said. ``That was his big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards recalled meeting Rogers in the 1950s as a star-struck
teen-ager after Rogers' performance in a Boston rodeo. Edwards kept
the program from that rodeo, and had it handy decades later when he
and Rogers were introduced at a western awards program in
California. By then, Edwards had become a successful recording
artist in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been carrying it around for a long time,'' Edwards
recalled. ``He signed it, and I'll never forget this as long as I
live. He wrote `Roy Rogers,' then he stopped and looked up at me.
`Do you mind if I sign Trigger, too?' That just melted my heart and
it went on from there.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Rogers contributed laudatory liner notes to Edwards'
album Happy Cowboy. In 1994, Edwards and several other western
performers joined Rogers on stage at a Tucson, Ariz., western music
festival to sing Happy Trails To You.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking at the time, `Golly, this is probably the
neatest thing I've ever done,' '' Edwards said. ``From being a kid
watching him in a 9-cent movie house, to singing with him on stage
in Tucson.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was born Leonard Slye on Nov. 5, 1911, in Cincinnati, but
began the trek to California in 1929. He made his first mark as a
singer in the mid-1930s, co-founding the group that would come to
be known as the Sons of the Pioneers. The group recorded hit
records, such as Tumbling Tumbleweeds and Cool Water, before Rogers
embarked on his movie career.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers replaced Autry as Republic's top cowboy when Autry left
to serve as a flier in the Army Air Forces during World War II.
Rogers was first teamed with Evans, a singer and sometime actress,
in the 1944 film Cowboy and the Senorita.'' They married in 1947,
14 months after the death of his first wife. Evans, born Frances
Octavia Smith in Uvalde, Texas, became known as the ``Queen of the
Cowgirls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and his wife eventually became well-known for their
religious beliefs and spoke at many religious gatherings, including
some with evangelist Billy Graham. Evans wrote several
inspirational books, including ``Angel Unaware'' about the couple's
daughter, Robin, who was born with Down syndrome and died in 1952
at age 2 of complications from the mumps.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy would continue to plague the family. Debbie, one of the
couple's adopted children, was killed in a church bus crash in
1964. The next year, another adopted child, John, choked to death
in Germany while serving in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Bible, it doesn't say you're going to get by without
having troubles,'' Rogers once said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Rogers is survived by six children or
stepchildren, 15 grandchildren and 33 great-grandchildren. A
memorial service is planned for Saturday at the Church of the
Valley in Rogers' home of Apple Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child dreamed of being a Roy Rogers or a Dale Evans, but
for people like Don (Edwards) and me, he created a way of life that
we're enjoying now with cowboy music and the image of cowboy
music,'' Steagall said on Monday. ``It's a great personal loss to
everybody who admires Roy and tried to live by the values they
learned from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I didn't see him very often,'' Steagall said, ``I
just figured he'd always be there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
