u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-TRIAL-     07-06 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-TRIAL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENOCIDE TRIAL OF BOSNIAN SERB DOCTOR OPENS IN THE HAGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE _ The U.N. tribunal dealing with war crimes in the
former Yugoslavia opened the trial on Monday of a Bosnian Serb
charged with the crime of genocide, the first time an international
trial for genocide has taken place in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The accused, Dr. Milan Kovacevic, 57, practiced anesthesiology
in Prijedor, but according to his indictment he played a key role
in the Serbs' plan to drive out and kill large numbers of Muslim
and Croat civilians from his area.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's proceedings opened in the main courtroom, one of the
tribunal's three courts. It is one of seven trials going on here
involving the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   During the opening session, Kovacevic pleaded not guilty to the
charge of genocide and not guilty to all other charges, including
crimes against humanity and other war crimes. The grey, stocky
physician hardly spoke and sat quietly, often taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   But his chief counsel, Dusan Vucicevic, a Serbian emigrant who
lives in Chicago, said the charge of genocide against his client
was `'improper and it can't be proven beyond a reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Vucicevic said his client bore no responsibility for the actions
of the army and the police. ``For each and every one of the
allegations, there is a reasonable explanation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the main leaders of the Balkan conflict are at large,
the case against the Serbian doctor is seen as especially
significant because the judges are expected to set new definitions
for genocide, the most heinous of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It would also send an important signal to a conference now going
on in Rome to set rules for a permanent international court to
prosecute crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   No conviction for genocide has ever been decided in an
international tribunal. Genocide was not part of international law
when the World War II trials began at Nuremberg and Tokyo and
therefore was not part of the criminal charges, although it was
used to describe Nazi crimes and was later used in local trials in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   After the Holocaust, though, the Convention on the Prevention
and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide was drawn up by the United
Nations in 1948 and went into effect in 1951. It defined genocide
as the destruction in whole or part of a national, ethnic, racial,
or religious group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the Genocide Convention was never applied
in an international court,'' said an expert at the tribunal. ``It's
the ultimate crime; it has a particular stigma attached to it. But
because we have no finished cases, the parameters of the law are
still vague.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of Kovacevic,'' he went on, ``we can expect the
judges to elaborate on the law, to outline what the destruction of
a group means, if it means not just collective murder but also
creating conditions that destroy or impair a group.''
</P>
<P>
   Some national courts have used variations of the Genocide
Convention, as Israel did for the 1961 trial of Adolf Eichmann, but
the court there _ for reasons of Israeli law _ defined the Nazi's
role in transporting Jews to death camps as crimes against the
Jewish people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the moment, a parallel U.N. tribunal is also trying dozens of
people on charges of genocide committed during the bloody conflict
in Rwanda in 1994. The tribunal, based in Tanzania, has not yet
issued a verdict, though there has been one guilty plea, and courts
in Rwanda have convicted some Hutu of genocide under local laws.
</P>
<P>
   Experts here expect Kovasevic's trial to be long and
complicated. They argue that there is no shortage of atrocities and
mass killings in the Balkan war, many of them well documented. But
they say the intention to commit genocide in Bosnia is less clear
cut and perhaps more difficult to prove than in the case of Rwanda,
where Hutu leaders made clear a policy of exterminating the Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core question of the Kovacevic case is whether ethnic
cleansing amounts to genocide,'' said Christian Chartier, the
spokesman for the tribunal here.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kovacevic is the first defendant to stand trial on
genocide charges before the tribunal, he is not the only suspect
facing those charges. Others indicted for genocide include the two
most-wanted suspects, the former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic and his wartime military commander, Ratko Mladic. Both
remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal uses the term ``ethnic cleansing'' for what
prosecutors have called a carefully planned Serbian campaign to
unite the territory where Serbs lived and to evict non-Serbs from
regions in Bosnia to which Serbs considered they had a historical
right.
</P>
<P>
   During that process, more than 700,000 Bosnian Muslims were
evicted and thousands tortured, raped, and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacevic was a key part of that campaign, his indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the chief prosecutor in his case, Brenda Hollis, told
the court that he put in place and helped carry out the campaign in
Prijedor.
</P>
<P>
   She said that at the onset of the war, Kovacevic, in addition to
his hospital work, was appointed deputy director of the ``Serbian
Crisis Staff'' of politicians, army commanders, and police chiefs.
This made him second in the political command of Prijedor and it
meant that he knew or had reason to know of the terror, the
looting, the torture and the killings of the local Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The municipality once had 112,000 people, 44 percent Muslim and
about 42 percent Serb. Between the end of April and the end of
December 1992, the Crisis Staff directed attacks on non-Serbs and
their detention and deportation, Hollis said.
</P>
<P>
   It also meant, she went on, that Kovacevic was accountable for
the three concentration camps of Prijedor, among the most notorious
of the Balkan war. At least 2,000 men were killed in two of the
camps, at Omarska and Keraterm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Omarkska, people saw corpses every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the third camp, Trnopolje, many Muslim women were tortured
and raped, mainly by Serbian soldiers and policemen, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kovasevic is said to be ill and has had at least one stroke,
according to a tribunal official. He has been in the court's
custody since July 1997. His indictment was kept secret by the
tribunal until he was arrested by members of a British-led NATO
force at the Prijedor Medical Center, where Kovacevic remained the
director. From there he was brought to The Hague.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
