<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-NOTEBOOK07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALL-STAR NOTEBOOK: Ripken's fielding streak questions
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Cal Ripken has been to 16 All-Star Games, but when he
sat in front of the media Monday, everyone wanted to know the
answer to just one question:
</P>
<P>
   When will the streak, now at 2,566 consecutive games, end?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how it would happen,'' Ripken said. ``It's
not going to go on forever. So, when it happens, when the streak
ends, it will take care of itself. The situation will present
itself, which will make sense, and it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, hitting just .258, has been criticized at times, some
feeling he is hurting the team being in the lineup every day. But
management is not about to bench him and Ripken feels he should be
in there every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to the ballpark with a simple approach,'' he said.
``(If) the manager is making his lineup, thinking I can be one of
the guys that can help us win, I'll play. I am considered the
everyday third baseman of the Baltimore Orioles. The streak itself
can by analyzed, dissected, opinions can be formed in all different
directions. But I don't worry about all that kind of stuff. I worry
about the thing that matters most, my approach to the game, it's my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors, rumors, rumors
</P>
<P>
   A lot of trade talk is flying around and the latest on the
Braves is that they are interested in Montreal's Mark Grudzielanek
to play second base.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have placed Grudzielanek on the block and the Braves
remain concerned about the shoulder of Keith Lockhart and are
disappointed with the play of Tony Graffanino.
</P>
<P>
   Another rumor: The Braves have also called the Orioles about
All-Star second baseman Roberto Alomar and the Reds about Bret
Boone, who is also here. It may be worth renting Alomar for the
rest of the season considering he probably will not cost a lot
because he is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Back home
</P>
<P>
   In Denver these days it's Andres this, Andres that. The local
media continue to pound the Rockies for not bringing back Andres
Galarraga, who signed with the Braves and had the best first half
of his career, hitting 28 homers and driving in 72 runs. ``It is
good to know that they miss me, but I am really surprised that they
aren't doing well,'' Galarraga said. ``They are so far away from
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the bases
</P>
<P>
   With only two shortstops on the NL team, expect starter Walt
Weiss to get a lot of playing time, replaced by Florida's Edgar
Renteria in the sixth inning. The only position where a player is
allowed to come back in the game is at catcher, and that is only if
there is an injury. ... ESPN will have 17 cameras at the game,
including what they call a bat track, which illustrates bat speed.
... It's interesting that Rockies third baseman Vinny Castilla has
made two All-Star Games and both times when Bobby Cox of the Braves
hasn't been the manager. Said Castilla, a former Brave, with a
grin, ``He likes Chipper better.'' ... When San Diego All-Star Andy
Ashby had a 75-pitch victory Sunday, he had the fewest pitches in a
complete game by a starter since pitches were first counted back in
1988. The previous low was Greg Maddux's 78-pitch wonder last year.
... Because two center fielders _ Ken Griffey Jr. and Kenny Lofton
_ were voted in as starters by the fans, some wondered who would
get the nod there. It will be Griffey while Lofton is in left. ...
There will be 23 first-time All-Stars participating tonight. ...
Galarraga on missing the home run derby because of back problems:
``I would have really loved to participate here.'' ... The Boone
family now has three generations of All-Stars, starting with Bret's
grandfather Ray in 1954 and again in '56 and father Bob, from
1976-79 and again in '83. ... When Griffey took batting practice
Monday, he was booed by the crowd, the fans upset he was not
participating in the home run derby. But at the last minute,
Griffey decided to enter and the jeers turned into cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
