<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACHELOR-PARTIES-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALE BONDING, BUT NO STRIPPERS IN CAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALLKILL, N.Y. _ Dressed in camouflage gear and war paint,
reeking of bug spray and perspiration and armed with rifles and
ammo, Dan Furlong and his buddies were having the time of their
lives, replaying the games of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Shouts of ``I nailed you, big daddy!'' and ``You got me, man!''
rose from the wooded playing field. From behind bunkers and thick
trees, their escape slowed by gopher holes and knee-high grass, two
teams fired gooey pellets of paint at each other. The ``dead'' left
the field with carbon dioxide-powered guns raised over their heads
in surrender, then compared welts with those who had fallen before
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish everybody would get killed so we could eat,'' said
Furlong, the center of attention this muggy summer afternoon.
Furlong, 30, is to be married Saturday, and this was his bachelor
party.
</P>
<P>
   The rowdy day of mock warfare _ a cross between a ``Die Hard''
movie and a game of capture the flag _ was organized for Furlong by
his best man, Mike Jackel, who a year ago chose the same way to
celebrate his passage from the single life to matrimony. They are
part of a small but growing legion of men who are shunning the
traditional bachelor party, a bacchanal with strippers, in favor of
more politically correct, if no less masculine, events.
</P>
<P>
   Paintball parties, like Furlong's, are popular. So are golf
outings, like the one for Pete Wolverton, a book editor in New York
City who joined his friends for five rounds in three days near
Cooperstown, in upstate New York. Or baseball excursions, like the
chartered bus trip to an Orioles game at Camden Yards in Baltimore
for John Massy, a Connecticut bond trader. Or an all-male weekend
in the Hamptons, the party of choice for Rob Gerstner, a New York
City businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Strip clubs, like Scores on the East Side of Manhattan, report
no loss in business. In fact, a spokesman there boasted that
celebrity grooms-to-be have included the New York Yankees' David
Cone and Roseanne's ex, Tom Arnold. But bridal magazines across the
nation have taken note of the movement away from debauchery to
parties built around adventure and athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really coming on strong,'' said Thomas Gunning, the
editor of Wedding Pages, which publishes 39 zoned editions. Gunning
recently commissioned an article on the trend away from liquor and
lap dancing. ``What modern, sophisticated woman is going to abide
that?'' he continued. ``This is a survival instinct among men.
Women will not stay with us if we're that stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that paintball parties don't sound a little odd, themselves,
when they are examined by experts. Activities like paintball or
other team sports are ``aggressive coalitionary behavior,'' said
Richard Wrangham, a Harvard University anthropologist, ``an
evolutionary necessity for the male of the species,'' who must
learn to hunt and wage war.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior, which involves ``aiming and chasing,'' is
inherently pleasurable to men, according to Steven Pinker, a
psychologist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. And its
``sheer physicality is one of the last refuges of maleness,'' said
Pepper Schwartz, a sociologist at the University of Washington.
``Doing this kind of guy thing,'' she said, ``is a way of saying `I
love this woman, but I'm still one of us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wedding consultants, who are usually not involved in the
bachelors' plans, nonetheless advise a tame celebration. ``I've
been suggesting this kind of thing to my bridegrooms,'' said
Claudia Hilbert, a party planner in Bronxville, N.Y. ``This way,
you don't have him rolling in _ or not rolling in _ for the
ceremony.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scott Torkos, 27, a police officer in Denville, N.J., said his
pals have not stopped talking about his paintball party last year.
``It's still a macho thing, but here you get to shoot and kill all
your friends,'' Torkos said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry McAward, the owner of the field where Torkos played, in
Jim Thorpe, Pa., said he had never been asked to provide a stripper
on the sidelines. McAward's theory, more colloquially expressed
than those of the academics, is that ``yelling and screaming like a
12-year-old does the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   There was bonding aplenty at Paintball Madness here, a 394-acre
complex a few miles from Middletown, N.Y., followed by a barbecue
in Furlong's honor at the home of his best man, Jackel, in Mahopac.
Two women were invited, Jackel's wife and his sister Meredith, and
their presence caused barely a ripple _ except when Lisa Jackel
``killed'' her husband in the first salvo of the first game. Since
they were teammates, the hit was recorded as friendly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Furlong's bride, however, did not get a chance to figuratively
eliminate him. She was at the manicurist, he said, getting nail
extensions so her hands would look perfect in the ``ring pictures''
two weeks hence. The pearly polish would be touched up right before
the wedding, Furlong said, but meanwhile she would get used to
moving about with long fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the game is either to capture the other team's flag
or to kill all the opponents by plugging them with .68-caliber
pellets, the size of marbles, that are made of vegetable oil,
dishwashing soap and water-soluble dye. Referees determine when a
player has been killed by examining the splat of paint on his
jumpsuit. The pellets leave raised, red welts on the skin; the
carbon dioxide rifles shoot with a report as loud as a pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Furlong, a youth pastor at a church in Yorktown, had a moment of
glory midway through the afternoon. He was patiently biding his
time in the shrubs near the corner of the field, just waiting for
someone from the other team to dare a run for the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Sessa, a 22-year-old intern at the church, did just that
when members of his team had Furlong outmanned, 2-to-1. Sessa raced
the length of the field unchallenged and had his hand outstretched
for the flag when Furlong aimed a volley of pellets at him. None
hit the younger man. But he stumbled out of bounds, empty-handed,
and thus lost the game.
</P>
<P>
   Furlong retreated in triumph to a chaise longue near the grill
where hamburgers hissed. ``This is a good way to get out of doing
the lawn,'' he said. ``There are 15 guys here who should be mowing
today but aren't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
