<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEEP-FIRES-COX     07-06 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEEP-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By RON HAYES
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM COAST _ Nobody died, but dozens of lives were lost all the
same.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning Monday, the homeless were returning home. They
stood in the ashes where they used to live, picked through the
rubble of their lives, and said goodbye to all the little things
that won't mean anything to anyone but them.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 Flint Lane, Reuben Levinton, 73, was down on his hands and
knees where the kitchen used to be, handing shattered knickknacks
to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is the stone egg I brought from Russia or
not,'' said Mary Levinton, 80.
</P>
<P>
   The Levintons learned their home had been lost when they
recognized the magnolia tree outside their kitchen window while
watching TV in the Palatka motel where they took refuge Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Three blocks east, on Flanders Lane, newlyweds Alan and Jodi
Lowe stood in their back yard and peered through the shell of their
former home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so strange,'' Alan Lowe said. ``The screen in my
satellite dish melted, but a plastic bird feeder handing in the
tree next to it wasn't touched.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it was throughout this middle-class neighborhood
where the average house costs $70,000 and all the street names
begin with F. House after house was untouched by the fire, the
lawns green, basketball nets hanging in the driveways, and then
suddenly a single home was ash and shell.
</P>
<P>
   In her back yard, Jodi Lowe turned to stare through the burned
woods between her block and the next block over. The dry ground
still smoldered in spots, and the pine trunks. ``I never could see
my neighbors before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Over at 1 Fielding Lane, David and Mary Hartman and their
18-year-old son Josh wandered aimlessly through the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the National Geographics, right there,'' David Hartman
said, kicking a mound of ash.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Hartman fled with two guitars and the Grateful Dead T-shirt
on his back. In the rubble he found an iron candleholder. ``It was
under my bed,'' he remembered. ``My bed was right about here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hartmans learned their house had burned Sunday night when
they called the emergency 800 number from a motel in St. Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
