</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROGAN-RUNNINGMATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brogan turns down Education job, becomes Bush's running mate
instead
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Wanted: Applicants for State Commissioner of
Education. Administer largest chunk of state budget. Also sits on
Cabinet, deciding marina leases, power plant siting, executive
pardons. Salary: $112,895.
</P>
<P>
   Application fee of $6,590.46 due July 17. Ability to raise
hundreds of thousands of dollars in a short period of time a must.
</P>
<P>
   So went the casting call Monday as both political parties
scrambled to find candidates for a job that until this weekend had
seemed a lock for Republican incumbent Frank Brogan, who on Monday
announced he would instead join the ticket of governor's candidate
Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   With Brogan abandoning what appeared to be an easy road to
re-election, only one candidate remained Monday in the race: Palm
Beach County's Ron Howard, who 12 years ago ran for the post as a
Republican and is now trying as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   A second Democrat who had hoped to challenge Brogan, Tallahassee
Community College instructor Eric Prier, Monday dropped out of the
race, having raised only $1,300 in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, though, is not likely to go unopposed for long.
Republican officials named a handful of potential candidates. Among
them: state Sen. John Grant of Tampa, who earlier this year
unsuccessfully sought the top job at the State Board of Community
Colleges; Rep. Bill Sublette of Orlando, who chairs the House
education budget committee; and Rep. Bill Andrews of Delray Beach,
who chairs the House K-12 Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats said to be considering a run: outgoing House
Minority Leader Buzz Ritchie of Pensacola; Rep. Cynthia Chestnut of
Gainesville, the former chairwoman of the House Education
Committee; Rep. Keith Arnold of Fort Myers, who prior to Brogan's
announcement was still running for governor; and Secretary of Labor
Doug Jamerson, a former state representative from St. Petersburg
who was defeated by Brogan four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged by the support,'' said Jamerson, adding that he
had been getting calls all day from people asking him to run.
</P>
<P>
   Sublette, an Orlando lawyer, said he will have to choose between
the education job and a run for an empty Senate seat. ``This is a
real shocker. It's thrown us into a tailspin,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lateness of Brogan's decision means that a candidate would
have to raise enough money for a statewide primary election in just
two months.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers agree Bush chose wisely with Brogan. Running
mates have not been Bush's strong suit: 1994 Rep. Tom Feeney
alienated many because of his unorthodox, libertarian views; this
past winter, Secretary of State Sandra Mortham quit the ticket
because of negative publicity over her financial management of her
office.
</P>
<P>
   But while clearly helping Bush and possibly helping himself _ it
would give Brogan a strategic post from which to seek the
governor's mansion _ the move gives an opportunity for the
Democrats to retain the balance of power on the Cabinet, even if
they lose the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats can win back the Education Commissioner's seat, and
the other five incumbents all win, Democrats would keep their
current 4-3 majority, even if Bush beats the Democrat front-runner,
Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay, for governor.
</P>
<P>
   And that possible scenario created some friction between Bush
and State Party Chairman Tom Slade.
</P>
<P>
   Slade, who has been out of the country for the past several
weeks, played a strong, not-quite-appreciated role in Mortham's
departure from the ticket. Bush, when asked if Slade approved of
Brogan's selection, answered tersely: ``Well, he found out about it
last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Slade could not be reached Monday, but did issue a news release
supporting the selection and acknowledging that the party must now
find a strong candidate on just 11 days notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no denying that we as a party have a task of holding
that seat,'' said GOP spokesman Bob Sparks. ``Do we wish we had
Frank Brogan again? Absolutely. But he has accepted a higher
calling. And that's that.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
