<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-BROGAN-COX     07-06 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BROGAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brogan announces acceptance on Bush's ticket
 &HT;    By Joe Vidueira and Brian Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ Maybe it was all those plugs for Education
Commissioner Frank Brogan at the end of every Jeb Bush for Governor
commercials that gave it away, but no one seemed surprised Monday
at gubernatorial candidate Bush's choice for running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a dynamic leader, very charismatic,'' said Schools
Superintendent Sara Wilcox, who succeeded Brogan in 1994. ``I can't
say I'm surprised. Frank Brogan achieves whatever he sets his mind
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogan's former associates praised the selection, saying they
had long ago predicted the Martin County educator's rapid ascent to
the highest levels of state politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``His character is impeccable, he's a great communicator and
he's the hardest worker I've ever seen,'' said former St. Lucie
Schools Superintendent David Mosrie, who Brogan named director of
public schools in 1996. ``He really walks the talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, Bush and Brogan were greeted by more than
100 cheering supporters as their private jet landed at Stuart Jet
Aviation. Stuart was a symbolic last stop for Brogan, who began his
political career here in 1988 when we was elected Martin County
schools superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Mary, by his side, Brogan told the crowd that by
joining the Bush ticket he would be able to further push his agenda
to improve education. Brogan said he believed that as lieutenant
governor working closely with Bush he could have more of an impact
on education than he does as education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who says he has visited more than 170 schools since
beginning his second campaign for governor, said that Lt. Gov.
Buddy MacKay ``cannot name one thing that he has done to enhance
the chances for a child to learn and Frank Brogan can name 100
things.''
</P>
<P>
   After the crowd left, Brogan and Bush parted company. Brogan
planned to spend some time in Martin County before beginning his
part of the campaign later this week. Meanwhile, Bush and his
family planned to depart today for a vacation in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Retired school board member and Port Salerno Elementary
principal Marion Carpenter said that she saw the spark of a future
leader when Brogan interviewed for his first teaching job in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   She said Brogan showed up in a three-piece suit and wing-tipped
shoes, and soon took over the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought: He's a leader, we gotta get him,'' Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, some were surprised Brogan accepted a role as
second-in-command. ``I thought he'd run for governor himself,''
said Carpenter. ``I guess this is a starting place.''
</P>
<P>
   Others saw a darker side in Brogan's meteoric rise, decrying his
conservative politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should pray for the health of Jeb Bush,'' said Tim
Black, vice president of the Martin County Education Association.
``Contrary to what Frank would have you believe, I never have
considered him a friend to teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogan's twin brother, John, who owns Brogan Pest Control in
Port St. Lucie, said his brother will relish the upcoming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quicker the pace, the hotter the fire, the more he likes
it,'' he said. But that's not the secret to his success, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an extremely hard worker, but he's also genuine and
sincere. And I think the general public appreciates that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosrie and others whose jobs may be endangered by wholesale
changes in the education department if the Bush-Brogan ticket
prevails looked at their boss' success philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'd wish he'd stay on as commissioner. But the
bigger picture is that now education will be elevated to a higher
level in the campaign (and in state government). He's doing the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What will the future hold for Brogan if the new GOP ticket
prevails?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Frank Brogan wants it to,'' Wilcox said. ``This may
be just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Vidueira and Brian Crowley are staff writers for the Palm
Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
