<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHERN-IRELAND-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TO ALLOW PROTESTANT MARCH IN BELFAST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ A day after a Protestant Orange
Order parade was blocked from marching through a Catholic
neighborhood, the British Parades Commission reversed two earlier
decisions Monday and gave permission for another Protestant march
to parade past a Catholic area.
</P>
<P>
   Commission chairman Alistair Graham said allowing the order to
march past the Lower Ormeau Road in Belfast next Monday should not
be seen as a tradeoff to help balance the decision banning the
march Sunday in the Drumcree area of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   A further ban, he said, would have risked inflaming passions
among pro-British Protestant loyalists who already feel aggrieved
at what they see as the authorities' eagerness to placate the
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot ignore the importance of perceptions in Northern
Ireland,'' Graham said at a news conference, ``and there is now a
clear emerging sense of deep hurt amongst loyalists, which arises
from our decisions to reroute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in danger of spilling over into a serious
law-and-order situation which is harmful to both communities,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   After two nights of sporadic violence over the Drumcree ban,
however, many people here considered the decision an attempt to
mollify the Protestants and a bid to head off possible new
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and experts said the decision was a weak, if not
disingenuous, attempt to make the government appear evenhanded,
alternating permissions and denials to weaken opposition. In
Ulster, pleasing one side usually outrages the other.
</P>
<P>
   The decison against the Drumcree Protestants produced Protestant
violence; the decision in favor of the Protestants next Monday is
expected to produce demonstrations by Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for residents of the Ormeau Road, John Gormley, said
the Catholic community would challenge the commission's ruling in
court, arguing that it had not met the legal guidelines set down
for the Orange marches.
</P>
<P>
   The experts said the decision was unlikely to defuse the
sitation at Drumcree, or end the fear that the violence endangers
the peace effort. Many feel that the most optimistic scenario is
that the inevitable public disorder in the next week will fade,
permitting the new Northern Ireland Assembly to resume its work
when it reconvenes in September. The least optimistic would be
Protestant unionist members' resignation from the new assembly,
which would vitiate the institution and raise the likelihood of
resumed sectarian killing.
</P>
<P>
   The Belfast march, which has twice been banned by the commission
in the last year, will be one of about 500 parades to celebrate the
victory of the Protestant William of Orange over his Catholic
father-in-law, King James II, at the Battle of the Boyne in 1690.
</P>
<P>
   Most Catholics find the parades offensive and triumphalist.
Protestants say they are a matter of freedom of assembly, a basic
right.
</P>
<P>
   The province was calm during the day Monday, but at night,
Protestants in Belfast continued their violent reaction, the police
said. Most of the incidents involved rioters throwing gasoline
bombs at the police. There were no injuries. A police spokesman
said at midnight, ``It's not as bad as last night, but the night is
young.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   People worried about the effects of sustained violence on the
peace effort, which nevertheless appeared to be moving ahead with
the start of work by the new assembly. It is to enact the peace
agreement approved in a referendum in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid the violence will break up the whole thing,'' said
Pauline Hegney, a Catholic mother of four, whose husband was shot
dead seven years ago by Protestant paramilitary forces. ``I don't
understand it,'' she added. ``Why should people want to march down
streets where they have no supporters?''
</P>
<P>
   But Andy Wood, a political consultant and former information
director for the British government here, said of the violence: ``I
don't think it puts the peace process in crisis. They are separate
matters. But it shows just how deep the fault line runs in parts of
Northern Ireland society.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and political leaders appealed Monday for restraint, and
for an end to the disorders caused by Protestants angry at the
British government's decision to deploy hundreds of combat-ready
British troops and armed policemen to block the 191-year-old annual
parade down a street in Drumcree, Portadown, 35 miles west of here.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred Orangemen camped out overnight in Drumcree,
sleeping in tents decorated with Union Jacks and vowing to stay
until they received permission for their march. They said that they
would remain peaceful, that the violent demonstrators were not
Orangemen and that Orangemen were not provoking the violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night the Orangemen were regaled by the Rev. Ian
Paisley, the hard-line Protestant leader known for his open
anti-Catholicism and opposition to the peace effort and the
assembly, which is to give Catholics more power. He did not
advocate violence, but he promised the campers they would win.
</P>
<P>
   Their mood Monday morning was jovial as they posed for
photographers and cameramen and answered reporters' questions. Two
years ago, in a similar dispute at Drumcree, Protestants rioted for
four days after the British government banned the march. The riots
forced the government to reverse its decision and allow the march.
The reversal in turn provoked Catholic rioting.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, protesters blocked dozens of roads, hijacked and
burned cars and fought several batttles with the police.
</P>
<P>
   Rioters in a neighborhood near the Belfast city center threw
flaming gasoline bombs at the police, who pushed the attackers back
by firing plastic bullets. There was only one serious injury in the
provincewide disturbances. An inspector's skull was fractured with
a brickbat in Londonderry.
</P>
<P>
   But the Protestants stayed largely in their own neighborhoods;
there were no serious clashes with Catholics. The police said the
level of violence on Sunday night was much lower than it had been
two years ago, during the last Drumcree crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, the political consultant, said ``What we need is four or
five days of the world's cheapest policeman _ rain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
