<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREMAIN-FLA-COX     07-06 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREMAIN-FLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIREMAIN
 &HT;    40,000 Florida resident return to homes
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger, Charles Elmore and Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUNNELL _ Crossing through charred forests and scorched fields,
nearly 40,000 residents who fled angry wildfires devouring their
rural county last week returned home Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For most, what they found was relief.
</P>
<P>
   While fires that at one point launched a fireball across
Interstate 95 burned nearly 49,000 acres, only 51 homes in Flagler
County were destroyed. Many more, surrounded by barren, blackened
landscape, remained safe behind a strip of green lawn that marked
firefighters' last line of defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a combat zone during World War II and that's what
this reminds me of,'' said Paul Economo, who learned through a
county hotline Sunday that his Palm Coast house had survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called up last night and . . . he said, `You're lucky,' ''
Economo said. ``He told me two of my neighbors weren't so lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   All around Central Florida, life tried, as best as possible, to
return to normal.
</P>
<P>
   I-95, closed since Friday between St. Augustine and Titusville,
reopened by lunchtime Monday. In Brevard and Volusia counties,
where fires burning since Memorial Day weekend devoured more than
200,000 acres, most returned home Sunday. Nearly all the fires,
particularly four that threatened to converge in a firestorm Friday
in Flagler County, had been sealed off by firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   After days of plotting fire attacks, efforts turned to relief.
</P>
<P>
   At an elementary school near Palm Coast, the center of the
fire's destruction, FEMA and state officials hung out their shingle
and offered help finding temporary shelter, paying rent, even
counseling. Small loans are available for minor repairs, but those
who completely lost homes will have to go through their insurance
carriers or the Small Business Administration, said FEMA community
relations officer Maria Munoz. By Sunday, 198 had requested housing
assistance from a FEMA hotline. Fifty more showed up at the school
by 3 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Central Florida relaxed, state officials shifted
their gaze north, where a new blaze ignited in a bone-dry stretch
of the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles flew to Bay County to survey 600 acres burned
by a fire possibly touched off by lightning Monday. Though the area
is sparsely populated, state officials worry it could spread
quickly and fear the Panhandle region of Florida will become their
tinderbox because it remains so dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get a break in this drought, we'll continue to have
fires,'' Chiles said. ``The good news is we have enough manpower.
That helped us a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the cost of fighting the fires has topped $116
million with losses estimated at $276 million. Altogether, 474,462
acres have burned statewide. About 100 people, mostly firefighters,
have been injured, and one elderly patient being evacuated from a
Flagler County nursing home suffered a heart attack and later died.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton plans to visit Volusia County on Thursday to
see the damage. Vice President Al Gore toured Flagler County last
week.
</P>
<P>
   What they will find is a battlefield, where an army of 7,000
firefighters from 44 states, including 200 who arrived overnight
from Maryland, waged war. Usually deserted country roads still
rumble with fire engines, tankers and trucks carrying platoons of
rescue workers. At intersections, National Guardsmen sent to
prevent looting stand watch, rifles slung across their shoulders. A
dusk-to-dawn curfew remains in effect in Flagler County.
</P>
<P>
   But even while the area remains in a kind of stand-down, rescue
workers are wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with this fire, it came through so fast, this
isn't dead. It could burn again,'' said John Tomaszewski, an
assistant fire chief from Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   A severe storm packing strong winds and hail and moving through
the area mid-afternoon Monday briefly set off alarms. But it passed
without fanning any more fires. Scattered storms were expected to
bring 1 to 2 inches of rain Monday, but officials say at least 10
inches is needed to douse the fires. There is a 50 percent chance
of more rain for the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   As they returned _ officially the county borders opened at 9
a.m. _ Flagler residents encountered signs of how narrowly the
battle was sometimes won.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all 51 of the houses destroyed are in Palm Coast, an area
of thickly wooded neighborhoods bordering I-95 where houses sit
sometimes only three to a street. Most of the houses were built in
the early 1980s and only one main road running north-south connects
them. The area resembles Wellington, with houses more widely
spaced; on every fifth lot, say, rather than side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Fires had been burning for more than 30 days here without much
worry. Then came Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A fire in the northwest corner near the Matanzas Woods
neighborhood suddenly sped southeast, pushed through treetops at up
to 35 mph, said Richard Wieser, Flagler County spokesman.
Firefighters saved most of the homes in the area before the fire
came to a brief standstill at I-95. Suddenly it fired its fireball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it jump I-95,'' said Jeff Aleshire, a Palm Coast
resident who ignored a voluntary evacuation and watched the fires
Thursday night. ``It was a big ball of fire basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Embers crossed four lanes of closed highway and ignited
neighborhoods further east. The next morning, state emergency
officials called for the countywide evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Desiree LaForte was one of the lucky ones. Her mother was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hear it on the phone yesterday was a little bit much for
me,'' said LaForte, who learned from the hotline that her house had
survived but her mother's had not. Monday morning she picked
through the chalky remains of her mother's one-story stucco house.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not going to take this well.''
</P>
<P>
   LaForte was about to give up searching the remains when her
brother-in-law eyed a sooty piece of iron, the end pieces to a park
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought that down from New Jersey when we moved,'' she
said. ``Good. At least we have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dixon had been playing golf just blocks from his Matanzas
Woods neighborhood when firefighters told him to start packing
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my golf clubs, a couple pairs of clothes and the
lawnmower. I figured there'd be no need to pack everything up
because we'd just be unloading it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dixon family home of nine years is now a pile of greasy
rubble. He and his wife April salvaged only one or two pieces of
his grandmother's china. Before noon, he stood in a driveway to
nowhere, debating options with an insurance agent.
</P>
<P>
   April Dixon weighed what to tell their two toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your 2-year-old says he wants to go home,'' she said,
tears welling, ``you just don't say anything. I try to change the
topic.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
