<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRES-SHELTER-COX     07-06 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-SHELTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELAND _ Floodwaters were noticeably missing and the numbers
were skewed _ think 22 cocker spaniels instead of two _ but Volusia
County's experimental ``ark'' sailed through the firestorm
peacefully and with high praise from its passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Animal control officers and volunteers operated a
people-and-pets shelter that took in 70 owners and 200 critters who
had to leave their homes. Dogs, cats, chickens, pigs, parakeets,
guinea hens, goldfish, five horses, one turtle and a pygmy goat,
most of them sleeping, eating and watching TV together in a
300-foot-long air conditioned building at the fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody called it a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What amazed me was how quiet it was,'' said Cindy Chesley, an
off-for-the-summer teacher who volunteered for kitchen duty. ``We
never heard any barking or any kind of loud noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners slept on cots, their pets beside them in cages, from
studio-apartment size wire enclosures _ for Great Danes _ to tiny
plastic carriers for puppies, Pomeranians and cats.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross brought food, the Salvation Army hooked up a
trailer outfitted with showers, and people kept coming through the
door with casseroles, blankets, pillows, toys, animal food, cages
and cat litter.
</P>
<P>
   Earl and Betty Hutson, who moved to DeLand last year from
Boynton Beach, even brought their Fun Bus for the kids to play in.
They converted the old school bus into a mobile play center with
miniature roller-coaster, jumping cage and slide.
</P>
<P>
   The people-and-pets shelter is a pilot program pushed by the
county's Animal Control Board, but never tested until now. By all
accounts, it was a thundering success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for this place, I don't know where we'd be,''
said Ed Maiocchi of Palm Coast, as he and wife Enid began hauling
their own and their son's pets out of the shelter, a total of five
dogs and nine cats.
</P>
<P>
   Kennel owner Mary Ann Meekins brought her own population
explosion _ 22 cocker spaniels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got so much walking, they were spoiled,'' Meekins said.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter will stay open through the end of the week, Director
Sergio Pacheco said _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McLachlin is a staff writer for the Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
