<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENNIS COSBY MURDER CASE GOES TO JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ As comedian Bill Cosby sat with his
family in the front row, a jury filed out of a courtroom here
Monday to begin deliberating the fate of the man accused of
murdering Cosby's son, Ennis.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance in court by Cosby, his wife, Camille, and their
daughters, Erika and Erinn, was their first at the two-week trial
of Mikail Markhasev.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors will return on Tuesday to resume deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday they heard Deputy District Attorney Anne Ingalls, in
closing arguments, tell jurors that Markhasev had convicted himself
with his own words.
</P>
<P>
   In letters that he wrote to another inmate while he was in the
county jail after his arrest, Ms. Ingalls said, Markhasev referred
to the Cosby killing as a ``robbery gone bad,'' a phrase she often
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis Cosby was shot to death while changing a flat tire about 1
a.m. on Jan. 16, 1997, beside a road on the west side of Los
Angeles. Stephanie Crane, a friend of Ennis Cosby's, testified that
he had called her when he got the flat and that she was waiting
behind him in her car as he fixed the tire. When a man came up to
her window, she fled, she said. When she returned, she found Ennis
Cosby dead, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ingalls reminded jurors that DNA evidence showed that a hair
found inside a cap wrapped around the murder weapon was almost
certainly Markhasev's. She referred to testimony from Christopher
So, who led police to the murder weapon, that Markhasev had said he
shot a black man, and that ``It's all over the news.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that another witness testified that Markhasev and a
friend, Eli Zakaria, were glued to the television in the hours
after the murder, looking for news of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   But, in their closing arguments Monday, Markhasev's lawyers said
the letters were fabricated by the inmate who prosecutors said had
received them, David Gomez, and they raised questions about how
different styles of handwriting were used in one letter.
</P>
<P>
   Markhasev's lawyers also attacked the credibility of So, who was
paid $40,000 by The National Enquirer for interviews and stands to
get a $100,000 reward if Markhasev is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   They said the prosecution was trying to ``torture'' evidence to
fit their theory of the crime. They pointed out that there was no
evidence placing Markhasev at the crime scene, and they raised
suspicions about the hair, noting that it was discovered nearly a
year after the cap was booked into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Henry J. Hall, a public defender, acknowledged in his closing
that he could not deliver on a promise he made to the jurors at the
start of the case: that he would prove it was Zakaria who pulled
the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can't prove to you, based on the evidence that has been
presented, that Eli Zakaria committed this crime,'' Hall said. But
he went on to argue that a composite sketch based on a description
by Ms. Crane more closely resembled Zakaria than Markhasev.
</P>
<P>
   Zakaria was expected to be a chief government witness in the
case but he refused to testify, reportedly saying that he would
assert his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination if put
on the stand. He appeared briefly in the courtroom once, when the
government compared his appearance with a composite sketch to
refute the defense contention that he is the man depicted.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby watched the defendant closely as he was brought out in the
morning. During a recess, Cosby chatted and laughed with Ms.
Ingalls, and later, as defense lawyers finished their summations,
he put a comforting hand on the shoulder of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Markhasev, who was 18 at the time, faces life in
prison without parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
