<SLUG> BC-NETSAVVY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Women Outscore Men in Net-IQ Test   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The high-tech industry is dominated by men, but women are just as
Internet savvy, according to a national test of Web surfers' online
intelligence.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women scored slightly higher than men on the online SAT-style
test sponsored by MCI Communications, the phone and Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   In the second annual test of Web-searching skills, women racked
up an average score of 82 _ equal to the national average _
compared with men's average of 80. The point difference is not
considered statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   Men make up two-thirds of Internet users nationwide and
constitute about the same portion of the 8,000 people who completed
the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cyberspace, we're all equal,'' said Diane Strahan,
executive director for community partnerships at Washington-based
MCI.
</P>
<P>
   By gender, maybe. But MCI also measured performance by state _
and California, birthplace of the high-tech industry, didn't even
come close to the top of the class.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Delaware was an ``A'' student, with a 94 score, while
California ranked behind 27 other states, with an 82 average.
</P>
<P>
   Utah was the No.2 state, and Alaska and Nebraska tied for third.
</P>
<P>
   Test-takers answered multiple-choice questions by searching the
Internet (although there was no way to prevent them from cheating).
It's no coincidence that the Internet intelligence test is similar
to the SAT test _ it was designed by a division of the Educational
Testing Service, the Princeton-based architects of the
college-entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   Results were measured by speed and accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Internet users' searching skills have improved
slightly. Last year's national average was 78, about 5 percent
lower than the 82 average for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans' Internet skills are improving _ we went from a `C+'
to a `B-,''' Strahan said.
</P>
<P>
   People ages 40 to 60 and those between 24 and 39 were the top
performers, each tallying up averages of 84. Test-takers who were
ages 18 to 23 years trailed the rest.
</P>
<P>
   A few people scored 100, which required correct answers to all
the questions within a few hours. MCI did not measure how many
people had perfect scores or determine who they were.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3 million people visited the site,
 &LR; www.nettest.mci.com &LR; , which went up in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
