</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALOMON-BONDS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALOMON TO DISBAND ITS BOND ARBITRAGE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Salomon Smith Barney said Monday in a memo to
employees that it would disband its U.S. bond arbitrage group _ for
years an important, although volatile, contributor to the profits
and vaunted trading reputation of Salomon Brothers _ after that
business suffered an estimated $15 million in losses in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The losses are relatively small for a firm that trades billions
of dollars. But the shuttering of the group and the departure of
its leaders illustrate how much has changed at Salomon _ a firm
once known for its swagger and its big market bets _ following the
Travelers Group's $9 billion acquisition of Salomon Inc. late last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Less risk, and particularly less big risk-taking with the firm's
own money, is now the order of the day, several people at Salomon
Smith Barney said Monday. The business of trading for customers is
now, some executives said, prized over proprietary trading with the
firm's own money.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Weill, the chairman of Travelers Group, and his
lieutenants at Travelers' merged investment firm, Salomon Smith
Barney, have prospered particularly through their careful
management of Main Street businesses that sell financial services
to private citizens and are said to be uneasy with the kinds of big
and sometimes spectacularly successful risk-taking Salomon has made
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney is ``going to be predominantly a retail
shop,'' an executive close to the firm said, adding, in reference
to Weill and his deputies James Dimon and Deryck Maughan, who are
co-chairmen and co-chief executives of Salomon Smith Barney,
``They're risk averse.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Salomon Smith Barney executive who spoke on the condition
of anonymity defended the closing as a sensible management move.
``There are now less opportunities in the U.S. bond markets,'' the
executive said. ``We now have a broader menu of options when we
decide how we want to use our capital.''
</P>
<P>
   In its memo to employees Monday, Salomon Smith Barney said that
Robert Stavis and Jeffrey Rosenbluth, the managing directors who
ran Salomon's bond arbitrage group, ``have decided to leave the
firm in order to pursue other opportunities.'' Stavis and
Rosenbluth, who have each spent more than 10 years at Salomon,
declined to comment when reached at their offices late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to some estimates at the firm, the U.S. bond arbitrage
group _ some 30 people in total _ might make a total loss of about
$15 million in the second quarter, after turning in a profit of
about $80 million in the three months ended March 31. The group's
employees will either be absorbed into the company's other bond
businesses or be let go, people at Salomon said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon and Maughan were the authors of Monday's memo to all the
firm's employees, which was titled Reorganization of Global
Arbitrage. ``Global arbitrage results this quarter will show a
small loss, a swing of about $100 million over the last quarter, in
large part driven by the reduced performance of the U.S. arbitrage
unit,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. bond arbitrage business has become less profitable in
recent years. More efficient markets mean that there are fewer easy
profit opportunities for such businesses. And, interest rates have
been more stable in recent years, reducing profit opportunities for
traders.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Effectively, Salomon is getting out of the bond arbitrage
business in the United States, assigning global responsibility for
that business to Costas Kaplanis, an executive based in London. In
its memo, Salomon said, ``We believe there continues to be
significant proprietary trading in other regions of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking big trading stakes has often caused embarrassing
quarterly losses for Salomon Brothers, which the firm was prepared
to accept as it often reaped huge annual profits from adventurous
trading. The closed business, several executives at the firm said
Monday, had regularly made big contributions to annual profits even
though it sometimes suffered quarterly losses.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon has often surprised investors with its sudden losses and
profits. Just last fall, for example, its profits for the three
months ended Sept. 30 were substantially reduced by a loss
estimated at about $100 million that the firm's equity traders _
who are not involved with the group closed Monday _ suffered on
investments betting on British Telecommunications PLC's ultimately
unsuccessful acquisition of MCI Communications Inc. When British
Telecom reduced its initial offer for MCI, Salomon's investments
soured.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other sudden losses, too. In 1994, Salomon's
bond business for institutional customers slumped, contributing to
an annual loss for that year of $400 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
