<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SAYS A FORMER GENERAL COMMITTED ADULTERY AND LIED
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Army's former deputy inspector-general engaged
in a pattern of ``inappropriate behavior'' or adulterous affairs
with the wives of four officers under his command, according to a
Pentagon report given to members of Congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Maj. Gen. David R.E. Hale, also ``sanctioned the
misuse of government resources'' to pay for international travel by
one of the women and then lied ``in an effort to deceive others
concerning his conduct,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The report, written by Eleanor Hill, the Pentagon's
inspector-general, significantly expands the controversy over Hale
and the accusations against him. The general, 53, retired in
February with the Army's blessing, even though a criminal complaint
accusing him of coercing sex had been filed by a subordinate's wife
while he was serving as deputy commander for NATO ground forces in
southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered Ms. Hill's
office to review the accusations and the Army's handling of the
case, including the decision to allow Hale to retire quietly, four
months after taking over as the Army's deputy inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the Army announced that it had begun a criminal
investigation based on Ms. Hill's findings, but the extent of the
accusations of wrongdoing was not clear until Monday. A copy of the
report, with the names blacked out to conceal the identities of the
women involved and other witnesses, was provided to The New York
Times by congressional staff members critical of how the Army
handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Army and other branches of the military
have been criticized for instances of sexual harassment and
misconduct that were ignored or investigated slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's response to the Hale accusations has prompted charges
of a double standard, giving senior officers more leeway than
junior officers or enlisted personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Army vigorously prosecuted its senior enlisted
soldier, Sgt. Maj. Gene McKinney, on 18 counts of sexual misconduct
involving six women, although he was ultimately convicted on only
one charge of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one more example of the disparity with which the
military operates,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., who has
strongly criticized the Army since Hale's case became public. ``If
you're a friend of the big guns and you've committed a crime, you
can just quietly disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hale has retired, the Army could recall him to active
duty to face court-martial. The Army's action last week strongly
suggested that he could face charges within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accusations first arose in March, Hale has refused to
comment publicly on the case, but the inspector-general's report
said he strongly denied the accusations. He also submitted a
40-page rebuttal, according to an official familiar with the case.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from a criminal complaint filed in January
by Donnamaria Carpino, the wife of an Army colonel who served under
Hale's command at the NATO base in Izmir, Turkey. She accused the
general of coercing her into having sex over a period of time in
the spring of last year by threatening to bring charges of adultery
against her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carpino divorced her husband in November, while Hale
divorced his wife in August 1997, after 30 years of marriage,
according to the report
</P>
<P>
   The inspector-general's report concluded that the
``preponderance of evidence'' showed their relationship was
consensual. But it also said that Hale's conduct fell under the
crime of adultery under the Uniform Code of Military Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry also uncovered evidence of adulterous affairs and of
other ``inappropriate relationships'' with other wives of
subordinates or former subordinates. The accusation of misuse of
taxpayer money involved the general's authorization that reimbursed
Ms. Carpino for the cost of a trip from Turkey to the United States
in May 1997, accompanying him, although ostensibly to attend to a
medical emergency involving her mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
