<SLUG> BC-RAIL-CONGESTION-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION PACIFIC FIGHTS TOUGHER REGULATION; SAYS CONGESTION IS
EASING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Union Pacific Railroad, seeking to fend off demands
for tougher federal regulation, said on Monday that congestion was
easing, capacity expanding, and competition with rival carriers
intensifying.
</P>
<P>
   And the company said that the whole railroad was now using a
single computer system for the first time since its 1996 merger
with Southern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But many customers are hardly reassured. Executives of the
Entergy Corp., a major electricity provider in the South and
Southwest, said the utility had not been able to get enough coal
delivered to its power plant in White Bluff, Ark., because of
congestion on the railroad. Several weeks ago, the utility came up
with a roundabout solution. Entergy now transfers coal from trains
to barges near Chester, Ill., and floats them down the Mississippi
River and up the Arkansas River to its plant. But the company says
it still cannot satisfy its demand for coal and has asked
regulators to allow a rival of Union Pacific to share its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Union Pacific have until Wednesday to file complaints
with the Surface Transportation Board, the principal railroad
regulator. The board will decide whether the government should do
more to clean up railroad congestion around the Houston area and
the Gulf of Mexico coast.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from members of Congress and Union Pacific
customers, the board, which is up for congressional reauthorization
this year, is also set to consider broader forms of relief for the
railroad's customers and tighter control over the whole rail
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson, R-Texas, has introduced a bill that
would make it easier for shippers to win rate cases that come
before the board in areas that lack competition. The bill would
also allow the transportation board to double, to 18 months, the
duration of emergency orders such as the one now requiring Union
Pacific to share some yards and tracks. That order, already
extended three times, expires next month.
</P>
<P>
   While the chances that Congress will act before its summer
recess are remote, such proposals are often meant to prod the
Surface Transportation Board to act on its own.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The merger with Southern Pacific to form the nation's largest
railroad caused what regulators called an unprecedented breakdown
in rail traffic through the heart of the nation. Economists
estimate that shippers have lost billions of dollars, and some
customers, like Entergy, have sued for compensation. Union Pacific
reached a settlement with DuPont, however, just last week.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific says there is no need to continue the emergency
order or impose any other rules. ``I don't think that by any
stretch of the imagination there's a congestion crisis on Union
Pacific,'' said Arvid E. Roach, a partner at the law firm of
Covington &AMP; Burling, which is responsible for presenting the
company's case to the Surface Transportation Board.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in Texas, the epicenter of a Union Pacific crisis
that began last year, yards have opened up and traffic is flowing
more smoothly, the company has said in its weekly reports.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Kollaer, president of the Greater Houston Partnership, a
leading business group, said that refineries and chemical plants
along the Gulf Coast were still having trouble moving their
products. Larry Parsons, the United Transportation Union general
chairman for much of Texas and Louisiana, confirmed the
improvements while adding that conditions were not back to normal.
But because the remedy has included a crash hiring program, he said
that inadequately trained brakemen and conductors were working on
the trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know one end of a boxcar from the other,'' he said.
``If you're a conductor and they send you one of these newbies out
there, you've got to watch this kid to keep him from getting killed
when he's running around.''
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific has said that its new employees receive ample
training, and Roach pointed to reduced accident rates this year.
Last year, however, a series of crashes left 11 dead.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad's worst snarls are now in and around Nebraska,
where coal trains, grain shipments, and cars bound for ports
converge on the nation's busiest tracks and its busiest yard, in
North Platte. In its latest reports, Union Pacific blames track
maintenance and the construction of new tracks and sidings.
</P>
<P>
   Checks with several utilities indicated that Union Pacific's
problems do not appear to be a factor in power shortages around the
Midwest. Entergy, however, has said it has had to switch from coal
to other fuels or buy power from other producers. Union Pacific
says it is shipping only about 75 percent of the coal it has
committed to carry, but this share represents a gain from about 50
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
   The transition to a single computer system for the entire
railroad has contributed to the tie-ups. Computers that could not
talk to each other sometimes lost track of shipments altogether.
The railroad said it delayed the final stage of its computer
integration, on the West Coast, from May 1 to July 1, adding
hundreds of technicians to help with the transition.
</P>
<P>
   While many customers have said the merger squelched competition,
Union Pacific has said it left two stronger competitors throughout
the Western United States. In the merger, it ceded or shared some
routes with Burlington Northern Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monopolists earn monopoly profits,'' Roach added. ``This
company has had losses for three quarters.'' The losses have
resulted from lost traffic and new investments to expand and
improve the rail system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
