<SLUG> BC-GLF-STEINBERG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBERG AIMS FOR 5TH SCGA TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (CORRECTS BYLINE SPELLING) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly 20 years ago, Craig Steinberg won the
Pacific-10 Conference golf championship and made a career decision.
The USC senior stuck to his studies and remained an amateur golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, today a 40-year-old San Fernando Valley optometrist
and attorney, never has regretted forgoing professional golf. And
the longtime Van Nuys resident is happy the way things have worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   His work has been satisfying, his family life rewarding. And his
golf game has taken him to the verge of history.
</P>
<P>
   When Steinberg tees up as defending champion Friday in the
opening round of the 99th Southern California Golf Association
championship in Murietta, he will be bidding for a record-tying
fifth title.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Stadler, Scott Simpson, Corey Pavin, Phil Mickelson, Steve
Pate and Mark O'Meara _ all of whom went on to successful careers
on the PGA Tour _ failed in their bids to win even one SCGA title.
No one since 1926 has won five _ Paul Hunter was the first and
last.
</P>
<P>
   Chatsworth's Tim Hogarth, one of 12 area entries in the 64-man
SCGA field, likes Steinberg's chances, even if the straight-hitting
Steinberg might prefer a course a bit tighter than 7,008-yard,
par-72 SCGA Members Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fabulous player and he gets better every time I see him
play,'' said Hogarth, the 1996 U.S. Public Links champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says this course doesn't fit him, because it's so open and
more of a bomber's course and he does better on a straighter
course. He's so straight it's scary. But I like his chances no
matter where he tees up.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, who won the SCGA in 1988, '91 and '92, outlasted
arguably the hottest amateur in the country last July when he won
his fourth title by one stroke at tight and familiar Lakeside.
</P>
<P>
   In the final round, Steinberg shot his second 67 of the
tournament to finish 4-under-par 276 and nip Walker Cup participant
Jason Gore, who was coming off consecutive wins in the state
amateur and state open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have enjoyed the last one the most,'' Steinberg said.
``It was at Lakeside, where I had caddied since I was 15, and I had
the good fortune of having the club president caddying for me.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Steinberg is coming off a strong showing in the state
amateur at Pebble Beach, where he won medalist honors, then reached
the second round of match play before losing 1-up to eventual
champion Ed Cuff Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings on that,'' Steinberg said. ``I played
very well. And in the match I lost, I wouldn't do anything
different. I had just one bogey and broke par at Pebble Beach. But
I would have rather lost to him on Saturday (in the final) than on
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuff also will be at Members Club this week. Longtime amateur
standout Mark Johnson will be there as well, bidding for one of the
few titles to elude him in a 26-year SCGA career.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 44, won the SCGA's high school title in 1972 and has
since won the state amateur, Pacific Coast amateur, SCGA
mid-amateur three times and SCGA tournament of club champions four
times.
</P>
<P>
   Cuff, a 1984 U.S. Amateur quarterfinalist, could become the
first player in 56 years to hold state and SCGA amateur titles at
the same time if he wins this week. A consistently strong
contender, he has been a state semifinalist three of the past five
years, defeating Tiger Woods one year. He'll certainly be a prime
challenger to Steinberg's title defense.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth thinks if a small group were to be formed including
Steinberg, Cuff, Johnson ``and I'd like to throw my name in there
once in a while, I think the (SCGA) winner could come out of that
group very easily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
