<SLUG> BC-ROYROGERS-COWTOWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY HAPPY TRAILS LED TO COWTOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It was Feb. 2, 1958, and Americans fretted
about losing the space race to the Soviet Union's Sputnik. Fort
Worth _ ``Cowtown'' _ took a breather from the Cold War to welcome
a hero to many, Roy Rogers, who rolled into town with wife Dale
Evans, sidekick Gabby Hayes, and the Sons of the Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final night of the Southwestern Exposition and Fat
Stock Show and Rogers was the host of a live telecast from the
rodeo, which NBC said easily beat out the 8 o'clock Sunday night
competition _ Ronald Reagan on CBS' ``General Electric Theater''
and ABC's ``Sid Caesar Show.'' NBC estimated the audience at 50
million.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands of the Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum sat a
13-year-old ninth-grader from Monnig Junior High, who had
worshipped Roy Rogers since he first saw the cowboy hero in
Saturday afternoon ``pitcher shows'' in Rising Star, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Gene Autry and Hopalong Cassidy, but Roy was the
epitome of the `good guy,' '' said Fort Worth City Councilman Jim
Lane, recalling an admiration that has wavered little over the
years, although he has stopped dressing like the ``King of the
Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really made me sad this morning when I heard he had died.
He was truly an American hero,'' said Lane, who owns a full-size
cutout of the singing cowboy, an official Roy Rogers lunch box,
saddle and other memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Television's Channel 5, then known as WBAP-TV, supplied the
local crew, and NBC brought in a director for the Stock Show
performance of ``The Chevrolet Show's'' Roy Roger's Musical Review.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers had been in town for a series of midnight-to-3 a.m.
rehearsals, held at the late hour because of the rodeo schedule,
said Johnny Hay, 79, a producer, director and on-air talent at WBAP
who helped out with cue cards during the Rogers show.
</P>
<P>
   The lettering, he recalled, was made extra large for Gabby, the
whiskered old-timer who, it turned out, didn't need them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had his lines memorized,'' Hay recalled. ``It was Roy who
couldn't read them. He wouldn't wear glasses. So at the last minute
I had to redo all of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the broadcast, a 24-year-old Bob Watt Jr., now the
Stock Show's general manager, was told that the coliseum dirt was
``too red'' for the new color TV cameras. He scrambled to find
something to change the hue without making the soil unsuitable for
the rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was found in cream-colored cotton seed hulls, a
feed filler, which he quickly spread the length and breadth of the
arena, the Stock Show chief recalled yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Rogers' live broadcast from the Stock Show went off
without a hitch except for the moment _ unseen by viewers at home _
when rodeo animals were released while six local dancers were still
on the coliseum floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us were equipped to climb up a wall, but when a steer
comes at you, you do it,'' recalled Ed Holleman, 71, of Fort Worth,
a dancer who choreographed the routines. As for Rogers, ``I had not
been a fan _ until I met him.''
</P>
<P>
   There were literally millions who never met Rogers but
maintained a lifelong affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been a nut about Roy Rogers,'' Lane said. ``I have a
palomino and a Jeep. He was just your buddy. When Dale Evans came
here last year, I was lucky enough to be on the stage with her. I
told her that Roy and I rode a million miles together.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
