<HEADER>
A2812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-VIAGRA-COX     07-06 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-VIAGRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medicaid not paying for as much Viagra as expected
 &HT;    By Mary Warejcka
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Poor men are not going as wild over
Viagra as state officials had feared.
</P>
<P>
   So the state Medicaid's $12 million-a-year projection for the
impotency drug is shrinking to $3 million to $5 million a year.
That sounds like a lot of money, but it is just a blip in Florida's
$7 billion yearly Medicaid budget.
</P>
<P>
   For $5 million, about 10 percent of the state's 176,000 men on
Medicaid age 19 or older _ or about 17,000 men _ would get three
pills a month. Recipients can get up to four pills a month.
</P>
<P>
   The taxpayer-paid coverage has resulted in a phone fury, said
Jerry Wells, state pharmacy program manager.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, people call to say impotency is a serious problem
and men need Viagra to help them feel better. On the other side,
callers are angry their taxes are being wasted.
</P>
<P>
   One day, two calls from the same senator's office were made to
Wells. One aide spoke against paying for the pills. Another wanted
to make sure a man who uses a wheelchair would be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The state Medicaid program must cover the drug unless the
federal government decides the drug is being abused, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fear with such popular drugs is that Medicaid patients will
trade their prescriptions for other drugs, services or cash on the
street, Wells said. There are no signs of that in Florida, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 44 days the drug was available, the state spent
about $2,700 a day, setting a $1 million yearly pace. So far,
13,819 pills have been distributed through 3,688 claims that cost a
total of $118,586.
</P>
<P>
   The state pays about $7.49 a pill but a $4.23 processing fee on
each prescription increases the price to about $8.58 a tablet.
</P>
<P>
   Wells expects the pace to still increase as doctors feel more
comfortable doling out Viagra and patients realize Medicaid covers
it.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast last year, the state paid 612 claims totaling
$260,000 for two different impotency drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra, which helps impotent men achieve and maintain erections,
is much more popular because a pill is simpler and less painful
than treatments that involve placing suppositories or having an
injection in the penis.
</P>
<P>
   But the drug is not for everyone. Experts warn that Viagra,
tested on a few thousand men, could cause unknown side effects in
the hundreds of thousands of men now taking it. So far, health
officials haven't heard of any major problems in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But at Palm Beach Gardens Medical Center's emergency room,
cardiologist Dennis Hanney has seen two men who have been near
death because they took Viagra and had been on a long-acting
nitroglycerin prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Warejcka is a staff writer for the Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
