<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS URGE UNION LEADERSHIP TO TRY AGAIN ON MERGER PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Minn., Mont., N.M.)   (fb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ A day after rejecting a merger with the American
Federation of Teachers, delegates at the National Education
Association convention gave their leaders a green light to
negotiate a revised merger agreement more to the delegates' liking.
</P>
<P>
   The 10,000 delegates to the convention, the Representative
Assembly, approved a resolution Monday that told the group's
officials to conduct a survey of why the merger was rejected and to
use that survey to guide the union in future merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream of uniting America's educators in a single
organization is very much alive,'' said Bob Chase, president of the
NEA.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the delegates gave for rejecting the merger agreement
was that the governing structure of the new union would be less
democratic than the NEA, that the teachers federation was too
militant and that they were unhappy that the merger would make the
education association part of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Merger supporters were delighted by Monday's resolution, saying
it breathed new life into their dream of a united voice to fight
the many attacks against the nation's public schools and public
school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the delegates stunned the union's leadership when
just 42 percent voted in favor of the merger, far less than the
two-thirds required for approval. The merger would have created the
largest union in American history by combining the NEA, which has
2.3 million members, and the American Federation of Teachers, with
950,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's resolution stated: ``The Representative Assembly
affirms its historic commitment to the concept of unity with the
AFT.'' Although the resolution set no specific date to resume
negotiations, it made clear that the delegates favored a merger,
but were unhappy with specific terms of the merger agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The vote against the merger left the NEA chapters in Florida,
Minnesota, Montana and New Mexico in limbo because they were on the
brink of merging with the teachers federation affiliates in their
states.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NEA's rules, such statewide mergers are prohibited,
but the resolution approved Monday directs the union's leadership
to develop guidelines to quickly address the question of merging
the state affiliates of the two unions.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates also voted for the two unions to extend their
agreement not to raid each other for members. In addition, the
delegates voted to continue the unions' joint council, in which
leaders from the two groups have cooperated in areas like teacher
quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
