<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2816 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BARDEN-2TAKES-     07-06 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BARDEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT ENTREPRENEUR SEES A `SLEEPER' MARKET IN NAMIBIA
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich., Ill., Ariz., Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(fb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHOEK, Namibia _ This windswept capital in the Namibian
desert is not the kind of arena where Michael Jackson normally
plays. And 500 buttoned-down executives and finance ministers
talking tariffs are not his usual audience. But the singer came in
May, striding up a conference room aisle in full fedora, lipstick
and Sgt. Pepper jacket, with a pushy entourage trailing along, to
give a quick speech deploring ``the plight of the children of the
universe.''
</P>
<P>
   It ended: ``My new business partner, Don Barden, and I are going
to be putting our money where our mouths are. We're going to be
looking at global investments that will bring economic development
to people and improvement to the lives of children.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the Gloved One to declare himself the Global One _ and
getting the staid World Economic Forum to make that its kickoff
speech here at one of its many regional meetings _ was one of the
quirkiest public relations coups southern Africa has ever seen. But
the versatile entrepreneur who managed it has some interesting
quirks himself.
</P>
<P>
   Donald H. Barden, 54, is one of America's wealthiest black
executives. He is the founder of a privately held conglomerate, the
Barden Companies, based in Detroit, which had estimated sales last
year of $110 million and was No. 14 on Black Enterprise magazine's
1998 list of 100 biggest black-owned industrial/service companies.
Barden is also one of a tiny few who have taken up a challenge
thrown down to African-American entrepreneurs by Ronald H. Brown,
the late commerce secretary: Come back to Africa and build a
business.
</P>
<P>
   Some might think Barden has a fatal attraction for risk. He does
not see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market is a real sleeper,'' he said during a joint
interview with Jackson in a small office in his Windhoek
car-rebuilding plant. ``Once the free-market system permeates, this
continent will be one of the world's most dynamic markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, most of Barden's risks were confined to the
American Midwest. He grew up as one of 13 siblings in Inkster,
Mich., outside Detroit. He was captain of his high school
basketball and football teams, but had to drop out of Central State
University in Ohio in 1963 because he could not afford the tuition.
Living with a big brother in Lorain, Ohio, he was a mover and a
laborer before opening a record store, then starting a label and
venturing into public relations.
</P>
<P>
   That was all before he, by chance, heard that a military
recruiting station near his office was looking for new space.
Barden helped it find a spot, and in that switch to real estate he
finally began to make some real money.
</P>
<P>
   Barden later founded The Lorain County Times, a weekly, sat on
the Lorain City Council and became a television anchor, where he
realized the profit potential in cable television. In 1983, after
wiring some small Michigan towns, he won the right to wire 375,000
Detroit households in partnership with a Canadian cable company.
</P>
<P>
   Barden sold his share of the cable television business for $105
million in 1994. He now owns five Illinois radio stations, an
Arizona software company and an Ohio real estate company that has
built jails and fancy suburbs. In 1995, he entered the gaming
industry; his riverboat, the Majestic Star of Gary, Ind., is
America's first black-owned casino.
</P>
<P>
   Barden doesn't shy from fights. In 1995, he took on Donald J.
Trump, publicly accusing him of ``extortion'' for demanding $25
million as part of a deal to share a wharf site in Gary. Nor is he
shy about sometimes using race to his advantage. He did so to win
the Detroit cable franchise, and last year he accused the city's
mayor of failing blacks and native sons by denying him a casino
license.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Barden's entry into Africa seems
counterintuitive. He chose Namibia, a country of only 1.7 million
people, instead of the obvious place, South Africa, with its higher
income and its population of 40 million. On top of that, Barden is
going into businesses he has never been in before: a General Motors
dealership and sales of canned food, drinks and mattresses. And his
target markets include some of the poorest, most forgotten people
in the world: the suffering millions of war-torn Angola and Congo,
the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   But there is method to his seeming madness. As Barden is quick
to point out, Namibia has excellent roads, railways and phones, a
benign if arid climate and a deep-water port at Walvis Bay. It has
had eight years of democratic government and a currency linked to
the relatively stable South African rand. And, most important,
little Namibia really, really wants him.
</P>
<P>
   Barden's connection with the country began in 1989, when he held
a cocktail party at his home for the ambassador of the South West
Africa People's Organization, the movement fighting to liberate the
country from South African rule. The movement succeeded in 1990,
and six years later he invited President Sam Nujoma to Detroit and
arranged a tour of a General Motors plant. GM was looking for a
route back into southern Africa, and Namibia was interested _ but
only if it got an assembly plant. The market was too small for GM
to bother with, but Barden suggested splitting the difference: if
the Namibian government would buy 800 GM vehicles through him, he
would build a plant to convert them to right-hand drive.
</P>
<P>
   That appealed perfectly to one of the pet peeves of Nujoma, a
sometimes cranky, sometimes jovial former guerrilla: his resentment
of South Africa. White rule is gone, but South African corporations
still dominate the regional customs union, and the high tariffs set
to protect their Volkswagen, BMW, Mercedes and Toyota local
assembly plants make cars in the whole subregion very pricey.
</P>
<P>
   Kano Audley Smith, managing director of the Namibian Barden
operations, said he could import GM cars, pay the duty, convert
them and still charge $1,000 to $18,000 less than a comparable
model from South Africa. ``If they were to price their vehicles
realistically, we'd be in trouble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter questioned the deal with Barden at a recent news
conference, President Nujoma cut her off, saying testily: ``We want
American products, not ones from those whites in South Africa. We
don't want to give our money back to white colonials. The cars are
cheaper, too _ you can go check.''
</P>
<P>
   About 125 pickups, police cars and school buses have already
been delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Barden says he has spent about $16 million to put together the
Windhoek plant and to train workers. But the car operation is
merely a foot in the African door, he says. He and Jackson envision
``investments eventually in the hundreds of millions,'' and are
particularly looking for casinos, resorts and theme parks. South
Africa's three major cities are granting casino licenses right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go 50-50 on everything,'' said Jackson, who once looked
into buying Sun City, the Indiana Jones-style casino resort complex
built in South Africa by Sol Kerzner, the South African casino
magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Barden were a little vague on how that would help
children, but Barden recovered, saying, ``If you're involved in
creating wealth, it puts you in a position to help the world.''
Because Jackson is a role model, he added, his focusing on business
would encourage children to grow up and do the same, leading to
economic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no disputing, for all the controversy that has
surrounded Michael Jackson, that he is indeed a role model for
children. The crowds that came out to see him even in tiny Namibia
were bigger than any crowds here ever before, including at
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Barden said their next investment would be warehouses in a new
tax-free zone on the Angolan border. Namibia may be tiny, but there
are millions of people in Angola, the former Zaire and western
Zambia with little access to goods because central African roads
are atrocious.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was crazy to seek out these markets _ Zaire had a
fierce civil war last year and a low-intensity war in Angola has
dragged on for 24 years _ Barden said: ``You think that if they
have a civil war, they're going to stop coming across the border to
buy goods? They still have to have food, mattresses, stereos,
refrigerators and beer, don't they? And they pay in diamonds _ that
is, they pay in cash they got from diamonds. In U.S. dollars.
That's pretty attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Namibians back him up on that. Most Angolans are poor, but
``we're used to seeing Angolans in the oil and diamond business
driving into Namibia in big U.S. cars to shop,'' said Philip H.
Namundjebo, an official in Namibia's offshore development agency.
</P>
<P>
   By investing in Africa, Barden and Jackson have become a rare
breed. Lots of American corporations send black executives to
Africa, but few black-owned companies have invested here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pioneer,'' acknowledged Millard W. Arnold, head of the
U.S. Commerce Department's Johannesburg office. ``He's been fairly
astute in maximizing an opportunity in a country like Namibia.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few other black-owned companies came. Ebony magazine has
a South African edition, for example, but is not widely available.
</P>
<P>
   With a 121 percent sales increase in 1997, Carson Holdings,
based in Johannesburg, which makes Dark and Lovely and Let's Jam
hair products, is doing better in Africa than its parent, Carson
Inc., is in the United States. It is run by Malcolm Yesner, a white
Zambian, but owned by an investment group headed by Roy Keith, a
black American.
</P>
<P>
   Procter Houston, another American, who arrived in 1995 to
distribute institutional furniture and says he is doing about $1.5
million in sales a year, said a ``second wave'' of black
entrepreneurs was landing in southern Africa now. He came out of
curiosity about the new government, he said, and found an amenable
environment. The newcomers, mostly engineers and computer
specialists, began arriving in the last year, partly thanks to
Arnold's efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some black investors, however, have been badly stung. Pepsi
South Africa, for example, which drew in celebrity investors like
Whitney Houston, Bill Cosby and Johnnie Cochran, just could not
make inroads into Coca-Cola's market dominance, and closed in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Barden seems unworried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about being here because Africa is our
homeland,'' he said. ``But we don't come in doing a lot of talk.
This isn't the first time I've built a building, or a new business.
We're here to get a job done, and make money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
