A2819 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYROGERS-MUSIC-TEX     07-06 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYROGERS-MUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS' MUSIC WILL FOREVER RIDE THE RANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever country music takes on pop overtones, doomsayers warn
that it's ``Happy Trails'' for good for the western branch of
``country-western.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roy Rogers was bigger than a passing trend, and so is the
sagebrush music he romanticized in the '40s and '50s. Roy Rogers'
music is as durable as an old saddle, and his status as both a
member of a musical group and as a solo artist helped make him an
icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He epitomized the cowboy image and romanticized cowboy song,
just as much as Gene Autry,'' said Bob Pinson, a researcher and
library acquisitions chief for the Country Music Foundation in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is the only person elected to the Country Music Hall of
Fame twice: He was inducted into the hall as a member of the Sons
of the Pioneers in the early '80s, then later in the decade as a
solo act.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded for RCA Victor and for Decca during his career. His
standards include ``Don't Fence Me In,'' ``I'm an Old Cowhand (From
the Rio Grande)'' (with the Sons of the Pioneers), ``May the Good
Lord Take a Likin' to Ya,'' ``California Rose,'' ``Rock Me to Sleep
in My Saddle'' and of course, ``Happy Trails'' with Dale Evans (who
wrote it), the Whippoorwills &AMP; Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Although to admit it might be blasphemy in many circles, Roy
Rogers' baritone had greater range and a melodic quality that
Autry's voice lacked. Roy's best can be found on Rhino's four-CD
``Songs of the West'' collection, issued in 1993. One of the four
discs is dedicated entirely to Rogers and Gene Autry, and various
cuts are scattered through the other three CDs.
</P>
<P>
   If you can get hold of ``Roll On, Texas Moon,'' on the German
Bear Family label, you'll have a fine collection of songs from nine
of Rogers' 1940s films.
</P>
<P>
   How versatile was he?
</P>
<P>
   Rogers furthered the cause of yodeling while with the Sons of
the Pioneers in the '30s. His own composition, ``Cowboy Night Herd
Song'' (1937), helped set the standard for future warblers.
</P>
<P>
   He could even swing a little, although self-consciously, as
exhibited by ``On the Old Spanish Trail'' from the 1947 movie of
the same title, with Spade Cooley and His Western Swing Band.
</P>
<P>
   MCA and the Country Music Hall of Fame issued a fine Rogers
retrospective CD in 1992, covering his career from the Sons of the
Pioneers to World War II. RCA's more commercial ``Tribute'' album
in 1991 included Clint Black, the Oak Ridge Boys and Lorrie Morgan
doing duets with Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' last chart recording, in fact, was his duet with Black,
a single called ``Hold On, Partner'' with an imaginative Old West
video of the two on horseback. Roy, then in his late 70s, still
looked noble, and Black looked like a younger version of Roy, with
smiling, squinty eyes above that broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Rogers' most enduring musical legacy is as a founder of
the Sons of the Pioneers. Modern-day groups Riders in the Sky (with
Rogers sound-alike Ranger Doug Green singing lead) and Sons of the
San Joaquin, as well as the still-intact Pioneers themselves, have
made a cottage industry of Southwestern harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   And a subculture of cowboy singers and poets has idealized Roy's
simple values into a quasi-religion, and their music delves back
even deeper than movie cowboys' romanticized vision. People like
Michael Martin Murphey, Red Steagall and Don Edwards are Roy's
soulmate successors, leaving behind what they see as the
mesquite-choked, fenced range that is contemporary country.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Rogers' greatest farewell, and the one to listen to now
(with a hankie) is his 1974 single ``Hoppy, Gene and Me.'' A
poignant tribute to the singing cowboy era, it scored on both pop
and country charts. No one has ever recorded a more gentle, more
loving message to his fans than this.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
