A2820 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-POWELL-HNS     07-06 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-POWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Powell deal creates crowd in Astros' bullpen
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ The Astros' trade for Jay Powell was hardly a blockbuster.
But it could be enough to shore up the shakiest area on the club.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the season, Doug Henry was the only proven
righthander in a bullpen that featured four lefties. That's no
longer a problem following Sunday's acquisition of Powell, who
helped the Florida Marlins win the World Series last fall.
</P>
<P>
   What was once a scarcity is now a logjam. The acquisition of
Powell, who won Game 7 of the 1997 World Series, gives the Astros
eight relievers, including four righthanders _ Henry, Powell, Bob
Scanlan and rookie Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Like most teams, the Astros opened the season with six relief
pitchers. They have carried seven the last two weeks and will
continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   That said, one of the current relievers will be forced out when
the Astros re-set the roster at 25 players Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're going to stay with 12 pitchers,'' general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``There has to be a reason to make a
move, and we haven't missed having an extra position player. With
our lineup, it's hard to get playing time for our bench players, so
it's a more prudent course for us to go with an extra pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent additions of Elarton and Powell appear to have
lessened the role of Scanlan, who could be the odd man out. At the
same time, carrying 12 pitchers might make it difficult for manager
Larry Dierker to find work for everyone in his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros fear that scenario, they might decide to return
the highly touted Elarton to Class AAA New Orleans, where he could
get regular work.
</P>
<P>
   But Elarton's two scoreless relief appearances probably were
enough to buy him some more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we make our move, that doesn't necessarily mean
we're going to stay that way for a while,'' Hunsicker said. ``We'll
just have to see how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the corresponding roster move, the Astros' bullpen
should be better with Powell, whom the Astros acquired along with
journeyman minor-league catcher Scott Makarewicz in exchange for
highly regarded catching prospect Ramon Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Castro was one of the Astros' two first-round picks in 1994. The
other was Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a good trade,'' All-Star second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``We needed a little righthanded help in the bullpen.
We did really well in the first half and it's good to see them
(Astros management) add a player who might help us in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powell is a good pitcher. He throws hard, and he has a good
slider and sinker.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Astros is more familiar with Powell than All-Star
left fielder Moises Alou, who played with Powell last season in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job for us in Florida last season, and I think
he'll do a great job for us in Houston,'' Alou said. ``He did very
well for us in the playoffs and it's always good to have players
who have done well in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to the playoffs this season, and Jay is a
guy who can help us get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker has been eyeing Powell, who will earn $320,000 this
season, since spring training. But the Marlins were reluctant to
listen to offers until recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros believed they could afford to part with Castro
because New Orleans catcher Mitch Meluskey is closer to reaching
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an opportunity for us to add a good, young arm to our
staff,'' Hunsicker said. ``I think he'll be a nice complement to
Doug Henry in our bullpen. He gives us another good setup man that
we can use in the seventh and eighth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Powell into a winning environment and giving him a
chance to work with (manager) Larry Dierker and (pitching coach)
Vern Ruhle is only going to make him better. We gave up a good,
young catcher in Castro, but we're trying to win this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker still would like to add a top-notch starter to the
rotation, but most players who fit into that category are
unavailable or too expensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
