<HEADER>
A2821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAKS-MARKETPLACE-ART-     07-06 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKS-MARKETPLACE-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: WALL ST. VIEW OF SAKS SALE _ NO BIG BARGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Stock chart for Proffitt's is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With his deal to acquire the glitzy Saks Holdings
Inc., Brad Martin, chairman of Proffitt's Inc., the Southern
department-store chain, has given his company a major makeover.
Proffitt's shareholders, though, seem to view the merger as the
Wall Street equivalent of a fashion don't.
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's stock fell $4 in heavy trading Monday after the deal
was announced. It closed at $36.6875, down 9.6 percent from its
closing price of $40.6875 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Saks' shareholders will get 0.82
share of Proffitt's stock for each Saks share. Proffitt's will
issue 52.5 million shares, putting a price tag of about $2 billion
on the deal. And the company will change its name to Saks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's investor reaction was a surprising putdown for Martin,
given that the company's share price has risen almost 60 percent in
the first half of the year. Since 1994, the company has acquired
five major department-store chains, and the stock has mostly gone
straight up. It bought Carson Pirie Scott, the Milwaukee-based
department-store chain, early this year without the stock missing a
beat.
</P>
<P>
   So why are investors stampeding out on news of the Saks deal?
</P>
<P>
   They seem to dislike a couple of aspects of the deal. Most
important is the price. In its bid for Saks, which includes 96
stores and a mail-order business called Folio, Proffitt's is paying
1.3 times the revenues of Saks in the last 12 months and 13 times
its earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization.
</P>
<P>
   That is much richer than Martin's past acquisitions. In the
Carson Pirie Scott purchase, for instance, he paid 0.8 times
revenues and nine times earnings before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization. Getting retailers on the cheap has
worked well for Martin and allowed him to expand Proffitt's
business to 234 stores in 24 states as well as to increase the
company's earnings by 20 percent on average over each of the last
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Driving hard bargains has allowed Martin to keep operating
margins high as he melds operations and cuts overlap. Proffitt's
margins of almost 12 percent are well above the 7.4 percent
industry average.
</P>
<P>
   Worries that the Saks acquisition will depress Proffitt's
earnings helped drive down the stock Monday. Although Proffitt's
said it expected the acquisition to add a penny or two to earnings
per share in the fourth quarter of 1998, and 3 to 5 cents a share
next year, some Wall Street analysts say the deal could dilute
earnings for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   If paying up is something new for Martin, so is buying a
high-fashion emporium like Saks. The other acquisitions by
Proffitt's, which is based in Birmingham, Ala., have been names few
on Fifth Avenue would recognize: G.R. Herberger's, based in St.
Cloud, Minn.; Younkers Department Stores of Iowa, and Parisian, a
chain found throughout the South. Buying a trendy store like Saks
not only may bring Proffitt's into the big time, but it may also
bring a greater chance of fashion flubs that can cause earnings
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   This was one reason Jeffrey Edelman, who follows retailing
stocks at Paine Webber, downgraded Proffitt's stock Monday from a
``buy'' rating to ``attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Longer-term there are some very interesting possibilities in
the acquisition,'' Edelman said. ``But Saks is not the traditional
department-store acquisition Brad Martin has made. The fashion
business adds more risk to the profile.''
</P>
<P>
   The size of the purchase is another worry. For the 12 months
ended May 2, Proffitt's generated sales of $3.6 billion and net
income of $140 million. During that period, Saks Holdings had sales
of $2.3 billion and net income of $57 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Glik, president of Glik's Stores, a department-store chain
with 57 outlets in the Midwest, said: ``Coming right on top of the
Carson acquisition in the spring, they're really stretching their
organization on this one. Brad Martin is the best in the industry
when it comes to working with people, but this one will be a lot of
work.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Furthermore, this acquisition may not afford as much room for
savings as Proffitt's other buyouts. Martin said he expected cost
savings at the combined operations of $10 million to $12 million in
1998; $60 million to $70 million in 1999, and $75 million to $85
million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Isaac Lagnado, president of Tactical Retail Solutions, a
market research firm in New York, said: ``The reality is Saks is
not some underperforming laggard like Proffitt's has bought in the
past. So the question is: Can you squeeze a whole lot of expense
percent out of that?''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of the merger, according to Martin, is the
ability to sell the Saks catalog merchandise to the 5.2 million
credit-card customers of Proffitt's. But the recent experience of
Saks with its Folio catalog has been disappointing. Arnold Fishman
of Marketing Logistics Inc. in Highland Park, Ill., says Saks is
dead last among department stores in sales through stand-alone
national catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus sold $155 million by catalog last year;
Bloomingdale's by Mail generated revenues of $140 million;
Nordstrom did $115 million, and sales at Saks came in at just under
$100 million. ``Saks has grown very slowly over the past five
years,'' Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the catalog potential, Proffitt's stock may remain
under pressure. Why? The matter of the big stake held by Investcorp
International of Bahrain. It and its affiliates own 18 percent of
Saks Holdings, and they hold 27 percent more for clients. Once
those shares are exchanged for 24 million Proffitt's shares, how
long will it be before they hit the market? Investcorp is known for
stakes in luxury-goods retailers, like Tiffany &AMP; Co., not in
mundane department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the 52.5 million shares to be issued and the stock that
Proffitt's already has outstanding, the holdings of Investcorp and
its affiliates and clients will amount to almost 17 percent of the
retailer's total shares. That's some potential sell order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
