<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TRIES TO STOP TOUGHER REGULATION
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to fend off demands for tougher federal regulation,
Union Pacific Railroad said that traffic congestion was easing,
capacity expanding and competition with rival carriers
intensifying.
</P>
<P>
   But many customers disagree. The industry's main regulator, the
Surface Transportation Board, has set Wednesday as the deadline for
complaints. The board will decide whether it should offer more
relief for the railroad's customers and tighter control over the
entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   THE SELLING OF THREE MILE ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   GPU Inc. is hoping to sell Unit 1 of Three Mile Island, which
was not involved in the nuclear-power-plant accident that occurred
in March 1979 when operators failed to close a pressure-relief
valve, allowing a million gallons of cooling water to escape and
causing the radioactive core to reach 5,000 degrees. It also wants
to sell the Oyster Creek nuclear plant in Forked River, N.J.
Analysts are speculating that one of the potential buyers is Peco
Energy of Philadelphia, which operates two nuclear plants in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Power, the United States' second-largest operator of
nuclear plants, has filed the first application to extend the life
of a nuclear plant. The three-unit Oconee nuclear power station in
western South Carolina has been producing power for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   FORD SALES JUMPED 9.8 PERCENT IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Ford reported a 9.8 percent increase in June car and light-truck
sales from June 1997, pushing total U.S. car and truck sales last
month to a seasonally adjusted annual selling rate of 16.7 million,
its highest rate in more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   GROWTH IN BUSINESS ACTIVITY SLOWS
</P>
<P>
   Business activity at nonmanufacturing companies in June expanded
at a slower pace than in May, the National Association of
Purchasing Management reported.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P 500 REACHES RECORD HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Investor optimism lifted stocks and sent the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index up 10.91 points, to a new high of 1,157.33. The Dow
Jones industrial average increased 66.51 points, to 9,091.77. The
Nasdaq composite index, which is heavily laden with technology
issues, rose 15.47 points, to 1,909.47, and is just 8.14 points
away from its April 22 record.
</P>
<P>
   30-YEAR BOND YIELD FALLS TO 5.57 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.57 percent,
from 5.60 percent Thursday, matching the low set on June 15 _ the
lowest it has been since the government began regular sales of
securities in 1977. The bond's price rose 12/32, to 107 31/32, with
much of that attributed to weakness in the Japanese yen compared
with the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT WAVE HURTS UTILITIES
</P>
<P>
   Two Midwestern utilities, Firstenergy and Illinova, said that
they had suffered huge losses from having to buy power on the open
market during the recent heat wave when prices surged. The
companies said the losses would result in lower earnings.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA PRESCRIPTIONS AT 2.9 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Viagra, Pfizer's drug to remedy male impotence, broke all sales
records in its first three months, according to an industry
consultant. Prescriptions for Viagra from April through June
totaled 2.9 million, for estimated sales of $259.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   FAA PLAN ENCOUNTERS HURDLES
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is trying to replace its
aging nationwide network of radio beacons and other navigation aids
with a satellite-based system. But some aviation experts think that
the new system will not be reliable, and they want the government
to maintain both systems.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIMISM OVER APPLE COMPUTER
</P>
<P>
   When Apple Macintosh fans gather on Wednesday, many will be
optimistic because the company appears to have stabilized its
management team, cut costs, made some money and halted a
precipitous decline in market share.
</P>
</TEXT>
