A2839 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYROGERS-MEMORY-TEX     07-06 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYROGERS-MEMORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE ROLE MODEL RIDES OFF INTO THE SETTING SUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was kid, I WAS Roy Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   It was as simple, and as sublime, as that.
</P>
<P>
   I galloped a stick horse named Trigger around the house where we
lived in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Socks, my devoted collie-shepherd mix, was transformed into
Bullet and happily frolicked with me as we chased bandits out of
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   I daydreamed of the day I would meet my own Dale Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Countless cool afternoons were spent in the darkness of the
Cactus Theater in downtown Carlsbad, watching Roy and Gabby Hayes
and the gang put the bad guys behind bars where they belonged.
</P>
<P>
   I combed my hair like he did, with that wave in the front. I
dismounted from my ``Trigger'' like he did. I even tried to sing
like he did, with that wondrous silky smooth voice and intense
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So when I heard Monday that Rogers, the ``King of the Cowboys,''
had died, my stomach did a slow flip-flop and then stuck in my
throat.
</P>
<P>
   I was fortunate to have plenty of excellent role models in my
family, but I wanted to grow up to be just like Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck off in the southeastern corner of nowhere in the early
'50s, I didn't know much about professional sports. Oh sure, I'd
heard of Willie Mays and Mickey Mantle and I would come to idolize
Hank Aaron and Eddie Mathews, but that was later.
</P>
<P>
   For at least half a dozen years, from the time I was old enough
to form my fingers into the semblance of a six-shooter and loop a
shoestring around a broomstick, turning it into a trusty palomino
steed, it was Roy Rogers who taught me as much as anyone about
right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He was Dudley Doright in our house long before the first TV set
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   My greatest lament today is that my own sons, growing up in a
far more complicated world, didn't have a Roy Rogers to emulate and
learn from.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize it at the time but Roy, with his bandana
knotted around his neck, his six-shooters tied low around his waist
and his guitar always handy at the campfire, was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Autry and Champion were OK and when television came along
with Hopalong, the Lone Ranger and the Cisco Kid, I certainly
watched. But none of them could touch Roy. He had a certain
charisma about him that simply eluded the rest of the silver screen
cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   That's why for a dozen years, between 1943 and 1954, he was the
No. 1 western star at the box office and starred in 87 films during
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Roy and Dale, Trigger and Bullet, Gabby and Pat, they were
household names across America. Sure, the movies were corny and
predictable, but when you were six and you sat in that darkened
theater, with your popcorn and your Coke, it just didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   All you cared about was that Roy and his crew were about to
teach the bad guys a lesson in good manners.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of shooting, but no blood was shed in a Roy
Rogers movie. There were no gaping wounds and if a bad guy died, he
did it discreetly. Most of the time Roy just shot the guns out of
their hands or walloped them in a good, old-fashioned fistfight.
</P>
<P>
   At heart, he disliked violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a boy,'' Rogers once said, ``our parents taught us
that hitting below the belt was a cowardly thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Rogers never hit below the belt. Never.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those of us who grew up watching Roy didn't know then
that his real name was Leonard Slye, or that before he broke into
movies he was a truck driver and peach picker.
</P>
<P>
   We just knew that he represented what was right about America.
There was no gray between right and wrong in those days. Things
were as black and white as the hats the actors wore.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was a far simpler time, before we lost the Kennedys and
Martin Luther King, before Vietnam and Watergate. We were lucky
then. We didn't grow up knowing about drugs, and HIV. There was no
movie rating system because it wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he quit making movies, Roy Rogers was still the same.
He and Dale had the All-American family, raising nine children,
several of them adopted. They believed in God and didn't apologize
for it.
</P>
<P>
   They lived, of course, in Apple Valley in California, where you
figured the sun was always shining, and you could always drop by
and visit Trigger at the Roy Rogers and Dale Evans Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Old Trigger was gone but hardly buried. Roy had him stuffed and
posed, rearing on his hind legs, like he did at the end of so many
pictures with Rogers on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't bear to put him in the ground,'' Roy said, and
those of us who had been Roy Rogers ourselves, for a short period
in our lives, understood perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   I wish now that I'd done the same with that old stick horse of
mine.
</P>
<P>
   You don't ever say goodbye to a friend like that.
</P>
<P>
   You just say, ``Happy trails to you, 'til we meet again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
