<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2841 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYROGERS-MOVIES-TEX     07-06 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYROGERS-MOVIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE TOOK TO THE SCREEN LIKE A COWBOY TO HIS SADDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man we came to know as Roy Rogers was down and out in LA
when an accidental meeting turned his life around.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Spencer and Bob Nolan, a musical duo on station KHJ, were in
the studio when Rogers, then known as Len Slye, flunked an audition
for a pop music program. They liked what they heard, so the duo
became a trio. But when Tim, Bob and Len added brothers Hugh and
Carl Farr and became the Sons of the Pioneers, they caught on in a
big way.
</P>
<P>
   They were different, limning western _ not country, not
hillbilly, but ``western'' _ songs, including many that have
attained permanence in our popular culture, including ``Tumbling
Tumbleweeds,'' ``Cool Water,'' ``Chant of the Wanderer.'' Roy
Rogers was in the ensemble only three years, but that was when the
Sons began recording with RCA Victor. Roy was their tenor, pure of
voice and strong when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republic Pictures was formed in 1935, with a
specialty in quickie westerns, those pointed at the
Saturday-matinee kiddie trade. Republic started with one bankable
cowboy star _ John Wayne. Then, the new company experimented
successfully with the concept of a singing cowboy: ``Tumbling
Tumbleweeds'' in 1935 was Gene Autry's first starring vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Autry movies proved so popular that Republic decided to
launch a second series with a warbling ranger. Seeking a ``new
face'' as well as a suitable voice, the company tabbed Len Slye as
the ``next Autry'' and changed his movie name to Roy Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, after he had learned to ride a horse, ``Come On,
Rangers'' introduced Roy as a new star. Next came ``Under Western
Stars,'' and the verdict was in: Roy was a hit, and Republic would
continue to ``build'' its new and likable personality.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republic had not envisioned making major films, its
loan of John Wayne to Walter Wanger and John Ford for the epochal
``Stagecoach'' had brought unexpected stature to Wayne. So in 1940,
the company produced ``Dark Command'' as a superwestern, brought in
the renowned Raoul Walsh to direct, and assembled a star cast
including Wayne, Claire Trevor, Walter Pidgeon, Marjorie Main ...
and Roy Rogers as Trevor's troubled younger brother. He was swamped
by the other players' authority, so it was back to the quickie
mill, where his star continued on an upward trajectory until he
surpassed Autry in popularity and became ``King of the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, a definite shift in the type of western in
which Roy Rogers appeared. His apprentice films usually were period
pieces, with Roy often a cavalryman. But his high-flying 1940s
entries were more sophisticated, with modern settings, elaborate
decor and Roy outfitted in custom-designed western regalia.
</P>
<P>
   The titles had a romantic ring _ ``The Yellow Rose of Texas,''
``Bells of Rosarita,'' ``Song of Nevada.'' The Sons of the Pioneers
of later edition were still around, giving musical support.
Automobiles were on the scene, but Roy usually rode to the rescue
or any other cliffhanger climax on Trigger, ``the smartest horse in
the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1944's ``The Cowboy and the Senorita,'' his leading lady for
the first of many times was Dale Evans, whom he married three years
later. They were etched as one of filmland's happiest couples, and
they certainly were resilient. When westerns dried up, after nearly
100 films, Roy and Dale formed their own TV company and rode to
fantastic business success in western products _ cattle,
thoroughbred horses, rodeos and a prolific restaurant chain.
</P>
<P>
   People who knew him said it couldn't have happened to a nicer
guy.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
