<HEADER>
A2843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-LANDANO-TRIAL-500-     07-06 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-LANDANO-TRIAL-500-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
AFTER JUDICIAL ODYSSEY, A SECOND TRIAL IN A NEW JERSEY OFFICER'S
DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of his alibi witnesses are dead, crucial evidence has been
lost and the police officers who arrested him have long since
retired. But after a 22-year legal odyssey that has taken him from
courtroom to prison to freedom and back again, Vincent James
Landano will go on trial again Tuesday for a murder he has
consistently maintained he never committed.
</P>
<P>
   Landano is charged with shooting a Newark police officer, John
Snow, during the robbery of a check-cashing office in Kearny, N.J.,
in August 1976. As he has since he was first arrested shortly after
the murder, he insists he was framed and was never anywhere near
the scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of the Snow murder in 1977, Landano served nearly 13
years of a life sentence before he was ordered released by a
federal judge who ruled that the prosecution had suppressed
evidence that might have persuaded the trial jury to acquit him.
</P>
<P>
   Now a graying 58-year-old with a wife, Camille, a little dog
named Sparky, a newly purchased house in Manville and a steady job
as a paralegal, Landano said he expected to be vindicated and
regain control over his own life. ``I've been fighting for 22 years
_ half of my life _ and I'll be damned if they are going to beat
me,'' he vowed. ``I'm not going into it to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Landano was freed in 1989, a series of Hudson County
prosecutors have continued to pursue him, maintaining in court
hearing after court hearing that there was convincing eyewitness
and physical evidence of his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The ``interests of justice and fair play will be best served''
by presenting the evidence again to a grand jury, Donald Gardner,
an assistant county prosecutor, said in early 1996. Later that
year, a grand jury indicted Landano once again.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be heard by Judge Shirley Tolentino of Superior
Court in Jersey City, in a small windowed courtroom where for the
last month the lawyers have toiled to find jurors with no prior
knowledge of the case. Only last week, they assembled a jury pool
of 48 people, who will be winnowed down Tuesday just before opening
statements.
</P>
<P>
   The Landano case has outlasted all the original judges,
prosecutors and defense lawyers and gained a special notoriety, not
only for its staying power but for the hostility that has grown up
among the players.
</P>
<P>
   At various times, Landano's lawyers have accused the prosecution
of coaching witnesses and planting evidence. Prosecutors have
demanded that judges order the defense not to discuss the case and
once elicited sympathy from a judge who scolded the defense for
trying to ``demonize'' the Hudson County prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   And Landano, who since his release has worn an electronic device
that permits the authorities to monitor his movements, is as openly
bitter about his experience as he is steadfast about his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been done the wrong,'' he said. ``I haven't done the
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, the prosecutor, was not available for comment Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Landano was an unemployed construction worker trying to kick a
drug habit when he was first arrested in connection with the death
of Snow, a 23-year veteran of the Newark Police Department who was
shot at close range outside the Hi-Way Check Cashing Service in
Kearny.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, in uniform and in a marked patrol car but off-duty,
was apparently making a scheduled delivery of $46,000 to the owner
of the office. He drove up just as two men were robbing the office.
One of the robbers ran up to the cruiser, shot Snow through the
neck, jumped into a stolen car and fled with his accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Landano maintained he was never at the scene and
was being framed by members of a Staten Island motorcycle gang that
called itself ``The Breed.'' Landano said he did know one of the
gang leaders, a childhood friend named Victor Forni who was later
arrested and convicted of helping to plan the robbery. But he said
he never knew other gang members, although one of them named
Landano as his accomplice in the robbery and the gunman in the Snow
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that followed the first trial, the case took on a
new life with enough twists and turns to qualify for a
made-for-television script.
</P>
<P>
   Landano met a West Orange, N.J., lawyer who was visiting another
client in prison. The lawyer, Neil Mullin, was intrigued with his
story and took Landano on as a client _ and a personal crusade _
for free. ``It was my life's work,'' Mullin said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Landano's wife, who met him when she attended a
prison basketball game staged to benefit a charity she supported,
Mullin searched for holes in the case. Eventually, he found enough
to convince Judge H. Lee Sarokin of U.S. District Court that
crucial evidence had been suppressed by the prosecution, including
evidence that cast doubt on the credibility of some state witnesses
and showed that some had expressed doubts about their
identification of Landano.
</P>
<P>
   Then the name of Forni, the gang leader, reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after Landano had already been indicted for the second
time, documents were made available to the defense from a drug
trafficking investigation in Florida. They included a statement
from an undercover sheriff's detective who said Forni had bragged
to him in 1988 that he had ``killed the cop in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors have said they do not believe he was the gunman,
and Forni, who served eight months in prison for his role in the
robbery, is listed as a potential state witness in the new trial,
as are two of his former gang cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the witnesses from the first trial will be heard by
the jury only through their 22-year-old words, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Some are dead, including three people who had testified that
Landano was with them at the time of the robbery and murder in
Kearny. So is the owner of the Hi-Way Check Cashing Service, who
was present during the robbery. One witness, who recounted the
motorcycle gang's past robberies, was found hanged in his prison
cell in what the authorities said appeared to be a homicide.
Physical evidence is missing, as are some tape recordings that
could have been of use to the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Casteleiro, Landano's trial lawyer, said he could not talk
about specific trial strategy. But he said the passage of time
presented challenges to both sides, as even the memories of living
witnesses are hazier than before and the trail of the crime has
grown colder.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have looked to forensic tools that were unavailable
at the first trial, including DNA testing and high-tech computer
enhancements of photographs, but have not made any major
breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Landano said he pinned much of his hope for acquittal on the
possibility that the jurors would hear what he has gone through for
the last 22 years. Tolentino has said either side may bring up in
open court that Landano has been convicted and that the conviction
had been overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time did not stand still after 1976,'' she said last month in
pretrial arguments in court.
</P>
<P>
   Landano said he wants little more than to make that clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about the truth _ to put to rest who didn't kill
Officer John Snow,'' he said last week. Then he added, ``Hopefully
who I am and what has been done to me will all become facts
presented to the jury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
