<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LIABILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ANOTHER DAMAGING DAMAGES BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate leadership and the White House are rushing to win
approval of a new, slimmer product liability bill that omits some
offensive provisions from prior versions, but still retains their
main defect. Like its flawed predecessors, the new proposal would
cut back on the rights of consumers and weaken the ability of
juries in civil suits to punish the makers and sellers of unsafe
products.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of dollars in campaign donations are pouring into
Congress, making this a fight between small-business lobbyists and
trial lawyers. But Congress' appetite for special-interest dollars
should not obscure the merits, or tempt senators to acquiesce to an
unwarranted rollback of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of ``reform,'' the bill intrudes into the
traditional legal domain of states by imposing national limits on
punitive damages over and above the compensation for actual harm
suffered. For small businesses with fewer than 25 full-time
employees and annual revenues of $5 million or less, the limit on
what an injured person could collect would be twice the actual lost
wages and medical expenses a person suffers, up to a maximum of
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound reasonable. But the bill's supporters exaggerate
the problem of unduly high jury awards while ignoring the value of
punitive damages in deterring dangerous practices. By lowering
small firms' legal exposure, the bill's practical impact would be
to increase the incentive for small companies, including those that
produce cheap ``junk guns'' lacking appropriate safety features, to
gamble on the continued manufacture of dangerous but profitable
products. At a time the nation should be moving to hold gun makers
accountable when they fail to protect against the foreseeable use
of their weapons by children or criminals, the measure moves in
exactly the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   No less troubling, the bill contains new standards for awarding
punitive damages that would also make it harder to hold larger
companies accountable for egregious misconduct. The supposed
ration-ale is to create a single nationwide standard. Instead it
would create a new kind of double standard in consumer rights.
There would be a cap on punitive damages for smaller businesses in
states that currently allow unlimited punitive damages. But states
that do not already impose such damages would not be required to
conform to the new national policy.
</P>
<P>
   Another flagrant double standard would deny construction workers
injured by defective machinery more than 18 years old any recourse
beyond their workers' compensation payments, while permitting
businesses to sue the manufacturer of the machinery to recover any
business losses resulting from the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, President Clinton vetoed a product liability bill
passed by Congress, declaring that it ``tilted the field against
consumers.'' So does this one, but Clinton has now sidled over to
the other side by striking a deal with the principal sponsors to
limit the punitive-damage cap to small businesses. With the White
House no longer willing to stand up for consumers across the board,
it is all the more critical that senators concerned about safe
products and a fair legal system take over the battle that Clinton
abandoned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
