<SLUG> BC-NY-FERRY-SERVICE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SPEED FERRY SERVICE BETWEEN STATEN ISLAND AND MIDTOWN
MANHATTAN TO END
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.J., Conn., N.Y.) (fb) 
By TERRY PRISTIN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A high-speed ferry service from Staten Island to
midtown Manhattan will be canceled after the last scheduled trip on
July 31 because it has not drawn enough passengers to break even,
the operator, New York Waterway, announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The company had hoped to attract at least 400 commuters a day
when it took over the service in January from New York Fast Ferry,
which had been unsuccessful with the operation. After New York
Waterway took it over, only 200 commuters regularly took the
round-trip ride between St. George Ferry Terminal and West 38th
Street, said Pat Smith, a spokesman for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The fares, which include bus service from the dock to midtown
locations, are $5 each way, $9 round trip and $150 for a one-month
pass. The ferry operates Monday through Friday, and the trip takes
25 minutes each way. The ferry leaves four times from Staten Island
in the morning and four times from Manhattan in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said this was the first time a route had been terminated
in the 11-year existence of New York Waterway, which operates eight
commuter routes in the New York metropolitan region and is the
largest privately operated commuter ferry service in the country.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, he said, the service has suffered from bad
publicity stemming from a lawsuit filed by Fast Ferry accusing the
city of reneging on several agreements, including a pledge to build
a covered dock on East 34th Street.
</P>
<P>
   But Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough president, said that
commuters who had become accustomed to Fast Ferry's large and
well-appointed boats were disappointed by what New York Waterway
offered. ``They weren't able to satisfy the prior demand,''
Molinari said. ``They didn't have boats that were large enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, said that New York Waterway's boat had a
capacity of 150 people. ``There never was a problem of
undercapacity,'' he said. ``The problem was not enough people came
to use the service.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case when Fast Ferry began its service from
Staten Island to East 34th Street in January 1997, offering an
alternative to the Staten Island Ferry, which goes only to
Whitehall Street. By late spring of that year, 1,650 passengers
were using the service each day.
</P>
<P>
   But ridership dropped sharply after the public transit system
started its ``one-city, one-fare'' system in July, eliminating the
50-cent toll on the Staten Island Ferry and enabling commuters to
travel from Staten Island to their destinations in Manhattan on one
$1.50 fare.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the new system significantly lowered the cost of
commuting from Staten Island, Molinari said that price was not a
decisive factor in dooming the ferry service. ``There are enough
people living on Staten Island who can afford to _ and would prefer
to _ pay the premium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking issue with Molinari, Deputy Mayor Randy Levine said
demand for the service was lacking. ``After six months,'' he said,
``it became clear that New York Waterway would have needed a city
subsidy to make this work. When we grant these licenses, the idea
is that we are not creating subsidized transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   While Staten Island commuters will have to make do with slower
service, others in Connecticut may get high-speed service next
year. Sea Conn LLC has said it plans to begin high-speed commuter
ferry service in the fall of 1999 to link New Haven, Bridgeport,
Stamford and La Guardia Airport to East 34th Street, Wall Street
and Battery Park City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
