</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ILLUSION OF DEMOCRACY IN NIGERIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   The high-level American delegation that landed in Nigeria on
Monday is the latest in a stream of international visitors that has
so far included British and Commonwealth officials and the United
Nations secretary general, Kofi Annan. All have carried essentially
the same message _ that Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, Nigeria's new
military ruler, should carry out a genuine transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   There must be a transition, but Abubakar is not the one to
manage it. The job belongs to Moshood Abiola, a civilian who by
most accounts won Nigeria's last elections, in 1993. When he
pressed his claim to the presidency he was jailed for treason. The
visitors have urged Abiola's release. But they have inexplicably
encouraged him to return to civilian life, which he has apparently
agreed to do, and let the military run things for the several
months, if not longer, it will take to organize fair elections.
Given the sordid history of past military rule in Nigeria, this is
a dangerous accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar has taken some reassuring measures since assuming the
presidency after the death of Gen. Sani Abacha last month. He has
released some 30 prominent political prisoners, including former
President Olusegun Obasanjo. He has also replaced some of Abacha's
crueler cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of political prisoners remain in jail, many who
have never even been charged. Previous military rulers also
released prisoners and replaced ministers when they took power. It
did not mean they were democrats. One was Abubakar's political
mentor, Ibrahim Babangida. In the 1980s he carried out some
important reforms. He held an election in 1993 featuring two
parties he created. But when the apparent winner, Abiola, was not
to his liking, he annulled the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola is expected to be released soon, but his freedom seems to
depend on his renunciation of the presidency. The military has no
business putting conditions on his release, nor should Washington
be seen as endorsing such a deal. It is naive to believe in
Abubakar's commitment to democracy at this point. The military has
earned the distrust of the Nigerian people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
