</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING JURY ADJOURNS AFTER FULL DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The jury in Don King's federal wire-fraud trial
adjourned Monday after its first full day of deliberations over
whether the promoter and his company defrauded a Lloyd's of London
insurance syndicate out of $350,000 by submitting a fake contract
for a canceled 1991 Julio Cesar Chavez bout.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors asked to see several exhibits _ including a $2
million contract sent to Lloyd's, which Chavez never signed _ and
for readings of testimony by Richard Hummers, a former accountant
for Don King Productions, and by King, when he testified on the
same charges in a 1995 trial, which ended in a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   The King testimony focused on what, if anything, he knew about
the $2 million contract and a rider, never seen by Chavez, that
called for him to be paid $350,000 in ``maintenance non-refundable
training expenses.'' Chavez signed a $1.5 million contract but
balked at fighting for that sum.
</P>
<P>
   King claimed no knowledge of the contract, but his lawyers in
the current trial say it nonetheless reflected an oral agreement to
pay Chavez $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The jury heard a readback of testimony by King in which he said,
``There is never no problem when you're giving a fighter more
money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
