A2862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TEACHERS-UNIONS-     07-06 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TEACHERS-UNIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RESHAPING THE TEACHERS' UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   Public education is under heavier attack today than at almost
any time in its history. Fearful of the voucher movements and
increasingly bad press, the two largest teachers' unions _ the
American Federation of Teachers and the National Education
Association _ are seeking to merge, thereby increasing their powers
to fight back. The merger efforts were dealt a setback Sunday, when
delegates to the NEA convention voted overwhelmingly against
merging with the teachers' federation. The merger, which may yet be
approved in some revised form, has been cast mainly in political
terms. But if the unions are to raise themselves in public esteem,
they need to lead the reform effort, not just follow it.
</P>
<P>
   With 3.3 million members between them, the AFT and the NEA would
together compose the nation's largest labor union. The two already
have great political clout and can often move legislation through
both Congress and many state houses. Sandra Feldman, president of
the AFT, and Bob Chase, president of the NEA, endorse reform,
seeking higher standards for teachers. But the plans have often
been stalled by local union leaders who fear defections if they
push to improve teacher performance too quickly. The gap between
national and local leadership seems particularly pronounced in the
NEA, whose membership prizes autonomy above all else.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between the unions has encouraged a retreat to
the lowest common denominator. Union officials argue that a merger
would make it possible for state and local union officials to
support reforms without fear of defection. But stimulating reform
will require more than a merger. For starters it will mean
developing strong and visible leadership on educational reforms _
and convincing the local organizations that they need to embrace
those reforms. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
