r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-SHORTAGE-LADN     07-06 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-SHORTAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM DEALERS JUGGLE SUPPLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As the strike against General Motors drags on,
dealers are either facing a shortage of popular models or banking
on their existing inventory to weather the production shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any Suburbans or Yukons and the next product
that will probably be hit is the pickup trucks,'' said George Pero,
sales manager at Parkway Super Center in Valencia, outside Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The facility is one of GM's new superstores in the area, selling
Cadillac, Oldsmobile, Pontiac, Buick and GMC Trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some orders taken in April or May, and they are not
being filled,'' Pero said.
</P>
<P>
   Most buyers have elected to wait out the strike because they
have already locked in the purchase price. If they choose to go
elsewhere for the vehicle they will probably end up paying sticker
price now that there is a shortage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dealership still has plenty of passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, negotiations continued Monday in Flint, Mich., as the
strike entered its second month.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding matters is the fact the big automaker, which has
about a 13 percent share of the Valley area market, is in the midst
of a planned vacation shutdown so it could take up to five weeks to
get the dealer supply train running again once the strike is
settled and plants reopen.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, some dealers are hoping their inventory
will tide them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into the strike with a huge inventory so we have
plenty of vehicles in stock,'' said Brad Jadwin, new car sales
manager at a Los Angeles Chevrolet dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Management at the dealership decided to bump up their inventory
a year ago, a move that seems to be paying off now. As of Friday,
there were about 282 new cars and trucks on the lot, roughly a
45-day supply, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has turned Steve Livingston, owner of Livingston
Motor Car Co. in Los Angeles, into a new car buyer.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago he bought 35 new vehicles from Los
Angeles-area GM dealers who had extra inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have inventory for about 120 days, so I'm in good shape,''
Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
