<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2869 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADET-TRIAL-TEX     07-06 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS GATHER FOR FORMER CADET DAVID GRAHAM'S CAPITAL MURDER
TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Wearing bluejeans and boots, summer
dresses and business suits, nearly 200 Hill Country residents
jammed a Comal County courtroom Monday on the first day of jury
selection for former Air Force Cadet David Graham's capital murder
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to question jurors individually until next week,
prosecutors and defense attorneys scanned the crowded court,
searching for any signs of prejudice _ like crossed arms, scowls or
bowed heads _ among the potential jurors.
</P>
<P>
   To select a panel of 12 impartial jurors for the high-profile
trial, District Judge Don Leonard will spend all week asking the
panelists about their knowledge of the charge against Graham, who
is accused of carrying out a December 1995 plot with his former
fiancee, Diane Zamora, to kill 16-year-old Adrianne Jones of
Mansfield, Texas. Graham, also of Mansfield, was a cadet at the Air
Force Academy and Zamora was a midshipman at the Naval Academy at
the time of their arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action was limited to taking a roll call of about 200
residents summoned to appear and instructing them to return in
groups of 30 this week. Prosecutors and defense attorneys will be
allowed to question the panelists Monday and Tuesday, and opening
arguments will begin July 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not required that you've never heard about this case,''
Leonard told the group of prospective jurors packed in the
courtroom. ``It is critically important that you can set aside what
you've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 181 potential jurors summoned Monday, 20 were excused for
hardships such as medical conditions and pre-arranged vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a black suit, striped tie and wire-rim glasses, Graham
stood up, shrugged and crossed his hands when he was introduced to
the prospective jurors. A dozen reporters from the Metroplex, as
well as Houston, San Antonio and New Braunfels, observed the first
stage of the selection process while more stood in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   During breaks, Graham and his mother, Janice Graham, embraced
over a waist-high barrier that separates the trial participants
from spectators. Bailiffs allowed Janice Graham, who sat on a seat
in the back throughout the day, to bring her son a cheeseburger for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   With a written statement from Graham detailing the slaying of
Jones, a gun found in his attic and Zamora's conviction, defense
attorney Dan Cogdell said getting an acquittal will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``But difficult cases are won every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Mike Parrish, the lead prosecutor,
also said the case will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a lot more difficult for us because everybody
expects David Graham to be convicted,'' Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said he expects a capital murder conviction and an
automatic life sentence for Graham, and joked that anything less
would be a ``kiss your sister'' compromise.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
