A2870 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT     07-06 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/6/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WALLKILL, N.Y. -- July 6, 1998 -- BACHELOR-PARTIES-2,
7-6 -- Splat! Michael Jackel's face mask is hit by a paintball
pellet at Dan Furlong's bachelor party, in which strategic war was
waged, with paintballs used as ammunition. Furlong and company are
part of a small but growing legion of men who are shunning the
traditional bachelor party, a bacchanal with strippers, in favor of
more politically correct, if no less masculine, events. (Mike
Peters/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WALLKILL, N.Y. -- July 6, 1998 -- BACHELOR-PARTIES-1,
7-6 -- Michael Jackel, from left, Bob Sherry, Dan Furlong and Mike
Byrnes frolicking in fatigues at Furlong's bachelor party, in which
strategic war was waged, with paintballs used as ammunition. ``I
wish everybody would get killed so we could eat,'' says Furlong,
30, who is to be married Saturday, of his bachelor party antics.
(Mike Peters/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MIDDLETOWN, Pa. -- July 6, 1998 -- 3MILE-NUKE-SALE-2,
7-6 -- John Langernbach works in the control room of Unit 1 at the
Three Mile Island nuclear power-generating plant. The plant's
owner, GPU, is trying to sell the unit, which was not involved in
the 1979 accident Q the most serious nuclear plant accident in the
United States to date. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LONDONDERRY TOWNSHIP, Pa. -- July 6, 1998 --
3MILE-NUKE-SALE-1, 7-6 -- Central Pennsylvania residents have
learned to live with the Three Mile Island nuclear plant, whose
cooling towers loom over the area. Almost 20 years have passed
since warning sirens blared, schools closed and more than 100,000
residents fled the area, afraid of radiation poisoning from the
most serious nuclear power plant accident in the United States.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- July 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-HEALTH-INSURANCE,
7-6 -- President Clinton with Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala on Monday. Administration officials say Clinton will
punish health insurance companies that deny coverage to sick
people, in violation of a 1996 law, by excluding them from the
lucrative insurance market for federal employees. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- July 6, 1998 -- CELEBRITY-PLANT, 7-6 -- Ron
Gagliardo, curator of tropical plants at the Atlanta Botanical
Garden, with his Amorphophallus titanum, the world's largest
flower. ``When I came in yesterday it smelled like a cross between
a dead animal and a rotting pumpkin,'' he says. Only six times in
history, including once last month at the Fairchild Tropical Garden
in Miami, has the rather smelly plant flowered in cultivation in
this country. (Michael A. Schwarz/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PARIS -- July 6, 1998 -- PARIS-MENS-FASHION, 7-6 -- It
was impossible to ignore the free and gentle breeze wafting through
Paris as designers led by Yohji Yamamoto and Rei Kawakubo
crystallized the romantic theme shown earlier in Milan, Italy. From
left, Yamamoto's crushed metal and fabric suit in white; Kawakubo's
ruffled shirt and distressed suit; Teal jacket, striped shirt and
white baggy pants by Dries van Noten. (Dan Lecca/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) FLINT, Mich. -- July 6, 1998 -- GM-STRIKE-2, 7-6 --
Brenda Domby, one of the strikers at a GM plant in Flint, makes
engine cradles on a production line that she says has very little
automation because it was was not designed for high production
rates. ``They get hung up, and then you have to pull and tug
them,'' she says. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) FLINT, Mich. -- July 6, 1998 -- GM-STRIKE-1, 7-6 --
Steven White and his son Nicholas picket outside a General Motors
parts factory in Flint, where fear of injury is a frequent refrain
among workers. GM is now fighting to eliminate the practice of
allowing White and others here to go home early with full pay if
they produce a certain number of parts. GM has delayed plans to
invest $180 million in White's factory until the union agrees to
abolish the practice, known as a ``pegged rate.'' (Peter Yates/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILAN, Italy -- July 6, 1998 -- MILAN-MENS-FASHION-2, 7-6
-- Designers can attract attention in two ways. They can command it
with vast reserves of professional esteem born of creating fashion
history, like Robert De Niro's luring movie audiences with the same
role. Otherwise, like Leonardo di Caprio, they had better offer
something new. From left, a more relaxed suit from Gucci; Armani
suit; slim tailored suit in steel gray by Valentino takes a
familiar approach. (Dan Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MILAN, Italy -- July 6, 1998 -- MILAN-MENS-FASHION-1, 7-6
-- Designers can attract attention in two ways. They can command it
with vast reserves of professional esteem born of creating fashion
history, like Robert De Niro's luring movie audiences with the same
role. Otherwise, like Leonardo di Caprio, they had better offer
something new. From left, Calvin Klein's white drawstring pullover
and dark gray slouch pants with a drop crotch; part of John
Bartlett's first Byblos line; Jean Paul Gaultier's knit top and
sailor pants. (Dan Lecca/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WINDHOEK, Namibia -- July 6, 1998 -- AFRICA-BARDEN, 7-6
-- Donald Barden and Michael Jackson this past May in Windhoek
following the announcement that they were to pool their resources.
``My new business partner, Don Barden, and I are going to be
putting our money where our mouths are,'' says the Gloved One.
``We're going to be looking at global investments that will bring
economic development to people and improvement to the lives of
children.'' (Jim Grobler/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LENOX, Mass. -- July 6, 1998 -- MUSIC-TANGLEWOOD-REVIEW,
7-6 -- Frederica von Stade sings while Seiji Ozawa conducts the
Boston Symphony Orchestra in Berlioz's ``Damnation of Faust'' at
Tanglewood. Some murky harmonies too weird even for Berlioz in the
lower woodwinds and some frayed edges in the excellent Tanglewood
Festival Chorus suggested under-rehearsal. (Alan E. Solomon/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ARMONK, N.Y. -- July 6, 1998 -- NAZI-ART, 7-6 -- Martha
and Ted Nierenberg at home in Armonk. When the Nazis invaded her
native Hungary on March 19, 1944, ``the whole family went into
hiding with a friend in Budapest,'' says Mrs. Nierenberg, now 74,
who remembers what her family left behind Q especially the mansion
of her maternal grandfather, Baron Maurice Herzog, on Andrassy
Boulevard, Budapest's Champs-Elysees. ``It was like a museum, like
the Frick,'' she says. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 6, 1998 -- MUSIC-GENDER, 7-6 -- Lori
Phillips, left, as Patience and Elaine Valby as Sarah, in Paula
Kimper's ``Patience and Sarah,'' presented as part of the Lincoln
Center Festival this week. The battle for recognition is over. The
question now is, What is women's music or what might it be? (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EASTER ISLAND, Chile -- July 6, 1998 --
SCI-EASTER-ISLAND-2, 7-6 -- Dr. Jose Miguel Ramirez, an
archeologist and head of the National Park of Rapa Nui Q the local
culture's name for Easter Island, the people themselves and their
indigenous language. ``This is not the tip a sunken continent like
Atlantis, and has nothing to do with aliens from outer space,''
says Ramirez, examining some of the island's most intractable
mysteries. ``We know it was human beings who came here and erected
these statues.'' (John Noble Wilford/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EASTER ISLAND, Chile -- July 6, 1998 --
SCI-EASTER-ISLAND-1, 7-6 -- At Tongariki on the south coast of
Easter Island, a number of the enigmatic statues known as moais
stand in a row. Over 900 have been found on the island.
Archaeologists at last are making progress in recovering the
history of Rapa Nui, which is the local culture's name for the
island, the people themselves and their indigenous language. They
also are gaining a better understanding of the motivations,
practices and economic foundations of the statue builders. (John
Noble Wilford/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
