A2874 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-PERCIVAL-LADN     07-06 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PERCIVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' ECCENTRIC STOPPER SET FOR ALL-STAR GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ During a recent Anaheim Angels game, manager
Terry Collins visited closer Troy Percival on the mound in a tight,
ninth-inning situation. After Percival got the last out for one of
his major-league leading 25 saves, he was asked what Collins had
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he said, to be honest with you,'' Percival
said.
</P>
<P>
   Percival, though, wasn't showing a lack of respect for his
manager. In fact, he said Collins' visit served a purpose by
allowing Percival to take a little breather and get his thoughts
together.
</P>
<P>
   Percival, like many of baseball's closers, enters a world of his
own when he's in a game. When Percival takes the mound, the tension
is high and the concession lines are short.
</P>
<P>
   Percival (1-3, 2.97 ERA) brings to the mound a fastball that is
consistently clocked at 95 mph, and he has a nasty breaking ball.
But stuff alone does not save games. A closer needs a certain
mentality to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just in a zone. You have to be,'' said Percival, who
will make his second All-Star game tonight in Denver. ``If you're
letting outside things get in your mind, you're not going to be
successful. You don't hear the fans, you don't hear the hitters.
You're focused in.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival, however, does not wait until the ninth to enter that
``zone.'' It starts much earlier. He usually drinks about seven or
eight cups of coffee throughout a game. And late in the game, he
starts his preparation ritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the seventh inning, I start locking in,'' he said. ``I
get myself stretched, get myself ready. If it's a tight game, I
pretty much stop talking to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Percival learned to ready himself for a game, but
maybe more important is how Percival has responded to his two
losses and three blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from (former Angels closer) Lee Smith,''
Percival said. ``You're not going to be successful every time. And
when you're not, you have to deal with it. I wasn't good at that
when I first got here ... dealing with failure. But I've gotten
better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of closer it's easy to have confidence in,''
Collins said. ``Because if he has a bad night, he's the first guy
to say, `Give me the baseball tomorrow. I don't care what the score
is. Get me in the game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see that mentality very often. Closers are always
under the gun. When they leave the mound, they've either done good
or done bad, they either saved the game or blew the save.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival served as Smith's set-up man in 1995, much as Mike
James has served as Percival's set-up man. Though James is on the
disabled list with a sore elbow, he remains Percival's best friend
on the team. The two met when James was traded to the Angels'
organization in 1994. They played together at Triple-A Vancouver
that year. And though they have little in common, something
clicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're completely opposite except for what we do here,'' James
said. ``If we met outside this arena, like a bar or something, we
probably would have fought. I'm a beach guy, he's a country guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival was born in Fontana, went to Moreno Valley High and UC
Riverside. James grew up surfing in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the other day I tried to get him on a surfboard and he
said, `No way are you going to get a fat guy on a board. There
isn't a board big enough,' '' James said with a laugh. ``He's taken
me out to do some of the things he likes to do, like going out to
the sand dunes and going to the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival isn't fat. But at 6-foot-3, 230 pounds, he looks more
like a catcher than a pitcher. And in fact, he was drafted as a
catcher. But after hitting .200 in 29 games in Rookie League for
Boise in 1990, Percival was given a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Angels coaches Frank Reberger and Bob Clear liked Percival's arm
and asked him if he would switch to pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having no success catching,'' Percival said. ``I was
sitting on the bench catching. If you're sitting on the bench in
A-ball catching, you probably want to try something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival, though, didn't jump at the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I didn't want to be a minor-league project,'' he
said. ``I asked them if they could get somebody in here that knew
what they were talking about and I'll throw for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels pitching coach Marcel Lachemann watched Percival and told
him what he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If it was me, I'd turn in my (catcher's) gear,' ''
Percival said. ``So I walked in and turned in my gear 10 minutes
later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
