</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TERROR-TRIAL-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OPENS IN N.Y. BOMB PLOT
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By DAVID ROHDE  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The defense lawyer for one of two men accused of
planning to set off a bomb in New York's subway system last summer
conceded in court Monday that her client did possess a powerful
explosive, but argued that the device was intended to defraud the
government of reward money from an anti-terrorism program and not
to inflict casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer, Jan Rostal, who is representing 24-year-old
Gazi Ibrahim Abu Mezer, said in her opening statement in Federal
District Court in Brooklyn that Abu Mezer and the government's key
witness, Abdel Rahman Mosabbah, conspired to defraud the State
Department of up to $4 million in reward money.
</P>
<P>
   But Mosabbah betrayed Abu Mezer, she argued, by falsely
portraying him to the authorities as a terrorist in order to
collect the reward money himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it about mayhem and murder,'' Rostal asked jurors, ``or
about getting money through simple, new-fashioned fraud?''
</P>
<P>
   But federal prosecutors portrayed Abu Mezer and his 23-year-old
codefendant, Lafi Khalil, as terrorists who traveled from New York
to North Carolina to build the bombs and were only hours or days
away from setting them off in a subway station when Mosabbah
courageously revealed the plot to law-enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nails and bullets were wrapped around pipes to inflict maximum
damage,'' a prosecutor, Bernadette Miragliotta, said referring to
the bomb. ``It was a bomb known as an anti-personnel device.''
</P>
<P>
   Khalil and Abu Mezer were arrested in a dramatic predawn raid on
a squalid apartment in Park Slope, Brooklyn, last July in which the
police have said they found a pipe bomb ``fully rigged and ready to
be detonated.'' Khalil and Abu Mezer were shot and wounded in the
raid, the police said, because officers opened fire when they
feared that one of the men was trying to set off the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The July raid came after Mobassah, who had been living with the
defendants, flagged down police officers in the street and told
them about the plot.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who were indicted last August on federal charges of
conspiring to use a weapon of mass destruction and related crimes,
face up to life in prison if convicted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Miragliotta told the jury of four men and eight women that the
government would provide witnesses who saw Abu Mezer and Khalil
purchase the gunpowder, pipes, nails and other components used to
make the bombs from hardware stores, a local Wal-Mart and other
businesses in Greenville, N.C., in early July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She said a copy of a typewritten letter mailed to the State
Department on July 27, threatening to set off a series of pipe
bombs unless millions of dollars were paid, was attached to the
trigger device. Prosecutors have said the letter threatened a
series of attacks against American and Jewish interests and
demanded the release of jailed Islamic militants, including Ramzi
Yousef, who is serving a life sentence for masterminding the
bombing of the World Trade Center in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Mosabbah took the stand as the prosecution's
lead witness and painted a chilling portrait of Abu Mezer. He
testified that Abu Mezer told him he opposed the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process and felt violence was the only
way Palestinians could reclaim their land.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Mezer, he testified, stated that violent attacks against
Americans were acceptable because the United States backs Israel.
The Palestinian lit gunpowder at one point in their apartment,
according to Mosabbah, and said he would ``burn them like this.''
When asked who, Abu Mezer replied ``the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rostal told jurors that the bomb and the letter were only
props in an effort by the defendants to defraud the government.
</P>
<P>
   She called Mosabbah ``an opportunist'' and pointed out that the
Federal Bureau of Investigation had flown his wife to the United
States and provided him with more than $70,000 in financial support
over the last 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   She also argued that Abu Mezer's statements to investigators
that he planned to set off the bombs were coerced by federal agents
while he was recovering from his wounds in Kings County Hospital.
Rostal told jurors that Abu Mezer was trying to impress people in
his hometown of Hebron on the occupied West Bank in Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
