<HEADLINE>
PALM FOUNDERS TO FORM NEW COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The two founders of Palm Computing, an
innovative Silicon Valley company that helped pioneer the market
for hand-held pen-based computers, have left the company.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Dubinsky, president of the Palm division of 3Com Corp.,
the networking giant, and Jeff Hawkins, the division's chief
technologist, said Monday that they were leaving to found a company
that will license the Palm operating-system software. The two
executives said they had not yet chosen a company name or a new
location.
</P>
<P>
   Founded six years ago amid a wave of pen-based computing
start-up ventures, Palm survived initially because it had two
crucial features that other pen-based computers lacked: It fit
comfortably in a man's dress-shirt pocket and it synchronized data
easily with desktop personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Strategies Inc., a market research firm, has estimated
that Palm has sold 1.6 million Palm Pilots, and Dataquest has
reported that the company has a 63 percent market share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
