<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECORD PACE FOR VIAGRA SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viagra, the Pfizer Inc. pill for correcting male impotence,
smashed all records in its first three months, according to IMS
Health, an industry consultant, which released numbers Monday.
</P>
<P>
   IMS also predicted that sales of Viagra would reach $1 billion
in the United States by March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Prescriptions for Viagra from April through June totaled 2.9
million, enough for estimated sales of $259.5 million, according to
IMS.
</P>
<P>
   Such huge sales appear easily to be a record. For example, one
of the leading drugs introduced last year _ Lipitor, a
cholesterol-reducing medicine from Warner-Lambert _ had sales of
$12.4 million in its first two months.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were encouraged that prescription renewals remained
strong, despite reports of the deaths of some Viagra users. A
Pfizer spokeswoman stressed that the drug was safe when used
correctly. On Monday, the company criticized the Prudential
Healthcare unit of Prudential Insurance and Humana Inc. for
declining to cover the cost of Viagra because they said they
regarded it as unsafe.
</P>
</TEXT>
