A2882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-370-     07-06 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-370-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT IN BRAWLEY CASE SEES DEFAMATION SUIT AS `LYNCHING'
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ In his summation Monday, Alton Maddox told
jurors that the Tawana Brawley defamation suit was an effort at
``three judicial lynchings'' of the Brawley advisers, ``financed by
rich fat cats in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, who has acted as his own lawyer during the case,
portrayed himself as a martyr to the Brawley cause, referring often
to his suspension from the bar because of an inquiry into his role
as Brawley's lawyer a decade ago. He portrayed the plaintiff,
Steven Pagones, as an agent of powerful New York City people _ whom
he did not identify _ who he said have contributed to Pagones'
defense. Those people, Maddox said, seek to use the Dutchess County
jurors to ruin him and the other two advisers, C. Vernon Mason and
the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the advisers' adversaries, Maddox said, was to
prevent the advisers from helping people like Miss Brawley, a black
15-year-old in 1987 who said that she had been raped by a group of
white men. ``We are here because we have stood up for the
oppressed,'' Maddox said, ``we have stood up for the poor, and now
it's time to be persecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   In a vividly personal closing statement, Maddox alternated
between eloquent appeals and folksy anecdotes, describing his own
childhood in the poverty of rural Georgia and confessing, with a
wry smile, ``I have an addiction'' to the television show ``Murder,
She Wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even in the touches of humor, he refused to step away from
the inflammatory accusations he made about Pagones a decade ago.
After confessing to having an addiction to the murder mystery
series, he told the jurors he wished that the television detective,
Jessica Fletcher, could be here to help solve the case. Pagones, he
said, ``wants to get away with murder and be rewarded,'' with a
defamation verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the allegations he made a decade ago, Maddox said
Pagones was a legitimate suspect in the kidnapping and rape of
Brawley and in the shooting death of a friend, Harry Crist.
</P>
<P>
   He said the grand jury report that exonerated Pagones and found
that Crist had committed suicide was ``a fraud which really should
be thrown in the trash can.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Maddox told the Brawley story from the advisers' vantage
point, he often seemed to be trying to connect with the jurors. He
appeared near tears as he told the jurors he believed that someday
there would be proof that Miss Brawley was attacked and that there
had been a huge cover-up on behalf of Pagones. ``No lie can live
forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Maddox, 53, it was a vintage performance. In the 1980s, he
was an omnipresent advocate in the racial turmoil of New York City.
But until the defamation trial began nearly eight months ago, he
had virtually vanished from the public stage. He often referred to
the fact that he can no longer practice law because of his
suspension as a result of the case.
</P>
<P>
   As he confidently walked the courtroom Monday, with his heels
clicking authoritatively on the wooden floor, he seemed happy to be
arguing a case again. At times, he referred to himself as
``Maddox,'' as he has often done through the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But often, too, he seemed to forget, and spoke more directly to
the jurors. ``I don't know what the outcome of this case will be,''
he said, his voice breaking. ``I know one thing: that I can hold my
head high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
