u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-CHARTER-REVISION-     07-06 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-CHARTER-REVISION-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTER PANEL TOLD TO SHIFT FOCUS OF WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an abrupt change of course, the chairman of New
York City's newly created Charter Revision Commission urged the
group on Monday to stop exploring contentious changes in the
balance of power in city government and to focus instead on a much
less controversial issue: campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Peter Powers, has been sharply criticized in
recent weeks for considering changes that could increase Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's authority at the expense of other branches of
the city government, particularly the Office of Public Advocate.
</P>
<P>
   But Powers insisted the about-face was not a response to the
criticism. Instead, he said that he had realized the commission did
not have enough time to consider so many changes this year, and
that certain issues needed consideration more urgently than others.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to campaign financing, Powers said he would ask the
11 other members of the commission to focus on the questions of
whether to eliminate partisan elections for city offices and
whether to make membership on the City Council a full-time job. All
three issues have been among the commission's top priorities all
along, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want is to stay focused on the issues we can do at this
time,'' Powers, a former deputy mayor and longtime friend of
Giuliani, said Monday afternoon. ``We have to take some and leave
others out. I think the time is right to make a statement about
ending soft money in city elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes to the City Charter must be approved in public
referendums, and the commission is hoping to place charter
questions on the ballot this November, apparently to meet
Giuliani's timetable.
</P>
<P>
   He created the commission two months ago, primarily as a means
to block another referendum _ on whether tax money should be spent
on building a stadium for the New York Yankees in Manhattan _ from
appearing on the ballot. Under city law, a charter-related question
takes precedence over other ballot questions.
</P>
<P>
   Although critics have accused the commission of doing the
mayor's bidding, a spokeswoman for Giuliani said he had nothing to
do with Powers' decision to delay consideration of the most
politically charged issues. The spokeswoman, Colleen Roche, said
that Giuliani, who appointed the commission members, wanted them to
decide by themselves which issues were most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has said from the beginning that it will be the
commission's responsibility to decide what should and should not be
included in the referendum,'' Ms. Roche said. ``They are assessing
what is ripe for this election and what is not.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Critics of the commission have been especially angry about
potential changes that could expand Giuliani's powers. In
particular, they have said they would resist changes to the budget
process and to the city's land procurement rules, both of which
could scale back the powers of the City Council and the community
boards.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said Monday that the commission might very well consider
such changes in the future, but definitely not before November.
</P>
<P>
   The critics, who have been especially angry about proposals to
eliminate the Office of Public Advocate and the Independent Budget
Office, were cheered by Powers' announcement, which came in the
form of a brief memorandum to the other commission members.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they were still troubled by the makeup of the
commission, whose members all have ties to Giuliani. ``It's a
welcome recognition of the error of their ways,'' said Frederick
Schwarz Jr., the chairman of a previous charter commission, who
took the unusual step of disparaging the new commission's plans in
a letter to Powers last week. ``But it's still not a representative
commission and it's still not independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said they still had plenty to worry about, especially
Powers' recommendation that the commission focus on whether to make
city elections nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking away partisan elections is a very serious change,
because you are depriving people of one of the chief ways of making
determinations on candidates,'' said Eric Lane, a professor at
Hofstra Law School who was the executive director of a 1989
commission on charter revision. ``If the commission members are
nonpartisan themselves, they will take a lot of time looking at
this issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
