u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-06 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S ULLRICH OUT TO DEFEND TOUR DE FRANCE CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Let's have no more jokes, please, about Jan Ullrich,
about how he will do his military service in his native Germany as
a blimp, and how, when his Telekom team shows up for a bicycle
race, he counts as two of the nine entries.
</P>
<P>
   True, Ullrich gained at least 20 pounds during the winter as he
chomped his way through banquets celebrating the first victory by a
German in the Tour de France. And true, when he showed up for the
first races of the year, in February, people worried that instead
of a bicycle with a titanium frame he should be riding something
made of a metal less likely to buckle.
</P>
<P>
   Always stocky, he weighed in after the winter revels at 183
pounds on his 6-foot frame, which explained his dismal results in
his first three months of racing.
</P>
<P>
   That is over now. The excess pounds have been sweated off. The
two cases of bronchitis and the earache that set back his training
are long behind him. His miserable April and his 78th-, 97th- and
134th-place finishes are memories.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Ullrich, who finished second and then first in
his initial two Tours de France, is back in form and hungry for
another victory in the world's greatest bicycle race. ``I'm at 90
percent now,'' he said a few weeks ago, ``and certain that I'll be
ready for the start of the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   There is scant reason to doubt him. In the Tour of Switzerland
last month, he showed that his time trial skills had returned, and
he stayed with all but the top climbers in the mountains. Then, in
the minor Route du Sud, he repeated his strong showing on ascents.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the two keys to his victory in the last Tour de
France: gaining minutes in the time trials and losing none to his
main rivals in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The formula should work just as well when the 85th Tour de
France starts its three-week journey on Saturday in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Dublin? Why not? The Tour de France has started outside the
mother country before _ in the Netherlands as recently as 1996, in
Spain in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   What's really new is that the start, usually at the beginning of
July, was pushed back a week because of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The later start means that the field in the roughly 2,392-mile
race, comprising 21 teams of nine riders each, will not finish in
Paris until Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Tour reaches France, in Brittany on July 14 after three
days in Ireland, it will follow a counterclockwise route, passing
through the Pyrenees first and then the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   At least on paper, the mountains are not as fearsome as they
have been. There will be two daily stages in the Pyrenees, followed
by a day off on July 23, and three in the Alps, but the first-rank
climbers have complained bitterly that this is not a course that
favors them.
</P>
<P>
   Not demanding enough, say both Richard Virenque, the Frenchman
with the Festina team who has won the top climber's jersey the last
four years and finished second over all last year, and Marco
Pantani, the Italian with Mercatone Uno who finished third last
year, won the Tour of Italy in June and is considered the dominant
climber in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Neither cyclist is an outstanding time trialer, as Ullrich is.
Because this Tour will have the customary two long races against
the clock _ 36 miles on July 18 and 32 miles on Aug. 1 _ Virenque
seems unlikely to repeat as one of the top three finishers. Pantani
is another case; he may be cool-headed enough to understand that
the riders, not the mountains, make the race.
</P>
<P>
   Other obvious contenders are riders in Ullrich's mold, if not
quite his class. They include Bjarne Riis of Denmark, Ullrich's
teammate and the winner of the 1996 Tour, but now a creaky 34 years
old. Abraham Olano, a Spaniard with Banesto, can climb and time
trial with the best, although not necessarily do both in the same
race. Laurent Jalabert, a Frenchman with ONCE, has been unable to
get over the highest mountains in his last two Tours and so has
changed his training methods, possibly for the better. Michael
Boogerd, a Dutchman with Rabobank, gets stronger all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Two more riders who should do well are Alex Zulle and Laurent
Dufaux, both Swiss and both with Festina, which is led by Virenque.
</P>
<P>
   If they can all work together, they can take turns making
trouble for Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   Days before the prologue in Dublin, however, the defending
champion's main threat still appears to be his appetite. If he can
restrict himself to the 6,000 to 7,000 calories a day that most
bicycle racers consume, he figures to be in the yellow jersey by
the finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
