<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED-LAWYER-NYT     07-06 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAWYER BORN ARMLESS IS UNIMPEDED BY DISABILITIES _ HIS OR
OTHERS'
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JOYCE WADLER  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fellow who had lost a leg in the subway and decided
to sue New York City Transit had the bad fortune to be confronted
in court by Jeffrey Samel, the lawyer for the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Samel has no arms. Also, Samel is very good. Samel, taking notes
with a pen in his mouth, established, under cross-examination, that
the plaintiff had been drunk when he landed on the subway tracks
and that the plaintiff had lied, under oath, about his drinking.
Samel contended that the plaintiff had been seen falling _ some
witnesses said jumping _ in front of the train when it was 20 feet
away, that it was too late for the motorman to stop and that the
motorman also could not turn. A subway train, as Samel enjoyed
reminding the jury, has no steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   So compelling was Samel's argument that the judge dismissed the
case. Damages, therefore, were never an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one wonders, isn't Samel's disability an issue?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't a lawyer with no arms the worst possible opponent a
physical-injuries lawyer could face in court?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard other lawyers, who haven't met me, are afraid of
me,'' Samel says, speaking with a lawyer's careful wording in his
offices in downtown Manhattan. ``That's what I've been told.
They're afraid my disability will negatively impact their case,
that the jury will never be able to award millions of dollars when
they see a person like me who is able to do everything. They start
out worrying about my disability. Then they see it's my abilities
as a lawyer they have to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of fellow 45-year-old Jeffrey Samel is: He
shakes hands, though his feels like cool plastic, because he likes
to do what everybody else does.
</P>
<P>
   This is Samel's most frequent case: A person, having had a few
drinks, leans over the tracks in a subway station to see if the
train is coming, falls on the tracks, and then sues the city. Samel
is often hired by New York City Transit.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, as in the case of an Emergency Medical Service
crew that failed to respond in time to save the life of an
asthmatic child who ultimately died, Samel represents the
plaintiff. (The case, he said, incensed him.) Most often, however,
Samel's clients are the defendants. This comes about, Samel says,
because he finds that many people who come to a lawyer regarding
physical injury are lying about the circumstances of their
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Samel does not believe his disability has won him clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the opposite,'' Samel says. ``I think there are
clients who have not come knocking on my door because they were
afraid the jury might think they were pulling a fast one, because
they were afraid how the jury would react.''
</P>
<P>
   Samel grew up in Queens. His disability was not caused by
thalidomide or drugs. It was an ``anomaly,'' a bad genetic toss of
the dice, yet Samel's parents, who owned a housewares store in
Manhattan, never treated him differently from their other two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught to believe that my disability never entitled me
to anything,'' Samel says. ``I wasn't special because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Samel graduated from New York University Law School in the top
10 percent of his class. By graduation, 70 percent of his class had
jobs. Samel, who got every interview he requested, did not.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a professor to intercede, the dean said there was
nothing to be done, Samel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been somewhat angry about that,'' Samel says. ``I
hate the word `anger'. But disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Queens district attorney, John J. Santucci, was the
first to hire Samel. Fifteen years ago, Samel struck out on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible Samel chose the side of the defendant because he
had to go through life with a severe infirmity and has no patience
with people who might complain?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Samel says firmly. ``I cannot abide falsehood. I don't
have a lot of patience with people who try to exploit an injury,
but I'm as sympathetic to someone who is legitimately hurt as
anyone else. I would never say to a person who lost a leg, `Hey, I
don't have arms, come on, get over it,' that would be a foolish
thing to say. But a person who has lost a leg can still be
gainfully employed, can fall in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Samel has. Three years ago, he married the former Dorothy
Thurneau, one of the lawyers in his firm. They live in Manhattan
and enjoy New York things _ galleries, the theater. Samel has a
silver paperweight that spells the word ``love,'' in Hebrew, on his
desk. It is a gift from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about anger, about being forced to live without arms,
Samel denies he ever felt rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born this way, so I never had to adapt the way I did
things,'' Samel says. ``When I was 3 years old, I put crayons in my
mouth to draw. I did all the things other people could do, I just
did them differently. The same way you might say I do things in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one thing I couldn't do, in high school,'' he says.
``Everybody was taking driver's ed. and I couldn't. My father said,
`We'll go looking to fix up a car.' But I realized I would either
kill myself or somebody else, and since everybody around me could
drive me anywhere I wanted, it didn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   More reflection.
</P>
<P>
   `` The only thing in life I regret, I can't play a musical
instrument. But I sing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
