<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMEX-STATE-EMPLOYEE-C     07-06 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMEX-STATE-EMPLOYEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State credit bills feature names such as Nordstrom and Macy's
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Last spring, Zelda Carmon did some power
shopping, dropping $675 on merchandise from Victoria's Secret, a
popular lingerie and mail-order company.
</P>
<P>
   Carmon didn't have to pay cash for her apparel. Instead, she
used the American Express card she carries for official State of
Texas business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a convenience thing,'' said Carmon, a clinical
nurse at M. D. Anderson Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   Convenient and common, but clearly against state rules.
</P>
<P>
   All over Texas, state employees routinely use their state
American Express cards for personal purchases even though rules
restrict the card to business expenses such as airline tickets and
hotels, newly released state records show. The state reimburses for
business expenses but not for personal purchases, and it isn't
liable for unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman-Marcus. Macy's. Nordstrom. Lord and Taylor.
Bloomingdale's. Gap Kids. Toys ``R'' Us. JCPenney. Dillard's. Ross
Dress for Less. Blockbuster Video. Land's End. These and other
shops show up on state employees' American Express bills, according
to bills obtained under the Texas open records law.
</P>
<P>
   Charges for tanning salons, glamour photographs, liquor,
groceries and video stores also show up on the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Workers who use the cards to buy things for themselves could be
prosecuted, but there appears to be little chance of criminal
charges. No one monitors credit card purchases at some state
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't monitor personal spending,'' said Richard Moore, vice
president for business affairs at the University of Texas Medical
Branch at Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   American Express sends the medical school a monthly report of
employee charges, but that probably ends up in the trash, Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   The UT medical school is not alone. Officials of UT's M. D.
Anderson Cancer Center and Texas Tech Health Sciences Center, whose
American Express billings were also obtained through open records
requests, acknowledge doing little to monitor personal purchases on
state charge cards.
</P>
<P>
   But the offices are beginning to crack down. They are randomly
monitoring purchases and sending warning letters to workers.
</P>
<P>
   Carmon said she did not know she could not use the charge card
for personal items. She ran up a $2,657 American Express bill in
March with nonstate purchases at a variety of stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't clear. It was a misunderstanding on my part,'' she
said. ``Now, I know we can't do that. I have corrected the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas General Services Commission recently reported that
state employees have run up nearly $2 million in overdue charge
card bills since 1991. Personal spending _ which historically
spikes in December _ has contributed to the debt, the commission
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million in debt is less than 2 percent of all charges by
state employees last year. In May, the state imposed a $200 limit
on retail spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas General Services Commission, which oversees the state
contract with American Express, relies on each state agency and
institution to monitor employee spending on the cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot be the conscience of these people carrying the
cards,'' said Tom Treadway, executive director of the General
Services Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Treadway has named a task force of key state agencies to improve
enforcement of the ban on personal American Express charges.
</P>
<P>
   At Treadway's agency, employees can be fired if they use the
American Express card for personal spending.
</P>
<P>
   State offices where enforcement has been lax view the American
Express card as an agreement between an individual state employee
and the charge card company. Under the state contract, state
employees undergo a credit check by American Express and are
responsible for paying for all charges they ring up. The state is
not liable for unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who am I to judge whether it was a personal expense or a
business expense?'' said Elmo Cavin, vice president for fiscal
affairs at Texas Tech Health Sciences Center.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say employees sometimes mistakenly charge
personal items on their state card.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nancy Ketchie, chief of human resources at M.D.
Anderson, said she accidentally used the state American Express
card in February to buy a $340 dog kennel for a puppy her nieces
and nephews had just received. The store had trouble processing her
personal MasterCard, and the young children were so excited that
the atmosphere became ``total pet store chaos,'' Ketchie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honest screw-up,'' she said. ``I pulled the wrong
card. I just looked for a green card.''
</P>
<P>
   An open records request for American Express charges at Texas
A&AMP;M University was denied. Texas A&AMP;M requested a ruling from the
Texas attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
