<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENBERG-COLUMN-COX     07-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENBERG-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weiss' perfect world
 &HT;    By Cheryl Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brody Weiss was sorry. He didn't mean to swallow the water in
the pool. But when you're almost 4, and it's a hot early-summer
day, well, there's nothing better than taking a big mouthful of the
cool blue water and spurting it high into the air.
</P>
<P>
   He never knew it would almost kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're blaming anybody,'' said his father,
Atlanta Braves shortstop Walt Weiss. ``It's an imperfect world.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours tonight, though, it will be as close to perfect
as Weiss could ever hope. Weiss is in his 11th major-league season.
He will play in his first All Star game, which happens to be at
Coors Field. That's where Weiss played the last four seasons with
the Colorado Rockies, and he also makes his permanent home in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from the stands, along with his wife and two other
sons, will be Brody. It's a moment Weiss hasn't had much of a
chance to anticipate, and Monday he couldn't begin to imagine what
he'll think or feel.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't want to take anything away from the honor of playing
in an All Star Game. He appreciates the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's going to be one of the most special moments of
my career and of my life,'' Weiss said. ``But life and death put a
spin on it. There's no doubt I look at the game in a different
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Just under a month ago, his wife, Terri, took Brody to a public
pool in suburban Atlanta. It was there Brody contracted the virus
caused by E. Coli bacteria when he swallowed water infected by a
sick child.
</P>
<P>
   The Weisses thought Brody just had the flu, so Weiss left on a
road trip. He was in Montreal when he got the call Brody had been
admitted to the hospital. His kidneys were only functioning at 50
percent. They would soon fail completely and he was put on
dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss returned to Atlanta and he and his wife spent quite a few
nights curled up on the seats in the hospital waiting room. There
is no treatment for the virus. It simply has to run its course.
</P>
<P>
   There was a chance Brody could die. At one point, Weiss believed
that could be a reality. Brody became unresponsive and his body
twitched, a sign of possible neurological damage.
</P>
<P>
   They had to prepare themselves for the worst. And then, for
reasons Weiss won't question, Brody started getting better. Weiss
rejoined his team June 26. Baseball wasn't much escape. Weiss would
count the minutes until he could get back to the hospital to be
with his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to be serious about it,'' said Weiss of playing.
``I tried to stay focused and I did okay. I realized I had an
obligation to the team and I tried to let my instincts take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Brody came out of intensive care - the same
day his father was named to his first All Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss would not have attended tonight's game if Brody was still
in danger. He's not taking any medication and is under no special
restrictions, though Weiss said he wouldn't be taking him to any
public pools for awhile. Brody just has to go in for blood work and
has become terrified of doctors and needles.
</P>
<P>
   He visited the family's doctor in Denver early Monday. The trip
from Atlanta was incredible. Rockies President and CEO Jerry
McMorris sent his private jet to get the Weiss family, even though
Weiss plays for the competition now. They've received tons of cards
and stuffed animals, many from Colorado fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an amazing guy,'' said Rockies left fielder Dante
Bichette. ``A lot of guys on the team are fathers. We knew what he
was feeling. It says a lot about Walt that everybody really came to
his aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss is blessed. His son will make a full recovery. Weiss
himself achieved a professional status of which he'd completely
stopped dreaming. He is a religious man. He believes everything
happened for a reason and it wasn't up to him to figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   Brody never asked why he was in the hospital. He never wondered
what was wrong with him. His parents eventually explained why he
was sick. And most of all, they made sure he knew it wasn't his
fault.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody swallows pool water, especially little boys on hot
days.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Rosenberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
