<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLSTAR-MARK-COX     07-06 1664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-MARK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire a power broker
 &HT;    By Cheryl Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He is a man of Babe Ruthian dimensions, not just in
stature but in his swing.
</P>
<P>
   He is the Sultan of Swat on a good weight-training program and a
little creatine.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, the first baseman for the St. Louis Cardinals, has
single-handedly brought renewed interest to baseball not only
because of the record he is chasing, but the way he has done it.
</P>
<P>
   He has 37 homers this season, more than halfway to the record of
61 set by Roger Maris in 1961. But unlike anyone else's, except
maybe Ruth's, McGwire's homers aren't just homers. They're
McHomers. Supersized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people understand what's going on here with this guy,''
said New York Mets All-Star Mike Piazza, among the best-hitting
catchers in history. ``I mean, he's one of the best, if not the
best, power hitter of all time. Obviously, I never saw Babe Ruth,
but it's hard to believe anybody ever hit them higher or farther.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is on pace to hit 70 home runs this season, and a few of
those he has hit have made history at the ballparks in which
they've landed.
</P>
<P>
   Maris broke the record of 60 set by Ruth in 1927. Some within
baseball wanted an asterisk next to Maris' name, because Maris had
161 games to set the mark, while Ruth had 154 .
</P>
<P>
   No one will question the legitimacy of a McGwire record. Most
weren't around when Ruth was doing his thing and have to rely on
clips to see his prowess at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to national TV contracts and endless sports highlights
show, everyone has a chance to see McGwire's prodigious homers each
evening. Everyone wants to know how far, how long, how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's a phenomenon,'' said McGwire's teammate, Ron Gant.
</P>
<P>
   The demand is so strong, thousands of people show up at batting
practice just to watch, just to say they were there when he hit one
out of the ballpark, or up on the roof, or off the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   To see McGwire go where no man _ or baseball _ has gone before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the balls he hits and the way he hits them, you don't
want to miss that,'' Baltimore Orioles third baseman Cal Ripken
said. ``You can relate, because you go to these places and people
show you where he hit them. And then you take your normal BP and
you hit a ball and you feel like you really got it, and it's still
about 200 feet short of where he hit it.'' ----
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how does he do it? There are a few major
leaguers around who can match McGwire in stature, including Toronto
Blue Jay Jose Canseco, his former teammate in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Canseco was the Bash in the Bash Brothers, the name by
which the two became known. McGwire hit 49 homers that season, his
highest total until hitting 52 in '96 and 58 last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Canseco had the brawn, the personality, the movie-star looks
_ and the tape-measure homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was over there, the guy who was hitting them so far was
Canseco,'' said Cardinals third base coach Rene Lachemann, who was
a coach with the A's. ``Mark is stronger than he was then, and he's
made certain adjustments. Now he turns major league ballparks into
Pony League fields.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had an almost pigeon-toed stance when he was with
Oakland. Now, he's opened his feet and stands more like a golfer.
This helps him swing more through the hips, as a golfer would, and
Lachemann said McGwire has a heck of a tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   He has shortened his stroke and has amazing bat speed to go with
his strength. According to Robert Adair, a Yale University
Professor of Physics who was dubbed Physicist to the National
League by then-Commissioner Bart Giamatti, most players hit the
ball with the sweet spot of the bat at a speed of 60-65 mph.
McGwire hits it between 70-75 mph.
</P>
<P>
   And he's getting stronger. McGwire did not lift weights in '91
and thought that hurt him. He has lifted ever since.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's good health is another key. A sore left heel limited
him to 27 games in '93. In '94, he first had a stress fracture in
his left foot, then had heel surgery on the foot. He played in 47
games that season.
</P>
<P>
   He considered retiring during the spring of '96 when he tore the
plantar fascia in his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his time away, he really came to understand how much he
loved the game,'' said Tony La Russa, who has managed McGwire in
Oakland and St. Louis. ``He came back with a renewed interest in
being professional, and now he keeps improving the mental side of
his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an advance scout's nightmare. He'll swing and miss a high
fastball, so you report that. The next time you throw a high
fastball, there it goes. Throw a breaking ball, swing and miss.
Next time you throw a breaking ball, there it goes. Throw him in _
people keep trying to crowd him _ there it goes. You've got to see
it to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox first baseman Mo Vaughn used to chat with McGwire
when either one of them would reach thefirstbase. They'd talk about
hitting, and most particularly, Vaughn's habit of releasing the bat
with one hand at the end of his swing.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was a straight, two-handed power hitter and figured he
didn't need to release. He already was sending balls over the
fences. Then a couple of years ago, Vaughn noticed something very,
very scary: McGwire was now fully extending his bat on the follow
through, releasing it at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Someone's in trouble,''' Vaughn said. ``The longer
you can keep the bat on the ball, you take it to another level.
That's what made his swing more devastating. That's when you hit
the light towers.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also said McGwire's trade last July 31 to the Cardinals _
and the National League _ could only help. The NL has a lower
strike zone. McGwire is a phenomenal low-ball hitter. He can lay
off the high pitches because they'll be called balls.
</P>
<P>
   He is hitting better to the gaps and is batting .310.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll kill anybody down low,'' Vaughn said. ``That's why he's
really going. Anything down low, it's damage. That's his stroke.
You cannot throw any low balls by him. You gotta bounce it by
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Eckersley remembers when, as Eckersley puts it, McGwire
was on ``Jump Street.'' A rookie. McGwire was like a big kid then.
But it doesn't surprise Eckersley, who played with McGwire for nine
years in Oakland and last season in St. Louis, that McGwire comes
off as reserved and almost surly at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hell of a lot more guarded now,'' said Eckersley, now a
reliever for the Red Sox. ``He sounds like a script. When he was a
kid, you'd hear the same story 20 times, he talked so much. That's
who he was. He's still like that deep inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley has an excellent perspective on McGwire, the Man, as
well as McGwire, the Mammoth Home Run Hitter.
</P>
<P>
   This is Eckersley's 24th season in the majors. He's pitched
against some of the best hitters of all time, including home-run
king Hank Aaron, who holds the career record with 755, and Reggie
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody like him,'' Eckersley said of McGwire. ``He's
the most awesome home-run hitter I've seen in my lifetime. I can't
imagine anyone being more powerful. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The two didn't play together for a year-and-a-half. Then McGwire
came to St. Louis, and Eckersley saw him hit balls at least 50 feet
farther than he used to.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's reaction to all the attention he's received is just
what Eckersley expected. Fifteen thousand people showed up before a
game at Houston to watch him take batting practice. McGwire said he
felt like a ``caged animal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand it,'' said McGwire at the time. ``Baseball
is a team game, and the media seems to keep making it an individual
thing. I come out here because I love to play, but all this
(attention) I'll never understand.''
</P>
<P>
   What if McGwire just wants to practice hitting balls to right
field? Will the crowd boo? There's a reason it's called batting
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like a freak,'' Eckersley said. ``When I saw him last
year, I don't know if he was having fun. Not everyone is suited for
that (attention). Some are suited more just to hit home runs.''
-----
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is not happy with the way the season is going because
his team is not winning. The Cards are 40-46, 12 1/2 games out of
first place in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason so many players are pulling for McGwire. If he
hits a meaningless homer but the team wins, he'll tell reporters to
go talk to the players who mattered.
</P>
<P>
   When they lose, he's mad, no matter what he's done at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire gets the most attention, but he isn't alone in the
pursuit of Maris' record. Sammy Sosa (33 homers) of the Chicago
Cubs and Ken Griffey Jr. (35) of theSeattle Marinersalso are on
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Who has the edge in the second half? Maybe no one. Sosa is more
of a free swinger and is a streaky hitter. Griffey tends to get
injured. McGwire is the most consistent, but he's had second-half
swoons. Last year he hit only 14 homers in July and August, and in
the past five seasons only 44 of his 167 homers came in those
months.
</P>
<P>
   Now it may just be a matter of whether the pressure and
distractions can get to McGwire. Eckersley, as much as he'd like to
see it, doesn't think McGwire _ or Sosa and Griffey Jr. _ will pass
Maris.
</P>
<P>
   There are too many variables, from injury to whether a team will
pitch to him later in the season. During his run, Maris actually
had some of his hair fall out from the stress, although he didn't
have the full support of his teammates _ most wanted Mickey Mantle,
also with the Yankees, to achieve the feat first.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone _ the players, the fans _ is rooting for McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better guy in baseball who can do it,'' Vaughn
said. ``I hope he attacks it and crushes it. He's the epitome of
slugging.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Rosenberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fitting end
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Yeah, an 18-hole playoff is inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   It also happens to be the right way to do things.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Golf Association, which is frequently maniacal
in adhering to its self-proclaimed mandate of protecting the
integrity of the game, does this particular exercise in a fair and
proper manner.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter that Monday's playoff for the U.S. Women's
Open championship eventually played itself out to a sudden-death
playoff lasting two holes, anyway. It doesn't matter, because the
18-hole playoff set it up.
</P>
<P>
   No sudden death in the immediate wake of the 72-hole event.
</P>
<P>
   No manufactured playoff of x-number of holes in some bastardized
compromise between sudden-death and full-form playoff formats.
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   And the show provided by a couple of 20-year-old women _
champion Se Ri Pak and amateur runner-up Jenny Chuasiriporn of Duke
University _ was a good one.
</P>
<P>
   Please. Stop.
</P>
<P>
   Don't start with the theory that the fact that a college senior
almost won the Open is somehow an indictment of the talent at the
professional level of women's golf. It is not. Or that two
20-year-olds playing for the championship is such an indictment. It
is not.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the only amateur ever to win was Catherine Lacoste
in 1967. Second of all, not since Barbara McIntire in 1956 has an
amateur come as close as a playoff to winning.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, a woman named Nancy Lopez was an amateur when she
tied for second in the Open in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Chuasiriporn will someday turn out to be
a Lopez or even a good professional. Pak, though, sure is off to a
terrific start with two majors (she won the McDonald's LPGA
Championship) as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, quite simply, is an astounding talent. She has a
purposeful, proud, arm-swinging walk that is perfect reflection of
her resolve.
</P>
<P>
   She was four shots down to Chuasiriporn after five holes in the
playoff. At the 18th hole _ stuck in a hazard and staring at
possible defeat with the match tied _ Pak called on that resolve
and her capacity to think clearly in difficult situations to
salvage a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   She disdained a drop, played a shot out and across the fairway
while standing in water halfway up her calves and survived into the
playoff when Chuasiriporn failed to get up-and-down from just off
the green and could do no better than match Pak's bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost don't have chance anymore,'' Pak said of her strategy
at the 18th hole. ``Almost, I lose already. Just want to try ...
last hole ... last chance ... last day. Just want to try
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak and Chuasiriporn posted two-over-par 73s on a demanding
Blackwolf Run Golf Course, and hit an assortment of excellent shots
under pressure in the process. Sure, there were flaws _
Chuasiriporn's triple-bogey-6 at the sixth hole, several short
putts missed, the matching bogeys at the end of regulation _ but
there was mostly good golf.
</P>
<P>
   They hit fairways and greens. They made birdies (seven). They
competed is what they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a good pressure player,'' Chuasiriporn said. ``It was a
matter of one good stroke, and she got it first.''
</P>
<P>
   It came, oh, so smoothly on the 20th hole of the day at
Blackwolf Run.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with Pak surrounded by family, and Chuasiriporn greeted
by college friends bearing bottles of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with a couple of 20-year-old women being 20-year-old
women _ Pak with Disney head covers on her metals, and Chuasiriporn
with a Duke mascot Blue Devil on one of hers.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with Chuasiriporn admitting she hadn't been a fan of
Pak's when watching LPGA Tour events, but saying, ``I will be
now.''
</P>
<P>
   It ended with Pak taking the $267,500 winner's check from the
$1.5million purse that was hers, win or lose, because Chuasiriporn
is an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with Pak, born in South Korea, and Chuasiriporn, born
in Baltimore to Thai parents, sharing a cart ride back toward the
clubhouse for a tournament-ending ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great putt,'' Chuasiriporn said. ``Awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' Pak replied. ``I feel like ... I don't know what to
feel like.''
</P>
<P>
   They should have shared the champagne, toasted the present and
wondered about the future's promise.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
