<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USOPEN-LEDE-COX     07-06 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pak wins playoff
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Se Ri Pak told the truth all week.
</P>
<P>
   She has ``no nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Proof came Monday at Blackwolf Run Golf Course in a playoff for
the U.S. Women's Open crown.
</P>
<P>
   She climbed out of a hole (a four-shot deficit), a hazard (at
the final hole of regulation) and into history.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, a 20-year-old sensation from Daejeon, South Korea, won the
title with a come-from-behind performance against Duke senior Jenny
Chuasiriporn, another 20-year-old, and grabbed the second major
championship of her LPGA Tour rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanged two-over-par 73s before Pak ran in an 18-foot
birdie putt on the second hole of the first U.S. Women's Open
sudden-death playoff and ended an entertaining and astonishingly
competitive round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is unbelievable,'' said Pak, who became the youngest Open
winner in history and the second rookie to win two majors.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing she does in the future will be unbelievable, because
Pak, who won the McDonald's LPGA Championship earlier this year,
already has stamped herself as a force in her sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (LPGA), maybe some people thinking I am lucky,'' Pak
said. ``Know now maybe this best week. I want to be No.1 in golf
world. Now, dream is coming to me.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the Open playoff was dramatic documentation of Pak's
emerging excellence.
</P>
<P>
   First, she steeled herself against Chuasiriporn's fast start and
her own slow one.
</P>
<P>
   Next, she steadied herself for a back-side run.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she set herself for victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't give up ever, ever,'' Pak said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, who was attempting to become the first amateur to
win the Open since Catherine Lacoste in 1967, blasted out of the
chute with three birdies in the first five holes, including a
chip-in to start. That burst, coupled with a Pak bogey at the third
hole, built Chuasiriporn's four-stroke advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that wasn't enough for me,'' Chuasiriporn said. ``I had
to make it more. This course can get you, and it did.''
</P>
<P>
   She never stretched the lead ... never, in fact, made another
birdie. And the course got her immediately after that third birdie
when Chuasiriporn took triple-bogey-6 at the sixth hole.
</P>
<P>
   She pulled a 9-iron into an unplayable lie, took penalty and
drop, hit onto the green and three-putted.
</P>
<P>
   A four-shot edge was down to one.
</P>
<P>
   Game back on.
</P>
<P>
   Pak bogeyed the eighth, though, and both bogeyed the ninth as
Chuasiriporn turned with a two-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, however, posted birdies at the 11th, 12th and moved ahead
for the first time with another birdie at the 14th. She bogeyed the
15th to create another tie, and then merely survived the 18th _ on
her own recovery and Chuasiriporn's wobble _ to reach the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Pak drove into the weeds on the embankment of a left-side water
hazard that is a waste bunker in Blackwolf Run's standard state.
She waded in, chopped out across the fairway, reached the green
with her third shot and then missed a par putt from 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, though, couldn't recreate Sunday's final-hole
magic where she rolled in a 40-foot birdie putt to catch Pak. This
time, she failed to get up-and-down from just off the green _ first
running her chip 12 feet past the hole and then missing the
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (putt) was the only time all day my hands were shaking,''
Chuasiriporn said. ``The chip came out a little hot and took away
any break I was playing. I thought (the putt) was going to be it. I
let it slip away there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak, given opportunity to continue, closed it out with the
birdie at the second playoff hole and her second one in two visits
to the 11th hole during the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going in,'' said Pak, who was walking with
clenched fists before the ball reached the hole.
</P>
<P>
   She cried in the embrace of her mother and father as the Open's
fourth consecutive foreign-born champion _ Sweden's Annika
Sorenstam in 1995 and '96 and Gibraltar's Alison Nicholas last year
_ and its youngest in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I cry,'' Pak said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, finally, all the days of ``no nervous'' simply required
release.
</P>
<P>
   She's still just a kid, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
