<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEFFIELD-KENDALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sheffield wants nothing to do with Kendall
 &HT;    By Cheryl Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Gary Sheffield didn't have any bruises on his face
Monday. That doesn't mean he's forgiven Pittsburgh Pirates catcher
and fellow NL All-StarJason Kendall for a fight they got into
during a game June 28 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has no intention of speaking to Kendall _ a guy
Sheffield doesn't want to see on any baseball field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room for players like that in the game,'' Sheffield
said. ``You won't see me sitting next to him on the bench. He's not
my teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield was crossing home plate when Kendall's helmet came
off. Kendall thought Sheffield intentionally knocked it off, and
started yelling profanities and calling him a cheap shot
(expletive) as Sheffield was going to the Dodgers dugout.
</P>
<P>
   A wrestling match ensued during which Sheffield said he tried to
pick up Kendall and got hit in the face with his shinguard, which
opened a cut near his eye. Sheffield said he's seen a lot worse
plays at home plate, that it was nothing intentional, and that he's
not the type of player who would do something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to show me up in front of 45,000 people,''
Sheffield said. ``I wasn't going to allow that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall feels situation is over and had nothing to say, although
he seemed surprised by Sheffield's comments. Both players received
three-game suspensions from NL President Len Coleman, and both will
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Their lockers were at opposite ends of the Colorado Rockies
clubhouse at Coors Field. Sheffield almost didn't have a locker
there at all. He didn't want to come to the All-Star game. He
hasn't been in Florida since he was traded from the Florida Marlins
on Friday, May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to get away from the game,'' Sheffield said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Tom Lasorda called Sheffield into his
office and persuaded him to participate in the game. He told
Sheffield he'd only have to show up Tuesday, the day of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball wouldn't allow that. So instead, the
Dodgers flew his two daughters and his parents in from St.
Petersburg and his son in from Phoenix and will put them up at a
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treat their players like God,'' Sheffield said. ``What
more can you ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Rosenberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
