<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY SCHEDULED TO PLAY ON SATURDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever since Todd Hundley underwent reconstructive
elbow surgery last September, the New York Mets had been reluctant
to say when their most popular player would be able to return to
the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed Monday when general manager Steve Phillips
announced that Hundley would rejoin the Mets on Saturday and make
his first major league start in the outfield that night against the
Montreal Expos at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put into words how I feel, to tell you the truth,''
Hundley said Monday from Port St. Lucie, Fla. ``It's been such a
long road, a very tough road. To be able to get back in, to go home
and play at Shea, it's going to be the best day of the year for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan since spring training had been for Hundley to rejoin
the Mets somewhere near the All-Star Game break. Apparently, the
Mets decided that the former catcher was ready for major league
action after he demonstrated that he could make long throws from
the outfield with no discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's even getting outfield assists now,'' Phillips said of
Hundley, who threw out a runner at second base on Sunday night in a
Class A game and will now play two games later this week with Class
AAA Norfolk before rejoining the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's return comes at a crucial time for the Mets, who have
been in a slump for weeks and find themselves five games behind the
San Francisco Giants in the National League wild-card race, the
Mets' only realistic doorway into the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' biggest problems have been a shaky bullpen and an
offense that has remained surprisingly meager even after the
acquisition of Mike Piazza in May. Whether the arrival of Hundley,
who like Piazza is an all-star catcher and a bona fide slugger,
will give the Mets the jolt they need is an intriguing question.
Hundley has not faced major league pitching in more than nine
months and may or may not be ready to hit with authority in the
weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he felt ready, Hundley replied: ``Yeah, yeah,
yeah. My hitting is coming and my swing is back to where it should
be.'' He added: ``I feel good, I feel confident and I'm seeing the
ball. It's just a matter of me getting some quality strikes to
swing at.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Hundley will first play in Indianapolis with Class
AAA Norfolk on Thursday and Friday nights. At Class A St. Lucie,
where he was batting .214 after going 0 for 5 Monday night, Hundley
had not been getting that many good pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the issue of how effectively Hundley will hit, and
how effectively he will play in the outfield _ he has been taking a
crash course in defense _ is the question of how Hundley will mesh
with Piazza, who, in effect, took away his job behind the plate
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who hit 71 home runs in the last two seasons for the
Mets, is expected to bat behind Piazza in the lineup and provide
him some protection. It might be the look of the middle of the
Mets' lineup for years to come _ and it might not be.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Hundley again refused to rule out the possibility
that he would want to catch after this season, which presents an
obvious problem should Piazza re-sign with the Mets. The common
assumption is that the Mets will give Piazza whatever he wants to
stay in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets also must decide how much money they may want to
commit to three other potential free agents _ Al Leiter, John
Franco and Dennis Cook, all of whom are having excellent years. In
addition, the Mets are saddled with millions of dollars of salary
obligations next year for three players _ Bernard Gilkey, Mel Rojas
and Brian McRae _ whom they would probably love to trade right now,
and probably can't.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Furthermore, there is no guarantee that Piazza wants to return
with the Mets. Phillips and Piazza's representatives are not
believed to have had any substantive contract talks yet, although
Nelson Doubleday, the Mets' co-owner, reiterated Monday his desire
to see both Piazza and Hundley remain with the Mets for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, absolutely,'' Doubleday said when asked if the plan was
still to re-sign Piazza. ``And we want Todd to spend the rest of
his life with the New York Mets. We just don't know what position
he will be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley has two guaranteed years left on his contract after this
season. His fears that the Mets would turn around and trade him to
a noncontending team after re-signing Piazza led Hundley to ask for
_ and the Mets to agree to _ a limited no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Piazza again stated in a television interview
Monday what he has been saying all along: that he hopes things work
out with the Mets and he can re-sign with them but that he also
wants very much to play for a contending team.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there is some question whether the Mets are just
that. After winning nine straight games from May 21-31 _ the last
seven after Piazza joined the team _ the Mets (44-39) were just
13-19 heading into the break, losing seven of their final nine
games.
</P>
<P>
   While Piazza is hitting .341 in 35 games since joining the Mets
on May 23, he is just 7 for 32 (.219) with one home run and seven
runs batted in with runners in scoring position. That says as much
about the Mets' inability to put men on base in front of him as it
does about Piazza's recent tendency to press with men on base.
</P>
<P>
   Can Hundley help change the Mets' production? In one sense, it
will be hard for him to do worse than the Mets' current starting
outfield _ Gilkey, McRae and Butch Huskey, all of whom are batting
lower than .250. But can he do better? And if so, enough to make a
difference for the Mets?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
