<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-CAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE BRONX AND BEYOND, SUMMER CAMP CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MACARENA HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If 11-year-old Joey Antonio had his way, he would
spend the next six weeks of his summer at home in the Kingsbridge
section of the Bronx watching television, preferably ``Fresh Prince
of Bel Air.'' But his mother had a different plan.
</P>
<P>
   ```Joey,' she said, `we need to find a place for you to go to
camp,''' he recalls his mother, Carmen Aquino, telling him two
weeks before he finished sixth grade at New Covenant Christian
School. ``My mom doesn't want me to sit home and do nothing. She
just says TV is bad for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey, along with hundreds of other New York City children,
started his first day of summer camp. Some were driven an hour from
their homes to get to a camp. For others it was much closer.
</P>
<P>
   Joey only had to walk across the street to the Kingsbridge
Heights Community Center, where his mother enrolled him in a day
camp. He will be one of more than a million children in New York
state who will be attending overnight or day camps this summer,
said Adam Weiss, the executive director of the New York section of
the American Camping Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education, teaming up with community organizations,
also opened several sites Monday for its summer program,
Break-Aways Camps, which incorporates academics into the camp
experience for 1,300 students with the goal of improving their
school records. The program is free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   At Kingsbridge Heights Community Center, about 12 neighborhood
teen-agers and 20-somethings will spend the summer teaching
physical education, art, and computer and drama classes to 100
children ages 6 through 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to make it too academic because we want to make
it fun,'' said the summer day camp's director, Michell Tollinchi,
24, who started working at the camp as a counselor when she was 14.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the surrounding community, the camp is not only a
lifeline for children, but also for parents. At Kingsbridge Heights
Community Center, about 90 percent of heads of households work, Ms.
Tollinchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aquino, Joey's mother, and other parents pay $575 to send
their children to Kingsbridge Heights Community Center for six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I send him to camp so that he won't be laying around at home,
so he can have fun and interaction with other kids,'' said Ms.
Aquino, a social worker.
</P>
<P>
   Two-income households, and the resulting day care problems, have
caused a 10 percent annual increase in the number of children
attending camps nationwide in the last few years, said Weiss of the
American Camping Association.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the children who will spend their days at the camp are
Ian Pershad, 8, and his sister, Keshia, 11. Ian spent much of his
day Monday drawing a portrait of another camper, Marissa Rodriguez,
11, on an 11-by-14-inch sheet of white paper. He was stuck on the
nose for about five minutes, and he did not pencil in her long
brown hair until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Marissa had similar difficulties. ``I can't draw his hat, and
his eyes are hard to draw because he's looking down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the table, Keshia was also drawing a portrait of a fellow
camper, Lizette Tagle, 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot more fun because at my grandmother's house I'd
be sleeping,'' Keshia said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
