</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUP'S GREAT, NOW GET OUT 
PUFF PARTY 
BENEFICIAL GIFTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with MONIQUE P. YAZIGI 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Yeganeh, who was parodied in the sitcom
``Seinfeld'' for his soup mania, is still drawing rave reviews from
foodies. His Soup Kitchen International, on West 55th Street near
Eighth Avenue, was listed at the top of 38 New York restaurants in
``America's Best Meal Deals,'' a slim volume from the Zagat Survey
restaurant raters. Soup Kitchen International's meal-in-a-cup
scored a 27 on a 30-point scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soup is terrific,'' said Nina Zagat, who, with her
husband, Tim, edited the listing of 1,411 restaurants in 35 cities.
``The food is a 27. That's very, very good. If you can get 27 food
for $13, you're willing to put up with a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, Yeganeh's singular way of greeting and treating
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people in our office tell their tales,'' she said.
``People talk about how he was abusive, and how if you'd ask a
question about what's in it or why do I have to wait on line, the
guy would say, `Get out of here.' He's awfully sweet to Tim and me
when we go by.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't go by soon. As is his custom, Yeganeh has closed Soup
Kitchen International for the summer and is said to be out of the
country, looking for new recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Puff Party
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The main difference between St. Bart's at
Christmastime and the Hamptons on the Fourth of July was that there
were no yachts this time. Other than that, for a certain segment of
the partygoing population, the long weekend was about soirees given
by Ted Field, the chairman of Interscope Communications, and Sean
Combs, the rap impresario known as Puff Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   For Field's party on Friday, beefy security guards turned away
would-be crashers. Those admitted to Field's rented estate in
Amagansett Revlon chairman Ronald O. Perelman; actor Mark Wahlberg;
director Penny Marshall, and ``downtown'' Julie Brown, a former MTV
veejay who came straight from a party that Playboy magazine had
given for her at a club in Southampton called Life's a Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Combs was also there, and clearly did not want to wait to have
fun. So he went to the deejay's booth and announced the guests by
name. ``Russell Simmons in the house,'' he said. ``Andre Harrell in
the house. Hamptons magazine in the house.'' And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same guests were in Combs' house in East Hampton the
next day. Mike Tyson seemed calm as he waited to be served by a
Mister Softee truck that Combs had hired to sit in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, as in St. Bart's, the crowd's mantra was:
``Where are you going next?'' And at 8 p.m., Combs announced that
the party was over, to the relief of neighbors who had worried all
year that this year's party would be as loud and long as last
year's, which did not break up until after 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Beneficial Gifts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No, Finn M.W. Caspersen did not give away the
multimillion-dollar golden parachute he received from his old
company, Beneficial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But after Beneficial joined forces with Household International,
its main competitor in the consumer loan business, in an $8.6
billion stock swap, he decided he did not want to accept an offer
to be chairman and a director. ``I think you have to make clean
breaks in life,'' he said. ``They said, `You have some
charities.'''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Peddie School in Hightstown, N.J., and the Harvard
Law School are dividing $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Caspersen graduated from Peddie in 1959 and Harvard Law School
in 1966, after time out for an undergraduate degree from Brown
University. He said that his most unforgettable Harvard moment was
``when I got the acceptance letter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have it,'' he said. ``I said, `I could end up in the
gutter, but I got into Harvard Law School.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
