<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-BOARD-SAFETY-460-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUFFLING OF N.Y.C. SCHOOL BOARD REVIVES TALKS ON POLICE IN THE
SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JACQUES STEINBERG   
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The formal installation of two new members of the New
York City Board of Education on Tuesday has prompted renewed talks
with City Hall over the long-idled proposal by Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani to put the police in charge of safety in some schools,
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new members, Terri Thomson of Queens, who said she
has an open mind about the proposal, could provide the mayor with
the majority he has long sought. And both City Hall and board
officials said the possibility of a majority voting with the mayor
and against Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, who opposes broad police
control in the schools, had prompted both sides to resume
negotiations. They said the framework of an agreement could be in
place perhaps by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, Crew and four of the board's seven
members have resisted the mayor's efforts to bring the troubled
school safety division under police control. The mayor said last
year that he would be willing to compromise; he proposed that the
police assume responsibility for safety in more than 100 of the
most violent schools. But talks bogged down over the concerns of
Crew and the board, including whether the board's safety officers
would become police employees and whether principals would have to
defer to police commanders in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday morning, however, the mayor will be dealing with a
board that has no clear stance on a police takeover. Two of the
four opponents to an expanded police role _ Luis Reyes of Manhattan
and Carol Gresser of Queens _ have been replaced by members named
by their respective borough presidents. The Manhattan
representative, Irving S. Hamer Jr., will continue to oppose a
broad takeover, according to Manhattan Borough President C.
Virginia Fields. But Gresser's successor, Thomson, and Queens
Borough President Claire Shulman, a sometime Giuliani ally, have
been far more circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an opinion on this,'' Thomson said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   She said that since being selected in March to replace Gresser
beginning July 1, she has been researching the issue by talking to
parents and principals and reading the reams of reports
commissioned on the subject over the last decade _ including the
most recent, in 1996, by a mayoral panel that endorsed a police
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to keep an open mind on every issue,'' said
Thomson, 49, a vice president for community relations at Citibank.
``I am going to vote my conscience based on what is right for the
kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
