</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-ASSESS-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FAMILIAR MISDEEDS PLAGUE NEW CHILD WELFARE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The news articles carry eerie echoes of the old days.
Two girls are repeatedly raped by parents in a Brooklyn home deemed
safe by the city. An emaciated toddler hidden in a dark, airless
room nearly starves on a urine-stained mattress because his
caseworker fails to visit his foster home in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, these kinds of horror stories persuaded Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani to create the Administration for Children's Services, to
put an end to sloppy child welfare investigations and family
assessments, and to insure that caseworkers would vigilantly
safeguard New York City's most vulnerable children.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, amid flashing cameras and barking questions, the
administration's commissioner, Nicholas Scoppetta, found himself
defending his agency's handling of those two recent cases, which
seem riddled with exactly the poor practices he vowed to eliminate.
A few days earlier, Giuliani publicly criticized the agency for
failing the Brooklyn girls by sending them home from foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Many people cannot help but wonder: What has truly changed?
</P>
<P>
   The unsatisfying answer, say lawyers, judges and caseworkers, is
that much has changed, but not enough to insure the safety of many
abused and neglected children. Nearly three years after its
creation, the Administration for Children's Services remains an
agency in transition, with its staff an awkward mixture of
committed, reform-minded caseworkers and negligent holdovers from
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some agency watchers are cheered by the changes under way, which
include aggressive hiring, more training and declining caseloads,
but they say it will take years for true reform to take hold.
Meanwhile, they say, some children will inevitably be harmed during
the city's watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are definitely moving in the right direction, but
realistically we're talking years from now in terms of systemic
change,'' said Monica Drinane, the lawyer in charge of the Legal
Aid Juvenile Rights Division, which represents the children in the
Staten Island and Brooklyn cases.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drinane said: ``Can we guarantee in the meantime that there
won't be cases like the ones we've seen these past few days? No, we
can't. But that doesn't mean we can afford to give up. Giving up is
not an option. How can we give up on children's lives?''
</P>
<P>
   The questions about the depth of the reforms could not come at a
more critical time. In three weeks, advocates for children will ask
a federal judge to appoint a receiver to take over the child
welfare agency. Despite Scoppetta's efforts, they say, New York
City still lags far behind where it should be. City officials, for
instance, still have no way to tell whether caseworkers are
actually making required visits or delivering court-ordered
services.
</P>
<P>
   Caseloads, which the city says have fallen to 16 from 27, are
still unevenly distributed. In Brooklyn, a supervisor said Monday
that workers have about 25 cases each.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, judges and lawyers for children say the city has
failed to devote enough money to finance desperately needed
services. Adolescents are in need of foster care beds, parents wait
months for drug treatment programs and children sleep in city
offices while officials scramble for beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed? Nothing's changed,'' said Marcia Robinson
Lowry, the executive director of Children Rights, the nonprofit
group that has sued the city on behalf of abused and neglected
children.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the 2-year-old Staten Island boy, who weighed 18
pounds when he was discovered on Saturday, his caseworker failed to
visit him at all in June. She last saw him on May 14, and then she
went out of town. No one was sent to check on him in her place,
agency officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Another caseworker, who stopped to visit three other children
who also lived in the boy's foster home, noticed that the boy
looked looked thin on June 15. But she never checked his bedroom or
his weight, officials say. He was not her responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In the sexual abuse case in Brooklyn, a caseworker was assigned
to see the girls twice a month. It is unclear whether she actually
did. It is also unclear whether city officials knew that child
welfare records show that the mother of the girls had been abused
as a teenager. The woman's aunt says she was raped by a relative
when she was 15.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its struggle to extend change from the top to workers on the
ground, New York City reflects the experiences of troubled agencies
around the country, which have stumbled in the march to reform.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after officials in Missouri and the District of
Columbia embarked on aggressive improvement plans, they are still
struggling to serve the abused and neglected children in their
care, according to the Center for the Study of Social Policy, a
nonprofit research group, which has monitored the progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that one cannot hope to turn the performance of a
large, complex bureaucracy around in one year, or even three or
four,'' according to a study by center officials, who have also
served as child welfare experts for New York City officials and
lawyers for the city's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes are slower than we would expect, and with New York
City being so big, it has to make it harder,'' Judith Meltzer, a
senior associate at the center.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Meltzer emphasized that some tasks should be completed
quickly, within six months or a year, including better training and
supervision and the development of a quality review program to
monitor the work of caseworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' she said, ``but it can be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
