<HEADLINE>
MAN KILLS HIMSELF IN HOSTAGE STANDOFF WITH POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man held his ex-girlfriend hostage for an hour and
a half Monday in the Brooklyn plumbing business where they worked,
then apparently shot her before killing himself during a standoff
with police, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Zuleica Bermudez, 30, was listed in critical
condition Monday night at Bellevue Hospital Center. Co-workers said
that a month ago, Ms. Bermudez had broken up with the man, Robert
Wayne Jiles, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, Helen Henry, 25, jumped from a second-floor
balcony during the standoff and was treated for ankle injuries and
released at Wyckoff Heights Medical Center in Brooklyn. All three
were employees of Dun-Rite Water Main and Sewer Contractors at
178-180 N. Ninth St. in Williamsburg, where the siege took place.
</P>
<P>
   Police were called at 11:25 a.m. by a report of an assault in
progress, said Chief Joseph Fox, a deputy chief for Brooklyn North.
When they arrived, Fox said, Jiles fired some shots and then
barricaded himself and Ms. Bermudez in an office on the building's
second floor.
</P>
<P>
   Police closed North Ninth Street between Driggs and Bedford
Avenues, and four officers entered the two-story building. One
officer, climbing the stairs to help a fleeing woman, was forced by
gunfire to take cover in an office across the hall from the
besieged couple and eventually was freed by officers who sawed the
wrought-iron grille off the office window, Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   At about 1 p.m., the officers heard several shots, and soon
found Jiles shot in the temple, Ms. Bermudez shot in the cheek, and
a .380-caliber semi-automatic handgun nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the couple, co-workers and Ms. Bermudez's ex-husband
described a relationship gone sour. ``Wayne was so quiet you would
never expect him to do something like this,'' said Eddie Santiago
Jr., 40, one of the company's 25 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bermudez, who was born in Panama and raised in Flatbush, had
apparently dated Jiles for about a year, and they had lived
together on South First Street in Williamsburg. She was a secretary
at Dun-Rite, and he did construction work on sewers, co-workers
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
