<SLUG> BC-CONN-GOVERNOR-RACE-345-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDING LONG SEARCH, KENNELLY FILLS 2ND SPOT ON DEMOCRATIC TICKET
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By MIKE ALLEN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Ending a search so prolonged and public that
it threatened to become an embarrassment to her gubernatorial
campaign, Rep. Barbara Kennelly plans to announce Tuesday that she
has chosen a former state legislator as her running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Courtney, 45, a lawyer who retired from the State House
of Representatives in 1994, agreed Monday afternoon to be the
Democratic candidate for lieutenant governor, one of Kennelly's
aides said. They are to make the announcement jointly on Tuesday in
Courtney's hometown of Vernon, east of Hartford, and then greet
voters at a diner, the aide said. In an effort to retain an element
of surprise about her selection, Kennelly confirmed Monday that she
had made her decision but would not say where she would announce it
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kennelly, who is retaining her seat in Congress while she
campaigns, has trailed Gov. John Rowland, a Republican who is
seeking a second term, in polls and fund-raising. Her campaign
staff had made overtures about the second slot on the ticket to
several prominent Connecticut Democrats, and even a few obscure
local officials. All took themselves out of the running.
</P>
<P>
   Her problem became such an open secret that last week a
political column in The Hartford Courant carried the headline,
``Wanted: Running Mate for Kennelly. Send Resumes.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtney, who was elected to the legislature four times, was
co-chairman of the House Human Services Committee and later
co-chairman of the Public Health Committee. He is known for being
liberal but practical, and received high marks for deft handling of
cuts to state programs for the poor, elderly and disabled during
the recession of the early 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   But he brings Kennelly's ticket none of the geographic diversity
that candidates often seek in a running mate. Vernon is just 13
miles from Hartford, where Kennelly is a lifelong resident.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, voters choose a governor and a lieutenant
governor as a pair. The current lieutenant governor, M. Jodi Rell,
will seek re-election with Rowland.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Party regulars had urged Kennelly to pick a running mate from
Fairfield County, home of many wealthy Democrats, or the New Haven
area, which is heavily populated. She had settled on a well-known
Fairfield County resident, Gene F. Eriquez, who is the mayor of
Danbury, but he developed a kidney ailment last month and withdrew
his name from consideration. Kennelly's supporters were especially
disappointed because Eriquez, an Italian-American, would have
brought ethnic diversity to the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, party officials, who said they insisted on
anonymity because they did not want to spoil Tuesday's
announcement, said they were enthusiastic about the choice because
Courtney's legislative experience would help the ticket attack
Rowland's administration for its record on education, the
environment and public health.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket has quite a bit of ground to make up. In a poll
released last week by the University of Connecticut, Rowland had a
lead of 28 percentage points, 55 percent to 27 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
