<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-OPEN-MEETINGS-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. CLOSED SCHOOL BOARD SESSION IS ASSAILED
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JACQUES STEINBERG   
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Again raising the concerns of the New York State
official who enforces the open meetings law, the Board of Education
has scheduled a closed-door retreat Wednesday with Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew in Palisades, N.Y., 25 miles north of its
Brooklyn headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which was announced in a notice sent to reporters
on Monday, comes 11 months after the board met quietly at the same
location _ earning a verbal rebuke from the same official, Robert
Freeman, the executive director of the New York State Committee on
Open Government, a state agency.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the board, William C. Thompson Jr., said the
board had scheduled a closed, or executive, session at the IBM
Conference Center on Route 9W so members could escape distractions
like ringing phones. In an interview, he said that the board would
adhere to the letter of the law, discussing only subjects that are
permitted in executive session _ including personnel, contracts and
matters under litigation _ but not policy, which is prohibited. He
added that the board's counsel had the authority to cut off
improper discussion.
</P>
<P>
   But Freeman said the public has no way to monitor compliance.
For example, he said, a conversation about an ongoing lawsuit
concerning the special education system could veer into discussion
of the system's overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules of human nature take over,'' Freeman said. ``And one
of the rules is that a group will drift into a new topic and that
new topic may not be among those that could validly be discussed in
private.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the board was violating the spirit of the law by
meeting so far from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of the open meetings law is to encourage members of
the public and others to become familiar with the decision-making
process,'' Freeman said. ``How can they do that if meetings are
held outside their communities?''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the location was irrelevant because the meeting
would not be open to the public.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At their retreat last year, the board members discussed a
proposal by the chancellor's staff to limit the size and autonomy
of alternative schools, a policy discussion that Freeman said
appeared to violate the open meetings law. If the board had taken
any action that should have been taken in public, the action could
be invalidated by a lawsuit against the board.
</P>
<P>
   At various times in recent years, the board has been criticized
by parents and others for using closed-door sessions improperly. In
1993, the Public Education Association, a nonprofit advocacy group,
won permission from a state Supreme Court justice to examine the
minutes of such meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-98 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980706.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-06 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-SUBWAY-RIDERS     07-06 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-SUBWAY-RIDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: HAPPY TIMES FOR METROHOLICS, BUT ...  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You could call Gene Russianoff a metroholic. To get
an idea of what a subway addict he is, consider how he ushered in
Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   Some people can be found in bars or clubs at midnight. But as
the third of July melted into the Fourth, Russianoff was standing
at the Union Street Station in Brooklyn with $63 in hand to buy the
new monthly subway pass that went on sale that very minute.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he was going anywhere, except straight back home on
foot. But as a leader of the advocacy group known as the
Straphangers Campaign, he wanted to be in the delivery room, as it
were, for the birth of the new system of unlimited-ride passes that
is being trumpeted as a millenial change.
</P>
<P>
   Russianoff even pondered hurling confetti at the token clerk,
but thought better of it. Just as well. You never know these days
if a festive gesture will become a quality-of-life offense.
</P>
<P>
   His desire to celebrate was understandable, though. Passes of
this type have long been the Straphangers' Holy Grail, and now they
are in hand. So is a big test of whether they will bring about the
miracles some are predicting. Russianoff acknowledged the point
Monday as he rode the No. 6 line from station to station to see how
the cards sold during the first morning rush they were in effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting what we want,'' he said, ``and now we'll find
out if it makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki proclaimed the other day that the fare
discounts would empower the rider. That had a nice ring to it, and
will no doubt provide the governor with a campaign sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   But you might want to remember that it was the same Pataki who
depowered the rider a few years ago when he cut state subsidies for
New York mass transit by hundreds of millions of dollars. He took
away so much money, in fact, that he brought about the largest
increase ever in the subway and bus fare, an increase that proved
to be unnecessary and is effectively being scaled back now.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's political interests aside, some have described
the new monthly and weekly passes as innovations that will alter
urban life. That seems a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, being able to take as many trains and buses as you want is
exciting. But life-altering? It is a phrase better saved for truly
cosmic change in the subways, like whatever it takes to persuade
the jughead standing above you that it is boorish of him to munch
on pizza as the train lurches through the tunnel. That would
require a real miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The goals of the new passes are less lofty, and some lend
themselves to easy measurement.
</P>
<P>
   Will subway and bus ridership increase? That seems to be a
given.
</P>
<P>
   Will subway and bus service improve enough to handle the extra
load? That cannot be taken for granted. The masters of the
underground have not done nearly enough to handle the extra 400,000
riders a day produced by the 11-rides-for-the-price-of-10 discount
that went into effect a year ago. So it is not unreasonable to ask
how bad the crowding has to get before they add more cars. Arms and
legs sticking out the doors as trains leave the station?
</P>
<P>
   Another obvious test is whether the new passes will lure
motorists out of their cars and onto mass transit. The Straphangers
Campaign and Pataki predict that will happen. But the discounts of
the last year have yet to do much good in this regard.
</P>
<P>
   While there are more subway riders, there are also more motor
vehicles than ever entering Manhattan, nearly a million a day
during the week. That no doubt is because these are good times, and
many more people are driving to work. Three cheers for the economy!
But the city center is choking on traffic, and political leaders
have done precious little to discourage people from driving into
town.
</P>
<P>
   Russianoff argued that lowering the mass-transit fare is only
part of the solution. Better subway service is also needed, he
said, and stern anti-car measures like tolls on the East River
bridges. Those kinds of steps are not necessarily out of the
question some day, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Pollyana-ish thought,'' he said, ``but if these passes
can happen, maybe other changes can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But let us, like Scarlett O'Hara, think about that
tomorrow, and deal with a more immediate anxiety. Have you thought
at all about how to keep your monthly pass safe? Lose it, and it's
goodbye $63. That's real money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
