<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-HOLIK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SIGN HOLIK FOR 3 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a week after losing Doug Gilmour to free agency, the
New Jersey Devils have signed Bobby Holik, their top-line center.
</P>
<P>
   Devils General Manager Lou Lamoriello confirmed Monday that
Holik, a restricted free agent who was coming off his best season,
signed a three-year deal over the weekend. Terms were not
announced, but the contract is believed to be worth about $7.5
million. Holik, 27, earned $714,000 last season when he led the
Devils in scoring with 29 goals and 36 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Gilmour, the Devils' third-leading scorer last
season behind Holik and defenseman Scott Niedermayer, made signing
Holik imperative. Gilmour signed a three-year, $18 million deal
last week with the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Holik, whose plus-minus rating was plus-23 last season, had said
he would not attend training camp without a new contract, and he
could have requested salary arbitration next week if a deal had not
been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gillis, Holik's agent, said he was not surprised that an
agreement came so quickly. Holik was vacationing in Wyoming on
Monday and was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Holik's offensive production was overshadowed by a season-ending
slump that continued into the playoffs. After not scoring a goal in
the Devils' final 16 regular-season games, he did not have a point
in five games in their first-round playoff loss to Ottawa. He
missed one game in the playoffs because of food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Other Devils who remain unsigned as Group II free agents are
Steve Thomas, Jason Arnott, Denis Pederson, Niedermayer and Petr
Sykora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
