<SLUG> BC-SNEAKER-SALES-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKERS OF ATHLETIC SHOES RETHINK STAR-POWER STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, Reebok International trusted that a
7-foot-1-inch behemoth named Shaquille O'Neal would shepherd the
company to global footwear domination. At the 1993 Super Show, a
sprawling sporting goods convention, the towering centerpiece of
Reebok's mammoth booth was a 15-foot photographic cutout of O'Neal,
the Orlando Magic's rookie center.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Fireman, Reebok's chairman, saw a limitless future for the
Shaq Attaq, the sneaker named for O'Neal, and a finite one for the
Nike Air Jordan shoes endorsed by Michael Jordan. ``I think Jordan
has three or four years of significance left, at the top,'' Fireman
said at the time. ``Shaq is next. We will use Shaq to catapult to
leadership throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But just last week Reebok waved goodbye to O'Neal, now a Los
Angeles Laker, convinced that he was not worth his $3 million
yearly fee. He simply had not delivered the rim-rocking marketplace
slam dunk that Reebok expected for its five-year investment. ``Even
when basketball sales were very good at Reebok, Shaq shoes didn't
sell very well,'' said John Horan, publisher of Sporting Goods
Intelligence, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok is not the only athletic shoe company to rethink this
kind of endorsement strategy, or at least to wonder if paying
enormous sums to players will produce significant sales.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a major shift in the athletic shoe market, an $8
billion (wholesale) domestic business, especially in the
high-priced ``signature'' basketball segment. In this rare air,
companies once vied fiercely to sign the new face, the silky
silhouette or the hot attitude judged most capable of sparking
sales of the latest $100-plus pair of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an oversaturation of athletes associated with
signature product,'' said Howe Burch, vice president of marketing
for Fila America. ``It's too much of a good thing, like the stock
market correcting itself. Whether it's athletes' off-court behavior
or people unhappy with the business of sports, people are tired of
it and they vote at retail.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Jordans remain the only sure thing in the signature market.
While O'Neal's impact on sales has been decidedly un-Jordanesque,
so has Reebok's experiment with Allen Iverson and Fila's with Grant
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we've been impacted by the problems in the basketball
category,'' Burch said, ``whether it's Grant's shoe, Chris Webber's
shoe or Jerry Stackhouse's shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended March 31, Fila's parent company lost $8.7
million. When Nike posted a $67.7 million lost last month, its
first quarterly loss in 13 years, Phil Knight, the company's
chairman, said: ``It was not a good year by Nike standards, but
then our futures aren't very good either.'' Nike's Asian business
is in turmoil, and it is laying off 1,600 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok lost $3.4 million in its first quarter ended March 31.
Converse reported that sales of its basketball line tumbled 50
percent in its first quarter, which also ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok's move to sever ties with O'Neal ``was a difficult
decision to make,'' said John Frascotti, Reebok's vice president of
sports marketing, but was apparently part of an evolving strategy
being adopted by other shoe companies: trim the ranks of well-paid
athletes and rely on the quality of the product. ``Consumers have
shifted away from being spoon-fed a formulaic approach to athlete
endorsement and are being more discreet,'' Frascotti said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is only the biggest National Basketball Association star
with whom Reebok has cut its lucrative endorsement ties. Reebok has
slashed its NBA roster from about 100 players to between 40 and 45.
Other casualties include the Milwaukee Bucks' Glenn Robinson. In
football, Reebok cut Dallas' Emmitt Smith; in baseball, it cut
Colorado's Larry Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Converse has parted ways with the Knicks' Larry Johnson _
Grandmama, his cross-dressing alter ego, left the gym two years ago
with nothing but free shoes _ and with Latrell Sprewell after
Sprewell choked his coach at Golden State, P.J. Carlesimo. Nike
showed the door to Oliver Miller (except for some merchandise) and
told two dozen others they would get performance bonuses, not
guaranteed cash.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball shoes are the highest-profile products in most
companies' portfolios, so they get the most attention when business
turns down. Some companies and analysts say they believe consumers
are shifting their tastes to the so-called brown shoes, footwear
made by outfits like Doc Martens and Timberland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletic shoe market is in terrible shape and the first to
go are the high-profile, expensive athletes,'' said Bob Williams,
president of Burns Sports, a Chicago-based service that matches
athletes with advertisers. ``The entire industry is in a bind
because research is finding that children aren't choosing athletic
shoes as their first choice, and leaving Nike and Reebok with their
pants down, trying to justify their expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the shoe companies had spent the past decade in a
follow-the-leader syndrome, bidding up the price for the
endorsement services of players whose ability to sell the products
were, at best, dubious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Dennis Rodman didn't work for Converse,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Jim Andrews, editor of the IEG Endorsement Insider, a new
monthly newsletter, ``They felt they had to sign up everybody, and
the consumer can't tell one from another.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Horan of Sporting Goods Intelligence, notes, the shift
in the basketball market is mainly at the high end.
``Moderate-price stuff is still selling well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the situation from a happy reserve is New Balance, the
Boston-based company that has largely avoided endorsements. New
Balance abides by a slogan it devised several years ago: ``Endorsed
by No One,'' partly because the company does not believe in the
concept and partly because of the risk in making such an expensive
investment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Balance is shielded from the fallout of declining sales in
basketball shoes. More than one-third of its $650 million in sales
is in running shoes, with barely 1 percent in basketball, said Paul
Heffernan, the company's vice president for global marketing.
``Foot Locker once said to us, `You're not into hero marketing, so
you won't get big in basketball,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one on New Balance's small athletic roster stars in the
company's television commercials or print advertisements. The
runner Keith Brantley is the highest-paid New Balance endorser at
$40,000 a year. The company's $13 million advertising budget this
year (up from $4 million) is puny compared with most of his
competitors'. ``If the budget went up to $25 million, I'd be doing
the same thing,'' Heffernan said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, agents for major league athletes know not to call New
Balance. ``I got a call from Jackie Joyner-Kersee and someone from
auto racing, but the big-ticket players, they know we won't do
it,'' Heffernan added. ``Our competitors are mainly marketeers.''
</P>
<P>
   Big names do not endorse K-Swiss, either. The tennis shoemaker's
biggest names are the Australian doubles team Todd Woodbridge and
Mark Woodforde, and the retired Virginia Wade. ``Making superior
shoes is where we want to be,'' said Steve Nichols, chairman of
K-Swiss. ``Guys like Lendl and Sampras, I don't know if they sell
shoes. But we have literally thousands of endorsers _ the people
who've worn our shoes for years.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are still big bets being made on stars the
shoe companies believe will survive and prosper into the
post-Jordan era. Reebok is wagering $5 million a year on Iverson,
the Philadelphia 76er guard. Hill's deal with Fila pays him $80
million over seven years, and Adidas America is paying richly, but
less than Hill's deal, for the Lakers' Kobe Bryant, who proved to
be more style than substance during most of his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got five young players with contracts we can live
with,'' said Sonny Vaccaro, a director of sports marketing for
Adidas America, referring to a group that includes Bryant, the
Boston Celtics' Antoine Walker and the teen-ager Tracy McGrady of
the Toronto Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike's still a million miles away from us, but if Kobe is what
we think he is, he can really lead the next generation,'' Vaccaro
said. But the two-year-old strategy has not dramatically altered
Adidas' sales or earnings, he said. Other sports, like soccer, are
carrying the company.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Converse has adopted a less expensive tack: signing
young players who are not as well known, like Cleveland's Brevin
Knight and Denver's Bobby Jackson, in order to cash in on their
hoped-for success.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shaq-less Reebok will focus less on its remaining
athletes and more on the marketing of its new DMX technology, which
will be featured in a variety of Reebok shoes, including Iverson's
signature line, The Answer II.
</P>
<P>
   Said Reebok's Frascotti: ``Five years ago, we took a tack to
establish ourselves in basketball, football and baseball, and we
used athletes as endorsers. But we're different than we were five
years ago. Now we've established our performance credentials.''
</P>
</TEXT>
